</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S ROOKIE ACE BACK ON TRACK, WINS SEVENTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Just above the Panda bear on the left field wall at
Qualcomm Stadium, there's an innovative scoreboard that the
Mariners considered for Safeco Field. All game long, it tracks the
number of pitches thrown, as well as the type and speed of the last
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   It's useful for fans, but the Mariners' decided not to use one
at their new ballpark because of concern it might distract the
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   But not all distractions are bad. As he set down the Padres in
the early innings Sunday, Mariners starter Freddy Garcia noticed he
hadn't thrown many pitches. The Mariners had challenged Garcia to
go deeper in games after back-to-back outings in which he failed to
last six innings. The scoreboard told him he had a great chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my pitches on the scoreboard, and I wanted to go seven
or eight innings,'' Garcia said. ``I thought that's what they
wanted, seven or eight innings. I figured I could go eight because
I hadn't thrown that many.''
</P>
<P>
   He did go eight innings, allowing one unearned run in a 4-1
Mariners win before 31,761 fans at the Q. The rookie right-hander
threw 123 pitches, more than he'd thrown in any start since his
third of the season, and said he considered the game his best so
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many pitches did he have? 123?'' said Mariners manager Lou
Piniella. ``That's what we like to see from him, that number, to
get us into the seventh or eighth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia improved to 7-2, and contributed on offense, as well.
After the Mariners took a 2-1 lead in the seventh inning, Garcia
delivered a two-out single that scored Tom Lampkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about my hitting, because we play in the
American League,'' said Garcia, who nonetheless took considerable
pride in a double he hit in spring training. ``But, yeah, I like
hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   What impressed Lampkin more than Garcia's hit was the way he
worked the count against Padres ace Andy Ashby, who fell to 6-4
despite eight strong innings of his own. Ashby might have won if
not for Lampkin, who victimized him twice.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Ashby tried to work a cutter inside and
left it too high. ``It was so bad, it about started to back up,''
Ashby said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Lampkin saw, too. The Mariners catcher thought it
was a backdoor slider, and he slammed it over the wall in right
field for his third homer of the year, and first hit since May 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing every day, it's a lot easier to remember
what you've done right,'' said Lampkin, who was playing for the
first time in a week. ``It's a lot easier to remember it tomorrow
at 7:00 than next Sunday at 1:00. I need to let that feeling run
over and over in my mind so the next time I get an opportunity,
it's like the same old thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin came to bat again in the seventh, with the score tied
1-1. Raul Ibanez had reached on an error by third baseman Dave
Magadan, and advanced to second on a sacrifice bunt by Russ Davis.
Lampkin then scorched a ball to first base, where it exploded off
the dirt and bowled over first baseman John Vander Wal. It went for
a double, and brought in Ibanez with the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had it, and it was gone,'' said Vander Wal. ``I just stuck
my glove up in front of my face. I haven't seen (this infield) as
bad as it was today. It just seemed like every ground ball was on a
trampoline when it hit the dirt, just bouncing up. It gets scary
when you're playing the infield and the ball's jumping like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The infield has been fine at night, Vander Wal said, but
different Sunday with the sun baking it. Vander Wal's own grounder,
which eluded David Bell at second for a fourth-inning single, told
Bell to watch out.
</P>
<P>
   It was a valuable lesson. With a 3-1 lead, two outs and a runner
on second in the eighth, Bell snared a grounder by Magadan that
took a similarly nasty hop. He gathered it and threw to first to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse to have a field in the major leagues that's
like that,'' said Bell. ``It's ridiculous. I'm happy I made the
plays. Maybe they can't control it, maybe it's something with the
ground or the sun, but it's just way too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Way too hard is what San Diego seemed to be for the Mariners
this weekend. With five projected starters on the disabled list,
the last-place Padres used patchwork lineups this series.
</P>
<P>
   The average salary among Sunday's regulars was just $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   But San Diego used its three top starters this weekend and won
two of the three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had won five straight series coming in, but they
knew road interleague games would be tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that causes us problems against NL teams on
the road is that we don't really have a combination of hitters that
can put the game in motion that well,'' said Piniella, whose team
has won just five times in 19 games at NL parks the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hit home runs, we do all right. If not, we struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   But not always. The Mariners hit a pair of solo homers
yesterday, but they could have done without them. As the
conventional scoreboard showed, Garcia needed only two runs to win.
</P>
</TEXT>
