<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SILENCING CITIZENS IN EGYPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 7:
</P>
<P>
   The rise of citizens' organizations working for civil liberties,
environmental protection or religious freedom has given people an
important new way to monitor their governments and defend their
rights. Unfortunately, Egypt passed a law late last month that puts
nongovernmental organizations more firmly under state control and
allows the government to shut down any group it wishes. The law is
a leap backward for Egypt, the Arab world's most democratic nation.
It needs immediate repeal.
</P>
<P>
   The new law technically applies to all nongovernmental
organizations. But Egypt's intellectuals, who are outraged about
it, expect it will be most harshly applied to the two kinds of
groups long targeted by the government, peaceful Islamic groups and
human rights organizations. The law seems to be in part an angry
response to a report issued last year by the country's leading
human rights organization, which criticized police torture of
hundreds of villagers, including children, during a murder
investigation. The report, and the subsequent detention of two
members of the rights group, brought the government worldwide
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's old law on nongovernmental groups was restrictive, but
the new one is worse. It gives the government control over their
activities, the composition of their boards of directors and
whether they can get funds from overseas _ a financial lifeline for
many groups. The law is vague enough to bar any activity the
government considers political, and activists can go to prison for
violating the rules. Egyptian officials argue that anyone who wants
to engage in political activity can found a party. But for years
the government has rejected every citizen application to form a new
political party.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration spokesman has called the new law ``the
wrong direction.'' Egypt's president, Hosni Mubarak, will be
visiting the United States shortly and should hear this from
President Clinton as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
