<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS END THEIR LOSING STEAK, CLEMENS' AND JETER'S STREAKS AS WELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The hardest aspect of the New York Mets' turmoil,
manager Bobby Valentine said, was preparing for Sunday night's game
against Roger Clemens and the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Mets had spent 24 hours sorting through their
infinite personality conflicts, firing and hiring coaches and
assigning blame. Who had time to prepare?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they needed a distraction. Maybe it was better if they
didn't think about Clemens, because the Mets battered Clemens and
the Yankees, 7-2, before 56,294 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With a single victory, the Mets ended Clemens' streak of 20
consecutive victories and their own string of eight consecutive
losses; avoided a sweep at the hands of the Yankees, whom they will
host at Shea in July; and finished a seasonlong streak compiled by
Derek Jeter. The Yankees' shortstop had reached base in every game
this season before going 0 for 4 Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' Al Leiter, whose poor relationship with Bob Apodaca
reportedly was among the reasons for the dismissal of the pitching
coach, had the best outing of his generally terrible season. Staked
to a big lead early, Leiter (3-5) pitched seven strong innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first loss for Clemens (5-1) since May 29, 1998, when
he was pitching for the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Even in spring training, Clemens spoke of his tendency to let
adrenaline overcome him in the early innings, and of the importance
of harnessing his extra energy and using it to his advantage _ and
that's exactly what he seemed to be doing in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing fastballs clocked from 94 to 96 mph, perhaps his best
hard stuff of the season, Clemens whiffed two of the first three
batters he faced and moved into ninth place on the all-time list of
strikeouts, passing Ferguson Jenkins (3,192 strikeouts).
</P>
<P>
   With his second pitch of the second inning, however, Clemens
threw a two-seam fastball low in the strike zone and Mike Piazza
hit it over the head of the center fielder Bernie Williams for a
double. Robin Ventura pulled a hanging off-speed pitch into right
field for a single, with Piazza stopping at third base.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody out, but hardly a dire situation for a power pitcher like
Clemens, who has the ability to get a strikeout or two and wriggle
his way out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday night's game, opponents were batting just .220
with runners in scoring position against Clemens; last year, he
held opponents to a .176 average with 73 strikeouts in 233 at-bats
with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens needed an out, with Brian McRae and Bobby Bonilla coming
up, and then he would be in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   But that's when he started having trouble with John Shulock, the
home plate umpire.
</P>
<P>
   On a 2-2 count to McRae, Clemens aimed a fastball at the outside
corner and McRae took it. Clemens froze, anticipating a strikeout.
Shulock called it a ball, and Clemens began looking in at Shulock.
Two pitches later, Clemens walked McRae, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla ambled to the plate, having gone hitless in his last 20
at-bats with runners in scoring position, batting .161. As a
low-ball hitter, he was susceptible to Clemens' high, hard stuff,
falling behind, 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla took two balls to even the count before Clemens tried a
breaking ball, its trajectory a hump before thumping hip high into
the mitt of catcher Joe Girardi. Ball three, Shulock called,
prompting Clemens to stalk around the mound a bit, smirking some.
He threw another fastball to Bonilla, who pulled a liner down the
right-field line for a two-run double _ a fan reached out to touch
it.
</P>
<P>
   All that adrenaline Clemens is wary of appeared to get the best
of him thereafter, and his streak of 20 consecutive victories
quickly evaporated. After Clemens fell behind in the count, 3-1,
Benny Agbayani poked a broken bat single to right field and two
more runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   In the third John Olerud singled and Piazza smashed a two-run
homer and the Yankees' sweep _ a near certainty, it seemed, given
the Mets' turmoil and the fact that Clemens was pitching _ was not
to be.
</P>
<P>
   After a few more hits and another run, Clemens walked off, head
down, probably somewhat confused. He'd had such great stuff in the
first inning, and yet he lasted only 2 2/3 innings and was charged
with eight hits, two walks and seven runs, his earned run average
ballooning to 5.18.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, ramming his cut fastball in on the hands of the Yankees'
hitters, allowed just two infield hits in the first four innings,
and faltered only once.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a 7-0 lead in the bottom of the fifth, Leiter walked two
batters and allowed a two-run double. But he retired Knoblauch and
Jeter, and the Mets cruised thereafter.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
