<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER'S WORDS HAVE SOME KICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Anaheim Angels pitcher Tim Belcher still didn't
want to talk to reporters Sunday about Saturday's fight with Los
Angeles Dodgers pitcher Chan Ho Park, explaining to an Angels
spokesperson he didn't want to let his feelings cause him to say
something he might regret. But as he did Saturday, Belcher released
a statement through the team:
</P>
<P>
   ``Regarding (Park's) comments that my tag was too aggressive and
my language too foul, I'll say this ... HANG WITH 'EM! That phrase,
hard tags and men cursing have been a part of our game forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``When players and teams fight, there are certain unwritten
rules of engagement. His adolescent exception was to attempt to
kick my face with his spikes. My reaction was self-defense and
justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to my bigger concern, I pitched one very poor inning and
lost the game. It is difficult to judge what effect the fight had
on my pitching. One thing is for certain, however, I tired quickly
in the sixth and made very poor pitches and a couple of poor
decisions. I should have gone after (Eric) Karros more than I did
and should have started (Devon) White with something soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing Matt's (Walbeck) grand slam go for (naught) really
hurts me. Beyond that, I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins said his biggest concern was that
everyone came away healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to see that happen, especially in our situation,'' he
said. ``We can't afford to have anyone else hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins called Sunday's win big, considering the distractions of
the past few days. Besides the fight, there was clubhouse
dissension over Collins himself. A group of players met with
general manager Bill Bavasi last week to discuss concerns they had
with the way Collins manages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt walking around the clubhouse today that these guys were
ready to play,'' Collins said. ``One thing they realize is we've
all got the same name on our jerseys, every one of us. Regardless
of their feelings for each other or myself, they realize they have
to get the job done. Guys on the bench were patting each other on
the back ... it's a matter of moving past it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really lost focus, and I don't think the ballclub lost
focus,'' first baseman Mo Vaughn said. ``In this clubhouse it's
been very, very consistent in terms of what we want to do,
regardless of what's going on. The responsibility of how you play
is up to the players.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is another problem to overcome _ pitcher Omar Olivares
will miss his turn in the rotation Wednesday in San Francisco
because of a strained left hamstring. Olivares, who hurt the
hamstring trying to beat out an infield grounder Friday night, is
not expected to miss any other starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we've got to do is make sure he's OK because he's
active on the mound,'' Collins said. ``He fields his position and
moves around a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more of a worry for me,'' Olivares said. ``How's it
going to be if I have to run and cover first base?''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he'd like to bring back Belcher on three days rest
to replace Olivares. Belcher made 81 pitches in Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to let him have (Sunday) off, kick back and see how he
is (today),'' Collins said. ``If I can help it, I don't want to use
a guy out of the bullpen. If Tim can do it, we'll try to get him
out there and cut his pitches down.''
</P>
<P>
   If Belcher can't do it, Collins' options include relievers Scott
Schoeneweis, Mark Petkovsek and Shigetoshi Hasegawa, with
Schoeneweis the favorite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
