<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HUBBELL'S GHOST SURVIVES CLEMENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBO-YANKS-METS) 
(mk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most people are afraid of ghosts, but baseball people
cherish ghosts and the best players chase them.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago Mark McGwire, with 70 home runs, and Sammy Sosa,
with 66, caught and passed Roger Maris' ghost. And until Sunday
night, Roger Clemens of the Yankees had been chasing the ghost of
Carl Hubbell, whose 24-game winning streak for the New York Giants
in 1936 and 1937 is the major league record.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday night, the Mets, the descendants of those Giants,
stopped Clemens' streak at 20 victories, knocking him out in the
third inning of a 7-2 rout.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell's ghost was the spiritual ``winning pitcher'' Sunday
night, but throughout their winning streaks, Clemens and Hubbell's
ghosts were always more different than alike.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is right-handed, Hubbell was left-handed. Clemens
depends on his fastball, Hubbell thrived on his screwball. Clemens
seldom completes nine innings, Hubbell almost always did. Clemens
doesn't relieve, Hubbell occasionally did. In the space age,
Clemens' nickname is Rocket. In the Depression, Hubbell was known
as the Meal Ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Clemens, a five-time Cy Young award winner with 237
career victories, is baseball's dominant pitcher of the last
decade, Hubbell was the dominant pitcher in his era, the legend
best remembered for striking out Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Jimmie
Foxx, Al Simmons and Joe Cronin in order in the 1934 all-star game
at the Polo Grounds in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell finished the 1936 season with 16 straight victories,
then opened the 1937 season with eight more before being knocked
out in the fourth inning of a 10-3 loss to the Brooklyn Dodgers, in
the opener of a May 31 doubleheader at the Polo Grounds that
attracted 61,756.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won the pennant each year, but lost both World Series
to the Yankees. Hubbell's 1-1 record in the 1936 Series did not
count in the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never tried to set any records, or go for any kind of
record,'' the Hall of Famer once said of his streak. ``It just
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell had a 26-6 record with a 2.31 earned run average in
1936, a 22-8 record with a 3.20 ERA in 1937. Over his 16 seasons,
all with the Giants, he was 253-154 with a 2.97 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell's streak was much more consistent than Clemens' streak,
much more compact. Hubbell needed only 27 games for his 24
victories, winning 21 of 22 starts, with 19 complete games and only
one no-decision; he picked up his other three victories in five
relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In Clemens' 30 starts during his streak, he had only five
complete games and 10 no-decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens twice was lucky to be taken off the hook by the Yankees
when he didn't pitch well. Early this season he was shelled for
seven runs in three-plus innings against Baltimore, then five runs
in two innings against Texas, but had no decision each time.
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens was shown a breakdown of Hubbell's streak, as
unearthed by the Elias Sports Bureau, he was impressed. ``Those 19
complete games, that's awesome,'' Clemens said. ``And didn't they
just have four starters in those days?''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching rotations were like that then; Hubbell usually started
with three days' rest, sometimes two or four. When Giants manager
Bill Terry needed a pitcher to lock up a victory, he occasionally
brought Hubbell in from the bullpen _ a role that Clemens has never
had with the Red Sox, the Blue Jays or the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I relieved maybe once in Boston,'' Clemens said. ``I
think I was coming back from something.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of expansion and interleague play, Clemens defeated 12
teams during his streak, including Detroit four times. In Hubbell's
era, there were only seven other National League teams. During his
streak, he had five victories over Cincinnati (two in relief); four
over St. Louis (one in relief), Chicago and Philadelphia; three
over Brooklyn and Pittsburgh; and one over the Boston Braves. He
outpitched Dizzy Dean of the Cardinals three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``What jumps out at me about Hubbell's streak are those 19
complete games,'' said Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching
coach. ``Those complete games take it out of you _ 19 complete
games in 22 starts, that's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The current Yankees, for example, haven't had a complete game
since last Sept. 14 when Orlando `El Duque' Hernandez stopped the
Red Sox, 3-0, at Yankee Stadium. In today's baseball, complete
games are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five and two-thirds,'' said Don Zimmer, the Yankees' bench
coach. ``That's now considered a quality start.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Roger Clemens the night his streak ended, two and
two-thirds innings can't even be considered a quality loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
