<HEADER>
A5318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NY     06-07 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN THE SOUND OF A DIAL TONE IS OMINOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leo Mondale has been working on the project for years, but he
still sounds a little awe-struck. ``This is quite a marvel,'' he
says. ``We do have truly global coverage. We can serve customers at
the poles, in the Himalayas, in the suburbs, wherever'' regular
cellular phones cannot.
</P>
<P>
   That vision, of the truly universal phone, is now reality.
Iridium, the company of which Mondale is chief financial officer,
proudly reported last month that a woman named Karla Wheelock had
used an Iridium satellite phone to call her mother in Mexico _ from
the top of Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Everest market is not a very large one, at
least not when measured in terms of demand for telephone service.
Investors, who only a year ago were in love with Iridium, now
dismiss it as a failure. Its financial plans were based on having
at least 300,000 subscribers by now. It has about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Iridium saga is not over. The company probably will come up
with the money it needs to keep operating, and it may yet garner
many more customers than it has. But its plight is merely one of
the most obvious indications of the fact that the past several
years have seen an explosion of investment in the
telecommunications industry. A plethora of companies are putting up
new wireless systems, installing trans-Atlantic cables, building
competitive local-access phone companies or installing domestic
long-distance systems.
</P>
<P>
   That investment reflects rapid expansion in the
telecommunications market as demand has soared for fax, cellular
and Internet services. Deregulation has made it possible to compete
with individual parts of the big phone companies' businesses.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of those investments have panned out _ or at least
have not yet gone bad. Some of them have proved to be bonanzas,
usually because bigger companies have taken over smaller ones. But
Iridium is far from being the only one in trouble. Seven years ago,
there were almost no junk-bond issues from the telecommunications
industry. Now, they make up 15 percent of junk bonds outstanding _
and 20 percent of such bonds in default.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new phone ventures have the same basic plan: invest
a lot of money building a system. Then, when it is up and running,
it becomes a money machine as customers pay for services that cost
little to provide once the infrastructure is in.
</P>
<P>
   The catch comes in getting enough money from the customers.
Already, prices for cellular service are falling as more and more
companies enter the market, and there are still a lot of systems
under construction. Iridium, whose phones connect to a network of
satellites in areas where cellular service is not available,
assumed customers would pay a premium over the old price of
cellular service. But the new cellular price is far lower, and
Iridium is clearly going to have to slash prices. It has brought in
a new chief executive and a new head of marketing. Mondale's
comments came at a meeting with analysts where he said the company
hoped to avoid filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   There is a game of financial chicken going on now at Iridium,
with the various parties that invested in the company, including
banks, phone companies and Motorola, whose technology is being
used, trying to get others to put up the hundreds of millions
needed to keep it going. In the end, with billions already
invested, the money will probably be found. Customers will benefit
while investors and lenders take losses.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street views Iridium's problems as exceptional, and money
continues to pour into new telecommunications ventures. The
assumption seems to be that the explosion of data transmission
means there cannot be too much fiber-optic cable. That assumption
is likely to be proved wrong within a few years, with a glut that
drives down prices.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, investors may remember that the history of
technology investing is littered with such periods, when expected
profits vanish due to overcapacity or obsolescence or both, and may
start to flee.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a dial tone _ or, to be specific, the
availability of too many such tones _ could be the sound that ends
the investment boom in communications technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
