<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5361 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALKER-AZR &LR;      06-07 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALKER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALKING CASE ADDS `NERD' DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BY JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Scott Falater's defense team isn't just putting on a
sleepwalking defense in the former Motorola engineer's murder
trial, which has focused national attention on Phoenix's Maricopa
County courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is also defending Falater as too mild-mannered and
controlled _ too much of a nerd _ to have deliberately stabbed his
wife to death.
</P>
<P>
   The nerd defense in this strangest of cases began to emerge two
weeks ago in defense attorney Michael Kimerer's opening statement.
He is asking the jury to accept this courtroom equation:
Sleepwalker plus nerd does not equal murderer.
</P>
<P>
   When Falater was a schoolboy near Chicago, Kimerer said, ``he
was thought of as being kind of a nerd.'' He had preferred science
to sports, liked chemistry sets and ham radio, tended a paper
route, and periodically wet his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trial's opening, the nerd defense has come up
repeatedly in a trial spawned by that horrific night in December
1997 when Falater admittedly stabbed his wife 44 times with a
hunting knife, dragged her into the backyard pool and then stashed
his bloody clothing before police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer has elicited descriptions of Falater-as-nerd from
several defense witnesses. They have also helped the defense
portray the 43-year-old defendant as a dedicated husband and
father, devout Mormon and respected engineer at Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of nerdy,'' 17-year-old daughter Megan testified.
``He plays around with his ham radio, but he's very friendly and
nice to all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater's sister also joined in. When Kimerer asked if she had
considered her brother to be a nerd, Laura Healy quickly answered,
``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Falater is to win acquittal, the defense must convince the
jury that the only explanation for the savage attack by such a
mild-mannered man was that Falater's overactive brain was asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the brain was awake, Kimerer acknowledges, but not the
part responsible for conscious thought and deliberate action.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer says the attack makes no sense because Falater had no
motive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just no rhyme or reason why Scott Falater would have
killed the woman that he loved more than anything else in the
world,'' said Kimerer. Sleepwalking is the only explanation that
makes sense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer established last week that Falater has a history of
sleepwalking. Falater's parents testified that they were once
amused by his infrequent late-night amblings, including the time
that he walked stark naked into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Healy testified about an incident that occurred when Scott was a
20-year-old student in Illinois grappling with the stress of final
exams and his pending marriage to Yarmila. She said he responded
furiously when she tried to block him from sleepwalking out a
kitchen door.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lifted me up and just tossed me through the air,'' Healy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer's first expert witness, Dr. Janet Tatman, told the jury
that violence is common among sleepwalkers, especially when they
are performing some purposeful activity.
</P>
<P>
   Tatman supported Kimerer's claim that Falater's deadly
sleepwalking episode was triggered by stress and sleep deprivation.
Several of Falater's former colleagues testified that the failure
of a new Motorola computer chip had put him under tremendous
strain. Falater coordinated the design, manufacture and marketing
of the chip.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer says Falater came home from work that fateful night in
1997, had a pleasant dinner with Yarmila and their two children,
watched TV, planned the next morning's seminary class at his
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point, Kimerer's scenario is supported by the
testimony of the two Falater children. He then relies on Falater's
recollection to say that his client attempted briefly to fix a
defective swimming pool pump. Unsuccessful, Falater gave up, kissed
Yarmila good night as she lay on the living room couch and went
upstairs to bed, the attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Kimerer's scenario is based partly on consultation
with sleepwalking experts, but mostly on what he regards as the
best explanation of the death of Yarmila Falater.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer says Falater was so exhausted that he fell immediately
into a deep sleep, the very stage of consciousness that is the
starting point for sleepwalking. But soon, probably within a half
hour, he arose from bed, subconsciously obsessed with fixing the
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Falater probably attacked his wife because she interfered as he
was using a hunting knife to dig an O-ring out of the pool pump,
Kimerer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The belief is that Yarmila went outside and said something or
touched him and he immediately went into a rage, a total frenzy and
stabbed her 44 times,'' he told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he did not commit the crime of premeditated murder because
he had no conscious awareness of what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kimerer and co-counsel Lori Voepel are successful with those
equations, Scott Falater, admitted killer, will walk out of
Maricopa County Superior Court a free man.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Juan Martinez, of course, has other ideas. He is
attempting to prove that Falater is a coldblooded murderer. He says
the attack was not an irrational eruption in the calm landscape of
a north Phoenix home, but the deliberate act of an increasingly
desperate man whose marriage had been crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has laid out the killing in grim detail,
describing a complex series of events that apparently unfolded over
a period of about 30 minutes before police received a 911 call at
10:57 p.m. The scenario relies on the autopsy report, an eyewitness
to some of the events, and the police report.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said Falater stabbed Yarmila 44 times, driving some of
the blows to the hilt of the hunting knife with a 4-inch blade and
slashing her hands as she tried to fight him off.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a scenario not disputed by the defense, Falater changed
out of his bloody clothes, changed into pajamas and a T-shirt, put
on a pair of gloves, dragged Yarmila a few yards to the pool,
rolled her in and held her head under.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he went back into the house, upstairs to the bedroom
and the bathroom, and then walked downstairs, where Phoenix police
arrested him at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez says one of the most telling pieces of evidence is that
Falater stashed his bloody clothes in the back of his Volvo. But
Kimerer says Falater was simply returning the clothes to where he
always kept them, for use in case he broke down.
</P>
<P>
   The defense continues today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
