<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY TV CAN'T BE  SHACKLED 
 JUST IMAGINE THIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (RETRANSMITTING - WAS ALSO SENT MAY 30) ``The scene is repeated
every day across America: Police officers armed with warrants burst
into a house in search of a quarry.
</P>
<P>
   When a camera crew is invited to follow, the images often make
powerful television, appearing on COPS, LAPD: Life on the Beat and
the Spanish-language program Placas (Shields), among others.
</P>
<P>
   But such reality TV shows may find police less welcoming
following two Supreme Court decisions allowing police to be sued
financially over the filming of arrests or searches on private
property. The high court ruled that so-called ``media ride-alongs''
may violate the Constitution's Fourth Amendment ban on unreasonable
searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this may dampen officers' desire to take media with
them. This is one more thing on the side of `is it worth it?' ''
said Penny Parrish, spokeswoman for the Minneapolis Police
Department.'' _The Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   To: Network Affiliates
</P>
<P>
   From: The Fox Network
</P>
<P>
   Re: Supreme Court Ruling
</P>
<P>
   To whom it may concern:
</P>
<P>
   By now you doubtless have read or heard about the Supreme Court
decisions involving media ride-alongs with police which, on first
glance, would appear to cripple the very foundation upon which our
popular ``reality'' shows are based.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Now is not the time to panic. Instead, this is the
time for creative thinking. When high winds and bad weather forced
Robbie Knievel to call off his first Grand Canyon Death Jump, did
we fold the tent and wait until the next Sweeps period? Certainly
not _ we simply rescheduled a second Death Jump for the end of May
Sweeps. As our nightly lineup has proved so often, if it's tacky
enough, millions of people will watch it.
</P>
<P>
   Please take a look at the following shows we have penciled in
for the fall lineup. We're excited, and hope you will be, too.
</P>
<P>
   `` Krispy Kreme: Life on the Sweets'' _ Gritty look at what goes
on inside the popular donut shop when the ``hot donuts'' sign
lights up late at night. Plenty of grainy, jumpy, hand-held camera
shots of the donuts coming off the conveyer belt, the crowd
gathering at the cash register and the sense of relief expressed
(through close-ups) by employees at enjoying near-24-hour
unofficial police protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGruff: All Bark, All Bite'' _ No-holds-barred,
documentary-style feature showing a day in the life of the Crime
Dog. Nothing is out-of-bounds, as the in-school question-and-answer
segment shows. (``Do you have a dog girlfriend?'' one third-grader
asks. ``Have you had your shots?'' wonders another.) Real inside
stuff; McGruff, for instance, unwinds at one point and reveals the
effects of job pressure while lapping pensively at a small bowl of
scotch. Includes hilarious outtake footage of McGruff clowning
around with oversize fire hydrant (to be shown under closing
credits).
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovely Rita, Meter Maid'' _ (Title tentative; still checking
for permission. Possible alternate: ``Ticket to Ride,'' though
similar licensing problems may arise.) Touching weekly stories of
the most misunderstood members of the Thin Blue Line. Follows the
brave men and women in their little scooters as they chalk tires,
check their watches and hand out tickets. Short bios of each week's
subjects. WARNING: Extremely graphic language directed at officers
by motorists. Suggest scheduling after 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Thinner Blue Line: Police Explorers'' _ Unflinching look at
teens who hope to further their dream of becoming police officers
by participating in the community volunteer program. Each week we
follow different Explorers as they struggle with classic on-the-job
challenges posed by civilians _ indifference, ridicule and
downright hostility _ as well as acne, dating woes and other teen
problems. NOTE: Will be edited to downplay subjects' repeated
references to how much they love guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Stories of the Highway Patrol Motor Pool'' _ The beauty
here is in the access. Inside footage of oil changes, brake jobs,
siren repair, etc. Nothing is off-limits _ the coffee breaks, the
gossip sessions, nothing. In short, the tears, the laughter and the
personal phone calls made on company time. Massive crossover
appeal. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5365 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONY-AWARDS-2TAKES-NY     06-07 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVAL OF `DEATH OF A SALESMAN' TAKES 4 TONY AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TONY-WINNERS) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ And may the best salesman win.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the closest races of this year's theater season, Brian
Dennehy won the Tony Award Sunday night for best actor in a play
for his portrayal of Willy Loman in ``Death of a Salesman,''
beating out the other favorite, Kevin Spacey, who was nominated for
his performance as Hickey in ``The Iceman Cometh.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy concluded his acceptance remarks by thanking the
playwright, Arthur Miller, as well as the crowd: ``Thank you for
`Death of a Salesman,' Arthur, thank you for Willy Loman and thank
you for this.''
</P>
<P>
   In what many are calling the season of the straight play, a
season that put the work of Tennessee Williams, Miller and Eugene
O'Neill on Broadway at the same time, ``Death of a Salesman'' raked
in the awards, including best revival of a play, at the 53rd annual
Tony ceremony at the Gershwin Theater here.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Falls of ``Salesman'' won for best director and Elizabeth
Franz won for best featured actress for her new, steely take on the
wife of Willy Loman. Topping it off, Miller received a special Tony
Award for lifetime achievement.
</P>
<P>
   In his acceptance speech, Miller said that if plays like
``Iceman'' and ``Salesman'' were received in the mail by producers
today, ``they would be unlikely to show up on a Broadway stage,''
rejected as too financially risky.
</P>
<P>
   He also encouraged the crowd to welcome a new generation of
American playwrights. One such young American playwright took home
the Tony Sunday night for best new play: Warren Leight for ``Side
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man,'' which has been struggling to fill the theater
lately, received another welcome boost from a Tony Award for Frank
Wood as best featured actor in a play for his performance as a
weary jazz musician.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising victory, the British choreographer Matthew
Bourne won for best director of a musical for his unorthodox
version of ``Swan Lake,'' featuring male swans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swan Lake'' had been ruled ineligible for consideration as
best musical by the Tony Administration Committee this spring.
``I'm absolutely astonished,'' Bourne said in his acceptance
speech. ``Best director of a musical that's not even a musical.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourne also won the award for best choreography, thanking ``the
composer of probably the greatest score on Broadway this or any
year, Tchaikovsky.''
</P>
<P>
   The costume designer of ``Swan Lake,'' Lez Brotherston, also
received a Tony award.
</P>
<P>
   It was a triumphant night for ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' which won
the Tony for best musical revival as well as for best actress in a
musical, Bernadette Peters.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' lost to ``Annie,''
two of its featured actors received Tonys Sunday night: Kristin
Chenoweth, who plays Sally, and Roger Bart, who plays Snoopy.
</P>
<P>
   The awards could offer a welcome lift to ``Charlie Brown,''
which has also been hanging on at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   In a race that some considered a test of art versus commerce,
``Fosse'' won for best musical, beating out the other leading
contender, ``Parade,'' which closed in February at Lincoln Center
Theater in the wake of mixed reviews and the financial troubles of
its co-producer, Livent. ``Fosse'' also won Tonys for lighting
design and orchestrations.
</P>
<P>
   Because a Tony Award can mean box office success as well as
artistic excellence, some argued that only ``Fosse'' was in a
position to benefit financially, particularly on the road, since
``Parade'' is no longer running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade,'' the story of the 1915 lynching of Leo Frank, a
Jewish factory supervisor, did earn its share of important prizes,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The award for best book went to ``Parade's'' author, Alfred
Uhry, best known for his play ``Driving Miss Daisy.''
</P>
<P>
   In his acceptance speech, Uhry announced that the musical would
start a yearlong tour in June in Atlanta and, ``Who knows, look for
us maybe to return to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   And the award for best score went to Jason Robert Brown, the
28-year-old composer of ``Parade.'' Brown thanked Harold Prince,
the director of ``Parade,'' for giving him the opportunity to write
his first musical score. (He also thanked his ``wonderful
supportive family _ no matter what I say in therapy.'') ``Parade''
was not the only production to win awards posthumously. Martin
Short won for best leading actor in a musical for his off-the-wall
performance in ``Little Me,'' which closed in February.
</P>
<P>
   In his reliably funny acceptance speech, Short said, ``Please be
seated'' when no one was standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people I could thank and should,'' Short
continued, ``but the reality is, I did it all myself.''
</P>
<P>
   As predicted, Dame Judi Dench won the Tony for best performance
by an actress in a play for her work in David Hare's ``Amy's
View,'' which marked Dame Judi's return to the New York stage after
40 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a category that had the designer Bob Crowley competing
against himself for his creations of a weathered bar in ``The
Iceman Cometh'' and his ethereal Illyria in ``Twelfth Night,'' the
award for scenic design went to Richard Hoover for his cold,
clanging cellblock in ``Not About Nightingales.'' The play by a
young Williams was recently unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to talk about a ghost in this room _ Tennessee,''
Hoover said, ``and I'm sure he's smiling right now, as I am
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony's second two hours opened with ``There's No
Business Like Show Business,'' from ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' and
featured scenes from the other nominated musicals, including ``The
Civil War'' and ``Fosse.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While some critics have bemoaned what they described as a dearth
of exciting work on Broadway this season, box office revenue and
attendance hit new records. Total grosses rose to more than $588
million, up 5.5 percent over last year, according to Variety, and
attendance reached nearly 12 million, a 2.9 percent jump.
Nevertheless, the increases were smaller than those of last year,
when box office rose 11.6 percent and attendance 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The American Theater Wing's 53rd annual Antoinette Perry Awards,
known as the Tonys, were named for Ms. Perry, an actress, director
and producer who died in 1946 after having been one of the leaders
of the wing, a theater service organization. The awards were first
presented in 1947 and first broadcast nationally in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   This year's nominees, announced on May 3, were selected by a
28-member committee. The 812 Tony voters, made up of theater
professionals and journalists, cast ballots in 21 categories. The
Tonys are presented by the wing and the League of American Theaters
and Producers, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The first hour of the ceremony, broadcast on PBS, included a
special Tony Award for regional theater, a grant of $25,000, which
went to the Crossroads Theater in New Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two hours of the presentation were shown on CBS
and featured the presentation of 12 awards.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, the ceremony received increased publicity
and ratings because it had Rosie O'Donnell as host and was held at
Radio City Music Hall. This year, Ms. O'Donnell said she was unable
to do the awards and the ceremony instead featured various
presenters.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's event, however, had its share of star power, with
presenters such as Phylicia Rashad, Chita Rivera and Laurence
Fishburne. Other celebrities included Bea Arthur, Calista
Flockhart, Julie Andrews, Carol Burnett, Alec Baldwin, Kevin Kline,
William Hurt, Sarah Jessica Parker and Matthew Broderick.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more interesting pairings were the past and current
Hickeys, Spacey and Jason Robards; and Swoosie Kurtz and Ben
Stiller, who appeared together in ``House of Blue Leaves'' in 1986,
for which Ms. Kurtz won a Tony. Hare and Dame Judi also presented
together; Hare has three shows on Broadway this season, including
``Amy's View,'' which features Dame Judi, and ``Via Dolorosa,'' his
one-man play about Israel, in which he stars. None of his works
were nominated as plays.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Miller, special Tony Awards went to the actress
Uta Hagen and to the production ``Fool Moon,'' a series of mimed
sketches created by and starring Bill Irwin and David Shiner, that
had been to Broadway twice before, in 1993 and 1995, and returned
last fall for a limited engagement.
</P>
<P>
   A special award for lifetime achievement was given to Isabelle
Stevenson, who served as president of the wing from 1966 until last
year, when she became chairwoman and was succeeded as president by
Roy Somlyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood on the sidelines for half a century and watched other
people receive Tony Awards,'' Ms. Stevenson said in her acceptance
remarks, ``and now at last I get my own.''
</P>
<P>
   The wing offers performances in hospitals and schools and a
series of seminars about the theater that are broadcast by the City
University of New York's educational cable television station.
</P>
<P>
   The wing was founded in 1917, when a group of women organized to
aid war relief. In addition to clothing and food collection
centers, Stage Women's War Relief, as it was then known,
established a canteen for servicemen on Broadway, and began to send
entertainers where they were needed. In the 1940s, the group was
renamed the American Theater Wing War Service and was a branch of
the British War Relief Society. After Pearl Harbor, the wing became
an independent organization perhaps most famous for its Stage Door
Canteens.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become an annual rite of Tony season, this year had
its share of prenomination confusion and controversy. The producers
of ``Salesman'' successfully petitioned the Tony administration
committee to have Ms. Franz considered as a featured rather than
leading actress because of the stiff competition from Dame Judi and
from Zoe Wanamaker, who starred in ``Electra.''
</P>
<P>
   And although the revised book of ``Annie Get Your Gun'' was
deemed Tony-eligible, the revised book of ``You're a Good Man,
Charlie Brown'' was not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
