<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-BLAZERS-HNS     06-07 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-BLAZERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PORTLAND, Ore. _ The Portland Trail Blazers made their little run,
took their little lead and allowed themselves a moment to fool
themselves one last time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The masses stuffed into the Rose Garden danced and sang. The
Trail Blazers seemed ready to all but disrobe as they did to
celebrate their second-round victory that would be their last.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs watched this, and center David Robinson
said they smiled, knowing what would come, almost choosing the way
to best fly into the NBA Finals for the first time in franchise
history. They could have waited for the Blazers to self-destruct
under the weight of their foolishness. They could have won in the
final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But as if to fittingly mark the occasion of their remarkable
flight to the Finals, the Spurs calmly kicked it into another gear
Sunday and more than blew past the exposed Trail Blazers 94-80.
</P>
<P>
   With sweeps of the conference semifinals and finals, the NBA's
first such feat of the decade, the Spurs began to lap the league, a
spectacular fourth quarter Sunday offering a reminder while they
wait for a challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for whoever comes out of the East,'' Spurs guard
Mario Elie said.
</P>
<P>
   But before they consider the Knicks or Pacers, the Spurs
dismissed the Trail Blazers with a performance more impressive than
even their 31-5 finish to the regular season or an 11-1 playoff
record.
</P>
<P>
   After a 22-point win Friday, the Spurs shrugged off the Blazers'
third-quarter run and rolled up a 19-point lead, dominating the
fourth quarter before Spurs coach Gregg Popovich, like a junior
high coach, could let all the fellows play for the fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we won, we proved something,'' Spurs forward Sean
Elliott said, as if the consecutive sweeps of the prodigious
talents of the Blazers and Lakers did not. ``We proved we're the
best team out there. We're not there yet. We still have a lot ahead
of us. We just need four more.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Elliott meant four more wins, the way the Spurs
finished off the Trail Blazers, he could have accurately meant they
would need just four more games to take an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the Blazers took their lead, the Spurs scored on
10 consecutive trips down the floor. While the Blazers quickly
reverted to desperate one-on-one moves and long jumpers, the Spurs
converted five consecutive layups, dunks or tips.
</P>
<P>
   They worked off one another confidently, easily, coming from
every direction and scoring as if they had been only waiting for
the right moment.
</P>
<P>
   In a span of 3{ minutes the Spurs put together a 17-4 run to an
81-67 lead, and within the first five minutes of the fourth quarter
Elliott, Robinson, Jaren Jackson, Tim Duncan and Avery Johnson
scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the way we did it shows how awesome our team is,'' Duncan
said. ``Everybody made a big play. A.J. Sean. Myself. Dave. Jaren.
We just read the defense and made a great play. People kept making
plays down the stretch, and that's what makes a championship
team.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the lottery-pick talent of the Blazers, the Spurs proved
more well-rounded, deep and balanced. It was not just that the
Spurs' bench outscored the Blazers' bench 23-10. Rather than simply
ride Duncan as they had to sweep the Lakers, the Spurs got whatever
they needed from a variety of sources.
</P>
<P>
   Everything started with Robinson and Duncan inside, and they
finished with 38 points. But with the Blazers determined to send
whatever defensive attention was necessary to force the other Spurs
to beat them, Johnson finished with 15, his fourth consecutive game
in double figures. Elliott had 16. And Jackson came off the bench
to make three fourth-quarter treys and score 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers seemed only to get in each other's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have togetherness and cohesion and a belief and the
desire to just win, and win only, then you'll be in the Spurs'
locker room,'' Portland guard Greg Anthony said. ``If you have any
other issues at hand, then those sometimes will dictate and
determine your fate. It's obviously no secret that we've had
issues, and that's so unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very good basketball team. They're playing as well
as anybody. It's almost as if they're destined.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs seemed to feel that way, celebrating with a few hugs
and high-fives but relatively quietly, with no wild dances to
remind of the Trail Blazers' revelry after beating the Jazz. No
champagne, no locker-room shouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 10 long years, but it's just what I imagined it
would be like,'' Robinson said. ``It's what I dream about. It just
feels good to get to where you want to be. We've grown a lot. I
feel good about what we have accomplished, and now we've got our
sights set on the next goal.''
</P>
<P>
   They might as well, having accomplished more than any Spurs team
ever has, and with the sweeps, more than even they expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we could beat these teams, but sweeps? No,'' Spurs
owner Peter Holt said. ``It's been 26 years we've been (in San
Antonio). Now we're going. This is beautiful. Beautiful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
