<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-07 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PORTLAND, Ore. _ After all the years and all of the characters who
were saltier than the rim on a margarita glass, it is more than a
bit ironic that the group of Spurs who at long last reached the NBA
Finals had the personality to match their locker-room celebration
drink of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water,'' said point guard and lightning rod Avery Johnson.
``We're just a group of working men who get to take a break now.
You get yourself a little sip and then get back to the job. There's
still work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Though how much of it remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   As the playoffs have progressed, so have the Spurs, becoming the
basketball version of an avalanche hurtling down a mountainside
burying every village in its path.
</P>
<P>
   They swept the Lakers. They swept the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   They started out the season 6-8 and have lost only six games
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's June,'' Mario Elie said. ``Do you realize how impressive
that is?''
</P>
<P>
   Impressive enough to make you wonder what might have happened if
the Chicago dynasty and Michael Jordan hadn't scattered into the
hoop winds?
</P>
<P>
   In none of their six championship seasons did the Bulls ever
sweep both the second and third rounds of the playoffs. In none of
their climbs to the top of the heap did the Bulls ever have to deal
with a two-headed front-line monster like Tim Duncan and David
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   In South Texas, just call them Los Toros.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could bring Chicago on, and I'd take my chances,'' Elie
said. ``I look at all of those championships won by the Bulls, and
they never really had to go through a team with a strong low-post
game. That's why I thought that our team in Houston in '97 with
Charles (Barkley) and Dream (Hakeem Olajuwon) could have given the
Bulls all they could handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're talking about this team with these two guys, Dave
and Tim, and I'm telling you we wouldn't give anything up. The only
mismatch out there on the floor would be me trying to guard Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, man, this is a team that can stand up to
anybody and do so many things to take you out of your game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are able to do it because they have Robinson _ a past
MVP _ and Duncan _ a future MVP _ and the ability to smother
offenses like a wet blanket thrown onto a campfire.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a coincidence that the high-profile offense of the
Lakers took a nose dive against the Spurs. And it is not
coincidence that the red-hot Blazers went south as well.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bit strange, though, to think of the Spurs and their
history of great offensive performers finally making it to the
Finals because this team works on all of the solid fundamental
parts of the game. And defense.
</P>
<P>
   The victory run this spring has been payback for all of the
heartbreak of the past. For the fancy finger rolls by the Iceman,
George Gervin, that couldn't carry them quite far enough. For the
skywalking antics of Larry Kenon and the slick moves of James Silas
and the sharpshooting of Louie Dampier that came up short.
</P>
<P>
   This was a makeup for Johnny Moore's bout with desert fever that
helped sidetrack a Spurs team. It was redemption for Rod
Strickland's ill-fated over-the-head pass and for Robinson getting
torched by Olajuwon in that fateful 1995 playoff meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some disappointments for those of us who have
been around the team for some years,'' Johnson said. ``In some
seasons, I always thought we were missing a little bit of depth or
something. In 1995, I did believe we had a team that was capable of
going all the way. That team did have all of the pieces, and to
lose to Houston really hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this team, well, just look at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at the way the Spurs kept their heads down and focused on
the task again Sunday. They withstood an early 8-0 blast by the
Blazers and then saw Portland tiptoe back to take a 59-58 lead on a
runner by Damon Stoudamire with 1:35 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've liked about this team is we just play for minutes
one through 48,'' coach Gregg Popovich said. ``We don't worry about
what's going on with the other team or what they're doing. We just
keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what happened when the Blazers pushed them. The Spurs
responded by taking the ball to the basket and taking the game and
the season to Portland. They were Sean Elliott going inside and
Duncan and Robinson following. They scored on 10 of their first 12
possessions of the fourth quarter and were on their way to a new
place, a different place.
</P>
<P>
   After three years in the ABA and 23 seasons in the NBA, the
Spurs who were always known for being hotter than jalapenos are
playing for the whole enchilada with a cool, cool group.
</P>
<P>
   Los Toros.
</P>
<P>
   Still water runs deep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
