<HEADER>
A5381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-TWINS-HNS &LR;      06-07 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TWINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MINNEAPOLIS _ When asked to describe Sunday's lopsided 13-6 loss to
the Minnesota Twins in one word, Tim Bogar had trouble coming up
with a response.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I might have to invent one,'' the Astros shortstop said. ``How
about ugly? Has anybody used that word? It was just flat-out ugly.
I've always been told if you're going to lose, lose quickly. This
one felt like a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   After Minnesota scored the most runs of any Astros opponent in
three years, words _ and explanations _ were hard to come by in the
Astros' clubhouse. Every pitch the Twins saw seemingly turned into
a hit. And everything that possibly could go wrong for the Astros
did.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros committed three errors, had two wild pitches and a
passed ball, gave up 16 hits and allowed four stolen bases _
through the first five innings.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Twins were done Sunday, every Minnesota starter
had at least two hits, catcher Javier Valentin came within a single
of the cycle, and the Astros' pitching staff looked like it had
just gone nine rounds with Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a TKO.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros delivered the first of many blows in the game,
knocking Twins starter LaTroy Hawkins out after only two innings.
But from that point, the Astros became Minnesota's personal
punching bag, stumbling around on defense while making the Twins'
season-high 21-hit outburst look all too easy.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 runs were the most allowed by the Astros since Colorado
scored 14 on June 6, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very sloppy start defensively, and we could never
turn the momentum,'' said Astros manager Larry Dierker, who watched
the Twins score nine consecutive runs to wipe out a 4-2 deficit.
``We didn't pitch real well. You're not going to win many games
when you are behind in the count. It was just a long day. I don't
think anybody enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you happened to be the Twins, who caught the
breaks and found the holes at just the right times. And for a team
that had lost four consecutive games, nine of its past 10 and 15 of
its past 20, a little luck never hurts.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Astros errors in the first inning led to the Twins'
first two runs. Alex Diaz, making his sixth start in left field,
bobbled a single by Brent Gates that tied the game at 1, and two
batters later catcher Paul Bako misplayed a high chopper in front
of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Minnesota's Ron Coomer hit a home run that
bounced off center fielder Richard Hidalgo's glove and over the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad, bad game,'' Bako said. ``The only thing good to
come out of it is it only counts for one loss. It seemed like so
long when we were out there. It just drained everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin finished 3-for-5, needing a single in his final at-bat
in the eighth inning to become the first Twins player to hit for
the cycle since Kirby Puckett on Aug. 1, 1986. He flied out to left
field. Valentin tripled in the second, homered in the fourth and
doubled in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates were kidding me that if I hit it to the wall I
should have pulled a hammy (hamstring) or missed first base and had
to go back,'' Valentin said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates and Todd Walker each had three hits for the Twins, who had
lost a pair of one-run games to the National League Central leaders
to start the interleague series.
</P>
<P>
   Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell went 3-for-3, including his
17th home run of the season and a fly-ball single off the Metrodome
roof. Russ Johnson hit his first home run since being called up
from the minors April 27, and Craig Biggio had a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   That was the extent of the damage by the Astros, who managed
only two runs off three Twins relievers over the final 7 innings.
Benj Sampson (1-0) pitched 3 scoreless innings in relief of Hawkins
to pick up the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, righthander Sean Bergman (3-2), who shut out
Milwaukee last Tuesday, lasted only 3 innings in his shortest
outing of the season for the Astros. He gave up 11 hits and six
runs, tying season highs set against Pittsburgh on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' bullpen struggled for the second straight day. Jeff
McCurry and Brian Williams combined to allow seven runs and 10 hits
in 4 innings. In the past two games, the Astros' relief corps has
surrendered 11 runs and 16 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were swinging, and everything they hit was finding
holes,'' Williams said. ``All you can try and do is make the
pitches. It seemed like every ball they hit was between first and
second base. I just went out there trying to shut them down and
keep the game close. I didn't end up doing that. I'm not happy with
it. I really don't know what to say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros held the lead briefly after scoring four runs during
the first two innings to send Hawkins to his early exit. Hawkins
allowed four runs on five hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, the Twins' fortunes changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes sometimes,'' Bogar said. ``It was one
of those days where we really didn't have a chance no matter what
we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
