<HEADER>
A5383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-HNS &LR;      06-07 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PARIS _ Trying, but failing, to fight back tears, Andre Agassi had
no explanation for what happened to him Sunday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the staggering emotion of the moment, he couldn't divulge why
he started so badly or how he could turn himself around so
completely. It was impossible for him to say how he almost lost the
French Open final, or how he found a way to will himself to win it,
thus completing the fifth career Grand Slam in men's tennis
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Agassi said. ``I really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically speaking, the reason was simple. He couldn't time a
ball to save his life for two cold, blustery sets, but once he
found his groove, it would be all blue skies. Indeed, the sun was
sparkling brightly on the Coupe Musketeers as Agassi held it aloft,
celebrating the most compelling, significant, surprising and
satisfying victory of his hot-and-cold, up-and-down career.
</P>
<P>
   ``My greatest moment ever on a tennis court,'' Agassi called the
1-6, 2-6, 6-4, 6-3, 6-4 comeback of a lifetime against Andrei
Medvedev. This from a guy who won Wimbledon in 1992, the U.S. Open
in '94 and the Australian Open in '95. But also a guy whose ranking
had sunk to 140th in the world two summers ago, when he nursed a
sore shoulder and tried to make a new marriage _ now doomed _ work.
</P>
<P>
   And who, in back-to-back French finals almost a decade ago
(1990-91), against Andres Gomez and then Jim Courier, had gone in
as the favorite and failed to close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean certainly the accomplishment of winning every Slam
speaks for itself,'' Agassi said, ``and accomplishing it on the
clay that has been a big obstacle for me, psychologically and
emotionally. There were so many reasons to be overwhelmed at that
moment (the end of the match), I don't know if I'll ever be able to
put words to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've done is astonishing on a certain level. This is the
greatest thing I could ever accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, seeded 13th and ranked 14th before this tournament,
jumps to No. 4 in the world with the victory; the 100th-ranked
Medvedev cracks the top 30 again. The 24-year-old Ukrainian was
trying to become the lowest-ranked player of the Open era to win a
Slam. But he had bet friends in Germany he would be in the top 50
by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won 100 marks from them,'' Medvedev said.
</P>
<P>
   He also won renewed respect for his game, which had slumped
since a semifinal appearance here in 1993 launched his rapid rise
to No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I made him work for the victory,'' Medvedev said.
``I left my heart and soul on the court. I think I proved I am
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Agassi's turnaround was, in one respect, the
biggest rally in the history of the Slams, given the paltry three
games he claimed in the first two sets. When Ivan Lendl defeated
John McEnroe here in 1984, the only other time during 31 years of
Open tennis when a two-set lead slipped away during the final of a
major, Lendl had at least won five games, although he also survived
a 3-all, 15-40 jam in the third set.
</P>
<P>
   After 52 minutes, Agassi was a quivering mess _ literally. On
the changeovers, he sat in his chair, both legs shaking furiously.
And with good reason. He was in a deep hole _ the first set had
lasted only 19 minutes _ and seemingly bamboozled. The game's best
returner hadn't won a point against Medvedev's first serve, and his
own serve was a disaster, far more of a liability than a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   He had confronted break points in six of seven games and managed
to stave off defeat just once. His second serve was a juicy treat
for the pouncing Medvedev, who won 84 percent of the points after
an Agassi fault.
</P>
<P>
   Even a 29-minute rain delay after the first game of the second
set was of no obvious help. Although he huddled with coach Brad
Gilbert, trying to figure out where he was going wrong, he lost
five consecutive games after play resumed and had to stave off
three set points against his serve in the sixth game. Medvedev
shrugged off the setback and proceeded to hold at love.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough time on the rain delay,'' Agassi's longtime
coach and friend Gilbert said. ``It was like he didn't know what
the hell was going on out there. Certainly my good coaching brought
him back to 6-2. God, I was really thinking, `Man, if we get
another rain delay, I'd better chill for a while.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But ultimately, it felt good for him to stop. We went over a
lot of things. I just told him, `Play your game; your game will
take you through. At least make him beat you playing your game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert admitted he also considered taking a two-by-four to
Agassi's skull to drive home that message but then thought better
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Both lost sets ended with pulverizing Medvedev aces. It took
Agassi nine games to so much as reach deuce against Medvedev's
serve. His first break didn't come until the 70th minute of the
match, and then he was broken back. At love.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shocking turn of events. But it also proved a horribly
false read. Agassi had fought his way into his third Roland Garros
final by suckering several opponents into thinking they had him.
The previous Sunday, he got defending champion Carlos Moya to bite,
and the unsuspecting Medvedev would be similarly duped. Tennis'
Rope-A-Dope?
</P>
<P>
   After 2 hours, 7 minutes, the match was dead level. No matter
that Medvedev held the lead in aces 21-1, or that Agassi had hit
just 57 percent of his first serves.
</P>
<P>
   The first signs of Agassi's resurgence were two strong service
games at the start of the third set, followed by his first break
for a 4-2 lead. Although Medvedev would immediately answer with
same, he had begun to press and Agassi pounced, breaking for the
set at love.
</P>
<P>
   From that point forward, he applied the pressure with scorching
returns and a down-the-line backhand that almost never failed him
at crucial junctures. He needed just a break in the second game to
claim the fourth set, and once he saved a break point in the second
game of the fifth set he was never in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the point probably where I will remember I made the
mistake,'' Medvedev said. ``It wasn't a big serve. For some reason,
instead of playing safer, which would be high topspin to his
backhand, I went for a strange shot, which would not have hurt him
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev went down swinging, though. He saved three match points
_ the first with his 23rd ace _ against his serve in the
next-to-last game, which went to five deuces and proved to be the
match's most pitched battle.
</P>
<P>
   But losing it didn't ruffle Agassi. Serving for the championship
after 2 hours, 50 minutes, he dropped just one point, winning when
Medvedev whacked a forehand long.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' Medvedev said, ``I cannot say I (did)
something wrong. I think Andre just played unbelievable. He
deserves all the credit. I'm human. I am disappointed that I didn't
win. But on the other hand, the happiness I have in my heart for
being in the hunt, in the competition, that by far outweighs the
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens in the future, if I win three Grand Slams in
a row or four, these two weeks will for sure be the happiest of my
life. I just came up short against a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   By one measuring stick at least, one of the five greatest ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This accomplishment could never be a burden,'' Agassi said.
``It's given me so much that I'll try to do more just because of
how good it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 25 years or so since somebody has won the French and
Wimbledon in the same year,'' Agassi said. ``That would be
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
