<HEADER>
A5384 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     06-07 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ It was widely speculated Sunday that Pete Sampras, nice guy
though he might be, was bearing Andre Agassi considerable malice.
</P>
<P>
   You could picture Pete sprawled on the sofa in front of his
big-screen TV for the start of the French Open final, his breakfast
untouched, sticking pins in an Agassi doll. Because, for all of
Sampras' accomplishments, and the list is prodigious, he had failed
to do what Andre was one match from doing.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Pete dozed off.
</P>
<P>
   And when he woke up, Agassi had the prize in hand, the Coupe
Musketeers, that goes to the champion of Roland Garros. In Agassi's
case, it signified an even bigger prize, the icing on his cake, the
completion of a rare career Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras had been gone from Paris for 10 days after failing to
survive into the third round of the French, the tournament that
routinely slams him grandly. The greatest player of his day,
Sampras never has made it past a semifinal on the terre battue, and
it's this void in his rsum that will deprive him of a universal
consensus that he is the greatest player of any day.
</P>
<P>
   If Pete's mind is right in the weeks ahead, he is a solid bet to
win a third consecutive Wimbledon for the second time, thereby
leaving him tied with Roy Emerson for most majors won, 12. Because
Emerson's record always has borne an asterisk _ Rod Laver, having
been banned as a professional, was absent from almost all the
tournaments Emmo won _ and given the greater depth on the tour
today, it's reasonable to insist Sampras' total is easily the more
remarkable accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   But the French thing dogs him. It keeps Sampras from receiving
his due in full. Pete's predictable annual flameout on the red clay
accentuates a conspicuous hole in his game.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the four players before Agassi who completed a
Slam in their lifetimes won the four events on only two surfaces,
grass and Roland Garros' red clay. There wasn't a hardcourt major
until the U.S. Open switched over at Flushing Meadow in 1978. The
Australian Open followed a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, of course, has won on grass and both kinds of
hardcourts _ the American DecoTurf II and the Aussies' Rebound Ace.
And the sum of his titles _ five at Wimbledon, four in New York,
two in Melbourne _ over a nine-year span is a supreme achievement,
clearly dwarfing what Agassi has done.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there were those, Andrei Medvedev among them, who surmised
after Agassi's astonishing, historic 1-6, 2-6, 6-4, 6-3, 6-4 win
over Medvedev that his four championships on the four surfaces made
him Sampras' near equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves to make the argument,'' Medvedev said.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, with no disrespect to either Andre(i) intended, hogwash.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' views on the subject will be known soon enough. Agassi,
for his part, tried to dodge the question but seemed to imply there
was room for a measure of debate.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder how badly each covets the other's accomplishments.
How many of his trophies would Sampras swap for the loving cup
Andre held high over his head here Sunday afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   Two? Three? None?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go to sleep at night,'' Agassi insisted, ``and honestly
say I wouldn't give up my career for anybody's.''
</P>
<P>
   A few folks close to Pete claim he has conceded defeat here,
that a Roland Garros pelt never will be his to claim. Almost 28,
with his leonine body starting to rebel at the rigors of his
profession, he would have to make major sacrifices to give himself
any kind of chance on Court Central.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras would have to dedicate himself to a clay-court training
regimen, and that would hinder his preparations for Wimbledon,
where another huge carrot on a string tantalizes him. A sixth
Wimbledon title, you see, will break the modern record he shares
with Bjorn Borg, as well as separating him in the Slam standings
from Borg and his childhood idol Laver, who also own 11 majors
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage in his career, Sampras sees surpassing Emerson as
his clearest, safest path to immortality, if not necessarily
unequivocal acceptance as the No. 1 for all time. He'll take the
two championships he needs wherever he can get them, and obviously
the lush lawns of the All England Club are most suited to his heavy
artillery.
</P>
<P>
   On dirt, Pete is just a panting, perspiring face in the crowd.
On grass, he is Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   As for Agassi, his going 4-for-4 merits a new look at his place
in history, which is unique. Remember, what he has done is
unprecedented in the Open era, and thus it must separate him from
the pack, too.
</P>
<P>
   Borg's 11 Slams don't include a U.S. Open. Ivan Lendl (eight)
and Mats Wilander (seven) are minus the Wimbledon leg. Jimmy
Connors (eight), Stefan Edberg (six) and Boris Becker (six) each
suffered from the same allergy to the crushed brick that bedevils
Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   And John McEnroe's seven were limited to Wimbledon and the U.S.
Open, although he came close here once, blowing a two-sets-to-love
lead to Lendl in the '84 final, the only Open-era precedent for
what happened to Andrei Medvedev on Sunday. Had he won, he might
have made more of an effort in Australia, where he rarely bothered
to play.
</P>
<P>
   How does Andre fit into this august group of Open-era titans? In
tennis, does a royal flush beat a full house, irrespective of all
other data? Does he receive bonus points for variety, or do we
deduct for his modest volume?
</P>
<P>
   I vote the former. But that doesn't mean he belongs in Sampras'
league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
