<SLUG> BC-LA-REFUGEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT ARRIVALS FROM KOSOVO SKEPTICAL OF PEACE PROCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It will take more than a peace treaty to satisfy
Kosovar refugees relocated to Southern California that it is safe
to return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Hajrush Vlashi, who is hosting nine of them at
least for the next few days, said Sunday they don't plan to return
home anytime soon. They want Slobodan Milosevic out of power and
the United States to remain in Kosovo after peace is forged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way they can feel safe is if the United States is
there, not the English, not the French,'' said Vlashi, speaking for
the family.
</P>
<P>
   That means an uncertain future for the 32-member extended family
from Kosovo that is scattered around host homes in the San Fernando
Valley and nearby Westlake Village, Calabasas and Simi Valley in
neighboring Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they felt safe, the families' farms and workplaces are
destroyed, they said. They said they have nothing to return to and
nothing with which to feed themselves until next spring.
</P>
<P>
   NATO seeks the immediate withdrawal of Yugoslav troops from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees in Vlashi's living room said they couldn't believe
peace talks had even started. They said they have heard empty
promises of peace in the past from the Serbs and expressed
frustration over a peace process that does not include their
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these negotiations are being done without the (Kosovo
Liberation Army) or Albanians, and they don't think that will be
good enough,'' Vlashi said.
</P>
<P>
   The newest arrivals to the home of Hajrush and Renee Vlashi are
his cousin Shukri Rexha and his wife, Nadire; daughter, Nazmije;
and 23-month-old son, Andi. They join Hajrush's father, Hisman
Vlashi; mother, Shefije; and three siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Rexha, a member of the KLA police, said he came reluctantly to
the United States for the sake of his family's safety. He said he
has buried massacred children and, two months ago, barely escaped
his own death as Serb soldiers chased him through Kosovo's craggy
hills.
</P>
<P>
   The family members arrived Wednesday and have nothing to do now
but figure out a way to help their countrymen from afar, he said.
Telling of their polarized reality, their two plans for the week
are to partake in a quintessential Southern California activity _
going to the beach _ and monitoring network news to fathom what
they can about the frail peace process regarding Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rexha, who had traveled to other European countries as a
musician before returning to join the fighting, said he is happy to
finally see Southern California, ``but when you have friends and
relatives suffering, it cuts that happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Rexha added that he is not at liberty to discuss how much
firepower the KLA still has to fight the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rexhas have had scant opportunities to take in California.
The first thing Hisman Vlashi told the Rexhas is that everything
Hajrush had told them when he moved to Southern California in 1989
is true, Hajrush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hot. There are more cars than people,'' he said. ``You
walk nowhere.'' The future is uncertain for the hosts as well, who
are still looking for ways to raise money so their relatives can
rent their own apartments and pay for their own food. The couple,
living on Hajrush's wages as a waiter and sporadic donations, are
having difficulty supporting nine relatives who go through six
loaves of sourdough bread at a meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bread is out of control,'' Renee Vlashi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
