<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PHANTOM MENACE' STILL GOING AT LIGHT SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in 2nd graf refers to Monday.)  
 
  
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace''
became the 14th member of the elite quarter-billion-dollar club
during the weekend as it continued to dominate business at the
nation's multiplexes with an estimated $32.2 million at 3,023
theaters during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth installment of the ``Star Wars'' saga has now taken
in $255.5 million in 19 days and will likely crack the $400 million
mark before it leaves theaters at the end of summer. ``Phantom
Menace,'' which saw grosses fall 34 percent from the previous
Friday-Sunday, is now the 12th highest grosser of all time and
should pass ``Jaws'' at $260 million for the 11th spot today or
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very big numbers,'' declared Tom Sherak, 20th
Century Fox's distribution chief. ``We obviously can't stay like
that, but we're clearly going to wind up in the top five of all
time.'' (Current No. 5 is ``Forrest Gump,'' at $329.5 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Sherak said audiences continue to be 59 percent male and that 15
percent of ``Phantom Menace'' attendees during the weekend had
already seen the movie at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   Movie analyst Arthur Rockwell noted that ``Phantom Menace'' _
which has probably sold slightly more than 50 million tickets _ had
clearly survived the mixed critical reception that emerged just
before it opened. ``This movie is about as review-proof as they
come,'' he added. ``All that negative buzz is history.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service, said ``Phantom Menace'' should take in somewhere between
$375 million and $410 million and will benefit from the fact that
about 74 percent of the nation's schools will have let out by next
weekend. However, ``Phantom Menace'' looks likely to finish second
next weekend to the opening of New Line's ``Austin Powers: The Spy
Who Shagged Me'' due to high interest among adolescents and young
adults, Bucksbaum said, and could hit $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Line has done a great job of getting the word out on
`Austin Powers,''' he added, citing an early trailer that mildly
spoofed ``Star Wars.'' Also opening next weekend with positive buzz
is Paramount's thriller ``The General's Daughter'' with John
Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' remained so dominant this weekend, however,
that it nearly matched the combined total of the next three films,
led by Universal's second weekend of ``Notting Hill'' with $15
million at 2,752 theaters. The well-reviewed romantic comedy,
starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant, lost about 32 percent from
its opening Friday-Sunday and has taken in close to $50million in
its first 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's only major opening, Disney's action-adventure
``Instinct,'' posted moderate totals in third with $10.2 million at
2,059 theaters. Disney marketing executive Chuck Viane said the
movie, in which Anthony Hopkins portrays a scientist who has lived
among gorillas, received solid response from audiences and should
perform well due to positive word of mouth and its uniqueness as an
adult-oriented offering in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Instinct'' was hurt by mixed reviews, since its
target audience is older than the average moviegoer, and had
performed slightly below expectations, since the weekend has
historically been a good launching point for films such as ``The
Rock,'' ``Congo,'' ``Con Air'' and ``The Truman Show.'' As a
result, Bucksbaum pointed out, the overall total for the 1999
weekend was down 14 percent from the same weekend last year, when
``The Truman Show'' debuted with $31.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said Disney faced a tough marketing challenge in
finding an audience for ``Instinct'' but added, ``Given that this
is a prime slot, the opening is a little soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal continued to post solid results for its fifth weekend
of ``The Mummy'' in fourth with $7.5 million at 3,411 theaters,
pushing it past $127.6 million to 100th on the all-time list over
``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' Fox's sixth weekend of ``Entrapment''
followed with $3.5 million at 2,584 sites to hit nearly $75 million
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' 10th weekend of its blockbuster virtual-reality
thriller ``The Matrix'' came in sixth with $2.4 million at 2,045
sites to top $159 million. By contrast, Sony's second weekend of
its similarly themed ``The Thirteenth Floor'' faded quickly with an
unimpressive $1.9 million at 1,815 theaters to give it $7.3 million
after 10 days. ``Floor,'' with a reported $18 million price tag,
will probably disappear with less than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time holdovers took the final three slots, led by Fox's
ninth weekend of ``Never Been Kissed'' with $1.7 million at 2,085
theaters, as it topped $51 million in another solid performance for
Drew Barrymore, who served as producer. Fox Searchlight's fourth
weekend of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' came in ninth with $1.1
million at 1,005 theaters, followed by Paramount's seventh weekend
of ``Election'' with $900,000 at 827 sites.
</P>
<P>
   MGM's fourth weekend of ``Tea With Mussolini'' finished 11th
with $780,000 at 271 theaters, followed by Universal's eighth
weekend of ``Life'' with $759,000 at 1,120 theaters. Sony has
posted a solid opening of John Sayles' adventure-drama, ``Limbo,''
with $150,000 at 10 screens in its first launch from the Screen
Gems banner and will expand the run soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 0143EDT &QL; 
