<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO'S TALL TANDEM REDEFINES BIG MAN'S GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Given the spectacular nature of the fire that
consumed the Portland Trail Blazers, it is popular to surmise that
the often-juvenile local team screwed up somehow, perhaps lighting
a stogie while pumping gas.
</P>
<P>
   However, the immediate evidence, following Sunday's 94-80
immolation at the Rose Garden, provides an obvious case of arson by
the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, the Spurs will show you the kerosene and rags in the back
of their bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of hearing what Portland did wrong, what the Lakers
did wrong,'' said Spurs' guard Mario Elie. ``Let's give the Spurs a
little bit of credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit is due. Long overdue. Their second straight 4-0 sweep of
a supposed power gave the Spurs not only their first Western
Conference championship, it left them with an 11-1 record in the
playoffs _ part of an astonishing 42-6 run since the Spurs were
6-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Avery (Johnson), and I said, `Do you realize
we've lost six games since February?''' Elie said. ``That is
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in this truncated, slipshod NBA season, it is a startling
feat. A good case can always be made about the decline of the NBA,
but there is no denying this fact:
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs start two of the five best centers in the league, and
no opponent is close to figuring out an effective response.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson and Tim Duncan are about to nudge awake the
basketball historians, who've rightfully nodded off this season. If
the 7-foot pair continue to dominate either New York or Indiana in
the Finals, they will make a case for the best big-man tandem in
the sport's chronicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 36 and I've been in the league a long time,'' said
teammate Jerome Kersey, ``and I don't remember two better offensive
centers on the same team at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kersey might be biased. He also might be wrong, or at least
incomplete about the offense part. They may be the best defensive
tandem, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the regular season, opponents shot just 40 percent against
the Spurs, the best mark since the league began tracking the stat
in 1970. The figure has been maintained in the postseason, which
was an especially wicked development here, where multiple Blazer
weapons were reduced to pure futility.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so long and so big,'' marveled Blazer forward Brian
Grant. ``They're both all-NBA and deserve to be. I think they'll
carry that team to their first championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Should that come to pass, no one will be more gratified than
Robinson, who might the most disrespected superstar in the NBA
galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 10 long years,'' said Robinson of his career that is
no longer absent a Finals appearance. ``It's just what I imagined
it to be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of years coming in here and answering hard
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard questions almost always concerned Robinson's softness.
The committed Christian and piano-playing, well-read, articulate
Annapolis graduate has always been viewed as lacking the requisite
Rottweiler demeanor for an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Robinson still isn't tearing pants legs off mail carriers.
But he now has teammates who do. And he has Duncan, the second-year
stud to whom he has surrendered the No. 1 offensive option, which
has allowed him to move from under the burden of carrying the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In the clincher, Robinson had 20 points and 10 rebounds, while
Duncan had 18 and 8. The Spurs can win when one scores 30 and the
other 10, and either can be the leader.
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable thing, watching two such agile athletes
redefine the traditional big man's game, and apparently without the
ego collisions that vex other double-star teams. The Blazers, as
the Lakers and Timberwolves before them, were helpless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on in the season, Tim and I weren't working together as
well on offense as we had the year before,'' he said. ``We had two
new people (Elie and Kersey) to work in, and we had no real
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after the slow start, (coach Greg Popovich) said we should
just quit trying to finesse things and go hard to the big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The results have been apparent this spring. The Spurs are
winning in the playoffs by an average of nearly 10 points a game,
an almost Bull-like dominance that isn't likely to end against
either Eastern opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said at the beginning of the playoffs that we were going to
get better and better,'' said Robinson, who after the game and
before the locker room doors opened, addressed the team with that
reminder.
</P>
<P>
   He also told his teammates how proud and pleased he was,
thanking everyone for a accepting roles avoiding the
finger-pointing after the slow start.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say much about what this ascension meant to his
often-criticized career.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't have to. Anyone who knows the Admiral knows the scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed facing the trials _ I really have,'' he said.
``That's what gives me the drive and desire to figure how to get to
the Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire is lit in Robinson. Scorch marks are all over the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
