<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5402 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PORTLAND-SPI &LR;      06-07 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PORTLAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS SWEEP TRAIL BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Their biggest mouthpiece, Isaiah Rider, sat
motionless in a corner at the end of the Portland Trail Blazers'
bench.
</P>
<P>
   His arms were crossed. His head lay between raised knees.
Presumably, his mind meandered into deep thought that moment in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Rider and Blazermania had actually been silenced long before the
Spurs completed a series sweep with Sunday's 94-80 Game 4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   So, figuratively, that white towel around Rider's neck did not
need to be thrown on the Rose Garden floor. Much like they the
entire Western Conference finals, the determined San Antonio Spurs
snatched that away, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll probably go on to win it all,'' Rider said of the
Spurs. ``If they don't, they had a great series here.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to typical Rider remarks, that would be an
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   In advancing to the NBA Finals for the first time, the Spurs won
their 10 straight playoff game. They also became the first team to
sweep the conference semifinal and final rounds since the 1989
Lakers, who won 11 straight en route the league finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, maintaining their stern we're-on-a-mission attitude
that got them this far, averted any elaborate postgame celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have four more games before we can even think about
celebrating,'' Spurs point guard Avery Johnson said. ``We are
excited, but not overly excited. No one is going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, the Spurs save their madness for the basketball
court.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most impressive is how methodically San Antonio pushed
aside the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Portland owned the league's best home record to this point
(27-3) but lost Games 3 and 4 to the Spurs by an average of 18
points. San Antonio won its sixth straight road game in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't bring it,'' Portland's Brian Grant said.
``Certain guys did, but when it was all said and done, their big
guys took away the middle and made it very difficult for us to do
anything right. Give them credit. They took it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The deep and richly talented Blazers were overrun by a team
playing arguably the best basketball of those still standing.
Whichever wins the Eastern Conference finals, New York or Indiana,
should know that San Antonio is boiling over with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``After going through the Western Conference playoffs, I feel
sorry for whoever comes out of the East,'' Spurs guard Mario Elie
said. ``We went through a hard road. We played three tough teams
and swept two of them (including the L.A. Lakers in the
semifinals). So you've got to give us a little credit.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio veteran David Robinson will settle for a
championship ring. It's taken him 10 seasons to get this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 10 long years, but it's just what I imagined it
would be,'' said Robinson, who powered the Spurs with 20 points and
10 rebounds. ``We've grown a lot. I feel good about what we've
accomplished. Our steady play throughout the game gives us a mental
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Spurs guard Steve Kerr, who won three titles with the
Chicago Bulls: ``I don't think I'll ever compare any team with
Michael Jordan on it, but this team is very mentally tough.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio won two close games at home in this series. Then,
after blowing out the Blazers in Game 3, the Spurs were immovable
Sunday. They withstood a fast start and led for most of 2{
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   After going ahead 12-11 in the first, Portland's only other lead
was 59-58 with 1:40 left in the third. And that was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan responded with a three-point play over Rasheed
Wallace, and San Antonio pulled away with a 20-6 run. Johnson's
19-footer put the Spurs in front 78-65 with 8:09 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Portland's objective was to double team Duncan and Robinson. But
whenever the Blazers crowded San Antonio's post players, Robinson
and Duncan made quick, sharp passes to outside shooters. Outside
scoring from Kerr, Sean Elliott and Jaren Jackson picked Portland
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bitter feeling,'' said Damon Stoudamire, who led
Portland with 21 points. ``It's rough. I cried. A couple of other
guys teared up, too. You want to remember the feeling and never let
it come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, who had been the picture of poise in defeating Utah
in the second round, fell off the wall and cracked their frame in
this series. Their offense often regressed to one-on-one play,
which held the Blazers back as much as San Antonio's insistence on
closing down the paint.
</P>
<P>
   In light of constant player complaints about playing time and
on-court bickering, the Blazers were not together in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer in bad thoughts and bad karma.
Unfortunately, we had some negative vibes seep into the mix,''
Blazers backup guard Greg Anthony said. ``It's obviously no secret
that we had issues. If you have other issues at hand, then those
sometimes will determine your fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about their team is their chemistry and their
selflessness. Their objective was to win. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, all is said and done for these Blazers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
