<P>
   ``We would expect the effect of the deal on Phoenix to be fairly
modest,'' said a source close to the negotiations. The exact number
of positions to be eliminated had not been determined, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal and Honeywell executives began negotiations again
in February after years of on-and-off talks. A source said the
companies' heads soon got serious.
</P>
<P>
   The timing appeared right because AlliedSignal had a succession
issue and Honeywell didn't want to become a small player in a
market where customers are outsourcing larger portions of the
aircraft, the source close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger will ideally position the combined entity for
enhanced revenue and income growth,'' Bossidy said in the company's
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Bossidy will serve as chairman until his planned retirement on
April 1, 2000. Bossidy, 64, who was cited in the June 21 issue of``
Fortune'' magazine as one of ``today's best CEOs,'' will focus on
integrating the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the different markets AlliedSignal and Honeywell serve,
the source said, merging them should be easy because both have good
corporate cultures which are action-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore, 58, Honeywell's CEO, will be the the new company's
chief executive officer until Bossidy's retirement. At that time,
Bonsignore will assume the additional responsibilities of chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Johnson, currently president and chief executive
officer of AlliedSignal's aerospace division will report to
Bonsignore.
</P>
<P>
   The merger sets up a new board of directors and a new management
team. The board includes nine members from the current AlliedSignal
board and six members from the current Honeywell board.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six key staff appointments, four are from AlliedSignal
and two are from Honeywell. None is based in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Mayor Skip Rimsza was optimistic that any job loss would
be minimal and that other companies seeing Honeywell's commitment
to the Valley, might follow its lead and increase their business
presence in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a tremendous number of businesses that may locate or
expand their presence in the Valley just to capitalize on the
support business a company of that size requires,'' Rimsza said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the merger AlliedSignal ranked No. 3 among the Valley's
largest employers, with approximately 10,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal has three facilities in the Valley: Its aerospace
division headquarters is at 34th and Washington streets. A
diversified manufacturer, AlliedSignal's aerospace division makes
collision-prevention and other safety instruments for aircraft. It
also has plants in Chandler and Tempe. AlliedSignal also employs
1,000 aerospace workers in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal's Arizona operations account for $5 billion in
revenue. It had revenue of $15 billion last year from sales of
automotive products, specialty chemicals and performance fibers.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, Honeywell's operations represented just over half
its 1998 revenue of $8.4 billion. Two of its three businesses:
Industrial Control and Space and Aviation Control, which accounted
for $2.5 billion and $2.3 billion respectively, are headquartered
here. Between the two divisions it employs 7,500, placing it No. 11
among the largest employers in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A company news release projected that the combined company's
stock price will see an 8.8 percent increase over the next three
years. The new Honeywell's stock price is expected to rise 17 cents
per share in 2000 to 32 cents per share in 2002. &QL; 
Riccardo A. Davis can be reached at (602) 444-8894 or at
riccardo.davis(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
