<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-LESSONS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW ONWARD TO THE NEXT KOSOVO _ IF THERE IS ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the goal of the allied bombing of Yugoslavia was
to force Slobodan Milosevic to pull his troops out of Kosovo and
cede control of that unhappy province to NATO, it appears to have
been a success, and more _ a refutation of the common wisdom that
air power alone could never make a despot back down.
</P>
<P>
   But if the purpose was also to warn evildoers in other lands
that the United States and its allies now stand ready to enforce
peace with bombs, it is a message that has brought more concern
than comfort.
</P>
<P>
   From India to Israel to Indonesia, countries with their own
unresolved ethnic conflicts _ and they are of epidemic proportions
in the postcommunist universe _ have scrutinized the Balkan
conflict for some indication of how this might affect their own
fates.
</P>
