by the wily Milosevic to gain time and consolidate his gains _
heralds the acceptance of a new global police mission by the West,
however bold the pronouncements and self-congratulation last week.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, the United States and its NATO allies have
couched the bombardment of Yugoslavia in high moral terms, as a
crusade to restore the rights of a maligned population and to
prevent the spread of chaos beyond the borders of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   But all along, many experts and foreign leaders have questioned
whether the allies would have acted had Kosovo been in Central
Asia, and how much the operation really had a tightly focused
purpose _ to define the reach, the role and the credibility of NATO
and the United States in postcommunist Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Now new questions can be added to the mix: Does the apparent
success of the air war change the logic? Will a newly confident
West be tempted to expand its horizons? Should tyrants in far-flung
parts of the globe think a second time before unleashing mayhem?
</P>
<P>
   Graham Allison, head of the Belfer Center for Science and
International Affairs at Harvard, is among those who see the
bombing of Kosovo as a strictly European phenomenon. ``I think that
this was an accident, a combination of circumstances which
partially have to do with Europe, partly with NATO, partly with
guilt about the earlier Bosnia story, partly to do with the notion
that more things are doable in the European setting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not likely to initiate a new messianic crusade,'' he
added, even though some people will inevitably ask why the West
doesn't take action ``when the next horror arises in Rwanda or
Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges of selectivity have already been leveled, raising
the questions of where NATO was during the genocide in Rwanda, and
why it is complicit with Turkey's repression of the Kurds or
Indonesia's repression of separatists in East Timor, and why it has
kept silent about Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of NATO planes bombing Israel to get its troops out
of the West Bank, or Canada to free Quebec, or England to get it
out of Northern Ireland, has become the stuff of comedy routines
based on the inconsistencies of NATO's Kosovo rationale.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fact is that separatist movements along ethnic and
religious lines and conflicts like the ones in the crumbling
Yugoslavia are likely to be the dominant problem of the near
future, and the temptation for interference by the West or other
powers will always be there.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that well-meaning nations can and should try to
jointly resolve conflicts has been a leitmotif of this century. The
creation of the League of Nations and the U.N. Security Council was
followed by various regional or individual efforts at peacekeeping,
including Syria's takeover of Lebanon with the consent of the Arab
League, Nigeria's efforts at stanching civil wars in West Africa,
and U.S. operations in Haiti, Somalia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   One outgrowth of the Kosovo operation was the announcement last
week that the 15 members of the European Union intend to form their
own military force for such missions, freeing the United States of
at least part of the burden of playing global cop.
</P>
<P>
   But the peacemaking efforts have always been selective, and only
rarely successful. The Security Council has been wary of using its
powers to employ military force under the U.N. Charter. Most U.N.
peacekeeping missions have been created largely to formalize
agreements, and have lasted only so long as the warring parties
needed them.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO action on Kosovo marked a new approach. First, the
allies claimed the right to use force against a sovereign state
only because it refused to sign a proffered agreement. Second,
instead of sending in troops, NATO chose a campaign of
progressively more destructive bombing, thus sharply lowering the
chance of casualties among allied soldiers, and the resistance back
home that body bags provoke.
</P>
<P>
   However effective the approach in the immediate term, it has
also been the source of considerable irritation abroad, and
considerable uncertainty about the future. One accusation rarely
noted in the U.S. press, but extensively accepted as truth abroad,
was that the bombing of Yugoslavia was a flagrant violation of
sovereignty and international law. In the Third World, where
boundaries are often in dispute and governments weak, these
principles are held to be virtually sacred.
</P>
<P>
   Among other nations, most notably Russia, the entire campaign
has been perceived exclusively as a power play by NATO, with the
Kosovar Albanians only providing a pretext. Coupled with the
expansion of NATO, the campaign has seriously lowered the standing
of the United States in Russian eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So the diplomatic costs of repeating the exercise too often
would be high, even if the prospects of military success were good.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is a sense among U.S. and foreign analysts
that even if the Kosovo operation did achieve its aims, it did so
at an exorbitant cost in armaments and destruction. A million
Kosovars were homeless, Serbia's economy lay in ruins, and
thousands of Serbs and Albanians were dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just overwhelmed them with destruction,'' said Earl Tilford
Jr., a former Air Force officer who now teaches at the Army War
College. ``It was technically excellent, but strategically
bankrupt.'' The question this poses elsewhere, of course, is how
many times the West will have the stomach to repeat the destruction
and the resources to repair the mess afterward.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the fact that having entered Bosnia and now
Kosovo, the United States is likely to remain mired in the south
Balkans for a generation. It is not the kind of garrison duty
likely to be repeated in too many places.
</P>
<P>
   And there are also doubts about the effectiveness of the Kosovo
operation as a deterrent. ``Does this mean that the next bad man,
whether an African potentate or someone in Asia or even Uzbekistan,
is going to think, `Oh my God, here they come?' I don't think so,''
said Allison. ``It wouldn't significantly affect the calculus,
though it would at least demonstrate what could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What may happen, argued Susan Woodward, an expert on the Balkans
at the Brookings Institution, is that dictators or even troubled
countries, fearing that their internal conflicts make them ripe
targets for a NATO onslaught and unable to resist it with
conventional arms, will be tempted to turn to nuclear or chemical
arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will not say, `I will think twice before I do horrible
things,''' Ms. Woodward said. ``Rather they will think, `I better
prepare better defensively against external interventions of that
kind.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not comfortable with the argument that if we compromised
we would lose our credibility,'' said Dmitri Simes, head of the
Nixon Center in Washington. ``That's not the kind of credibility we
need. Everybody understands that the United States, especially with
NATO, is a global force. We have to understand how different our
actions look elsewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
