<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5574 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BKN-COACHES-CLOTHES     06-07 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BKN-COACHES-CLOTHES-REVIEW-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING GOOD WHILE EVERYBODY SWEATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) 
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Ohio, Mich.)  (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he struts along the basketball sidelines, screaming out plays
while wearing a Giorgio Armani suit, P.J. Carlesimo feels blessed.
But sometimes he also feels foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of nights when you're sweating through a $2,000
suit that you kind of wonder why you're wearing a shirt and tie,''
said Carlesimo, coach of the Golden State Warriors. ``I think the
baseball managers and football coaches are smarter than basketball
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans watching the National Basketball Association playoffs this
weekend will no doubt note the visual disconnect between the baggy
jerseys of perspiring players engaged in grueling competition and
the sleek suits of coaches equally focused on the game. Carlesimo,
whose team failed to make the playoffs and whose wardrobe is
strictly Saks Fifth Avenue, makes it look good.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, NBA coaches are widely considered to be the best
dressed in the world, as these things go. While their counterparts
in the National Football League and major-league baseball wear
warm-up jackets, baseball caps and, in the case of baseball
managers, team uniforms, the coaches in the media-savvy NBA wear
suits by some of the most trend-setting designers on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley of the Miami Heat has his Armani suits and sports
coats shipped directly from Italy. Chuck Daly, who recently retired
from the Orlando Magic, sat on the bench in the finely finished
fabrics of Hugo Boss and Ermenegildo Zegna, and the relatively
diminutive Mike Fratello, a veteran of 13 NBA seasons, is one of
the league's most exciting sideline personalities, mostly because
of his antics and his fashion flair. Fratello, who was dismissed
last week by the Cleveland Cavaliers, favored Boss.
</P>
<P>
   When Carlesimo left Seton Hall and entered the league five years
ago, he had no choice but to trade up in his clothing. Upon signing
to coach the Portland Trail Blazers, he was notified that one of
the team's sponsors, a local clothing store, wanted to outfit him
in Donna Karan (whose line President Clinton has been known to
wear).
</P>
<P>
   Now at Golden State, he has an agreement with Saks Fifth Avenue
that calls for him to dress in Armani or Zegna throughout the
season. While Carlesimo appreciates his good fortune, he says that
dressing to the nines is not necessarily practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to coach in what we wear at practice, which would
be closer to what NFL coaches wear in good weather _ a coaching
shirt and slacks,'' Carlesimo said. ``But I think that it has
become an image thing in the NBA and that it's going to be
difficult to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Because their game is played indoors, NBA coaches have always
worn suits. But it was not until the mid-1980s that many of them
started paying attention to the label inside their clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Don Casey, an NBA assistant coach for 18 years, said the shift
began when David Stern became the league's commissioner and
embarked on what has become the greatest mass-marketing campaign in
the history of professional sports. As the league gained fame and
an international following, the top players and coaches became
celebrities. The media began to take note of what the coaches were
wearing as they glowered or exploded or sat catatonic on the
sidelines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They didn't dress like that in the '60s and '70s,'' said
Casey, who during his brief stint as the head coach of the Los
Angeles Clippers was viewed as one of the league's worst-dressed
coaches in his lackluster suits and ties. ``The coaches were just
people coaching the game, but when national TV came in, the coaches
started becoming entities and looking professional and like _
you're on Wall Street _ came the look.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, who wore Armani while leading the Los Angeles Lakers to
four championships during the 1980s, and Daly, who became a dapper
dresser while coaching in Detroit, are considered to be the
pioneers of the current trend. While other coaches were wearing
cotton-blend shirts and polyester ties, Riley and Daly were walking
the court in shoes handmade by Bally and suits worth thousands of
dollars. Now, many of the league's coaches, armed with lucrative
clothing deals of their own, can match the Riley look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that now there's that pressure to keep up with the
Joneses,'' Casey said. ``Still, sometimes I don't feel like wearing
a tie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 0919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MENTAL-HEALTHCARE-R     06-07 0265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MENTAL-HEALTHCARE-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating) 
 UNDATED: psychiatric intervention.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police departments across the country refer officers with
troubling memories to therapists who specialize in treating
post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Robert Volpe, the father of Justin Volpe, the New
York City police officer who pleaded guilty to savagely assaulting
a suspect in a precinct bathroom, employed the sort of therapeutic
language found on Internet sites devoted to police post-traumatic
stress disorder to defend his son. He likened police work to combat
and suggested that his son suffered memories of traumatic
experiences on the job.
</P>
<P>
   As a diagnosis, post-traumatic stress disorder ``just started
taking off in 1985 and it keeps growing,'' said Allan Young,
chairman of the department of Social Studies of Medicine,
Anthropology and Psychiatry at McGill University in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   If the pool of patients grows and parity laws require insurers
to pay for all demands for treatment, something will have to give,
experts say. A 1997 study by the Employee Benefit Research
Institute warned that as mental-health parity causes employer costs
to rise, workers can expect to see erosion in other benefits, and
that some employers could react by dropping health-insurance
coverage altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The correct approach, said Ms. Rappaport of the National
Alliance for the Mentally Ill, is ``redirecting money already in
the system for those who have the most severe disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   The priority is simple, she said: ``You save the neediest
first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 0920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MUSEUM-BLOCKBUSTERS     06-07 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MUSEUM-BLOCKBUSTERS-REVIEW-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY RENOIR BEATS YOUR VERMEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Summer is blockbuster season, from the multiplex to
the august halls of culture. That's one way to explain a big van
Gogh show at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Or ``Impressionists in
Winter,'' the first exhibition to assemble the snowscapes of Monet,
Renoir, Gauguin and others, served up by the Brooklyn Museum of Art
in the city's hottest months.
</P>
<P>
   Museums may shun comparisons with Hollywood but they, too,
strive for that explosion of interest (named for a super-powerful
World War II bomb) that spells ``blockbuster,'' filling the
coffers, swelling the membership rolls and exciting envy at fellow
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museums have discovered advertising,'' said David Ross,
director of the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art and former
director of the Whitney Museum of American Art. ``You can advertise
garbage and make millions. Imagine if you advertise something with
real value.''
</P>
<P>
   With Americans flocking to art museums in record numbers, such
hits _ shows that seize you by the lapels and bellow, ``What! You
haven't lined up for `The Treasury of Saint Francis of Assisi'
yet?'' _ lend a gloss and urgency to art, science and history,
while posing questions about commercialism and exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows in the museum world arched last December when Ben
Hartley, director of communications and sponsorship for the Solomon
R. Guggenheim Museum in New York, said, ``We are in the
entertainment business and competing against other forms of
entertainment out there.'' The Guggenheim reached blockbuster
nirvana with its show on motorcycles, which drew half a million
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But blockbusters have their defenders. ``These great moments of
acute interest create exceptional teaching opportunities,'' said
Ellen Futter, director of the Museum of Natural History, whose show
``Epidemic!'' on infectious diseases, has drawn more than 150,000
visitors since Feb. 27. ``They create a gateway to learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum calendars are replete with big exhibitions of plainly
blockbuster ambitions _ shows on Ingres' portraiture, the age of
the Pyramids, new archaeological finds from China and the
ever-popular impressionists, truly the museum world's most reliable
moneymakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Met weighed in last month with ``Cezanne to van Gogh,''
featuring the renowned collection of van Gogh's physician, Dr.
Paul-Ferdinand Gachet. ``I don't sit around thinking what will
bring in crowds,'' said Philippe de Montebello, who after two
decades as director was recently elevated to chief executive
officer as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Museum of Art days later opened its
``Impressionists in Winter,'' lauded by the museum's director,
Arnold Lehman, as ``literally the coolest show.''
</P>
<P>
   A show last year at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, ``Monet
in the 20th Century,'' became the most popular in the country in
1998, drawing nearly 566,000 visitors. The recent Jackson Pollock
show at the Museum of Modern Art in New York also proved a bonanza,
drawing nearly 330,000 visitors, a striking number, if still short
of the 940,000 _ more than 8,000 a day _ who swamped the museum's
Matisse show of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The John Singer Sargent show, which closed last week at the
National Gallery in Washington, drew about 425,000 visitors, or
nearly 4,500 a day, catapulting it into the realm of the smash 1995
Vermeer show, said Dodge Thompson, the chief of exhibitions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The modern age of blockbusters arrived with a sensational show
in 1948. With the museums of war-shattered Germany in ruins and
many of their treasures recovered by the Allies from salt mines and
other caches, the U.S. authorities shipped 202 masterpieces to the
National Gallery for exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Called simply ``Paintings From the Berlin Museums,'' the show,
with its Rembrandts, Vermeers, Titians, Duerers, van Eycks,
Botticellis, Breughels and a Bosch, drew near-riotous crowds. The
intense interest and short run of just 40 days, made for the
unprecedented arithmetic of an average 24,124 visitors a day.
</P>
<P>
   When the Louvre's Mona Lisa went on view at the National Gallery
in 1963, it drew an average daily attendance of more than 19,200,
for a total of 518,525.
</P>
<P>
   In overall numbers, the Met may hold the modern record, with
more than 1.2 million visitors to its ``Treasures of Tutankhamun''
of 1978 to '79.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bigger blockbusters on the horizon may not really be
blockbusters at all, but permanent installations. The new Gottesman
Hall of Planet Earth opens at the Museum of Natural History on June
12, the first stage of the spherical Rose Center for Earth and
Space to be unveiled early next year, replacing the old
planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Met opened its new Greek Galleries in a soaring
barrel-vaulted space hemmed in since World War II, drawing throngs
of visitors tabulated at more than 10,000 a day, until guards gave
up counting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 0920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2239 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BKN-COACHES-CLOTHES     06-07 0769
</HEADER>
