<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2248 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-INDONESIA-REVIEW-NY     06-07 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-INDONESIA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDONESIA, THE VOTING IS ONLY A FIRST STEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ With drums, whistles and war whoops, with
dancers, tumblers and female impersonators, Indonesians have
grasped the first great truth about free elections: They can be
lots of fun.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another truth as well. One election does not make a
country a democracy. Institutions, traditions and social cohesion
do. So the big question on the eve of Indonesia's first free
election in 44 years is whether it will set the world's
fourth-most-populous nation on the path toward democratic stability
or toward new turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   One foreign election expert wishes, in fact, that the
parliamentary election scheduled for tomorrow could be a trial run.
People are learning about democracy here by trial and error, the
expert said, and the stakes are far too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year ago, Indonesians were political naifs,'' said the
expert, a foreign diplomat. ``Now that picture is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Suharto was forced to resign the presidency in May 1998,
Indonesia has been learning fast, moving from street demonstrations
to party organizing, from utopian philosophizing to the beginnings
of coalition building. Still, nobody knows what patterns the voting
will take or how this nation of more than 200 million jostling and
often feuding people will manage the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the people will vote freely, or perhaps they will
continue to answer to the village headman, as they have for
generations. Maybe the losers will accept the outcome or maybe the
results will trigger a new wave of demonstrations, followed by
riots and the use of military force.
</P>
<P>
   How effectively will a new government begin the building of
democratic institutions? Will it respond to the public demand for
an end to what is known as KKN _ the Indonesian initials for
corruption, collusion and nepotism?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a transition to democracy as inevitable, despite
the holding of elections,'' said David Timberman, an American
electoral expert. ``There is nothing inexorable about this process.
Its outcomes depend a lot on the leadership and behavior of the new
political parties in Parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard work still lies ahead, said Jusuf Wanandi, the head of
the Center for Strategic and International Studies, an independent
policy institute. ``I am much more optimistic about the election
than about what comes after,'' he said. ``I am dreading the
difficulties we will have in creating a real coalition government _
animosities, jealousies, prima donnas.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, worst-case scenarios have so far not been realized,
beginning with the largely peaceful and raucously enthusiastic
three-week election campaign that is now ending.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts warn that the campaign revelers may be setting
themselves up for harsh disappointments when the results come in.
But Indonesia has shown a great deal more political maturity in the
past year than many people _ notably Suharto _ gave them credit
for.
</P>
<P>
   Just to get as far as this has been an extraordinary
achievement. Indonesia had no revolution. It did not overturn its
government, only the man at the top. It did not change its
constitution or its basic laws, reform its institutions or bring
any but a few low-ranking soldiers to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic reform in Indonesia, so far, floats on air. Yet it is
undeniably a force in play, a clear expression of popular will. The
force appears to have begun building even when Suharto was in
power, and to have burst forth since he departed.
</P>
<P>
   A newly free press has emerged, even as the politically
intrusive military has been humbled and the government has shown a
new responsiveness to public opinion. The elections themselves,
created by Suharto's holdover Parliament, are the results of this
reformist pressure, which the Suharto men who still run Indonesia
have been unable to ignore, political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The country has avoided calamity over the past year, remaining
far more stable than many had expected. A surge of pre-election
violence was widely predicted, but it did not materialize except
for clashes in some already unstable areas. There has been no wave
of religious warfare. Student demonstrators have withdrawn from the
streets to participate in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Though the economy has not recovered yet from a battering during
East Asia's financial crisis a year ago, the harvest has been good
and there have been no food riots; the currency has stabilized at
double its lowest rate 18 months ago and there is a glimmer of hope
for better times.
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesia still lacks the solid middle class that would form
the foundation of a thoroughgoing democracy, said Juwono Sudarsono,
the minister of education and a leading political analyst. Politics
remains a battleground between haves and have-nots and between
factions and ethnic groups, rather than a true discourse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go,'' Juwono said, noting that
Indonesia's middle class is far more shallow than those of the
emerging democracies of Thailand, South Korea or the Philippines.
``It could be 25 years before we can achieve their level of 30
percent of the population being middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   The first free election in a newly independent Indonesia was
also its last, in 1955. Shortly afterward, the country's founding
president, Sukarno, decreed that parliamentary democracy was not
working and instituted in its place an authoritarian model he
called ``guided democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was responding to the political realities of the day but also
to the popular mood, which demanded firm leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that there is a cyclical aspect to this whole
thing, that authoritarianism and democracy are popular at different
times and that we are now in a very anti-authoritarian point in the
cycle,'' said Herbert Feith, an Australian political scientist who
was here during the 1955 election.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he said, new democratic institutions are not yet in place.
But he said the mood of the nation _ the public discourse _ can be
a powerful force in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Suharto crowd lost control of the public discourse, and
the discourse has a life of its own,'' Feith said. Whatever
happens, he suggested, the tide of democratic reform in Indonesia
is not likely to be easily reversed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
