<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5592 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TURKEY-TERMS-REVIEW     06-07 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TURKEY-TERMS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TURKEY, SPEAKING OF KURDISH PROBLEMS, DON'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (Eds: Words in bold should be set in italics.) 
(The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Before the Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah
Ocalan went on trial last Monday, Turkish officials decided to
ensure that the official press would choose its words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan, who is known as Apo, is charged with treason in
connection with his role in organizing and waging the long-running
war between Kurds who inhabit the southeastern part of Turkey and
the Turkish government. Moreover, the Kurdish issue is among the
most sensitive in the country.
</P>
<P>
   So the Interior Ministry issued a directive listing terms that
must not be used when discussing Ocalan, his movement or Kurds in
general. It is binding on reporters and commentators for the
Anatolia news agency, the state-run TRT radio and television
network, and public affairs officers at all government agencies,
though not on reporters for privately owned press outlets or on
foreign correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   In the government's view, violence in Kurdish provinces is
simply terror sponsored from abroad, mainly by Iraq, Syria and
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Officials reject the idea that it is a war, that the insurgent
Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, has any popular base, or that
there is any political aspect to the fighting. They often insist
there is no ``Kurdish problem'' in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Kurdistan Workers Party, however, say that
what has been under way in southeastern Turkey since 1984 is a war
to free Kurds from oppression. The Kurds have been blocked from all
forms of legal protest, they assert, and have taken up arms as a
last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreigners agree, in whole or in part. Turkey's treatment
of its more than 10 million Kurds has been widely criticized
abroad, and has come under new scrutiny during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry directive said that the government needs
to adopt a ``unity of terminology'' in presenting its case to the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking recent developments into consideration,'' it said, ``we
do not want to leave room for future discussions or ill-intentioned
debates stemming from terms that have been used.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the unacceptable terms, followed by what the
government says are correct ones that should be used in their
place:
</P>
<P>
   Guerrilla _  &UR; Terrorist. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Urban guerrilla _  &UR; Terrorist element. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rural guerrilla/Rebel _  &UR; Bandit. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Refugee _  &UR; Shelter seekers. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rebellion/Kurdish uprising/Kurdish rebellion/Kurdish national
independence war/Kurds' independence struggle/revolution/armed
revolt _  &UR; Terrorist actions. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PKK/separatists/separatist gang/separatist groups _  &UR; Terrorist
organization PKK/ Bloody terrorist organization/murder gang. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Operation/military sweep/security operation _  &UR; Search for
terrorists and criminals/pursuit of criminals. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish/of Kurdish background _  &UR; Turkish citizen/our citizens
who are identified as Kurds. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   People of the Kurdish race _  &UR; People from separatist
environments. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Regional commander/governor _  &UR; An official. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Temporary cease-fire _  &UR; Break in terrorist actions/temporary
halt of terror. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Calling for peace _  &UR; Stopping terror actions temporarily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Guerrilla commander _  &UR; Person in charge of regional terrorists. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Apo _  &UR; The terrorist Ocalan. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish militia _  &UR; Those who help and conceal
terrorists/terrorist collaborators. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Leader of the organization _  &UR; Those accountable for terrorist
actions. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Separatist _  &UR; Terrorist. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Separatist organization _  &UR; Terrorist organization. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Marxist-Leninist organization/Marxist-Leninist PKK _  &UR; Terror
organization/Terror organization PKK (NOTE: The fact that the
organization is Marxist-Leninist may be used in personal contacts
abroad.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Crime against humanity _  &UR; Terror crime/mass murder/massacre. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Resident of the Southeast/People of Southeast Anatolia/Eastern
and Southeastern Anatolians _  &UR; Our citizens in the east of Turkey. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish Parliament in Exile _  &UR; Meeting under the terror
organization PKK's control. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Member of Kurdish Parliament _  &UR; Member of the terror
organization. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish flag/so-called Kurdish flag _  &UR; Symbol of the terror
organization. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Low-intensity warfare _  &UR; Fight against terrorism. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish nation _  &UR; Formation in northern Iraq. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi Kurdish leaders _  &UR; Heads of northern Iraqi tribes. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   National assembly/regional assembly _  &UR; Terrorist meetings. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
