u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     06-07 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE PAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
Angeles, phone: 310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Anniversary of Massacre, Silence and Introspection
</P>
<P>
   Beijing marked the 10th anniversary of the massacre at Tiananmen
Square with a nervous silence. Over the last decade, there has been
little public discussion of the incident, which began on the night
of June 3, 1989, and lasted until the morning of June 4.
</P>
<P>
   An unknown number of pro-democracy demonstrators were killed
when tanks rolled in to quell six weeks of protest.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have never given a public accounting of the
death toll; the estimates of witnesses and human rights
organizations range from several hundred to more than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Exiled leaders of the democracy movement, including some who
spent years in prison, gathered at Harvard University to mark the
occasion. They acknowledged mistakes they had made, but insisted
that the movement they began has changed China for the better.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton briefly acknowledged the
anniversary and argued that only by pushing ahead on expanding
trade with Beijing can the United States remain ``a force for
change in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine Die in Arkansas Crash as Plane Lands During Storm
</P>
<P>
   An American Airlines jet crashed on landing in Little Rock,
Ark., killing eight passengers and the pilot. Investigators first
began concentrating on the severe weather, which may have blown the
plane off the runway, but it soon became clear that the reason for
the incident may be far more complex. Federal officials said some
of the plane's braking devices did not appear to have been properly
set up. Although the pilot was experienced, he had been on duty
near the maximum of 14 hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID FIRESTONE
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Officials Move to Lift Ban on the Pill
</P>
<P>
   In a major step toward approving the birth control pill, Japan's
top medical advisory council suddenly reversed its position and
recommended allowing the pill to be sold. Japan is the only
industrialized country to ban the pill, and the issue has been
debated for decades. Some feminists argue that the ban reflects
male domination of Japanese society and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The case for the pill got a lift recently from the speedy
approval of Viagra, which treats impotence in men. That provoked an
uproar from women's groups who demanded that the pill also be
approved. The pill could be available this fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHERYL WuDUNN
</P>
<P>
   European Nations Vote to Become Military Power
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's 15 member nations decided to become a
single military power and to appoint a single foreign and security
policy official.
</P>
<P>
   By late 2000, according to a plan announced at the European
Summit in Cologne, Germany, the European leaders would establish a
command headquarters and a joint force for peacekeeping missions in
future crises like those in Kosovo and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Making the European Union a military power would enable NATO
members, as well as several nations that are not members of NATO,
to mount their own campaigns without having to rely on American
might.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch to Offer Trading on the Internet
</P>
<P>
   The thundering herd just made a sharp U-turn. For more than two
decades, Merrill Lynch, the United States' biggest stock brokers,
scoffed at ``do it yourself'' discount investing.
</P>
<P>
   But recently even some of Merrill's well-heeled clients have
been lured by the excitement _ and far lower commissions _ of
trading for themselves on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6 million households now trade stocks over the
Internet, accounting for one in every seven stock trades in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   So the brokerage bent to the pressures of the Internet era and
said it would introduce a flat rate of $29.95 per trade on the
World Wide Web. Just don't ask for any advice.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAUL HANSELL
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble Withdraws Offer to Buy Ingram
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble, the United States' biggest bookseller, decided
to withdraw its $600 million offer to buy Ingram Book Group, the
largest book wholesaler, after federal officials prepared to
challenge the deal on antitrust grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a victory for smaller bookstores, which have
grown dependent on Ingram. They had argued that they would be put
in a perilous position if their main competitor also owned their
primary supplier.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters Strike Averted
</P>
<P>
   James P. Hoffa, the Teamsters' new president, had his first
chance to demonstrate that he could be a heavyweight at the
bargaining table like his famous father, James R. Hoffa. The
younger Hoffa received respectable marks for negotiating a contract
for 12,800 workers who haul new cars to dealers. In an era when
companies are cutting retirement benefits, he won higher pensions,
health coverage for workers who retire at age 55 and prescription
benefits for retirees over 65.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Worries Over Muscle Drug
</P>
<P>
   Scientists were surprised _ and concerned. Iowa State University
researchers conducted tests on androstenedione, the drug Mark
McGwire said he used on his way to becoming baseball's home run
king. And around which a multimillion-dollar business sprang up on
claims that it builds muscle.
</P>
<P>
   In natural form, it converts to testosterone, which does build
muscle. The scientists put 30 young men on 100 milligrams, some on
placebos; some on weight training, some not. The finding: No
increase in testosterone or muscle, but increases in estrogen,
which can cause pancreatic cancer and heart disease in men. The
implication: a possible ban if larger studies corroborate the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   _ HOLCOMB B. NOBLE
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Ordered to Jail in Olympic Bomb Case
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta judge ordered two reporters for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution to be jailed for refusing to reveal the
sources who told them that Richard Jewell, a part-time security
guard, was a leading suspect in the bombing at the 1996 Summer
Olympic Games in Atlanta. Another man has been charged in the
bombing, and Jewell is suing the newspaper for libel. Peter
Canfield, the attorney for the newspaper, has filed an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton Edges Closer
</P>
<P>
   The curtain lifted a few more inches on Hillary Rodham Clinton's
plans _ though not, it would seem, by the first lady's choice. Rep.
Nita Lowey, the Westchester County Democrat who had said she would
run for the Senate from New York if Mrs. Clinton did not, called
Mrs. Clinton to inform her that she was giving up and would instead
run for the House.
</P>
<P>
   And Mrs. Clinton did nothing to talk her out of it. If that
wasn't a clear enough sign that the first lady has settled on
running, Mrs. Clinton made it clearer Friday morning, announcing
that she would form an exploratory committee in early July.
</P>
<P>
   _ ADAM NAGOURNEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
