<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-CO     06-07 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A word on behalf of pork barrel politics
 &HT;    For release June 9, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it's time to take another, softer look at pork barrel
politics, that long-deprecated practice of Washington lawmakers
bringing the bacon to the folks back home.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, it was not a custom I favored (except when it
came to my own ZIP code), but you might say I have been bombed back
to reality.
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Clinton asked the Congress for $6 billion to prosecute
the war in Yugoslavia, the GOP-dominated body told the president
that it was not enough: ``Here, take $12 billion,'' was the
collective response.
</P>
<P>
   Another $6 billion had been found so easily and quickly and it
just makes you wonder how big the pile of money is that Congress
sits upon and, in turn, why all the carping about pork barrel
politics?
</P>
<P>
   What is all that wrong with a piece of bacon for, say,
Pascagoula, Miss., to keep hundreds of Americans on the job at the
shipbuilding yard there? Why is it wasteful to provide a
billion-dollar loan program for embattled American steel companies?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, there seem to be many abuses. Such as $750,000
for grasshopper research in Alaska. That sounds ridiculous to us,
but what do we know about it? Are grasshoppers destroying whatever
crops there are in Alaska? Are they impacting the economy severely?
Is it meaningful to the people of Alaska, whose taxes go to
Washington to be part of doubling the appropriation for bombing
Yugoslavia?
</P>
<P>
   News stories talk about red-faced legislators sorting through
fine print and finding pork in the form of a $4 million grant for a
forestry research center at Auburn University in Alabama, and $5
million for a law enforcement academy in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, none of it's in my back yard. But I sure wasn't
carping when those federal funds were pouring into my area, South
Florida, more than a decade ago to build a rapid transit system
that Ronald Reagan, as president, continually ridiculed. (He said
he could have hired limousines for all the riders and spent less
money in doing so.)
</P>
<P>
   What pork barrel does is return to states, cities,
neighborhoods, some of the taxes that were sent up to Washington
that are sitting around doing nothing else _ or we wouldn't have $6
billion extra available to double the president's request.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about whether we should or should not wage battle
with the Serbs, it's about money _ where it is, where it's been
hiding and who should get it _ or at least some of it.
</P>
<P>
   One can go down a list of what social programs can be helped
immeasurably by a boost of $6 billion and come up with dozens.
</P>
<P>
   Was that rainy-day money the president and the Congress gave
away? If a part of the U.S. is ravaged by a hurricane, a flood and
an earthquake, will there be enough money left in Uncle Sam's piggy
bank to help out, or did it all go to the bombs for Yugoslavia?
</P>
<P>
   I'm quite certain that beyond the $6 billion, there's plenty
left.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me back to those pork barrel projects,
appropriations slipped into legislation by lawmakers trying to do
something for the folks who sent them up to Capitol Hill, the
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   As time and change ravage what had been their incomes and
industries, a little boost from the piggy bank is pretty important
to them. Especially when you know that $12 billion can be plucked
out of the air to fight a foreign war.
</P>
<P>
   And since we've got all that surplus, I must ask, whatever
happened to that hefty tax cut the young GOP crusaders were going
to get us?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
