u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX     06-07 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Sensible ruling on school sexual harassment
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent common-sense Supreme Court ruling on schoolhouse
sexual harassment has driven even normally sane conservatives into
great curlicues of loopiness, composed in about equal parts of
ridicule, outrage and panic.
</P>
<P>
   The court held that in especially aggravated cases, parents can
sue a school for failing to take reasonable steps to stop egregious
sexual harassment by a classmate. The Georgia case involved a
fifth-grade girl who, she says, was for months groped, grabbed and
sexually taunted by a boy. The girl's mother says the school failed
to respond usefully to her repeated pleas for intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Whether all of this is true can now be worked out in a civil
suit. The fact that the boy eventually pleaded guilty to sexual
battery gives provisional credence to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem almost self-evident that schools, which after all
exist for the welfare of their students, could be held to account
when they are in negligent or willful default in that stewardship.
The court agreed, though thinly, 5 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, this is a conservative court. The dissenting four are
simply more conservative than the conservative majority.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you'd think the gates of a liberal hell had been loosed and
left-wing devils set free. This, as some commentators have it, is
political correctness run amok. Schools will be bankrupted if a boy
chases a girl on the playground, and the boy will be branded a
harasser for life. Flirtation will go to court _ and flirts to
juvie hall? Blowing a kiss will be forbidden. If unwanted advances
are actionable, isn't it just a matter of time until courts flip
the coin and let rejected suitors sue for the emotional hurt of the
rejection?
</P>
<P>
   And on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Give the eagerly worried two points: Piranha lawyers will swarm
to this new blood, as if we weren't litigious enough already. And
school administrations, which as a rule are not the first place you
look for intelligence, are perfectly capable of turning overwrought
legal worries into idiot codes of conduct. We all remember with a
cringe the fool North Carolina principal who kicked out a
6-year-old boy as a sexual harasser for kissing a little girl on
her cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Parental, voter and PTA prudence can control the latter impulse,
and the court emphasized it was not licensing the former.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the majority, said that to be
liable a school must have ``actual knowledge'' of ``severe,
pervasive and objective harassment'' and show ``deliberate
indifference'' to it. And the misbehavior must be so severe it
impairs its victim's learning.
</P>
<P>
   These are very high bars. The lawyer for the National School
Boards Association _ believe me, no lefty outfit _ says such
occasions will be rare.
</P>
<P>
   No one, certainly not the court majority, holds that schools
should be liable for the inchoate sexuality of childhood. Equally,
though, schools should not be in the business of teaching, by their
forfeit, that it is the lot of girls to put up, abandoned, with
gross and open-ended sexual imposition.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
