<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISAAC-HAYES-IN-SOUTH-     06-07 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISAAC-HAYES-IN-SOUTH-PARK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIL TO THE CHEF: ISAAC HAYES ON `SOUTH PARK,' `SHAFT,' MUSIC AND
MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of actor/singer Isaac Hayes.) 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Call him an entertainer.
 &HT;    ``That pretty much encapsulates the whole thing,'' Isaac Hayes
says. ``I don't say I'm a 
composer/writer/arranger/musician/producer/DJ/voiceover-person/actor
.
 &HT;    ``Just saying I'm an entertainer covers it all,'' he says, ``and
I've been at it for 40 years. I paid my dues and worked hard. I've
had my ups and downs and my setbacks, and I'm still in it.''
 &HT;    Blessed with a voice that's deep, silky and soulful, Hayes has
sold millions of albums, winning two Grammys and an Oscar for ``The
Theme from Shaft'' in 1972. He's also acted in 28 movies, including
``Truck Turner'' (1974) and ``It Could Happen to You'' (1994), and
guest-starred on television shows ranging from ``The A-Team'' to
``The Rockford Files.''
 &HT;    These days, the 56-year-old multiple-threat artist is enjoying
an unlikely surge in popularity with college students and preteens,
thanks to his role as Chef, the libidinous, crooning cook in Comedy
Central's still-hot, still-controversial animated series, ``South
Park.''
 &HT;    The show centers on the rude, potty-mouthed escapades of Kenny,
Cartman, Kyle and Stan, third-grade boys with a fondness for
flatulence, sex, death and anal probes. As Chef, Hayes provides the
show's only modestly cool adult presence.
 &HT;    But the small screen is only the beginning. On June 18, ``South
Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone _ along with Hayes and
guest voices Eric Idle, George Clooney and Minnie Driver _ reach
for the brass ring with a big-screen enterprise entitled ``South
Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut.''
 &HT;    ``I'd never done animation before,'' Hayes says by cellular
telephone while on the road somewhere in New York. ``I actually
always wanted to do it, and had my sights set on a more Disneylike
type of animation.
 &HT;    ``I never imagined that I'd be doing this cartoon for television
that would become a movie,'' he says. ```South Park' just hit, and
it caught everybody by surprise.
 &HT;    ``Chef is a lovable character,'' he adds. ``He's endearing to a
lot of women and men _ men because he says things they want to say
and women because he's very candid. He'll say, `I'll make sweet
love, right now.'
 &HT;    ``I think of Chef as my alter-ego.''
 &HT;    Hayes chuckles, but ``South Park's'' popularity is no laughing
matter for the many infuriated parents who blame the show for
corrupting America's children. One kid, in a much-reported
incident, even set a fire after watching an episode two years ago.
 &HT;    Hayes, a thrice-divorced father of 11 children and grandfather
of 14, argues that those pointing fingers should actually be
peering long and hard into a mirror.
 &HT;    ```South Park' is an adult cartoon, totally an adult cartoon,''
he says. ``Adults love it, but kids got ahold of it. It's up to the
parents to not allow kids to see it.
 &HT;    ``Parents let kids see it,'' he says. ``I've got parents
bringing kids to me to sign autographs on all sorts of `South Park'
paraphernalia. What do you do? What do you say?
 &HT;    ``Kids are not stupid,'' he adds, warming to his topic.
``They're people. Treat them like little people. They know right
from wrong.''
 &HT;    Hayes is on a roll.
 &HT;    ``When we were kids, we said `s--t' and `f--k' behind the backs
of our parents, our teachers and our preachers,'' he says. ``We did
all of that, and most of us didn't turn out too bad.
 &HT;    ``So kids know. You've got to give them credit.''
 &HT;    Beyond ``South Park,'' Hayes has several other irons in the
fire, including radio, music and movie ventures, as well as a pet
charitable cause.
 &HT;    ``I've got a radio show on KISS in New York that I do five days
a week, and I'm doing some acting,'' he says. ``I'm in `Reindeer
Games' with Ben Affleck, Gary Sinise and Clarence Williams, which
John Frankenheimer directed _ I play a crazy man in a prison.
 &HT;    ``I did a song for the `South Park' soundtrack,'' he continues,
``and I'm working on my own CD, which I hope will be out in 2000.
I'll be doing a few concert appearances during the summer, and I'm
also the international spokesperson for the World Literacy
Crusade'' _ an effort to ease poverty, crime and hopelessness by
increasing literacy in inner cities around the world.
 &HT;    ``I'm busy,'' he sums up. ``I'm working seven days a week,
practically.''
 &HT;    That wasn't always the case, however. Not long ago, Hayes felt
as if the world had passed him by.
 &HT;    ``The lowest point was in the 1980s,'' he says. ``Record
companies turned on classic soul artists and left us hanging out to
dry to go with the hip-hop generation. It turns out the hip-hop
guys were sampling us so much that they had to turn back to us and
give us our props.
 &HT;    ``I didn't mind things being hard in my early days, when I was
starting out,'' he adds. ``Everybody's got to come out of
nonexistence. You've got to take on challenges and make a lot of
sacrifices, but victory is sweet when you come by it that way.
 &HT;    ``It was tougher to deal with being abandoned by the record
companies,'' Hayes admits. ``But things are all right now. They are
all right.''
 &HT;    As the old saying has it, what goes around comes around, so it's
no surprise that a new version of ``Shaft'' is in the works, to
star Samuel L. Jackson under the direction of John Singleton. Hayes
may be involved in the film _ acting, handling the music or doing
both _ but nothing has been decided.
 &HT;    ``John and I have spoken several times, but he plays his cards
close to the chest,'' Hayes says. ``He doesn't make any kind of
commitment. If they use me to do the music, that'll be fine. John
knows where to reach me, but I won't hold my breath.
 &HT;    ``I do like the idea of redoing `Shaft,''' he admits. ``It was
such a huge success, and it initiated a lot of things for a lot of
people in the 1970s. But it's got to have a very powerful script,
because there have been so many great action movies since `Shaft'
came out.''
 &HT;    As the conversation comes to an end, Hayes' thoughts flit back
to Covington, Tenn., the small town in which he was born. To him it
represents both his past and, quite possibly, his future.
 &HT;    ``Every now and again I go back there,'' he says warmly. ``I
look at the land where I was born. There used to be a tin-top house
where I lived. That was my beginnings, and I have fond memories of
those days. They stay with me and they keep my feet on the
ground.''
 &HT;    He pauses in thought.
 &HT;    ``That area is growing fast now,'' Hayes says, ``and I was
thinking of going back there, buying me some property and building
myself a farm or a ranch. I like life in the city, but I'm a
country boy at heart.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
