<SLUG> BC-POP-SINGER-BRITNEY-SPEARS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUBBLE-GUM GODDESS: BRITNEY SPEARS AND THE MAKING OF AN ADOLESCENT
IDOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of pop singer Britney Spears.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    They may be making her into a teen idol, but Britney Spears
isn't taking it lying down.
 &HT;    Actually, she was for a while, but she's back on her feet now,
and she isn't letting controversy stand in her way.
 &HT;    While the 17-year-old singer was convalescing from a dislocated
left leg, injured while stretching before a dance rehearsal for a
video, her debut album, ``Baby One More Time,'' spent four of the
first six weeks after its January release at No. 1 atop the
Billboard charts, selling nearly 200,000 copies a week.
 &HT;    You couldn't turn on the radio without hearing Spears' first
single, the album's title track. Meanwhile, overnight its
midriff-baring video turned Spears into a sex symbol for the
pubescent set.
 &HT;    Needless to say, it made the pain of her injury a lot more
bearable.
 &HT;    ``I'm, like, really thankful, really, really happy about
everything,'' the Kentwood, La., native says. ``I never really
expected for it to go to No. 1. With the single doing so well, I
was just going to be happy if it went on the charts at, like, No.
47 or something.
 &HT;    ``When they called and told me, I was sleeping,'' she adds, ``so
I thought they meant the single went to No. 1. Then they said, `No,
your album,' and I was completely overwhelmed. I called everyone.''
 &HT;    At the same time, Spears says she isn't surprised that her music
has found a ready market, especially in the wake of young, male
vocal groups such as the Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync.
 &HT;    ``That is on the radio all the time,'' she says. ``I think
people feel it would be nice to hear a change, to hear a girl
sound. I think the audience, the public, wants to hear it.''
 &HT;    Her success may have come overnight, but Spears didn't exactly
come out of nowhere. She's been singing publicly since kindergarten
_ shyly, she adds _ and plowed through the talent-contest circuit
as a tot. Her first show-business audition was for ``The Mickey
Mouse Club'' at age 8. Told she was too young, Spears moved to New
York, where she studied at the Off-Broadway Dance Center and the
Professional Performing Arts School, filmed some television
commercials and appeared in the hit Off-Broadway comedy
``Ruthless.''
 &HT;    Three years later, she was finally accepted to ``The Mickey
Mouse Club,'' on which she appeared for two years with future 'N
Sync members Justin Timberlake and J.C. Chasez. It was a good
connection to make _ Spears later opened for the group on a tour
prior to her album's release.
 &HT;    Even now, Spears appreciates what ``The Mickey Mouse Club'' did
for her.
 &HT;    ``We got to sing, dance and act,'' Spears says. ``That's when I
realized I love to sing the best and I love to perform, and that's
what I really wanted to focus on.''
 &HT;    After the show's sudden cancellation, Spears _ who has two
siblings, ``so cute'' 8-year-old Jamie Lynn and 21-year-old Bryan,
who she says is on the protective side _ returned to Kentwood for a
``normal'' year of school. That's normal, as opposed to her touring
schedule, when she's accompanied by an adult friend of the family
as chaperon/tutor.
 &HT;    At the end of the school year she headed back to New York, where
she landed a deal with Jive Records in short order. The company
hooked her up with producers Eric Foster and Max Martin. Martin, a
Backstreet Boys veteran, wrote ``Baby One More Time,'' and as soon
as Jive executives played the song for her, Spears smelled a hit.
 &HT;    ``I went into the office, and all of a sudden they have this
song and I'm totally blown away,'' she recalls. ``I was totally
flattered Max Martin would allow me to sing that song.''
 &HT;    The song certainly kicked doors open for Spears, though it
raised a number of other issues as well. The lyrics of her songs
are mildly suggestive at most, but her videos and photo sessions
have made her as much a teen-dream pinup as any of her male
counterparts.
 &HT;    A brazen, cheesecake spread for a recent Rolling Stone story
drew controversy over its use of schoolgirl props to accompany
highly seductive poses, and a recent television appearance on a
Nickelodeon awards show drew criticism _ and at least one sponsor
withdrawal _ over Spears' performance, clearly without a bra.
 &HT;    The combination of overt sexuality and preteen ambiance has
troubled many observers, but Spears says she's comfortable with her
role as a sex symbol.
 &HT;    ``The first time I saw that there were even guys that were
interested was when I went down to MTV to do the request thing, and
there were so many guys down there,'' says Spears, who's currently
without a boyfriend. ``I'd never seen that, because I'm so used to
opening for 'N Sync and seeing all these girls.
 &HT;    ``And all of a sudden I went to MTV and there were all these
guys and it hit me, `Oh my goodness!'
 &HT;    ``It's cute and flattering,'' she says, ``because they have
their little shirts, all saying `Can you go to the prom with me?'
It's really cute ... But I think after a while it'll probably be
annoying.''
 &HT;    Even now, Spears adds, it's caused her to become a bit more wary
about who she hangs out with, though she spends most of her time
with people who were friends before she became a pop sensation.
 &HT;    ``When I come home I see my main friends,'' she says, ``but I
really don't tell anybody I'm coming home, because if I did I'd
have to go visit 9 million people. So I just kind of sneak home and
totally relax.
 &HT;    ``My sister's little friends, when they're over here, it's like
really weird,'' the singer adds, ``because they'll see me and come
and give me a really big hug, and they're, like, staring at you.
It's kind of funny.''
 &HT;    This summer will bring Spears' closest encounter with her fans
to date, as she mounts her first tour as a headliner _ a
song-and-dance extravaganza with a full band, rather than the taped
backup she performed to when she toured with 'N Sync.
 &HT;    With tickets selling out nationwide _ thanks in part to
producers' decision to book smaller theaters rather than arenas _
the tour shows all the signs of being yet another high point in
what has so far been a remarkably easy climb to the top.
 &HT;    ``I guess it has been, yeah,'' Spears acknowledges. ``The worst
thing about the business, I think, is just the traveling and being
overseas and being so far away from home. But other than that, I
haven't really experienced anything really bad.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
