<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNIFER-LOPEZ-STEPS-TO-THE-MIKE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE RECORD: JENNIFER LOPEZ HAS MUSIC ON HER MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jennifer Lopez from her album, ``On the
6.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Let's assume that Jennifer Lopez can sing. It isn't enough that
she's a gorgeous movie star, famous and rich beyond most people's
wildest dreams _ the highest-paid Latina in Hollywood _ so let's
assume that she can sing, too.
 &HT;    What would she sing?
 &HT;    Well, to judge by her just-released debut album, ``On the 6,''
she'd sing an exhilarating mix of rhythm-and-blues songs plus dance
grooves. She'd even co-write three of the cuts.
 &HT;    That's right _ let's assume that Jennifer Lopez can write songs.
 &HT;    ``The music is a little like me,'' the actress-turned-singer
says. ``It's street, but there is also a soft side.''
 &HT;    The dominant voice on the album is that of a young woman fired
by determination to get everything life has to offer.
 &HT;    ``If I had to describe myself in one word, it would be `strong'
_ I've always wanted to sing and I always go after what I want,''
says the 29-year-old star of the films ``Selena'' (1997) and ``Out
of Sight'' (1998).
 &HT;    The Bronx-born Lopez says that ``On the 6'' is intensely
personal, right down to its title.
 &HT;    ``The 6 is a train I used to take from the Bronx into Manhattan
for music and dance lessons,'' she says. ``It's my journey. But
what I love about the title is that the 6 is also a way to get back
home.''
 &HT;    The release of her first album comes as no surprise to her fans.
Lopez fell in love with singing after playing the title role in the
movie ``Selena'' _ though she was allowed only to lip-sync to the
slain superstar's own recordings.
 &HT;    But Lopez was serious enough about singing to invest her own
money to cut a demo record in Spanish and submit it to Sony's
specialty Work label. They loved it, but had a suggestion. Why not
sing the songs in English, to add crossover appeal?
 &HT;    Lopez didn't mind, though the Spanish market alone can be enough
to launch a hit CD. By 2009 Latinos will be the largest minority
group in the United States. American sales of Latin music neared
$600 million in 1998, and are 46 percent higher this year.
 &HT;    But the novice singer relished the chance to reach non-Hispanic
audiences, which she says are increasingly open to Latin music.
 &HT;    ``I think people are really getting into this music because the
passion of it is undeniable,'' Lopez says. ``I want to introduce
people to music with a Latin flavor. I'll throw in a line where you
can learn about my people. I want to throw in a little Spanish
guitar and bongo.''
 &HT;    Singing connects her with something inside herself, Lopez adds.
 &HT;    ``My mom used to take me to dance class at age 5,'' she recalls,
``but I was much more interested in the singing. I studied acting,
but deep in my heart I always wanted to sing. It is my first love _
I think with music you can truly offer something beautiful.''
 &HT;    Of course, she isn't quitting her day job as a movie star. In
films such as ``Money Train'' (1995), ``Anaconda'' (1997), ``Blood
and Wine'' (1997) and ``U-Turn'' (1997), Lopez has captivated
moviegoers with her in-your-face, fiery charm.
 &HT;    In the process, she's brought a welcome Latina presence to a
film industry which for most of its history has been a whites-only
preserve. Growing up in the Bronx, daughter of a kindergarten
teacher and a computer specialist, Lopez's favorite film featured a
Latina character played by the very Caucasian Natalie Wood.
 &HT;    ``I sat through `West Side Story' about 37 times,'' she says,
``because it was the only movie about my people.''
 &HT;    Lopez saw herself in the classic 1961 film, but not in its
heroine. She preferred the peppery character played by Rita Moreno.
 &HT;    ``I never wanted to be that wimpy Maria, who sits around pining
for her guy,'' she recalls. ``Who needs it? I wanted to be Anita,
who danced her way to the top.''
 &HT;    Dancing worked for Lopez, who was only 21 when she was hired as
a Fly Girl on television's ``In Living Color.'' Her big-screen
debut came in Gregory Nava's ``My Family'' (1995), when she was 25.
 &HT;    ``I've always wanted to do things fast,'' Lopez says. ``It's
like I have a fire in me.''
 &HT;    Only two years later, her role as the slain Tejano star Selena
put her on the map.
 &HT;    ``Ever since playing her, I've had people come up and say, `Look
what you've done for our people _ you've given us a part of our
hero back,''' Lopez says. ``That has been extremely rewarding.''
 &HT;    Last summer she scored in a sexy turn opposite George Clooney in
``Out of Sight.'' She still gets asked about the extended scene in
which she and the ``E.R.'' star got up close and personal in a car
trunk _ and talked about old movies, not only in the film but in
real life.
 &HT;    ``The trunk was pretty cramped and uncomfortable,'' she recalls.
``We would lie there in the dark and talk about movies between
takes. Part of you couldn't wait for it to be over.''
 &HT;    Lopez may make movies and CDs, but much of the press seems most
interested in her love life, particularly following the end of her
brief marriage to waiter-turned-club-manager Ojani Noa. A
persistent rumor has linked her with rapper Sean ``Puff Daddy''
Combs.
 &HT;    ``We're just friends,'' Lopez says with a sigh. ``The gossip is
horrible, but I don't want to defend myself.''
 &HT;    In a way, she says, her marriage, which took place just before
the success of ``Selena,'' protected her from the full impact of
stardom.
 &HT;    ``Now it's weird,'' she says. ``I'm single. So if I show up in a
club and I'm there with Oscar de la Hoya or Puff Daddy, it's news _
I read that I'm dating these men. Meanwhile, I'm wondering, `Can't
I just talk to people anymore without it being a big thing?'''
 &HT;    The flip side of her fame is that, especially since winning
critical acclaim in a non-ethnic role in ``Out of Sight,'' Lopez is
finding her way out of the typecasting that threatens most minority
performers.
 &HT;    ``Now I get roles that just say `the woman' and not `the
Hispanic woman,''' she says. ``I love movies where race doesn't
come up even once _ I can do a role and people won't even think
about it. And that's the way it should be.''
 &HT;    Otherwise, she says, the perks of stardom are overrated.
 &HT;    ``You know, I don't have any habits,'' she says. ``I don't
smoke, I don't drink, I don't do cars or houses.''
 &HT;    Well, maybe she has one habit, she admits, raising a stylish
foot onto a nearby chair. When it comes to buying shoes, she could
give Imelda Marcos a few pointers. And making movie-star money does
come in handy that way.
 &HT;    ``The day you buy your first pair of $500 Dolce &AMP; Gabbana shoes,
you're like, `Ohhhh, I'm in heaven,''' Lopez purrs. ``I don't even
wear some of these shoes _ I save them. I just look at them.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``On the 6,'' consult the Sony
Music Website at www.music.sony.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
