<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGER-SARAH-MCLACHLA     06-07 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-SARAH-MCLACHLAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SARAH McLACHLAN: LILITH'S LEAD LADY IS MOMMY-MINDED  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer/songwriter Sarah McLachlan.) 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talking about Sarah McLachlan these days, the phrase that people
keep coming back to is ``one-woman industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider her workload: Most people would be content with her
upcoming special for Canadian television and her new live album,
``The Mirror Ball,'' to be released June 15. But McLachlan also
recently co-authored the cookbook ``Plenty,'' and is currently
preparing for her third tour with Lilith Fair, the annual summer
music festival she created and still runs. Lilith is set for more
than 40 North American dates, starting in July and ending in time
for her to catch her breath before a mini-Lilith tour of Australia
in December.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, on top of all that Sarah McLachlan is trying to
have a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wee bit crazy,'' she admits with a laugh. ``I seem to
like piling the stuff on lately. I guess I've just gotten used to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the third and final Lilith,'' she says. ``We had
a three-year plan right from the beginning, just because we knew
how much work was involved to make it happen. It's incredibly
rewarding, but it's an awful lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we're all sort of selfish now,'' McLachlan adds.
``We're all in our 30s, and we want to have kids. So it was Lilith
or kids. You can't do both _ it's too much work.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old singer is quick to point out, however, that
she's hardly shopping for baby clothes just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan for my life to stop as soon as I get pregnant,''
she says firmly, ``and that's if I get pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan is as refreshingly direct in person as she is in her
music. For example, she says she doesn't spend a lot of time
reading her clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I say things, I don't tend to read much of my own press
or anything,'' she says. ``I already said it, so why would I do
that? I think it's amusing, generally, that people are so
interested in me.''
</P>
<P>
   That same cut-to-the-chase frankness jumps off the screen in
McLachlan's television special, which combines performances of
close to a dozen of her favorite songs _ filmed last year before a
capacity crowd in Portland, Ore. _ with candid backstage footage
and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really exciting to film this special,'' she says.
``There were eight cameras whizzing around the whole time. It helps
things when you're being filmed and being immortalized _ you damn
well do a good job. So there's definitely a higher level of
excitement than normal. It raises the stakes.''
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan is coming off what by any standards would have to
count as a bizarre year. For one thing, she found herself in court
being sued over songwriting credits on four songs from her first
album, ``Touch,'' in a case since settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was her surreal-if-peripheral involvement in the
recent White House sex scandal, in which Kenneth Starr's report to
Congress revealed that McLachlan's music played a part in the
affair between Bill Clinton and White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
Both the president and the intern identified with McLachlan's
haunting, romantic lyrics, the Starr report said, and the two
discussed them at length.
</P>
<P>
   Even by the standards of rock 'n' roll, that was a strange thing
to have happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all just so funny to me,'' McLachlan says, laughing. ``I
missed a lot of that because I was in England at the time. The
story hit just when I got to London, so people started asking me
about it. But it was all secondhand to me _ I kind of missed that
whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and his mistress are far from McLachlan's only
fans _ she's had four gold records and a five-year streak of top-40
hits such as ``Sweet Surrender,'' ``I Will Remember You'' and
``Surfacing.'' In her own quiet way, the Canadian-born singer ranks
right up there with Celine, Shania and Alanis among the top female
exports from north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of McLachlan's mainstream appeal came in May, when her
wrenching love song ``I Will Remember You'' was featured in its
entirety in the season finales of both ``Melrose Place'' and
``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say there's a lot of creative license involved in
these songs,'' McLachlan says, ``but often there's a lot of me in
them as well. People are always asking me what a song is about, and
I'll say to them, `What does it mean to you?' Because that's what's
important.''
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan's own life, which has had its share of troubles, fuels
her music. She grew up in Halifax, Nova Scotia, as a skinny,
introverted girl who studied piano and guitar. An adoptee, she
didn't meet her birth mother until she was 19, around the same time
that she signed her first record contract, with the renegade
Canadian label Nettwerk Records.
</P>
<P>
   The hits started coming fast and furious, and all of a sudden
the young singer was on MTV, magazine covers and ``The Tonight Show
with Jay Leno.'' McLachlan struck a particular chord with Leno _
she'll make her ninth appearance on June 18, singing ``I Will
Remember'' to boost the live CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just so sweet to me,'' McLachlan says of the ``Tonight
Show'' crew. ``They keep asking me back. And it's a great
promotional tool _ you get a huge TV audience, and that's always a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Given her wide-eyed beauty and wholesome presence, it's not
surprising that McLachlan has already been approached by Hollywood
types interested in steering her onto the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are phoning me up about it these days,'' she
says dubiously. ``I don't know about the acting thing. I'd probably
start laughing. I don't know if I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it's not as if McLachlan were looking for anything more
to pencil into her already crowded schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``October is looking rather free right now,'' she says
hopefully, ``and I'm hoping to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband/drummer, Ashwin Sood, recently bought their
dream house in North Vancouver, British Columbia. Until Lilith
kicks into full gear in July, McLachlan says she's happy to simply
hang out there and get to know the area between Lilith planning
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, I hiked in the mountains,'' she says excitedly,
``and there was like 20 feet of snow. Then I drove 15 minutes back
to Vancouver and swam in my pool, because it was sunny and warm.
It's unbelievable to have those two worlds so close together.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a great world in which to raise a child, she thinks, and
with all the complexities involved in her ever-expanding music
empire, McLachlan admits that that's mostly where her thoughts are
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about being a mom,'' she says quietly.
``I've thought about that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Sarah McLachlan, consult her
official Website at www.sarahmclachlan.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
