<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: A diamond in the rough
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The responsibilities of management are heavy. It's
a reality our youngest son quickly learned after his classmates
voted him to be coach of their softball team for the school's
spring tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Coming home from school that day, his excitement soon gave way
to feverish planning. Hunched over a diagram of a baseball diamond
at the kitchen table, he peppered me with questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the shortstop play?'' he asked. Keep in mind, this is
our soccer son. He's played hours of softball in our back yard with
friends and family, but he's never actually stepped onto a Little
League field and he's not exactly well-versed in the intricacies of
the game
</P>
<P>
   . . . like where the shortstop plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between second and third,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to believe I didn't know what I was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure it's not between first and second?'' he
countered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Positive.''
</P>
<P>
   As the mother of three boys, I learned long ago not to be
offended when they automatically assume that, because I'm ``a
girl,'' I know nothing.
</P>
<P>
   What this son doesn't know is that his father dragged me to
countless baseball games during and after our courtship. I know
where the shortstop plays, son. I also know baseball can be as
exciting as watching worms crawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many fielders are there?'' he asked next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine,'' I answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he moaned, ``I have to get 26 players on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, the school softball tournament has rules all its own.
Everyone in the class plays the whole 25-minute game. You carefully
decide who plays the regular positions, then scatter the other
players around like salt on popcorn. Three pitches per batter,
delivered by one of your own teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the tournament, each class wore different-colored
bandanas to distinguish teams. Hordes of children took to the
numerous makeshift softball fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could a ball possibly drop with that many kids in the
field?'' I asked my husband.
</P>
<P>
   It could, and did _ many times. Like any random school class,
there were star athletes and kids who had never picked up a
softball in their lives. I was impressed, watching from the
sidelines, how the kids encouraged the weakest players, shouting
out ``Good swing.'' ``Nice try.'' ``You'll get it next time!''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it made for mixed results. Our son dealt with the
dilemmas of upper management _ everything from loose bandanas to
jammed thumbs to near-uprisings over who plays where. It didn't
help that his class lost its first three games. A team meeting was
called between games and our son reassigned positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have to play center field?'' one boy moaned.
</P>
<P>
   I was proud to hear our son counter not with a dictum, but a
question: ``What position would you like to play?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' the other child said. Sizing up the situation
as unwarranted grumbling, his coach said, ``No, I need you in
center field.'' Nice reply.
</P>
<P>
   The class won its next two games, playing wonderfully. The last
game was close, with our team leading until a slugger from the
other team hit the ball a country mile, knocking in three runs to
win.
</P>
<P>
   After a rallying meeting with their teacher, the class dispersed
and our son walked over to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we do now?'' I asked, since we were now eliminated
from the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch,'' he said, handing over to me _ gladly, I think _
his coaching bandana. As he walked off with his classmates, he
turned and asked a final question:
</P>
<P>
   ``When does soccer season start?''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
