<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: `Roadshow' and eBay slow cleaning
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ ``The Antiques Roadshow'' has seized my
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I've never watched the program all the way through.
It's not the sort of show one looks for ahead of time. It's a show
that beckons weary channel surfers after they discover everything
on the other 37 channels is aimed at hipper, younger demographic
segments.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its third season, ``The Antiques Roadshow'' is becoming
something of a public-television cult. Not as much as ``This Old
House,'' but I'll take it over any British sitcom or the guy with
'70s hair who shows you how to paint trees.
</P>
<P>
   It consists of kindly experts appraising stuff regular folks
haul out of their attics, closet boxes and garages. Many of these
things turn out to be amazingly valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners of these newly identified treasures take the news
with a handshake and a grin. Others as though they've won a beauty
pageant. And unlike ``The Jerry Springer Show,'' nobody has tried
to beat up an appraiser yet.
</P>
<P>
   The usual scene is an owner of a mystery object standing
expectantly by an antiques expert who displays the item for the
camera and holds forth on its fascinating and unexpected history.
</P>
<P>
   Expert: ``Yes, this lovely piece of ceramics may have been used
as a decorative tile in the kitchen of your late aunt Deb's
Airstream trailer, but you might be surprised to know it was
originally an ornament in an altar panel of a Renaissance-era
cathedral in northern France. The slogan ``Bless Our Mobile Home''
was added sometime after the 16th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner: ``Hoo-boy! And we used to use it for a coaster!''
</P>
<P>
   Expert: ``Yes, well, once you wipe off those coffee-mug rings,
it could be worth $50,000. Unless, of course, you were among the
Nazis who stole it during the occupation. In which case, you will
be arrested, deported and quite likely tried for war crimes. These
Interpol and U.S. Customs Service officers standing behind me will
sort out those kinds of details after a few hours of interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't try to run. All the exits have been secured. Now,
let's look at that next piece, shall we?''
</P>
<P>
   Every object tells a story.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing finds of ``Antiques Roadshow'' have their
counterpart on the Web at the on-line auction-house eBay.
</P>
<P>
   There, Monkees lunch boxes and Astro Boy pencil sharpeners are
worth their weight in rubies. Across the globe, eBay aficionados
stare at their screens and chant: ``Why didn't I hold on to that
junk?''
</P>
<P>
   This can turn the suspicion that there is more in one's garage
than meets the eye into an unhealthy obsession.
</P>
<P>
   I look at all the boxes in my garage differently these days.
This slows cleaning considerably. I move box to box contemplating
all the contents.
</P>
<P>
   Item 1 _ ``My Little Pony'' pencil box containing crayon
fragments, short pencils and soft-plastic hair barrettes chewed
into abstract shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Estimated value: $0.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like trash but the pencil box might go for $580 on eBay
($900, if it's the rare ``My Little Pnoy'' misprint.) The pencils
might be identified on the ``Antiques Roadshow'' as rare
first-editions of the Ticonderoga, enhanced No. 2 pencil, circa
1912, worth tens of dollars to collectors. You could add hoops to
the ends of the barrettes and sell them around the middle school as
earrings.
</P>
<P>
   Revised appraisal: $700.
</P>
<P>
   Item 2 _ Box containing a small, rusted fork, plastic dog
figurine and a ceramic coaster bearing an image of Saint Apollonius
the Younger with the slogan ``Bless Our Mobile Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimated value: 75 cents, but only if you hold a garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again. Fondue sets are back in style and this fork is part
of a particularly popular mid-'70s set. Note the avocado-colored
Bakelite handle. The dog figurine is ``Binky,'' the beloved
sidekick of ``Sherm the Worm,'' a short-lived 1980s cartoon with a
scary, cultlike following on the Internet. Originally given away
with McDonalds' children's meals, they command $100 on eBay. The
ceramic coaster should be discretely disposed of through some
intermediary whose silence can be purchased. Do not expect to
receive its full $50,000 value.
</P>
<P>
   Revised appraisal: $15,108.
</P>
<P>
   Garage cleaning is an adventure now. I'm getting garbage bags, a
broom and an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
