<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small apples outweigh the Big one
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ So far, no one has asked me to make plans for
a New York Senate bid, but that's OK. In addition to being
politically naive, I'd hate to have to go on national television
and say dumb stuff like first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton said to
CBS's Dan Rather: ``Everything that happens in America happens in
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   We could quibble here and say it all depends on what she means
by ``everything'' but that's another Clinton story.
</P>
<P>
   Although her candidacy is as yet (SET ITAL)officially(END ITAL)
undeclared, even we dummies in the hinterlands know what Mrs.
Clinton is up to. She's courting the local vote.
</P>
<P>
   She's making nice to the folks who live in that place where
``everything'' happens. That'll work _ for now. But what about
later? Like when she finally flings her fedora into a presidential
race (which she's sure to do if for no other reason than to get one
up on Bill)? Then what? Are we yokels supposed to forget that the
candidate once considered us little more than flyspecks on the
window of New York where ``everything'' happens?
</P>
<P>
   Even bumpkins vote and pay taxes, and we're known to have
memories like long-tailed elephants. Truth is, most of us living
out here in Nowheresville like it just fine and it'd be a pretty
tough sell to convince us otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, the village I call home, has one stoplight, one
grocery store, and 2,500 souls. There's a bakery, a barber shop,
and a beauty parlor. We have pizza, a dime store, a library, an
electrician, and a plumber. I figure if I need more than that, I'm
over-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   On early summer mornings, I take my coffee and newspaper to the
front porch. I can sit in the swing in my nightshirt and watch all
of the world I want to see, pass by. Banger and his wife, Millie,
always wave and tell me I'm working too hard. I ask if they'd like
to help.
</P>
<P>
   We have a few joggers and a lot of walkers, sometimes entire
families, since exercise awareness hit town a few years ago. Most
bicycles have baby ``buddy seats'' on the back and in the evenings
even the tiny fry are out taking the air from Mommy or Daddy's
rumble seat.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in our village do a lot for each other without even
knowing it. For instance, there's a billboard next to the tracks
that the Lions put there to keep us abreast of what's happening
around town. This week's sign reads: ``Operation Sandbox'' and
gives a number to call to have the Jaycees deliver a free load of
sand to your kid's backyard sandbox. My need for clean sand passed
years ago, but it still does me good to read the sign.
</P>
<P>
   If I had a swimming pool I'd call the volunteer fire department,
and they'd send a pumper over to fill it. They suck the water out
of one of the abandoned limestone quarries that ring our town. They
used to be the village's major employers until the absentee owners
felt it wasn't worth spending the million bucks it'd take to meet
clean air standards.
</P>
<P>
   Come the end of June, we'll be having Homecoming week and
there'll be a lot of new faces _ to me anyway. I've only lived here
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be a long parade on Saturday with tractors and horses
and even some floats. A bunch of folks will gather on my front
porch since I live on the main street, and we'll probably have a
bloody Mary and watch the Shriners wheel around in their little
cars.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have carnival rides, and bed races, cotton candy, and a
beer tent and one night, a group called Forever Plaid is coming to
sing.
</P>
<P>
   Does it get much better than this?
</P>
<P>
   So the way I see it, Mrs. Clinton, you can form your committee,
conduct your polls, and jump into the race with both feet (SET
ITAL)and(END ITAL) James Carville, but don't forget that not a
whole helluva lot would be happening in New York without the rest
of us out here keeping the nation's act together.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
