<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `You've got mail!' not so bad after all
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I'll probably lose my membership in the hip Internet
writers club for saying this, but I kind of like America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Now, please don't send me any e-mail documenting your horrific
encounters with AOL's billing department or the Terms of Service
police. Don't write to tell me how long it takes you to dial in,
how many times the system has crashed or logged you off while you
were in the middle of something very important, or how overpriced
it is.
</P>
<P>
   I know. I've been there. Believe me, I've been there.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL is such an easy target for ridicule. Members love
complaining about the seemingly relentless busy signals, the
increasingly annoying ``You've Got Mail'' announcement at the start
of each session and, of course, the never-ending stream of teen-age
boys sending racy instant messages to any screen name that looks
remotely female.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a certain portion of the online population that
feels it is too mature, too sophisticated and far too Web-savvy for
anything as pedestrian and as cutesy as America Online. MindSpring,
AT&AMP;T, Earthlink and a dozen other Internet service providers are
hoping and praying that your disgust with AOL will send you flying
into their waiting arms.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, AOL members encounter a number of problems. With about 17
million members and 20 million users, there are going to be days
when dialing into the service is close to impossible. The instant
message service so beloved by teen-agers and public relations
professionals who use it to message their clients during meetings
and interviews can drive you crazy. So can the endless stream of
junk mail offering everything from 6-cents-a-minute phone service
to discount modems.
</P>
<P>
   But turn off the junk mail _ go to keyword ``Mail Controls'' and
choose what can be sent to you and by whom. Ignore IMs from people
you don't know. Set the parental controls to keep your kids away
from things you don't want them to see. Then start poking around
some of the channels, and you'll find this service is packed with
more information than you might think.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Web historians will look back on AOL as one of the
original online communities. The basic infrastructure of the
service offers members the best way on the Web to post messages and
exchange opinions about the events of the day, whether it's the war
in Kosovo or reaction to the new ``Star Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   Some of AOL's chat rooms have a deservedly bad reputation as
sleazy online singles bars, but the message boards, many of which
are moderated by AOL staffers to keep the discussion on track,
often receive thousands of coherent messages per hour when big news
breaks. At last check, the ``Star Wars'' message board had nearly
20,000 member reviews. AOL executives like to call the service
``America's watercooler,'' and for better or worse, it probably is.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if chatting or even reading notes from random strangers
isn't quite what you want in an online service, it still would be
wrong to dismiss AOL out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   For Web users who don't want to fuss with Yahoo! searches or a
bookmarked list of Web sites longer than the average Christmas card
list, AOL is an amazingly handy place. The personal finance channel
will bring you to nearly every type of money management
information, from stock quotes to initial stock offerings, market
news and a selection of four online brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   AOL also offers a special channel called ``Influence,'' which
features, among other things, an AOL-friendly version of the
popular online magazine Salon. For purists, there is a link to the
actual Salon Web site.
</P>
<P>
   (Depending on the version of AOL, you'll have either the
Netscape or Internet Explorer browser. Both seem to work fairly
well and are seamlessly integrated into the service.)
</P>
<P>
   AOL also has some very quirky features such as the New York
Observer, which may have a Web site somewhere, but I know I'm too
lazy to look for it. Here I can read the latest dish on the rich
and famous, including the fact that CBS-TV President Mel Karmazin
just bought a condo in New York's Trump Tower for $11.4 million.
You can also read Maureen Dowd's New York Times column and find
tips on redecorating your drab den or whipping up a tasty dinner
with just three ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's infrastructure may be riddled with problems big and small,
but the service itself is very good at organizing its own content
and integrating the Web's most popular sites in one place. You will
find what you are looking for here.
</P>
<P>
   Its unlimited service is more expensive than the average ISP,
but you do get a high level of organization and hand-holding in
addition to built-in child safety controls. If you don't mind a few
busy signals and take the time to set the mail controls, AOL will
hand the novice Web surfer the Internet on a virtual silver
platter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
