<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disney has Atlanta kids by the ears
 &HT;    By Kelly Milner Halls
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Radio Disney hit the AM airwaves of Atlanta in
1997, kids breathed a sigh of relief _ they could finally stop
changing the station.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out more than 70 percent of 6- to 12-year-olds in the area
were constantly switching from station to station trying to find
something to entertain them.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the upbeat music, contests and zany but G-rated antics of
the Radio Disney DJs, including Atlanta's favorite after-school
duo, Just Plain Mark and Zippy. AM 590 suddenly got tot-hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio Disney _ we're all ears'' sings out 24 hours a day,
seven days a week, and the tunes take center stage. What kind of
tunes? Happy tunes, of course, by artists like the Spice Girls,
Backstreet Boys, Hanson, Weird Al Yankovic, James Brown and
hundreds of others. Radio Disney floods the kid-centered cosmos
with kicky, danceable tunes. And get this _ strictly nonsexual
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Censorship, you may ask?
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way,'' says 9-year-old Moreland ``Mo'' Isom, a Radio
Disney kid correspondent in Atlanta. ``But I don't think changing a
few words is a bad thing. I think it makes things better for kids.
Then you don't have to change the channel just to get away from
those songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly, says Kellie Wander, operations director in Atlanta for
Radio Disney. ``Kids need something of their own, `edutainment'
their parents can trust. Radio Disney has tried to provide that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's programming that won't cross the boundaries,'' she says,
``but we have lots of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to radio personalities and contest giveaways, Radio
Disney makes learning fun by featuring ABC News for Kids, Back in
Time With Dusty Pages, and Izatafact, written by the people who
bring you Weekly Reader Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Though the shows are broadcast from Disneyland in California or
Walt Disney World in Florida, each of 41 cities considers Radio
Disney its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do so many fun, crazy things,'' Mo says. ``We go to
concerts and play games and hand out prizes. All that happens here
in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And all the activities are free,'' Wander says. ``Nothing
Radio Disney is ever for sale. If you snag a Radio Disney T-shirt,
you won it on the show or at a special local event.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
