<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peace agreement talks stall
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peace talks between leaders of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and Yugoslavia have bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed settlement, all Serb troops would pull out of
Kosovo during the next seven days. NATO planes will continue to
bomb the region until the soldiers have left.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and European troops then would occupy the area to maintain
peace. The United Nations is also expected to send troops. Nearly 1
million refugees then would be able to return home. Plus, money
would be lent from all over the world to help rebuild Kosovo after
11 weeks of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The region of Kosovo wanted to be independent of Yugoslavia.
Yugoslavia is run by Serbs who are Christians. The people of Kosovo
are ethnic Albanians, and they follow the Muslim faith.
</P>
<P>
   Kids' star orbits the earth
</P>
<P>
   Star bright, star light, the first star I see tonight _ may not
really be a star, but a kid-made satellite from afar.
</P>
<P>
   Starshine, a hollow ball studded with tiny mirrors, was created
by kids in Utah, with help from students around the world. It was
released from the Space Shuttle Discovery on Saturday. It will
orbit 250 miles above the earth and will travel around the planet
every hour and a half. (That's 16 times a day!)
</P>
<P>
   The best time to see the new star is just after the sun has set.
It will be dark on the ground, but the satellite still will be in
the sunlight. The mirrors will reflect the light to earth. For more
information about Starshine and how to track it, visit
spacekids.hq.nasa.gov/starshine.
</P>
<P>
   Are you a Southerner?
</P>
<P>
   Are Delaware, Kentucky and Oklahoma part of the South? A new
survey asked residents in states across the country if they lived
in the South. The researchers, at the University of North Carolina,
were surprised by the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-nine percent of those questioned in Kentucky said they
lived in a Southern state, even though most Kentuckians fought for
the North during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, only 14 percent of Delaware residents said they lived
in South. And in Oklahoma, which wasn't even a state during the
Civil War, 69 percent said they were Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
