<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5657 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CD-BURN08-COX     06-07 2067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-BURN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recordable media is a real disc-o inferno
 &HT;    By Alexis Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Few innovations have had as much impact in the
field of personal technology as the introduction of the compact
disc in the 1980s. From its humble beginnings, the CD has managed
to establish a dedicated following willing to abandon their beloved
vinyl records for dependable digital discs.
</P>
<P>
   CD-ROMs transformed our computers from a dull, word-based medium
to an animated multimedia experience of sounds and pictures, and
now the digital video disc (DVD), which is like a video CD, is on
its way to revolutionizing home theater.
</P>
<P>
   But the CD has not stopped there. In the quest to enrich our
computer experience with audio and video _ coupled with the need
for more storage space, computers have evolved into a kind of
refuge for new compact disc recording technologies because of their
immense storage capacities. Although neither the CD or DVD format
began with computers, their recordable versions, the newest
revolution in CD media, have quickly gained popularity with
computer enthusiasts and are now on the cusp of becoming mainstream
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   These recordable technologies will allow ordinary users to
create permanent or semi-permanent archives of audio files and in
some cases data and video files.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe the only thing that can slow the compact disc's
whirring success is the incredibly rapid growth of the technology
and the ever-expanding number of formats and acronyms each
development brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is advancing at a very rapid rate, but until we
decide what route we're going to use, compatibility problems will
be standard problems,'' cautioned Joe Miller owner of FJM Audio.
</P>
<P>
   As for what recordable technology to invest in, there is an
alphabet soup of possibilities but only four widely accepted
formats that show some promise: minidisc; CD audio recorders; two
flavors of CD-format optical discs _ CD-recordable and
CD-rewritable _ and, in the very distant future, DVD-R.
</P>
<P>
   Each presents different benefits and disadvantages, with the
only real similarity being the laser beam each unit uses to
``burn'' or change the surface structure of the blank disc.
</P>
<P>
   So read on and discover the best way to navigate through the
fragmented market and bring yourself into the digital recording
age.
</P>
<P>
   Minidisc (MD)
</P>
<P>
   Sony and Sharp are hoping recent sales surges in Europe and
Japan can be duplicated in the United States with both companies
spearheading an effort to revive the minidisc format. The MD works
by recording digital music onto tiny discs inside a 2.75-inch
cartridge that resembles a 3.5-inch floppy. The companies have
fashioned sleek players as small as 3 inches wide and a scant 4
ounces in weight.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is relatively little prerecorded music available
in the MD format, it's being touted for its ability to make
recordings from any analog or digital music source, including CD
players, tape decks, even the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With blank discs selling for a little more than $3 apiece and
units ranging from $300 to $500 in component and portable versions,
minidisc recorders are less costly than CD recorders, but far
pricier than the portable CD players they aim to displace.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle facing the minidisc is that although it has
become popular abroad, CDs weren't as entrenched there as they are
here and U.S. consumers are not as quick to jump to a new platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got people saying, `I'm not replacing my CDs, I just
replaced my albums.' The minidisc is like the Rodney Dangerfield of
the music business: It gets no respect at all,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Verdict: Overall, minidisc is best suited for dubbing
commercial recordings for personal use at home, in portables and
for making casual live recordings. It is least suited to high
quality recording.
</P>
<P>
   CD audio recorders
</P>
<P>
   Manufactured to look and function like any other stereo
component, the CD home-audio recorder could become the most
significant product available to audiophiles since the release of
the first compact disc.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer and Phillips have released the first wave of CD home
recorders compatible with any stereo system that has digital
outjacks. The recorder, priced about $600, enables the user to copy
audio from CD players, cassette decks, turntables, radio and even
TV (for cable or satellite music channels) quickly and
conveniently. However, the drives are currently only single speed
and the blank discs are expensive at $6 or more each, thanks to a
royalty agreement with the recording industry, which also requires
that a special ``copyright flag'' be embedded on blank discs and
that CD recorders accept only these flagged discs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Verdict: Factors such as the artificially high price of blank
media (virtually identical to the recordable CDs for computers,
which sell for little more than $1 or $2 each because the copyright
agreement doesn't affect them) and other copyright issues, such as
an installed antipiracy system called the Serial Copy Management
System (SCMS) that prevents the user from making a copy of a
digitally recorded copy, may prevent this from being a contender in
home recording.
</P>
<P>
   CD-Recordable (CD-R)
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a few years ago, it would have been inconceivable
for most people to possess the technology necessary to replicate
CDs in-house. These days it seems many professional studios,
software developers and others have the capability to churn out
CDs. Markets that aren't even associated with optical storage such
as hospitals and banks can be found investing in this popular
technology, according to Dave Ulich, president of Information
Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   With many computers being ordered in custom configurations with
CD-R/RW drives installed, this format seems poised to become a
mainstream data-storage technology. With low-priced drives and
media, combined with user-friendly software, there has been
increased public demand for these drives.
</P>
<P>
   Nate Seim, production director at Wright State University's
radio station and a student engineer at the Wright State Television
Center, can't remember life without his CD-R. ``Having a CD burner
is the greatest thing in the world. You've got a friend that has a
really good CD ... you just pop it in and get an exact duplicate.
You want a certain PlayStation game ... it's yours. And with the
blank media being as inexpensive as it is, it's a win-win
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my CD-R drive about a year ago so they were still
very expensive and I hoped that I had made a good investment. Today
I can honestly say it is by far the best thing I've ever bought for
my computer.''
</P>
<P>
   CD-R drives cost as little as $300. Just as important, the cost
of blank media has fallen to a dollar or two per disc, depending on
how many you buy at one time.
</P>
<P>
   With a capacity of 650 MB, this makes CD-R easily the cheapest
storage space around, archiving files for a fraction of a penny per
megabyte. And the process of creating your own CD-ROM disc has
become far easier thanks to improved CD recording software.
</P>
<P>
   CD-R and its relative CD-RW are good ways to create permanent or
semi-permanent archives of any type of file _ data, audio or video.
Until recently, removable storage options like Iomega Zip were the
preferred method of storage, but with CD-R and CD-RW technologies
descending from their former stratospheric price levels, they have
become cost-effective for users.
</P>
<P>
   Miller sees CD-R in his future. As owner of FJM Audio, he keeps
himself aware of emerging technologies and understands why CD-R has
gained such immense popularity. ``CD-R media is incredibly
convenient, durable, cost-effective and reliable. I prefer to use
CD media whenever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Verdict: The unique thing about CD-R is its compatibility with
CD media, making it cheap and interchangeable. Fully optical
technology like CDs promise much better longevity than magnetic
media like tape and disks for storing very large memory-intensive
files. The drawbacks are that they are not sold in portable units,
and because the discs are not reusable, they are not
environmentally friendly. Also, the computer involvement makes this
method more complicated than the others.
</P>
<P>
   CD-Rewritable (CD-RW)
</P>
<P>
   CD-RW discs employ a ``phase change'' technology through which
the discs can be used thousands of times for recording. The chief
problem is that most CD players are not sensitive enough to detect
the differences in reflectivity on the disc, with only CD-ROM and
DVD-ROM players able to interface with them.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of CD-RW drives is $200 more than its CD-R cousin, and
blank CD-RW discs cost about $12 apiece. CD-RW drives can be used
to write CD-R discs, but CD-R drives cannot write CD-RW discs. For
CD-RW discs to rerecord, the disc must be reformatted, which can
take as long as 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Verdict: Even CD-RW, an erasable, recordable CD format, is not
likely to supplant CD-R because of the cost of the blank media and
the fact that many CD players will not play back CD-RW media.
</P>
<P>
   Recordable Digital Versatile Disc (DVD-R)
</P>
<P>
   Right on the heels of recordable CDs is the DVD recordable
format, which ups the ante from megabytes to gigabytes, holding up
to eight times as much data as CD-R discs. Although the current
cost of DVD recordable drives is far too expensive for most
consumers, it is expected that the price will fall quickly over the
next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Just as much of the attraction of CD-R comes from its inherently
compatible nature, so a primary selling feature of DVD-R will be
its ability to be read by any DVD device. However, given some of
the historical compatibility problems among the first CD-R media,
CD audio recorders and CD-ROM drives manufactured, it is reasonable
to speculate the same issues could also affect early generations of
DVD-R products.
</P>
<P>
   _ Verdict: Given DVD-R's write-once nature, similar uses for
CD-R are expected, including data storage, distribution and
archiving. Unfortunately, developing the critical mass that CD-R
has established lies in the far-off future when hardware prices
fall substantially. For the time being DVD-R will impact a select
group of professionals; our turn will come later.
</P>
<P>
   The future
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing in today's technologies instead of waiting for
future generations of digital recorders makes sense when you
consider that they are available now and at affordable prices,''
said Seim.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what fate is in store for the CD, DVD, CD-R/RW
or minidisc, but there are some factors to look at when purchasing
to help make a more informed decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start with the application first: What do you want to do with
your hardware? It's the same way you buy a computer. You buy from
the software back to the hardware by figuring out what you want to
do and what features you need to be able to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, try and settle on a technology that's going to be around
for a while. Invest wisely so you'll have viable equipment a couple
years from now,'' said Bill Sellers, owner of Encore Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Before you buy
</P>
<P>
   When choosing digital recording equipment, remember:
</P>
<P>
   _ A hardware manufacturer may claim a device can do something
that requires software or media that is not supplied with the
product.
</P>
<P>
   _ CD technology is evolving rapidly. What was true yesterday may
be false today and what is scheduled for tomorrow may never happen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The more you understand about a new technology such as
recordable media, the more likely you are to avoid problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some problems may arise from hardware, software or procedures,
but most arise from the interaction of components.
</P>
<P>
   _ CD media are very sensitive to light and heat. A disc can be
destroyed if exposed to either of these for too long.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mobile CD players are more fussy about recorded discs than
home audio players or CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   _ When in doubt, read. Sources include these Internet sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.philips.com/home.html
</P>
<P>
   www.world.sony.com/top.html
</P>
<P>
   www.pioneerelectronics.com
</P>
<P>
   www.cddb.com
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're interested in trying a CD-R, FJM Audio offers a
booth with the ability to copy your old LPs, cassettes or CDs onto
CD. FJM's Web site is: www.erinet.com/fjmaudio/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
