<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take me out to the old Internet site
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you can't make it to that afternoon baseball game
and can't watch on television, the Web may be the next best thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sites like CBS SportsLine let you follow major league games
pitch by pitch, inning by inning, complete with little baserunner
icons that tell you who's actually on first. So if it's OK with
your boss, you can watch at work.
</P>
<P>
   The June issue of Yahoo! Internet Life takes a look at baseball
Web-casts. The article looks at four sites _ www
</P>
<P>
   .sportsline.com, www
</P>
<P>
   .totalbaseball.com, www
</P>
<P>
   .espn.com and sites on America Online that can be accessed by
the keywords ``AL scores'' and ``NL scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Total Baseball Online's site comes with an illustrated strike
zone and play-by-play text description. Big games _ like the
All-Star Game or World Series _ come with photos. A separate chart
notes each grounder, line drive, pop-up and foul ball.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's site displays its Web broadcast with scores and updates
on note cards. When a hitter comes to the plate, his photo is shown
along with statistics, including batting average and RBI total.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS SportsLine site is ``the most graphically intensive Web
broadcast,'' according to the article. It sets up a virtual stadium
on your screen, complete with organ music and hot dog vendors. The
screen image also has a box that updates scores from other games.
</P>
<P>
   The AOL sites are the simplest. Each features a basic
scoreboard, updated by pitch by pitch. A chat room and forum
combination called the ``grandstand'' gives fans a chance to gripe
or root with like-minded brethren.
</P>
<P>
   The June issue of Yahoo! Internet Life also takes a look at Web
sites devoted to the summer's movies and movie review sites.
</P>
<P>
   A more interesting piece is the one exploring sites focused on
movie rumors, including: www.aint-it-cool-news.com;
www.corona.bc.ca/films; www.darkhorizons.com; www.cinescape.com;
and www.countingdown.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's, Macy's join wedding Web site
</P>
<P>
   WeddingChannel.com has added to its wedding-planning resources
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The site, at www
</P>
<P>
   .weddingchannel.com, has affiliated with Federated Department
stores and is creating an integrated in-store and online bridal
registry. Federated Department Stores chains include Macy's,
Bloomingdale's, Burdines, Rich's and Stern's.
</P>
<P>
   The site's features include a guest management tool that lets
you create a database of guests and vendors as well as track
invitations, RSVPs, gifts and thank-you notes.
</P>
<P>
   Couples can also create a customizable home page that can be
updated for wedding plans and logistics and that can be accessed by
guests via password.
</P>
<P>
   Another site for online auto buying
</P>
<P>
   Another car-buying Web site has joined the fray. Now, www
</P>
<P>
   .carsdirect.com joins Autobytel.com, carpoint.msn.com and
several others hoping to make the Internet the reference resource
for people buying cars.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Oaks, Calif.-based Carsdirect.com was launched in May.
The site offers car prices and options on more than 2,500 makes and
models.
</P>
<P>
   It also lets you get a loan and buy the car, all online. You can
arrange for delivery at a dealer, at your office or at home.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Carsdirect.com and other auto-buying Web
sites is that the others refer a customer to a dealer to buy their
car. Carsdirect.com lets you buy the car online.
</P>
<P>
   Carsdirect.com has arrangements with dealers in 10 markets _
Atlanta, Chicago, Denver, Dallas, Los Angeles, Miami, New York, San
Francisco, Seattle and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for that to expand to 40 by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
