r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE08-COX     06-07 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rain or shine, sites track weather well
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The weather is a big deal, no matter how you look at
it.
</P>
<P>
   If you travel a lot for business, you need to know if you should
bring a sweater along on your trip to Seattle. On the weekend, you
want to know if you should try for golf on Saturday or wait until
the rain ends and shoot for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of weather information. It's still a popular
feature in newspapers, and radio stations seem to give a weather
report every 15 minutes or so. TV is full of the stuff; there's
even an entire cable channel _ the Weather Channel _ devoted to it.
And, if you hang out on the Web, you probably already know there's
no shortage of sites devoted to the weather.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to write about weather reports on the Web
and not start with one of the main sources of weather information _
even for other weather sites _ the National Weather Service. You'll
be able to find a NWS site based in Peachtree City at
www.srh.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   /FTPROOT/FFC/HTML/.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for flash and fancy graphics, this isn't for
you. This page, however, is filled with information. You can use
various links to read the latest weather watches and warnings; get
a five-day forecast for the Atlanta area or other parts of the
state; get the short-term forecast; find out current conditions; or
take a look at radar images. All those links were working fine a
few days ago, but the link to software for a meteorological
calculator was not working.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who want a little more flash and splash in a
site, then cable television's Weather Channel at www.weather.com is
definitely the place for you.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be able to get forecasts, weather maps and even watch
video clips. You can also check forecasts for cities around the
globe. The weakness here _ it is a big one and ironic, too,
considering the source _ is the lack of detailed weather
information. For instance, the entire forecast for Atlanta given
one day last week was ``isolated t-storms, hi 83 degrees, lo 66
degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see what I mean, then bop over to the next site,
one run by the Weather Underground at
www.wunderground.com/US/GA/Atlanta.html. You'll find more than a
screenful of data such as humidity, dew point, current wind and
almost anything you'd want to know. Then, on top of all that, you
get a much longer and more detailed forecast. Neither the Weather
Channel approach nor this site's way of doing things is ``right,''
but the two approaches are very different and should help you find
a page that suits your taste in weather information.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Interactive Media (which is owned by Cox Enterprises, the
Atlanta-based company that also owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) offers weather information at www
</P>
<P>
   .accessatlanta.com/weather/. The amount of information you'll
find here falls somewhere between the sparse text at the Weather
Channel site and the verbose detail at Weather Underground. But one
really good feature of this site, for those of you who do want
detailed weather information, is the ability to click on a link
that will take you to various National Weather Service sites where
you'll get the complete story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
