<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speakers weather the outdoors
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Now that we're officially into the summer season,
you may be thinking about spending more of your time hanging around
your yard. As you hang out, you may want to listen to a tune or
two.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake, however, to drag the speakers from the
audio system in the family room out onto the deck. Most speakers
weren't meant to stand up to the rain and extreme temperatures
summer can bring.
</P>
<P>
   You need a good outdoor speaker to provide dependable
performance through the outside activity season.
</P>
<P>
   A Bose company spokesman said the company's 151 Environmental
Speakers have been on the market about five years and have proven
their toughness.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers can stand temperatures up to 158 degrees or down to
13 below zero. The Bose spokesman said temperatures lower than that
can damage the speakers, so you should bring them inside before
hard winter hits.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker driver cone, grille, terminal posts and other
hardware on the Bose 151 Environmental are all stainless steel to
prevent deterioration from high humidity and even from saltwater.
The speakers exceed marine industry tests for resistance to salt
fog by 66 percent, Bose says.
</P>
<P>
   Each speaker weighs four pounds and can be wall mounted or
hidden in the landscaping around yards, hot tubs, decks and pools.
They use 4.5-inch Bose full-range drivers and are compatile for
receivers and amplifiers rated 10 to 80 watts per channel.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers sell for about $279 a pair from most retailers
carrying Bose products.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
