<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A venture capitalist's rise from bankruptcy
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Learn how a bankrupt Texas real estate developer has
remade himself into a venture capitalist in the June issue of
DigitalSouth magazine. The magazine's cover story profiles Dennis
Murphee, whose venture capital firm Murphee &AMP; Co. has $75 million
under management. Among the companies Murphee has invested in are
Journee Software, ModelOffice and World.hire.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Apple Computer has introduced a new equipment
standard with its iMac computers. Old peripherals such as mice,
printers and Zip drives don't work with these new computers, and
that has confused a lot of users. Now you can learn all about this
new standard, called USB, and what peripherals will work with it in
the June issue of MacWorld magazine. The magazine lists more than
200 peripherals that check out as USB-compatible.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Before there was ``Star Wars,'' there was ``Star Trek,'' and the
famous series of TV shows lives on. Now you can participate in the
``Star Trek'' adventure through a computer CD game. In ``Star Trek:
The Next Generation,'' you get to play one of a variety of
interstellar races. The idea is to develop this race through
exploration, alliances and economic development. Published by
Hasbro Interactive, ``Star Trek'' is available only for PCs with
operating systems Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   The season is right to check out Microsoft's ``Baseball 2000''
computer CD. The game features 3-D graphics, recognizable players
and rosters that accurately reflect the 1999 lineups of the real
teams. ``Baseball 2000'' is only available for PCs running Windows
95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Tired of your screen saver? Then check out freesaver.com. This
site offers more than 500 free screen savers for both PCs and Macs.
Freesaver lists its screen savers in alphabetical order and also
provides a thumbnail preview of each one. You'll find this site at
www.freesaver.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
