<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5710 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EIZENSTAT-$ADV13-COX     06-07 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIZENSTAT-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EIZENSTAT DOESN'T FIT THE MOLD OF CAPTIAL MOVERS AND SHAKERS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 13.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shortly after their son and his boss, Jimmy Carter,
lost good jobs in 1980, Leo and Sylvia Eizenstat came up from
Georgia to provide solace and advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My inclination was to go back to Atlanta,'' recalled Stuart
Eizenstat, who had been President Carter's chief domestic policy
adviser. ``I didn't consider myself any sort of Washington
insider.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Eizenstat was surprised when his father thought
differently. Nearly two decades later, he still quotes the sage
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'I'd rather have you happy in Washington 500 miles
away than unhappy next door. ... Your real life is public policy
issues and politics. This is the city for it and you ought to stay
here.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Leo Eizenstat knew his son well.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Eizenstat stayed and became _ if he wasn't already _ a
consummate Washington insider. Respected on both sides of the
political aisle, he prospered as a lawyer and lobbyist during the
12 years that Republicans occupied the White House. For the past
six years, he has been one of President Clinton's top
trouble-shooters.
</P>
<P>
   He helped hammer out a global-warming treaty that was acceptable
to delegates from 160 nations but that has yet to be ratified by
the U.S. Senate. He is negotiating a settlement between Holocaust
survivors and Swiss banks on the restitution of Jewish property
stolen by Nazis. Angry Mexicans threw eggs at him on an
international tour to explain U.S. punishment of foreign firms that
invested in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat has served as U.S. ambassador to the European Union
and as under secretary of commerce for international trade.
Currently, he is under secretary of state for economic, business
and agricultural affairs. And if confirmed by the Senate, he will
soon become deputy Treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a deeply religious man _ ``entirely comfortable
living the two integral parts that make him whole _ his American
and his Jewish identities,'' said David Harris, executive director
of the American Jewish Committee, which recently gave Eizenstat its
highest honor, the Distinguished Service Award.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Jewish Times said Eizenstat ``may be the Jewish
community's best-ever asset in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``The accident of my being born in Chicago rather than Atlanta
was simply that it was during the war,'' explained Stuart
Eizenstat. The year was 1943. Leo Eizenstat was in the Army. Sylvia
was with her family in Chicago. So Stuart emerged in the Midwest
rather than in the Southern city where his father had been born and
reared and where his grandfather had settled in 1904 after
emigrating from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of eight months, Stuart moved to Morningside, a leafy
Atlanta neighborhood of shady sidewalks and well-tended yards where
he would spend his childhood. He would walk to Morningside
Elementary School. He belonged to the Devoted Sons of Israel, a
youth group. He spent summer weeks at Camp Blue Star in North
Carolina, sharing outdoor experiences with other Jewish children
from across the South. He was a shy, studious, serious boy.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism was not uncommon in this era, but Morningside was
a Jewish enclave of sorts. Eizenstat remembers only a couple of
instances of overt discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Once his mother drove her son and a few friends to a lake where
they were greeted by a sign that said ``No Blacks or Jews
Allowed.'' Another time, he was walking home from Hebrew school
when two brothers who lived nearby jumped him, tried to rip his
books apart and beat him up.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was also a racially segregated city in the 1940s and
'50s when Stuart Eizenstat grew up. A boyhood memory: He had been
at a movie downtown and was taking a bus back to Morningside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the buses were segregated. I was at the back part
of the white section. There was an older black lady with satchels
who was standing right next to me. My inclination was to simply get
up and give her the seat. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember sort of struggling with this notion. Would she get
into difficulty? Would it be a problem for me? Would it cause a
disruption? And in the end, I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   With hindsight, ``it struck me how easily one accepts
established patterns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, when asked about being honored as an All-City and
honorable mention All-American high school basketball player,
Eizenstat says, ``It should be with an asterisk because it was in
pre-integration days.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's designated deputy Treasury secretary
received his early economics lessons from his father and his Uncle
Berry Eizenstat, who were partners in a wholesale shoe business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My uncle was the inside guy. My father was the drummer, the
outside guy,'' recalled Eizenstat. ``His customers were basically
the small-town merchants in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   During his boyhood summers, Stuart unpacked and packed shoes in
this family operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember having a conversation, when I was still a teenager,
with my father, saying 'I would be interested in going into your
business,' `` Eizenstat said. ``He said 'Under no circumstances.'
``
</P>
<P>
   His father, who died in 1986, foresaw a sweeping economic
change. The small town dry goods merchants who were his customers
would be pushed out of business by the national retail chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'They are selling shoes at retail cheaper than I can
sell them at wholesale. That may be good for the consumer, but it's
bad for the small-town merchant who is the backbone of these
communities,' `` the son recalled. ``That was one early lesson and
that has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson came as he was unpacking a carton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to my uncle, 'These look strange.' He said, 'These are
Asian shoes,' `` Eizenstat said. His uncle explained how the
imported shoes cost less than those made in America and how
troubling that was because of longstanding relationships with
domestic manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very early glimpse of just the beginnings of a
globalized economy,'' Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Turning down invitations to play basketball at Oglethorpe
College and the University of Pennsylvania, Eizenstat entered the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill in the fall of 1960.
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday when his fraternity house kitchen was closed,
Eizenstat and some friends were headed to a Howard Johnson's for
dinner and found their way blocked by a group of protesting black
students from North Carolina A&AMP;T. That sit-in demonstration
awakened ``my civil rights consciousness,'' he said. Soon he was
signing petitions and boycotting restaurants that would not
voluntarily desegregate.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons he still cannot articulate, the shy scholar also
jumped into campus politics. In the summer of 1963, he went to
Washington as a congressional intern. ``I suppose I got what my
wife calls the incurable disease of Potomac Fever that summer,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, however, he had not yet met Fran _ the Brandeis
University graduate whom he would wed. That would come several
years later, when he was at Harvard Law School and she was doing
graduate work at Boston University. They were invited to the
birthday party of a mutual friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we were the only single people there,'' said Eizenstat.
``I must say I didn't quite realize that this was being set up.''
</P>
<P>
   They were newlyweds in a Washington apartment and watching TV
together when Lyndon Baines Johnson made his shocking announcement
that he would not seek re-election in 1968. ``I almost fell off the
bed,'' said Eizenstat. At the time, he was an LBJ speechwriter
``working like a dog'' on a memo pertaining to the re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first call was ... to see if I could stop working on the
memo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Henry Bauer, Jr., an Atlanta attorney and a lifelong friend,
talked Eizenstat into meeting Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him at the old Hurt Building downtown. He had on khaki
pants and a khaki open shirt. I was immediately taken with him,''
Eizenstat said. ``I saw in him somebody who could build a bridge
between rural and urban Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was running for governor, and Eizenstat became his
campaign policy director. After the peanut farmer from Plains won,
though, Eizenstat went into private practice with an Atlanta law
firm rather than join the administration. But when Carter was
appointed chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee in 1974, the young attorney agreed to help him write a
series of issue papers for their party's candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The issue papers were well received nationally. Eizenstat and
Carter went out to celebrate and talk about the future. It was
Eizenstat who brought up presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had lunch at Underground Atlanta and I said, 'My view is
that it's going to be a particularly weak field in '76. Kennedy
can't run because of Chappaquiddick. Humphrey is too old. He's lost
before. It's just not a strong field. If you ran and did at all
well in any of the Southern primaries, you'd have a good chance of
being vice president on a ticket.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He laughed and said, 'I've already decided I'm going to run.
Why don't you join our team?' ``
</P>
<P>
   A presidential campaign later, Stuart and Fran Eizenstat _ now
with young sons Jay and Brian _ were headed back to Washington _
this time to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
