<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, June 7, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-CENTENNIAL (Yosemite National Park, Calif.) _ When Camp
Curry opened in this majestic place 100 years ago, you could rent a
tent for $2 a day or $12 a week, get three squares a day and a
clean napkin with every meal. That year, 1899, only 4,500 people
visited Yosemite. This year, more than 4.5 million people will come
and about 333,000 of them will stay at Camp Curry, now called Curry
Village. By LARRY D. HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   YUPPIE-PROTEST (San Francisco) _ A rally ostensibly organized to
protect the civil rights of yuppie newcomers to the Mission
District apparently attracted just about everybody in the
neighborhood _ except the yuppies. Instead, a crowd of about 200
Mission residents gathered to defend themselves against what some
of them called false accusations by spoiled, wealthy newcomers
buying up property in their neighborhood. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-AMERICANS (San Francisco) _ The fund-raising scandal
involving San Francisco real estate broker Chong Lo three years ago
_ as national concern arose over Asian campaign contributions _
hasn't dampened Asian American participation in politics, but has
made the community more wary of those casting themselves as
leaders. By TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HISPANIC (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Despite being called a
traitor over his handling of Proposition 187, California Gov. Gray
Davis' reputation appears to have thrived among California's Latino
population, according to a San Francisco Examiner-KTVU poll. By
ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PORTS-LABOR (San Francisco) _ This year, cargo valued at more
than $300 billion will move in and out of West Coast ports. That is
why labor leaders and economists shudder at the thought of trouble
on the docks. Negotiators in mid-May began work on a new three-year
contract that would replace the agreement expiring July 1 covering
10,000 West Coast longshoremen. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   SNART-CARDS (San Francisco) _ Visa wants America to like smart
cards. So does MasterCard. So does the government. But America
isn't cooperating. Not yet anyway. By JOHN BERGER.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-LAWSUITS (Albany, N.Y.) _ A handful of lawyers say they've
been busy working with businesses that want to guard against
lawsuits arising from computer problems caused by the vaunted Y2K
glitch. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   SF-TOURISM (San Francisco) _ You are going to pay more to fly
this summer. Such is the consensus of travel and tourism industry
watchers about the coming summer travel season. It's a season, they
say, that promises to be lively for travelers and prosperous for
places that rely on tourist dollars, such as San Francisco. By
DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-CREEK (San Francisco) _ Scott Lasser, in San
Francisco to offer readings from his new baseball novel, ``Battle
Creek,'' is a bonds trader on Wall Street who wrote the bulk of his
book while commuting to work from Westchester County. By EDVINS
BEITIKS,
</P>
<P>
   TV-GAYS-CHILDREN (San Francisco) _ Stations in 23 of the top 30
TV markets have scheduled ``It's Elementary,'' the critically
acclaimed San Francisco-made documentary about homosexuality and
tolerance. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Once again San Francisco has
fallen behind Silicon Valley. The city of Mountain View, population
54,206, main export software, has an ``Ambience Committee.'' When I
came to the Bay Area 22 years ago, I lived in a kind of tract home
in Mountain View. If the town had an Ambience Committee then, it
required homeowners to park pickups in driveways, and developers to
build theme malls with corny wooden mills. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
