 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2547 - June 7, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2547 -- June 7, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. THE NEXT STEP FOR THE WAR-CRIMES TRIBUNAL Peter Maass, author
of ``Love Thy Neighbour : A Story of War,'' which chronicled the
conflict in Bosnia, writes that if the war-crimes tribunal in The
Hague hopes to be seen as an impartial arbiter of justice, it
should match its indictment of Slobodan Milosovic with a move
against President Tudjman of Croatia. New York Times Op-Ed. 800
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
IS THE PRIORITY JUSTICE OR PEACE? This is a changing era, as a
high-level French official has pointed out. The old rules of
absolute sovereignty, of non-intervention in the way another state
treats its own citizens, are no longer acceptable to the moral
sense of states who consider themselves responsible for the
``international community.'' By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
MBEKI MUST ADDRESS SOUTH AFRICA'S VIOLENCE AND CRIME Mark
Mathabane, author of ``Kaffir Boy,'' a memoir about growing up in
South Africa, and the forthcoming ``Ubuntu,'' writes why he has
reason to hope that Thabo Mbeki, Nelson Mandela's successor as
president, will redress the injustices that are partly to blame for
the upward spiral of crime and violence that threatens the future
of South Africa's fragile democracy. New York Times Op-Ed. 800
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
THE PLOT IS IN THE DOT DNA carries genetic information which is
faithfully transferred from one generation to the next. Could DNA
also be used to hide and transmit clandestine messages across the
world? By Marie-Thirhse Heemels. From Nature News Service. (N/A
France and Spain. Embargo 19h00 BST June 9.)
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE A. GRILLING TIPS TO CUT CANCER
RISK
</P>
<P>
   When firing up the barbeque this summer, backyard chefs should
avoid charring meat, poultry and fish. 350 words. B. FIBRE HELPS
PREVENT HEART DISEASE IN WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   Eating cereal for breakfast each morning may help minimize the
risk of
</P>
<P>
   heart disease in women. 300 words. C. SUMMER OZONE POSES HEALTH
RISK
</P>
<P>
   Sizzling summer temperatures intensify the health risk posed by
outdoor ozone pollution, warns doctors. 300 words. 6. NEW STRATEGY
AGAINST MALARIA NEEDED New strains of malaria are emerging around
the world that can resist the inexpensive drugs that have been, for
so long, the mainstay in the fight against this disease. A group of
malaria experts warn that malaria should start being treated with
two-drug combination therapies. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet
News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
TRYING ONE'S IMPATIENS : VERSATILE FLOWER A SHADY SUCCESS
Impatiens, a flowering garden plant, is enticing for its love of
shade. In dark or dappled areas under trees or on the north side of
a wall, in suburbs or in the shadows of skyscrapers, this plant
thrives. Here is a preview of the many kinds of impatiens you might
try in your garden. By Susan McClure. 1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS FROM DISCOVER MAGAZINE This month's news from
the science front includes a Discover dialogue with NASA astronaut
and biochemist, Shannon Lucid; a potential cure for spinal cord
injuries based on research using guinea pigs whose crushed spinal
cords, with the use of the chemical polyethylene glycol regained
some sensation and motor control ; a Yale astronomer's discovery
that nearby stars that closely resemble our sun, shoot off powerful
flares; and an overview of NASA's ten centres and their specific
missions. From Discover magazine. 1,000 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
NEW LOOK AT DIETING : FAT CAN BE A FRIEND For three decades we have
been bombarded with advice to eat less fat, but now a growing
number of nutrition, health and obesity specialists maintain that
in trying to squeeze some of the heart-damaging grease from our
high-fat diets, they have sent people the wrong message. It's not
fat per se that is the problem, experts now say, but the kinds of
fats and other foods we fill up on when we cut back on
appetite-satisfying fat. By Jane E. Brody. New York Times Science
Times. 1,900 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
THE OPEN SECRET Public key cryptography - the breakthrough that
revolutionized email and ecommerce - was first discovered by
American geeks. Right? Wrong. By Steven Levy. From WIRED magazine.
(N/A Japan.) 4,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________
