<P>
   &UR; THE WAR BETWEEN MEN AND WOMEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE B&AMP;W AND TWO COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT SAPOLSKY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As most newlyweds quickly learn, intimate relationships can buzz
with tension. Couples struggle over money, in-laws, ex-lovers ...
and how much the woman's placenta should grow when she gets
pregnant. It's true: Although he doesn't know it, a guy wants his
woman to have a fast-growing placenta, while the woman does all she
can to keep it down to a reasonable size. Free-lance writer Robert
Sapolsky explains.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-WAR-OF-SEXES-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREEN GOLD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT KUNZIG &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout civilization, emeralds have long been symbols of
immortality, cures for dysentery and preservers of chastity. Why
such reverence? Because emeralds are very rare _ rarer than
diamonds. They are rare, says geologist Alain Cheilletz, because
they are a mixture of elements that don't ordinarily get a chance
to mix: ``They are a mineral that shouldn't exist at all.'' Robert
Kunzig, European Editor at Discover magazine, reports on Earth's
green gold.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-GREEN-GOLD-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Both stories are also available in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
