A5784 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-PANDA-NAT     06-07 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-PANDA-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        AILING PANDA A LINK TO U.S. CHINA RELATIONS OF YEARS PAST
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 4 -- It was twenty-seven years ago when a pair
of giant panda cubs - Ling-Ling, a female, and Hsing-Hsing, a male
- arrived at the National Zoo as a gift of friendship from the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   Now at a time when the U.S.-China relationship is at a rocky
point, so too is the health of the elderly surviving male panda,
Hsing-Hsing. National Zoo officials announced this week,
Hsing-Hsing (pronounced Shing Shing) - who perhaps is one of the
most symbolic links to a more hopeful time between the two nations
- is suffering from a life threatening illness.
</P>
<P>
   Hsing-Hsing is battling kidney dysfunction that may not be
reversible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the nations are recovering from NATO's accidental
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade and the recently
released Congressional report alleging Chinese espionage of U.S.
military secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials say they aren't sure how much longer Hsing-Hsing
has to live. Officials have given the panda medicines and fluids to
hydrate and stabilize his condition.
</P>
<P>
   To treat his arthritis, Hsing-Hsing is also taking
anti-inflammatory drugs, which could aggravate his kidney problems.
But the panda would lose his appetite and energy without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling better, but Hsing-Hsing's long term prognosis
remains the same, which is not good,'' said National Zoo
spokeswoman Margie Gibson. ``He is very old for a panda. He's lived
a good, long life.'' Zoo officials are hopeful they can get two
more pandas despite, political difficulties. In June, the zoo is
sending a team to China to negotiate for the pandas, Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The zoological relationship has always been separate,'' Gibson
said. ``The pandas are not political even though Hsing Hsing's
illness is at a symbolic point. The zoological relationship is more
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing attracted thousands of visitors to the
zoo over the years. The pair tried to mate, producing several cubs,
none of whom lived more than a few days. Ling Ling died of old age
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Giant pandas typically live about 15 years in captivity, Gibson
said. Pandas, native to China, are endangered with only about 1,000
left worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the panda house this week were greeted with a sign
saying Hsing-Hsing's scheduled feedings had been cancelled and the
panda house may be closed periodically.
</P>
<P>
   Hsing-Hsing looked lethargic in the zoo's panda house on Friday.
He munched bamboo, while slumped a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coincidental about the timing of Hsing-Hsing's illness,''
said visitor Jack Good, of Alexandria, Va. ``But what can you do?
These things happen. I'd seen him once before but wanted to see him
again when I heard he was sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorful ``get well'' cards from local Washington elementary
school students were displayed near the Panda House. But visitors
from around the nation stopped in to pay a special visit to
Hsing-Hsing.
</P>
<P>
   One visitor, Elaine Pinckney, of Vermont, said the Panda House
was the highlight of her trip to the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen Hsing-Hsing,'' Pinckney said. ``He's so cute.
He's the main attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaning over the railing in front of the Panda House,
14-year-old Travis Ligon, said,: ``He's so cute. I don't want to
leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
