A5840 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-TEX     06-07 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSION FOR MUSIC DRIVES CLIBURN AMATEUR PIANISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A glass installer, a TV news anchor, a hair
stylist, a casino manager, homemakers and doctors. This week, they
will gather in Fort Worth as musicians, along with others, for an
event that will underline the city's position as one of the piano
capitals of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-two pianists from around the world will compete in the
first International Piano Competition for Outstanding Amateurs on
Wednesday through Sunday at Ed Landreth Auditorium at Texas
Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's sponsored by the Van Cliburn Foundation, the same
organization that presents the prestigious Van Cliburn
International Piano Competition every four years, the International
Competition for Amateurs is in some ways the opposite of the main
Cliburn Competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission of the Cliburn Foundation is to propagate
classical music, particularly classical piano music,'' said Richard
Rodzinski, the foundation's executive director. ``Primarily, we do
that through the Cliburn Competition, the concert series, the
recordings, the radio broadcasts and the education program. One
area that we had not brought attention to was the making of music
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cliburn-sponsored amateur competition is open only to people
who are older than 30 and who are not professional pianists or
piano teachers. It doesn't seek to set up a career for the winners;
instead, it aims to recognize the art of the amateur _ the musician
who plays purely for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the main Cliburn Competition, which will next be
held in 2001, draws a group of young pianists, ages 30 and younger,
who are for the most part already deeply involved in professional
musical careers; it aims to enhance existing careers.
</P>
<P>
   The prize at the amateur competition clearly reflects that these
people are here for the fun of it. While the top prize at the main
Cliburn Competition is valued at more than a quarter of a million
dollars when engagements and perks are added up, the top prize at
the amateur competition is $2,000 cash, a pair of subscriptions to
the main Cliburn Competition, a collection of compact discs and the
opportunity to appear with an orchestra in Paris sometime before
2005.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur competition will also serve as a testing ground for
several new ideas for the main competition. A new jury scoring
system will replace the old ``pass/no pass'' system, in which each
juror voted simply for or against sending a competitor to the next
round. Under the new system, devised by mathematician John McBain
of Delphi Automotive Systems and successfully applied to the
Indianapolis International Violin Competition, jurors will be able
to give higher scores to competitors they particularly favor.
</P>
<P>
   Rodzinski says that the new system has been adopted for the main
Cliburn Competition. Other ideas being tested, but which have not
yet been adopted for the 2001 Cliburn, include the awarding of an
audience favorite award, decided by the vote of audience members at
the final round, and a special press jury award given by attending
music critics.
</P>
<P>
   Juror John Owings, head of the piano department at TCU and a
past winner of the Casadesus International Piano Competition, said
serving on this jury will be different than at usual piano
competitions for aspiring professional performers. ``I'll have to
get a sense of what the level of playing is,'' he said. ``But
musicality will always be the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Owings has heard several of the competitors play in master
classes at TCU in conjunction with the special Amateurs Week at the
TCU/Cliburn Piano Institute, and said that the quality of playing
may be quite high.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth amateur competition is not the first event of its
type. In 1989, French music lover Gerard Bekerman founded the
Concours des Grands Amateurs de Piano, which has been held annually
in Paris. Bekerman has enthusiastically endorsed the
Cliburn-sponsored amateur competition, and will assist the jury in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   How frequently the Cliburn amateur competition will occur has
not been determined. The response has been enthusiastic enough that
it almost certainly will be repeated, probably every two or four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the last preparations for the competition are taking
place in living rooms around the world. While the main Cliburn
Competition quadrennially brings 35 of the most talented young
pianists in the world to Fort Worth, the amateur competition has
drawn an extraordinary mixture of occupations.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors include Lauren Green, news anchor for Fox News in
New York, and Michael Kimmelman, chief art critic for The New York
Times, along with professors, many computer programmers and
computer scientists, and several doctors and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Close to home, Judith Sherrard of Grapevine, 45 years old and
the mother of three children, ages 5, 8 and 12, will compete with a
program of Poulenc, Scarlatti and Mendelssohn. A graduate of
Arlington High School in Arlington, Sherrard majored in piano
briefly at Indiana University before switching to English
literature; she taught at Galveston College before becoming a
full-time homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   For Sherrard, as for most of the competitors, playing the piano
is just part of a much fuller life. She plays when she can on her
1903 Steinway grand, but gets in most of her practicing on a rented
electronic piano that can be silenced while everyone else in the
house sleeps. She admits that she occasionally finds G.I. Joe or a
Barbie shoe hidden away inside the grand, and that everyone in the
family has heard her music quite a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the dog knows the music by now,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But, she says, ``I've never played better in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SCHEDULE OF EVENTS: All events are at Ed Landreth Auditorium,
University Drive at Cantey Street, Texas Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminaries:
</P>
<P>
   Each competitor will perform one 10-minute program.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: 10-11:30 a.m., 3-6 p.m., 8-11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: 10 a.m.-1 p.m., 3-7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Friday: 10 a.m.-1 p.m., 3-5 p.m., 8-11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Semifinals: Up to 18 competitors will perform one 20-minute
program.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: 2-5:30 p.m., 7:30-11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Finals and awards: Six competitors will perform one 30-minute
program.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday: 3-8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices:
</P>
<P>
   Preliminaries: $5 per session, $25 for all sessions
</P>
<P>
   Semifinals: $10 per session, $15 for all sessions
</P>
<P>
   Finals and awards: $20
</P>
<P>
   For information, call (817) 335-9000
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
