<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5862 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-CREEK-HNS     06-07 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-CREEK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL FAN PITCHES A HOME RUN IN `BATTLE CREEK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scott Lasser turned the battered baseball glove
over and over in his hand. It was a Wilson A2000 model Lasser
hadn't seen in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lasser, offering readings from his new baseball novel, ``Battle
Creek'' (William Morrow and Co. $24. 266 pages), got the glove
earlier that week from his sister, who wound up with it when her
brother went from playing the outfield to first base at Andover
High School in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've seen this glove since '77,'' said Lasser, a
bonds trader on Wall Street who wrote the bulk of ``Battle Creek''
while commuting to work from Westchester County, N.Y. ``My sister
returning it, after all these years, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasser's younger sister, Kelly, a San Francisco designer, said
she was not surprised her brother's first book is about baseball.
``It was almost a religion in our family,'' she said. ``I had to
throw the ball for an hour in the back yard before I could eat
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime I show up for a softball game they're always impressed
I have an A2000,'' said Lasser, who got the glove from her father.
``He instilled discipline in us. He'd tell us that, in baseball,
you're never alone out there. It's a team game.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Lasser, 37, said he wasn't sure his first novel would be
about baseball until after he'd started it. Drawing on his own
playing days and his father's lifelong commitment to the game,
Lasser created a book in which raw rookies and weather-beaten
veterans team up to try and win Michigan's semipro Single-A
championship at Battle Creek.
</P>
<P>
   At last month's reading, Lasser chose a chapter on Ben Mercer,
an aging pitcher who's trying to sneak up a wooden fire escape to
see a woman 10 years younger than he is. Talking to himself, he
falls through a railing into a compost heap 12 feet below.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ankle is on fire,'' Lasser reads. ``He rolls about in the
rotting grapefruit rinds and coffee grounds, an organic ooze of
squash an potato skins, egg shells, long-forgotten tomatoes, and
newly formed mold ... he does what any man in his situation would
do: he rises to his feet, wipes himself off, and heads for his
car.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus of ``Battle Creek,'' though, is Gil Davison, manager
of the team Mercer pitches for, Koch and Sons. Davison, in his 60s,
has a love affair with baseball that overwhelms him as he stands in
the dugout at the championship tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember this, Gil tells himself, knowing that he will not do
it again. Remember how it looks, with one inning to go, three outs,
to the win. Remember the people standing with their fingers hooked
through the metal fence, remember the milky blue of the stadium
paint and the similar color of the sky. Remember the cereal ads
hanging from the outfield fence, and the sound of practice
grounders rolling across the infield an the jumping dust in their
wake ...''
</P>
<P>
   Lasser said his high school playing days came back to him while
writing ``Battle Creek,'' along with passages from some of his
favorite baseball books: ``The Natural,'' by Bernard Malamud;
``Veracruz Blues,'' a contemporary novel of baseball in Mexico; and
``A False Spring,'' a nearly forgotten book about Pat Jordan's
rookie spring with the Milwaukee Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Each book ``helps you to see through the game and why people
play it,'' he said, adding, ``I never set out to write about
baseball. I didn't really think it was a legitimate literary topic.
But the more I thought about it, the more I got tied up with it,
through my father, through my youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Detroit, Lasser grew up a Tigers fan. ``Being a
Tigers fan is an education,'' he said. ``A long and painful road.
But then you have the '68 Tigers ... you can't take a memory like
that away.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasser, whose next projects are a book of short stories and a
novel about Wall Street, is not sure why baseball holds such a
special place in the heart of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football and basketball are truly American games, too,'' he
said, ``but there's something about baseball that is very
compelling, especially for a writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's because it's a summer game, the sounds of it, the
smells of it. The smells of cut grass, of infield dirt, of summer
games at night ... distinctively physical touches.''
</P>
<P>
   There's the father-son thing, too, said Lasser, who's been
tossing the ball around with his 9-year-old son, Charlie, who plays
in Little League. ``The game just gets a hold of you and won't let
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
