<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-07 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ART ATTACKS, CALL AN AMIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Once again San Francisco has fallen behind
Silicon Valley. The city of Mountain View, population 54,206, main
export software, has an ``Ambience Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   I assume that's spelled ``ambience,'' the English way, rather
than ambiance, the French way. Mountain View surely can't be that
uppity.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, when KTVU-TV reported that Mountain View has an
Ambience Committee, everyone in my newsroom fell over laughing.
</P>
<P>
   When I came to the San Francisco Bay area 22 years ago, I lived
in an Eichler (a kind of tract home that now has cachet, pardon the
French) in Mountain View. If the town had an Ambience Committee
then, it required homeowners to park pickups in driveways, and
developers to build theme malls with corny wooden mills.
</P>
<P>
   The best ambience in all of Mountain View was in the tiny La
Poblanita restaurant on Castro Street. It wasn't because the decor
was anything, but because the customers were so happy eating the
fine chile verde.
</P>
<P>
   That was ambient. But La Poblanita is gone now, and Castro
Street, like all of Silicon Valley, glitters with the ambience of
stock options and BMWs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an accident that the head of Mountain View's Ambience
Committee is the city's economic development manager.
</P>
<P>
   Give the guy credit. His committee banned white plastic chairs
at outdoor restaurants. Those chairs look cheap even sitting in
Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   If they'd been invented in 1977, I wouldn't have put one in my
Eichler.
</P>
<P>
   After my pals and I quit laughing about Mountain View's attempt
at civic upward mobility, we thought a little more about it.
</P>
<P>
   If the Ambience Committee in Mountain View can outlaw white
plastic chairs in outdoor restaurants because they look cheesy,
imagine what a city with San Francisco's ambience can do.
</P>
<P>
   And, man, do we love committees. San Francisco already has a
Toilet Commission, and people actually agree to sit on it _ the
commission, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   Think how our nobility, not to mention their esthetics sheriff,
Stanlee Gatti, would clamor to sit on an ambience committee.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the committee would have to decide what San
Francisco's ambience is, or even if we'd use that word. It's a
froufrou word that sounds classy to people who strive too hard to
have class.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Mayor Willie Brown would like it, so ambience it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Pray to San Francisco's raffish gods that Brown doesn't appoint
the entire San Francisco Ambience Committee. If that happened, the
City Hall dress code of suit and tie would be extended to every
coffeehouse and rock concert in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Every building would have to have a gold-leaf dome on top, like
the mayor's big gilded hat on top of City Hall. But it would have
to be smaller.
</P>
<P>
   A Brown-dominated Ambience Committee would eliminate his most
hated thing, clutter. There would be no clutter of news boxes on
the streets to bring a clutter of bad news to all those squalling,
messy people.
</P>
<P>
   The really messy, the homeless, would be shipped out in the name
of quality of ambience.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no clutter of candidates running against Brown
either, because he fiercely believes he's the best thing for San
Francisco ambience since the invention of fog.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, if Brown was dictating the decor (and he is),
would be one big hotel that only a few people can afford.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it would go with an Ambience Committee of one.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's popularity has diminished. So now is the time to load
the San Francisco Ambience Committee with people who don't use the
word ``ambience'' _ or think it's what they don't get right away
after dialing 911.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain a real San Francisco ambience, the Ambience
Committee should be a rainbow of ambient enlightenment itself. It
should include gays of all orientations, Art Deco or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   It should include white heterosexual males of the Giants'
windbreaker persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   The Ambience Committee should include computer geeks in black
vinyl jackets, old folks in gardening gear, mechanics in
grease-stained overalls and rich kids in rolled-up jeans that will
never be stained by anything greasier than drippings from their
Thai smoked duck wraps.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also should include members of the cap-backwards
community, even if they're getting hard to find because the new
style is caps with brims all the way around, so you can't tell when
they're backwards.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, when you talk about ambience in San Francisco, you come
back to people.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how an Ambience Committee can save people from high
rents and ugly lofts, but I know something about San Francisco
committees. If we get all those folks on a committee, they won't
agree on anything.
</P>
<P>
   Let a hundred San Francisco ambiences bloom. But don't call it
ambience. Maybe Silicon Valley's aura and cafe chairs need
cleansing, but not ours in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
