<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
June 8. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR: Oscar Goodman, mob lawyer with Kansas City connections,
is in a runoff Tuesday to become the mayor of Las Vegas. The
flamboyant criminal defense attorney who admits he was once a
mouthpiece for the mob, defended the Civellas and other gangsters
in Kansas City. We profile Goodman's colorful past and talk to
Strike Force members in Kansas City who may not remember him as
fondly. Mark Morris. 25. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL (business) _ On any given day, tractor-trailer rigs queue
up for a mile or more on both sides of the Mexican border at
Laredo, Texas, waiting to cross. A phenomenal increase in trade, a
preoccupation with illegal drugs and illegal aliens, and differing
business cultures each play a part in the daily backlog. From 1,000
miles away, Doug Luciani of the Greater Kansas City Chamber of
commerce smells opportunity in the exhaust of that daily jam. By
Eric Palmer. Photo, graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SHOP (business) _ Online retailing is capturing more and more
consumer dollars, and threatening the future of the shopping mall.
By Mark Couch.
</P>
<P>
   YELLOW (business) _ Yellow Corp. is buying a regional trucking
company for $160 million. By Randolph Heaster
</P>
<P>
   LEVITT (business) _ SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt will be in Kansas
City on June 30 to host a town hall meeting on small business. By
Mark Davis
</P>
