<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, June 8:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Bonn, Germany) _ Ledeall. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO is backing off from talk
of intensifying the bombing until they see what the Russians are
going to do. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ White House reaction, plans,
etc. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ The Pentagon thinks there is a
split between the Serbian military and Milosevic, with the military
supposedly irked that they did not have a chance to finish off the
KLA and wanting to buy time. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Tentative: Possible Kosovo debate
in Congress during discussion on Pentagon spending. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COSIC (Belgrade) _ Rare interview with the former prime
minister who essentially invented Kosovo as an issue and was later
tossed out by Milosevic. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is also working on developments in Macedonia and
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta) _ Ballot counting continues amid a
sense of exhilaration. But the ruling party is getting a bit
fidgety; top party official talks about fears of having to settle
for third place. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BALLOTING (Dadap) _ As the ballot counting began in
this fishing village west of Jakarta today, a crowd of eagle-eyed
locals encircled a makeshift polling place. They watched as workers
laboriously unfolded and called out each vote. It was a tedious
business, but nobody here was complaining. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CABINET (Jerusalem) _ Parliament is sworn in; oddly,
Netanyahu is still in charge because there is no new government. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-POLAND (Poland) _ Pontiff's trip continues. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CLINTON (Washington) _ Developments. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH-CONFERENCE (Washington) _ White House mental
health conference: the two first couples are together again,
pushing for parity in mental health insurance coverage; we look at
how they interact and what it means to the coming campaigns of the
two candidates. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HABEUS (Washington) _ Court turns screws on inmates by
ruling that an inmate who has not appealed all the way through the
state's highest court can not yet go for federal habeus review.
Round up. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MINISTER-GAY-MARRIAGE (California) _ As the gay issue continues
to divide congregations around the country, a California minister
faces trial for marrying 40 gay couples. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-BLACKS-TAXIS (Miami) _ Society Cab has become more than a
taxi ride in some of Miami's black communities. In a part of the
city where taxi drivers must carry change for a quarter because
even a dime is more than most people can tip, the drivers are the
only ones who regularly answer calls in Miami's harshest
neighborhoods. Now, a piece of county legislation may do what
gunfire could not: do away with older cabs like the ones in
Society's fleet of 23. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   ALEXANDER-2000 (Maryville, Tenn.) _ The last time he ran for
president, Lamar Alexander saw no need to parade before voters his
membership in the elite fellowship of Eagle Scouts. To any son of
this modest, contented hill town, it would have been a vainglorious
boast. But this time around, the self-effacement is over,
jettisoned with the flannel shirts and statewide hikes. He is
convinced by a year of Washington scandal that his moment has
finally arrived. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   WHITMAN-CONSERVATIVES (Trenton, N.J.) _ As she prepares to run
for the Senate, Gov. Christie Whitman finds herself in a political
squeeze between conservative and moderate Republicans. By Jerry
Gray.
</P>
<P>
   STUN-GUNS-PRISONS (Undated) _ Amnesty International says prisons
are using stun belts to control prisoners. Is this legal? By
Williams Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-CHARTER-SCHOOLS (Phoenix) _ Most states _ including New
York, where the first charter schools are to open in the fall _ are
just beginning to grapple with a future in which families will be
able to choose among dozens of public schools operating under
charters that hold them to state standards, but give them freedom
to experiment and independence in hiring and spending. But Arizona
is already living it. The state now has more than 300 charter
schools, more than 70 in Phoenix alone, serving nearly 5 percent of
all students. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FREE-HEROIN-PROGRAM (New York) _ Taking a bold approach to
drug addiction, researchers at Columbia University are offering
free heroin to addicts and paying them to use it under a federally
authorized program aimed at finding a cure for their addictions.
Two trials involving heroin injections are among six related
drug-addiction studies being conducted at Columbia's College of
Physicians and Surgeons, all of which focus on the role existing
medications can play in defeating drug addictions. By Christopher
S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-RESEARCH (Washington) _ The director of the
National Institutes of Health has touched off a passionate debate
by proposing that scientists disclose and disseminate on the
Internet the results of biomedical research, so the full text of
their reports would be available at no cost to anyone with a
computer anywhere in the world. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-FIGHT (Washington) _ A private investigator with a
criminal record and dubious background is at the center of a big
legislative and legal fight that will determine what steps banks
and telephone companies must take to keep their records of all
their customers' activities private. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ADS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Demand for commercial time on the
broadcast TV networks for the 1999-2000 season, which begins in
September, is exceeding even the most optimistic forecasts made by
top television executives as recently as last month. Estimates are
that the networks will sell $7.25 billion or more worth of
commercial time during the prime-time programs they will present
during the 1999-2000 season. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   LAZARD-REORG (Undated) _ Lazard Partners announced a
reorganization that is intended to encourage its New York, London
and Paris investment banks to work more closely together,
continuing the push of its cguef executive Michel David-Weill. The
most prominent partner in New York, Steven Rattner, will surrender
the position of deputy chief executive to William Loomis, but will
remain as deputy. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Shanghai) _ China has admitted, in a newspaper
report, that there are deep divisions within leadership about
proposed entry to the World Trade Organization. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Dateline to come) _ ``Foreign Affairs'' by
Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
