A5885 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-HNS &LR;      06-07 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS GIRD FOR A DATE WITH DESTINY _ JAN. 1, 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was the opening day of Produce Palace, a
gourmet grocery store in a Detroit suburb. But business was over
not long after it started.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours into the day, a customer produced a credit card with
an expiration date of 00, as in the year 2000. The store's
computerized register couldn't comprehend this oddity and crashed.
Customers lined up 20 deep, and then finally stormed out.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1995, and store owner Mike Yarsike had just become
one of the first victims of a Y2K problem. Soon after, he also
became one of the first people to file a Y2K lawsuit _ in this case
against the maker of his registers. In 1998, he agreed to a
$260,000 settlement from manufacturer TEC America Inc. of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated the cost of getting the nation's computers and
electronic equipment ready to accept the year 2000 will be in the
tens of billions of dollars. That may pale next to the cost of Y2K
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are predicting this is going to be as big as the
tobacco industry (lawsuits),'' said Jonathan Summers, a lawyer for
Thuillez, Ford, Gold &AMP; Johnson in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Summers attended a Y2K seminar in New Orleans last year, and
since then has been keeping an eye on Y2K legal issues. While he
hasn't filed any lawsuits, he has talked to a number of clients
about protecting themselves from possible lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real avalanche of litigation isn't going to occur until
after Jan. 1, assuming there are breakdowns,'' he said. ``We're all
kind of sitting back, waiting to see what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As Dec. 31 approaches, many businesses that could be affected by
the Y2K computer bug are readying themselves on two fronts:
ensuring the machinery will work, and ensuring the business won't
be sued if it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts fear that many computers originally programmed
to recognize only the last two digits of a year will fail or
malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines might assume it is
1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if there's losses, there's going to be litigation,''
Summers said. ``If there's a pocket out there somebody can point
to, there's going to be litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, lawsuits have already started. In the past
few years, IBM, AT&AMP;T and Lucent Technologies have all been sued for
selling programs or equipment with Y2K problems. A California
lawsuit claims some stores, including Circuit City and CompUSA,
failed to warn consumers about Year 2000 problems in equipment,
like VCRs or computers, purchased at those stores.
</P>
<P>
   Most insurance companies, meanwhile, have announced they will
not cover Y2K lawsuits. Businesses, insurers say, should have seen
it coming and should have done something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies are sending letters out to their customers,
said Joe Distell, an agent with Reidman Insurance of West Sand
Lake, N.Y. He specializes in commercial insurance.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he said, could lead to further lawsuits _ clients
suing their insurers, claiming the companies have no right to say
they won't cover Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, legislation is being proposed across the United
States in an effort to protect against an onslaught of Y2K-related
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   On the federal end, the bills include attempts to limit awards,
a requirement giving companies an opportunity to fix Y2K problems
before being sued and protection for retailers that sell faulty
products made by other companies.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 states are working on Y2K bills. At least 11 have
enacted some. Most are geared to protecting companies.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are generally opposed to legislation that protects
companies. Walter Effross, a professor at the Washington College of
Law at American University in Washington, D.C., said such laws are
just a cop-out for companies that knew about Y2K problems for years
but ignored them until too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly not the case of manufacturers all of a sudden
waking up to the fact that there's something wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Effross, who recently testified before a House of
Representatives Y2K subcommittee, said companies can take simple
measures to protect themselves: stock up on inventory if they're
worried about suppliers, contact equipment manufacturers to see if
key machinery is Y2K compliant and, if the company manufactures
software, either make sure the program works or get upgrades to
customers as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Polster, a lawyer with DeLorenzo, Pasquariello and Weiskoph
in Schenectady, N.Y., said there were many reasons why a company
could be sued for a Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   A supply company could be sued if its plant breaks down and it
can't supply what has been promised. A stockbroker could be sued
for recommending the stock from a company that loses value if it is
not compliant. And a company can be sued if it sells a product
that, like the registers at the Produce Palace outside Detroit,
breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Polster, who spent the past six months learning all he could
about Y2K, is preparing for what could be a very busy year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It upsets me there are so many people doing nothing,'' he
said. ``And there are people who will be injured as a result of
their inaction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
