<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH READY TO HIT CAMPAIGN TRAIL IN EARNEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His teen-age daughter has already concluded that
Texas Gov. George W. Bush is not as cool as people think he is. Now
the rest of the country will get a chance to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning a stay-at-home strategy that has made him the stealth
candidate of Campaign 2000 _ unseen but feared by opponents _ the
governor will leave Texas for the first time this week to defend
his status as the Republican presidential front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Few political debuts have generated so much interest. After
weeks of enjoying favorable polls from the comfort of the
Governor's Mansion, Bush will finally confront the swirling demands
of sky-high expectations, pent-up media skepticism and the
indignities that come with dusk-to-dawn campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   At least 100 reporters and photographers plan to join Bush in
Austin on Saturday as he sets off on a four-day swing to Iowa and
New Hampshire, the traditional leadoff states for presidential
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a media circus,'' said Dennis Goldford, a
political science professor at Drake University in Des Moines,
Iowa. ``This is hardball. He may have owned the Texas Rangers, but
I don't know if he can play hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush's GOP rivals, the trip marks a welcome new phase in
what promises to be a grueling struggle for the Republican
nomination. After weeks of shadow boxing with a front-runner who
refused to leave his corner, they might finally get a chance to
land a punch.
</P>
<P>
   Ten other Republicans have acknowledged White House ambitions,
but none comes close to Bush in early presidential polls. The first
nominating contests will not occur until February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the campaign begin,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for
Elizabeth Dole. ``The governor has a sizable first-place lead. The
question is, `Can he hold it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The road to the White House is littered with the wreckage of
other campaigns that began in Texas. Former Sen. Lloyd Bentsen in
1976, former Gov. John Connally in 1980 and Sen. Phil Gramm in 1996
all learned the hard way that promising poll numbers and a long
list of wealthy donors do not guarantee success.
</P>
<P>
   But none of them started with as much potential as Bush, who is
far ahead of his rivals in terms of campaign contributions,
endorsements and poll support.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor raised $7.6 million in the first three months
of the year without even holding a fund-raiser. Aides said he is on
track to more than double that amount in the second quarter. At
least 16 of the nation's 31 Republican governors have endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has to show that the support is justified. Although other
candidates have the luxury of committing their early campaign
blunders while almost no one is watching, Bush will be in the
spotlight from the moment he climbs on his campaign plane.
</P>
<P>
   It has been called the political equivalent of opening a
Broadway play without rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who repeated his daughter's assessment to reporters last
week, said he is eager to hit the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read all the stories and I've seen the TV about politics
in the year 2000,'' he said. ``Now I need to go out and look people
in the eye and hear what they have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, Bush will be the featured attraction at separate
fund-raisers for two congressmen, Reps. James Nussle and Greg
Ganske. At least 2,000 Iowans are expected to turn out for Ganske's
event at the state fairgrounds in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bulk of his time will be spent shaking everybody's hand.
The hard part is shaking everybody's hand and having 100 cameras
trying to get the same shot,'' said campaign spokeswoman Mindy
Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's crowded New Hampshire schedule includes a mix of formal
events and up-close-and-personal campaigning. The Texas governor
plans to greet early morning shift workers at a plant in Derry,
chat with diners at a restaurant and drop by a fire station.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will take time out Sunday to celebrate his father's 75th
birthday with other family members in Kennebunkport, Maine, which
served as a summer White House for former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The shake-down cruise to Iowa and New Hampshire is a prelude to
a busy month that will include a five-day swing to the East Coast,
Pennsylvania and Michigan, and a four-day trip to California.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Pitney, a political science professor at Claremont McKenna
College in Claremont, Calif., said Bush does not necessarily have
to dazzle audiences, but he does have to avoid any embarrassing
gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is looking for the stumble,'' Pitney said. ``He
needs to show that he can campaign effectively and that he can
handle issues smoothly even when he's evading them. He doesn't have
to solve Kosovo. He only needs to pronounce it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
