 BUDGET-HNS  
 Monday, June 7, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)    WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDICARE (Washington) _ President Clinton plans to offer
one of the last major domestic initiatives of his presidency _ a
controversial proposal to extend prescription drug coverage to
millions of Medicare recipients willing to pay a low monthly
premium. The idea was dubbed too costly by a bipartisan commission
that failed to agree on how to reform Medicare in March. BY STEWART
M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   SUPREME-COURT (Washington) _ With less than a month left in its
current term, the Supreme Court still has some tough cases to
decide. Two of them will further define the scope of the Americans
with Disabilities Act, and another will determine how much power
police have in dealing with street gangs. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Ever since he was kicked out of the
White House inner circle for cavorting with a prostitute, political
consultant-turned-pundit Dick Morris has been dumping on President
Clinton. Now he's turned against Hillary Clinton, too, predicting
that she can't win a Senate seat in New York. But he underestimates
her. She has more assets than liabilities. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
