<HEADER>
A5892 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAGEDIES-DESENSITIZE     06-07 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAGEDIES-DESENSITIZE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDIES HAVE MADE NATION NUMB, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
and SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ It started with a rash of tornadoes in late
January that killed seven and injured 55 in the Little Rock area.
</P>
<P>
   In May, 13 people drowned when a tour boat sank in Hot Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedies, coupled with Tuesday's deadly crash of American
Airlines Flight 1420, have some people in Arkansas wondering when
the state is going to get a break from bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm getting a little numb to it,'' said Roger Andrews
Jr., a 32-year-old Sherwood, Ark., resident who was at Little Rock
National Airport on Friday when passengers who were on the
ill-fated flight returned to view the wreckage. ``Maybe we should
just all leave the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas is hardly alone in dealing with an unusually high
number of tragedies this year. Nationwide, the drumbeat of disaster
has been pounding the collective psyche of Americans on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   In April, 14 students and a teacher died in the Columbine High
School shootings near Littleton, Colo. In early May, dozens of
tornadoes killed 44 in the Oklahoma City area. Six days later, a
bus accident near New Orleans killed 22.
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of the events and the intense media coverage may
contribute to people being desensitized to the plight of those hit
by tragedy, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   That response, said one Little Rock counselor, is a matter of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We develop mechanisms to deal with trauma in our lives,'' said
Cheryl Campbell, who has studied the effects of trauma and stress.
``When there's a lot of trauma going on, you get desensitized.''
</P>
<P>
   If the incidents that have resulted in multiple deaths and loss
of property had been spread over time, people might have responded
differently to each tragedy, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People heal over time,'' said Ralph Hyman, who teaches
psychiatry to residents at the University of Arkansas for Medical
Services. ``If trauma happens in a short period of time, people
haven't healed, and so they become numbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's crash was yet another trauma that Americans have gone
through together. But it seemed to some, who were not directly
touched by the accident, to be not as tragic, more like a major car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The plane landed where it was supposed to, it happened at night,
and the wreckage wasn't accessible to the masses, except via
photographs and videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people lost their lives Tuesday night, but a plane crash
does not reveal a larger-picture issue, such as the Columbine
shootings and the subsequent discussions about guns in the hands of
youngsters, child rearing and violence in the media, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   John Sommerville, a history professor at the University of
Florida in Gainesville, Fla., and author of How the News Makes Us
Dumb, said that the crash was an isolated incident and that unless
people want to identify and empathize with the victims, they don't
really get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always struck me as odd that plane crashes chase
everything else off the page when they have no larger political or
social context,'' Sommerville said. ``They just scare us more than
anything else, and that's what the news is good at _ creating
anxieties and insecurities.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who did not consider the crash to be tragic might be
looking at the glass as half-full, said an instructor at the
Poynter Institute of Media Studies in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that people are looking at how many people survived
vs. what could have happened,'' said Aly Colon, who teaches ethics
and diversity at the institute. ``They might be pleased it isn't a
greater tragedy. ... That might have an impact. If people are
noting that so many people got out alive and it could have been
worse, that could cause people to be more accepting, though not
necessarily pleased about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatively low number of fatalities in the crash likely
contributed to the life-goes-on atmosphere in Little Rock and its
airport just a day after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``With nine deaths, the Red Cross doesn't have to go out and get
a school gymnasium,'' said Janet Sonier, a crisis counselor in Fort
Worth. ``There's not the impact on the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent images of death and destruction across the country
might lead people to perceive the crash as a ``here we go again''
situation, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Colon echoed that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it becomes very difficult over a period of time to
sustain the surprise and shock to the tremendous amount of tragic
news that continues to flood the news media,'' Colon said. ``In
this case, you are dealing with an event that happened and was
somewhat isolated with one particular airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the glut of information that is permeating all
different types of media is going to at some point begin to dull
the sensitivity that people have to it,'' she said. ``The element
of surprise, of newness, of freshness begins to wear. People need
to take a break.''
</P>
<P>
   To Charlie Robinson of West Helena, Ark., each of the tragedies
in Arkansas has been disturbing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and his father were in Little Rock on Friday to buy
automobile parts and stopped by the airport. Sitting on the
tailgate of a pickup, they used binoculars to try to get a view of
the crash site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we're hit one time after another,'' Robinson
said. ``I don't know what we've got to do to catch a break, but it
just seems like we can't catch one right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russellville, Ark., it was clear that the deaths of six
residents who were on Flight 1420 has not numbed the town's
reaction, said Rick Fahr, a reporter at The Courier, the town's
daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen just exactly the opposite,'' he said. ``We didn't
just lose John Q. Public walking down the street. These people were
heavily involved in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has got to be something that stays with them
(townspeople) the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
