<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-ADVENTURE-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plunging into the unknown in quest of knowledge is the special
legacy of this millennium. Where must the explorer go now to find
unknown territory?
</P>
<P>
   Find out in the following articles from ``Into the Unknown:
1,000 Years of Human Daring,'' the third of six special issues to
be published by The New York Times Magazine. Available from The New
York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   These articles, which are for release June 6 or thereafter, will
move on the wire starting Fri., June 4. Many feature LOCAL ANGLE
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   For rates on one-shots, ``partnerships'' and packages of three
or six articles per issue, please contact your New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, listed at the end of this advisory.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FOLLOWING SPECIAL PACKAGE of three articles will move on
June 4 FREE to Centerpiece clients. To become a subscriber, please
contact your sales rep for details. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---
 &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-WHY-GO &LR;  -- Why do people seek adventure?
Surviving the unusual, from kayaking to space travel, means
stepping across an inner boundary. It's in those moments when you
go from calmness to curiosity to worry to panic that you learn the
most and your life changes _ and you have a wonderful time. By
Andrea Barrett, who won the National Book Award for ``Ship Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-HUCK &LR;  -- Mark Twain launched a fictional
adventure 115 years ago that still resonates: A village boy named
Huck Finn and a fugitive slave named Jim raft down the Mississippi
River together. In a latter-day version, essayist Stanley Crouch
and Southern novelist Richard Ford set out to see how life, and
race relations, have changed. Here is an account by Crouch, author
of ``Notes of A Hanging Judge,'' a New York Daily News columnist
and a former commentator for CBS' ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-FOREST &LR;  -- He took the No. 4 train, got off at
Fordham Road and hiked to a huge wall of trees with a tiny sign in
front: ``The Forest.'' He got an OK from the security guard, picked
up his knapsack full of Kit-Kat bars, sour pickles and V-8 juice,
clipped an emergency beeper to his tent and strode into New York
City's last primeval forest. That night he met a coyote and a skunk
_ and attained the urban adventurer's version of Thoreau's inner
peace. By Charles Siebert, who wrote ``Wickerby: An Urban
Pastoral.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE 3 FEATURES ABOVE, in addition to ARTWORK below, which will
be detailed in a separate Millennium Art Budget,
(BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-ART-BUDGET), to move June 11, may be published
by Millennium Series package clients. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----
 &UR; MAPPING the MILLENNIUM: ``Points of No Return'' ... A Chronicle of
reminders that traveling the globe is a risky business. &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By Stephen Mihm &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Artwork availability: 35mm color slides or electronic transmission
(via E-MAIL, NEWSCOM or WIECK photo database) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-FINN &LR;  -- For Richard Ford, heading down the
Mississippi River in the same boat with Stanley Crouch was an
opportunity to confront a difficult truth about himself _ and the
limits of thinking in black and white. The Pulitzer Prize-winning
novelist's books include ``The Sportswriter.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-SAINT &LR;  -- Walking and giving, walking and
singing, walking and praying: That's what one medieval Italian
roustabout did, and his path over a desolate Umbrian landscape
became a proving ground for sainthood. This author retraces the
steps of St. Francis of Assisi and finds out why he talked to birds
and flowers, and why fish refused to die in his hands and hunted
animals sought refuge at his side. By Gretel Ehrlich, who wrote
``Questions of Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-BRAIN &LR;  -- Brain scans can locate the home of
memory and the land of language. They may eventually help to map
consciousness. This ``traveler'' enters the narrow mouth of a
Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) machine at Memorial Sloan Cancer
Center in New York. The scans show 226,000,000 data points in 21
``slices'' of his brain and lead him on a journey to the center of
his mind. By Stephen S. Hall, a contributing science writer for The
New York Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The following articles, and 1 piece of art, are available for
purchase as ONE-SHOT features. They are FREE to subscribers to the
Millennium Plus partnership package. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-CARTOON-MACK &LR;  -- ``Overheard at the Explorer's Club,'' a
cartoon by Stan Mack, is a witty, urbane view of the sort of folks
who study the whales of the Galapagos and find mystical qualities
in the gallstones of llamas ... and then gather to talk about it
all in fancy ballrooms with crystal chandeliers and dainty hors
d'oeuvres. (Available in 35mm slide or via electronic transmission)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-NIGERIA &LR;  -- Still they come, close to a million
legal immigrants every year, for a new life in America. The first
census, in 1790, counted 3.9 million Americans. Today, with
ceaseless immigration, there are 275 million. For Murphy Popoola, a
Nigerian, to become an American is an escape. But it may also be a
way to return to Nigeria as a citizen of the world. By Roger Cohen,
the Berlin bureau chief of The New York Times and author of
``Hearts Grown Brutal: Sagas of Sarajevo.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-YOUTH &LR;  -- It's after college. Do you know where
your young people are? Here are profiles of six youthful wanderers
who, in an era of packaged tours, set out on their own for remote
corners of the globe to find danger, surprise, odd people and very
bizarre food. By Leslie Downer, a London-based writer who
hitchhiked from Greece to India in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-TECH &LR;  -- In a wired world, it's time to pull
the plug. Thanks to beepers, cell phones, faxes and Global Village
modems, a traveler simply can't get lost. Here's an idea: Climb
1,300 feet above the Pacific Ocean to a Benedictine hermitage _ a
place where friends and bosses can't reach you _ and where you,
therefore, can reach a deeper self. By Pico Iyer, the author of
``Tropical Classical'' and, coming out this winter, ``The Global
Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-CEZANNE &LR;  -- Cezanne worshiped Mounte
Ste.-Victoire as the epitome of Nature at its most sublime. And
Petrarch climbed Mount Ventoux to commune with the gods. But the
author, a decidedly urban traveler, scales the peaks _ and
concludes that mountains, far from sublime, are like glorified
Stairmasters for the upwardly mobile. By Michael Kimmelman, chief
art critic for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-CHINA &LR;  -- Decades before Columbus, Zheng He
sailed from China with 300 ships and 28,000 men. His fleet got as
far as Africa and could have easily reached America, but the
Chinese turned back. What happened? By Nicholas D. Kristof, Tokyo
bureau chief of The New York Times and the author, with Sheryl
WuDunn, of ``China Wakes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-BOOKS &LR;  -- Armchair adventure, anyone? We like
stories of dangerous exploits, tales of high altitudes and deep
water. Adventure novels keep us entertained _ and alive. We love
legends of people who come out alive after terrible experiences.
Beyond mere escapism, travel stories help us discern the limits of
human frailty, prepare for the unexpected and imagine what we'd do
in perilous circumstances. By Annie Proulx, the author, most
recently, of ``Close Range,'' a collection of short stories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-WORDS &LR;  -- The word ``adventurer'' has had a
wild ride through the millennium. Today, to be ``adventuresome'' is
to be bold and daring, to take risks without a connotation of
heedlessness or imprudence. Saunter back a few decades, though, and
``adventurer'' meant a brawler, a plunderer, and even the Devil
himself. By William Safire, the veteran New York Times political
analyst and ``On Language'' columnist for The Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-OCEAN &LR;  -- A novelist sent to the bottom of the
sea finds illumination in the darkest of places. His bird's-eye
view is provided by the bubble cockpit of a Johnson-Sea-Link
submersible, a robotic, eerily anthropomorphic, high-tech
contraption with baskets, tentacles and mobile arms. There he can
say hello to angel-fish, deep-sea fireflies and whales about 1,043
feet below the sunny, sparkling waters off Chub Cay in the Bahamas.
By Robert Stone, author of seven books including ``Damascus Gate.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-DISASTER &LR;  -- Ever go on a journey that turns
out worse than staying home? Here's a log of low travel points of
the millennium, from the 14th century, when a Moroccan explorer
nearly died from food poisoning, to the 20th century, when a
British climber failed to make it up Nanga Parbat, because he
sneezed. A succinct report on explorers who should have stayed in
bed that day. By John Tierney, a columnist for The New York Times
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-SAVOY &LR;  -- After discovering lost Incan cities,
Gene Savoy is searching for something truly exotic: the Fountain of
Youth. Savoy, the 72-year-old travel journalist and explorer, is
sailing around the world in a catamaran, with a crew of middle-age
men _ and BBC cameras on board. By Brad Wetzler, a writer for
Outside magazine and a contributing editor for George.
</P>
<P>
   .........................................................
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S. and Canada: BOB FARNELL at 1-800-535-4425; fax,
717-646-4850. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thank you very much.
</P>
