<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMART-CARDS-HNS &LR;      06-07 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS STILL HAVEN'T WARMED UP TO SMART CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN BERGER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Visa wants America to like smart cards. So does
MasterCard. So does the government. But America isn't cooperating.
Not yet anyway.
</P>
<P>
   A smart card looks much like a credit card _ the kind with a
black magnetic stripe on the back. Instead of the stripe, however,
smart cards have an embedded computer chip that can store
electronic money and consumer information.
</P>
<P>
   Prevalent in Europe and parts of Asia, the technology has not
caught on in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic data stripes are a way to store a limited amount of
information on a plastic card, like bank or credit card account
information. A standard stripe holds enough data to provide fairly
secure access to bank accounts or other services. The magnetic
stripe contains an identification code, and the card reader _ such
as a cash register or an ATM machine _ uses that code to retrieve
information about the customer from a central database. The
information is stored on a computer server linked to the
card-reading device.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a magnetic stripe, smart cards have tiny
microprocessor chips on board, according to Paul Beverly, vice
president of communications for Schlumberger Smart Cards and
Terminals of San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The chip can be a simple memory storage device, or it can be a
more sophisticated processor. The chips can store relatively vast
amounts of data about their users, so a smart card can be used for
much more complicated tasks. These tasks include holding electronic
money, storing detailed personal health and financial profiles, or
acting as a highly secure key card for access to facilities and
computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   A unit of international conglomerate Schlumberger Ltd.,
Schlumberger Smart Cards is the world's leading manufacturer of
smart card technology, according to Faulkner &AMP; Gray's Card
Technology, an industry trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   The company makes smart cards, readers, development tools and
offers other related products and services. Card Technology says
1.25 billion smart cards were sold in 1998, with a 27 percent
increase expected for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   According to Olivier Piou, another Schlumberger vice president,
the company's sales grew 40 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger has installed more than 1 million smart card
terminals in 60 countries, including pay phone systems, banking and
point-of-sale terminals, multispace parking equipment and ticket
vending machines. The company has seen a lot of growth in
telecommunications and banking applications, especially in mobile
phone tools.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this growth, most of the action continues to be
centered in Europe. Schlumberger sells about 60 percent of its
smart cards in Europe; the U.S. market accounts for only about 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, several small-scale efforts to use smart
card technology have begun, however.
</P>
<P>
   In the Health Passport Project, being taken out for a test run
in the Midwest, smart cards are being issued to a test group of
pregnant women, mothers and children who get assistance from public
health programs like Medicaid and welfare. The cards store fairly
detailed health records for their owners and can transfer that
information to a central database.
</P>
<P>
   A trial program that concluded late last year _ in which
Schlumberger, other card manufacturers and several major credit
card companies took part _ tried to excite consumers and merchants
about using smart cards for commerce, but problems with card
readers and consumer indifference took a toll on the year-long
trial.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the program, about 600 merchants accepted
free smart card readers for use in their establishments. By the
time the program ended, though, only 200 merchants were still
participating.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has also mandated the use of smart
cards for employees to access federal buildings and its computer
networks. The cards can provide portable profiles of network users,
who can easily access files and sign onto networks without having
to enter a password.
</P>
<P>
   Spyrus Inc. of Santa Clara, Calif., has provided smart card
technology for that program, according to Bob Davis, vice president
of marketing. Spyrus makes hardware and software in systems for
encryption and secure identification, Davis said. The privately
held company had sales of about $20 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the smart card market has been much more active
in Europe and the Pacific Rim,'' Davis said, but the product is
starting to spread in the United States, especially for
identification and authentication uses.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger also has deals in the works with major banks and
hopes to announce new partnerships before the end of the year,
Beverly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
