<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5962 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-TALKS-BOS &LR;      06-07 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALKAN TALKS COLLAPSE AND NATO STEPS UP BOMBING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT PITZER AND DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMANOVO, Macedonia _ Talks on ending the Balkan war collapsed
overnight, and NATO officials vowed an immediate intensification of
the air attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav delegation ``presented a proposal that would not
guarantee the safe return of all the refugees, or the full
withdrawal of the Yugoslav forces,'' Lieutenant General Sir Michael
Jackson, commander of NATO troops in Macedonia, said early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO therefore has no alternative,'' he added, ``than to
continue and indeed intensify the air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, NATO B-52 bombers struck at Yugoslav Army
positions in a Kosovo region near the Albanian border where both
NATO and Yugoslav sources reported heavy fighting between Serb and
ethnic Albanian forces. The bombing continued and early Monday,
according to various reports, and concentrated on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens sounded in Belgrade, the capital, and Pancevo
and Novi Sad to the north early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO jets also hit western Kosovo late Sunday, firing 30
missiles at targets there over 35 minutes, the state-run Tanjug
news agency reported. Several missiles fell on Mount Pastrik, along
the border with Albania, and one struck the district Grmija in the
provincial capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between NATO and Yugoslav military commanders on Kosovo's
border with Macedonia broke down as Belgrade's delegation failed to
return on time after a break from the 10-hour marathon session.
Before the breakdown in talks, NATO said it would not continue the
discussions for a third day.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials reportedly held out on signing a six-page
document that would stipulate the withdrawal of 40,000 Serb
soldiers and police from Kosovo within seven days. The Yugoslavs
said that they needed at least two weeks to complete the pullout,
and that there were not enough guarantees that they would not be
attacked by rebels from the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the Serbs were simply stalling for time. The
talks, initially expected to end on Saturday, became more strained
as they stretched into a second day.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO insisted that the talks were not negotiations but
simply a case of their putting to Yugoslav Army officers the
timetables and routes under which Serb forces would pull out of
Kosovo, the Serbs insisted that they needed to consult with their
political masters in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials had expected the discussions to be wrapped up
Saturday, with Yugoslav generals reading and signing a ``military
technical agreement'' that lays out what Yugoslav Army and police
forces must do to end NATO's air campaign. But after nearly six
hours, they ended inconclusively and resumed Sunday morning at an
air base run by French NATO forces in Kumanovo, just northwest of
Skopje, the Macedonian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, commander of the 16,000 NATO troops in Macedonia who
are poised to enter Kosovo as peacekeepers, met Sunday with
Yugoslav generals Svetozar Marjanovic and Blagoje Kovacevic in a
tented hangar at the French base to hammer out details of the
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   After the pause was announced, the representative of the Italian
forces, Colonel Carmine de Pascale, emerged, visibly irritated.
``Very big problems have been created by the Serbs,'' he said
without elaborating, ``and they can only be solved'' by Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Lieutenant General Yevgeny Barmianchev, military attache
at the Russian Embassy here, attended Sunday's meeting as an
observer, apparently to reassure the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are the Serbs' biggest ally, and it was a Russian
envoy, Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, who helped broker the deal Milosevic
agreed to last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian news agency Itar-Tass said the main snag concerned
the entry of peacekeepers into Kosovo. The agency said NATO had
been insisting Serbs begin withdrawing within 24 hours, at which
time NATO forces from Macedonia would begin entering Kosovo. The
agency said Russia was arguing that a peacekeeping operation could
not begin until the United Nations Security Council approved it.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has insisted all along that the Kosovo crisis should be
handled by the United Nations, not NATO. As part of the peace plan,
the foreign ministers from the seven leading industrial nations and
Russia are to begin drafting a UN Security Council resolution
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution also is expected to set out a command structure
for the peacekeepers. Russia has agreed to contribute troops for
Kosovo, but insists they will not be under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has ruled out a separate command for any Russian force,
which may number up to 10,000 men.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very difficult step toward peace has been taken, but many
issues are still being resolved purely on NATO's terms,'' Russian
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier sign that the peace plan was in serious jeopardy,
the chief architect of the deal, Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari, postponed a visit to Beijing to discuss it with Chinese
leaders. China, like Russia, is a permanent member of the UN
Security Council and can veto any resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, NATO flew just about 400 sorties, less than the 600 to
700 they had been averaging for the previous two weeks, and most of
them focused in Kosovo, giving the Yugoslav capital a fourth
consecutive day without bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said Serb forces were
looting areas in Pristina and in the town of Prizren, to the west.
He said that if looters are spotted during a Serb withdrawal ``they
will be subject to NATO air operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO's refusal to call off its airstrikes until it
could verify a Serb withdrawal was being vindicated by the Serb
stalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't come this far to stumble at the final hurdle,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the talks collapsing, the fighting on the border of Kosovo
and Albania showed no sign of abating. Russian NTV television
showed footage of Serb artillery blasting at villages in the
mountainous border area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 100 heavy shells hit our village Monday,'' one man
identified as a Kosovar Albanian told the station.
</P>
<P>
   In Oslo, the Kosovo Liberation Army's political leader expressed
skepticism that Belgrade would implement the peace plan. The
leader, Hashim Thaci, also asserted that Serb forces had begun
using poison gas against civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting between Serbian forces'' and the KLA ``continues with
the same intensity as before,'' Thaci said at a news conference.
``The only difference between Sunday and Monday is that they used a
gas that has hurt civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Sunday on Fox TV, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
said that if Milosevic ``does not comply with what he has agreed .
. . NATO will be prepared to continue the military action.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solana also expressed optimism that the plan would be
implemented and hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanians who have
fled the violence would return home ``by winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Cullen of the Globe staff contributed from Belgrade,
Filipov from Moscow, and Pitzer from Kumanovo. Material from
Reuters and the Associated Press also was used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
