<HEADLINE>
BRAVES THROW SINKER AT RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BRAVES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After 19 days in first place, the Red Sox left the
country Sunday afternoon not knowing whether they'd still be there
after clearing customs in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Their grip on the top spot in the American League East was
loosened by the Atlanta Braves, who have spent the better part of
the decade flaunting their superiority and did so again with a 3-2,
10-inning win in the rubber match of their three-game set before a
sellout crowd of 32,184 at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, who have been inhaling Sox dust since
losing two of three on Yawkey Way in mid-May, had a chance
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night to leapfrog the Sox back into first by a half-game.
But the Mets pounded Roger Clemens for seven runs in 2 2/3 innings,
ending his streak of 20 straight wins, in a 7-2 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Braves catcher Javy Lopez, who already ruined one story line
this weekend when he broke Tom Gordon's save streak Saturday,
Sunday spoiled what could have become the Parable of the Prodigal
Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, whose ninth-inning, two-out, two-run double down the
third-base line beat Gordon, Sunday delivered a two-out RBI single
to center in the 10th that pinned the loss on Mark Portugal, who
went from starter to full-time father to reborn reliever in six
tumultuous days.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, pitching for the first time since walking out on the
club a week ago, made his first relief appearance in almost three
years and was in his third inning of work when Walt Weiss opened
the 10th with a single just under the glove of second baseman Jose
Offerman. Bret Boone bunted pinch runner Otis Nixon to second, and
Portugal was lifted for Jim Corsi after issuing an intentional walk
to Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Corsi retired Brian Jordan on a fly to left, but Lopez, after
fouling off a couple of two-strike pitches, lined a 2-2 pitch to
center to bring home Nixon with the deciding run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit it where we weren't,'' Corsi said. ``I threw a lot of
good pitches, but what are you going to do? He hit a slider off the
end of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, overmatched by Pedro Martinez in the series opener,
shied away from declaring that their two subsequent late-inning,
one-run wins over the Sox made them overqualified to occupy the
same field as their ex-cousins. Instead, the Braves' clubhouse was
full of opinions that the Sox were worthy of being in the same
high-rent district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what they're trying to do here, which is pitch
well and catch the ball, is going to afford them the opportunity to
win a lot of ballgames,'' said Tom Glavine, the Braves' pitcher of
impeccable pedigree (two Cy Young Awards) and the proper birthright
(Billerica) to offer his take on the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can continue to get clutch hitting like they've gotten
to put them in first place, then they'll stay there. But if not, I
don't see them going away in terms of contending for a playoff
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood, the unheralded part of the pitching troika that
Atlanta threw at the Sox this weekend (Glavine and Greg Maddux, who
have six Cy Youngs between them, worked the first two games), held
the Sox without a hit until John Valentin led off the seventh by
lining a first-pitch single to left.
</P>
<P>
   Two outs later, Troy O'Leary took advantage of some indecision
by Millwood, who twice shook off Lopez, to hit a home run just to
the right of the 420-foot sign in the triangle, tying the score at
2-2.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary had the last of the Sox' three hits on the afternoon, a
two-out single in the ninth off Braves reliever Rudy Seanez.
Atlanta closer John Rocker, whose sprint from the bullpen would be
clocked somewhere between Carl Lewis and Wendell Kim, struck out
the side in the 10th for his 12th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games could have gone either way _ they came down right
to the wire these last two days,'' said Sox reliever Rheal Cormier,
who replaced starter Pat Rapp in the seventh, when the Braves
scored their second run on two hit batsmen, an intentional walk, a
throwing error by Offerman, and a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pitched well, we pitched well,'' Cormier said. ``They're
a good team. They're not in first place for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who finished this brief homestand 3-3, taking two out
of three from the Tigers and dropping two of three to the Braves,
play three against the Expos in Montreal, and three in Shea Stadium
against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over with now,'' said Portugal, who was speaking of his
own week of flip-flops between spending more time with his kids vs.
staying on board with the Sox. ``Time to get on a bird and go to
Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still with a half-game lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
