<HEADER>
A5970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN-     06-07 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTUGAL FINDS RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nice week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mark Portugal popped his shoulder out of its socket,
gave up six runs in three innings, then cleaned out his locker and
stormed out of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday he told teammates he was retiring. Wednesday he stayed
home for his first day of retirement after 18 1/2 years in pro
ball, but he hedged on Thursday when he showed up at Pawtucket for
the Sox exhibition game against their Triple A affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Friday he came out of retirement and out of the starting
rotation. Sunday he was back on the mound, picking up a loss in 2
1/3 innings of pretty good relief against the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   As comebacks go, this was something short of Nixon in '68, Elvis
in '69, or Jordan in '95, but Portugal was glad to be back pitching
after his tumultuous week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just good to get back on the field,'' said the
36-year-old righthander. ``When the phone rang in the bullpen I
didn't expect to get the call and I was a little nervous. So it was
just good to go out and feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans treated him well. He was applauded when he warmed
up in the pen, when he came in to pitch, and even when he was
pulled in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nice,'' he said. ``This has always been a good baseball
city and it's nice to know they can sympathize with some of the
things I've been going through.''
</P>
<P>
   His manager and teammates never revealed his situation, but
Portugal was not embarrassed to admit that he wanted to quit so he
could spend more time with his three children, who live with his
ex-wife. All ballplayers miss a lot of family moments during the
season. Divorced ballplayers can become strangers to their kids.
</P>
<P>
   How could fans be anything but sympathetic? This wasn't Oil Can
Boyd quitting because he didn't make the All-Star team. It wasn't
Bill Lee pouting because the Sox traded one of his friends. It
wasn't Gene Conley drinking 19 beers and buying a ticket to
Jerusalem. Portugal is a divorced dad, who was (at least
temporarily) willing to torch a big salary and a possible
postseason ticket, just to spend more time with his kids. In the
eyes of most fans, this made him something more than just another
journeyman righty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is more important than a ballclub,'' he said again
Sunday. ``I've got three children relying on me for a number of
things. Money isn't everything. I've played this game a long time
and made a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a decision that reflected on myself in an angry,
depressed mood. But we've got a first-place team and I want to be
part of that. For 18 1/2 years, this is an opportunity I've played
for.''
</P>
<P>
   He has pitched in Elizabethton, Wisconsin Rapids, Visalia,
Orlando, Torledo, Portland, Tucson, Minnesota, Houston, San
Francisco, Cincinnati, Philadelphia, and Boston. In all those
places, in all those years, he has pitched exactly one inning of
major league postseason ball _ giving up four runs in one inning
against the Braves when he was with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's got a chance to pitch in big games again, but only if
the Sox make the playoffs and only if he stays healthy and
unretired.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's kids were at the game Sunday. He waved to them as he
came off the mound after getting the Braves out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It was good to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of days I've been apprehensive coming to
the park,'' he said. ``And if I wouldn't have pitched today, I
think when we came back from this trip it would have been a little
difficult. But it's nice that the people that support the Red Sox
backed me. From the sound of it, the fans in the stands
understood.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal surrendered a single to Walt Weiss to start the 10th
and picked up his 87th career loss when Weiss came around to score
on a Javy Lopez single off Jim Corsi. Then he showered, packed, and
flew to Montreal while his kids went home to Providence.
</P>
<P>
   It is the life of a big league ballplayer and it is a darned
good life, but it is not a life without sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   For Portugal, the good news is that Father's Day is June 20 and
the Red Sox will be playing against the Texas Rangers . . . at
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
