<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDELIBLE WIN FOR INKSTER 
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN'S OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ To the very end, Juli Inkster stayed on the
attack. If the US Women's Open was ``my tournament to win,'' she
was going to keep a firm hold and not let up, not even with a
five-shot lead on the 72d hole.
</P>
<P>
   So from 163 yards, Inkster rifled her approach shot over water
she probably didn't even see, over a bunker that was not part of
the equation, dead on target at a flag that was not supposed to be
attacked. After nearly knocking down the pin, Inkster took two
putts to complete her smashing knockout of the field in the 54th
renewal of this championship at Old Waverly Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a champion,'' Inkster said to herself as she stood over
that shot in the fairway at 18, and indeed she proved that with a
couple of exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   Her closing round of 1-under 71 completed a record 16-under 272,
beating the previous best by six shots. Unheralded LPGA Tour
veteran Sherri Turner finished second (71_277) and rising star
Kelli Kuehne (74_279) fell to third with a double bogey at the
18th, but there was only one serious threat to Inkster.
</P>
<P>
   Herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't win,'' said Inkster, who earned $315,000, ``I
would have no one to blame but myself. I didn't sleep very good
(Saturday night), but I just told myself, `I've got to have the
heart to win this thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Heart? No question, and with a polished game it has made her one
of the most respected players in women's golf. It's her third win
of the year and her fourth in eight months. It also goes a long way
in erasing bitter memories of 1992 when she squandered a 54-hole
lead and lost a US Women's Open playoff to Patty Sheehan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devastated for a long time (after 1992),'' said Inkster,
38 and three times a major winner, but never before in this
prestigious tournament. ``But to come back and win today, no one
can take that away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   There really wasn't much chance of taking it away from her,
either, not unless she planned to let go, which she had no
intention of doing. Indeed, Inkster had an answer for everything
her playing partner did on the front side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelli was just zinging it to the hole, playing great,'' said
Inkster, who merely zinged it herself. When Kuehne, who started the
day 11-under, four shots behind, made a birdie from 12 feet on the
par-5 second, Inkster made hers from 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a few too many shots back,'' said Kuehne, at 22 showing
the promise that was predicted of her after US Amateur triumphs in
1995 and '96. ``I was not supposed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kuehne was pointing to fate, she may have a point, because
after her birdie at No. 2, she finished off the front with seven
strong pars, many of them after birdie attempts burned the cup. She
got closer when Inkster bogeyed the par-4 fifth, just her second of
the tournament and her first in 37 holes, but that would be it.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster birdied the par-4 sixth, then made the shot of the
tournament on the par-3 seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``An all-world bunker shot,'' said Inkster. Her tee shot had
come to rest under soft sand and the devilish lip of a steep
bunker. A fried egg, they call it. A tournament-saver, is what it
was. With bogey or even a double staring her in the face, and
Kuehne lining up a very makeable 15-footer, Inkster remembered
something Meg Mallon had told her. ``Just take a big swing and kind
of quit on it and keep that club face open.''
</P>
<P>
   From a fried egg to a piece of cotton, the ball came out and hit
softly, rolling within inches of the hole. Inkster had her par and
when Kuehne missed another birdie attempt, the lead was still four.
Even when, at the eighth, Inkster hiccuped and missed a putt inside
of 2 feet (``My only bad putt of the week'') for her third and
final bogey of the tournament, the Open had been closed by one of
the game's best front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``With how tough the course played today, with the wind and the
greens being harder, there was no way someone was going to shoot
8-under,'' said Inkster, referring to the rounds Kuehne, Lorie
Kane, and Becky Iverson had posted earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   She was right, too. There were just 10 sub-par rounds fired, but
nothing lower than 67. Turner, five back at the start, caused a
stir when she holed out a 7-wood at the par-4 11th for eagle, but
even with that drama she was still four back.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne bogeyed the par-5 10th, Turner followed her eagle with
back-to-back bogeys, and Inkster converted her 19th and final
birdie of the tournament at the 13th hole to reach the
never-before-seen score of 16-under at a US Open.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mallon (72_281) nor Dottie Pepper (76_285) threatened,
though they both threatened to squeeze the life out of Inkster when
it was all over. Mallon and Pepper stayed by the scoring trailer
off the 18th hole and waited for their friend to finish her victory
waltz over this course in the deep south. When she did, the tears
flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the pain she's been through,'' said Mallon, the Open
winner in 1991. She was referring to 1992. ``She's riding a great
high. It was meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, those were Juli Inkster's sentiments exactly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
