<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IS GRAND FOR AGASSI 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Gil Reyes, a great boulder of a man who looks as if he
could lift Stade Roland Garros and the 16,000 tennis aficionados
within, as a sort of Atlasian trick, was talking about his pupil,
Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him grow more this year than ever before. He can
live with disappointment _ but not regret. That's very good. The
best is when your dreams come together with destiny. That day is
today for Andre.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, at the close of an afternoon strewn with rocks and
pitfalls, enlivened by growls of thunder and downpours while a
menacing bear named Medvedev barred the path, Reyes was proven a
prophet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was destiny,'' softly said Agassi, newly crowned
Sunday as King Andre III of France.
</P>
<P>
   When it ended with his unanswerable serve on a fourth match
point, the rehabilitated Agassi _ back from the limbo of a No. 140
world ranking 21 months ago _ had performed an Atlas stunt himself,
lifting the full house to a frenzy of joy and cheering. Their
favorite had come through after all in a resurrective 1-6, 2-6,
6-4, 6-3, 6-4 triumph over Ukrainian Andrei Medvedev that seemed a
crawl up the Hillary Step without oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but he had expanded a very exclusive club. Fred
Perry, Don Budge, Rod Laver, and Roy Emerson were the only men to
win all four majors, Emerson the most recent entrant 35 years ago.
Nearly blackballed with yellow balls by the Ukrainian, Agassi was
``most welcome,'' said the Grand Slammer of 1938, Budge, over the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Having won Wimbledon in 1992, the US Open in 1994, and Australia
in 1995, Agassi had struck the last, seemingly lost chord, and
renamed the club the Quintessential Quintet.
</P>
<P>
   But before Agassi and destiny had their day, Reyes, longtime
friend and trainer, who pounded Agassi into a frame of fitness that
he'd never fit before, looked like a lousy prognosticator. Agassi
was playing tennis he would always regret, and his dreams were the
kind of hallucinations that make psychiatrists rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very scary out there,'' said Agassi, shaking his
bearded, bald head. ``I couldn't move my legs, couldn't breathe. It
was nerves. Absolutely. I was embarrassed. In shock. It was gonna
be a blowout, and Andrei was playing very well. I had flashbacks of
losing the finals in 1990 and 1991, and the feeling I've long held
that I'd never get another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As Agassi overhit and underhit, punished the net, and lost track
of the court, the first set went in 19 minutes. The second was
decided in about the same time, and he would face a break point
tantamount to match point at 4-4 in the third. Call 911.
</P>
<P>
   Instead destiny may have been calling _ just before Agassi went
altogether catatonic. The jingle was felt on his brow. A raindrop.
Then many more descended from the sky, enough to drive them indoors
to the dressing room for a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so glad it rained,'' said Agassi, who was leading, 1-0,
in the second. ``I was confused. (Coach) Brad Gilbert was there to
give me perspective, reassure me that shot-for-shot I was better. I
just had to get my feet going, get moving, and execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain hadn't been his ally in the 1991 finale, a five-set loss to
Jim Courier. Agassi led, 6-3, 3-1, at the first interruption.
Courier adjusted in the dressing room as Agassi did this time.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the second set went awry for him, much as the first,
``at least I knew what was wrong,'' said Agassi. ``I started to
loosen up and execute my shots, and it would pay off later.'' He
cut his mistakes drastically: 26 errors for the first two sets, but
only 25 more for the next three.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi began to make the other Andrei play longer points, and
the ursine 6-foot-4-inch Medvedev (whose name means bear at home)
started missing his grizzly forehand. Still, Medvedev, a citizen of
Kiev, remained deceptively dangerous, sizeable but quick, and kept
blackjacking his way out of trouble spots with a serve that sizzled
for 23 aces and 29 winners.
</P>
<P>
   The new champion's lonely journey of nearly three hours from
disaster to _ well, destiny? _ didn't begin to look hopeful until
the 70-minute mark when he saw his first break points, and took
Medvedev's serve to 2-4 only to lose his own to 4-3, and fall into
that awful break point hole at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to try something different,'' said Agassi, who flung
himself at the net for a game-saving volley, and angled a tough
volley to break serve in the next game, earning the third set.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're OK now,'' croaked a suffering Gilbert, who'd been dining
on his own nails. A more appropriate dish would have been Crow Kiev
for those of us who believed Agassi would crush No. 100 Medvedev.
At least until 2:25 had been played and Agassi forged ahead for the
first time _ and for good _ with sparkling retrieves that cost
Medvedev his serve to 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   By then sunshine and blue sky had taken over along with Agassi,
but it would take a ferocious battering of his finest groundies to
dent and finally tip over Medvedev.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look happy. I look sad,'' said Medvedev, ``because I
wanted to win this badly. But inside I'm smiling because this was
the best day of my life.'' He was back with his lady love, Anke
Huber, after a long separation, and had gone farther than
imaginable for the longest-shot finalist in tourney history. He
again looked like the 18-year-old who'd been a semifinalist and
rose to No. 4 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But Agassi looks as never before, taking his ranking up 10
notches to No. 4, and is a fiery factor again after seeming burned
out. ``I believe there's more success left in my game, and that if
I can do it here I can do it in a few other places, a few other
cities,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
