<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-CHARISMATIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC GETS ROYAL TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ The morning after was still but brilliant. The
atmosphere from the day before, madcap and electric, had been
replaced by a racetrack's usual morning atmosphere of quiet and
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic was there in stall 17 of Barn 10 at Belmont Park.
Standing. In a few hours more, he was to be vanned down the hill to
the clinic on the backstretch, where three screws would be inserted
into the cannon bone of his left foreleg. His cracked sesamoid
bones were too fragile for any screws; they would heal nature's
way.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Selway performed a successful 2 1/2-hour surgery on
Charismatic Sunday. He said the injury ``was not the worst of this
kind I've ever seen, but it was a nasty one. He'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the barn, from time to time, a stablehand of trainer D.
Wayne Lukas would stop by and pat Charismatic on the head. Gentle
pats, loving pats. ``The barn is pretty shook up,'' said Lukas.
``My job now is keep their spirits up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas's wife, the former Laura Pinelli, is a trainer herself,
``and she deals with this all the time,'' said Lukas, ``but she
doesn't handle this part very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Few could. Even the souls whose sensitivities have been chilled
by a lifetime at a racetrack _ where winning, no matter how huge
the win, always is followed by losing, where throroughbreds are
always one step away from tragedy _ had their hearts melt when
Charismatic broke down at the wire of Saturday's 131st Belmont
Stakes and jockey Chris Antley jumped off one-16th of a mile past
the finish and tenderly took Charismatic's left leg in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real, pure animal lovers have a lot of trouble with (this
aspect of racing),'' said Lukas about the reality that horses get
hurt or occasionally die while running. On the other hand, said
Lukas, never since one thoroughbred began racing another has so
much veterinary aid been available.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas said Charismatic had shown no sign of soreness, even with
his of five races in a little more than two months. ``This horse
never had an ice boot in his life,'' said Lukas, listing various
remedies for ailing equine joints and bones, ``and never had an
electrolyte jug after a race, which is standard. He never even had
a cold water bandage.'' So there was no sign.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont grandstand and clubhouse were empty. The day before,
some 85,818 fans had swarmed to the track, the largest crowd ever
at Belmont, either to see a Belmont Stakes or any race, either to
see Secretariat, Ruffian, Affirmed, Forego, or Kelso.
</P>
<P>
   They were there to see a Triple Crown, perhaps, there to see
Charismatic jump from an unwanted claiming horse to greatness. Or
maybe they were there to see Silverbulletday, the filly, take on
the boys. In any case, they were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't always play out the Hollywood scripts like we'd
want,'' said Lukas. ``Life isn't that way. We can't play it all out
and just have it fall into place. That isn't reality. But we
already played out two great scripts (in the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness, which Charismatic won).''
</P>
<P>
   Cesor Arredondo, a groom in the Lukas stable, had tended to the
horse and also tended to the human broken hearts. He had talked to
Joanne McNamara, Charismatic's exercise rider, ``and she was down
but I just wouldn't let her mope,'' said the groom.
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, several horse vans were lined up to transport
several of the Belmont runners to Kennedy Airport and back to
Louisville, Ky., their home base. Charismatic had a ticket on that
flight but the colt was remaining there in stall 17 of Barn 10,
waiting for the surgery to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas talked about the injury and the surgery. The cannon bone
is between the knee and the ankle and an injury merely to the
cannon bone would not be totally devastating. Indeed, said Lukas,
he had a horse running in Sunday's seventh race at Belmont, Quaker
Ridge, who'd had screws inserted to repair a virtually identical
fracture.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, if it wasn't for the (fractured) sesamoid,''
said Lukas, ``horses come right off the operating table and they'll
stand, almost sound. But the sesamoid they won't touch. The
sesamoid is in the back of the ankle; but the sesamoid is a bone
where if you put a screw in it, it's like bad wood and it'll
probably crack where you put the screw in. You can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic's racing career, said Lukas, ``definitely is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shock of the Belmont finish, Lukas had been most
cooperative with the media later Saturday evening, even displaying
the X-ray of Charismatic's injury and answering all questions. And
Sunday, Lukas was not distraught, concerned more with boosting the
spirits of his help.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the end, Lukas had even more respect for the Triple
Crown and how injuries, illness, and fate can step in any time, no
matter how talented the horse seeking racing's most elusive
accomplishment. Truly, only the great thoroughbred can take on all
comers three times in five weeks and vanquish all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you run in the Triple Crown races, you gain more
respect for those few who have won it,'' said Lukas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
