<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HONE GAME FOR HOME WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Walter Zenga is a pragmatist. And Zenga was
appalled, even offended, when the Revolution were humiliated by Los
Angeles at Foxboro Stadium last August, on a day when he was being
honored at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Zenga was offered the job as the Revolution's coach
after that game, he basically pledged that his team would not be
embarrassed at home before supportive audiences. That goal seems to
have been achieved. But until the Revolution took a 2-0 victory
over Chicago Saturday night they had not displayed an ability to
actually win at home.
</P>
<P>
   The Zenga defensive mindset appears to be having a positive
effect. This was the fourth Revolution shutout of the season, the
first step in limiting blowout defeats. Though the team has but 11
points in 11 matches, only 1 point ahead of last year's pace, the
shutout total is double what the Revolution had by August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in four seasons, the Revolution are forming a
credible identity. Defensive soccer might not have a glamorous
reputation, but it is a practical concept that provides a
foundation on which to build an attack. Even with everyone
supposedly thinking defense, the Revolution surrendered several
chances that mostly were squandered by Chicago striker Ante Razov.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution started the game without two of their best
defenders, Mike Burns and Richard Goulooze. The solution was to
switch to a 3-5-2 formation with Edwin Gorter at sweeper for most
of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter has had a mostly unrewarding experience since being
brought to the Revolution by former coach Thomas Rongen as the
team's midfield leader last year. Gorter, 35, has not consistently
been in position to display his exquisite technical skills and
lethal long-range shooting ability.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the sweeper position provide the stage to which Gorter
is accustomed. But, like many of his teammates, Gorter might have
to sacrifice some glory for the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy that I am not here on a paid vacation anymore,''
Gorter said. ``I don't think I played badly but I know I can play
much better. But it was nice to be out there. It doesn't matter to
me what position I play. I played sweeper for about eight games
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The other major Revolution change has been the addition of John
Harkes, who has started the last three games after recovering from
a sprained right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, the Revolution are evolving into a competent,
consistent team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a happy, healthier group and we are all fighting
together as a team,'' Gorter said. ``We have chemistry, and that is
the important thing. I really believe we are on the right road now
and the time to confirm it is going to be against Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will meet Miami next Sunday. In a warmup game,
they will meet CD Santa Clara, the first Azorean team to be
promoted to Portugal's Primeira Division, in an exhibition at 7:30
p.m. Thursday. Santa Clara will hold a press conference at 12:30
p.m. Wednesday at Academica in Fall River and play an exhibition
against the Santa Clara veteran team at 7:30 p.m. Wednesday at
Bishop Connolly High School . . . The Revolution failed to hold the
lead against opponents from May 1 through May 29, but have trailed
for only 14 minutes of their last two games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
