<SLUG> BC-HKM-PROVIDENCE-ROCHESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDENCE PILES IT ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Two more wins and the Bruins capture the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Easy now. Before you rush down to Government Center and camp out
at City Hall for the parade, understand that we're talking the
Providence Bruins and the Calder Cup. All went quiet on Causeway
Street a few weeks back. For now, this is the Hub of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Paced by Cameron Mann's four points, including a hat trick, the
Baby B's rolled to an easy 6-0 win over the Rochester Americans
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night before a crowd of 8,269 at the Civic Center to take a
commanding 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven Calder finals _ the
American Hockey League championship.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Mann, the 99th pick overall in the '95 draft,
scored the first, fourth, and sixth Bruins goals and assisted on
the second, scored by Antti Laaksonen. Steven King, who scored
twice in the 4-2 Game 1 win Saturday night, also scored for
Providence, along with Landon Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely learned a lot, being up there,'' said Mann,
referring to his 33-game stint in Boston this season, when he at
one point looked as if he might figure prominently in Boston's
offensive plans. ``But I've learned a lot here, too, and it's given
me some confidence in my game.''
</P>
<P>
   John Grahame, now 9-0 at the Civic Center in the postseason,
turned back 27 shots for his first shutout in postseason play. In
the other net, Rochester star Martin Biron was chased midway
through the first period, the Bruins connecting for three goals on
their first four shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for John,'' said Providence coach Peter Laviolette,
whose club will meet the Amerks again Wednesday night in Rochester,
followed by Game 4 there Friday. ``Martin Biron has gotten a lot of
the spotlight in the AHL this year. It's terrific to see John
Grahame step up to the plate and show what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Grahame possibly could make the jump to Boston next season, if
Robbie Tallas, left unprotected in the expansion draft later this
month, is claimed by Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mann now has six goals in eight postseason games this year . . .
Four of Providence's strikes came on the power play, two of those
by Mann . . . Boston president/GM Harry Sinden was in attendance .
. . Wilson now has six goals in eight postseason games and five of
those have come on the power play . . . If the Bruins win the next
two, it will be the first Calder Cup championship to come to
Providence since 1956 . . . The Bruins were without their leading
playoff scorer, Eric Nickulas (8-11_19), who received a game
misconduct in Game 1 for his heavy check on defenseman Alexandre
Boikov. Nickulas was tagged with a five-minute boarding penalty and
the game misconduct, making him ineligible for Game 2. He is
expected to play in Game 3 . . . Boikov, who had to be helped off
the ice after needing some five minutes to shake the cobwebs, did
not suit up Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ron and Charlotte Grahame were in attendance, watching their son
tend net. Ron is the former Boston netminder the Bruins traded to
Los Angeles for the Kings' first pick in the '79 draft _ the No. 8
choice the Bruins used to select Ray Bourque. Charlotte Grahame
works in the Colorado Avalanche front office as secretary to Pierre
Lacroix, the club's general manager . . . The last time the Boston
Bruins won back-to-back games in a final playoff round: April 30
and May 2, 1972, on way to dumping the Rangers for what remains
Boston's last Stanley Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
