<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAMBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVVED UP CAMBY SETTING PACE FOR KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Larry Johnson always will be the maker of The Shot.
That won't change. But another Larry, the coach of the Indiana
Pacers, believes one of Johnson's teammates made the wild ending
all possible _ Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than a month, the former University of
Massachusetts front-liner has gone from being the Knicks' version
of Stan Papi to an indispensable, irreplaceable part in a machine
that won't quit. After the Knicks' win Saturday night, Larry Bird
didn't hesitate when asked about Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus was the best player out there,'' the Indiana coach said
matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   He was good. He had 21 points, 11 rebounds, and 2 blocks. He
made two gigantic free throws in the final minute _ and he's not
exactly Mark Price at the line. He was in the middle of everything.
He caused Bill Walton to gush, ``Toronto traded this guy?''
</P>
<P>
   No one was seen carrying `We Want Oakley' signs in the din of
Madison Square Garden after Johnson's improbable 4-point play with
5.7 seconds remaining gave New York a 92-91 victory and a 2-1 lead
over Indiana in the Eastern Conference Finals. Game 4 is Monday
night in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bird also fingered Camby for what he felt was the game's pivotal
play. Indiana was nursing an 89-84 lead without much luck and
Johnson flung up a trey that didn't have the same luck as some of
his other prayers in the game. As the ball was coming down, three
Pacers watched it as if looking at some astronomical phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Out of nowhere, Camby swooped in among them, got a hand on the
ball, and got it back for the Knicks, who promptly called timeout.
The Knicks eventually scored on the possession, cutting the deficit
to 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody went after him,'' Bird sneered in disgust. Moments
later, Bird offered another salute to Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scored points and got a lot of rebounds and kept the ball
alive,'' Bird said. ``He had a phenomenal game. That's something we
need from some of our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this the same Marcus Camby widely derided as too soft and too
lazy? The same one who, not by his own choice, came to New York in
a deal for the popular Charles Oakley and then withered on the
bench for much of the season?
</P>
<P>
   Yup, it's one and the same. Camby and Latrell Sprewell have
become the poster boys for the Knicks' astonishing run. They bring
to the table exactly what ousted general manager Ernie Grunfeld
hoped they'd bring: athleticism, quickness, energy, and, of course,
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted all year long was to get in the game and prove
myself,'' said Camby, who's averaging 10.7 points and 9.3 rebounds
against Indiana. ``I never lost my confidence in the game while
waiting for the opportunity to come and to make the best of the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 15 games of the season, when coach Jeff Van Gundy
finally woke up and gave him the opportunity, Camby averaged 10.3
points, 5.8 rebounds, and 1.7 blocks in 25 minutes. He shot 58
percent from the field. He was huge in what many Knicks watchers
consider to be the biggest game of the regular season, a big
comeback win at Miami April 23. The next night, he blocked seven
shots in a huge win at Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   He was everywhere in Game 3, a performance he said was the best
game he had played as a Knick. (Frankly, there wasn't much
competition. His season high was 22 points in a meaningless season
finale against Miami.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I had other games in my career, but definitely, this was
probably my best game in a while, especially for a game so
important,'' he said. ``But it's not over. I want to go out there
and win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   He's going to be getting more chances as this series progresses.
Van Gundy, who was reluctant to embrace Camby for a number of
reasons, started him in the second half. It was both a signal that
Camby deserved to be out there as well as a necessity; the Pacers
were using Chris Mullin to guard Chris Dudley and were getting away
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Camby starts Monday night is incidental. The Knicks need
his energy every time he's on the floor. Undoubtedly Bird will
challenge the Davis boys to start getting physical with Camby, who
isn't known as a banger. But they also will have to deal with his
quickness and his size, a combination that made him so appealing in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he's here. New Yorkers are only beginning to see what
many _ including Camby _ believe has been there all along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
