<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-BRAVES-MILLWOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLWOOD SHAKES OFF LOST OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Kevin Millwood didn't pitch a perfect game, a
no-hitter, or a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   And despite allowing just two runs and two hits in eight
innings, the Braves starter didn't even get a win Sunday at Fenway
Park.
</P>
<P>
   But Millwood, according to Atlanta pitching coach Leo Mazzone,
did what he does best against the Red Sox, who succumbed in 10
innings, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Kevin always seems to do, no matter what the score, when
he comes out of the ballgame, we're in it,'' said Mazzone. ``In the
last year and a half that he's pitched here, he'll give up some
runs here and there, but he's always pitching according to the
scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, who threw only 96 pitches, left the game tied at 2-2
after inducing John Valentin _ who had ended his no-hit bid an
inning earlier with a single to left _ to pop out with two runners
on in the Red Sox eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's basically a fastball pitcher and he throws a very heavy
ball,'' said Mazzone. ``When you play catch with him, it's like
catching a cement block. I think he's learned a lot from Glavine,
Smoltz and Maddux. He's watched how they go about their business
and he's taken advantage of that, how they approach the game and
get people out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really improved his thought process on situational
pitches and location. He's a learner. He's not intimidated. He's a
country boy from North Carolina who wants to play a little
hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Millwood, who once went 8 2/3 innings for the Braves' Triple
A farm team in Richmond before losing a no-hitter, relied on his
fastball one too many times when he gave up a game-tying, two-run,
422-foot shot to Troy O'Leary in the seventh, prompting manager
Bobby Cox to remark with a grin, ``At least it wasn't a cheapie.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves catcher Javy Lopez, who had the winning hit against the
Red Sox on successive days, wasn't quite as flippant. ``One
mistake,'' lamented Lopez, who was shaken off by Millwood before
the home run pitch ``cost him the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he became quite human in the seventh, Millwood, whose
perfect game ended with a fifth-inning walk to O'Leary, thought he
had a good chance to pitch his first no-hitter at any pro level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had a real shot at it,'' he said. ``If I just go
out there and make my pitches, there's a good chance it'll happen.
That's the longest I've been with a no-hitter, but I'd have been
happy with one hit and no runs _ and that didn't happen either.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood said he has two breaking balls, ``and if I could have
gotten one of them over, I could have gotten the win.''
</P>
<P>
   But with his heavy fastball working and his curveball not very
sharp, Millwood shook off Lopez, stepped off the rubber, and
reloaded with his favorite pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to throw a fastball in and (Lopez) wouldn't call
it,'' said Millwood. ``It's my responsibility to throw what I want
to throw and if something bad happens, then it falls on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, O'Leary deposited the ball to the right of the
center-field triangle, and what fell on Millwood's shoulders after
that was keeping Atlanta from losing the game and the series to the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I whine and pout about the home run, then I'm not going to
do myself or my team any good,'' he said. ``I wanted to throw the
fastball inside even if it wasn't a strike. I just got it out over
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood responded to adversity by shutting down the Red Sox in
the eighth, escaping from that little jam by getting his revenge
against Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit a couple of line drives earlier and when they go
right at people (right field and second base), you start thinking,
hey, he's got a shot at this thing here,'' said Mazzone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to throw a no-hitter, then I thought he
was going to throw a shutout because his pitch count was way down,
but unfortunately he pitched a great game and didn't get either
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
