u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-BOS &LR;      06-07 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WIN AND A SAVE FOR WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ Just when it appeared Tiger Woods might surrender
the lead in Sunday's final round of the 24th Memorial at Muirfield
GC, after a potentially destructive shot out of the rough on the
14th hole never made it to the green, he holed his next shot out of
the wiry rough to save par and maintain the lead he'd held for the
better part of three days.
</P>
<P>
   Playing alongside PGA champion Vijay Singh, Woods saved par out
of a back trap on the 16th, and when Singh failed to make a birdie
putt on the 17th, it was a gentle walk to the clubhouse. Woods, who
nearly missed the cut in this tournament two years ago when he was
the game's main story, put it away.
</P>
<P>
   The final numbers were 15-under-par 273 (68-66-70-69) and gave
Woods a two-shot victory over Singh, who took a bogey on the 72d
hole and finished 69_275. Following Woods's similar run to victory
over a strong international field in the DeutscheBank Open two
weeks ago in Heidelburg, Germany, it serves as a suitable entree to
the 99th US Open in two weeks in Pinehurst, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   There were no other contenders in the tournament created by Jack
Nicklaus in the booming suburbs of his hometown of Columbus until
world No. 1 David Duval shot himself into it with an eagle on the
seventh. But Duval could not get closer and finished 70_279 to end
up in a tie for third with Olin Browne, who had the day's best
round (65), and Paraguay's Carlos Franco, who birdied the 17th to
set up a 68.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who is just 23, claimed his ninth victory on the PGA Tour
and joined Duval as the only multiple winners this year. Woods also
has four seconds, five thirds, and 35 Top 10s since turning
professional Aug. 26, 1996. Only Horton Smith had won more
tournaments at that age. As Nicklaus noted, ``He has the ability to
do things nobody else can do.'' It isn't just the length of his
shots, it's course management and short game finesse.
</P>
<P>
   There also was some restructuring of his game with teaching guru
Butch Harmon. ``I'm making these changes,'' he said, ``and it's
just a matter of being patient with them. People were saying, `Oh,
geez, you're not winning.' The changes I was making in my game were
going to be beneficial down the long haul. I just had to be
patient. I'm starting to understand how to play the game a little
bit better than I had before.''
</P>
<P>
   This virtually became match play on the second nine. Singh
surged into the picture with birdies on the 11th (2 iron, 15 feet,
two putts) and 12th (8 iron, 5 feet), but Woods responded by
draining a 15-footer on the 12th. After flubbing his first shot out
of the rough on the 14th, Woods made the shot of the tournament and
saw it go in the hole. After that, he got up and down out of a sand
trap on the 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, who won the PGA Championship at Sahalee in Redmond,
Wash., last August and said major titles are on his mind, saw his
chances diminish when he went into a bunker on the 14th, just found
the fringe on his second shot, and watched his chip end up 6 feet
from the pin. He missed his saving putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved the challenge of chipping and putting or
scrambling,'' said Woods. The 14th? ``After I flubbed the first
one,'' he said, ``the second one was sitting perfect. It was
sitting up, and it was a shot I knew I could spin it and it would
stop. The only problem was it so fast right-to-left and down the
slope. I thought, `Hmm, that has potential.' It went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Woods, who did a serious dance around the green and was
still in front by two, played it out with a matching birdie on the
15th, two pars, and a bogey out of a bunker on the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   The last words should be left to Nicklaus, who will be the
honoree at next year's 25th Memorial in the millennium year and the
year of his 60th birthday. ``Most players at 23 don't have the
imagination he does,'' said the host. ``As far as he hits it,
there's no reason to practice his short game. But he has, and
that's why he's winning and why he's there all the time. He's a
full package.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
