<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
b x &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BYline &LR;      06-07 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BYline 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Susan Bickelhaupt
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Globe Staff
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Maybe it was high tech- nology gone awry, or
maybe it was just a human misstep. But when Marty Jemison's foot
slipped off his bike pedal yesterday, just 200 yards from the
finish, his shot at victory slipped, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob Piil of Denmark dashed past Jemison to dart over the line
first and win the 156-mile USPRO Championships in 6 hours 4 minutes
44 seconds, earning $33,500. He was just ahead of Brian Walton of
Canada, Harm Jansen of the Netherlands, and Morten Sonne of
Denmark, who all were given the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Jemison, 34, cruised in three seconds later. But even though he
didn't take first place, he still received honors as first American
finisher and national champion. He was awarded the stars and
stripes jersey, which will stay in the family when he rides in the
Tour de France next month, since Postal Service teammate George
Hincapie won it last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, this feels good,'' said Jemison, who was national amateur
champion in 1993. And he mat- ter-of-factly explained his misstep
that came just when he was ready to sprint to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dropped back a little bit and was going to give it 100
percent go, and felt like I could have won the sprint, but I pulled
my right foot out of my pedal,'' said Jemison, who later added ``it
was a malfunction of the pedal.'' (On racing bikes like Jemison's
the bike shoe clips into the pedal.) Ei- ther way, his opponents
took advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   For four hours the 131 racers looked like they were on a Sunday
ride along the banks of the Schuylkill River; for two hours they
looked like  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  they were rushing home to
dinner, and for half an hour they seemed to be racing from a
burning building. More then 700,000 spectators lined the streets to
watch the racing that started at 9 a.m. and made 10 main laps of
the 14.4-mile loop around the downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the race is so long, it's on the last three laps when you
have to pay real attention,'' said Piil, who won last Tuesday's
91-mile circuit race in Lancaster, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing less than a minute behind Jemison was Fred Rodriguez
of Piedmont, Calif., who now rides for the Italian Mapei team. He
had closed the gap on the five leaders to 25 seconds as the race
made its three final laps.
</P>
<P>
   But he was riding alone, and didn't want to use all his energy
chasing the leaders, he said. ``And they saw me coming and sped
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Petra Rossner of Germany defended her title in the women's
72-mile race as she won a sprint finish in 3 hours 1 minute 23
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Rossner, who also won the race in 1996, said she looks forward
to it, not just because she likes the course, but because she likes
the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not a climber, but the crowd is so great ... they
just pull me up,'' she said. The course was lined with spectators
ringing cow-H bells, waving signs, and spraying water in the 84-
degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   As the riders made their way down the climb, the pack tried to
even out the race and beat Rossner to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   But the sprinter dashed in front and raised her hands in
victory. Karen Dunne of Colorado Springs was given second place and
German Hanka Kupfernagel _ currently the top women's road racer _
was third.
</P>
