<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6009 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JONES-BOS &LR;      06-07 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES EFFORT CUT JOHNSON, TRAINER TO QUICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ Next to his fighter, Don Turner had the most
frustrating vantage point of all at the Mississippi Coast Coliseum
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   From the corner of International Boxing Federation light
heavyweight champion Reggie Johnson, the veteran trainer could see,
round after round, openings in which to attack Roy Jones. He would
watch the World Boxing Association-World Boxing Council titleholder
make fundamental errors, his feet spread too wide, his hands too
low, his chin tipped forward ahead of his fists, ready to be
clipped.
</P>
<P>
   Turner would observe these things with a hopeful eye, convey
them to Johnson, and then sit in frustration and learn that they
didn't mean a thing, not even to a competent professional opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy is the best off-balance fighter I've ever seen,'' Turner
said, the marvel clearly in his voice after Jones (40-1) so
dominated the light heavyweight unification fight that he won every
round on all three judges' cards, 120-106. ``He's extremely fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Michael Jordan and the other players in the NBA. You
got Roy Jones and the other fighters. I was really surprised at the
difference in hand speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie is a very competent fighter. He's probably the next
best light heavyweight in the world, but you can't hit Roy Jones
twice in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   To be accurate, Johnson had ample problems hitting Jones once in
a row. According to CompuBox stats, Johnson threw a total of 380
punches and landed only 49, a less than 13 percent connect rate,
while Jones was drilling him with more than half of his 520
punches, landing 273. But cold numbers could not paint as true a
picture of Jones's dominance over a very fine professional fighter
as well as the expression on Turner's face. It was a combination of
respect, awe, frustration, and wonderment at how one man could be
blessed with such speed.
</P>
<P>
   For Johnson, it was even more frustrating because he was on the
receiving end of so many right-hand leads to the face, a punch that
normally connects only against the most amateurish opposition.
Johnson was knocked flat less than two minutes into the fight by
one such right. That punch was a precursor to his being driven to
the floor again in the third round by a left-right combination that
came so fast many at ringside thought the right had missed until
the replay was shown.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson got up both times because he is exceedingly brave and a
proud professional who plodded on to what he knew would be the
eventual conclusion, always looking to take advantage of Jones's
mistakes yet finding there was nothing he could do with them but
marvel at how meaningless they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't offset his speed,'' Johnson (39-6-1) said. ``I
thought maybe I could time him and neutralize his hand speed, but I
couldn't. He does a lot of things wrong, but his hands make up for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Jones did wrong Saturday night was impossible to
decipher because what he did most of the time was bomb and bang
Johnson to the head and ribs with rapid-fire combinations, a
stinging jab, and rights that traveled from the balcony to
Johnson's face so fast the soon-to-be ex-IBF champion could do
little but resign himself to absorbing them.
</P>
<P>
   Having won the middleweight, super middleweight, and light
heavyweight titles and dominated all his opposition in all three
classes, all that is left for the 30-year-old Jones now is talk of
the ultimate challenge _ moving up to the heavyweight division.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much discussion and debate on that point over the
past year. Jones made Evander Holyfield his target because he is
Jones's size, but the three-time heavyweight champ was at ringside
Saturday night and said after the fight he had no interest in
facing him. The same was true of Holyfield's trainer, who just
happened to be the same man who sat crouched for 12 rounds in
Reggie Johnson's corner wondering when what he saw with his own
eyes was going to have some effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only fight for Evander is Lennox Lewis,'' Turner said.
``Why would he fight Roy Jones?
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy Jones is a great fighter in a weight class that doesn't
have many great fighters. He has more speed than anybody. Too much
speed. But he doesn't punch hard enough to stay with the best
heavyweights.''
</P>
<P>
   What he does have though, is greatness. A greatness proven time
and again during his career. A greatness that is a gift from a
higher power but one he has learned to use to perfection. It was on
display again Saturday night for Reggie Johnson and the man who sat
in his corner to marvel at as they slowly learned to believe their
eyes were lying to them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
