<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-PROCHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORRISON, MEET CLEAR HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ As far as hurdlers go, Melissa Morrison is a
tiny thing. Just 5 feet 4 inches and 115 pounds, she feared she
would have trouble with the gusty headwinds Sunday at the Mitchel
Athletic Complex, where the Track and Field Association kicked off
its new professional league with a meet it called the
ProChampionships.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, Morrison came up big, blowing away her competition
to win the 100-meter hurdles in 12.98 seconds and taking home
$100,000 for winning the race, which had been randomly drawn just
days ago as the jackpot event in a new-style meet that offered
appearance fees but no prize money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Invest it,'' answered a gleeful Morrison when asked what she
would do with the bounty. ``And pay off my Visa card and my
mother's Visa card and take her shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Morrison, a promising but little-known 27-year-old fellow
North Carolinian whose career has been up and down, sprinter Marion
Jones was undefeated last season 21 times at 100 meters as she
began her quest for an unprecedented five gold medals _ at 100,
200, the long jump, and 4 x 100 and 4 x 40 relays _ at the 2000
Olympics in Sydney. Although the slowest in at least two seasons,
Jones's 11.33 win Sunday kept the streak alive. Hoping that
upcoming competitors won't hear about the 10-mile per hour
headwind, the reigning world champion seemed pleased, even playful.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to look at the time and say, oh, we've got
her now,'' chuckled Jones, who has a personal best of 10.71 and ran
no slower than 11.01 last season. ``Let them think that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other winners included Stacy Dragila, who broke her US record in
the pole vault with a jump of 14 feet, 10 3/4 inches; Obadele
Thompson in the 100 meters (10.29); Maurice Greene in the 200
(20.37); and Regina Jacobs in the 800 (1:59.64).
</P>
<P>
   Whether track and field, languishing as a spectator and
television sport in the US, was a winner remains to be seen,
although everyone connected with the event termed it a good start.
With a crowd generously announced at 3,184, TFA founder Brian
Vandenberg said he was ``thrilled'' with Sunday's shakedown event,
which boasted a two-hour, finals-only format ideal for television.
Between mid-April and mid-June of next year, TFA plans to put on
somewhere between five and eight meets, although locations and
schedule are not expected to be announced until October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was just a glimpse of what we're trying to do,'' said
Vandenberg.
</P>
<P>
   As for the athletes, no one was complaining. ``I think it's
great,'' said Bob Kennedy, second in the 3,000 meters to Kenya's
Paul Bitok. ``It's going to get stronger as they publicize it
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Not helping were the withdrawals of headliners and Olympic gold
medalists Michael Johnson after the death of his maternal
grandmother last week and Gail Devers with a nagging hamstring
injury. With them also went two key matchups (Devers and Jones in
the 100; Johnson and Greene in the 200, in which Greene won their
most recent meeting in last year's Prefontaine Classic) that would
have lent the inaugural meet some panache. But the crowd seemed
happy to embrace the lesser-known Morrison in their absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize I had so many relatives living in New York,''
joked Morrison about their eagerness to befriend a big-money
winner.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging she was a bit nervous entering the race,
knowing $100,000 was at stake, Morrison said she tried to approach
it as any other race. ``I tried not to think about it,'' she said
of the bonus. ``I think I did a pretty good job of blocking it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, she has had practice. In March, Morrison lost her
father to cardiac arrest and last June, on the day of the 110-meter
hurdle finals at the US Championships (she finished fourth), her
sister died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, they are with me always,'' she said. ``I know they
want me to do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, they got their wish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
