<HEADER>
A6015 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERB-CLEANSING-BOS &LR;      06-07 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-CLEANSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV DESERTER TELLS OF `CLEANSING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEKESCSABA, Hungary _ The skin on his gaunt face is stretched so
tight, it makes his green eyes look unnaturally big and perpetually
startled, like a small child's. Five cheap stuffed animals hang
from the wall by his bunk bed at the refugee camp here, giving him
some faint comfort when he is awakened by his frequent nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't look like a tool of ``ethnic cleansing,'' the
Serb-coined term for the forced removal of a different ethnic
group.
</P>
<P>
   But as a sniper in the Yugoslav Army until February of this
year, that's what Goran says he witnessed and even participated in
when he was on the front lines in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot praise myself. I am just happy that I am alive,''
said Goran, shrugging as he recounted his service in _ and
desertion from _ the army.
</P>
<P>
   On the condition that his real name not be used, Goran, 20,
detailed his life _ as an abandoned baby, a dutiful recruit, and
then a frightened deserter who rode his bicycle hundreds of miles
to cross the border into Hungary, where he has asked for political
asylum.
</P>
<P>
   As a soldier in Kosovo, Goran said, he shot at people from a
trench, and was in missions where Yugoslav soldiers surrounded
villages, attacked them, and then killed anyone who remained.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers were directed by superiors to steal from the Kosovars,
and to turn the booty in to the army, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to independently verify Goran's description of
his military service. However, his account synchronizes with the
stories told by legions of refugees who made it out of Kosovo
alive. Goran's description runs counter to the official Serb claims
that the refugees were escaping NATO bombing, and it suggests that
the activity was indeed an organized effort, and not the random
violence of rogue soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Goran joined the army last year, in part to fulfill his
mandatory military service and in part to give some structure to a
haphazard life.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 months, Goran and his twin brother were dropped into a
garbage can by their mother, who Goran says was an alcoholic. The
brother died; Goran was found by a gypsy woman who was rummaging
around for some food.
</P>
<P>
   He was put into a Yugoslav orphanage and adopted by an old
woman, who died when he was 7. Goran was returned to the orphanage,
and at age 10 found his personal case file on a desk there. Only
when he read his file, Goran said, did he realize that the old
woman who cared for him for seven years was not his biological
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Goran ran away, apprenticing himself to bakers and tire fixers,
who gave him some food and a place to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined the army, he said, he had heard that Albanian
``terrorists'' were hurting Serb civilians in Kosovo. ``I did not
know at all about the ethnic cleansing before I went to Kosovo,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He trained to be a sniper at a camp in Subotica, a small city
near the Hungarian border.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Aug. 1 of last year, the new soldiers were bused past
their normal training camp, and taken directly to a train. They
were loaded onto the cars _ eight soldiers each in 30 cars _ and
guarded by military police who threatened them with court-martial
if they tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
   The train began to move south. Belgrade went by, then Nis.
Terrified, Goran realized they were being taken to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, Goran said, the soldiers were ordered to call home.
``They told us to say we were in Kosovo, there were no problems,
and not to spread any stupid information,'' Goran said.
</P>
<P>
   In the province, Goran was stationed in Suva Reka, Jezerce,
Djakovica, and Stimlje. ``I thought I was going to die,'' he said,
since he was sometimes left without adequate food or ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Goran said he had been ordered to shoot at three kinds of
uniforms: ``Russian'' uniforms, which he describes as basic
camouflage pattern; white uniforms with Kosovo Liberation Army arm
patches; and black uniforms with many pockets, such as
photographers also wear.
</P>
<P>
   He looks away when asked if he killed anyone. ``I don't know,''
he said. ``I tried to shoot at my targets' legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about what happened at the villages, Goran looked down at
the table and took a long drag on his cigarette. ``There was ethnic
cleansing,'' he said, looking up. ``Yes, it happened. Villages were
burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to shoot at the villages from three directions,
leaving only one direction for retreat,'' he said. ``It was a
message that they had to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
