<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6016 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV13-NY     06-07 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKIT: THE UNRECOGNIZED ADMONITION LINGERS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 13)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kennedy Library occasionally releases tapes recorded
secretly by JFK of conversations with other political leaders. In
his San Francisco Examiner column, the hardballing Chris Matthews
reported a familiar but curious locution on one of those
transcripts. It will be semantically examined here for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   JFK called Mayor Richard Daley of Chicago to complain in salty
language that one of his local representatives was ``sticking it
right up us'' in not supporting him on a civil rights bill. Daley
replied: ``He'll do it. The last time I told him, `Now  &UR; look it &LR; 
... you vote for anything the president wants ... and that's the
way it's gonna be.'''
</P>
<P>
   The tape's transcriber got it wrong. The admonition is one word:
 &UR; lookit &LR; . You won't find  &UR; lookit &LR;  in most dictionaries, though it
is a widely used, if somewhat outdated, urban Americanism, on the
order of  &UR; see here &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lookit &LR;  began as a corruption of the transitive verb  &UR; look at &LR; ,
as used by Theodore Dreiser in his 1925 novel, ``An American
Tragedy'': ``Oh, do look at those sleeves ....  &UR; Lookit &LR;  the
collar.'' But the intransitive verb has a different meaning. In
Philip Barry's 1939 ``Philadelphia Story,'' the character played by
Cary Grant in the movie says to Katharine Hepburn, `` &UR; Lookit &LR; ,
Tracy, don't you think you've done enough notes for one day?''
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, Mayor Raymond Flynn of Boston told a conference
of mayors in 1991, `` &UR; Lookit &LR; , cities are tired of being portrayed
as, quote, problem areas.'' (Democratic mayors are especially keen
users of  &UR; lookit &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   The meaning is not ``look at it'' or even ``consider this.'' The
syllable  &UR; -it &LR;  has nothing to do with the word  &UR; it &LR; . The meaning
ranges between the imperative ``pay attention'' and the more severe
``look at me when I'm talking to you'' (perhaps rooted in the
medieval  &UR; look ye &LR; ). The closest one-word synonym is  &UR; listen &LR; ,
punched up by the recent favorite of football coaches,  &UR; listen up! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hold still for a further nuance. ( &UR; Lookit &LR; , we're nothing if not
thorough in this column.) I posted a query about this unexamined
Americanism on the American Dialect Society list-server. (I think
 &UR; list-server &LR;  may be a nonsexist word for ``somebody who waits on
lists,'' unless it is ``somebody who hands you a list,'' as in ``My
name is Rodney and I am your  &UR; list-server &LR;  this evening.'')
</P>
<P>
   Dennis R. Preston from the department of linguistics and
languages at Michigan State University, who says he is a
Midwesterner, contributes this contour to the introductory
admonition: ``The tone of  &UR; lookit &LR;  for me is usually exasperated
(` &UR; Lookit &LR; , I've been trying to explain ...') or even aggressive
(` &UR; Lookit &LR; , I got me a knuckle sammich here you gonna hafta munch
if ...').''
</P>
<P>
   M.E.G.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth Greenfield _ her initials spelled the acronym
MEG, which became the first name she was known by _ died last month
at 68. The Washington Post editorialist and Newsweek columnist, a
Pulitzer Prize winner and later a Pulitzer board member, was long
an inspiration to every opinionmonger in the nation. She was
suitably eulogized by journalists and political figures for her
incredibly good sense and zero tolerance for hypocrisy and
pomposity.
</P>
<P>
   Because Meg was often a secret source of On Language, a word is
in order here about her love of the political lingo. At a time when
Washington colloquies were endangered by an outbreak of
 &UR; watershed &LR; , she drew a bead on that vogue word and effectively
blasted it out of the shallow water of pretentious discourse.
</P>
<P>
   When, in 1968, Newsweek compounded the cliche with ``a
 &UR; watershed &LR;  in the quagmire,'' she responded with, ``I have become
an incurable, even obsessive collector of printed  &UR; watersheds &LR; , of
which I believe I now have the best collection in town _
 &UR; watersheds &LR;  perching on escalation ladders,  &UR; watersheds &LR;  embedded
in arms spirals,  &UR; watersheds &LR;  wrapped (like chicken livers,
perhaps) in an enigma. It is not, however, an expression I would
dare to use myself. I came to that drainage basin two years ago and
paddled left, into the sunset.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a turning point. She did the same thing to  &UR; virtually &LR; ,
the cop-out modifier, and to  &UR; crossroads &LR; , the pothole in the path
of every headline writer. Miss Greenfield (no Ms. for Meg) insisted
that words be used to transmit clear meaning, and rejected those
that confused the reader or diffused her focus.
</P>
<P>
   We shared a taste for arcane puns. A generation ago, in an
article about the Palestine Liberation Organization and its leader,
I used the title ``That's My Baby,'' and wondered if someone,
somewhere would catch the dim allusion. Silence for a day. Then in
came the call from Meg, singing in her sweetly rasping voice:
``Yasser, that's my baby. No sir, don't mean maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   It pained Meg not to be outrageous enough to do the same above
her editorials. Though she may have been the first to consider
``Between Iraq and a Hard Place'' in a headline, she felt that the
dignity of her editorial page would not permit really deep
groaners.
</P>
<P>
   When her deputy Stephen Rosenfeld addressed a difficulty being
faced in a Latin American republic, she called me to pass along his
rhyming bilingual encapsulation: ``Tsoris in Honduras.'' (She
called again to object to my spelling of the Yiddish word for
``trouble''; her version is  &UR; tsouris &LR; , closer to Honduras.)
</P>
<P>
   And when Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh was arrested for some
wrongdoing, Meg had the forgiving headline in type but could not
bring herself to run it. So she passed it on to me: ``Let Bhagwans
Be Bhagwans.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us in the world of words knew the little lady of
towering stature to be serious and funny, astringent and wise. She
leaves a void.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
