<HEADER>
A6017 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PEACE-ANALYSIS     06-07 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PEACE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING INTO MILOSOVIC'S HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't think a peace deal means that NATO has won the war.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's abrupt acceptance of
Western peace terms last week should not be read as capitulation.
Even if looks like a worse deal than the Rambouillet plan he
rejected, it is not. If anything, the deal contains many elements
in it that the canny Serbian dictator has wanted all along.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, last week's agreement is stunningly lacking in key
details _ giving Milosevic plenty of wiggle room in negotiations on
what happens next _ and it raises the specter of Kosovo's possible
partition.
</P>
<P>
   Further, it gives Milosevic just what he calculated he needed
months ago: a Western security presence, bringing with it Western
money. Why that need? The emergence of the Kosovo Liberation Army
left him little choice.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his own forces failed to smash the KLA's spirit _ or
halt Albania's support for them _ Milosevic knew he had a problem
that was not likely to go away. His own forces could never
completely guarantee that the KLA was routed. To ensure that the
KLA is held in check, Milosevic knew what he needed: Western troops
on the ground that would be there to disarm them. Last week's peace
deal will do just that.
</P>
<P>
   But getting his own public to accept such forces was a problem.
And Milosevic had other, equally important things to accomplish
first. Accomplish them, he has.
</P>
<P>
   One aim was to lower the number of Kosovars in the province, who
compromised an uncomfortable 90 percent of the population. While
the peace deal assures that the nearly 1 million Kosovars who fled
can return home, it is unlikely that all will.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the 75,231 that have left the region for the
United States, Australia, and Israel and other countries already
realize they're on track to a far better life than what they had
back home. Those who've quit the refugee camps for a new life in
Albania may decide they are better staying there, too.
</P>
<P>
   A second objective was to undermine the power of those Kosovars
clamoring for independence or supporting the KLA. It remains
unclear just how many Kosovars have been killed, but among them are
likely to be key community leaders who could have mobilized
followers. And Kosovars who do return are likely to be distracted,
for the time being: They will have to focus on rebuilding their
shattered lives, not agitating for political freedom.
</P>
<P>
   As importantly, Milosevic has consolidated his grip on power in
Serbia. Had he signed the Rambouillet deal, he would have appeared
to have capitulated to the West. Now he looks domestically like a
peacebroker who saved his people from further destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the NATO bombing campaign, which continued into this week,
helped him strengthen his grip back home by shattering his
opposition. The most loyal proponents of democracy are now bitter
and disenchanted with the West. He has all but destroyed the
independent media. The powers Milosevic assumed during his wartime
state of emergency are likely to remain, ensuring that Serbia
becomes a virtual police state.
</P>
<P>
   Even the outrage expressed by Deputy Prime Minister Vojislav
Seselj _ who has said he will quit _ and his Radical Party plays
into Milosevic's hands. With the threat of extreme nationalists who
could sink the deal, the West will hasten to ensure Milosevic stays
in power, because he can guarantee the peace and keep Seselj under
control. His power, alas, is likely to remain unquestioned and
absolute.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that Milosevic has embraced the deal has also
guaranteed his impunity, for now. The peace plan notably makes no
mention of the International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia, which indicted Milosevic and his top aides last week.
It remains unclear just how NATO will make good on its promises to
to the tribunal that its investigators would be able to ride in
with the troops.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Russian troops, traditional allies of the Serbs,
will patrol a part of Kosovo also raises the potential for the
province's future partition. Russian troops could choose to patrol
the north, along the Serbian border. That would ensure that
mineral-rich territory, with many of the key Serbian religious
sites, remains in Slavic hands. Kosovo's Serbs will feel
comfortable remaining there.
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovar Albanians may not. They may chose to group wherever
American, British, or other NATO troops patrol, feeling more
comfortable under their oversight.
</P>
<P>
   The net result may be a Serb-dominated north, and a Kosovar
dominated south.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most importantly, last week's peace deal means Milosevic
may have found a way to hang on to power while solving some of his
country's long-term economic problems. One reason Milosevic has
resorted time and again to war over the last decade was because he
knew he could not hold onto power while making the painful
transition from a communist economy to a free-market one.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Western aid is likely to come pouring into the region (with
some of it being skimmed off the top for Milosevic and his
cronies). The money surrounding the 50,000 peacekeepers in the
region alone will go a long way to rejuvenating business. And
someone will have to foot the bill _ or loan Serbia the money _ to
repair the damage done by the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is not to say Milosevic didn't make some flawed
calculations over the last few months. He expected the NATO
alliance to fissure earlier, and for less bombing to occur. The
flow of refugees to neighboring countries did not destabilize the
region _ and his neighbors, Albania and Macedonia _ as much as he
would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   But he wisely calculated that NATO would not risk putting in the
ground troops that would sweep him and his regime from power.
Knowing that, he has accepted a deal that may well solve some of
his most pressing domestic problems _ while ensuring he gets what
he wants most: continued power in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Neuffer, a visiting fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations, is on leave from the Globe, where she last was European
bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
