<SLUG> BC-FOREIGH-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PARIS, WORKERS RULE THE RAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Last week's crippling public transit strike here was
partly a case of France's fiery passion for justice.
</P>
<P>
   And partly a bonfire of its vanities.
</P>
<P>
   Rail and bus workers began their walkout Wednesday morning after
hearing that Eric Douet, a fellow worker, had been badly beaten
Tuesday by illegal peddlers at a Metro station in northern Paris.
</P>
<P>
   When word spread that Douet had died, the strike spread across
all of Paris's subway network, a third of its buses, and parts of
suburban rail lines, as well as to transit systems in Marseille and
Lyon, France's second- and third-largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on Paris was immediate and disabling: nearly 200
miles of traffic jams on roads in and around the city, lines as
long as 50 people at taxi stands, and tens of thousands of
commuters walking, bicycling, roller-skating, and hitchhiking to
work _ or taking the day off.
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't have been darker for the City of Light, with
the strike coming just as it was hosting a series of conventions,
and a Grand Slam tennis tournament, that had hotels teeming with
visitors from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Still, watching the ``esprit'' that saw transit workers stand by
their comrades, it was difficult not to feel at least grudging
respect _ at least at first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The cause, after all, was a noble one: ensuring the safety of
public transit workers and passengers. Transit unions responded
with a speed and determination that would be tough to imagine in
the United States, where strikes by public workers usually bring
legal injunctions, and where strikes of any type are tough to mount
and sustain. And the French government, from the prime minister to
the transportation chief, immediately endorsed the need for
enhanced safety at subway stations.
</P>
<P>
   All of which seemed a fitting tribute not only to a tradition of
citizen action tracing back to the French Revolution and the
student protests of the 1960s, but to the memory of the martyred
Metro worker, Douet, whom the Associated Press identified as a
39-year-old father of four.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, however, the facts of what really happened to Douet
began to be filled in. And for many, moral outrage began to be
replaced by a sense that, however worthy the cause of subway
safety, powerful trade unions had rushed to judgment on Douet's
death, perhaps to advance a political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy Wednesday evening found ``no traces of violence'' on
the Paris ticket inspector, who had in fact died from a ruptured
blood vessel in his brain, according to the local prosecutor's
office. It remains to be determined whether the aneurysm had been
induced by Tuesday's confrontation with vendors illegally selling
goods in the Metro.
</P>
<P>
   To Anne Bunde-Birouste, an American who has lived here for 13
years, last week's strike conjures up the best and worst of France:
``They're very concerned in this country about increasing violence,
and they're ready to make an effort to stop it. . . . But they
don't really care if they inconvenience people because they want to
make that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it inconvenienced everyone in my family,'' added
Bunde-Birouste, a program director for an international health
promotion agency. ``I take transport, my employees take it, and my
guest needed to take it and couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Baron Eric de Rothschild, one of France's leading business and
civic figures, is less sympathetic to the strikers: ``It shows to
the government that if it ever does anything against unions, they
have the power one day or other to stop the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nicole Kac-Ohana, a rheumatologist in Paris, tried to be
philosophic. This strike and others recently reflect an
unwillingness to attack problems head-on, which characterizes the
French approach to everything from the Kosovo crisis to labor
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even don't know, they even are not sure, but they're
doing and they're doing in a special way,'' she said of last week's
unannounced strike. That ``special way,'' she added, ``is always
the way to bother people.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Parisians think of the recent work stoppage, they'll
have to put up with at least another half-day of it. Both the bus
and subway systems were expected to be closed Monday afternoon for
three hours so workers can attend Douet's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Tye is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
