<HEADER>
A6024 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVACY-MEDICAL-BOS &LR;      06-07 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-MEDICAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY BILL FOR PATIENTS IS DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In hospital administrators' suites, insurance
company offices, and in Senate committee chambers, the same debate
rages and the same impasse prevails: how to protect a person's
medical privacy while guaranteeing health care providers needed
information.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, once a theoretical problem, has in the computer age
become a practical one. The wrangle on Capitol Hill proves it has
also become a political problem.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are pharmaceutical companies, medical researchers,
data collectors, and law enforcement agencies which want more and
easier access to patients' records.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are consumer advocates and civil libertarians
pushing for patients to have more control over their records.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, no federal law guarantees a patient's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories abound. A computer disc with the names of
HIV-positive individuals was given to a newspaper. A medical center
inadvertently left thousands of patient records open on the
Internet. Employers fired workers after reading their medical
histories. Psychiatrists were ordered by insurers to turn over
verbatim notes from their sessions with patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to ensure the privacy of health records
increasingly is at risk,'' the Congressional Research Service, the
research arm of the Library of Congress, concluded this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a federally appointed panel on vital and health
statistics declared a ``health privacy crisis,'' prompting Congress
to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts in the Senate to merge three separate bills on patient
privacy fell apart last month, though negotiations are set to
resume in the Health and Human Services Committee on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head hurts from dealing with this issue,'' complained a
Senate aide after dozens of meetings failed to produce agreement on
a compromise proposal being drafted by Senator James M. Jeffords,
Republican of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that Jeffords's bill would be a strong step toward
improving medical privacy. It would establish a framework to grant
individuals ownership over their medical records and the right to
control access to them, with some exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   However, consumer advocates, civil libertarians, and some
medical care providers warn that the exceptions are too broad and
will do more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid the compromise bill will compromise privacy,'' said
Richard Sobel, a research fellow at the Berkman Center at Harvard
University. ``You can't have just a little bit of privacy
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   One exception would require patients to grant their managed-care
providers and insurers complete access to their records for
``health care operations'' such as billing.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say the terms are so vague that almost anyone
could open and read patient files. They want to narrow the list of
people with access to records and give individuals the right to
refuse such a blanket authorization, a provision providers reject
outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the integrated system we have now it is not possible for
any hospital or health plan to ask consent every time the
information is used,'' said Carol Kelly, speaking on behalf of the
Health Care Alliance, an umbrella group representing business
interests ranging from insurance to pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is necessary for information to move freely within that
entity and avoid having to ask patients for their signature every
time the information moves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern relates to a provision Sobel refers to as ``docs
to cops'' that would allow law enforcement personnel, including the
police, to read medical records without having to establish
probable cause or get approval from the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that there be a neutral third party
between those seeking information and those who have it _ someone
like a judge or jury,'' said Patti Goldman, a lobbyist with the
American Hospital Association.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most contentious aspect is whether states would be
allowed to enact more restrictive privacy laws or whether the
federal law would override all state rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Alliance and the American Hospital Association
want one federal standard that would preempt the patchwork of state
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two states passed two different laws governing patient
information and a hospital was on the state line, the institution
could really be hamstrung on how and when to disclose that
information,'' said Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates, however, want states to keep existing laws,
and to pass new ones if they provide better protections. They point
to Massachusetts, which might be prohibited under the proposed
measure from passing the strictest medical privacy bill in the
country. The bill is now in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said states should be able to insist
on better protections as unforeseen developments arise in such
areas as genetic testing or new epidemics.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who introduced his own bill, also seeks to forbid
hospitals or insurers from giving private researchers medical
records unless all information identifying a person by name is
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Also remaining to be worked out are the liability terms for
someone who unlawfully shares or exposes an individual's medical
history.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, led by Senator Robert F. Bennett of Utah, insist a
person or entity could be sued only if the information was
``intentionally or willfully'' released, while Democrats, led by
Kennedy, want to lower the standard to allow anyone who suffers a
breach to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is crucial for the law to be enforced effectively, and that
means the basic principle that if your rights to privacy are
violated, you can hold someone responsible in court,'' said Chai R.
Feldblum, a Georgetown University law professor who represents
disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   Even if these issues are resolved, Margo Goldberg, a
psychiatrist from the Boston area and a leader of the National
Coalition for Patient Rights, pointed out that the proposed
legislation does not deal with one of the greatest threats to
patient privacy: cradle-to-grave'' electronic medical records that
are just now being developed to follow patients throughout their
lifetimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
