A6026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-AMERICANS-HNS &LR;      06-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-AMERICANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN AMERICANS LEARN LESSON FROM FUND-SCANDALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The scandal involving a political fund-raiser
three years ago hasn't dissuaded Asian Americans from participating
in politics, politicians and activists say, but has made the
community more wary of those casting themselves as leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser, Chong Lo, was sentenced in federal court last
week for mortgage loan fraud unrelated to her political activities.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the sentencing, and recent allegations of Chinese
spying at U.S. nuclear weapons facilities, David Lee, president of
the Chinese American Voter Education Committee in San Francisco,
said Asian Americans still have a long road to political
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asians are still on the suspect list of the national psyche,''
Lee said. ``It's kind of moved from donors to spies, but it seems
like the whole loyalty question, which was at heart of the campaign
donations scandal, and the Japanese internment in World War II, is
coming back again.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lee emphasized that, although Lo was active in raising
money, she was convicted of wrongdoing unrelated to her political
work, and she was never charged with taking improper foreign
campaign donations, as Democratic Party fund-raiser John Huang was
accused of doing after Lo's arrest in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no linkage between China and Chong Lo,'' he said.
``It was more of a personal issue of defrauding lenders. Her
problems were very personal problems and John Huang's were State
Department problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the suspicions of disloyalty that the recent spy
scandal has inflamed against Asian and Asian-American scientists
and engineers is a much graver concern than one individual's
fraudulent business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Lo, 52, was convicted in U.S. District Court in San Francisco
last September of 12 counts of bank and mail fraud for making false
statements on loan documents while working as a mortgage broker.
</P>
<P>
   She was sentenced on June 2 to 27 months in federal prison and
pay $126,000 in restitution to those she defrauded. Lo plans to
appeal the conviction and remains free on bail.
</P>
<P>
   At the time she was arrested, in July 1996, Lo was chair of an
Asian-American political action group, the Lotus Fund, and was
organizing a gala San Francisco event designed to raise $400,000
for the Democratic National Committee. Lo had hoped President
Clinton would speak at the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   But within days, the gala was canceled and party officials were
disavowing ties to her.
</P>
<P>
   Lo's conviction has made politically-active Asian Americans more
cautious about checking out the credentials of political
colleagues, even if they share the same goals and support the same
causes, said San Francisco Supervisor Leland Yee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chong Lo situation made us more careful, even of people in
our own community,'' he said. ``If another Lotus Fund group came
along and asked for an endorsement or attendance at an event or a
contribution, we would take a little more time to evaluate that
request.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some political observers predicted that the controversy
over campaign contributions would dampen Asian-American political
participation, Lee said such involvement has actually blossomed in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The donor issue was a very small elite group of people
participating,'' he said. ``We're talking about registering and
voting. Asians are recognizing that Latinos have been very
successful in this area and the majority of political power in the
Latino community is not based on financial contributions, it's
based on votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Lo is similar to Huang and others is in her interest in
gaining access to political circles, said Henry Der, a deputy to
California Superintendent of Schools Delaine Eastin and former
director of Chinese for Affirmative Action.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these individuals tried to leverage their contacts, their
ability to raise money to gain access to the party in power,'' he
said. ``They were not advancing issues for poor people in the
(Asian-American) community, like more housing, and better bilingual
education opportunities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
