<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLIGHT-BLACKS-BOS &LR;      06-07 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-BLACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS LOOK FOR A PLACE TO CALL HOME IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ During his first week in Boston, Dr. Kevin Hibbert
walked proudly through the halls of Children's Hospital in Boston,
a stethoscope swinging from his neck. He felt he had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But at night, loneliness sunk in. He searched for black
nightclubs and restaurants, and would end up at the same one or two
spots. He even joined a black ski club _ and he doesn't even ski.
</P>
<P>
   Finding other young black professionals in a city known mostly
for Irish-theme pubs and college-age dance clubs seemed impossible.
And black women? They were elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to keep pretending that it doesn't matter,'' Hibbert
said. ``I'm tired. I've been doing it for three years and I don't
want to do it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   So at the end of the month, Hibbert is moving to Los Angeles.
Add him to the list of black professionals who are leaving Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, hundreds of black professionals have fled the city
after spending a year or two here, through a revolving door that
undermines the potential power of the black middle class. For
Boston, which struggles to live down a reputation for racial
tension, the brain drain has hurt companies seeking to diversify
its staffs, and diminishes the political and social clout of the
black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It destabilizes neighborhoods and communities, point blank,''
said George ``Chip'' Greenidge, who is organizing a conference that
seeks to make Boston a more welcoming city for blacks. ``It's very
important for 15- and 16-year-olds to see a brother getting up in
the morning and jumping on the bus to get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   This week a committee of African-Americans is holding the first
State of Young Black Boston conference. Greenidge and other black
leaders have worked for more than a year organizing the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Workshops concerning issues such as understanding Boston
politics, buying a home, volunteerism, and what to do on the
weekend are centered on building a Boston that's more comfortable
for black people.
</P>
<P>
   But change will not come easy, some say, especially for one of
America's oldest cities, a place where blacks and whites still
argue over whether racism, in its subtlest forms, exists _ and
where the discussion often turns ugly and ends before it can start.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say Boston is a racist city, it has to be
acknowledged and not debated,'' said Jane Edmonds, president and
chief executive of Jane C. Edmonds &AMP; Associates, a Boston
management consulting firm. ``It's difficult to engage people in a
discussion about that. If you do, you may be seen as a militant,
someone who doesn't think clear.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the label that Jacqueline Wallace fears. She says she
doesn't like raising the issue because she thinks many white
Bostonians won't understand. But she can't help but speak up: ``For
someone to say racism doesn't exist here, they're out to lunch,''
said Wallace, manager of the School to Work Initiatives at Bell
Atlantic. ``It's everywhere you turn.''
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans point to the lack of black-owned businesses,
the lack of large, black middle-class neighborhoods, of having
little political clout, and to things even harder for non-blacks to
understand. Things such as the reserved, almost aloof mannerisms of
many longtime Bostonians, who to an outsider often come across as
rude. Blacks who were not raised in the city have a hard time
understanding why people in Boston won't smile when they pass them
on the street. For many, it's an unsettling experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Washington, D.C. There it's a totally different
ballgame. Every time you pass someone, you say `hello,' '' Wallace
said. ``Here, I can walk into a store and people won't even
acknowledge me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wallace views that as evidence of prejudice _ she says she
doesn't see it happening to white people _ others say a person's
perceptions are distorted by the city's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons are, many blacks, Latinos, and other people
of color agree that life in the Boston area comes with sandpaper
uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a ton of people who have left. I probably know more
than 30 people who have gone,'' said Alvin Crawford, who himself
left Boston a year ago to work for Ogilvy Interactive in Manhattan.
``It's tragic, especially for a city that's that big.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city with a population of about 558,000, blacks accounted
for 26 percent of the residents in 1995, the most recent figures
available. Latinos made up 12 percent and Asian-Americans and
American Indians collectively made up 6 percent, according to the
Massachusetts Institute for Social and Economic Research. Whites
made up 55.7 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino said he doesn't think Boston is an
unwelcoming city for blacks or any other minority group. And he
said that opening more black clubs and restaurants would create
more division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were trying to get a more integrated community.
That's what we want,'' Menino said. ``You go to Atlanta and the two
groups don't meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Menino said that if someone feels uncomfortable, it is because
they are thinking negatively. He said he occasionally goes to Chef
Lee's on Blue Hill Avenue for soul food, and ``I'm the only white
person there and I don't feel uncomfortable. It's all mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford agrees _ to a point. He said blacks ``have to be
willing to step outside of their comfort zone,'' but he said they
also need to have places where they can enjoy their music, their
food, their culture.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said he had a rich life in Boston, but he had to work
at it. He also thinks businesses need to invest in companies such
as The Partnership, a company that has for 11 years worked with the
private sector to retain and groom blacks in mid-level and senior
management.
</P>
<P>
   Bennie Wiley, president and chief executive of The Partnership,
said the key to keeping people of color is to help them establish
important relationships, to make them feel connected. ``If people
don't establish relationships that are important to them
professionally and socially, there is more motivation to leave when
other opportunities come along,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly why Hibbert is leaving. He never found his dream
woman, never made strong friendships, never found a mentor at
Children's Hospital. What lured him to UCLA Medical Center? The
chairman of pediatrics, who is black, told him, ``If you come here,
I will help guide your career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was telling me that here,'' he said. ``No white folks.
No black folks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
