<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.H.-KING-BOS &LR;      06-07 1638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.H.-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORK PAYS OFF FOR KING DAY CRUSADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ AND JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ They faced no firehoses, billy clubs, or dogs,
no guns or bombs or hurled bottles _ only stares, harsh words, and
a cold Yankee indifference to their hopes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   It took more than a decade, but a devoted group of civil rights
activists finally won the battle to persuade the state of New
Hampshire to honor Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. with a holiday
bearing his name. Governor Jeanne Shaheen signed legislation Monday
making the third Monday in January Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Civil
Rights Day
</P>
<P>
   For a committee of two dozen people as patient and relentless as
water wearing away at rock, victory brought with it a deep
satisfaction that New Hampshire is at last in step with the rest of
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I remember anything, I remember him,'' said Steve
Davis, a teacher at St. Paul's School in Concord, recalling how
King was a hero in the Philadelphia neighborhood where he grew up.
``One part of his message was non-violence but another part was
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1990 _ a year when the black population of New
Hampshire's capital city of 36,000 could all have dined in one
restaurant _ when Davis brought his extended family north to
Concord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything about New Hampshire when I came here,''
said Davis, 49, a school administrator, coach, and athlete. ``A
couple of the first nights here I lay in bed shaking and wondering
if I had done the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few stops in between, Davis moved north from Philadelphia
to the campus of St. Paul's School, an academic sanctuary where a
private trout stream flows through the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Davis did not know was that he had moved to
one of two states in the nation that did not celebrate a holiday
bearing Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s name. Since 1992, the state
had stood alone in its refusal to honor the slain civil rights
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Though new to the faculty of one of the wealthiest preparatory
schools in the world, Davis gambled. He invited a friend to speak
to an assembly on the eve of the 1990 Martin Luther King holiday.
The speech left the school's minority students hungry for a more
formal way to honor King.
</P>
<P>
   In response, and much to the surprise of everyone, the rector
declared the next day a holiday. Students worked through the night
making signs and crafting a plan. ``I was holding my breath the
whole time because this is St. Paul's. They just don't do this
stuff, so I thought that, man if this doesn't work, I'm out of here
quick,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   At the obligatory morning chapel, speeches were made, prayers
said, and the president of the student body, an African-American,
gave his speech. ``We put a hook in the speech at the end,'' Davis
recalled. ``He said, `If you believe in peace and justice, please
stand' and everybody had to stand. Then he said, `If you believe in
peace and justice, we are going outside to march on the Capitol and
we are going to do it right now.' There was a huge roar and people
just ran out,'' Davis recalled.
</P>
<P>
   That marked the state's first student march in support of the
King holiday, but it would take hundreds of marches and rallies to
persuade the 424-member Legislature. It was at that first march
where Davis heard about Arnie Alpert, and the movement for a King
holiday grew stronger legs.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert, one of the few members of the Martin Luther King Day
Committee in 1988, is the American Friends Service Committee's sole
staff member in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never said this to him, but just watching him operate _
he was the model of Martin Luther King,'' Davis said. ``He never
got excited. He never got upset. He always took everything in
stride, but he never gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Alpert, 44, grew up in Longmeadow, Mass., in a family that was
politically aware, but not politically active. A slightly built man
whose soft-spoken words emerge from behind a Groucho Marx
moustache, he has had the New Hampshire State House virtually
surrounded for nearly two decades _ moving from one inexpensive
second-floor office to another in buildings across from the State
House, staying just yards from the Capitol steps.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert came to activism through his opposition to nuclear power.
In 1977 he was one of the 1,414 people arrested for occupying the
Seabrook nuclear power plant, so his first two weeks in Concord
were spent jailed in the National Guard armory.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the training in non-violence required of all who took
part in the occupation of the power plant that led Alpert to the
American Friends Service Committee, a Quaker group with
longstanding ties to King, which Alpert joined in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has repeatedly been arrested for civil
disobedience: sitting silently on the sofa in Senator Warren
Rudman's office for five days to protest US policies in Nicaragua;
passing out leaflets in a shopping mall denouncing the corporate
exploitation of foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually don't have a record of convictions except for that
last one (the mall leaflets),'' said Alpert, who is appealing that
case to the state Supreme Court in a test of free speech
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert offered the King Day Committee continuity, public
relations skills, a phone, and office space. They made do with
little money, relying instead on volunteers and Alpert's skill in
winning press coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was never a formal group. At one point Lionel was the
chair,'' Alpert said of longtime Representative Lionel Johnson, of
Manchester. ``After that, sometimes Will Thomas served as secretary
and sometimes I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Manchester native Will Thomas, 56, was a founding member of the
committee. A high school history teacher, he turned to non-violent
activism after King's assassination in 1968. ``I was inspired by
King. I learned that you may be beaten, you may be imprisoned, you
may be temporarily sidetracked but you don't give up. My political
activity is an extension of my beliefs that were formed in the
'60s. My wife says that I never left the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for a King holiday was a family affair for Lionel
Johnson, the owner of a Manchester dry-cleaning business and one of
three African-Americans now serving in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1979 when Portsmouth Representive James Splaine
filed the first bill to create a King holiday, momentum grew as one
school board after another voted to celebrate it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Johnson's daughter Vanessa, by then a Manchester School
Board member, persuaded her colleagues to buck the Manchester Union
Leader newspaper, the state's most prominent conservative voice and
a staunch foe of King and a holiday in his name. By a 7-6 vote, the
school board made King's birthday a holiday in the state's largest
school district.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Johnson, Alpert said, worked from the inside,
persuading his fellow legislators that King's message was far
greater than his frailties as a man. The best Johnson could win was
a compromise. In 1991 the state enacted Civil Rights Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be up front,'' Johnson said. ``If we were to
continue with just Martin Luther King Day we never would have
gotten the holiday. It was the same old cop-out. They said, `Why
should one man have his name on a day when Rosa Parks or Abraham
Lincoln don't have a day of their own?' '' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state after state passed King Day bills; by January
1989, 44 states had a King holiday, including Massachusetts and
Connecticut, which passed legislation in 1974, becoming the second
and third states to do so, behind Illinois. In 1993, when Arizona
began celebrating the holiday, New Hampshire became the lone
holdout, drawing the attention of white supremacist groups who
supported the state's stance. Questions began to be raised about
New Hampshire's commitment to racial equality.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the engine of the King Day struggle has churned
strongest in Portsmouth, a town soaked in the history of enslaved
Africans and their descendants for more than 350 years. King was a
guest preacher at Portsmouth's People's Baptist Church in 1952 when
he was a doctoral student at Boston University. People's disbanded
in the 1960s and reappeared as New Hope Baptist Church. So it was
no surprise that New Hope would play a key role in New Hampshire's
King Day crusade.
</P>
<P>
   The church sits on 16 acres of mostly untouched land along
Peverly Hill Road, a horse farm on one side and New Hope Pastor
Arthur Hilson's house on the other. Last week, New Hope Baptist was
flush with the joy of the men and women Hilson calls ``the King Day
warriors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilson's deep connections to the nation's civil rights struggles
have made him an obvious powerpoint for New Hampshire's King Day
fight. He is New England's agent for the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, founded by King.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did here was make the fight a visible thing,'' said
Hilson. ``I brought people in from the (civil rights) movement.
Jesse (Jackson) was here twice, and King's daughter (Bernice King)
delivered a King Day message,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those faces, and their words, made the struggle real for many,
particularly the state's young.
</P>
<P>
   What motivated Mike Vlacich, 26, son of a bookbinder and a
former student aide at Concord High School, to organize a
1,200-student march at the State House in 1991 was, he said, ``what
Martin Luther King did for working people and the poor and people
of color everywhere. It was wrong not to honor Martin Luther King.
I do think people misunderstood who we (New Hampshire residents)
were because of it, but now we've finally done it,'' Vlacich said.
He is now a special assistant for policy in Shaheen's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
