<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-07 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN BOMBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks like deja vu all over again. Even as President Clinton
claims another political victory, some Republicans are going after
him, oblivious to lessons from earlier tangles with him.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are no longer trying to snare Clinton over a sex
scandal; they know that doesn't work. No, this time they are trying
to snare Clinton on the air war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Clinton was right all along; ground troops
were not necessary, despite what military experts and even some
Democrats said. It appears that NATO has won the war with the sole
use of air power, as evidenced by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's concessions last week. The peace deal he says he is
willing to accept is strikingly similar to the earlier peace
proposal he rejected before attacking Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Milosevic stalls on his acceptance of the deal, the air
war has clearly had an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is gaining even more leverage on Milosevic by continuing
the bombing until he sees clear evidence of the Yugoslav
president's final acceptance of the terms for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some Republicans are continuing to politically bomb Clinton.
But the GOP's bombs are not quite having the effect on Clinton that
NATO's bombs are having on Milosevic. The Republicans are finding
that tossing these bombs may be doing more political damage to them
than they are doing to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a federal judge last week said at a hearing that he
will decide early this week whether to hear a case brought by 31
members of Congress, including four Democrats, who argued that the
US bombing of Yugoslavia is illegal. The hearing came about the
same time that a peace agreement was accepted by the Yugoslav
parliament, which is controlled by Milsoevic.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge does not dismiss the case, a hearing on the s case
is scheduled for June 23, by which time it could well be a moot
issue, if the peace agreement is signed on by all parties. it could
also be another embarassment for the Republicans if the case goes
forward. Their argument against Clinton on his role in the war
appears even weaker than the impeachment charges on which Clinton
was easily acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   The members of Congress bringing the case to court argue that
Clinton is violating the War Powers Act of 1973 because he did not
get congressional authorization for the use of US troops in a
conflict that goes beyond 60 days. They refer to a 213-213 House
vote on authorization of the war, and a vote of 427-2 against the
US declaring war in the Yugoslav conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The President's counsel, Philip Bartz, says the group is asking
the courts to involve itself in a political matter. More bluntly,
the group wants the court to intervene in an ongoing battle between
the Clinton administration and Congressional conservatives who are
apparently still bitter over their failure to get Clinton ousted on
impeachment charges. With this motivation, the largely Republican
group is again over-reaching in their efforts to get Clinton in
their clutches.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Rep. Roscoe Bartlett, a Republican from
Maryland, defended the suit, saying its purpose is to declare the
US involvement in the conflict illegal, and thus put pressure on
Clintion to end the conflict, if it is not ended by the time the
case is heard.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Bartlett exposes his true motives, telling reporters:
``He will either comply with the law, or we will impeach him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett and other Republicans with a single-minded dislike of
Clinton apparently have not learned anything from their failed
impeachment experience.
</P>
<P>
   The American public never wanted Clinton impeached, but
right-wing Republicans kept pushing forward until they fell off a
political cliff.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Republicans are doing again what most Americans do not
want them to do: seeking legal action against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is successful in forcing Milosevic to end the war and
fully accept the peace terms, he will look more like a war hero
than the incompetent commander in chief his critics have tried to
paint him as. And right now things are headed Clinton's way.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may still be a little early for the White House, and
NATO, to do any serious celebrating, there has to be more than a
few wide smiles around the White House these days _ including some
from Vice President Al Gore Jr., who will reap some political
benefits from the war's resolution, and Hillary Rodham Clinton, all
but certain to run for the US Senate seat in New York. There
probably won't be many negative questions about her husband's
handling of the war as she campaigns across the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the widest smile of all may be Clinton's, as he looks back
on the times he had two strikes against him, on the impeachment
trial and now on the Kosovo conflict, and hits a home run to win
both games.
</P>
<P>
   And the right-wing Republicans can only shake their heads, once
again, and wonder how he managed to beat them again. Perhaps they
might consider that in such battles, the good guys do win _ and, in
the eyes of the American public, conservative Republican's all-out
``get Clinton'' campaigns are definitely not seen as good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
