</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WISDOM OF GALBRAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was US ambassador to India, he gave ``The Last Hurrah''
to Jawaharlal Nehru. The prime minister was ``enchanted'' with
Edwin O'Connor's novel of Frank Skeffington, a mayor much like
Boston's James Michael Curley. Both recipient and donor liked the
last chapter, in which Skeffington resolutely refuses to repent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd Do It Again!'' was Curley's own autobiography, its theme
echoed in the latest book among the dozens written by John Kenneth
Galbraith. ``Name-Dropping: From FDR On'' is mischievously and
merrily unrepentant. The author really did know Eleanor Roosevelt:
``Her dress was agreeably utilitarian; the effect was always of
tweed.'' And Harry Truman: ``He had an active mind and superb
common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith's recollections exude a triumphal air. As its
self-mocking title suggests, he considers modesty an over-rated
virtue. The dust jacket notes that the author was ``born in 1908.''
The tone is as insistent as Bruce Springsteen's ``born in the
USA,'' although Galbraith was born in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a degree from Ontario Agricultural College, he has
moved in rarefied circles of academe, politics, and diplomacy with
a farm boy's hard-won self-assurance. For more than six decades, he
has deployed wit and intelligence to dismantle a structure he once
baptized as ``the conventional wisdom.'' It must be marvelous to be
proven right while still upright.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Galbraith's genius is his ability to accept yes for an
answer. A Galbraith hero, Adlai Stevenson, proposed in the 1950s
that money spent on auto tailfins be spent on education, echoing
the arguments of Galbraith's ``The Affluent Society.'' He twice
lost to Eisenhower, whom the professor now calls ``one of the most
underestimated presidents of our time. A Republican, he accepted
the great social legacy of Franklin D. Roosevelt and the 20-year
New Deal era and made it an integral part of American life, FDR
initiated, Truman continued, Eisenhower confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   By saluting a conservative slogan, ``If it ain't broke, don't
fix it,'' Galbraith has broadened the liberal canon. Liking Ike is
now OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name-Dropping'' includes confessions of the author's
ineptitude in politics. He regrets having opposed George McGovern's
choice of Kevin White as a vice presidential candidate in 1972
because he feared, ``as a leader of the Massachusetts delegation .
. . an unseemly row on the floor.'' It's hard to imagine unrest in
the group Tip O'Neill called ``the cast of `Hair.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR; , Galbraith's world is more like the cast of a Noel
Coward play, particularly his annual garden party after Harvard's
commencement. The hedgerows bristle with honorary degree recipients
and Nobel laureates outnumber dandelions as Mr. and Mrs. Galbraith
preside at a ritual that has enriched more than 35 June
 &UR; afternoon &LR; s.
</P>
<P>
   Indomitable, of course. Indestructible, surely. Galbraith has
also reached the point where he is bigger than Harvard, or at least
taller, the spire of Memorial Church excepted.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's reputation is liberal in large part because of
Galbraith. Every university is conservative in some respects, but
Harvard's board of overseers has too often been a treehouse of
Colonel Blimps and Major Hooples, several of whom sought to deny
tenure to Galbraith in 1947, according to Henry Rosovsky, a Harvard
legend himself, in his essay, ``The Most Famous Professor at
Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   A beacon of liberalism, Galbraith has outlasted his critics and
outshone an institution whose self-regard he has often satirized.
He rejected what he called ``the highly implausible traditions'' of
Harvard life, favoring intellect over sentiment without
surrendering the loyalty and affection of generations of students
and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   This 90-year-old memoirist may have more to offer. He once
approvingly quoted Noel Coward: ``I have a memory like an elephant.
In fact, elephants often consult me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
