<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STETHOSCOPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING TOUCH: RELIANCE ON STETHOSCOPE WANES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing is more symbolic of the doctor's art than the
stethoscope; one physician-writer even likens it to a therapeutic
``umbilical cord'' that represents the intimate bond between the
doctor and patient.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, nearly 200 years after its invention, the stethoscope is
losing its once preeminent place as a diagnostic tool to more
accurate, though costly, high-tech tests like the echocardiogram
and CT scan.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians still, of course, carry their stethoscopes like a
badge of honor, draped around their necks. But compared to their
elders, today's young doctors have proven less skilled at detecting
and interpreting the faint whooshes and clicks of a sick heart.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that's just technological evolution: what's the point
of making such an effort to learn the subtleties of ausculation
(listening to heart sounds) when there's an ultrasound test
(echocardiogram) that shows the beating heart and its glitches in a
detailed, computerized image?
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the stethoscope say this new attitude leads to the
overuse of costly tests. Beyond this, these critics feel that those
who accept the ``death of the stethoscope'' are part of a
disheartening trend in which doctors are becoming remote, less of
the ``hands-on'' healers who listened not only to their patients'
bodies but their thoughts and fears as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that it's an enormous problem and a huge amount is
being lost,'' says Dr. William Silen, a veteran surgeon and
renowned diagnostician who is Dean for Faculty Development and
Diversity at Harvard Medical School. Silen contends that with his
hands and ears he could render just as accurate a diagnosis of
abdominal pain (his specialty) as a CT scan could _ and do it more
cheaply. In fact, it is wrong-headed cost cutting by managed care
companies, says Silen, that's responsible for declining hands-on
competence. ``(Doctors) are not acquiring the skills in history
taking and physical examination because they're not given the time
to do these things,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has prompted a re-examination of the training of new
doctors. Some medical schools, including Harvard's, have expanded
their training in the use of stethoscopes and other hands-on
methods of diagnoses. To help the less aurally gifted, one company
has just introduced an electronic stethoscope that amplifies heart
sounds 14 times and filters out unimportant noise. The
Hewlett-Packard Stethos, ``has lots of advantages'' over the
traditional type, says Dr. Julian Aroesty, a cardiologist at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center who recently tried it out, ``except
that it's more expensive'' at about $350 vs. $50 to $100 for a
traditional model.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors and medical educators argue that expert abilities
in using the stethoscope and tapping and feeling different parts of
the body may not be quite as crucial  &UR; today &LR;  as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I trained as an intern in 1963 and 1964, that's what we
spent our time doing with patients _ listening to their story and
listening to their heart,'' says Dr. Marshall Wolf, vice chairman
for medical education at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listened because we didn't have that much therapy _ we
couldn't fix the blood vessels or operate on the heart'' to the
extent now possible.
</P>
<P>
   While  &UR; today &LR; 's young doctors can't hear all the fine points of
heart sounds, Wolf adds, ``they have a different set of skills:
they know a lot of things that people of my generation never
dreamed of'' and which may be more important to the patient's
outcome _ especially very sick patients in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wolf says, the ability to perform a physical exam and use
a stethoscope are important for doctors who see relatively healthy
patients and need to screen them for hidden health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Aroesty, who calls auscultation with the stethoscope ``a dying
art,'' says it's a skill ``that has been lost in part because it's
not needed as much as it was before _ the same reason kids  &UR; today &LR; 
can't add and subtract because they all have hand calculators.''
The doctors' version of hand calculators include the
echocardiogram, CT, and MRI tests that create computerized pictures
of normal and abnormal structures of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been bemoaning the erosion of physical exam and
auscultation skills since the 1980s, but the most urgent wakeup
call came in September 1997, when the Journal of the American
Medical Association published the results of a test of stethoscope
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers led by Dr. Salvatore Mangione at the Allegheny
University of the Health Sciences played recordings of heart sounds
representing 12 different abnormalities, and asked 453 resident
physicians and medical students to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   On average, the internal medicine and family practice physicians
correctly identified only 20 percent of the heart problems, which
wasn't significantly better than the medical students. The
researchers called this accuracy rate ``disturbingly low'' and
raised concerns that this was also true of other ``bedside
diagnostic skills.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been raging ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Those who deplore the trend argue not so much that patient care
is suffering, but that it's costing the health care system millions
of dollars in needless, expensive echocardiograms and other tests.
Skillful use of the stethoscope ``is the most cost-effective way to
determine what's the next test'' a patient should have, contends
Dr. Robert J. Adolphe, a semi-retired cardiologist at the
University of Cincinnati who wrote an editorial in the journal
Chest last year titled ``In Defense of the Stethoscope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that those of us who know how to use a
stethoscope are (virtually) gone,'' says Adolph. ``I'm not sure
that there are going to be any teachers around'' to train the next
generation, he adds, ``and I think it's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors had for centuries pressed their ears to
patients' bodies as a crude diagnostic method, the first
stethoscope is credited to the French doctor Rene Laennec who, in
1816, rolled paper into a tube that relayed the sound to his ear.
History books say that Laennec's invention stemmed from his
uneasiness about placing his ear directly on a woman patient's
chest.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar stethoscope with its rubber tube, metal listening
part, and earpieces, has changed little in recent decades while
serving as the workhorse of diagnosis _ and not just for the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use my stethoscope every time I walk in to see a patient,''
says Dr. Ellen Rothman, a resident in pediatrics at Children's
Hospital in Boston. ``I listen to the heart, the lungs, and the
belly _ it's a great screening tool.'' She adds that young children
frequently have respiratory symptoms, and Rothman and other doctors
emphasize that even if the stethoscope became outdated for cardiac
diagnoses, it would have full employment for use in detecting fluid
in the lungs, wheezing, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1970s, when computerized images using ultrasound
technology became available, listening to the sounds of the heart
was the only noninvasive way to detect and identify different heart
problems. And it took lots of training and experience.
</P>
<P>
   As one author notes, it calls for identifying ``sounds that are
at the threshold of audibility and are packed into a very short
time interval,'' sometimes just fractions of a second. Studies have
shown that doctors who are trained musicians do better at
auscultation.
</P>
<P>
   An expert at the skill can detect quite a list of conditions by
identifying characteristic sounds, known as murmurs, clicks,
rumbles, snaps, gallops, and rubs. The sounds are emitted by blood
flowing over and through deformed or leaky valves, or by extra or
mistimed openings and shuttings of valves.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the critics, the fading of stethoscope skills
sharply reflects the downgrading of hands-on medicine, which may in
itself, in some intangible way, help patients get better. Dr.
Michael Kirsch, a physician in Highland Heights, Ohio, who compares
the stethoscope to an umbilical cord, says that technology is one
of the forces that are driving doctors and patients apart. ``This
is a complaint I hear a lot _ patients say, `All I'm getting are
tests and prescriptions','' says Kirsch.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns are not lost on medical educators. ``There's no
doubt that the average young physician's skills'' in examining
patients ``are not going to be what the best clinicians had several
decades ago,'' says Dr. Paul Wang, an attending cardiologist at New
England Medical Center who teaches at Tufts University School of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   At Tufts, training in physical exam skills is now being started
earlier. And there's a conscious effort to teach doctors how to
build a rapport with patients, Wang says.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Armstrong, director of medical education at Harvard
Medical School, says Harvard has been bolstering the teaching of
basic hands-on skills for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the first year of medical school, she says, students
are ``learning to speak with patients and capture their story, and
learn many of these qualities you're looking for in your doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Stethoscope and other physical exam skills are receiving more
attention and time, adds Armstrong. And, she said, students will
have to demonstrate that they are competent in these skills by
taking a new practical exam that's going to launched later this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
