<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-CRUISES-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE LINES ARE COURTING THE SIPPY-CUP SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You marry, you have kids, you kiss grown-up vacations goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Or you leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise ships sure make it tempting to travel with children.
Since Disney sailed into the competition last year, there's a
renewed interest in the family dollar. Norwegian expanded its
program to include toddlers, Princess dropped the minimum age to
include infants, and Carnival expects 200,000 children to sail
before the year ends.
</P>
<P>
   But a parent worries: Can a child sit through a six-course meal?
</P>
<P>
   Meet ours, ``Master Wilson,'' as his ticket dubbed him. He's
nearly 3, still in diapers, fond of elephants, peanut butter and
wearing cowboy boots (and nothing else).
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we learned after a week with Wilson aboard the
Norwegian Sea, on a cruise to Mexico and Honduras:
</P>
<P>
   Our first concern _ seasickness _ arrives soon after we leave
the Port of Houston and sail into choppy swells 8 feet high. Wilson
hobbles down the narrow hall, maintaining his balance with his
elephant, Toothbrush, under his arm. The seasickness medicine stays
in the suitcase all week.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner brings our next worry. We see on the menu that pate,
salad, pheasant consomme, beef Wellington and a cheese course will
arrive before Wilson's favorite: dessert. We know the number of
kids on board is 200 among 1,500 total. The odds that our dining
companions will also eat rice with their hands, as Wilson does, are
against us.
</P>
<P>
   We get lucky and find ourselves across a table from 10-year-old
Ashley. Her appreciation for Beanie Babies, Matchbox cars and
macaroni and cheese saved us during Western Night, Caribbean Night,
casual night and two formal-wear nights.
</P>
<P>
   TIP: Ask in advance to be seated with another family. It's a top
complaint among parents on Internet cruise-review sites. Improve
your odds by traveling at times when children are off from school.
If that doesn't work, ask the maitre d' to move you.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian, like other major cruise lines, has menus aimed at
picky eaters. The standards arrive on heavy china: burgers, fries,
hot dogs, grilled cheese and the beloved peanut butter-and-jelly
sandwich. Because the waiters know that parents stuff the tip
envelope at week's end, the sandwich comes with the crust removed.
</P>
<P>
   Another TIP: Not every meal has to be eaten over nine pieces of
silverware. Save the endurance tests for dinner and try the
buffet-service dining room near the swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   Large cruise lines such as Norwegian, Princess, Holland America,
Royal Caribbean and Carnival embrace children with hourly programs
crammed with scavenger hunts, magic shows and silly games. But find
out where you'll be parking the kids. Some ships place children
beside arcades and ice cream parlors _ and some have wading pools,
teen-age discos, even playrooms with Little Tykes toys. But other
ships house their programs in windowless rooms near the bottom of
the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Quiz your travel agent about counselor training, too, and
whether different ages are lumped together for programs. Because
activities beyond Play-Doh and easel painting can leave a toddler
bewildered, one of the best alternatives can be baby-sitting.
</P>
<P>
   On our cruise, group sitting is free for potty-trained kids, but
for Wilson, we paid $8 an hour for a Swedish woman at the reception
desk to moonlight as a sitter. She took him to see ``Peter Pan''
and fed him chocolate. We had wine with dinner and champagne at a
blues show. All three of us awoke happy the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   TIP: Not all ships offer baby-sitting, so check first if you
want a night out.
</P>
<P>
   Space can be a concern for large families, but veteran cruisers
joke that cabin size doesn't matter, because nobody spends time
there anyway. Newer ships have added suites for families who want
extra bathrooms, and larger ships even have connecting rooms. Most,
though, translate to a cabin with bunks or cramming the twin beds
together.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson surprised us in a stateroom: He found a bathroom door to
hang from; two closets to hide in; a bed to crawl under; a space to
sleep between us when the beds were put together; and a window
seat, where early bird walkers on the promenade deck caught him
wearing his cowboy boots and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   But the best time for our family came outside the cabin, when we
kicked back in deck chairs and the ocean was all we could see. One
of us realized that we were so far from the mainland it would cost
$7.95 a minute to call work. So we didn't bother.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
