   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-RESEARCH (Washington) _ The director of the
National Institutes of Health has touched off a passionate debate
by proposing that scientists disclose and disseminate on the
Internet the results of biomedical research, so the full text of
their reports would be available at no cost to anyone with a
computer anywhere in the world. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TUMOR-DRILL (Undated) _ A delicate but destructive machine,
a kind of molecular power drill deployed by tumors to punch their
way through the body's compartments, has been visualized for the
first time by biologists at Sweden's Karolinska Institute. The
power drill exists not for the benefit of tumors, though they
exploit it, but for normal remodeling of the tough walls that
surrounds the body's main organs and tissues. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FINCH-FEEDBACK (Undated) _ Among songbirds, the zebra finch
is a one-hit wonder. It learns a tune in its youth, and then is
condemned to repeat it forever, like an aging pop star on the
oldies circuit. A young zebra finch learns through auditory
feedback, listening to its own sounds and comparing them to a song
in its head until it gets it right. Little has been known about how
a mature finch, a ``closed learner'' (compared to a canary, for
example, which learns new tunes all the time) maintains its song.
But recent studies with deafened adult finches have suggested that
they use feedback as well. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA-STARGAZING (Undated) _ In speeches to astronomical
meetings in Chicago last week, NASA Administrator Dan Goldin
announced that he would apply the ``cheaper, faster, better''
philosophy that has revitalized planetary exploration to deeper
studies of the origin and structure of the universe, and challenged
the stargazing community to dream up innovative bold ideas. By John
Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ A researcher has injected neural stem
cells into the brains of fetal monkeys and found that the stem
cells spread out and evolved into the right kinds of tissue in
various parts of the brain. This is the scenario that stem cell
researchers who envision using these pliable cells to replace
damaged organs have been hoping for. The results are not directly
applicable to humans, since the monkeys were still in a fetal
stage, but they allow the researchers to study how the stem cells
migrate around in the brain and evolve. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ESSAY (Undated) _ Medical science can measure most things
these days, but one quantity remains eternally, enragingly
imprecise: how long doctors should take to do their work. The
single feat dangling permanently out of reach of the biomedical
revolution seems to be how to make the whole magnificent enterprise
run on time. By Abigail Zuger.
</P>
