<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6051 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     06-07 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: FALLS BY ELDERLY, A PERILOUS YET PREVENTABLE
EPIDEMIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom tripped over an untied shoelace, fell into a closet that
should have been closed and broke his arm when he landed on a
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth slipped going up the poorly lighted stairs in her home, hit
her head on an upper rung and needed four stitches to close the
wound in her scalp.
</P>
<P>
   Betty was near the bottom during a mountain hike when her
sneaker-clad foot slipped on a wet rock and she fell, breaking her
wrist.
</P>
<P>
   All three were over 50 when they fell and all three were lucky
that the injuries they sustained were not considerably worse. Falls
among older people and the resulting injuries that can cause
long-term disability and even death are rising in epidemic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published last month in The Journal of the American
Medical Association, Finnish researchers documented an alarming
increase in the number and incidence of falls sustained by people
over 50 since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Finns over 50 the number of falls nearly quadrupled _
from 5,622 in 1970 to 21,574 in 1995, and the rate of falls per
100,000 population nearly tripled. But even when the researchers
took the increasing age of the population into account, the risk of
falling had more than doubled for men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Finnish researchers and experts here say the problem is
no different in the United States and Britain. They attribute the
rise in falls and costly fall-related injuries to a number of
factors, many of which are preventable.
</P>
<P>
   Older people are more likely to have health problems, including
physical impairments, and more likely to be taking multiple
medications that can impair balance, reaction time, strength or
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few older people do the kinds of exercises that help
to reduce age-related declines in muscle strength and balance.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to a new Yale study, relatively few homes,
including housing for the elderly, have accommodations that can
mitigate the risk of falling.
</P>
<P>
   People 72 or older may find their own homes hazardous, according
to findings by Dr. Thomas M. Gill and colleagues at the Yale School
of Medicine published in April in The American Journal of Public
Health. The school's Program on Aging conducted a study of 1,000
people ages 72 and older living in and around New Haven in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The participants, 72 percent of them women and 69 percent of
whom were living alone, were members of Project Safety, a study
financed by the National Institute on Aging designed to assess
factors that influence the day-to-day functioning of older people.
</P>
<P>
   Each participant's home was examined for the presence of 20
potential environmental hazards, and virtually all residences,
including housing for the elderly, were found to contain one or
more conditions that could result in disabling accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The most dangerous part of the house, the study revealed, was
the floor in living rooms, bedrooms and hallways. In nearly 80
percent of homes the floor was a minefield of trip hazards: loose
throw rugs, runners and mats; curled carpet edges; electrical cords
and other small objects in pathways, and uncarpeted, slippery
floors, among them.
</P>
<P>
   Stairways presented the second most common trouble zone. Night
lights were missing in more than two-thirds of homes, and even in
daylight, lighting was often poor. In 20 percent of homes, light
switches were lacking at the top and bottom of stairways.
</P>
<P>
   Other hazards included lack of a sturdy handrail that extended
the full length of the stairway, uneven steps (some higher, lower
or narrower than others) and steps in need of repair.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The bathroom was found to be the most dangerous room. Two or
more hazards were found in 59 percent of bathrooms. More than 60
percent lacked grab bars in the tub or shower, about the only
hazard that was not found in housing for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Other common hazards included loose mats, slippery tubs and
showers lacking nonskid mats or abrasive strips, poor lighting and
toilets that were wobbly or too low to allow older people to rise
from them safely. The living room was second most dangerous, with
42 percent having two or more hazards, mostly trip hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens came next, with 40 percent having two or more hazards.
Light switches were hard to find in more than two-thirds of
kitchens, especially in the dark, and trip hazards were found on
nearly a third of kitchen floors.
</P>
<P>
   Other kitchen hazards included unstable step stools, poor
lighting and storage of frequently used objects in places that
required reaching up or bending over. Living rooms were next with
dim lighting, shadows or glare and chairs that were too low to get
out of easily, along with many floor hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of falls occur at home, and about a quarter of all
falls result from hazards like slippery or wet surfaces, poor
lighting, inadequate footwear and cluttered pathways in a home. To
help avoid these kinds of falls, Dr. Mary Tinette, director of
Yale's Program on Aging, suggests two proven measures.
</P>
<P>
   One involves exercises that increase physical strength and
balance. Strength training, like lifts with hand and leg weights,
has grown in popularity among older people. These exercises have
two benefits: they increase people's physical strength, thus
decreasing their chances of falling, and they increase bone mass so
that if a fall should occur, the risk of fracture is reduced.
Muscle strength is important to nearly every activity of daily
living, from getting out of the bed to climbing stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Tai chi has been demonstrated by osteoporosis researchers at the
Hospital for Special Surgery in New York to improve balance and
decrease the risk of falls in older people.
</P>
<P>
   Another important measure for maintaining balance is avoiding
side effects like dizziness and vision impairment caused by
medications. Those most at risk of falls take four or more
medications. Certain drugs, for example some drugs used to treat
high blood pressure or heart ailments, can cause dizziness, central
nervous system depression and movement disorders that increase the
risk of falls.
</P>
<P>
   Tinette suggests that people discuss with their physicians the
possibility of reducing the number of drugs taken and keeping
dosages to the minimum necessary to control the ailment. Effective
alternative medications can sometimes be prescribed to avoid the
side effects that make falls more likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish researchers also attributed the increase in falls
among the older people to an increase in alcohol consumption and
the use of psychotropic drugs. Older people are more susceptible to
the adverse effects of mind-altering chemicals; an amount of
alcohol that was handled well at 40 may become a serious hazard at
60.
</P>
<P>
   The fall-prevention program of the American Academy of
Orthopaedic Surgeons suggests a number of ways to help the elderly
stay on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Install sturdy hand rails on all stairways and grab bars in
the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cover stairs with tightly woven carpet or nonslip treads.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid climbing and reaching up to high shelves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a step stool with handrails
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not wax floors and always clean up spills as soon as they
happen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wear low-heeled shoes with nonskid soles. Avoid thick, heavy
soles and keep laces tied so that the shoes fit snugly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try not to use a bed that is too high, and before getting out
of bed, sit on the edge for a few minutes to be sure you are not
dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   The academy offers a free brochure on fall prevention, available
by calling (800) 824-2663 or by sending a stamped, self-addressed
business-size envelope to Don't Let a Fall Be Your Last Trip,
American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons, P.O. Box 1998, Des
Plaines, Ill. 60017.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
