<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SUMMERTIME, WHEN LEAVES TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The methodology for choosing one's friends is always a complex
business, but one of my enduring criteria, along with decency and
humor, is that they exhibit a literary curiosity. This is not
snobbish: It can mean anything from an amused regard for the
semiotic clues in ``The X-Files'' (1066 on a hotel room door!) to
an appreciation of urban billboards; just as often, the trait
presents as a fondness for good gumshoe or for Edith Wharton. The
point is that their curiosity ignites my own, and some ensuing
attention is paid to the narrative thread that unites us all.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was that my recent innocent question to two eminently
trustworthy bibliophiles _ ``What are you reading?'' _ launched
wonderful stream-of-consciousness sojourns with each of them. One
half-apologized that he was immersed in ``village novels,'' which
sent us from Barbara Pym to Thomas Hardy to Virginia Woolf, whose
protagonist in ``The Years'' exhibits a healthy fear of clipped
roses and rural clergymen. Next came the sigh from a friend with
one foot in the 19th century, who conceded that, these days, he was
``doing time'' with contemporary fiction. ``I'm thinking of going
toward Dickens, actually,'' he said, his voice lighting up. ``I'm
interested in seeing if he's as flat as I remember. I don't mean
that in a bad way.''
</P>
<P>
   What he meant, of course, was that in Dickens plot is
everything; what I liked about his comment was that its
eccentricity made me stretch. And stretching is one of the
requisite pleasures of reading in the summer, when we foster the
illusion that there is more time to read _ though there is, in
fact, quite a bit less. Instead there is grass to mow, rivers to
row, gardens to govern. But still we beat on toward the promise of
time's expanding chambers: all those unread novels and untraveled
literary paths, giving us, like the ever-hopeful Gatsby, our blue
lawns and green light.
</P>
<P>
   Many twinklings on the horizon this summer; certainly the most
neon among them is the much-buzzed ``Turn of the Century,'' Kurt
Andersen's wickedly funny satire of New York manners set the day
after tomorrow, in the year 2000 _ a world where cell phones and
moral consciences continue to shrink, but where the latte from
Starbucks is still very, very venti. Mischief-makers Christopher
Buckley and Julian Barnes have focused their acerbic sights on,
respectively, Washington, D.C., (``Little Green Men'') and that
other sceptred isle (``England, England''); Salman Rushdie, whose
inimitable humor is too often lost in the excesses of his
imagination, has gone global-rock 'n' roll in ``The Ground Beneath
Her Feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The most literary ado of the season is being made about Ralph
Ellison's ``Juneteenth,'' to be published this week; the great
manuscript _ some four decades in progress, and still uncompleted
at Ellison's death in 1994 _ has been whittled to less than a third
its original size. Raising even more questions about posthumous
publication will be Scribner's release of Ernest Hemingway's ``True
at First Light'' later this month; the fictional memoir (ridiculous
term) is the last of the unpublished literary estate, and perhaps
ought to have stayed that way. If nothing else, these contributions
might entice readers to return to Ellison's only other novel,
``Invisible Man,'' or to any of Hemingway's finest work _ this
year, for me, it was ``A Farewell to Arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to war, which brings us to Ward Just, who in ``A
Dangerous Friend'' has delivered a hauntingly, melancholy Saigon
novel that the narrator insists is not a war story. No matter; as
Just, a former war correspondent turned novelist, has continually
implied, the truth never lies in mere truths. Sebastian Faulks
(whose 1996 bestseller about the First World War, ``Birdsong,'' is
on my why-haven't-I-read-this? list) has turned to the Second World
War in the recently released ``Charlotte Gray.'' Fellow British
writer Pat Barker, whose critical reputation was ensured with her
World War I ``Regeneration'' trilogy, has gone back to the domestic
novel with ``Another World,'' but the old soldier at its center _
clinging to and trapped by his memories of combat _ is the
cornerstone of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart O'Nan, who in previous novels has written about World
War II (``A World Away'') and Vietnam (``The Names of the Dead''),
has frighteningly captured a plague in small-town, 19th-century
Wisconsin in the tersely realized ``A Prayer for the Dying.''
Equally scary but, one must assume, less literary will be Thomas
Harris's forthcoming ``Hannibal,'' the ``Silence of the Lambs''
sequel for which Lecter lovers are no doubt hungering. The summer's
stock of thrillers seems as inviting as it's been in years, with
contributions from John Katzenbach (``Hart's War''), Patricia
Cornwell's ``Black Notice'' (a Kay Scarpetta novel coming next
month), John le Carre's respectably pin-striped ``Single &AMP;
Single,'' and Martin Cruz Smith's latest ``Gorky Park''
installment, ``Havana Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   If last June's heat-wave madness award went to ``Bridget Jones's
Diary,'' the publicity for which was as overblown as an inflatable
dragon, this year's bumper crop of babe fiction alleges almost as
much but delivers even less. The most touted among this dubious
harvest are American Melissa Bank's debut collection, ``Girls'
Guide to Hunting and Fishing,'' which is graceful but forgettable,
and British writer Sue Margolis's ``Neurotica,'' which is shrill.
Turn instead to Julie Hecht's hilarious collection from 1997, ``Do
the Windows Open?,'' or to Lorrie Moore's stunning 1998 stories,
``Birds of America.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's finest work in American fiction has come in the
short story, a form that is lovingly honored in Houghton Mifflin's
premier one-volume edition, ``The Best American Short Stories of
the Century.'' Selected by John Updike and series editor Katrina
Kenison, the 55 stories present a remarkable portrait of America
since 1915 (the series' inception); they also compose a revealing
tribute to the tenets of short fiction as it has changed over the
decades. Two of the writers honored therein, Annie Proulx and Gish
Jen, are showcased in their own collections this spring: Proulx's
indelibly tough Wyoming stories in ``Close Range,'' and Jen's
graciously intelligent ``Who's Irish?''. Other notable literary
collections include Christopher Tilghman's ``The Way People Run''
and Nathan Englander's taut debut stories, ``For the Relief of
Unbearable Urges''; those who like their prose hard-edged will find
that quality in Thom Jones's ``Sonny Liston Was a Friend of Mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of roaming the natural world this spring: In ``Bone by
Bone,'' Peter Matthieson completes his Watson trilogy, set in the
Florida Everglades. David Guterson, returning to the Washington
state he so carefully evoked in ``Snow Falling on Cedars,''
captures the smaller world of a dying man in ``East of the
Mountains.'' Two novels attempt to inhabit the perspective of other
mammals, with mixed results. Paul Auster's ``Timbuktu'' follows
around a faithful dog named Mr. Bones whose owner has died, but the
novel reads like an anthropomorphic, video-cam day trip. In ``The
White Bone,'' with an imagined society of African elephants,
Barbara Gowdy fares somewhat better _ she doesn't make her animals
silly extensions of human fancy, like Auster, but you may have
trouble keeping all the names straight.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back to that village fiction where we began: the perfect
scaffolding, after all, for order and reason and civilization,
which means that anything might happen within those county lines,
and often does. This literary license, wherein the domestic houses
the unruly, has been a mainstay for writers from Jane Austen to
William Trevor; the tradition is valiantly upheld this season in
Penelope Lively's ``Spiderweb,'' a beautifully crafted novel based
in Somerset. For those summer readers for whom even a small
township in the west of England seems a little, well, modern, I
refer you to that sublime architecture of village fiction, George
Eliot's ``Middlemarch.'' Like Thoreau wandering Concord, you may
travel widely there without ever leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   And to a friend who eschews the contemporary for the glory days
of Eliot and English order, I might also mention Michael
Cunningham's homage to Virginia Woolf in his 1998 novel, ``The
Hours.'' Which will then entice you to turn to Woolf's ``Mrs.
Dalloway,'' which is, in fact, one of the superior camouflage acts
in literary history: a war novel posing as a domestic one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
