<HEADER>
A6054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-IRISH-BOS &LR;      06-07 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IRISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRY TRUTHS OF REAL LIFE IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WHO'S IRISH? 
By Gish Jen. Knopf. 
208 pp. $22. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody's having more fun with American diversity than Gish Jen.
Even using the word diversity does an injustice to her, since her
fiction has none of the reverence and political correctness usually
associated with it. Jen is the writer whose 1996 novel ``Mona in
the Promised Land,'' her second, tells the story of a single-minded
Chinese-American teen who converts to Judaism, matzo balls and all.
On the book jacket: a bagel superimposed over a bowl of won-ton
soup. And Jen is the writer who begins her new collection of
stories, ``Who's Irish?'', with the portrait of a miffed Chinese
immigrant whose daughter and Irish son-in-law deliver therapy-era
clunkers like, ``I'm not telling you what to do. . . . I'm telling
you how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   It would all be about culture clash and the problems of
assimilation, except that Jen is too good-humored and ambitious to
wrestle with moral judgment. One of the greatest charms of her
fiction is her position as a bemused chronicler _ of the way things
are in this crazy mishmash of an America, of the power and the
limitations of family roots, and, most important, of the hugely
comic potential in human nature. For the most part, no matter how
complicated or ``sensitive'' the situation _ a Chinese-American
woman mistaken for Japanese by a friend, a Chinese immigrant
awkwardly romancing the American country-club set _ Jen is there to
attach a smirk to the confusion. She's like the loving parent to
her characters as they go through their identity crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Irish?'' is a strong addition to her body of work, which
in addition to ``Mona in the Promised Land'' includes ``Typical
American,'' a novel about three immigrants caught in the promise of
1950s America. The collection is mostly peopled with Asian
immigrants and their American-born children, particularly those who
struggle with the old-world thinking of their parents. Recalling
his school experience, a Japanese-American man recalls, ``The ones
with immigrant parents in particular seemed to do nothing but
perform, perform, only to be pronounced still lacking.'' In
``House, House, Home,'' the heroine is a Chinese-American woman who
isn't interested in pursuing her parents' American Dream of money,
business, and material reward. She wants to be an artist, and
marries an unconventional art teacher more than twice her age to
rid herself of any remnant of immigrant concerns with social
acceptance. But the marriage falters. ``Could an elective outsider
ever know what it was like to be the other kind of outsider?'' she
wonders.
</P>
<P>
   The book has eight stories, all of them good. Two contain
characters and the nostalgic tone from ``Mona in the Promised
Land,'' and two are long, more serious, and beautifully fleshed
out. The best of the long stories is ``Duncan in China,'' with a
momentous hike up the mountain of Tai Shan that brings to mind
nothing less than the famous muddle of E. M. Forster's ``Passage to
India.'' Duncan is an aimless Chinese-American who moves to China
to find himself, and to avoid his mother's deification of a
wealthy, BMW-driving brother. But when he is face to face with the
conditions in China, and with a poverty-stricken cousin who
suffered through the Cultural Revolution, he realizes just how
American he is. After landing in Shandong, Duncan sees that ``the
China of the early 1980s had more to do with eating melon seeds
around a coal heater the size of a bread box than about Sung
dynasty porcelain.'' Naturally, the story is so much richer than
its summarization, and a few of the dialogue exchanges, ridden with
misunderstanding, are models of nuance.
</P>
<P>
   While both her novels contain serious drama, with incidents of
family violence and racial discrimination, a redemptive lightness
almost always hovers close by. They are, ultimately, comedies. One
of the revelations of ``Who's Irish?'' is Jen's ability to portray
hopelessness without falling back on a sweet moment. Two of the
stories here, ``Chin'' and ``Birthmates,'' are fairly unrelenting
in their sadness. ``Birthmates,'' which recently earned its way
into ``Best American Short Stories of the Century,'' is a
heartbreaking look at Art Woo, a failing businessman in the
computer industry. An emotionally stunted man who could not help
his ex-wife grieve for their 4 1/2-month-old fetus, Art finds
himself staying at a welfare hotel during a computer conference,
slipping further than ever from the American Dream. A cold bath of
a story, ``Birthmates'' ends with an unforgettably powerful image.
</P>
<P>
   But even in these heavy moments, Jen never lets her tales slip
into the realm of lesson. Her imagination is far too lively for
that. First and foremost, her fiction is about her characters, and
the amusing, and sometimes, tragic, ways they find out who they are
in American society. Never relying on political correctness _ or
the backlash against it _ for her ballast, Jen deals with the
realities, and not the theories, of living in this country.
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Gilbert writes about television and books for the
Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
