<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW &AMP; RECOMMENDED &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Timbuktu'' by Paul Auster (Holt, $22). Life and death and the
meaning of both, from the viewpoint of a dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Clearing in the Distance: Frederick Law Olmsted and America
in the Nineteenth Century'' by Witold Rybczynski (Scribner, $28).
The life of America's greatest landscape architect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Close Range: Wyoming Stories'' by Annie Proulx (Scribner,
$25). Tales of folks and life as sharp and spiky as barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identity's Architect: A Biography of Erik H. Erikson'' by
Lawrence J. Friedman (Scribner, $35). A detailed and panoramic life
of a faded culture hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Night Inspector'' by Frederick Busch (Harmony Books, $23).
A dark novel of Victorian New York, with Herman Melville as
protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   ``East of the Mountains'' by David Guterson (Harcourt Brace,
$25). The struggles of a man at the end of his days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adultery: And Other Diversions'' by Tim Parks (Arcade,
$23.95). Essays by the novelist, on the tension between freedom,
necessity, and mortality.
</P>
<P>
   (Selected from books recently reviewed in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
