<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      06-07 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING UP THE BOOKBAG FOR A MURDEROUS SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As spring turns into summer, I always find myself looking for
mystery and detective novels that combine my desire for a strong
sense of place (no doubt because the scent of faraway places with
strange-sounding names is in the air) with a story of our days;
escape combined with compelling immediacy. Winter is a single malt
and a contemplative view of crime; fall is all nostalgia and a
willingness to venture into the past; high summer is short reads
between quick dips. But the transition from spring to early summer
is full of the promise of places to come and the memory of events
just told.
</P>
<P>
   In such a mood I ventured in to Pamela Thomas-Graham's ``Blue
Blood'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23). Thomas-Graham's first Ivy League
mystery, ``A Darker Shade of Crimson,'' was set at Harvard; now she
has come to Yale, and no doubt she will move on to the Big Green of
Dartmouth. But for the nonce she has chosen to tell us the tale of
a controversial Yale Law School professor, impossibly young and
improbably beautiful, who is found on a deserted New Haven street
dead of multiple stab wounds. A dean of a college is suspected of
the crime, and 30-year-old African-American economics professor
Nikki Chase hurries down from Cambridge to solve the crime. The
plot is remarkably silly, the writing flat, and though
Thomas-Graham has clearly done some eyeball research on the Yale
campus, she gets a good bit wrong (including, it appears, believing
that a college at Yale is overseen by a dean, rather than a master
_ a confusion I take personally, having once been the latter and
never the former). There is a good amount of aimless activity
through which Chase solves the crime ahead of the police
(naturally) and is confronted by the mad murderer high in Harkness
Tower, the symbol of the Yale campus. I enjoyed the book, since
it's fun to see one's own neighborhood used, or misused, but the
enterprise also struck me as in bad taste and quite graceless.
Dartmouth beware.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Dana Stabenow keeps on getting better. All
her books tell us about Kate Shugak, a lively feminist in Alaska,
and in ``Hunter's Moon'' (Putnam, $23.95), Kate and a friend have
been hired to guide some German computer executives into the
wilderness in search of big game. Soon they are the game, and then
Kate is, too, as Stabenow replays variants on ``And Then There Were
None,'' the Christie classic. The Germans are objectionable and
stupid, Alaska is its always appealing self, and Kate's hunt pulls
us into summer splendidly.
</P>
<P>
   James Thayer's ``Terminal Event'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) is a
riveting look at an airplane crash that leaves no survivors. Jon
Durant, a former National Transportation Safety Board investigator,
invites himself into the investigation because his wife was among
those killed. Durant needs to believe a bomber destroyed the plane,
while primary investigators are inclined to blame pilot error.
Thayer takes us step-by-step through the complex and technical
detail of such an investigation without putting a foot wrong; a
mountainside in the state of Washington comes alive in painstaking,
compelling detail. This is, I suspect, going to be the best book of
the summer, but it isn't for reading on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muscle Memory'' by William C. Tapply (St. Martin's, $23.95)
will be fine for the plane. Brady Coyne, a Boston lawyer who keeps
getting drawn into criminal investigations, manages to do what he
is actually supposed to do this time, to help a former professional
basketball player handle a divorce suit. The player's wife, who is
demanding a divorce for reasons he claims to be unable to grasp, is
found murdered, and Coyne soon discovers that just about everybody
is lying to him. The alert reader will see the solution to all this
dishonesty well before Coyne does, but it's rather nice to be more
intelligent than a lawyer for a change, and Tapply tells a good
story.
</P>
<P>
   So does K. C. Constantine, whose ``Blood Mud'' (Mysterious
Press, $23) brings Mario Balzic _ retired as police chief of
Rocksburg, Pa. _ back into action as a private cop. The dialogue is
as true (and coarse) as ever; the sense of a country living on the
edge, next to despair but not quite there yet, is as sharp as ever;
and anyone who has admired Constantine in the past will be happy to
see him fully back in command. If you're not familiar with him,
this book is a good chance to make Balzic's acquaintance. Do it
now, before too much cholesterol and too many tall glasses of
Chardonnay do him in.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the book that will stay with me the longest is Tom
Nolan's ``Ross Macdonald: A Biography'' (Scribner, $32), which
enters a fairly crowded field and more than holds its own. Strictly
as biography, Nolan's is the best we have on Macdonald: full of
rich, relevant details, careful, well told, compassionate without
being reverential. One wonders why the publisher wanted a two-page
introduction by Sue Grafton. It adds nothing, and this study
requires no boosting, just plain reading and respect. Nolan reviews
mystery fiction, he knows what a reader will need, and he ushers
those of us who read this kind of stuff all year long into the
inner thoughts of a writer who was a man for all seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Robin W. Winks is chairman of the Department of History at Yale
University.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
