<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PRINCETON-FUSION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST TO TAME ENERGY OF STARS REVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Colo., N.J., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLAINSBORO, N.J. _ In its heyday it was a palace among physics
laboratories, with an enviably fat budget, ample support staff and
the prestige that comes to research institutions working at the
cutting edge in solving global problems. But today, the Princeton
Plasma Physics Laboratory, still a leader in hydrogen fusion
research, is so short of cash that it can no longer afford even a
receptionist.
</P>
<P>
   However, a dry spell of discouragements and spending cuts for
fusion research may be ending. With their backs to a financial
wall, specialists in the field are banding together to pursue the
elusive goal of harnessing thermonuclear fusion, the process that
drives the sun and hydrogen bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the field say the new spirit calls for lean,
selective financing of small-scale experiments as well as the large
ones that have dominated the field's history, increased cooperation
between long-standing competitors, and a lot of patience.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of hydrogen fusion, the joining together of hydrogen
nuclei to produce useful energy, have suffered too many
frustrations over the years to hope for too much too soon. Fusion
energy will not come tomorrow. But it could become a reality in the
mid-21st century, believers say, and slow the carbon dioxide
pollution of the atmosphere by the burning of fossil fuels _ a
problem that may be leading to disastrous global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by tight budgetary constraints imposed by Congress,
competing fusion laboratories have begun sharing and coordinating
their research to a greater extent than ever and have drafted
guidelines for allocating their limited resources as they would an
investment portfolio, giving major financing to the most promising
projects but gambling some funds for high-risk but potentially
fruitful experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Next month fusion scientists and engineers from around the world
will hold a meeting in Snowmass, Colo., to discuss all the devices
and proposals currently on the table. It will be the first meeting
of its kind, according to its co-chairman, Dr. Michael E. Mauel of
Columbia University, and it signals a growing realization that if
fusion energy is ever to become a reality it will require global
cooperation rather than endless competition between nations and
individual laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The main obstacle to accelerated research fusion, many
scientists say, is the disincentive created by low fossil fuel
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' said Dr. Robert J. Goldston, director of the
Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory in New Jersey, ``a bottle of
table water costs more than a bottle of gasoline. But cheap oil
won't last forever, and in any case, the burning of fossil fuels
may be contributing to global warming. Fusion, which could produce
enormous amounts of energy at reasonable cost with only negligible
amounts of radioactive waste and no pollution of the atmosphere,
may be our only practical alternative to fossil fuels.''
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that hydrogen fusion can be achieved. Huge pulses
of fusion power have already been generated by experimental fusion
reactors in the United States and Europe. The trouble is that until
now, conventional generating plants have had to supply more energy
to kindle a thermonuclear pulse than the pulse itself produces.
</P>
<P>
   No one has yet been able to squeeze thermonuclear fuel tightly
enough and long enough to ignite a self-sustaining fusion reaction.
</P>
<P>
   In the sun, energy is produced when hydrogen nuclei fuse to
produce helium, a heavier element. But for hydrogen nuclei to
overcome their mutual electrostatic repulsion and get close enough
to fuse, they must have very high velocities, that is to say, they
must be very, very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of different reactor designs have been built, tested and
abandoned over the years, most of which belong to one of two main
categories: magnetic confinement, the squeezing of plasma by
magnetic fields; and inertial confinement, the squeezing of hot gas
by the implosion of miniature hydrogen bombs.
</P>
<P>
   A magnetic confinement device uses powerful interlocked magnetic
fields to contain and compress hot, electrically charged plasma (a
kind of gas) within a vacuum chamber. The plasma must never touch
the solid walls of its container; otherwise, it instantly loses its
heat and can never be coaxed into undergoing fusion. Everything
depends on keeping the plasma's magnetic bottle tightly stoppered,
which is no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the stars of magnetic fusion experiments have been
devices called tokamaks. One of the largest and most successful of
these machines was the Princeton laboratory's big Tokamak Fusion
Test Reactor, which in 1994 produced a record-breaking pulse of
10.7 million watts of fusion power. It was shut down two years ago
for lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   The device's lineage goes back to the early 1950s, when the
Soviet scientists Andrei Sakharov and Igor Tamm proposed the design
and named it tokamak _ the Russian acronym for ``toroidal magnetic
chamber'' _ a doughnut-shaped machine that compresses fusion fuel
magnetically.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the seemingly simple tokamak idea proved to
conceal endless pitfalls and complications, and despite great
progress in understanding the behavior of plasmas, commercial
fusion power by magnetic confinement is still only a dream.
</P>
<P>
   A competing approach to fusion is inertial confinement, in which
hydrogen bombs the size of small BB pellets would be detonated in a
target chamber, transferring their energy to a metal ``blanket.''
</P>
<P>
   In an inertial confinement reactor, each hydrogen-filled pellet
would be the target of batteries of high-powered lasers, particle
beams or X-rays. A blast of this radiation would vaporize the
plastic outer layer of the tiny fusion pellet. The resulting
implosion would drive the plasma formed from the vaporized pellet
inward on itself, compressing and heating the fusion fuel inside it
until a thermonuclear explosion occurs.
</P>
<P>
   The thermonuclear pop of each pellet, yielding energy equivalent
to the blast of 100 pounds of TNT, could simulate a thermonuclear
weapon explosion _ a similarity that has important implications for
both science and thermonuclear weapons programs. The Lawrence
Livermore Laboratory in California is a leader in this approach to
fusion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Livermore is a crucial player in the Science-Based Stockpile
Stewardship and Management Program, which monitors the health of
the nation's nuclear weapons. Fusion experiments using the
gargantuan laser array Livermore is building as the National
Ignition Facility will help the laboratory evaluate the nuclear
stockpile without having to detonate nuclear explosions banned by
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Because their research has both scientific and military
purposes, Livermore and the other two weapons laboratories
supported by the Department of Energy, Sandia and Los Alamos
National Laboratories, receive financing for both categories of
research. This makes them richer than laboratories like the
Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory, which receive only science
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for funding has always been a source of friction
between rival partisans of magnetic and inertial fusion, and the
sharing of ideas, experimental data and equipment was often
minimal. Experiments by rival camps sometimes wastefully duplicated
research.
</P>
<P>
   But a new spirit of closer cooperation has developed. In an
interview, Mauel, a Columbia University fusion expert, praised
leaders of the magnetic and inertial confinement fields for healing
many of their long-standing differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. E. Michael Campbell, the laser director at Livermore, and
Rob Goldston, the Princeton director, are doing a wonderful job
bringing us all together as a team,'' Mauel said. ``As a
co-chairman of the big fusion meeting we're holding in Snowmass
next month, I know that there's still competition among us. But
we're working together more than we used to.''
</P>
<P>
   A center of interest in the fusion race is the National Ignition
Facility that Livermore is building _ a $1.2 billion array of 192
lasers packed into a building that could contain a football
stadium. When it begins operating in 2003, its scientists hope that
progress toward sustained power-producing fusion will be greatly
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   At Princeton, financing will remain much less lavish. The
laboratory will have to spend $48 million in the next three years
just to demolish its decommissioned Tokamak Fusion Test Reactor,
which still contains traces of the radioactive tritium it used as
fuel. The big machine's reaction chamber will be filled with
concrete and then sawed into pieces for disposal, safely isolating
the tritium until it decays harmlessly.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in the 1980s, the Princeton center employed about
1,300 people. Today it has about 400.
</P>
<P>
   But the laboratory has retained most of its senior scientists
and is still doing important experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Goldston and his colleagues believe magnetic fusion research in
the United States will need a bit more than $300 million a year to
regain momentum _ a substantial increase from its present level of
$223 million. At its peak, magnetic confinement research received
as much as $370 million.
</P>
<P>
   But fusion physicists are learning to live within tight budgets.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of no-frills research that has followed the
closing of its big tokamak, Princeton has already completed a much
more modest fusion reactor called a spherical tokamak, which
resembles an apple with a thin core rather than a doughnut. The
$23.8 million machine incorporates a highly efficient magnetic
confinement system and will begin full operation in August. (By
comparison, Princeton's big tokamak shut down two years ago cost
more than $1.4 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   Other magnetic fusion projects in the United States are under
way at the General Atomics Co. (which operates its big DIII-D
tokamak in San Diego), the Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory, the Naval
Research Laboratory, the University of Rochester, the University of
Wisconsin, Oak Ridge National Laboratory and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, however, multimillion-dollar tokamaks,
stellarators, spheromaks, inertial confinement systems and other
devices with unfamiliar names have fallen far short of the
conditions needed to sustain a thermonuclear ``burn'' _ the
continuous joining-together of hydrogen nuclei into helium.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers, members of Congress and many scientists outside the
fusion research community have grown weary with the ever-receding
goal and the huge cost of many fusion experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many of the heady predictions during the early years
of fusion research proved to be wildly overblown. Enthusiasts used
to claim that hydrogen, the most abundant of all substances in the
universe, could power the world cheaply and forever.
</P>
<P>
   However, ordinary hydrogen is not viewed as a fusion fuel that
could be used in the foreseeable future. Commercial reactors of the
near future, if such are built, will almost certainly require fuel
mixtures of two hydrogen isotopes _ deuterium and tritium, not
common hydrogen. Tritium, which is radioactive, is produced only at
great expense from reactors that burn uranium.
</P>
<P>
   Another impediment is that the fusion of deuterium and tritium
can be ignited only at a temperature around 100 million degrees
Celsius (180 million degrees Fahrenheit) after being compressed to
a density 20 times that of lead. These conditions are difficult to
create.
</P>
<P>
   Confining a dollop of super-hot compressed plasma has proved to
be harder than compressing and shaping a blob of jelly using only
rubber bands. Each clever idea of the plasma physicists for solving
this problem has been matched by a new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, federal support for the fusion energy has program
declined by 40 percent, and last year the United States withdrew
from a partnership with Russia, Japan and Europe intended to create
a gigantic fusion research machine _the International Thermonuclear
Experimental Reactor. It was a heavy blow to fusion prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just too expensive,'' Goldston said. ``We simply have
to choose a path consistent with national priorities. It will take
longer, but we'll get there. We must get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
