<HEADLINE>
VENTURA WRESTLES WITH POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading Jesse Ventura's recently published autobiography, ``I
Ain't Got Time to Bleed: Reworking the Body Politic From the Bottom
Up,'' I had the impression that the new governor of Minnesota is
not the figure of fun many think he is. Consider the following:
</P>
<P>
   --He won.
</P>
<P>
   --Some of his ideas are interesting.
</P>
<P>
   --He's bigger than you.
</P>
<P>
   --Anybody Garrison Keillor despises have something going for
him.
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography, Ventura reveals the secret of his
political success: ``The bottom line is that my opponents were
boring.''
</P>
<P>
   To be boring in America at the end of the 20th century is the
kiss of death. Who would know this better than a former
professional wrestler?
</P>
<P>
   Ventura places himself in a distinguished company of
entertainers who have gone into politics: Ronald Reagan, Sonny
Bono, Fred ``Gopher'' Grandy, among others. He observes, ``There's
a lot about entertainment that translates directly to the kind of
public relations you have to do in public office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I Ain't Got Time to Bleed'' (the title is a line spoken by the
character he portrayed in the movie ``Predator'') has not been
getting the attention it deserves, which is curious, because it has
just about everything it takes to make a bestseller _ sex,
violence, drunkenness, tragedy, romance, redemption, power,
celebrity names, nods to fate and destiny, and, not least, his
political manifesto. Ventura's controversial proposals to
decriminalize prostitution and drug possession have gotten a lot of
attention, but he also has some interesting ideas about education
and campaign reform, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else it may be, ``I Ain't Got Time to Bleed'' isn't
boring, in contrast to the recent NBC movie ``The Jesse Ventura
Story,'' which presented a G-rated Norman Rockwell version of his
life. If I'm not mistaken _ I was flipping, I admit it _ the TV
movie didn't dwell upon his marijuana and steroid use, his visits
to Nevada brothels, his drinking bouts, and a variety of other
youthful and not-so-youthful high jinks that are recounted with a
mixture of pride and rue in his book. Ventura admits to having sown
vast acres of wild oats, and he did it all long before he was
elected, unlike certain other office holders.
</P>
<P>
   Professional wrestling and politics have a lot more in common
besides what Ventura calls the f-word _ fake. He writes, ``Toughing
it out in the ring against hails of insults and dealing with all
the backstabbing and betrayal and infighting _ what better training
is there for public office?''
</P>
<P>
   There are some major differences. For example, Ventura explains,
``the prime directive of wrestling is to protect your opponent as
you would protect yourself.'' Which means it must be a more
civilized arena than politics, by and large.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little scary to discover how close Ventura came to never
running for office. He'd done a pilot for a TV series called ``Tag
Team'' about two professional wrestlers who become police officers.
The concept for the show originated with a 6-year-old boy, the son
of a writer. Surprisingly, television being what it is, the network
killed it, leaving Ventura at a loose end.
</P>
<P>
   It was fate, he reveals. The show was canceled because he was
destined to become governor. ``I hope I'm not destined to become
president,'' he writes. ``I don't say that with arrogance. . . . I
don't want the presidency. I'll never say never, because you never
know what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. You never know.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
