<SLUG> BC-ART-SARGENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUMMER OF SARGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This may be the ``Sargent Summer'' in Boston, but there are
ambitious shows all over the state, from ``Stuart Davis in
Gloucester'' to ``Introjection: Tony Oursler Midcareer Survey,
1976-1999'' in Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   And there's MASS MoCA. At last. Thirteen years in the making,
the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art in North Adams has
finally opened on a 13-acre campus of 19th-century factory
buildings, several newly renovated. MASS MoCA has evolved into a
huge center for visual and performing arts, an especially
sympathetic home for the too-big, the too-experimental, the
too-tough-to-categorize. A day there is a glorious dip into
end-of-century culture. This first summer, look for major
installations by the likes of Oursler, Joseph Beuys, Robert
Rauschenberg, and Mario Merz; a series of sound installations,
including one in an abandoned quarry; lectures by a list including
South Africa's distinguished anti-apartheid artist William
Kentridge; performances including a collaboration by choreographer
Trisha Brown and artist Terry Winters (June 26); and the new 3-D
digital opera ``Monsters of Grace,'' by Philip Glass and Robert
Wilson (July 17.) MASS MoCA is putting the state on the
contemporary art map as no Boston institution has managed to do.
</P>
<P>
   MoCA is the latest and largest addition to the already rich
northern Berkshire art scene. The Williams College Museum of Art,
where the MoCA idea was hatched all those years ago, has organized
an important retrospective of the work of Oursler, a video artist
who gives his explorations of human neuroses and psychoses a veneer
of humor.
</P>
<P>
   The Clark Art Institute, also in Williamstown, offers
``Jean-Francois Millet: Drawn Into the Light'' (June 20-Sept. 6),
the largest assemblage of Millet works seen in the United States in
a quarter-century. On the checklist are star paintings like the
1857 ``The Gleaners'' from Paris's Musee d'Orsay, which hasn't lent
it in decades. Bravo to the Clark for coaxing it away.
</P>
<P>
   It was the great early-20th-century American painter John Sloan
who persuaded Stuart Davis to start summering on Cape Ann in 1915.
The area, Davis later wrote, ``had the brilliant light of
Provincetown, but with the important additions of topographical
severity and the architectural beauties of the Gloucester
schooner.'' He was a regular there until 1934, painting pivotal
pictures that form the core of ``Stuart Davis in Gloucester,'' at
the Cape Ann Historical Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine art trail
</P>
<P>
   The state of Maine has latched on to the art-tourism phenomenon
by group-hyping its seven major art museums, in communities from
Ogunquit to Orono, as the ``Maine Art Museum Trail.'' Among trail
members' notable shows are ``Love and the American Dream'' at the
Portland Museum of Art (June 24-Oct. 17) and ``Inventing Acadia:
Artists and Tourists at Mount Desert'' at the Farnsworth Art Museum
in Rockland. The trail's Web site is www.maineartmuseums.org.
</P>
<P>
   Another trail member, the Colby Museum of Art, follows another
art world trend: the new wing. Next month, Colby opens its
9,000-square-foot Lunder Wing, named for museum patrons Peter and
Paula Lunder and designed by Los Angeles architect Frederick
Fisher, also responsible for the award-winning redesign of the P.S.
1 Contemporary Art Center in Long Island City, N.Y. Colby, which
already has a wing dedicated to the paintings of Alex Katz, now has
space to show more of its historic and contemporary collections,
which run from John Singleton Copley to Sol LeWitt.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home
</P>
<P>
   Back in Boston, the Institute of Contemporary Art devotes its
space to ``Kerry James Marshall: Mementos'' (Tuesday to Aug. 22). A
native of Birmingham, Ala., Marshall came of age with the civil
rights movement, which this exhibition of his painting, sculpture,
and video honors.
</P>
<P>
   The DeCordova Museum in Lincoln presents the 1999 edition of the
DeCordova Annual (June 12-Sept. 6), a much-anticipated series of
mini-shows featuring discrete bodies of work by contemporary New
England artists, a dozen this time. Visitors will want to get
outside to enjoy the DeCordova's sculpture park, too, and the
yearlong outdoor terrace installation of the bronze self-portraits
of Robert Arneson, opening June 19.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered peripheral to a contemporary art scene anchored
in Europe and the United States, countries in Asia, Africa, and
South America have come into their own in recent years. The Peabody
Essex Museum in Salem recognizes one such nation's current work in
``Timeless Visions: Contemporary Art of India,'' up through Oct.
31.
</P>
<P>
   Return to the Age of Aquarius with ``Linda McCartney's Sixties:
Portrait of an Era,'' black-and-white photos of icons including the
Who, the Stones, and, of course, the Beatles, at the Currier
Gallery of Art in Manchester, N.H. (Aug. 14-Oct. 4).
</P>
<P>
   The late collector Paul Mellon revived the reputation of George
Stubbs, previously categorized as a ``horse painter.'' To honor
Mellon's prescience and his generosity to many US museums, the Yale
Center for British Art in New Haven offers ``George Stubbs in the
Collection of Paul Mellon: A Memorial Exhibition,'' through Sept.
5.
</P>
<P>
   Evicted from three buildings in just a decade, Real Art Ways, a
notable alternative space in Hartford, has once again rebounded.
RAW unveils its newly renovated galleries at 56 Arbor St. on June
27. If you're in Hartford soon, check out the shows at its
venerable Wadsworth Atheneum: ``Caravaggio's `St. John' &AMP;
Masterpieces from the Capitoline Museum in Rome,'' up only through
June 20, so hurry; ``Norman Lewis: Black Paintings, 1946-1977,''
through June 27; and ``Alfred Stieglitz, Georgia O'Keeffe, &AMP;
American Modernism,'' through July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all this other activity, Sargent rules the summer. In
addition to the presentation of the traveling ``John Singer
Sargent'' show at the MFA, there are related exhibitions at
Harvard's Fogg Art Museum and the Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum.
The Gardner's ``Sargent: The Late Landscapes,'' up through Sept.
26, focuses on a little-examined aspect of the work of a painter
typecast as portraitist. The Fogg's ``Sargent in the Studio:
Drawings, Sketchbooks, and Oil Sketches'' (June 10-Sept. 5) reveals
the behind-the-scenes labor of an artist whose work looks
spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   If Sargent strikes you as glib _ a reaction shared by many _
take in another, grittier Harvard show, ``Death by Hogarth,'' that
18th-century satirist's examination of the implications of the word
``execution,'' at the Fogg Art Museum through July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Should you want to dig into the construction project that is
disrupting Boston for the foreseeable future, pay a visit to the
Boston University Art Gallery's ``Boston Artists and the Big Dig.''
Up through June 27, it includes 12 artists' responses to what is,
in addition to everything else, a massive visual fact of life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
