<SLUG> BC-DANCE-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAPING INTO THE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, it almost went under a few months ago, but Dance Umbrella
is flying again, with an International Aerial Dance Festival that
gathers 11 companies of performers who are airborne, courtesy of
bungee cords, harnesses, and trapezes. Among the highlights of the
June 17-20 shows at the Emerson Majestic Theatre in Boston will be
David Parsons's ``Caught,'' a deer-trapped-in-headlights solo in
which strobe lights capture a dancer whizzing through the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Summer Dance Festival, primarily a training program
in jazz, tap, and musical theater, also offers free informal
performances on City Hall Plaza at 6 p.m. on July 9, 16, and 23.
Noted jazz dancer Danny Buraczeski is among the choreographers
showing work in the series.
</P>
<P>
   To catch the rest of the summer dance scene, you'll have to
travel. Not far, though, in the case of the Summer Stages Dance
program at Concord Academy in Concord, Mass. The school's new
Graham Gund-designed fitness facility includes a 2,500-square-foot
studio/performance space, headquarters for the dance program run by
academy faculty members Amy Spencer and Richard Colton. Essentially
an intensive student workshop, the summer program also features a
``Meet the Artist'' series, open to the public, with the
distinguished dance critic and historian Marcia B. Siegel
moderating presentations by faculty artists: Heidi Latsky &AMP; Larry
Goldhuber on July 15; Randall Jaynes on July 22; and Arthur Aviles
on July 29.
</P>
<P>
   Dance companies are ever seeking new settings in which to
perform; resorts are always on the lookout for new attractions to
lure guests. Both needs are met when the Boston-based flamenco
troupe Ramon de los Reyes dances at the Seven Hills Country Inn and
Restaurant in the Berkshire town of Lenox on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a lean season for ballet in Boston, but if you drive
west this summer, things improve. The Saratoga Performing Arts
Center in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., the summer home of the New York
City Ballet, presents another Balanchine-based troupe this year,
too: Edward Villella's Miami City Ballet, which dances at SPAC June
11 and 12. Miami's programs feature some of Villella's greatest
Balanchine roles, including ``Prodigal Son'' and ``Rubies.'' The
July 7-24 City Ballet season at SPAC, meanwhile, opens with five
performances of the controversial new ``Swan Lake,'' choreographed
by current company director Peter Martins.
</P>
<P>
   A contingent from New York City Ballet turns up in Manchester,
Vt., for a July 28 show at the Southern Vermont Art Center, a
lovely theater halfway up a mountain. On the program, which is
presented by Ballet Manchester, is Martins's ``Barber Violin
Concerto.'' Ballet Manchester also presents six principals from the
Hartford Ballet at SVAC on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Bates Dance Festival at Bates College in Lewiston, Maine,
offers 12 public performances this year, including Doug Varone and
Dancers in a July 23 and 24 program featuring Varone's new ``Bel
Canto,'' a comic dance set to Bellini. Other Bates highlights
include Philadelphia-based hip-hop troupe Rennie Harris
PureMovement in ``Rome &AMP; Jewels'' on Aug. 6 and 7, and ``New Works:
Sean Curran &AMP; Victoria Marks'' on Aug. 12. Performances are in
Bates's Schaeffer Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Bolshoi principal Nina Ananiashvili is one of the great dramatic
ballerinas of the late 20th century. Among the fellow Bolshoi
dancers she brings to the Berkshires for her Aug. 25-29 Jacob's
Pillow run is Alexei Ratmansky, a choreographer who will present
two US premieres. Highlights from the standard Russian repertory
are also on the Ananiashvili program.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pillow highlight is the return of the Mark Morris Dance
Group, Aug. 3-8, with Morris's ``Dancing Honeymoon,'' set to songs
of Gershwin, Kern, and Porter. The Morris gig is even more notable
than usual, since the company isn't scheduled for a Boston visit
next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Pillow presents the Trisha Brown Company July 7-11, in the
world premiere of Brown's first work set to jazz, a collaboration
with trumpeter Dave Douglas and painter Terry Winters. There's a
related first, the Brown/Winter lecture/performance at the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art (MASS MoCA) in North Adams
on June 26. An off-campus Pillow presentation, the event coincides
with a joint show of works on paper by Winters and Brown: Turns out
the choreographer is an impressive draftsman, too.
</P>
<P>
   How many times have you longed for a bed during a performance?
Berkshire-based choreographer Laurie McLeod is providing them. Each
audience member at her series of three open rehearsals in MASS
MoCA's theater _ Aug. 6, 10, and 12 _ gets a futon to lie on while
watching the dancers of her ``Victory Girl Productions'' clamber up
the walls and dangle from the rafters. After each run-through, the
audience will make suggestions and McLeod will incorporate them or
not, presenting the evolved version the next time around, for a
very relaxed audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
