<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      06-07 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.C., Fla., Md., Va., Calif., Colo., R.I., Pa.)  (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IN THE LAB: A Gonorrhea Vaccine Is Tested in Mice
</P>
<P>
   Researchers working with mice have developed a vaccine for
gonorrhea that is delivered through the nose and reduces vaginal
colonization of gonorrhea bacteria. The findings were reported last
week in Chicago at a conference of the American Society for
Microbiology.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 62 million people suffer from gonorrhea worldwide,
according to the World Health Organization. The American Social
Health Association, an organization that studies sexually
transmitted diseases, estimates that in the United States, 650,000
new cases are reported each year, though experts note that the rate
has been declining fairly steadily over the past decade. But the
disease is rising among young people and in minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The research, involving 60 mice, was conducted at the Uniformed
Services University of the Health Sciences in Bethesda, Md. Dr. Ann
Jerse, a microbiologist at the university and her colleagues found
that when proteins from the bacteria that causes gonorrhea were
applied in the noses of the mice, cells in the nasal cavity
attached themselves to the foreign antigen and eventually migrated
to the vagina, where they were found to stimulate local immunity
throughout the mice. ``This is a real breakthrough,'' said Jerse.
``Gonorrhea is an expensive and painful disease.''
</P>
<P>
   It also is a leading cause of infertility among women worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Gonorrhea can be cured with antibiotics, but symptoms in women
often go unnoticed until it causes permanent scarring of the
reproductive organs.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the gonorrhea experiment in mice bodes well for
other nasal vaccinations in animal trials, including meningitis and
the influenza virus. ``We are cautiously optimistic,'' said Linda
Alexander, president and chief executive officer of American Social
Health Association, which is in Research Triangle Park, N.C.
``Vaccines offer the only true hope in protection against sexually
transmitted diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   THERAPIES: Vitamin E Disappoints as Skin Healer
</P>
<P>
   In a recent study, researchers were surprised to find that
vitamin E oil, generally recommended to help wounds heal more
smoothly, was not effective. ``We were shocked,'' said Dr. Leslie
S. Baumann, the director of cosmetic dermatology at the University
of Miami School of Medicine, who conducted the research. ``We
thought we had proven how great vitamin E was. Instead, it was
obvious that it was worse than the placebo.''
</P>
<P>
   In the small study, published recently in The Journal of
Dermatologic Surgery, Baumann enrolled 15 patients who had
undergone surgery to remove skin cancers. They were given the two
creams and instructed to use each on one half of the wound.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the patients dropped out of the study within 48 hours
because of skin irritation from what turned out to be the vitamin E
cream. Two others later developed similar rashes.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of one week, half the patients thought the area
treated with the placebo, a Vaseline-like ointment, was healing
better, though later 70 percent reported no difference. Physicians
called in after 12 weeks to examine the wounds thought there was no
difference in 60 percent of the wounds, and that the ointment side
was better in 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary in the journal, Dr. Arnold W. Klein of Los
Angeles noted that many cosmetics contained a form of vitamin E
that was less likely than the one used to cause rashes and
suggested further research with them, as well as with different
doses. Baumann said she had been trying to replicate the way her
patients had been dosing themselves _ by breaking open vitamin E
capsules and applying their contents to their wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David H. McDaniel, an assistant professor of dermatology at
Eastern Virginia Medical School in Virginia Beach, said there had
been quite a ``tug of war'' about vitamin E among researchers. His
patients most often apply the contents of vitamin E capsules
directly to their wounds, a practice he said would seem to be of
``unpredictable benefit'' at best, he said. ``If somebody comes in
for a consultation, I'll tell them that I've seen it work in some
cases and cause rashes in other cases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To help healing, Baumann recommends taking 500 milligrams of
vitamin C twice a day to aid collagen production; applying an
antibacterial ointment; and covering a wound with a polyurethane
dressing like Tegaderm.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: A Closer Look at Those Who Stay Slim
</P>
<P>
   The National Weight Control Registry is keeping tabs on more
than 2,500 people who have lost weight, and researchers are looking
for more volunteers to join the study. Participants must have lost
at least 30 pounds and kept it off for at least one year.
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since the study began, the researchers have
come up with some general findings about people who lose weight and
keep it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've learned so far is that these people have not found
any secret to maintaining a weight loss,'' said Dr. James O. Hill
of the University of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But there seem to be three common factors, he added: They eat a
low-fat diet, watch their total calorie intake and have a ``very
high level of physical activity.'' Most walk each day and many do
so briskly for at least an hour. They also reported doing
bicycling, aerobics or resistance training.
</P>
<P>
   Hill and his colleague, Dr. Rena Wing of the University of
Pittsburgh and the Brown University School of Medicine, are trying
to identify the psychological, physiological and behavioral factors
that separate these people from the millions who try and fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like these people are so different from other
people,'' Wing said. Most had tried to lose weight before, but
failed. ``It seems to me that they had a whole different approach:
`This time I'm going to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The registry can be reached at (800) 606-6927 or at the e-mail
address Registry(AT)MSX.UPMC.edu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
