<SLUG> BC-ACTOR-MYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT POWERS AUSTIN POWERS? QUIET OBSERVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mike Myers's public image is not exactly that of a
bookworm. The former ``Saturday Night Live'' comic achieved fame
playing highly social characters such as Wayne Campbell, the genial
teenage host of the cable access rock party (and later hit-film
franchise) ``Wayne's World.'' Or the talkative Linda Richman, the
world's most effusive Barbra Streisand fan, based on Myers's own
mother-in-law. Even the bent, blase Dieter, MC of the German dance
show ``Sprockets,'' gets out there and mixes.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Myers has enjoyed great success with his most outgoing
character yet: Austin Powers, a swinging British superspy
cryogenically frozen in the 1960s, thawed out, and ready to resume
his playboy lifestyle in the more conservative 1990s. The 1997
low-budget ``Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery'' was not
only a solid profit maker for New Line Cinema. The spoof of James
Bond films and early psychedelia struck a deep chord in kids and
pop-culture pundits alike, resulting in a kind of media afterlife
that's raised the bucktoothed, furry-chested sex symbol to an
almost Connery-like status of his own.
</P>
<P>
   But it is, paradoxically, the introverted Myers's penchant for
quiet observation and in-depth study that has made Austin and his
other comic creations such detail-rich screams.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father was an encyclopedia salesman, and I always joke
that that made Mike a comedy and pop-culture encyclopedia,'' says
Jay Roach, director of ``Man of Mystery'' and its sequel, which
opens Friday. ``He can absorb anything and store it, categorize it
and cross-reference it. He does that in the writing process and the
performance process. What he also stores is his own recombined,
reinterpreted versions of things. There's a spirit of organized
chaos that Mike makes possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sequel, the naughtily subtitled ``The Spy Who Shagged
Me'' (ask a British friend), our hero's longtime, uptight nemesis
Dr. Evil (also played by Myers) manages to steal Austin's
magnificent mojo. The villain takes the all-important life force
back through a time machine to Carnaby Street-era London. Austin
pursues and is assisted in his quest by miniskirted mod squadette
Felicity Shagwell (Heather Graham of ``Boogie Nights''), a CIA
agent as uninhibited as he is _ or was before the mojo went
missing.
</P>
<P>
   In typical fashion, Myers, 36, is more interested in discussing
the serious emotional themes of the Austin Powers movies than their
silly shenanigans and infantile-to-sophomoric gag range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central question of the first movie was: Will Austin find
love despite his outmoded sexual mores?'' Myers, short and stocky
and a model of soft-spoken Canadian politeness, says with utter
sincerity. ``The central question of `The Spy Who Shagged Me' is:
Will Austin find love despite his lack of belief in love due to a
broken heart and a rekindling of his old swinger ways? We don't
have a whole lot in common, but Austin and I are believers in true
love, to that extent.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarities end there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's the least flirtatious guy I've ever worked with,'' says
Heather Graham. ``He's so incredibly devoted to his wife. It's very
romantic. And it's just funny that the man who makes the movies
about the swinging guy is really like that.''
</P>
<P>
   `Not a big hugger'
</P>
<P>
   Myers says he's more than just conjugally committed. ``I have a
very healthy and well-maintained proximic bubble. Much to the
amusement/frustration of my New York Jewish wife and her family,
I'm not a big hugger. I'm a very shy person, ultimately. And it's
not only being Canadian, but from growing up in a British-Canadian
house. You don't cry a lot, you tend to shake hands and not hug.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Myers and his wife of seven years, writer Robin
Ruzan, are almost always in close, well, proximity. She's often at
his side during interviews and hockey games, sure signs of true
love if there ever were any.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what shocked us both was how different our upbringings
were, but how we nevertheless came to the same conclusions about
how we wanted to live,'' he says of the match. ``We literally do
say `How did we find each other? What are the odds?' I mean, I'm so
Protestant, so English, and so Canadian. She's Jewish, such a New
Yorker, and so American. I don't even know if it's that opposites
attracted each other. It's more just shock that two different
laboratories came up with the same equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Family has always been a source of strength and inspiration for
Myers. He speaks with wistful affection of his father, who died in
1991 after a harrowing battle with Alzheimer's disease. The elder
Myers moved his family from Liverpool to the Toronto suburb of
Scarborough before Mike was born, and brought his love of absurdist
British comedy along with him. When not, yes, giving his three sons
(Mike's the youngest) encyclopedias to read, he would immerse them
in reruns of ``The Goon Show,'' ``Beyond the Fringe,'' and ``Monty
Python's Flying Circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike's mother, meanwhile, had once been an actress, and she
detected talent in her son at an early age. Mike appeared in a
number of Canadian commercials as a kid, and on graduating from
high school he had to choose between college and a gig with
Toronto's Second City improvisational comedy group. He chose to go
with the organization that trained Gilda Radner, Dan Aykroyd,
Martin Short, and many others who'd made their mark in TV sketch
comedy, and like most of them ended up getting his big break on
``SNL.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada the salad bowl
</P>
<P>
   Myers sees a link between Canada and comedy _ and no, not a glib
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're an observer nation,'' he says. ``We're not
America, we're not England, we're also not the country your parents
came from. It's an odd thing; we're not a melting pot, we're a
salad bowl. So we tend to observe how people talk, how they do
things. We even have a ministry of multiculturalism. And because of
that, we have this wonderful appetizer tray of the world and the
world's behavior. I think that's what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Myers's approach hasn't always worked. Following the
$100 million-plus success of his debut feature ``Wayne's World,''
``So I Married an Axe Murderer'' crashed both critically and
financially and was followed by several years of professional
inactivity. Even though his own dramatic portrayal of disco
impresario Steve Rubell earned high praise, the
not-intended-to-be-a-comedy ``54'' was laughed off screens last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Powers has put Myers back on top, but it has also brought
with it heightened expectations of popularity that may not be
realistically attainable. Like a true academic, though, he keeps
the ups and downs of stardom in detached perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an amazingly positive experience, I've enjoyed every
aspect of it,'' he says. ``But if you make stuff, and I made stuff
on `Saturday Night Live' for six years, one of the deaths of
creativity is being results-oriented, having any sort of
expectation or attachment. What you have to do is just focus on
what you're working on at the time. I love doing that, and that's
kind of where my emphasis lies. Having said that, that Austin
Powers has met an audience, that anyone should like it, is kind of
a miracle and kind of amazing _ I always thought of it as just this
great cosmic in joke that was specific to my house. It's nice; just
for total accuracy, I don't shun it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never make any plans. You can't. It has to do with one
day finding out my father has Alzheimer's and one day he's dead. I
think what happens is you stop and realize it's bigger than you.
You have to drop all plans for world domination at that point. It
really is Operation Meteor (that) can hit the planet at any time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
