<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIN' REUNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reunions, high ticket prices, teen idols, a new concert tent,
and Woodstock's 30th anniversary help shape this soon-to-be frantic
summer pop season. Many of the same faces are surfacing again _
from Jimmy Buffett to Steve Miller to Tony Bennett _ but the
excitement lies in the return of Bruce Springsteen and the E Street
Band, as well as in one-time-only double bills of Bob Dylan/Paul
Simon, Alanis Morissette/Tori Amos, and Ani DiFranco/Maceo Parker.
</P>
<P>
   For the more stout of heart, rap-metal band Limp Bizkit blares
onto the road. And, let's face it, any summer in which Cher is
touring has got to provide some much-needed comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   The Springsteen tour will dwarf all others. He comes to the
FleetCenter Aug. 19 and 21, though late last week the rumor was
that he would add as many as three more dates before tickets
actually go on sale. Springsteen has played somber acoustic music
the past few years, but his return to rock arenas with his New
Jersey brothers should again earn him lion-heart status.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen brings a consummate showmanship, as does the other
big reunion group _ Boston's J. Geils Band, which plays in its home
town June 23-24. Between Springsteen and Geils's Peter Wolf,
they'll bop around stage more often than a dozen shoe-gazing bands
combined. (The other expected reunion, of Crosby, Stills, Nash, and
Young, has been postponed till the fall.)
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen is charging a top ticket of $67.50 _ hardly cheap,
but a bargain next to Cher's $75 at her Tweeter Center show July
17, Dylan/Simon's $115 at their Tweeter date July 22, and the
almost unfathomable $151 to see Whitney Houston at the Wang Center
July 7-8. Was it that long ago that Houston played reasonably
priced concerts on Boston Common?
</P>
<P>
   No stadiums, but . . .
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, there are no stadium shows this summer. We had two
Foxboro Stadium headliners last month _ the Dave Matthews Band and
George Strait _ but that's it for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the summer is jampacked at the 19,900-capacity Tweeter
Center in Mansfield and the new, 5,000-seat BankBoston Pavilion on
Northern Avenue's Pier 8 in Boston. The latter venue, which opens
July 10 with the Temptations and Ashford &AMP; Simpson, will have
harbor views, though there are worries about noise from Logan
Airport traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Noise concerns haven't deterred a crowd of artists from signing
on for performances at the site, however. Among the more appealing
acts: soul diva Aretha Franklin on July 12, disco survivor Donna
Summer on July 14, dance-rockers Jamiroquai on July 18, the
swinging Brian Setzer Orchestra July 20, country star Faith Hill
July 27, jazz dean Tony Bennett Aug. 20, and the Latin-spiced Gipsy
Kings Sept. 10-11.
</P>
<P>
   The new pavilion also has booked more classic rock acts, a sign
that some former arena rockers have shrunk into the tent market.
These include Chicago and the Doobie Brothers July 11; Jethro Tull
Aug. 26; and the Moody Blues Aug. 31. (The last is not announced
officially yet.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite these moves, classic rock is still a major force at the
larger Tweeter Center. The Don Law Co., which books the venue for
SFX Entertainment, reports fast-moving sales for the
Journey/Foreigner bill June 20, and the hair-band odyssey of
Poison, Ratt, Great White, and LA Guns July 15. Sales have also
been brisk for ex-Pink Floyd singer/ guitarist Roger Waters Aug. 4,
and the Steve Miller/George Thorogood &AMP; the Destroyers bill July
31. The Allman Brothers Band is there twice this summer _ June 26
and Aug. 20 _ though that's one fewer than its three appearances
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Boomers will again be served, but so will teenagers. The growing
teen market has already caused 'N Sync's shows of July 24-25 at the
Tweeter Center to sell out. Look for the same for Britney Spears at
BankBoston Pavilion Sept. 1. Other teen-slanted bills are Brandy
and Tyrese at Tweeter June 25 and a Nickelodeon-sponsored night
with Monica, Tatyana Ali, and 98 Degrees at Tweeter June 29.
Meanwhile, far older teen idols (Mickey Dolenz, Peter Noone, and
Bobby Sherman) play the North Shore Music Theatre in Beverly July
24.
</P>
<P>
   As for festivals, there's the first-time Guinness Fleadh at
Suffolk Downs June 19 with Elvis Costello, Hootie and the Blowfish,
and many others (unfortunately, not Van Morrison, who would have
put it over the top).
</P>
<P>
   But there's no Lollapalooza, H.O.R.D.E., or Smoking Grooves,
since these fests have fallen victim to the enormous number of
radio-sponsored shows nationwide. The recent WBCN alternative-rock
River Rave _ with the Red Hot Chili Peppers headlining _ was really
a de facto Lollapalooza. That leaves the Ozzfest and Lilith Fair as
two of the bigger festivals left. The Ozzfest is at Tweeter June 16
and 18. The Lilith Fair arrives at the Mansfield venue Aug. 3, but
it will be the last year for the fair, says founder Sarah
McLachlan. She headlines a potent Lilith lineup that includes the
Pretenders, Sheryl Crow, and Aimee Mann.
</P>
<P>
   A choice of smaller fests
</P>
<P>
   Smaller festivals have gained momentum, notably the neo-hippie
Berkshire Mountains Music Festival in Great Barrington Aug. 13-15
(run by Boston's Gamelan Productions and featuring Los Lobos,
Strangefolk, the Slip, and Jiggle the Handle); the Vans Warped Tour
in Northampton July 17 with Cypress Hill, Ice T, and Blink 182; and
the Cape Cod Summer Music Festival at Falmouth's Barnstable County
Fairgrounds July 31 with Maceo Parker, Morphine, and Violent
Femmes.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of New England, Woodstock, the granddaddy of rock
festivals, will make the summer's biggest splash July 23-25 at the
decommissioned Griffiss Air Force Base in Rome, N.Y. Everyone from
Aerosmith and the Dave Matthews Band to Korn, Limp Bizkit, DMX,
Wyclef Jean, Rage Against the Machine, Metallica, and even Willie
Nelson is performing.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Woodstock will attempt to be cutting-edge, defying
the general summer trend toward predictability. Among the more
far-out shows closer to Boston: the Electronica tour with Orbital,
Crystal Method, and Lo-Fi All Stars at Worcester Palladium July 10;
and the in-your-face Limp Bizkit/Kid Rock/Staind bill at Lowell's
Tsongas Arena July 23.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot to interest folk-rockers this summer, starting
with Ani DiFranco at the FleetCenter June 17 and the Dylan/Simon
bill at the Tweeter Center July 22-23.
</P>
<P>
   Country fans also have much to crow about. Video goddess Shania
Twain is at the FleetCenter June 14. Country-rock/folkie Mary
Chapin Carpenter is at BankBoston Pavilion July 23, followed by
Lyle Lovett July 31 and Dwight Yoakam (with Deanna Carter) Aug. 15.
Holliston native/Nashville star Jo Dee Messina is at Indian Ranch
in Webster that same day, and the Mavericks at Hampton Beach (N.H.)
Casino Ballroom that same night.
</P>
<P>
   The never-shy Wynonna belts it out at the South Shore Music
Circus July 14 and North Shore Music Theatre July 19. The Music
Circus also has Lorrie Morgan June 18, Martina McBride July 17, and
Vince Gill Aug. 14. Alabama headlines the WKLB Country Festival
with Ty Herndon and the Kinleys at Tweeter Aug. 28. Traditionalist
Junior Brown is at the Middle East July 22 and the Beachcomber in
Wellfleet July 23.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a blues fan, you'll have a busy summer. B. B. King is
at BankBoston Pavilion Sept. 14. Buddy Guy, Jimmie Vaughan, and
Shemekia Copeland are at the Music Circus June 19 in a sweet bill.
Susan Tedeschi is at the Music Circus Sept. 3. The City of
Presidents Blues Festival is at Quincy's Veterans Memorial Stadium
June 27 with James Cotton, Shirley Lewis, Bruce Katz, Love Dogs,
and more. Former Rolling Stone Mick Taylor is at the House of Blues
July 8-9. The Winter Island Blues Festival in Salem is July 10
(with Booker T &AMP; the MGs and Derek Trucks) and July 11 with
Shemekia Copeland and Entrain. The annual Battle of the Blues Bands
is at Harpers Ferry July 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one of the most-asked questions: Where are the
Backstreet Boys? Look for them in the fall, not summer. Where is
Ricky Martin? Same thing. Hey, not everyone tours in the summer. It
just seems that way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
