<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CLASSICAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAVALLI OPERA TOPS FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An international audience has gathered for the Boston Early
Music Festival June 7-13, and the centerpiece of more than 100
official and concurrent events will be a major new production of
``Ercole Amante,'' a spectacular opera the Italian composer
Francesco Cavalli wrote for the court of Louis XIV. The cast
includes Nathaniel Watson, Lisa Saffer, and William Hite, and the
work is under the artistic direction of Paul O'Dette and Stephen
Stubbs. Following the Boston run, the cast moves out to Tanglewood
for another pair of performances, before moving on to the Utrecht
Festival in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Constantin Lifschitz is not the most publicized of the young
Russian pianists, but he is the most significant. His superior
technical skills can be taken for granted; what is so compelling is
how personal, risky, intense, and emotionally exposed his playing
is. His program at the Taubman Institute and International Piano
Festival and at Monadnock Music features music by Bach (the Italian
Concerto and French Ouverture), Beethoven (six bagatelles), Chopin
(two scherzi), and Shostakovich (Sonata 2).
</P>
<P>
   Tanglewood's Festival of Contemporary Music this year is under
the artistic direction of Asian-American composer Tan Dun and
features several works by another of the composers in residence,
Britain's George Benjamin. The festival is an interesting place to
find out what is on the minds of young composers _ what they are
thinking about and listening to will frequently turn out to be what
the rest of us will be thinking about and listening to in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Tanglewood has announced what looks like a very strong season.
Among the highlights should be a suite from Andre Previn's opera
``A Streetcar Named Desire'' (July 10), Seiji Ozawa conducting a
Duke Ellington program with Wynton Marsalis (July 24), a joint
concert by the Tanglewood Music Center Orchestra and the Gustav
Mahler Youth Orchestra under Ozawa Aug. 1, and the Gustav Mahler
Orchestra in a performance of Mahler's Seventh Symphony under the
direction of Claudio Abbado Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Lifschitz's recital comes in a context of 10 others in a crowded
two weeks of activity at the Taubman Institute. Among the
distinguished recitalists will be Beth Levin (July 16), Kemal Gekic
(July 17), and Piotr Anderszewski, the last the most remarkable
pianist to have emerged from Poland since Krystian Zimerman (July
20). Lifschitz shares the Monadnock Music schedule with the New
Zealand and Ciompi String Quartets; pianists Christopher Taylor,
Sergey Schepkin, Virginia Eskin, and Russell Sherman; and the piano
trio Triple Helix. Monadnock's opera this summer is Rossini's ``La
Cenerentola'' (Aug. 28) with D'Anna Fortunato returning to the
title role she sang there 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another traditional haunt of lovers of piano music, chamber
music, unusual repertory, and important if unheralded artists is
the Newport Festival, July 9-25. This summer's debut artists
include pianists from Cuba (Juana Zayas), Ireland (John O'Conor),
Russia (Vladimir Ovchinnikov), Azerbaijan (Farhad Badalbeily), and
Argentina (Nelson Goerner). Victor Borge returns July 16 for an
 &UR; evening &LR;  of comedy in music, and the eminent British pianist Dame
Moura Lympany emerges from retirement for high tea and a
``conversation'' July 24. The season closes July 25 with an
appearance by that great Newport favorite Dubravka Tomsic.
</P>
<P>
   Not so very long ago, if you wanted to hear music in the summer
you had to travel out of town. The gap has now been filled. July in
Jordan presents a full schedule in air-conditioned Jordan Hall.
Among the participants are Russell Sherman, Wha-Kyung Byun, and a
number of their most celebrated students in a program of piano
ensemble music (July 6), the Apollo Ensemble (July 7), Aston Magna
(July 14), the Borromeo String Qaurtet and friends (July 20), and
the Handel &AMP; Haydn Society (July 22). Popular attractions include
violinist Mark O'Connor (July 8) and Arlo Guthrie (July 22).
</P>
<P>
   Early music continues beyond the confines of the Early Music
Festival in the Boston University Series coordinated by Mark Kroll
(Wednesdays June 9-30) and in the International Baroque Institute
at the Longy School of Music (July 20-24). The Society for
Historically Performed Performance tours a New England circuit that
brings it to Lindsey Chapel in Emmanuel Church Thursdays from June
24 to July 22.
</P>
<P>
   The goals of the early-music movement are continued in the
activities of American Classics, which works to recover American
popular music from earlier periods. There will be three concerts in
the Longy School beginning June 15 with a cowboy music program
called ``How the West Was Sung.'' The Lydian Quartet's annual
summer festival at Brandeis University runs Sunday nights through
June. Lee Hyla and David Rakowski are the composers in residence at
the Composers Conference and Chamber Music Center at Wellesley
College July 28-Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout New England there seems to be a chamber-music
festival wherever at least three musicians can find three folding
chairs. The Rockport Festival, under the direction of David Deveau,
offers strong programs throughout June. The Cape &AMP; Islands Chamber
Music Festival flourishes in various locations Aug. 3-20. The
granddaddy of them all is Marlboro Music on weekends from July 17
through Aug. 15 in Persons Auditorium at Marlboro College in
southern Vermont; programs at Marlboro are never announced in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Opera is not quite the missing art it used to be in New England
summers. The big event of the season will be the premiere of
Stephen Paulus's ``Summer,'' based on the novel by Edith Wharton,
in the Koussevitsky Arts Center at Berkshire Community College
beginn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
