<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-SHAKESPEARE-BOS     06-07 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-SHAKESPEARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONG, DANCE, BARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man of the summer who has 'em all ravin', to paraphrase Cole
Porter, is the bard from Stratford-on-Av'n. There's nothing new
about Shakespeare in the summer, but the success of ``Shakespeare
in Love'' has theater companies hunting for every word good Will
has written. Leading the charge is the Oscar-winning star of that
film, Gwyneth Paltrow, returning to the Williamstown, Mass., stage
for ``As You Like It,'' the run of which is already sold out.
</P>
<P>
   If your taste runs less to Shakespeare than to commercial
theater, particularly musicals, there's good news for you, too,
since the downtown scene is more lively than usual, fueled by
``Titanic'' and the return of ``Rent.'' ``Titanic,'' now renamed
``Titanic: A New Musical,'' begins its two-week run at the Wang
Theatre Wednesday and opens for review Friday. The show, unlike the
movie, was not immediately embraced when it opened, in 1997, but as
the kinks with the complicated stagecraft were ironed out, both
audiences and critics started to warm to it, and when it deservedly
won that year's Tony for best musical, along with four other Tonys
(one for the Maury Yeston score), its success was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rent'' _ June 15-28 at the Shubert Theatre _ has gone in the
opposite direction, opening to spectacular reviews and immediately
becoming the hot ticket and Tony winner of the 1996 season.
Reactions started to cool when it began to tour the following year,
so it will be interesting to see how it plays now that both the
hype and anti-hype have cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Another summer entry downtown is ``Fame _ The Musical,'' which
runs from July 6 to 18 at the Colonial Theatre, and is based on the
1980 movie about New York's High School of the Performing Arts. The
musical keeps the title song, but has a new score by Jacques Levy
and Steve Margoshes. It's followed at the Colonial by the revival
of ``Evita,'' July 21-Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial New England Shakespeare festival begins with the
touring members of the Royal Shakespeare Company in New Haven
performing ``Troilus and Cressida'' beginning June 25 at the Long
Wharf Theatre, where it will play in repertory with Brian Friel's
adaptation of Turgenev's ``A Month in the Country,'' which begins
July 23. The visit is part of this year's International Festival of
Arts &AMP; Ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Boston, ``Measure for Measure'' is this year's Publick
offering of Shakespeare on the Charles. It follows ``Yeomen of the
Guard,'' which is there now, but the local theater community might
be a bit more intrigued by the third production, ``Nine,'' Aug.
5-Sept. 5, in which Lyric and Publick Theatre artistic director
Spiro Veloudos plays the Federico Fellini/Marcello Mastroianni
character from ``8 1/2,'' the film from which Yeston and Arthur
Kopit adapted the musical.
</P>
<P>
   `Caesar' on the Common
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth Shakespeare Company gets serious with its
Shakespeare this year, ``Julius Caesar,'' running from July 30 to
Aug. 14 at the Parkman Bandstand on Boston Common. Company head
Steven Maler will again be directing. In addition to the usual high
quality of the production values, you can't beat the ticket price _
it's free.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you have tickets, you won't be seeing Paltrow in ``As You
Like It'' at Williamstown (Aug. 4-15), but tickets remain for Bebe
Neuwirth (opposite her old ``Cheers'' cohort Roger Rees) in ``The
Taming of the Shrew'' (July 7-18). Another fellow who brushed up
his Shakespeare, Tom Stoppard, will be represented by ``Rosencrantz
and Guildenstern Are Dead'' on the smaller Nikos Stage. Other
highlights are Tennessee Williams's ``Camino Real'' (June 23-July
4) with Ethan Hawke and Blair Brown; ``A Raisin in the Sun'' (July
21-Aug. 1) with James McDaniel; and Arthur Miller's ``The Price''
(Aug. 18-29), all on the Main Stage. Three new plays follow ``R&AMP;G''
on the Nikos Stage: Warren Leight's ``Glimmer Brothers'' with David
Schwimmer (July 14-25); John Guare's ``Chaucer in Rome'' (July
28-Aug. 8); and Kenneth Lonergan's ``The Waverly Gallery'' (Aug.
11-22). WTF also goes to the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary
Art, in North Adams, for a musical set inside the atom, ``Quark
Victory,'' July 22-31.
</P>
<P>
   The best Shakespeare you can find year in, year out is at the
Lenox-based Shakespeare &AMP; Company. This season's outdoor mainstage
production is ``Love's Labour's Lost'' (July 23-Aug. 9), performed
at Edith Wharton's estate, the Mount. The company's artistic
director, Tina Packer, won't be leading that production, though.
She's moving indoors to the new 500-seat Duffin Theatre on East
Street at Lenox Memorial Middle and High School, where she'll be
directing Jonathan Epstein in ``Richard III,'' July 8-Aug. 1. Back
at the Mount, the Wharton adaptations are ``Glimpses of the Moon''
(June 18-Sept. 4) and ``Summer'' (Aug. 10-Oct. 17). The season
opens with Tod Randolph as Virginia Woolf in ``A Room of One's
Own,'' May 28-Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Western Massachusetts, the Berkshire Theatre
Festival in Stockbridge has a nice mix of quality writers and
directors. Christopher Renshaw (``The King and I'') opens the
season with the Sherlock Holmes mystery ``The Crucifer of Blood''
(June 24-July 10). Eric Hill follows with Orson Welles's ``Moby
Dick _ Rehearsed'' (July 13-31); Karen Allen stars in Joan
Ackermann's ``The Batting Cage'' (Aug. 3-14); and the mainstage
season concludes with David Ives's new comedy, ``Lives of the
Saints'' (Aug. 17-Sept. 4). The smaller BTF Unicorn has been one of
the more daring Berkshire venues under Hill's direction and offers
one of the more intriguing Shakespeare pieces of the season,
``Love's Fire'' (June 16-July 17), with seven top writers,
including Tony Kushner and Eric Bogosian, transforming his sonnets
into short plays. Richard Corley, who directed the sensational
``Quills'' two years ago, is back with his adaptation of ``Shoot
the Piano Player'' (July 22-Aug. 7); and Hill closes the season
directing ``Starr's Last Tape'' (Aug. 24-28).
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the Berkshires
</P>
<P>
   The newest kid on the Berkshire block is Barrington Stage Co. in
Sheffield, which opens with a revival of Jerry Herman's ``Mack and
Mabel'' (June 22-July 18) and follows with George C. Wolfe's
adaptation of Zora Neale Hurston's ``Spunk'' (July 21-Aug. 8),
closing with ``Tea'' (Aug. 5-22), Velina Hasu Houston's story about
the daughter of a Japanese war bride and an Indian-African-American
serviceman. In a new venue, Theatre Under the Stars, the company
presents the regional premiere of ``St. Nicholas,'' Conor ``The
Weir'' McPherson's one-man play about that lowliest of creatures,
the theater critic.
</P>
<P>
   Barrington Stage isn't the only theater to dare a season sans
Shakespeare. The American Repertory Theatre has a post-season
season with David Mamet's ``Boston Marriage,'' through June 27 at
the Hasty Pudding Theatre, and Eric Bogosian's ``Wake Up and Smell
the Coffee,'' June 22-27 at the Loeb Drama Center in Cambridge.
Davis Robinson directs the premiere of Beau Jest's latest
collaboration, ``The Last Resort,'' June 9-26 in the company's
South End theater, and Wellesley Summer Theatre has Brian Friel's
``Dancing at Lughnasa'' through June 26.
</P>
<P>
   North of Boston, Israel Horovitz's Gloucester Stage Company in
Gloucester is doing a season of his plays for its 20th-anniversary
season _ ``Park Your Car in Harvard Yard'' (July 7-18), ``Fighting
Over Beverly'' (July 28-Aug. 15), the premiere of ``Fast Hands''
(Aug. 18-Sept. 5), and ``Strong Man's Weak Child'' (Sept. 8-26).
</P>
<P>
   At the North Shore Music Theatre in Beverly, ``My Fair Lady''
continues through June 20, followed by the company's coproduction
with the Huntington of ``The Mikado'' June 29-July 18. Other
highlights include ``Kiss of the Spider Woman'' (Sept. 7-26) and
``The Secret Garden'' (Oct. 5-24).
</P>
<P>
   Going south, the Wellfleet Harbor Actors Theatre presents a
production of Steven Dietz's Pirandellian play within a play within
a play, ``Private Eyes'' (through June 20; a different production
returns to Shakespeare &AMP; Company, Aug. 5-Sept. 5); John Patrick
Shanley's ``Psychopathia Sexualis'' (June 30-July 24); David Ives's
``Mere Mortals'' (July 30-Sept. 5); and Sam Shepard's ``Eyes for
Consuela'' (Sept. 16-Oct. 10). The Provincetown Repertory Theatre
begins with Horton Foote's ``The Trip to Bountiful'' (June 15-July
3) and continues with Tennessee Williams's ``The Glass Menagerie''
(July 13-Aug. 8) and ``Goreyphobia'' (Aug. 17-Sept. 11). ``On the
Twentieth Century'' continues at the Goodspeed Opera House in East
Haddam, Conn., through July 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
