<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass., Calif., Ill., Ariz., Wash.)  (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turbocharged Lizards
</P>
<P>
   An easy way to improve the performance of a race car is by
adding a turbocharger, a compressor that pumps extra air into the
engine, allowing the fuel to burn more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have discovered that a monitor lizard is similarly
souped up. It comes equipped with a turbocharger of its own, a
``throat pump'' that provides extra air for the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   When lizards walk and run, they amble from side to side, flexing
their bodies laterally. The muscles that are responsible for this
flexing work in a different direction to expand the chest for
breathing. So, according to one hypothesis, at higher speeds
flexing predominates and breathing suffers, meaning that most
lizards cannot get enough air.
</P>
<P>
   Studies of monitor lizards have tended to contradict this
hypothesis, however, because they have not shown any constraint on
oxygen consumption. The new work, by scientists from Harvard, the
University of Massachusetts and the University of California at
Irvine, demonstrates that the difference is the monitor lizard's
throat pump.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who reported on their work in the journal
Science, used videoradiography _ moving X-rays, in essence _ to
view what went on inside a lizard as it trundled along on a
treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   As the lizard breathes, air is drawn both into the lungs and
into an expanding cavity in the throat area. The cavity contracts,
pumping the air into the lungs. When the researchers disabled the
throat pump by propping the mouth open, monitor lizards showed the
same impairment of lung activity as other lizards.
</P>
<P>
   The Making of a Disaster
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch, which struck Central America in October, was
the deadliest storm in the Western Hemisphere this century. About
11,000 people were killed, mostly in Honduras and Nicaragua, in the
flooding and mudslides that accompanied days of torrential rain.
</P>
<P>
   But while it was torrential, that rain was not exceptional,
according to a new study by British and American researchers.
Rainfall amounts in the storm, they say in a letter to the journal
Nature, were comparable to other severe storms in the Atlantic
region.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists had a bit of good luck: one rain gauge survived
the deluge (they are often destroyed in hurricanes), and recorded
35 inches of rain over four days ended Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggested that other factors were largely
responsible for the widespread damage and loss of life. Among
these, they say, were the timing of the storm (it came at the end
of the rainy season, when the ground was already saturated and
could not soak up any more rain), the deforestation of hillsides
for use in agriculture, and forecasts that had predicted the storm
would move to the north and stay at sea, when it turned south and
inland.
</P>
<P>
   Wind-Borne Pollution
</P>
<P>
   National parks and wilderness areas are innocent bystanders amid
the violence that is air pollution, soiled by contaminants carried
on the wind from urban areas. Things have gotten so bad that in
April, the Clinton administration asked states to develop
long-range plans for cleaning up the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of the extent of the problem comes from a study
of the air at Mount Rainier National Park in Washington, which
shows that it has higher concentrations of ozone than nearby urban
areas. Elevated ozone levels can harm vegetation and animals,
including humans.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by a scientist with the U.S. Geological Survey,
showed that the park, which is only 60 miles from Seattle, has the
highest average weekly levels of ozone of any location in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this is from ozone-creating compounds produced by the
burning of fossil fuels in cars and industry in the Seattle area.
But the problem is exacerbated because of Mount Rainier's
elevation. Ozone concentrations tend to increase at higher
altitudes as some ozone from the stratosphere disperses downward.
</P>
<P>
   A Failed Planet
</P>
<P>
   Astronomy has been awash in recent discoveries of planets
orbiting other stars. Now, researchers from the University of
Arizona say they may have found the remnants of a failed planet
circling a double star system 150 light-years from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers analyzed infrared emissions from material around
the star system and determined that it was coming from dust similar
to that in the bands of dustin the asteroid belt between Mars and
Jupiter. That belt resulted from a would-be planet that could not
form because of Jupiter's huge gravitational forces. The scientists
concluded that similar forces must be at work in the double star
system to account for the debris.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
