<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT WISE TO SAVE FOR COLLEGE IN CHILD'S NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When was the last time you filled out a college financial aid
form? You continue to advise readers to use their own name on
college savings, because the student's name will hinder the
applicant's eligibility. As a parent of five, I have filled out
said forms, and there is a section for listing the parents' assets.
Why? Because the parental assets are computed to determine the
family contribution. That means the more the parents have, the more
they are expected to contribute, and therefore the less financial
aid given. Short of going to court and disowning your child, your
assets will be calculated into the allotment of aid. Please check
your sources for educational financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Bethlehem, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The last time I filled out financial aid forms was about a
year ago, and if I had a choice of doing it again or a root
canal... well, I'd have to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   You're correct that both the parents' and students' assets must
be listed on financial aid applications, but they are treated very
differently when it comes to awarding grants. How differently? The
assumption is that each year the student should be willing to
contribute 35 percent of his or her assets to the cost of
education. Only up to 5.65 percent of the assets of the parents,
though, are deemed to be available to meet the college bills. It's
for that reason that the authors of the 1999 edition of ``Paying
for College Without Going Broke'' by Kalman A. Chaney and Geoff
Mertz say (in a headline, no less), If you have any hope of
financial aid, never put money in your child's name. They cite as
an example a college savings fund of $40,000 in the parents' name
which would be assessed for up to $2,260 for the first year of
college. The same asset in the student's name would be assessed for
up to $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   One further factor that sometimes arises here is that when money
is put in the student's name, it's usually done through a uniform
gifts to minors account. More than a couple of time over the years
I've had letters from people who bitterly regret having made that
move, but for a different reason. This is because once the minor
attains majority status, the money is legally his or hers, with no
strings attached. And if it then turns out that the owner of this
money is more attracted to a motorcycle or a muscle car than
tuition bills, there's nothing that the donor can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a recent column you mentioned that money saved for
children's education is best saved in the parent's name, as that
would increase the child's ability to obtain financial aid. Is this
true even with the new Education IRAs which allow contributions of
$500 a year and provide tax-free accumulations?
</P>
<P>
   K.M., Rancho Santa Margarita, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The editors of the book cited above, ``How To Pay for College
Without Going Broke,'' are very leery of the Education IRA. Noting
first that there had been no firm ruling on how Education IRAs will
be treated on financial aid applications, they're pretty clearly
leaning toward the opinion that they will be treated as the
student's assets. ``At the present time,'' they summarize, ``it
seems that Education IRAs are only appropriate for upper-income
families with relatively young children who are absolutely certain
they will not qualify for financial aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Note that the phrase ``upper income'' does not necessarily
relate to assets.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the numbers. If you put $500 into an Education IRA at
the start of every year and achieve 10 percent annual returns, over
the course of 12 years you would amass $10,692, and the pool will
be tax-free only if it is used for educational expenses. Suppose,
on the other hand, that a similar amount was invested in a parent's
name at the start of every year, and an amount sufficient to pay
the tax liability was withdrawn at the end of the year. After 12
years, you would have accumulated $9,050, and the student aid
formula would require that no more than $511 of it be applied to
the student's educational cost!
</P>
<P>
   So who should be attracted to the Education IRA? Primarily
people with a very substantial income level. But people with
substantial assets and moderate income would probably be better off
keeping the money in their own names. Editors Chaney and Martz cite
one case in their book to demonstrate how substantial a parent's
assets can be without disqualifying the child for aid -- that of a
person who owned a $1 million New York City apartment and a stock
portfolio worth more than $2 million, and whose daughter qualified
for a $4,000-a-year need-based grant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a single woman, 53, and plan on retiring in 10 years. My
current salary is $43,000 a year, and I contribute $5,000 of it to
a 401(k) program, with the money invested in T. Rowe Price's
Mid-Cap and Science and Technology funds. I also have both taxable
and tax-deferred portfolios. The taxable account includes $22,000
in Seligman's Michigan Municipal Tax Exempt fund, $3,300 in
Seligman Common Stock, $8,000 in Kemper High-Yield, $3,000 in
Kemper Small-Cap, and $12,000 in Kemper US Government Bond funds.
In an IRA portfolio I have $7,500 in Putnam Growth and Income and
$27,000 in Putnam Voyager funds. Do you think I am being too
conservative with my Seligman and Kemper investments? Why do you
anticipate the funds will amount to in 10 years?
</P>
<P>
   P.R., Auburn Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, I would tend to think you're being too conservative, but
I also hesitate to suggest major changes. That's for several
reasons, but largely because conservative portfolios such as yours
tend to get that way on purpose, reflecting a limited appetite for
risk on the part of the owner. The thing that stands out to me is
that big position in the Seligman Michigan tax-exempt fund. Are you
sure that your tax bill is heavy enough so that this $22,000 is
working hard enough for you? With a 4.6 percent yield that's free
of both state and federal taxes, it seems attractive enough. But
its 10-year record of average annual total returns is 7.45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As alternatives, you might consider two funds that would
generate taxable distributions but that would also likely offer
considerably higher total returns. One is Seligman's Income fund, a
balanced offering with 36 percent of its assets in stocks and a 4.1
percent yield. Its 10-year total return is 10.49 percent. The
second is Seligman High Yield, a junk bond fund with a 10-year
record of 11.39 percent average annual total return and a current
yield of 9.9 percent. I think that if you examine your tax
situation closely, you'd find that you would be better off at the
end of a decade on an after-tax basis if you were to switch to one
of these funds and pay the tax liabilities that are inherent in
these holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Currently I calculate the fund portfolio is 49.3 percent
invested in stocks, which also seems like a conservative number.
While you don't give a balance for your 401(k), whatever the amount
is, and all of the substantial ongoing contributions, will be in
stocks, so the total portfolio probably is nowhere near as heavily
dominated by fixed-income issues as it appears from your list. And
as I said at the outset, conservative portfolios usually don't get
that way by accident, so if you're comfortable with this, I'd say
it's fine.
</P>
<P>
   As for a growth projection, if we use an estimate of 8 percent
average annual growth within the portfolio -- based upon
expectations of about 6 percent growth from the fixed income side
and about 10 percent from the stocks -- the estimated accumulation
would be $178,758. And presuming that youve just begun the 401(k),
if we estimate 10 percent average annual portfolio gains within the
account and $5,000 annual contributions, you would amass $83,329
over the course of a decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
