<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-CRUISES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: we didn't bother. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing that had our attention at that moment was what to
do next, and that is maybe the best thing about cruising as a
family: undivided quality time. No worries about dinner or driving
or cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Sea docked at Cozumel, Mexico and Roatan,
Honduras. Adventurous cruisers got the creative options: A jeep to
ride in the Mexican jungle (if you're over 6); Aztec ruins to climb
(not recommended for children); and dolphins to swim with (must be
8 or older).
</P>
<P>
   Some cruise lines have changed their shore excursions to
accommodate kids, and some even offer kids-only treks into Alaska
and on some islands. We learned to explore on our own, at Wilson's
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises can be affordable when you consider that meals, rooms
and entertainment are one fee. Most large lines treat children as a
``third passenger,'' meaning they are charged a rate, often $99 or
$199 per child, plus port charges, which vary.
</P>
<P>
   But the shore excursions can get pricey with children. The
Tropical Safari Jeep Tour was $68 a person, the Tulum Ruins tour
was $69, Dolphin Discovery was $87. It's another reason to try your
own thing.
</P>
<P>
   In Cozumel, we rented a taxi and took the Little Man into as
many discount jewelry stores as he could tolerate, then we sat on
the curb and watched college kids drunk on tequila navigate
scooters. Wilson was amused.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we found Chakannaab State Park and a shallow
lagoon of purple water, where Wilson spent hours combing a
limestone reef searching for blue-legged hermit crabs and
yellow-painted sea snails. It cost us $14 admission; Wilson got in
free.
</P>
<P>
   On Roatan _ a diver's secret for 20 years and now a cruise ship
destination 30 miles off the coast of Honduras _ we spent $38 each
(children 3 and under free) for a bumpy bus ride through the jungle
to a private resort named Tabyana Beach. We spent the day under
coconut trees, on pearly sand, beside a reef second in size to the
one off the coast of Australia. The water there was so clear that
Wilson could stand and watch while schools of silver-sided
angelfish swam around him.
</P>
<P>
   Years from now, he may not remember these little things. But we
will. And that's why we'd go again. And we'd take him along.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
