<HEADLINE>
GOP CONGRESS, CLINTON FACING NEW BUDGET STRUGGLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six weeks after approving a balanced federal budget
for fiscal 2000, Congress returned this week to a spending showdown
so bitter that it threatens another government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton accused Republican lawmakers of approving a
``blueprint for chaos'' that calls for deep cuts in domestic
programs to stay within the spending limits agreed to in the 1997
balanced-budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority budget plan is simply not realistic,'' Clinton
told reporters in the Rose Garden after a Cabinet meeting Thursday.
``It is a blueprint for chaos, and we can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked Congress to work with him on a bipartisan budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who spoke as lawmakers were taking their Memorial
Day vacation, added that a divided House has not passed any of the
13 appropriations bills that fund the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cuts would be so damaging that Congress itself to date
has been unwilling and unable to move some of the most basic and
normally noncontroversial spending bills out of their committee,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there seems to be no easy solution to the split between
Republicans and Democrats over spending priorities and between GOP
conservatives and moderates over adhering to the caps.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how Congress can cut more than $20 billion from
current spending to stick to the fiscal 2000 spending limit of $538
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that it is a lot easier to promise fiscal
restraint than it is to deliver on it,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, a deficit hawk for his entire congressional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is that we all committed to a fiscal
responsibility wedding, but now people are saying, `I don't want to
go down the aisle.'''
</P>
<P>
   When it returns, the House will try to jump-start the stalled
appropriations process. Just before the recess, it did not pass the
first of the 13 appropriations bills that will keep the government
operating after Oct. 1, the start of the new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this happening in a time of budget surplus?
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that ``every penny'' of this year's budget surplus of
more than $100 billion is from the surfeit in the Social Security
trust fund, setting up a conflict with anyone who wants to protect
the national retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that sticking to budget caps agreed to in the 1997
balanced budget deal, protecting Social Security by refusing to dip
into the fund, passing huge emergency spending bills and approving
tax cuts are incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem comes down to two words: spending caps. The caps
look a lot different from the vantage of surplus politics than the
perspective of deficit politics,'' said Marshall Wittmann, director
of congressional relations at the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's money to be spent, people in Washington want to
spend it,'' said Wittmann, a Waco native. ``Pigs are attracted to
slop. People in Fort Worth understand this.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Brookings Institution on Wednesday, Jacob
Lew, director of the Office of Management and Budget, complained
about the GOP plan to stay within the spending limit by boosting
defense and making deep cuts in popular domestic programs. He said
that the Labor, Health and Human Services and Education departments
would be cut by 18 percent from current levels.
</P>
<P>
   Lew said that the funding plans ``leave Congress with no
apparent alternative but to break the budget caps and spend the
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lew's advocacy of President Clinton's proposals to raise
money by increasing cigarette taxes and other fees has no GOP
support.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Lew's criticism, Gramm said, ``Other than the guy at
the top, he's the biggest double-talker in this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., ranking member on the House
Appropriations Committee, told reporters, ``We're headed for
another budget train wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the impasse over spending was so great that House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., ended up agreeing to a $20 billion
increase over the limits _ a move that enraged the conservative GOP
base.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the current House speaker's effort to move the
appropriations bills, Obey said, the speaker's ``problem is that if
they try to short-circuit the problem (by raising the caps), the
right-wingers won't abide it.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., got a taste of that
opposition before recess when a group of conservatives stalled the
appropriations bills with a slew of budget-cutting amendments to an
appropriations bill.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
