<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUPPIE-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUPPIE RALLY TURNS INTO ANTI-YUPPIE GATHERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A rally ostensibly organized to protect the
civil rights of yuppie newcomers to the Mission District of the
city apparently attracted just about everybody in the neighborhood
except the yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of about 200 Mission residents, responding angrily to an
advertisement for the ``Stop the Hate'' rally, gathered to defend
themselves against what some of them called false accusations by
wealthy newcomers buying up property in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Mission residents should demand an end to yuppie-led
gentrification of the neighborhood, said Van Jones, one leader of
the counter-rally.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was held Sunday on the very spot _ by Dolores
Park _ where the original Stop the Hate rally was to be held. It
was unclear whether the original Stop the Hate rally was a hoax or
if its sponsors _ purportedly groups such as Safe Parking for
Utility Vehicles Working Group _ simply decided not to show.
</P>
<P>
   The economic boom in the San Francisco Bay area and a shortage
of housing have caused prices for homes and apartments to soar,
pitting working-class people against the more affluent in a
competition for housing.
</P>
<P>
   No one appeared to be in charge of the counter-rally. At first
it resembled a large outdoor garden party where almost everyone was
chatting amicably and greeting neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Then someone produced a megaphone, and the speeches began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your ancestors came here to take our lands,'' shouted one
speaker, Cristianne Dugan-Cuadra, who identified herself as a
junior studying art at San Francisco State. ``We don't want you
riding your sports utility vehicles, showing off what you've got,
while kids in the Mission District aren't graduating because of
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   If any of the newcomers were around, they kept a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   The police monitored the demonstration and says there were no
fights or arrests.
</P>
<P>
   An advertisement for the rally that ran in the San Francisco
Weekly claimed that new residents of the Mission have been victims
of hate crimes and ``are treated with contempt and targeted by
vandals.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad listed a number of purported rally sponsors but gave no
addresses and listed only a single telephone number. On Sunday
after the rally, the phone number was answered by a recorded
message left by someone who called himself Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between older, lower-income Mission residents and
wealthy newcomers have grown in recent months, with the appearance
of fliers from a group calling itself the Mission Yuppie
Eradication Project. The fliers urged residents to destroy ``yuppie
bars and restaurants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
