<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETA BLOCKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the beta that beta blockers block?
</P>
<P>
   A. The drugs are mainstays in the treatment of high blood
pressure and cardiac problems that can follow a heart attack. The
beta blockers, which include propranol and atenolol, slow the
heartbeat, decrease blood pressure, normalize some irregular heart
rhythms and reduce the contraction force of the heart muscle. They
work by blocking the action of the hormones adrenaline and
norepinephrine, powerful stimulants that are released by the body
during stress or exercise and that raise blood pressure and tell
the heart to beat faster and pump harder.
</P>
<P>
   More technically called beta-adrenergic blockers, the drugs
actually block a class of chemical receptors called beta nerve
receptors on the surface of cells in the sympathetic nervous system
that help control the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Unblocked, these receptors, or attachment sites for molecules,
are where adrenaline and norepinephrine normally attach to the
cells and transmit chemical messages governing the heart.
</P>
<P>
   When the beta receptor sites are blocked so that the hormones
are limited in their action, a complex change takes place in the
heart's chemical responses, according to ``The Mayo Clinic Heart
Book.''
</P>
<P>
   As the heart rate, blood pressure and force of contraction drop,
the circulatory system's need for oxygen is reduced. That is
especially helpful in people whose oxygen supply is reduced by
circulatory system disease.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New
York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to: Question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
