A6097 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ESSAY-WAITINGROOM     06-07 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ESSAY-WAITINGROOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING WAITING ROOMS TO RUN ON TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crowd was growing larger and its mood was turning ugly.
People were muttering to each other, picking up magazines and
tossing them aside, checking their watches, snarling at the
personnel behind the check-in counter.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather at JFK? A train out of service at Penn Station? No,
actually, this was the scene a few weeks ago in the waiting room of
the medical clinic where I work, where one of the creakiest known
systems of human processing, health care in action, had temporarily
ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it was the arrival of a couple of sick people that
had jammed the works of a system intended to deal with sick people
should come as no surprise. Medical science can measure most things
these days, but one quantity remains eternally, enragingly
imprecise: how long doctors should take to do their work. The
single feat dangling permanently out of reach of the biomedical
revolution seems to be how to make the whole magnificent enterprise
run on time.
</P>
<P>
   And so waiting continues to be one of the great levelers of
health care. The lavishly insured do it and the totally uncovered
do it, on Park Avenue and at Bellevue they do it, for specialists
and for GP's, for emergencies and for checkups, for good care, bad
care, and occasionally for no care at all (``He's stuck in the OR.
Would you like to reschedule?'').
</P>
<P>
   Once, waiting was not considered a problem. The doctor's time
was of the essence; nobody else's mattered. The impoverished came
to the hospital dispensary early in the morning, a couple of
hundred at a time, and waited. The well-off came to office hours, a
handful at a time, and waited. Specific appointment times were
rare.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as efficiency, cost-effectiveness and consumer satisfaction
become prominent health care goals, the value of everyone's time is
getting a certain amount of lip service. Still some of the new
principles of patient flow might well apply to flipping burgers on
a fast-food grill. More patients mean more cash, after all, and
idle doctors mean money lost. Lavish overbooking can compensate for
costly broken appointments. The usual solution to an overbooked
waiting room and a sluggish cash flow alike: speed that doctor up.
</P>
<P>
   But the profit-making assembly line of health care never did run
smooth. A set of studies published in The Journal of Family
Practice last year showed that the more time a doctor spent with a
patient, the more satisfied with the visit the patient was,
particularly when the doctor took some time just to chat. Faster
doctors who saw more patients a day had less satisfied patients.
Their patients were also less likely to be up to date on
immunizations and important screening tests like mammograms.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that patients who are generally satisfied
with their doctors are less likely to sue if something goes wrong.
Surveys from around the world confirm that the single greatest
stressor for a medical provider in the course of the day's work is
to be behind schedule. No study is needed to show that stressed
doctors do not chat.
</P>
<P>
   And so hospitals, clinics and medical offices are now creating
schedules from complicated multivariate equations that balance
cash, stress, waiting time, no-show rates, patient satisfaction,
malpractice considerations, and just incidentally, the nature of
the health care dispensed.
</P>
<P>
   All the solutions are different. My clinic recently sliced our
allotted time with each patient down to 20 minutes. This was
intended to balance out a very high rate of broken appointments so
that each of us might do better at meeting a quota of 1.43 patients
per hour _ a modest demand, actually, considering a recent United
Hospital Fund study that clocked average physician speed in New
York City at 1.9 to 3.1 patients per hour.
</P>
<P>
   On some days the new system is fine: The right number of
appointments are broken and everyone chats up a storm. On other
days the world pours in, with appointments and without, each
patient more complicated and time-consuming than the last. These
are the days of near-riot in the waiting room as doctors register
ear-popping sonic boom speeds _ 3.2, 4.7, 5.3 patients per hour.
Those hours are chat-free.
</P>
<P>
   Some patients are calling ahead now for the equivalent of a
highway traffic report. Down the hall, one of my colleagues has
stopped looking at her watch and just hopes for the best. Another
is trying to reset her internal odometer with the help of an oven
timer perched on her desk. When it dings, she winds things up.
</P>
<P>
   A third is a true subversive at heart. She works slowly, and is
rumored to lock her door on occasion, and turn off the volume on
her phone. I happen to know that she has an immersion heater and a
large stash of tea bags in a desk drawer. It gives me a certain
pleasure to imagine that sometimes when things are bad out there in
the waiting room _ the crowds howling, the receptionists pleading,
the accusations and apologies flowing thick and fast _ inside her
examining room all is serene as doctor and patient methodically
sort through a lifetime of problems over a cup of tea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6098 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FINCH-FEEDBACK-NY     06-07 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FINCH-FEEDBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ZEBRA FINCH: A SONGBIRD THAT WORKS A LIFETIME TO KEEP ITS SONG
ON KEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among songbirds, the zebra finch is a one-hit wonder. It learns
a tune in its youth, and then is condemned to repeat it forever,
like an aging pop star on the oldies circuit.
</P>
<P>
   But while it might be thought that having to perform, say,
``Billy Don't Be a Hero'' every night could lead to a certain
hardening of the synapses, adult zebra finches maintain flexibility
in the brain. In fact, according to a new study, that's how they
keep in shape musically.
</P>
<P>
   A young zebra finch learns through auditory feedback, listening
to its own sounds and comparing them to a song in its head until it
gets it right. Little has been known about how a mature finch, a
``closed learner'' (compared to a canary, for example, which learns
new tunes all the time) maintains its song. But earlier studies
with deafened adult finches have suggested that they use feedback
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The new research, by Anthony Leonardo, a graduate student at the
California Institute of Technology, further explores the role of
feedback, not by deafening birds but by confusing them. Leonardo
developed a computer-controlled system for recording a finch as it
sings and then playing back certain notes in time-lagged fashion.
So a bird hears a jumble of notes: its own song out of its beak,
plus the playback from a loudspeaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a couple of weeks to months, you get very dramatic
changes in the songs,'' Leonardo said. Some notes were discarded,
new ones created and others distorted. Most of all, the birds
started to stutter, repeating the same note over and over. ``To a
human, it sounds kind of like a broken record,'' said Leonardo, who
described his results in the journal Nature. Once the confusing
feedback was removed, the birds' songs returned to normal over a
period of months.
</P>
<P>
   What might be happening, Leonardo said, is that adult birds are
using feedback in much the same way that young birds do, comparing
it to what they intended to sing. ``But we're putting an error
signal into the song, and they go about correcting things, and it
just gets worse and worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that the birds are not doing any error
correction at all, but rather using the feedback of one note to
prepare the next. In this case, hearing a faulty note would produce
another faulty one: garbage in, garbage out.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the experiments show that while a zebra finch might
be a one-trick pony, it is far from a dullard, retaining a large
degree of flexibility in the brain. ``The system is quite dynamic,
even in adulthood,'' Leonardo said. Perhaps graying pop stars could
take heart: it's never too late to develop a new song and hit the
comeback trail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
