</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EXERTION-SYNDROME-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINFUL MUSCLE PROBLEM SEEN IN ATHLETIC WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass., Ill., W.Va.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By JANIS GRAHAM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Jasmine Belanger, the mysterious leg pain started about a
year and a half ago, after she had been running regularly for six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Every time she approached a distance of four miles, the muscle
in her lower right calf would start to throb, quickly becoming
excruciatingly painful.
</P>
<P>
   The peculiar thing about the pain was that it completely
vanished within minutes after she stopped running, leaving no
residual ache. And it never occurred when she cycled, did the
Stairmaster or played tennis or volleyball. Repeatedly, Ms.
Belanger, 31, a New York City investment banker, tried to ``run
through'' the discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe I was just being wimpy, that it was a matter
of no pain, no gain,'' she said. ``But I couldn't do it. Once the
throbbing started, it was impossible to continue running.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Ms. Belanger consulted four different sports
podiatrists, who prescribed remedies for flat feet, weak muscles
and a leg-length discrepancy. But whenever she resumed running, the
pain came back.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Belanger's symptoms, she discovered two months ago after
consulting an orthopedic surgeon, turned out to be typical of
chronic exertional compartment syndrome or CECS, a problem that
most frequently occurs in the legs of runners and soccer players
but also in the forearms of kayakers, canoeists, rowers and
gymnasts. Bodybuilders and athletes who use anabolic steroids also
appear to be at increased risk for CECS.
</P>
<P>
   With the syndrome, the fascia, inelastic tissue that creates a
compartment around a muscle, is too small to accommodate the muscle
when it expands during exercise. As a result, pressure builds up in
the overly tight compartment, compressing nerves, cutting off blood
and oxygen supplies to the area, and, consequently, causing pain.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1997 Australian study, as many as 3 percent of
athletes who seek the services of a sports medicine clinic have the
syndrome. Although statistics are not available for this country,
many U.S. experts think it is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to 10 or 15 years ago, there is no question that we
are seeing it much more frequently,'' said Dr. Mark R. Hutchinson,
an orthopedic surgeon at the University of Illinois in Chicago. He
recently wrote about CECS for the journal The Physician and Sports
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Among women, in particular, the problem of the syndrome may be
growing, according to a review of CECS studies from 1967 to the
present that was published in a recent issue of The American
Journal of Sports Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The chief author, Dr. Lyle J. Micheli of Children's Hospital in
Boston, noted that in his own practice he treated only eight women
for the syndrome from 1980 to 1989, while he saw 45 women with the
problem from 1990 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This rise is explained in part by increased participation of
women in sports. ``But we also suspect that women are more
susceptible to compartment syndrome than men, although we don't yet
know why this would be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, it takes people anywhere from one to two years to get
a correct diagnosis. ``I think CECS is often missed because many in
the medical community don't know to differentiate between different
types of leg pain,'' Hutchinson said. ``Everything is shin
splints.''
</P>
<P>
   Shin splints, a common problem among runners, occurs when the
tendons attached to the bones of the lower leg become inflamed and
irritated.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that distinguishes CECS from other leg
complaints is ``the leg is rarely tender and seems normal when
examined,'' explained Dr. Jo Hannafin, orthopedic director of the
Women's Sports Medicine Center at the Hospital for Special Surgery
in New York. ``Another hallmark of CECS is that symptoms vanish
completely in a matter of minutes once the activity is stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most athletes can engage in a variety of other
sports with no trouble; only activities like running or rowing,
which put nonstop, repetitive pressure on the muscle compartments,
trigger symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The gold standard test for the syndrome is compartment pressure
testing, Hutchinson said. A large needle attached to a small device
that measures pressure is inserted into the muscle, then readings
are taken before and after exercise. If pressure readings are
abnormally high, it is a definitive diagnosis of CECS.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent small study, massage and stretching may
help some athletes exercise for a longer period before pain sets
in, but only surgery has been shown to cure the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves athletes with the condition with the choice of
discontinuing the activity that causes the pain or having a
fasciotomy, surgery that slices through the fascia and releases the
muscle so it can expand freely, Micheli said.
</P>
<P>
   Performed through small incisions, the surgery is usually done
in a hospital under local or general anesthesia, and the patient
goes home the same day. The rate of success for fasciotomies in the
leg range from 75 percent to 95 percent, according to studies.
</P>
<P>
   Data on fasciotomies to the forearm are scarce, but most experts
believe the arm operation is ``just as effective as it is for the
legs,'' said Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   Full recovery takes at least six weeks. Ms. Belanger, who had a
fasciotomy in her right leg two months ago, has already begun
running.
</P>
<P>
   Her motivation: ``I wanted to be a senior citizen who gets up at
six in the morning and goes for a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, however, question the need for recreational
athletes like Ms. Belanger to have surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``CECS is a benign condition,'' said Dr. David Humphries, an
Australian sports medicine physician who wrote an article on the
syndrome for the medical Web site Medscape (www.medscape.com). ``I
think people who are not elite athletes would be better advised to
take up a different sport than to go through all the nonsense of
compartment pressure testing and surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some do well with the advice to cross-train,'' said Dr.
Randall R. Swain, clinical associate professor of family and sports
medicine at the West Virginia University School of Medicine in
Charleston. ``But if you know most runners, then you know most
won't quit if there is a surgery that can help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6135 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-INTERNET-RESEARCH     06-07 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INTERNET-RESEARCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO SHOULD PUBLISH RESEARCH RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Wis., N.M., N.Y., Ore., N.D.)   (af)  
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The director of the National Institutes of Health
has touched off a passionate debate by proposing that scientists
disclose and disseminate on the Internet the results of biomedical
research, so the full text of their reports would be available at
no cost to anyone with a computer anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Dr. Harold E. Varmus, said his proposal for an
electronic publishing operation, called E-biomed, would speed the
progress of science by accelerating the exchange of information
among researchers and by vastly increasing access to it.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, the proposed new Web site could be ``a
democratizing force'' because any legitimate researchers, ``however
remotely located or poorly known,'' could enter reports on it.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say they hope to coordinate their Web site
with the established scientific journals, some of which have begun
electronic publishing in a limited way. But the publishers of
scholarly journals, including many scientific societies, are
predictably cool to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   They say the new system would permit researchers to bypass paper
journals and circumvent the process of peer review, by which
scientists evaluate new work before it is published, and they fear
that the NIH will become a rival that could put them out of the
publishing business or slash the revenues they derive from their
journals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jerome P. Kassirer, editor in chief of The New England
Journal of Medicine, which has 240,000 paid subscribers, said,
``E-biomed could have a disastrous effect on clinical journals.''
He worries that ``subscribers would have no reason for
subscribing'' if they could get the contents of journals free on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal is owned and published by the
Massachusetts Medical Society. It has for years had a strict policy
against publishing manuscripts whose ``essential substance'' has
been published elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society for Microbiology, which publishes 10
scholarly journals, and the American Physiological Society, which
has 14, express similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Today's scientific journals trace their ancestry to The
Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society, in England, and
the Journal des Scavants, in France. Both began publishing in 1665,
with a commitment to test scientific ideas by the experimental
method.
</P>
<P>
   In the 300 years since the gold standard of scientific
communication has the publication of a paper that has been reviewed
by expert colleagues, in a scientific journal.
</P>
<P>
   Varmus proposed two compartments or divisions for the new Web
site. Articles published in the first compartment would be subject
to scientific review by members of the editorial boards of various
journals. This is the process of peer review used for decades by
The New England Journal of Medicine, The Journal of the American
Medical Association, Science, Nature, Cell, Lancet and dozens of
other journals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, or as an alternative, Varmus said, reports could be
posted immediately on the Internet, ``prior to any conventional
peer review.''
</P>
<P>
   For their work to be disseminated in this way, Varmus said,
researchers would need to get approval from ``two individuals with
appropriate credentials.'' Such credentials, he said, ``should be
broad enough to include several thousands of scientists, but
stringent enough to provide protection of the data base from
extraneous or outrageous material.''
</P>
<P>
   Varmus described this compartment of E-biomed as a ``general
repository.'' And he said ``virtually any legitimate work'' could
be posted there ``without traditional editorial review.''
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists say, however, that E-biomed could confuse or
alarm consumers by disseminating unverified information and ``junk
science'' not reviewed by experts in the field. They acknowledge
that Web users already have access to a huge amount of medical and
scientific information of widely varying quality, but they say it
is different when the government tries to organize a system for
publishing and distributing it.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Michael M. Cox, a biochemist at the University of
Wisconsin in Madison, said, ``The publication of an electronic
journal, supported by the NIH, as described in the Varmus proposal,
is among the very worst ideas I have ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is not subject to careful peer review, ``it will
inevitably become a massive repository of taxpayer-supported
junk,'' Cox said. ``Since it will be supported or sponsored in some
way by the NIH, it will be perceived as being legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal gets strong support from Rep. John Edward
Porter, R-Ill., who is chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee responsible for the budget of the health institutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``NIH is providing wonderful leadership to the scientific
community in encouraging use of the Internet to share
information,'' Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   Subscription prices, especially for highly technical journals
sold by large commercial publishers, have risen sharply in recent
years. Libraries pay $10,000 to $15,000 a year for titles on some
subjects like brain research.
</P>
<P>
   E-biomed, as envisioned by Varmus, would offer ``instantaneous,
cost-free access'' to research reports on biology and medicine,
thus saving money for individual scientists, libraries,
laboratories and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Physicists and mathematicians already post many of their
findings, prior to publication in a journal, on a Web site operated
by the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico (xxx.lanl.gov).
But doctors say that biomedical research, especially clinical
research, is different because it can influence the care and
treatment of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Frank, executive director of the American Physiological
Society, which publishes more than 35,000 pages a year in its
journals, said a patient could be injured or killed if a doctor
prescribed a certain course of treatment based on unverified
information posted on the proposed E-biomed site.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard M. Glass, interim co-editor of The Journal of the
American Medical Association, said articles ``often get changed
very extensively'' as they go through the review process. Because
authors are enthusiastic about their work, he said, they often draw
conclusions that go beyond the data, and they may see new
treatments as being more effective than they really are.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, supporters of E-biomed say it could make
valuable information swiftly available to doctors, patients,
researchers and the taxpayers who pay for much of the research.
</P>
<P>
   Charles V. Mobbs, an associate professor of neurobiology at the
Mount Sinai School of Medicine, in New York City, said, ``The
taxpayer is willing to pay for our research; we have an obligation
to make the results of that research available as quickly and
efficiently as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobbs praised Varmus' proposal, saying it could ``revolutionize
the way in which biomedical scientists carry out their work.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, in the electronic version of their
reports, scientists could include film sequences, three-dimensional
images and large sets of data for which there is no space in
printed journals. This would presumably make it easier for other
scientists to replicate and build on the results.
</P>
<P>
   Varmus said that all reports filed in E-biomed could be searched
with a single computerized ``search engine,'' and readers could
jump electronically, by ``hyperlinks,'' to other articles, data
bases and Web sites. In addition, he said, E-biomed could become
``a communal site'' for worldwide discussion of scientific issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-biomed could be the most important change in scientific
communication since the formal journal,'' Dr. David J. Lipman, a
co-author of the proposal for electronic publishing, said in an
interview. Referring to NIH's new $15.6 billion budget, he added,
``We want to get the greatest public benefit in return for that $15
billion investment. We want the most possible eyes to see the
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipman is director of the National Center for Biotechnology
Information, a unit of the National Library of Medicine at the NIH.
</P>
<P>
   In outlining the proposal last month, Varmus said, ``The single
greatest attraction of E-biomed is that all of its scientific
content will be available without barriers to any user with
Internet access.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the proposal profess not to be alarmed at the
potential distribution of ``junk science'' over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One researcher who sent an e-mail comment to the NIH, Dr. Bruce
Swanson of Adelaide, Australia, drew an analogy to the spread of
literacy and printing technology in medieval Europe. ``Were all
books going to be authoritative and accurate?'' he asked. ``Were
some dangerous to society? We can imagine priests saying, `Mass
printing and wide dissemination of books is OK so long as we insure
that every book is approved by a priest review process.'''
</P>
<P>
   Other commenters worry that E-biomed would expand the role and
power of the government. ``I am adamantly opposed to any federal
clearinghouse for scientific information,'' said David H. Farrell,
an associate professor of oral molecular biology at the Oregon
Health Sciences University, in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence P. Reynolds, a professor of reproductive physiology at
North Dakota State University, in Fargo, said: ``It's intrusive for
the government to play the role it's proposing. More than that,
it's unnecessary. Journals are already beginning to publish reports
in electronic format.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Reynolds acknowledged, in many cases, the full text of
articles is available only to paid subscribers or to consumers who
pay a special fee.
</P>
<P>
   E-biomed, as described by Varmus, would have a ``governing
board'' composed of scientists, editors, computer specialists and
representatives of agencies that finance biomedical research. The
NIH would ``assemble'' the board, which in turn would develop
``rules of operation'' for the E-biomed site, Varmus said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, of the American Physiological Society, said he worried
that the choice of board members might be influenced by politics,
and that appointments might have to be cleared through the
department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and critics of E-biomed agree that something like it
is probably inevitable. ``Scientific communication is going to go
electronic,'' said Anthony J. Mazzaschi of the Association of
American Medical Colleges. ``It's just a question of when and
how.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
