<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-0608     06-07 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MACEDONIAN VILLAGE SHELLED AT SAME TIME KOSOVO TALKS COLLAPSED
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0608.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAZINCE, Macedonia _ Monday was the latest of the dark days for
refugee Xhemil Ismani, who woke up with his bags packed to go back
home to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   First, he heard on BBC radio that NATO's negotiations with
Yugoslav generals to end the fighting in Kosovo had collapsed
overnight. Then, he discovered the war had expanded to breach his
safe haven here in Macedonia, with the shelling of this Macedonian
village from Serb-held Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have some few last bombs to spend. They know this
is a war they are losing. Now they are trying to destroy everything
that is Albanian -- the houses, the people, the children,
everything,'' said Ismani, 41, an English teacher who had come to
see if friends here made it safely through the attack. He lives a
few miles down the road with a family who
</P>
<P>
   gave him refuge in nearby Tetovo.
</P>
<P>
   The assault on Macedonia was a shocking rarity. While
Yugoslavia's Serb-controlled military have repeatedly attacked
positions next door in Albania where the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army is quartered, Yugoslavia has tried not to fray its more
friendly relations with Macedonia -- which has absorbed nearly a
quarter-million of Kosovo's ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the attack was an angry, unsanctioned outburst by rogue
Serb soldiers, or a calculated message related to the collapse of
peace talks, the two events did happen almost simultaneously at
about 3 a.m. (local time) Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ismani was among the score or more of people drawn to this
normally subdued rural village Monday afternoon to gawk at the
holes in roofs, shrapnel-pocked walls and two-foot-wide dents in
the earth made by the ordnance that Macedonian police here believe
was fired from a Serb military outpost just over the border. No
injuries were reported, though several houses were hit.
</P>
<P>
   Ismani, who had hoped the talks would make it safe to go home
within days, was frustrated at seeing his planned return to the
Kosovo town of Urosevac aborted. And the Macedonian villagers here
were fretting that they might have to become refugees, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a chance, I would find a safer place for my
children,'' said Mustafa Abdiseljam, 56, whose red tile roof was
disfigured by a blackened hole about a yard in diameter.
Fortunately for his family of 12, the explosive blew into an
unoccupied second-floor sitting room.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the failure of the talks was related to the attack
on this ethnic Albanian village, a simple place where horses draw
haycarts down narrow bricked streets and many make do without
indoor plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a demand to stop the war in Kosovo. The next thing
we know, Macedonian villages are being bombed,'' said Abdiseljam,
who showed journalists the sitting room where wooden roof beams had
crashed onto floor cushions. Intricate needle-point renditions of
flower bouquets were intact on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to tell a journalist where his family would sleep
Monday night. ``I'm afraid Serb forces will come here and massacre
my family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other villagers and refugees said this is just one more example
of how the Serb-dominated Yugoslav leadership and Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic can never be trusted. They voiced
doubts that Yugoslavia will live up to any agreement and fears that
Macedonia will be drawn into fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Serbs are lying. Even if they sign a (peace)
document, they will do the same things,'' said Enver Tusha, whose
family has been staying in a house next door to Abdiseljam's. His
family ran outside when the first explosion hit, and Tusha said he
saw the explosives arrive in a low arc from the direction of the
Yugoslav military outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Besim Nesimi, commander of the border police here, said all
evidence points to the Serbs as launching the attack, but he
refused to detail the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no room for thinking,'' he said. ``I am sure of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
