<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-BLACKS-TAXIS-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI CAB COMPANY TRAVELS WHERE OTHERS FEAR TO TRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ On a slow Sunday morning, with a warm rain drumming
softly against the iron awnings of the last taxi company in Liberty
City, Al Hooks and Charles Richardson stood on a sidewalk and
counted off the men who were shot to death while driving for
Society Cab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Pollack, got killed at 85th Street and 14th Court, and
King Ballard, on 82d Street and 15th Street,'' said Hooks, a
manager and 30-year veteran at Society Cab who was shot in the
stomach in a robbery in 1984. ``Pinkney, at 83rd and 14th Avenue.
He called for help. And Mereday, 31st and 59th. And Willie Jackson,
924d and 334d. Henley Beecham was the last one, January, 17th and
51st Street.''
</P>
<P>
   The men could not recall all the names of the drivers who were
killed in robberies in the last 20 years. But being cab drivers,
they remembered the cross-streets. ``There might be another one,''
said Hooks, glancing at Richardson for help.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who has been shot in the shoulder and stabbed in the
chest with an ice pick in his 40 some-odd years of driving for
Society, shook his head. ``More than I care to remember,'' he said.
Then, for a moment, there was only the thump of rain and a ringing
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxi service,'' answered the dispatcher, Mattie Hunter, like
there was nothing special about it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Society Cab has become more than a taxi ride in some of Miami's
black communities. In a part of the city where taxi drivers must
carry change for a quarter because even a dime is more than most
people can tip, the drivers are the only ones who regularly answer
calls in Miami's harshest neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a piece of county legislation may do what gunfire could
not. In response to constant complaints from tourists that
Miami-Dade taxis are old, ugly and filthy, the county commission
has enacted a new taxi law that could gradually do away with older
cabs like the ones in Society's fleet of 23.
</P>
<P>
   In a neighborhood where people labor for minimum wage and taxi
drivers regularly settle for what people have in their pockets,
drivers cannot afford new taxis. Society's drivers have asked for
an exemption, but county officials have balked so far, but were
expected to consider that exemption this week. Without it, say the
drivers, Society will fade from existence.
</P>
<P>
   The black and mint-green cabs have been running for 50 years,
through riots and gang warfare, serving Liberty City, Overtown,
Opa-Locka, Carol City and other places, an area of tens of
thousands of people where gunfire is sometimes more consistent than
bus service, and crime is the cross people bear. They do it to make
a living, said drivers who work here, and because this is their
home, too. It may seem like a battle zone, but it is also a place
where mothers work two jobs, where old people go to church, said
Richardson. He knows, because he drives them there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people here could do better, they wouldn't live here, but
they are here,'' said the 61-year-old Richardson. ``What are the
good people gonna do if we're not here? The other cab companies,
they don't even come out here.''
</P>
<P>
   The tourists who complained about taxis have almost certainly
never ridden in a Society cab. These cabs do not work the airports,
do not travel across the causeways to Miami Beach. They work 79th
Street and Little Haiti, and a dozen housing projects known only by
their street names, like Pork 'n' Bean Project, and an area people
here just call the Graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 40 or so drivers at Society Cab, the only black-owned,
black-operated taxi company in Miami-Dade County, most have been
shot or been shot at, or stabbed, or choked. Some, like Richardson,
still have the bullet inside them, and some, like Hooks, have left
bullets inside other people. At least 90 percent of them have been
robbed, and many cabs are dented from thrown rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin ``Dark 'n' Lovely'' Scott holds the record for bullet
wounds among Society cabbies, with nine. His wounds forced him into
semi-retirement.
</P>
<P>
   All the drivers, women and men, are black. The only Hispanic
driver to ever work for Society was robbed and locked in the trunk
of his car, in his first week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been shot,'' said 62-year-old Daniel Ponder. ``But
I did have to shoot a man once.'' Most drivers are armed, because
they work too hard, they say, to give their earnings over to a
crackhead with a dime-store knife.
</P>
<P>
   Often, they get calls from other cab companies, saying they have
a fare who wants to go to Liberty City or elsewhere in the inner
city. ``The other company takes them to Biscayne Boulevard,'' the
bayside street that a great many Miamians regard as a sort of fence
between safety and risk, Hooks said. ``We take them from there.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   They see themselves not so much as cab drivers as ferrymen,
carrying their fares along treacherous rivers of asphalt, avoiding
the street corners where chunks of concrete and bullets fly out of
nowhere. Over time, the taxi service has become such a respected
part of the community that mothers trust drivers to take their
children to grandmothers, day care, schools and, sometimes, the
emergency room at Jackson Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers routinely work for just a promise of payment, or
part of it. On a recent weekend, veteran driver Clyde Bain drove a
young woman more than 40 blocks to her data-processing job in North
Miami, fighting a downpour and wildly weaving traffic on Interstate
95. The meter showed $17.50. He took $17, no tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know her. She works. She has kids,'' said Bain, a native of
the Bahamas whose daughter will graduate from the University of
Miami this spring. ``If she's making minimum wage,'' he said of his
fare, ``then this ride cost her three hours work.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Fasze, 19, gets off work at her job in a North Miami
office at 4:30 a.m. ``I can't get a ride home from the other
companies,'' she said. ``They're afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   A bus ride would take three or four hours, and no one, said
Bain, stands at a bus stop in inner-city Miami at 4:30 in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   He has been robbed just twice, but two drivers have died in cabs
he owned. It seems like too much risk for too little reward, but
Bain said that is a matter of perspective. People who live in
safer, nicer worlds, he said, would see it as foolish. But he has
raised a family with dignity, and every day the wheels of his taxi
turn, they bring other working people closer to that dignity.
</P>
<P>
   The sad truth, he said, is that most Miamians will not miss the
drivers if they are put out of business, because they do not know
they exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never see an area like this,'' said the 56-year-old Bain,
who has been driving for 20 years. ``They hit the expressway and
pass us by. They don't know that there are hard-working people,
trying to raise kids, to just eat. They think everybody out here is
trying to rob and steal.''
</P>
<P>
   His cab splashes through the heart of Liberty City, through
streets lined with tiny homes with postage-stamp yards, past
abandoned stores, past store-front churches with spray-painted
crosses and one that offers in neat letters, ``The Way, The Truth,
The Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not seem like a lot,'' he said, referring to the
struggle he sees going on here, and his role in it. ``But it is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The company pre-dates this new, troubled Miami.
</P>
<P>
   It began in 1949, Hooks said, with a ``phone on a post,''
outside the now-closed Cafe Society on Northwest 20th Street and
Third Avenue. From then into the 1960s, Miami's black neighborhoods
rang with music from high-end dance clubs, where Cab Calloway
shouted ``Hidie-Hidie-Hey,'' and Sammy Davis Jr. danced in a haze
of cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Society Cab was part of it. Its original owners painted a top
hat, cane and white gloves on their doors, promising that ``before
you can get your hat, cane and gloves, the cab is there,'' Hooks
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was Cafe Society, Harlem Square, Rockland Palace, Sir
John's, the Mary Elizabeth, the Night Beat,'' all gone, Hooks said.
``The riots killed them.''
</P>
<P>
   They folded in the violence that would become shorthand for
Overtown and Liberty City, for decades. First there were the riots
after the killing of Martin Luther King Jr., in 1968, the McDuffie
riots _ sparked by the killing of a black man by the police _ in
the 1980s, and the more recent drug wars that left gang members and
innocent bystanders bleeding in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   All the other black-owned cab companies folded. Buses ran only
when it was safe. But Society kept running, Hooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Crack cocaine changed everything in the mid-1980s, as it did in
other inner cities, as addicts fed their habits with anything they
could steal. Society's cabs became targets, and life in the
driver's seat of the Ford Crown Victorias and Chevrolet Caprices
became much cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   On Mother's Day 1994, three young men climbed into Al Hooks' cab
at 14th and 65th. He drove awhile, until one man shoved a gun at
him and said, ``OK, Papa, give it up,'' Hooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he said, ``we had a confrontation. He shot me once in
the stomach. I shot him in the chest. Bullet ripped me all open.''
</P>
<P>
   In the trauma unit, the police asked him if he could describe
his adversary. ``I looked over beside me and said, `There he is.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The man was lying next to him.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's most terrifying attack was in 1970, when a man who
sat in the back seat mumbling to himself reached across the seat,
circled an arm around his throat and drove an ice pick into his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   The two men fought in the cab, then out the door, with the car
still rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought in the street,'' said Richardson, who finally got to
his radio and called for help. He did not call the police, but the
cab company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family,'' explained Hooks.
</P>
<P>
   The cabs swarmed there. They did it when Al Hooks went down in
1984, and when Franklin ``Dark 'n' Lovely'' Scott was shot last
year. They even carried him to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the drivers tend to pick up people they
know by sight, or by address. Many of them pass strangers by, and
pick up passengers who have grown old with the company, or at least
grown familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers like Hooks and Bain are proud that their hard work
paved the way for a better life for their families, but they like
to believe it gives others, people they know only by address, a
push in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they have been scarred too often, by bullets and rocks and
ice picks, to have romantic notions of their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But if they did not believe they were doing something grander,
something deeper, the drivers said, there would be no reason to
risk so much for a $4 fare that pays $3.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
