<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEVELAND-ORCHESTRA-N     06-07 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEVELAND-ORCHESTRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HIGH-STAKES MUSICAL CHAIRS, AS ORCHESTRAS SEEK NEW LEADERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cleveland Orchestra announced on Monday that Franz
Welser-Moest would become its music director in 2002 on the
departure of Christoph von Dohnanyi, who has held that position
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Dohnanyi, who is 69 and is also the principal conductor of the
Philharmonia Orchestra of London, revealed two years ago that he
intended to resign, saying he wanted to give the orchestra time to
make an orderly transition. Welser-Moest, a 38-year-old Austrian,
has been the music director of the Zurich Opera since 1995 and was
the music director of the London Philharmonic from 1990 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the Cleveland Orchestra, on the eve of the annual
conference of the American Symphony Orchestra League, which begins
on Wednesday in Chicago, is the first out of the blocks in a race
among several top ensembles in the United States and abroad to snap
up the choice candidates in what is considered a limited field.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Orchestra is looking to replace Wolfgang
Sawallisch, who announced a decision similar to Dohnanyi's but
plans to stay until a successor is in place. The New York
Philharmonic has impressed its own desire for an orderly transition
on Kurt Masur, whose current contract expires in 2002. The Berlin
Philharmonic, meanwhile, in its search for a successor to Claudio
Abbado in 2002, is said to have refined the list of candidates to
Daniel Barenboim and Sir Simon Rattle, with Barenboim expected to
carry the vote this month.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's choice is sure to raise the perennial issue of the
paucity of American music directors among major American
orchestras. ``We were looking for somebody well grounded in the
classical traditions of this orchestra as well as someone to lead
it into 21st century,'' said Thomas W. Morris, the orchestra's
executive director. ``That was the sum total of the requirements.
Being an American was not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Orchestra has employed more American conductors
than most in recent decades, with Lorin Maazel the music director
from 1972 to 1982 and Leonard Slatkin the director of its Blossom
Festival from 1991 through this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Welser-Moest's appointment comes as no surprise. He was said to
be a candidate for the music directorship of the St. Louis
Symphony, assumed by Hans Vonk in 1996, and his name has arisen in
speculation about Cleveland and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But Welser-Moest's most closely analogous experience, with the
London Philharmonic, was far from untroubled. Though widely
respected as a musician, he was scarred by administrative battles
in a tense and politicized atmosphere as the city's five major
orchestras jockeyed for adequate shares of shrinking financing. The
London Philharmonic was in particular administrative disarray, and
no successor to Welser-Moest was announced until last November,
when Masur was named principal conductor as of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Cleveland offered me the job, I was more than thrilled,''
Welser-Moest said on Monday. ``The Cleveland Orchestra has always
been very special.''
</P>
<P>
   He has committed, in a five-year contract, to spend 16 to 18
weeks a season with the orchestra, some 50 percent more than
Dohnanyi does now. He plans to curtail his activity at the Zurich
Opera, where his contract calls for two new productions and 35
performances a season, he said. ``At the moment,'' he added, ``I am
fulfilling that contract exactly 200 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   So with one seat suddenly occupied in a high-stakes game of
musical chairs, the Cleveland Orchestra has undoubtedly set the
agenda for informal discussion at the conference in Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
