<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6187 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-TUMOR-DRILL-ART-N     06-07 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TUMOR-DRILL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRILL-LIKE MECHANISM IN SPREAD OF TUMORS IS REVEALED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., N.C.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A delicate but destructive machine, a kind of molecular power
drill deployed by tumors to punch their way through the body's
compartments, has been visualized for the first time by biologists
at Sweden's Karolinska Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The power drill exists not for the benefit of tumors, though
they exploit it, but for normal remodeling of the tough walls that
surround the body's main organs and tissues. The wall, a matrix
made mostly of collagen fibers, needs to be degraded from time to
time: when the organism is growing or when wounds have to be
repaired. So cells known as fibroblasts, which also make the
matrix, are equipped with a miniature power drill for busting holes
in it.
</P>
<P>
   This tool has long been of interest to cancer biologists because
it provides the escape mechanism for tumors to spread from one part
of the body to another. Tumor cells intent on breaking out from the
organ where they originate can apparently trick the fibroblast
cells into their matrix destruction mode.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the body's molecular machines, the power drill is a
protein woven from a single ribbon of atoms. The ribbon is
precisely coiled and pleated in ways that confer specialized roles
on each of its separate regions or domains.
</P>
<P>
   The precise anatomy of the power drill protein has been brought
to light by Dr. Karl Tryggvason of the Karolinska Institute in
Stockholm, together with colleagues there and at the University of
Exeter in England. From their work, published in Science, the main
components of the miniature machine can be recognized, although
much remains to be understood about its operation.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly for so destructive a device, the machine has a
guard plate that shrouds its active center. Only when the guard
plate is cut away can the machine chew up matrix. Next is the
active center, which is not literally a drill but rather a
specialized catalytic device for cutting collagen.
</P>
<P>
   Further along the ribbon are three regions known as fibronectin
domains. Their purpose is not known for sure but they may serve as
claws to bring the collagen fiber to the active center.
</P>
<P>
   At the tail end of the ribbon is a complex domain that seems in
part to be the machine's off-switch because it is activated by
substances that are known to shut the power drill down. But the
domain may also have a role in helping to home in on the collagen
fibers.
</P>
<P>
   The power drill protein is secreted, in inert form, by the
fibroblasts, but these cells carry on their surface a cutting
device that activates the protein by severing its guard plate area.
</P>
<P>
   Tryggvason said he became interested in the protein 20 years ago
when trying to understand how a spreading tumor managed to cross
the matrix wall. Working as a postdoctoral student at the National
Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md., he and a colleague first
purified the protein in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   It is known to biologists as matrix metalloproteinase-2, metallo
referring to the zinc atom that is part of its collagen-chewing
maw, and 2 because it is part of a family of 16 proteins that
remold connective tissue. The specialty of matrix
metalloproteinase-2 is chewing up collagen IV, the type of collagen
that is the main component of the extracellular matrix.
</P>
<P>
   To visualize the protein's working parts, Tryggvason had to make
it form regular crystals that could be X-rayed so as to reveal the
twists and turns of its backbone ribbon. Biologists have been
trying to snap the protein's X-ray picture for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely difficult to crystallize,'' Tryggvason said.
The reason is that the protein is not only good at chewing up
collagen but chews itself up too. Many attempts to make crystals
triggered the self-destruct mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   Tryggvason succeeded by synthesizing a mutant form of the human
protein, one in which the active center was permanently disarmed by
making a minute change in the DNA of the gene that specifies its
structure.
</P>
<P>
   Other metalloproteinases are also involved in the breakout of
tumors, and drugs that inhibit them have been developed as an
anti-cancer strategy. But patients developed serious side effects
after several months.
</P>
<P>
   Biostratum, a privately held company co-founded by Tryggvason
and located in Research Triangle Park, N.C., said it hoped to
develop a drug that would inhibit matrix metalloproteinase-2 alone,
curbing tumor growth with fewer side effects than the drugs that
inhibit all metalloproteinases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
