<HEADER>
A6195 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORT-DRINK-LIFEBEAT-     06-07 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORT-DRINK-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH ENERGY DRINKS AND SNACKS FUEL ATHLETES
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a whitewater kayaker with a sport drink 
 By CLIFTON DANIEL 
 c.1999 New York Times Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When competitive runner Gray Fore goes for a relatively short,
five-mile jaunt, she travels light, toting nothing more than a
bottle of water.
</P>
<P>
   But when training dictates a two-hour, 15-mile run, she prepares
like an astronaut on a moon mission, loaded down with energy bars,
power gels and sports drinks, which she munches and guzzles at
intervals along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might just be all in my mind, but they definitely help,''
said Fore, of Wilmington, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sports drinks, now available in a range of neon colors, are in
demand these days _ and not just from serious athletes. Even casual
runners, cyclists and sports enthusiasts are looking for ways to
boost their body's power and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Tagging along for the race are an assortment of concentrated
''sports snacks,'' as well, such as the PowerBar and its ilk _ an
assortment of granola-like energy bars and gels designed to give
runners and cyclists a boost. MUNCH ON
</P>
<P>
   Before a 13-mile run, Fore stokes her furnace with a PowerBar, a
flat, 4-inch slab of oat bran, pear juice concentrate and a slew of
other, unpronounceable ingredients like maltodextrin, a complex
carbohydrate.
</P>
<P>
   Like most things that are good for you, the bars aren't close to
delicious. As the joke goes, the chief ingredient is sawdust. Some
brands, including PowerBar's Harvest Bar and the Clif Bar, are
designed to taste better, with flavors that include chocolate chip
cookie dough.
</P>
<P>
   But granola bars can be hard to digest, so every five miles into
a long run, Fore refuels with ''power gel,'' a high-energy goop
with nutritional properties similar to a PowerBar but with the
texture of fruit-flavored icing.
</P>
<P>
   Runners and cyclists often stash their food and drinks at set
locations along their route, carry fanny packs or bike bottles, or
carry packets of power gel in special pockets in their running
shorts. HYDRATE YOUR THIRST
</P>
<P>
   Fore fell in love with power drinks after being offered an
ice-cold, cherry Powerade after a race.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me tell you, that stuff was fantastic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For exercise lasting over an hour, sports drinks' blend of
carbohydrates and electrolytes will enhance performance for
athletes _- even weekend athletes. Carbohydrates are for energy,
and electrolytes such as sodium and potassium maintain fluid
balance.
</P>
<P>
   Dehydration, say health and fitness experts, is a real threat to
athletes, and can cause fatigue, headaches and muscle cramps. After
all, on warm days, you can easily lose a pound of water during a
half-hour of running.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid dehydration, someone engaged in strenuous exercise
should drink about 5 to 12 ounces every 15 to 20 minutes, according
to a report by the American College of Sports Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Other findings: The day before a race or workout, eat well and
drink plenty of fluids. Two hours before a race or workout, drink
around 16 ounces of fluid.
</P>
<P>
   During exercise, drink early and often. Go for cool, tasty
beverages. You'll drink more. (Avoid soda or fruit juice, however.
They aren't diluted enough.)
</P>
<P>
   After exercising, drink extra fluids even beyond your feelings
of thirst. GO, GATORS
</P>
<P>
   Gatorade is the granddaddy of sports drinks and rules what's
called the ''active thirst market'' with a 79.4 percent share,
according to Beverage Digest. The closest competitors are Powerade,
with 11.2 percent of the market, and All Sport, with 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Born of necessity in 1965, Gatorade was conceived when coaches
for the University of Florida football team noticed their players
were flagging during the second half of every game.
</P>
<P>
   College researchers analyzed team members' sweat to see what
vital nutrients players might be losing. They came up with a
concoction that contained sodium, potassium and carbohydrates
(sugars and starches) _ all essential to muscle performance.
</P>
<P>
   Sodium also helps the body absorb carbohydrates. And it spurs
athletes to drink more, which helps speed rehydration, said Don
Printy, dietitian for New Hanover Regional Medical Center in North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ''A sports drink provides the perfect 'twofer' before, during
and after a run,'' says Liz Applegate, in ''Runner's World''
magazine. ''It hydrates and energizes you.''
</P>
<P>
   The original Gatorade tasted like nothing so much as salty
water. Legend has it that a coach's wife added lemon or lime to the
mix to make it more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, the newly energized Gators became known as the
''second-half team.'' When they beat Georgia Tech in 1967, Tech
coach Bobby Dodd was supposed to have said: ''We didn't have
Gatorade and that's what made the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Stokely-Van Camp bought the formula and started marketing the
drink as Gatorade in 1967. Quaker Oats Co. took over Stokely-Van
Camp, and Gatorade, in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Gatorade alone brings in $1.5 billion per year in sales. The
beverage's biggest threat comes not from another sports drink
company, but from Mother Nature. ''Water is one of Gatorade's
biggest competitors,'' said Gatorade spokeswoman Jill Kinney.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study, however, shows that taste may be winning out
over convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M researcher and physiologist Jack Wilmore collaborated
with the University of Western Australia for a study that pitted
water against sports drinks. During and after a 90-minute workout,
runners were allowed to drink as much as they wanted. They drank
over 50 percent more sports drink than water.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on this search for flavor, sports drinks _ which
used to be available only in generic lemon-lime _ now come in
exotic flavors and neon colors, such as All Sport's Extreme
Watermelon and Gatorade's Whitewater Splash. THE COST OF A BOOST
</P>
<P>
   Keeping your energy up isn't cheap, at least not compared with
pennies-per-gallon tap water. A gallon of Gatorade, the priciest of
the sports drinks, sells for about $4. Athletes might do better
with the powdered form, which costs the same, but makes two
gallons. PowerBars run about $1.59, which works out to 70.17 cents
per ounce, compared to 26.9 cents per ounce for a Nature Valley
Crunchy Granola Bar, a fairly high-end snack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Clifton Daniel wrote this article for The Morning Star in
Wilmington, N.C.) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
