<HEADER>
A6196 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEIRLOOM-TOMATOES-LIF     06-07 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEIRLOOM-TOMATOES-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEIRLOOM TOMATOES: EVERYBODY'S TASTE OF SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a selection of red and orange heirloom
tomatoes. 
 By KAREN BAAR 
 c.1999 Karen Baar 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baylor Lowes was surprised when he confronted the tomato cart at
Bix Restaurant in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ''The waiter brought out a large stainless cart, the way they
used to serve prime rib,'' Lowes explains. ''There was an exotic
mixture of heirloom tomatoes _ red, variegated, yellow, green and
purple _ which he went on to describe as he prepared and dressed
the salad. It was quite entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to eat in a tony restaurant to sample
heirloom tomatoes. Home gardeners have been growing them for years,
and they're now appearing frequently at farmers markets, too.
</P>
<P>
   What's driving this trend is flavor so exquisite, it's hard to
believe these odd-shaped, colorful vegetables bear any relation at
all to those sold at the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   An heirloom vegetable is open pollinated, meaning it will breed
true and consistently from seed, even though its parentage may be
complex.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the literal definition,'' says Lawrence
Davis-Hollander, director of the Eastern Native Seed Conservancy.
''But we also say that heirlooms are varieties that are 50 years
old or older and have been handed down for a couple of generations
or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Hollander estimates 5,000 to 7,000 tomatoes meet this
definition. Many of their names such as Cherokee Purple or Aunt
Lucy's Italian Plum, describe their heritage, while Czech Yellow,
Biely Naliv, and countless others evoke immigrants' tales.
</P>
<P>
   The tomato seeds that came to this country in the bags of
European immigrants certainly had a circuitous journey. Wild
tomatoes originated in South America. They were first domesticated
and cultivated by pre-Columbian Indians in what is Mexico today; in
fact, the name ''tomato'' comes from the Nahuatl word tomatl.
</P>
<P>
   Explorers brought tomatoes from the Americas to Europe in the
early 1500s. A member of the sometimes deadly nightshade family,
the tomato was feared as a poisonous fruit in some places.
</P>
<P>
   But by the mid-17th century they were being consumed in Spain,
and by the 18th century they had become a part of Italian cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the tomato remained an object of suspicion for the
English and, by extension, the American colonists, until the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   Since then there has been a total about-face.
</P>
<P>
   ''No American kitchen garden is complete without its tomatoes,''
says William Woys Weaver, author of ''Heirloom vegetable
Gardening.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is probably safe to say that Americans judge vegetable
gardens today by the tomatoes in them, rather than by the cabbages
or carrots or other vegetables,'' Weaver adds.
</P>
<P>
   But heirloom varieties are not standard fare at supermarkets,
because they don't fit into what Joel Patraker, assistant director
of Greenmarket, a farmers market in New York City, calls the
food-mile scenario.
</P>
<P>
   On average, he says, the food we eat travels 3,000 miles to get
to our plates. Tomatoes sold at the supermarket, therefore, must
have a long shelf life and be able to withstand being packed in
cartons of 25 pounds or more.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget the profit motive. Large farms in this
country tend toward monoculture; that is, they grow one big crop.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, because heirloom tomato plants are less productive
and tend to be more susceptible to disease than modern hybrids,
they are even less attractive to large growers.
</P>
<P>
   But these issues aren't as important to home gardeners, who
select vegetables based on taste, a quality heirlooms have in
spades.
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Hollander compares heirloom tomatoes to wine: ''They might
even be more complex than wine. Every tomato tastes different,
especially when grown in different soil in different years. It's
about locality and regionality.''
</P>
<P>
   Divine taste is not the only reason for buying heirloom
tomatoes. Buying these gems means buying locally, thereby helping
to preserve the dwindling number of small farms in this country.
</P>
<P>
   At least for the foreseeable future, you'll find heirlooms only
by planting your own or buying from local farmers. But things are
changing, thanks to the growing sophistication of American
consumers, who, once they've tasted how wonderful these tomatoes
can be, keep coming back for more.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, we may even see them in the supermarket, following in
the path of other gourmet foods.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you asked a farmer ten years ago if he thought he'd see his
mesclun in Stop &AMP; Shop, he'd have said no,'' says Davis-Hollander.
''I think eventually more heirlooms will get into the supermarket.
It will remain somewhat of a niche market, but there will be a
bigger niche.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, why not try growing them? It's easy to get started.
Driven by an eager market, more and more seed companies, including
mainstream catalogs, are offering seeds for heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe your aunt Tillie or a friend will give you some seeds.
Then you can become a link in the chain of gardeners who are
preserving this precious and delicious-heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Heirloom Index
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of heirloom tomato varieties, so you can
experiment in your garden indefinitely until you find your
favorites. Before planting, however, consider how you're most
likely to use them _ sliced in salads, cooked in pasta sauces,
dried, or just eaten whole _ and choose the varieties best suited
for that purpose. SLICING TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   A good slicing tomato is meaty, with a fruity, complex taste and
a pleasing balance of sugar and acid that can stand up to a
vinaigrette. Here are some examples:
</P>
<P>
   Brandywine. Probably the most famous of all American heirlooms,
large and lobed in pink or yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Oxheart. Sometimes called strawberry tomato because of its
shape, large and reddish orange. White Wonder On the small side,
cream-colored or yellowish white.
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple. Described as ''a big ugly sucker but incredibly
tasty,'' large and yellow, with pink stripes or marbling.
</P>
<P>
   Pruden's Purple. Large and meaty, pale pink to purple. PASTE
TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   When making tomato paste or sauce, look for varieties with more
pulp and less water, as well as a sweet, rich taste.
</P>
<P>
   Grandma Mary Red. Good size, high proportion of meat to juice.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Patti's Italian Paste. Red heart-shaped fruit, good
production.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertie. Slightly square, five inches long, flavorful, and
meaty. TOMATOES FOR DRYING
</P>
<P>
   Even more so than paste tomatoes, good drying tomatoes should
have a deep ''tomatoey'' flavor and a low juice content.
</P>
<P>
   Principe Borghese. Small, red, and plum-shaped.
</P>
<P>
   Black Plum. Brownish red to mahogany in color, plum-shaped,
about one and a half inches long. CHERRY AND OTHER SMALL TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Because it's so simple just to pop these into your mouth, look
for a juicy, mild, sweet flavor. They shouldn't be overly sugary;
it's good to have some tartness.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Pear. Small, pear-shaped, mild, and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Red Pear. A bit larger than the yellow pear and more
full-flavored.
</P>
<P>
   Red Currant. Tiny fruit in clusters, with intense flavor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Karen Baar lives and gardens in Connecticut.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
