<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWI-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FIRST WORLD WAR': TOOLS FOR DESTRUCTION, BUT NONE FOR TURNING
BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight decades after the close of World War I, its formative
impact on this bloody century remains all too clear. As the eminent
military historian John Keegan points out in his latest book, the
First World War not only swept away the great empires of Central
and Eastern Europe and left 10 million dead, but also left ``a
legacy of political rancor and racial hatred so intense that no
explanation of the causes of the Second World War can stand without
reference to those roots.''
</P>
<P>
   The war opened the way to totalitarianism, ``a new word for a
system that rejected the liberalism and constitutionalism which had
inspired European politics since the eclipse of monarchy in 1789.''
And the chaos left in the war's wake fertilized deadly impulses
that persist, as the current crisis in Kosovo attests, to this day:
from the massacre of ethnic minorities to ``the extinction of small
national sovereignties, the destruction of parliaments and the
elevation of commissars, gauleiters and warlords to power over
voiceless millions.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``The First World War,'' Keegan has written a kind of
companion volume to his 1989 book ``The Second World War.'' Once
again, he uses his military expertise to analyze strategic and
operational developments and put them into historical perspective.
And once again, he uses his narrative abilities, honed in a dozen
books (including such classic works as ``The Face of Battle'' and
``The Mask of Command''), to bring to life such famous engagements
as Gallipoli, Verdun and Passchendaele.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan's book is at once more analytic and less encyclopedic
than Martin Gilbert's 1994 book ``The First World War: A Complete
History.'' Although Keegan does an eloquent job of evoking the mood
on the battlefield and the appalling loss of life suffered during
operations like the Somme, his account relies less on the
testimonies of individual soldiers than Gilbert's. Instead, his
narrative is animated by sharply stated assessments of long-term
strategies and short-term tactics, political goals and military
means.
</P>
<P>
   He blames the German Kaiser's ``strategically unnecessary
attempt to match Britain's maritime strength'' in the years before
1914 for contributing to the ``fatal hostility between the two
countries'' and for galvanizing ``the neurotic climate of suspicion
and insecurity from which the First World War was born.'' He
contends that the Germans' ``failure to match the Allies in tank
development must be judged one of their worst military
miscalculations of the war.'' And he argues that the British
general Douglas Haig's ``profligacy with men'' prolonged the agony
on the western front: ``On the Somme he had sent the flower of
British youth to death or mutilation,'' Keegan writes; ``at
Passchendaele he had tipped the survivors into the slough of
despond.''
</P>
<P>
   On the much debated question of the generalship of World War I,
Keegan is of two minds. He concedes that the opulent life style of
many generals _ ``the well-polished entourage, the glittering motor
cars, the cavalry escorts, the regular routine, the heavy dinners,
the uninterrupted hours of sleep'' _ stood in harsh contrast to the
``cold rations, wet boots, sodden uniforms, flooded trenches'' that
their subordinates had to endure. He also argues, however, that
most of the accusations of ``incompetence and incomprehension''
made against these generals were probably misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   With ``battle-altering resources'' like reliable armored,
cross-country vehicles and portable two-way radios a tantalizing
few years out of reach, Keegan writes, ``the generals were trapped
within the iron fetters of a technology all too adequate for mass
destruction of life but quite inadequate to restore to them the
flexibilities of control that would have kept destruction of life
within bearable limits.''
</P>
<P>
   As Keegan sees it, World War I was both tragic and unnecessary _
``unnecessary because the train of events that led to its outbreak
might have been broken at any point during the five weeks of crisis
that preceded the first clash of arms, had prudence or common good
will found a voice.'' Like many historians before him, he
acknowledges the role that interlinking alliances and abstract
military strategies played in setting off the conflagration, and he
adds that ``the existence of a permanent medium of negotiation
between the European powers'' _ like regular summit conferences, or
a ``hot line'' between government leaders _ might have robbed such
war plans of ``their menacing instantaneity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks between the slaying of the Hapsburg heir, Archduke
Franz Ferdinand, by Serbian-backed assassins on June 28, 1914, and
the outbreak of fighting in August, he suggests, ``events
successively and progressively overwhelmed the capacity of
statesmen and diplomats to control and contain them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Honorable and able men though they were,'' he writes, ``the
servants of the chancelleries and foreign officers of the great
powers in the July crisis were bound to the wheel of the written
note, the encipherment routine, the telegraph schedule. The
potentialities of the telephone, which might have cut across the
barriers to communication, seem to have eluded their imaginative
powers. The potentialities of radio, available but unused, evaded
them altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this volume, Keegan captures the anomalous, even
surreal quality of the war. He describes the persistence of archaic
uniforms (frogged jackets and scarlet trousers for France's light
cavalry; similarly antiquated outfits adorned in 10 shades of red
for the Austrians) and ancient methods of communication (signal
flags on the high seas; runners and carrier pigeons on land),
alongside such technological innovations as the submarine, the
airplane and the tank.
</P>
<P>
   He shows how cruelly the combatants' original expectations for a
quick, short war were betrayed. And he meticulously traces the
terrible escalation of a local crisis (Austria's determination to
punish Serbia for the assassination of Archduke Ferdinand) into a
world war, a war that claimed the lives of 1 million British, 1.7
million French, 1.5 million of the Hapsburg Empire, 2 million
Germans and 1.7 million Russians. It was a war that would transform
``a prosperous continent at the height of its success as a source
and agent of global wealth and power and at one of the peaks of its
intellectual and cultural achievement'' into what the English poet
Siegfried Sassoon called ``death's gray land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
