<SLUG> BC-TV-GAYS-CHILDREN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM ON GAYS GETS MIXED REVIEW FROM PBS AFFILIATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If the point of showing the groundbreaking
documentary ``It's Elementary'' on television is to stimulate a
public dialogue on teaching children about tolerance of
homosexuality _ well, it's halfway there and the video's only just
hitting the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a full-tilt crusade by the Christian right to keep it
off public television, the buzz is up about the broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Stations in 23 of the top 30 markets have scheduled the
critically acclaimed San Francisco-made documentary, starting with
WNET in New York last week and stretching through September. Five
others have said they will air it; Dallas and Cleveland are the two
biggest stations to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 89 public stations of 347 across the country have
scheduled it, 17 more are on board but haven't set a date, and 53
are still considering it.
</P>
<P>
   KQED of San Francisco is sponsoring the broadcast after the
Public Broadcasting System, ever skittish about scaring off its
congressional sponsors with controversial programming, turned it
down for national distribution without saying why.
</P>
<P>
   The hope of KQED and the film producers is that the broadcasts
will encourage people to go beyond what they think they know about
the subject and get them talking to each other about their
legitimate, highly charged differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a huge cultural turning point,'' said Debra
Chasnoff, who directed and (with Helen Cohen) co-produced the
77-minute video, cut to just under an hour for TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really significant. When we started working on
this film in the early '90s, people said America is not ready to
talk about this at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, since the debut in 1996, people have found it
harder and harder to avoid the issue of educating children about
the existence of gays and lesbians and about tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefly aimed at adults, the film is in use now by about 3,000
schools, plus 500 colleges of education, mostly to help teachers,
Chasnoff said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, gay students and their parents have
successfully sued schools for failing to protect them from vicious
harassment. Gay and lesbian teen-agers have been coming out of the
closet and, with their parents, forcing schools to deal with their
presence. Gay and lesbian parents, like Chasnoff, have stepped up
efforts to ensure their own young children aren't ostracized in
class.
</P>
<P>
   When Chasnoff started the film, her eldest son, now 10, was
entering kindergarten in a San Francisco public school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought his family _ two moms _ was the greatest thing on
Earth,'' Chasnoff said. ``I was really concerned about what kind of
information he would start to get from other kids or from the lack
of discussion of lesbians and gay people in the elementary school
curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   Her concerns were confirmed in one hair-raising moment, when she
and her partner spoke to his second-grade class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked in. One little boy looked at me and said, `Are you a
lesbian?' Then he screamed and ran to the other side of the room,''
Chasnoff said. ``Where do they get the idea, by second grade, that
a classmate's mom is a potential object of disgust?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Elementary'' takes viewers into six classrooms, where it
becomes clear that even the youngest have heard about gay people
and have absorbed negative attitudes about them.
</P>
<P>
   In one New York City classroom, children volunteer dozens of
words they associate with ``gay,'' including ``love,'' ``pervert''
and ``sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The message of the video is that homophobia gets ingrained early
and hurts people, and that schools are one place to teach
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals was to open up the public dialogue on the
issue when nobody was talking about it. Should the schools be doing
this or not? It was just assumed that of course they don't talk
about it in schools,'' Chasnoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Several conservative Christian groups are trying to keep the
show off the air. The organizations include the American Family
Association, the Florida-based Coral Ridge Ministries, and the
Concerned Women for America.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, KQED is taking special care with its own
presentation later this month to include views outside of the
film's, wrapping it into a two-hour program that includes an
in-studio debate and viewer call-ins.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen people who haven't seen the film are being
invited, most of them parents representing the full range of
attitudes about homosexuality, said Mary Bitterman, president and
chief executive of KQED.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not looking for people who would just polarize the
discussion because their minds are completely set,'' Bitterman
said. Instead of representatives of the groups crusading against
the film, the station sought ``people in our community who may be
supportive of what those organizations do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
