<HEADLINE>
UNION, PORT LEADERS HUNKER DOWN FOR CONTRACT TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This year, cargo valued at more than $300
billion will move in and out of ports in Oakland, Long Beach, Los
Angeles and elsewhere along the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   It is lumber and grain bound for Asian markets, and Barbie dolls
destined for American girls, and there's every reason to believe
the future for trade is bright.
</P>
<P>
   That is why labor leaders and economists _ as well as
manufacturers, retailers, shippers and others around the world
whose fortunes are tied to open seas and efficient ports _ shudder
at the thought of trouble on the docks.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators in mid-May began work on a new three-year contract
that would replace the agreement expiring July 1 and bind 10,000
West Coast members of the International Longshore and Warehouse
Union (ILWU) to 90 U.S. and foreign shipping operators.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone involved in the negotiations, which are taking place in
San Francisco, took an oath of silence until they have a product.
Both sides, however, have said they expect a satisfactory result,
considering that the pressure to maintain the flow of trade is
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those assurances, there is a history of tension in the
longshoremen-shippers relationship, and several volleys of tough
talk were fired by both sides earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for negotiations that Joseph Miniace, the
president and chief executive of the San Francisco-based Pacific
Maritime Association, representing shippers and terminal operators
in contract talks, called the most important in PMA's 50-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   Art Pulaski, executive secretary and treasurer of the California
Labor Federation, which coordinates legislative and political
action on behalf of 2.1 million union members, said of California
ports: ``These are the ports of entry of California's prosperity
and growth. The contract affects not simply 10,000 jobs, but
hundreds of thousands of jobs that depend on California trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is now no public airing of details under
discussion, Miniace said in a recent letter to PMA members that
increasing economic pressures have ``highlighted concerns about
stagnating and declining productivity at West Coast marine cargo
terminals.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Terminal operators have not enjoyed the return on
investments through productivity increases that other industry
sectors have experienced. The productivity issues will not go away,
and its improvement will remain a high priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Productivity is likewise a mantra for the ILWU, said its San
Francisco-based president, Brian McWilliams. ``Every quarter it's
the same old thing _ productivity is down and the West Coast is
going to lose business because of its high labor costs and, of
course, the unreliability of the work force,'' he said in a
pre-contract negotiations letter to members. ``And yet for all
PMA's predictions of industry disaster, every quarter we are
breaking records for the most containers moved through our ports.''
</P>
<P>
   In the talks, productivity is a word with many meanings, but
fundamentally it means efficiently moving cargo about so that it
can get to market quickly. It also means the use of technological
enhancements that threaten some traditional union jobs, and these
are the issues on the table, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, record-keeping and planning for how a vessel is
loaded and unloaded _ for years done on paper on the docks _ can
now be done by computer from anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our work, our jurisdiction, and they're trying to
take some of that work away,'' said a source familiar with the 104
issues that the ILWU negotiating team took into the talks. ``They
want to send that off to a right-to-work state like Utah and pay
somebody eight dollars an hour to key it into a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Boyle, the director of the Maritime Division of the Port of
Oakland, the fourth largest port in the nation, believes both sides
can benefit by enhancing productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about how we can move forward and make our operations
more productive, take advantage of the automation, the innovation,
that's around and available, and still have a viable, productive
work force,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the ILWU wants better benefits packages and pension
and wage increases, according to a source close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ILWU members are relatively handsomely compensated. The standard
hourly wage is $25.68, but that does not include overtime or
bonuses paid those with certain skills, which fatten checks.
</P>
<P>
   According to PMA research, the average fully registered ILWU
longshore workers paid for at least 2,000 hours last year earned
$99,016, while clerks and foremen _ ``walking bosses'' _ earned up
to $117,617 and $156,251, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
