<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6217 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MEERKAT-SENTINELS     06-07 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEERKAT-SENTINELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS SHATTER THE MYTH OF THE BRAVE MEERKAT SENTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While his compatriots scuffle about in the sand for delicious
scorpions or fat, tasty mice, one meerkat stands alone, bolt
upright on an exposed perch, scanning for hawks with dark eyes
wide, ready to call out at the first sign of danger. Like other
such guards in the animal kingdom, these endearingly vulnerable
meerkat sentinels have long impressed biologists as true altruists
_ creatures willing to forgo food and to brave danger to protect
others.
</P>
<P>
   Now a study in the current Science suggests that these beasts
may not be such adorable heroes after all. Researchers have
discovered that meerkats abandon their hunting to act as guards
only when their bellies are good and full. And they appear to do
so, not as an act of noble daring, but because by being the first
to see a predator, they can be sure of being the first down a hole
and out of harm's way. Standing guard, researchers concluded, may
be the safest thing to do once a meerkat has had enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say the discovery that sentinel behavior can arise
from the most selfish of motives suggests that other apparently
self-sacrificing acts could well turn out to be self-serving upon
closer scrutiny. In addition, the researchers say, the new study _
which exactly fulfills a set of predictions for the behavior of a
selfish sentinel _ may explain why some animals fight for the
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that quite a lot of sentinels are selfish,'' said
Dr. Tim Clutton-Brock, a behavioral ecologist at Cambridge
University in England, who observed meerkats for thousands of hours
with more than 30 colleagues over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kevin J. McGowan, a behavioral ecologist at Cornell
University in New York state who has studied sentinel behavior in
birds, said that biologists had assumed such behaviors were
altruistic, often with little evidence. ``There are a lot of things
that people know for a fact that simply aren't so,'' he said.
Calling the study important, he said of the meerkats: ``Each one of
these guys is doing his own selfish best.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why the researchers figured the sentinel post
risky when they first started studying meerkats in the Kalahari
Desert in southern Africa. Skittish to begin with, meerkats,
peering nervously from an exposed perch waiting for a hawk to soar
in, do seem at risk of being eaten and appear particularly daring.
In addition, while the other protected meerkats are at their
leisure to dig away for food, heads stuck in the sand, rear ends
very much exposed, the poor sentinel seems forced to fast.
</P>
<P>
   So Clutton-Brock said he and colleagues at first accepted the
standard altruistic explanation. According to a theory known as
kin-selection, altruists get their genes passed on by helping
relatives who share their genes to survive and reproduce, just as
they could by producing their own offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers found that while meerkats live in family groups,
unrelated animals that join the group often act as sentinels.
Meerkats even act as sentinels when they are alone and no one needs
protection. Looking closer, the researchers found that these
supposedly daring sentinels always positioned themselves near a
hole where they could dive for cover. And never in more than 2,000
hours of observations was a sentinel attacked or killed. Meanwhile,
Clutton-Brock said, other meerkats were hauled away by predators.
</P>
<P>
   And, while the researchers had thought these sentinels rotated
shifts, they found instead that who was on duty depended largely on
who had last eaten the most. Simply by providing a meerkat with a
hearty meal of a hard-boiled egg, the researchers could speed the
return of that animal to a sentinel post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful set of data that fulfill my predictions and
then some,'' said Dr. Peter Bednekoff, behavioral ecologist at
Eastern Michigan University in Ypsilanti, who first suggested the
notion of selfish sentinels. He said other examples were likely to
be identified soon.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the animal kingdom sentinels, a group that includes
monkeys, scrub jays and antelopes, have it as easy as meerkats.
</P>
<P>
   At least in some species, sentinel behavior is indeed deadly and
self-sacrificial. In the dwarf mongoose, males low in the hierarchy
make up a rear guard. Keeping watch from behind as the group hunts
for food, these sentinels are often killed as they run to catch up
with their escaping companions. And some sentinels take these risks
to benefit their close relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Even the adorable meerkat may yet redeem itself as a bit of an
altruist. Although being a sentinel may itself not entail great
risk, it is hard to imagine a selfish reason for their giving a
shout of warning before dashing for cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is why do they give an alarm call?'' said
Dr. Paul W. Sherman, animal behaviorist at Cornell. Describing the
study as fascinating, he added: ``The call tells us there's
something more than selfishness involved.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, meerkats have reason to be altruists. Although
unrelated animals live in meerkat groups, most are close relatives,
individuals whose evolutionary fates are closely linked.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman noted that such mixtures of selfishness and altruism
should not be surprising. In research with ground squirrels, he
found both self-sacrificing and selfish alarm calls. Female ground
squirrels give an altruistic alarm call that endangers the caller
while effectively alerting the young nearby. But there is also a
selfish alarm call that squirrels give, not to protect others, but
to protect themselves. When callers make the selfish whistle, a
pandemonium of running, whistling squirrels ensues in which the
original caller can hide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
