<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAMUEL-JACKSON-LADN &LR;      06-07 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMUEL-JACKSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR PLAYS SECOND FIDDLE IN INDIE FILM 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Does Samuel L. Jackson want to be Morgan Freeman?
</P>
<P>
   He's certainly not giving up the action and suspense genres for
art films. The 50-year-old Jackson is wrapping up work on the
military courtroom drama ``Rules of Engagement'' with Tommy Lee
Jones, and he plans to star next in an update of ``Shaft,''
directed by John Singleton. In July, Jackson will star in the
``Deep Blue Sea,'' a scientists-vs.-killer-shark epic.
</P>
<P>
   But when he heard that Freeman had bowed out of the independent
film ``The Red Violin'' because of a scheduling conflict, Jackson
stepped forward to claim the small but important role of violin
expert Charles Morritz for himself. He'd read the script, which he
found ``very moving,'' and saw the role of Morritz as an
opportunity to keep changing as an actor.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, ``Violin'' director Francois Girard
recalled, ``When I met with Sam, I wasn't sure if he knew that
(Freeman) had been up for the role first, so I was kind of dancing
around that fact. Then Sam said, `I want you to know I'd be honored
to be your next choice after Morgan Freeman.' To me, that was very
elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that he figured if it was good enough for Freeman,
it was good enough for him. ``If you think of me in the same
sentence that you think of Morgan Freeman, I figure ... hey, I'll
do it,'' said Jackson, with obvious admiration for his fellow
actor.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, being released Friday by Lions Gate Films (which
released the critically acclaimed ``Gods and Monsters'' last year),
Jackson plays a top violin appraiser who discovers a shocking
secret about the priceless red violin of the title. The film is
unusual in many respects. The story of the almost humanlike
instrument is told in a series of flashbacks over the course of
four centuries, with Jackson's character appearing on screen for
less than 20 brief, but pivotal, minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After the secret of the violin is revealed, it is Morritz who
realizes the violin may be too valuable to be simply auctioned off
to the highest bidder. He is forced to make a life-changing
decision about the instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, the violin is, by turns, the unborn child of
the violin maker, the mother of a young orphan prodigy and the
lover of a flamboyant virtuoso. The story, which takes the audience
from Europe to China to North America, is a far cry from the
underworld inhabited by some of Jackson's most memorable
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, at 50 _ albeit a hip, youthful 50 _ seems to be making
sure he will still be getting challenging roles at 60. The
62-year-old Freeman's career isn't a bad model to emulate. Like
Freeman, Jackson only came into his own as a film actor later in
life. Now, when directors want a dignified actor who exudes moral
authority, they call Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson started in theater and has played a range of
roles, he has become known on film for low-life characters like
crack addict Gator in ``Jungle Fever'' and hit man Jules Winfield
in ``Pulp Fiction.'' He admits those roles weigh a little heavily
at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got paid for each reference I've had to Jules (from
fans), I'd be terrifically rich,'' said Jackson with a weary smile.
``At least three times a week, someone comes up and asks me, `Hey,
you know what they call a Quarter Pounder with Cheese in France?'
And I say, `No _ what?''' Jackson said, feigning wide-eyed
ignorance at the line from ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added with a shrug, ``it doesn't really bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Jackson seems to take it all in stride. Describing the
violin of the movie's title, he says, ``It's been through cultural
differences, it's been through social change, it's been in
jeopardy.'' The same could be said of Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   After growing up in Tennessee and becoming a student activist at
Morehouse College, Jackson made a name for himself on the New York
stage. Later he fought and won a battle with substance abuse. In
his career, his persistence in going after roles that weren't
necessarily written for a black actor finally paid off. His intense
portrayal of Gator in 1991's ``Jungle Fever'' cemented his fame.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's enjoying his success _ but also appears to be staying
very grounded, even as he takes roles in such blockbusters as
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like to see my movies in a theater, with an
audience,'' Jackson says. ``I consciously plan to do things that
make sense to an audience, so I like to see if I made the right
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the common claim among actors that they don't
like to watch themselves on screen? ``Come on,'' Jackson says
dismissively. ``If you don't like watching yourself, do theater. Or
get another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Girard, whose quirky credits include ``Thirty Two Short Films by
Glenn Gould,'' admires Jackson's emotional honesty and his striving
to keep growing as an actor. ``We live in a system that tends to
keep us where we've been successful,'' said Girard, a slightly
built 36-year-old with the rather wild-eyed look of an artist.
``It's the same thing for directors: We keep getting offered the
same type of projects ... It's the responsibility of the artist to
escape that.''
</P>
<P>
   To aid in Jackson's preparation for the role, Girard sent him
stacks of information about violins and their appraisal. Jackson
learned from a top appraiser who served as a consultant on the film
how to handle and examine a violin like an expert.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson recalls there was even a bit of real-life drama
involving the violin during the filming _ somewhat mirroring the
emotional backdrop against which the violin's story is told.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the violins I handle in the movie is actually a $5
million Stradivarius,'' said Jackson. ``The producer got someone to
lend it to us ... and he carried it to Montreal and left it with
this other assessor, who has a vault in his house there.''
</P>
<P>
   Continued Jackson, ``The day before we were supposed to use the
violin, the assessor's wife discovered he was having an affair, and
locked him out of the house. They had to get the police to go to
his house so they could get the violin.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson flashes one of his mischievous, toothy grins. The actor
knows that wherever a film is set _ and whether the characters are
made of flesh and blood or wood _ passion is universal. It's his
talent at ``showing that on the outside,'' as he puts it, that he
counts on to keep him on top in the fickle world of Hollywood.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
