<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     06-07 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT OF APPEALS KO ' S TAX DOLLARS FOR RELIGIOUS SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 27, the U.S. First Circuit Court of Appeals
short-circuited any attempt to pass school voucher laws that
transmit taxpayer dollars into religious schools. The ruling
directly affects the states and territories under its jurisdiction:
Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island and Puerto Rico.
However, the court's ruling will be felt by every state of the
nation. This is the first religious voucher case to reach the
federal appellate level.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a clear victory for opponents of voucher
systems that would put public funds into religious schools. It was
a clear victory for those who understand constitutional history and
the founders' mandate to keep church and state separated.
</P>
<P>
   This court case arose in Maine. The state legislature had
enacted a statute that provides schooling for students who live in
rural communities that don't have any public schools. For these
students, the state pays grants directly to qualified private
schools that are non-sectarian.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's Constitution and its Declaration of Rights do not
specifically prohibit the payment of tax dollars to religious
schools. Article I, Section 3 of the state's Declaration of Rights
proclaims that `no subordination nor preference of any one sect or
denomination to another shall ever be established by law.` But less
than two months ago, the Maine Supreme Court upheld the state law
that excludes taxpayer funding for religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Elwood Strout and other parents challenged the law in federal
court claiming that it discriminates against religious schools and
violates their religious liberty. The parents, who live in rural
areas that do not have public schools, wanted the state to pay the
tuition for their children to attend St. Dominic's Regional High
School, a private sectarian school in Lewiston.
</P>
<P>
   The parents lost at the federal district court level and
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In the case (Strout vs. Commissioner, Maine Department of
Education), the unanimous appeals court issued a sweeping decision
that declares, in part: ``A statement to the effect that `Congress
shall make no law respecting the establishment of religion,' U.S.
Const. amend. 1, is hardly equivocal language. ... Separation of
church and state constituted a paramount principle and goal in the
minds of some of the most influential of the Framers both by dint
of historical experience, and personal conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Further in the decision, the court declares, ``Upholding the
Establishment Clause, which is aimed at avoiding an entangled
church and state, is such a paramount interest. In the long run, an
entanglement of the two has been shown by history to be oppressive
of religious freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The court made short work of the parents' claim that the Maine
law violates the Free Exercise Clause of the First Amendment and
thereby their religious freedom. The court pointed out that the law
`does not prevent attendance at a religious school. Nor does it
prevent religious education of children in Maine. All it means is
that the cost of religious education must be borne by the parents
and not the state.`
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of the decision, the court agrees that parents
have `a fundamental right to direct the upbringing and education of
their children.` However, the court notes, ``that fundamental right
does not require the state to directly pay for a sectarian
education. Here, the statute does not prevent the parents from
doing what they wish; it only prevents the state from helping pay
for their wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bill of Rights protects an individual's fundamental
liberties from encroachment by the government. Freedom of speech,
as guaranteed by the First Amendment, does not force that the
government pay to print the pamphlets that someone wishes to
distribute. Nor can a citizen demand that the government buy him a
gun because the Second Amendment guarantees ``the right of the
people to keep and bear arms.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a major loss for the religious right, which wants to tap
taxpayer dollars for the honor of sending their children to
sectarian schools. The American Center for Law and Justice, founded
by TV preacher Pat Robertson, made a tactical error by involving
itself in this case and taking it to the First Circuit Court of
Appeals. There was little hope of winning, a summary judgement at
the district court level should have indicated as much. The Maine
Supreme Court's own ruling in a similar case should have alerted
ACLJ to forego an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps ACLJ has money to burn. According to a news story in The
Virginian Pilot, June 2, Robertson recently reached a deal with
Liberian dictator Charles Taylor which allows Robertson's company,
Freedom Gold Ltd., to mine for gold in the Bukon Jedeh region of
Liberia. The Virginian Pilot sketched Taylor's escapades: He fled
to the United States in 1983 after allegedly stealing $1 million
from the Liberian government. He escaped from a Massachusetts jail
in 1985, and four years later started a bloody civil war in
Liberia. But this isn't the first mining deal Robertson has made
with dictators. In the early 1990s, he made a deal with Zaire's
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko to dig for diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been wiser if Robertson had simply offered to pay
for the Strouts and the other parents to send their children to a
religious school of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is a firm decision by a federal appellate court that
cannot be ignored by other federal districts. And the moves in
various state legislatures to pass voucher laws will be stymied.
This is a clear indication that such laws will be challenged in
federal court. And will likely be struck down.
</P>
<P>
   If we are to remain faithful to the intent of the founders and
the religious clauses of the First Amendment, American taxpayers
must never be forced to subsidize religious institutions.
Fortunately, the First Circuit Court of Appeals recognized that
truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
