<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLS GIVES DAVIS HIGH RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Gray Davis' reputation appears to have
thrived among California's Hispanic population despite criticism
over his handling of a ballot initiative designed to cut off
government services to illegal immigrants, a new survey shows.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of California voters, taken a week after Davis hosted
a three-day visit by Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, shows 75
percent of Hispanic voters rate Davis' job performance as
``excellent or good.'' Davis, a Democrat, recently angered Hispanic
advocates by sending the fate of Proposition 187 to a court
mediator instead of dropping his defense of the anti-illegal
immigrant measure altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Davis got high marks among all voters surveyed as well, with 56
percent of them giving him the two highest ratings and 36 percent
saying he was doing a ``fair or poor job'' after six months in
office.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, former Gov. Pete Wilson scored a 15 percent
``excellent or good'' poll rating in his early years in office _ at
the time of a brutal recession _ and former Gov. Ronald Reagan
never got higher than a 42 percent ``excellent or good'' rating
from the Field Poll during his two terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this shows is that `It's the economy, stupid,''' said Del
Ali of Research 2000 in Rockville, Md., which conducted the poll
for the San Francisco Examiner and KTVU-TV. ``Despite what you may
think on Proposition 187, Gray is not a confrontational or
controversial character. He's just right in the middle of the road,
right where you should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican consultant Dan Schnur conceded that the governor is
doing at least part of his job well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When economic times are good, what you want is the most
cautious, risk-adverse, impossibly inert governor you could
possibly find. By that measure, he's doing a hell of a job,''
Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner-KTVU poll on Davis' performance was part of a
larger statewide survey that asked voters their views on the
upcoming U.S. Senate race, a school voucher initiative, and another
March 2000 ballot measure that would outlaw gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was elected last year by a 20-point margin over
then-Attorney General Dan Lungren. It was one of the biggest
landslides in California history, and it came, analysts believe,
because voters felt turned off by Lungren's conservatism and
comfortable with Davis' centrist mantra.
</P>
<P>
   As for Davis' apparent support among Hispanic voters, Garry
South, a political adviser to the governor, said: ``Most Latino
voters are moderate in nature. They didn't appreciate 187 ... but
they are far more concerned about their daily lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In the poll, only 13 percent of Republicans said they think
Davis is doing a poor job. Thirty-nine percent of Republicans think
he's doing an ``excellent or good'' job.
</P>
<P>
   The Research 2000 pollsters questioned 810 registered voters
across California May 27-29. The survey attempted to match the
racial makeup and party affiliations of the state's registered
voters. Among the other findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ A measure to outlaw gay marriages in California is getting
less- than-expected support, with only 54 percent of those surveyed
saying they would vote for the initiative next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., continues to dominate any
match-up with the current field of Republicans considering a run
against her next year. She remains one of the most popular and
well-recognized politicians in California, with 57 percent of those
surveyed having a favorable view of her. One-third of those
surveyed held an unfavorable opinion of her after seven years in
office.
</P>
<P>
   The two highest-ranking Republicans in the state _ Insurance
Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush and Secretary of State Bill Jones _
both score well compared with other Republicans in a theoretical
contest against Feinstein, but many Californians don't recognize
their names.
</P>
<P>
   _ According to the poll, those surveyed don't like a March 2000
ballot initiative that would allow taxpayer-supported vouchers so
people can send their children to private or parochial schools. A
similar measure on the November 1993 ballot only got 30 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed 54 percent of those surveyed oppose the measure,
compared to 41 percent in favor. Asians, Hispanics and blacks
particularly oppose the initiative, according to the poll _ with
opposition ranging from 68 percent to 71 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
