<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MENTAL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIME TO 'BREAK THE SILENCE' ON MENTAL ILLNESS, MRS. GORE SAYS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tipper Gore hosted the first-ever White House
conference on mental health Monday, continuing her own recovery
from depression as she aided the Clinton administration's efforts
to battle the stigma of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   With her husband, Vice President Al Gore, at her side, Mrs. Gore
convened the one-day conference with her first discussion in a
public forum of her own battle with depression following the
life-threatening injuries to her son in a car accident in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental illness is not just something that happens to other
people, somebody over there,'' she said. ``We have to realize that
it happens in our American families, in our American communities,
and that means it calls on a response from all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore told the conference it was time to ``break the
silence'' about mental illness, the way it was with cancer and AIDS
in previous decades, to encourage those suffering from mental
health problems to seek help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must recognize mental illness for what it is _ it is an
illness that can be treated, and it can be treated successfully,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton used the conference to announce a $7.3 million
study of mental illness by the National Institute of Mental Health.
He also ordered the 285 health plans used by federal employees to
cover mental illness and substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-six years ago, President Kennedy said we had to return
mental health to the mainstream of American medicine,'' Clinton
said. ``Thirty-six years ago he said it, and we're still waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House also announced a national training program for
teachers to identify and help troubled children, an idea stemming
from the recent student shootings in Colorado and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, held at Howard University in Washington, was
linked to more than 1,000 sites nationwide by satellite and
involved five Cabinet secretaries and 20 members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews about her depression, Mrs. Gore has
declined to discuss her symptoms or the treatment she underwent.
But Monday, she disclosed that she sought professional help after
friends told her, as she put it, ``I was not myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, the leading candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination, told the conference that the Gore family
learned from his wife's experience that ``when mental illness
strikes, it affects not only the person who is involved but the
entire family.'' He said his family became ``much stronger'' as a
result of the experience, but did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, too, praised the Gores as examples of how to deal with
mental illness in a family. And he added a political tone to the
conference in observing that the Gores have done more than others
in turning ``family values into real concrete improvement'' for
average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton at the
conference also highlighted the ever increasing importance of
politics in White House events. Mrs. Clinton, who said ``we should
do whatever it takes to remove the stigma from mental illness,'' is
preparing to run for the U.S. Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the least political of the primary participants in the
conference was Mrs. Gore, who has long championed the issue of
mental illness, her interest in the subject stemming to her
childhood and her mother's periodic bouts with clinical depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her to be my national adviser for mental illness
because she knows more and cares more about this issue than anyone
else I personally know,'' the president said of Mrs. Gore, who does
volunteer work with the mentally ill and homeless in Washington and
who has two degrees related to family therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
