<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDICAPPED-CYCLIST-N     06-07 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDICAPPED-CYCLIST-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C., S.C.) 
 MAN USES ARMS TO TACKLE CYCLING TEST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By GARY HENDERSON Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.    
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTANBURG, S.C. _ Two years ago, Van Epps rode onto the pages
of cycling's record books.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first person on an arm-powered cycle to complete
the Assault on Mount Mitchell, a 105-mile ride from Spartanburg to
the summit of the highest mountain in North Carolina. And he's done
it twice since then.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Epps is disabled. He lost his right leg eight years
ago in a bicycle accident. He spent months in the hospital and has
undergone more than a dozen surgery related to the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Epps left another set of tire tracks in the books.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old cyclist became the first person riding an
arm-powered cycle to qualify for the prestigious 750-mile
Paris-Brest-Paris ride.
</P>
<P>
   The bicycle ride through France began in 1891 and takes place
every four years. This year's event begins Aug. 23. Because of its
length, it is considered one of the toughest cycling events in
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Qualifying is big,'' Epps said. ``Going over there is bigger.
There will be no support help; just me and the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps conquered the 6,684-foot Mount Mitchell for the third time
in the middle of May. Then, he qualified for the Paris-Brest-Paris
on a large tricycle called a Freedom Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   Paris-Brest-Paris is billed as a ride, not a race. Cyclists,
however, must complete it in no more than 80 hours. Riders are
eliminated if they don't make it to checkpoints on time.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, Epps had to complete four long-distance rides within
a certain period of time. The distances ranged from 125 to 375
miles.
</P>
<P>
   For Epps, and the other riders who will tackle the
Paris-Brest-Paris challenge, it is a personal race against the
clock. Riders are allowed to rest, or even sleep, as long as they
reach the checkpoints in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The riders with legs have more time to rest because they're
faster,'' said Epps, a high school teacher who lives in
Spartanburg.
</P>
<P>
   He will have additional time if his mentor and trainer, John
Bryan, is successful with his training plan that would move Epps
from a tricycle onto a two-wheel bike.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Bryan has to teach Epps how to ride the custom
two-wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can learn to ride it, he'll pick up one to one and a
half miles per hour,'' Bryan said. ``Over the course of 750 miles,
that'll give him 10 hours he can sleep and rest. That's the only
way Van will be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan's plan draws on his 45 years experience as a mechanical
engineer. He has designed a way to install small wheels that Epps
can lower with a lever to prevent him from toppling over at low
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could call them training wheels,'' Bryan said.
``Able-bodied riders can put the legs down to stabilize themselves.
Van can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan, 64, knows about the Paris-Brest-Paris ride from
experience when he finished the course in 1983. ``I cherish this,''
he said, showing off the medal he received for finishing the ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris-Brest-Paris course covers a meandering route through
the French countryside, from Paris to the Brittany Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the riders who've qualified are physically strong,'' Bryan
said. ``The question is, `Are they mentally ready?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan is the founder and promoter of the Assault on Mount
Mitchell bicycle ride, an event that will celebrate its 25th
anniversary next May. He is also an official qualifier for the
Paris-Brest-Paris, in charge of an area covering several southern
states.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan's encouragement helped Epps return to riding after his
accident, spurred him to try the Assault on Mount Mitchell and gave
him the confidence to try for Paris-Brest-Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French are going to be skeptical when Van shows up,''
Byran said. ``But after he passes a few of the checkpoints, the
word will pass all up and down that highway. They'll all know about
him.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Journal in Spartanburg, S.C., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
