<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HILLARY'S TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ever since he was kicked out of the White House
inner circle for carelessly cavorting with a prostitute, political
consultant-turned-pundit Dick Morris has been vengefully dumping on
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's publicly turned against Hillary Clinton, too, brashly
predicting in the Hill, a weekly newspaper that covers Congress,
that if she runs for the U.S. Senate from New York, she will surely
lose.
</P>
<P>
   What brass. What balderdash.
</P>
<P>
   Morris contends the first lady's issues will be mushy with a
moderate Republican opponent and that she _ like other women
candidates without issues, will come across as ``strident, bitchy,
arrogant and contentious.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, he says she can't fight off the carpetbagger charge and
is so well known that she'll never get more support than she has
right now. A recent trial heat shows her losing to New York GOP
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani by 43.7 percent to 49.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. Take that, tough lady. Morris didn't even go into other
complaints that she will siphon funds and attention from less
famous Democratic candidates, unite Republicans tired of the very
name Clinton and confuse voters who expect her to huddle over her
own hearthstone and tend to her duties as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Morris's real zinger is his claim that ``everybody in New York
state knows all there is to know about the first lady. Any vote she
doesn't get right now she isn't going to get as the race unfolds.
But (Giuliani) is not well known in parts of upstate. As his
recognition increases ... he will increase his vote share and widen
his lead over Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   How did Morris ever get a reputation as a big political thinker?
He makes an assumption that the more people get to know Giuliani,
the better they will like him. But wait a minute. Maybe ignorance
is bliss. Maybe a smart-aleck Manhattan mayor won't translate well
in upstate New York. It's a definite possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Morris makes a second silly assumption that Hillary Clinton's
image is frozen in the public mind. But which image? She transforms
herself regularly and is undoubtedly about to do it again. She has
played more parts in the White House than Judi Dench has on stage.
</P>
<P>
   We could put this rubbish down to the customary partisan
campaign clang. But the sexist undertone is painfully striking, as
outrageous as it is unmistakable, a barely disguised double
standard imposed on her candidacy traceable to the fact that she is
female.
</P>
<P>
   Naively, we of her gender had thought the worst was behind us
with Geraldine Ferraro and the increasing number of women in
Congress. To judge by the early attacks on Hillary Clinton, we
ain't seen nothin' yet.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Breslin, the New York Post's blue-collar columnist,
incredibly admonished the first lady: ``Please don't cry when you
lose.'' What patronizing poppycock. Has this man been on an
isolated desert island the past six years? She never cries in
public. Bill cries, Ronald Reagan cried. But Hillary does not.
</P>
<P>
   She is being tackled for never having lived in New York state or
spending much time there, although legally she is required to have
a local residence only on Election Day 2000. Yet precedents exist
for male political carpetbagging all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers elected Robert Kennedy of Massachusetts in 1964 and
James Buckley of Connecticut in 1970 to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker John D. ``Jay'' Rockefeller IV moved to West Virginia
for the sole purpose of seeking office there and has held its
junior Senate seat for 15 years. Rep. Patrick Kennedy, son of Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, relocated his base to Rhode
Island for the same reason and is expected to seek a Senate seat
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Texan Michael Huffington moved to California to run for the
Senate, but throwing money around turned out to be his only
political idea and he deservedly lost. Many others over the decades
have uprooted themselves to find an electoral environment more
agreeable than their native soil. Why not Hillary Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   Other critics describe the first lady as audacious and vain for
daring to run for the Senate without previously having held an
elective public office. She is depicted as having sinister motives
of revenge, rather than the familiar unisex ambition for power
common to all politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Congress is full of doctors, lawyers and business executives
who had never previously stood for election and who won because of
_ rather than in spite of _ their ``outsider'' status. Of the 74
Republican freshmen elected to the House in 1994, 48 had no
legislative experience and many had not held any state office.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Steve Forbes, Patrick Buchanan, Elizabeth Dole and
Gary Bauer are campaigning for no less than the presidency, the
highest political honor we can bestow, without having first held
any other elective office.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hillary Clinton is a mere wife. The same critics who
decry her qualifications also dredge up stale controversies that
sprang from her obvious influence over public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans cite her failed health care reforms during Bill
Clinton's firs
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
