<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO SEEK MEDICARE EXPANSION TO COVER DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is preparing one of the last
major domestic initiatives of his presidency _ a politically
appealing but expensive proposal to have Uncle Sam pay part of the
bill for prescription drugs for nearly 40 million Americans over
age 65.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may outline the multibillion-dollar proposal before
leaving for the Group of Eight summit in Cologne, Germany, next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official, speaking Monday on condition of
anonymity, said Clinton is weighing a variety of ways to pay for
the expanded Medicare coverage. Clinton may draw money from the
federal budget surplus, finance part of the plan through Medicare
cost savings or obtain co-payments from beneficiaries, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever option the president decides upon, the cost to the
beneficiary will be substantially below the costs the elderly bear
from private insurance,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source of funding, Clinton faces a tough sell on
Capitol Hill where the Republican-controlled House and Senate have
been leery of expanding Medicare coverage at a time when the
entitlement program already faces bankruptcy in 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said last month that his panel would not take up
Medicare reform until late summer at the earliest _ a timetable
that virtually forestalls final congressional action this year.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that elderly Americans face enormous costs from
prescription drugs, with 80 percent of retired people taking a
prescription drug each day. Drug prices rose 51 percent between
1990 and 1995 alone.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan Medicare commission led by Sen. John Breaux, D-La.,
and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., concluded earlier this year that
universal coverage for prescription drugs was too expensive because
it would cost $20 billion a year now _ and more when the Baby Boom
generation begins to retire in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the commission proposed Medicare coverage for
prescription drugs for couples with joint incomes of less than
$13,000. But the proposal failed to win majority support from the
commission and was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Medicare reimburses elderly Americans for hospital
costs and a share of costs for physicians. But Medicare does not
pay for prescription medications given outside a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   An official at the federal Health Care Finance Administration
which administers the Medicare program said Monday the Clinton
administration proposal will seek to expand prescription drug
subsidies currently provided to 6.7 million Medicare beneficiaries
who have elected to receive health care under health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of those managed care plans have been offering drug
coverage _ either at a low cost or at no cost to the
beneficiaries,'' the HCFA official explained, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``The White House plan would make that kind of
coverage available to other Medicare beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton would propose voluntary
co-paid prescription drug coverage for considerably less than the
$90 per month premium now available to the elderly under
supplemental insurance sold by private companies.
</P>
<P>
   White House chief of staff John Podesta said on CBS News' ``Face
the Nation'' that Clinton's plan would ask Medicare beneficiaries
to pay ``a modest premium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But in exchange for that, they will have a prescription drug
benefit that's better than anything you could buy today in the open
market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The White House warned in March that 15 million Medicare
beneficiaries ``have absolutely no prescription drug coverage,
millions more have totally inadequate coverage and our nation's
elderly are paying excessively high costs for their desperately
needed medications.'' The White House added: ``The president's
Medicare reform proposal will address these unmet challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing prescription drug coverage for America's elderly
promises to be a hot issue in the presidential campaign in 2000.
Americans over age 60 voted for Republican candidates for the House
and Senate in 1998 _ a reversal in their support for Clinton in his
presidential campaigns in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
