<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-CENTENNIAL-H     06-07 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-CENTENNIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR CHANGES IN STORE FOR 100-YEAR-OLD YOSEMITE CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. _ When Camp Curry opened in this
majestic place 100 years ago this month, you could rent a tent for
$2 a day or $12 a week, get three squares a day and a clean napkin
with every meal.
</P>
<P>
   That year, 1899, only 4,500 people visited Yosemite, one of the
crown jewels of America's national parks. Some 290 of them stayed
in the 25 tents at Camp Curry.
</P>
<P>
   This year, more than 4.5 million people will trek to Yosemite
and about 333,000 of them will stay at Camp Curry, now called Curry
Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed,'' Loy Cutshall said, sitting beneath
7,000-foot Glacier Point and admiring nearby Half Dome. ``But there
is something permanent here that won't ever change.''
</P>
<P>
   Loy and Robert Cutshall, of Brea, Calif., first saw Yosemite
more than 50 years ago as young camp workers. Both now 70, they
honeymooned here _ in Cabin 261 _ and will celebrate their 48th
wedding anniversary next week.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, along with the first big wave of summer season
tourists, they celebrated Camp Curry's 100th birthday in a series
of special events put on by the Yosemite Concession Services Corp.,
which now runs Curry Village. The nearly 1,200 square miles of
scenic wild lands that comprise the park itself were set aside in
1890.
</P>
<P>
   While visitors took a nostalgic look back at the past 100 years,
they also were taking an uneasy look forward to the next 100.
</P>
<P>
   The vast numbers of tourists have long put increasing pressure
on this narrow little valley carved into the middle of the Sierra
Nevada. Man's footprint has been ever larger and Mother Nature has
been fighting a losing battle.
</P>
<P>
   More than two years ago, Mother Nature struck back. On New
Year's Day 1997, heavy rains and a melting snowpack sent the Merced
River roaring out of its banks in the worst flooding in the valley
in 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   Roads, campgrounds and buildings were destroyed to the tune of
$178 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   With the destruction came opportunity _ and controversy. The
National Park Service tried to combine repairs with the long-term
goal of reducing congestion and restoring the valley to a more
natural state.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the Park Service proposed moving 210
buildings and replacing 440 others of the original 495 rooms at the
Yosemite Lodge. That would involve building an access road closer
to the Merced, which has wild and scenic rivers protection, adding
bike and walking paths and relocating eight acres of parking.
</P>
<P>
   Climbers disagreed and sued to block the lodge redevelopment.
The Sierra Club also filed suit and, in October, U.S. District
Judge Charles Breyer agreed. It was back to the drawing boards.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt announced that the
Park Service was combining four separate park redevelopment plans
into one. A draft of that plan was due this month but has been put
off until early winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have listened to the public responses to previous planning
proposals and we got the message loud and clear,'' Babbitt said.
``It makes sense that we roll things into one comprehensive package
that can be reviewed in total.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken together, it will meet our expectations to restore
natural areas and to protect resources while at the same time
improving the quality of visitor experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt may be overly optimistic about meeting expectations. The
$176 million Valley Implementation Plan, for instance, may include
proposals to move employee housing outside the park, to El Portal.
</P>
<P>
   That brought vigorous opposition last week from the descendants
of David and Jennie Curry, the Redwood City school teachers who
opened Camp Curry on June 1, 1899, because they wanted an
affordable alternative to the $4-a-day Sentinel Hotel in the
valley.
</P>
<P>
   Their grandsons _ David Curry of Berkeley and John Curry of
Hilton Head, S.C. _ say moving employee housing out of the park
would destroy one of the biggest incentives for young people to
work there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 1,500 summer employees here and 500 in the winter
and most of them are here totally for the experience of living in
the park, not for the job,'' said John Curry, a resort consultant
who worked in Yosemite as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they are quality people. You couldn't get that employee if
it weren't for the ability to live in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   David Curry said part of the park's strengths is that workers
have a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to be attracted to this community if workers
are scattered somewhere outside the park, if their kids can't go to
school here. ... One hundred years of experience is being whittled
away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are other controversies. The new master plan will contain
proposals to sharply limit vehicle traffic into the valley by
creating a central parking area and using shuttles to ferry
visitors into the park.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say that would end the bumper-to-bus traffic that
pollutes the valley throughout the summer and, increasingly, in the
winter. Others argue it is just moving the problem.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a battle brewing pitting some counties around
Yosemite and conservationists against the Park Service over
development of a regional transit system feeding the park and over
the use of diesel buses.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of diesel-spewing buses ``are a step backwards, even
compared to cars, which I have no particular love for,'' said David
Brower, founder of Earth Island Institute and Friends of the Earth,
and onetime executive director of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week to California Department of
Transportation, Brower said the ``level of pollution generated by
diesel engines is unacceptable both for human health and for the
health of wildlife and trees in the Park.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
