A6260 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HESAID-SHESAID08-COX     06-07 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HESAID-SHESAID08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHE SAID: A siren call a mother just can't resist
 &HT;    By Maureen Downey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One recent night while pacing the floor with a restless infant,
I decided that parents fall into two basic groups: those who let
their babies cry themselves to sleep and those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   I'm in the second group, which is why I'm writing this on
deadline instead of last night, when I should have. A 16-pound air
raid siren ran me off of my computer. Given the choice between
placating my editor or little Becca Lucia, I'll take my daughter.
She yells a lot louder.
</P>
<P>
   Most parents will stand outside their baby's room some nights,
resisting with every ounce of will the urge to dash in and snatch
up a crying infant. With our older two children I just gave up
immediately, rocking or nursing them to sleep against the advice of
the experts. My instincts then _ and now _ won't let me follow the
experts.
</P>
<P>
   I've been rewarded with warm, empathetic kids who won't let me
kill the bugs in the house. (I have to gently escort them outside.)
Neither of our older children has ever been bothered with
nightmares; neither tries to sneak into our bed in the middle of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   A friend shakes her head over my nighttime floor pacing and
insists I haven't learned a thing from having two older kids. She's
wrong. What I've learned is how quickly babies grow up and turn
into independent children who don't need rocking.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, our oldest graduates from elementary school. She
doesn't need me to cuddle, or read from ``Goodnight Moon.'' She
closes her door at bedtime and rereads ``The Diary of Anne Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's a good thing. Because now it's the twins' turn.
</P>
<P>
   When baby cries, it's time to get tough
</P>
<P>
   By Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   You've all heard this sound. It starts out as a wail, then turns
gutteral and strangulated, like a scary infant death rattle.
</P>
<P>
   This is my evening serenade. This is the time when Rebecca
Lucia, the usually delightful biscuit of love, becomes a raging,
head-spinning, Exorcist-style pocket monster. And her softhearted
mother, for the umpteenth time, will trot upstairs to rescue the
screaming angel from behind the bars of her prison crib.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, as I write this column, we've been through the ritual
yet again. We pretend to put her down, we wait through the screams,
then, against my stern protests, Maureen picks her back up. And
there they are, the picture of Madonna-ish tranquility, Becca
sucking away and Maureen giving me the hairy eyeball.
</P>
<P>
   The poor little thing rubs her eyes and puts her fist in her
mouth and is obviously tired. She should be. It's almost 11 p.m.
But unlike her brother Joseph, Becca does not like to sleep. She
does not go gently into that good night. She is dragged kicking and
screaming beneath the waters of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The pediatrician tells us that at 5 months an infant can learn
to put herself to sleep. Most babies will resist at first, says the
doctor, but within three days the fight will dwindle to a few
moments of whimpering, and then it's off to dreamland.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we haven't made it past Day One yet. In fact I think
Becca's stamina is actually increasing, as we train her to hold out
longer. (Her current record is 56 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   I have no desire to let babies cry. But I don't think we should
practice this halfhearted tough love. I say let's soldier through,
at least one night. Or else let's just admit defeat, brew some
coffee and call it a slumber party.
</P>
<P>
   Write married staffers Maureen Downey and Bo Emerson at The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
E-mail them at bemerson(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
