<HEADER>
A6262 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-CHANGES08-COX     06-07 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-CHANGES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN Headline News getting a new format
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the deal: It's the news for people without much free
time. People with remotes.
</P>
<P>
   A bit succinct, perhaps, but that's right up CNN Headline News'
alley. On Monday, the cable network that provides the latest news
every half-hour unveiled format changes aimed at better serving its
younger-skew-
</P>
<P>
   ing, increasingly time-pressed, audience.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 6 p.m. June 15, there'll be more stories. Graphics
highlighting upcoming stories. Plus no more grouping of stories by
topics, such as politics, international news or _ where's that
clicker?! _ science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   And get ready, sports fans. That ticker of scores and stock info
will keep running onscreen, even when the network cuts away to
national commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the youngest demographics of all the news networks,''
said Headline News president Bob Furnad, who characterized
competitor MSNBC's audience as nearly six years older than Headline
News' ``time optimizers.'' ``(They're) people who are juggling work
and the gym and hobbies and family and have little time, but people
to whom news is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the major changes announced Monday:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More news: Story count has already been increased by 50
percent each half-hour, Furnad said. Packages from CNN, which
generally run about two minutes, are being cut down by as much as
45 seconds. On Sunday nights and Monday mornings, ``Week
at-a-Glance'' will flag important upcoming events; on weekends,
``Headline News Best Bets on . . .'' will use input from Time Inc.
magazines to recommend movies, investments, etc.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Less ``flow'': That's news biz talk for grouping stories by
topics, which Headline News will eschew in hopes of keeping
viewers. Or maybe not. An onscreen ``sidebar'' will identify the
next two stories coming up on the news segment. ``We think that
time optimizers will find the network more useful,'' Furnad said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Less repetition: The 24-hour broadcast day will be divided
into four, six-hour ``dayparts,'' each with its own name, on-air
color and anchor. (For instance, ``Third Watch,'' from 6 p.m. to
midnight, will feature popular anchor Lynne Russell and green as
its main color.) And with the exception of some major breaking
stories, one daypart's news packages won't repeat on another's.
``So if you saw a Wolf Blitzer package today at 7 a.m., you won't
see that Wolf Blitzer piece this afternoon between noon and six,''
Furnad vowed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More stocks and jocks: Furnad hears the most complaints about
the ``superticker'' disappearing during commercials. But now, the
onscreen ``crawl,'' featuring sports scores, stock quotes, state
news and weather, will be larger, easier-to-read _ and remain
visible during national advertising.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More visibility: The network will spend several million
dollars on promotion _ both on sister channels and elsewhere _ in
an offbeat ad campaign created by a New York agency. It's the first
time Headline News has hired an outside agency to promote itself.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
