<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6264 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOTFATIGUE-2ndTake-     06-07 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOTFATIGUE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: safety proposals. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Safety Board's in-depth investigations have clearly
demonstrated that fatigue is a major factor in transportation
accidents,'' the report says. ``Despite the many statements made by
the DOT about the importance of addressing fatigue in
transportation, only one of the three intermodal recommendations
issued to the DOT more than 10 years ago has been fully
implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting a two-year time frame, NTSB officials went on to call
for research-based FAA regulations that set hours of service and
consider predictable ``human sleep and rest'' needs and circadian
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that accidents can be prevented by making sure
people are more alert during certain times of the day and working
so many hours,'' said Ted Lopatkiewicz, NTSB public affairs
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, identifying fatigue as an accident factor is
difficult for investigators. Unlike drugs or alcohol, no one can be
chemically tested for exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Little Rock will be relying primarily on
circumstantial evidence, such as admissions of fatigue, co-workers'
testimony, recorded voice transmissions that indicate tiredness,
logging of long duty or flight hours, hours slept and circadian
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation watchers say myriad psychological factors could be at
work, including what Burnett calls ``get-there-itis,'' which
affects some pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, ``You want to get the plane down and get home,''
Burnett said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's what many believe is a common pilot mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilots don't tend to say, `We're too fatigued,''' said David
Stempler, president of the Air Travelers Association in Washington.
``One of the great traits pilots have is their can-do spirit, that
they think they can accomplish anything. But that's also one of
their problems _ they could say, `Let's get to Little Rock
tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to revise work-shift times have been stalemated almost
every step of the way by a lack of resolution among the FAA, pilots
associations and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue factors began grabbing attention in Washington in 1989,
after the NTSB found several transportation accidents during that
decade were at least partially caused by fatigue. It urged the
industry to launch fatigue research programs, develop educational
materials and upgrade regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the NTSB placed ``operator fatigue'' on its list of
most wanted transportation safety improvements. It has stayed there
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The only major change has been to bring noncommercial, or cargo,
planes under many of the same standards as commercial flights,
shortening some pilot duty and flight times in that industry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the FAA announced the formation of a rule-making
committee to tackle some of the fatigue issues and, a few years
later, came up with proposals that included minimum daily rest
periods of at least 10 hours and 36 consecutive hours of rest
within seven calendar days of duty. Those recommendations
languished. In 1996, another working group was formed and
established goals but couldn't decide how to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   Unions such as the Air Line Pilots Association, based in
Herndon, Va., lobbied for many changes but ran into opposition from
airlines and air-equipment manufacturers, their officials said.
They have pushed for tighter duty times, proposing 12-hour duty
times and greater rest periods for pilots and crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines have been opposed to it because they see it as
restricting their ability to schedule pilots,'' said Bob Flocke, a
spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   But Walt Coleman, president of the Regional Airline Association,
said airlines simply want regulations grounded in scientific
theory, not guesswork.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious issue in that there's a continuing
difference of opinion as to what some will say is a contributing
factor,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that pilots must meet their responsibilities ``to
be fit to fly'' and must acknowledge their fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   There's more to the debate than just caps on shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Other fatigue concerns include adequate rest time for reserve
pilots _ those who are ``on call'' for 24 hours over as many as
five days with no guaranteed rest periods _ and rest periods that
take into account commute times from pilots' homes.
</P>
<P>
   Only five carriers have schedules that permit crew rest while on
reserve status. American is not among them, said American Airlines
Capt. Rich Rubin, the Allied Pilots Association's expert on pilot
fatigue. The Allied Pilots represent American's 9,300 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Stemper said that he believes that a tragedy tied to fatigue
unfortunately will have to be the motivating force in revising and
unifying work-shift limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a very complicated set of regulations, and that
makes it very hard for the guys in the business,'' Stemper said.
``Unfortunately, it's sort of a tombstone mentality at the FAA.
Until things get really bad, it doesn't get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, FAA chief Jane Garvey met Friday morning with a group
of pilots, including Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working quietly within the system for years to get
the FAA to take this important step to protect the ... public,''
said Rubin, a Miami-based 767 captain who chaired the FAA working
group on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he believes that the maximum period for continuous
duty should be 12 hours. ``Fatigue is typically a factor of time on
task and time awake. When you're fatigued, you make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
