<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6272 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOTFATIGUE-1000(2Ta     06-07 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOTFATIGUE-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE ROCK CRASH RAISES ISSUE OF PILOT FATIGUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MILES MOFFEIT 
and MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aviation experts believe that it is a significant factor in many
airplane accidents. Federal safety board officials have
consistently ranked it among their ``most wanted safety
improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   It also happens to be a political hot potato that has been
tossed back and forth within the Federal Aviation Administration
since the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The subject: pilot fatigue and whether decades-old regulations
governing how long pilots work need to be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators study the June 1 crash of American Airlines
Flight 1420, possible weariness in the cockpit is a focus of the
National Transportation Safety Board, which has pushed for FAA
policy revisions to reduce fatigue in transportation industries.
</P>
<P>
   Some aviation experts are troubled that American pilot Richard
Buschmann, who was killed in the crash, had logged 13 hours and 20
minutes. They wonder whether a powerful mix of fatigue and other
stresses contributed to Buschmann's decision to land despite
gale-force storms around Little Rock National Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the crash, the safety board released new safety
recommendations to the FAA, urging revisions to pilot work shifts
now capped at 16 hours and rebuking them for dragging their feet on
revisions since 1989. The NTSB report and the questions surrounding
the Little Rock crash have reopened the debate on pilot fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Although FAA officials declined to comment on the NTSB report,
they said Friday that they would step up surveillance of the
flight/duty time rules and that air carriers must comply with
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has never cited a carrier for failure to comply with
duty time rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting the airlines on notice that we're going to be
enforcing the existing regulation,'' FAA spokeswoman Diane
Spitaliere said.
</P>
<P>
   The new scrutiny is unrelated to the Little Rock crash, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buschmann was well within federal standards, but his workload is
still viewed by some as too lengthy _ 7 1/2 hours of his shift
involved flying the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Former NTSB Chairman Jim Burnett, a safety consultant who
visited the Little Rock wreckage this week, said duty limits on
pilots should be re-examined. Current law restricts pilots of large
commercial planes to 16-hour shifts and no more than eight ``flight
hours'' on the shift. American Airlines' standard, stated in labor
contracts, is 14 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett contends that those limits are lax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked 14 hours yesterday, but what I do is not critical to
human lives the way pilots' jobs are,'' Burnett said. ``The last
act of every pilot's workday is landing the airplane. That act may
become routine, but at the end of a 14-hour workday, judgment calls
may not be alert enough to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Other aviation experts caution against drawing quick conclusions
based on the Little Rock crash.
</P>
<P>
   Although pilot fatigue has been viewed as a factor in crashes
involving planes flying for at least 20 small U.S. air carriers,
including cargo companies, in the last 20 years, according to NTSB
records, fatigue findings have been rarer in major airline
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important issue, but a slippery issue,'' said Mike
Overly, editor of the Aviation Safety Monitor based in Ohio. ``It's
just very difficult to pin down. It seems you might be able to look
at the duty hours and say they're too close (to the limit), but you
don't know actually what transpired.''
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines is not releasing recent work schedules of the
Flight 1420 cockpit crew. Nor are company officials commenting on
whether exhaustion could have been a factor. But airline spokesman
Tim Smith said the pilots were within allowable work-shift limits
set by union contracts and federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both pilots had been off for several days prior to the
accident,'' Smith said, stressing that most of American's work
limits are tougher than federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigators acknowledged that they would be studying
possible fatigue factors in examining the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have recovered recorders and the tower transmissions. From
here we will go into understanding what the pilots were trying to
do,'' said George Black, an NTSB spokesman, adding that the
circadian rhythms of the crew would be examined.
</P>
<P>
   Circadian rhythms are a hot topic among NASA researchers who
have developed fatigue countermeasure programs. They believe flight
duties should, whenever possible, be scheduled to conform with
natural body rhythms, which cause most people to function more
alertly in late morning and early evening hours. They also
recommend that work shifts should be scheduled to ensure that crew
members stay alert.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The new safety recommendations issued by NTSB officials June 1
urge the Federal Aviation Administration to establish
scientifically based standards for addressing crew fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Although it praised some agencies for making headway in
fatigue-education programs, the safety report sharply criticized
the U.S. Department of Transportation and the FAA for not
addressing many NTSB safety proposals.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
