<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Oppressive heat and humidity will continue for one more day
across the Northeast before a cool front slowly sags southward into
the region. Areas from southern New England to Virginia will see
temperatures soaring into the '90s as well as very high humidities
to make it feel as if it is near 110 degrees in many locations.
</P>
<P>
   A cool front stretching from northern New England to the upper
Great Lakes will spark a line of fast moving, strong thunderstorms
over northern New York, Vermont and New Hampshire. The passage of
the front in the upper Great Lakes will be more benign as only a
few showers are expected.
</P>
<P>
   A ridge of high pressure off the Carolina coast will keep much
of the southern Atlantic states under mostly sunny skies and very
warm temperatures. Meanwhile, a weak disturbance aloft will trigger
more showers and thunderstorms from Florida to Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by a warm, moist flow from the Gulf of Mexico,
thunderstorms will erupt in the central Great Plains. A low
pressure system moving out of the Rockies will initiate a few more
showers and perhaps a rumble of thunder over the Dakotas. Behind
this storm, much of Montana will once again see periods of rain and
drizzle as well as temperatures struggling to reach the upper 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will inundate the Pacific Northwest as cool, moist air
from the Pacific is forced up the coastal ranges. Sunny skies will
prevail across the Southwest, except on the immediate Southern
California coastline where a persistent marine layer will slowly
dissipate throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Heat Index
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the Northeast have been under a heat warning for Monday
and Tuesday. A heat warning is usually issued when the heat index
is forecasted to rise above 100 degrees on consecutive days. The
heat index, a warm season analog to wind chill, is an attempt to
quantify the effects on humans of the combination of warmth and
high humidity. When the air has a high moisture content, cooling by
evaporation from the skin is reduced and the stress on the human
body is increased. However, the heat index does not account for
variables like wind or sunshine, which can contribute to heat
stress.
</P>
</TEXT>
