<HEADER>
A6276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT08-COX     06-07 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IBM: MICROSOFT BROKE THE ANTITRUST LAWS
 &HT;    460&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in the Microsoft trial, a
federal court heard a corporate witness provide clear evidence
Monday that the software giant had broken the nation's antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed accusations came from Garry Norris, a mid-level IBM
Corp. manager.
</P>
<P>
   He testified that Microsoft refused to renew IBM's licenses for
Windows at a competitive price because IBM would not agree to stop
selling computers loaded with its competing OS/2 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would Microsoft tolerate IBM's resolve to market its Lotus
Smart Suite, an all-inclusive business product in competition with
Microsoft Office, Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, IBM did obtain a Windows 95 license. But, Norris
charged, Microsoft charged an inflated royalty, and it agreed to
sign only 15 minutes before Windows 95 went on public sale in 1995.
That, in itself, cost IBM millions of dollars in lost revenue
because the company was unable to preload the operating system on
its machines prior to the rollout.
</P>
<P>
   Norris quoted Mark Baber, a former Microsoft executive who
negotiated with IBM during the period, as telling him: ``This is
the only game in town. Where else are you going to go?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crystal clear to us that there was no viable commercial
alternative,'' said Norris, who kept a detailed journal of his
troubled negotiations with Microsoft officials.
</P>
<P>
   Norris served a crucial witness for the government after none of
the nation's major computer makers proved willing to support the
government's claims that Microsoft uses the prices for its dominant
Windows operating system to penalize enemies and reward allies.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that, the Justice Department was obliged to issue
subpoenas to compel Norris to testify and for IBM to produce a
welter of purportedly incriminating documents. Once he took the
witness stand, however, Norris became a highly cooperative witness
for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Summarizing outside the courtroom what he viewed as the
``devastating impact'' of Norris's testimony, David Boies, the
government's lead lawyer, said, ``When you have monopoly power, the
law says you are clearly not free to go out and try to induce
people not to compete. Agreements not to compete are fundamentally
inconsistent with the free market system and the anti-trust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Murray, a Microsoft spokesman, said the ``government had
presented a selective and one-sided narrative of the complex
business relationship'' between the two large firms. It will be
corrected when Norris is cross-examined, probably on Tuesday,
Murray predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Microsoft President Steve Ballmer said in a CNBC
interview that ``we didn't try to push out OS/2 in any sense in the
negotiations we had with IBM.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   On the witness stand, Norris recalled that Microsoft Chairman
Bill Gates became so angry over IBM's defiance on the software
issue that the multibillionaire screamed at Norris's boss during a
phone call a July 1995 while Norris stood nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty loud,'' Norris said, eliciting nervous laughter
in the crowded courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Norris worked for an IBM division based in Raleigh,
N.C., that produced a line of personal computers closely mated to a
``family'' of Microsoft software. Meantime, another IBM division
based in Austin, Tex., was marketing both OS/2 and Windows versions
of Lotus Smart Suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we were competing, we were suffering,'' Norris said.
``They were a liability to the IBM PC company.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris, frustrated by his inability to strike what he viewed as
fair agreements with Microsoft in 1995 and 1996, testified that IBM
saw the total fees it paid to Microsoft rise from $40 million in
1996 to $440 million last year as a result of its stance.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who will rule in
the antitrust trial later this year, took frequent notes,
occasionally asked clarifying questions and closely studied e-mails
and other documents projected on a 10-foot screen in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
