</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories on Kosovo for
Tuesday, June 8.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Bonn, Germany) _ Ledeall. Daylong talks among
foreign ministers of the United States, six other Western nations
and Russia broke up Monday without Moscow's agreement on tough NATO
peace terms for Kosovo that are laid out in a draft U.N. Security
Council resolution. Developing. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ When he heard the news of a
peace deal between NATO and the Yugoslav government last week _ a
deal that might send him back home after two months as a refugee _
Ismet Memaj reacted by celebrating. ``I drank all day,'' said
Memaj, a 52-year-old construction worker. ``It's true. I was so
happy.'' By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO held back most of Monday
on carrying out threats to intensify its bombing of Yugoslavia if
Belgrade did not promptly accept allied terms on Kosovo. Allied
officials said they hoped that the restraint would help persuade
Russia to back a U.N. Security Council resolution on ending the
crisis. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Jazince, Macedonia) _ Macedonian government
officials Monday said over thirty rounds were fired into this
border village by Yugoslav forces Sunday night from inside Kosovo.
The attack was the most serious eruption of violence along the
Kosovo-Macedonia border since NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia began in
late March. What motivated the attack was not clear, but they
illustrated both the ability of Yugoslav forces to destabilize the
border area and the continuing operations of the Kosovo Liberation
Army in Macedonia. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ White House reaction, plans,
etc. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Krnjaca, Serbia) _ For five years they have
lived, four adults in a single room, in this drab compound of
makeshift huts on the outskirts of Belgrade. The Sehovac family,
Serbs who fled Sarajevo in 1994, are sunk in a world of depression
and bitterness. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ The military talks
intended to seal the withdrawal of Serbian forces from Kosovo fell
apart over the weekend when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
realized that this technical military agreement would become the
legal basis for the Kosovo peacekeeping forces, rather than a U.N.
referendum, which he believed had been agreed to in the peace
settlement reached last week, according to NATO and senior Western
diplomats. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
