<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLPHONES-EMAIL-COX     06-07 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONES-EMAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Email over the cell phone? Soon, Southern LINC says
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern LINC said Tuesday it plans to offer its
customers the ability to send and receive E-mail from their
wireless phone.
</P>
<P>
   The features, expected to be available by fall, include using
your cellular phone screen as a small Web browser, access to
bookmarked Web sites to check stock prices, weather conditions or
any other text-based information available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The new features will be available to Southern LINC's customers
in its six-state coverage area. The company has not said how much
it would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Southern LINC is the telecommunications division of Southern
Company, a regional utility company based in Atlanta. The company
has more than 100,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Southern LINC's digital wireless coverage area includes part of
southeastern Mississippi, including Biloxi, Hattiesburg and
Meridian; most of Alabama and Georgia, sections of north Florida,
including Pensacola and Panama City, and smaller bits of southern
Tennessee and western South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The company's product is a blend of two-way radio and cell
phone: It gives one-button access to one person or a group, or
traditional cellular phone service or paging, which transmits
numbers or words.
</P>
<P>
   The new features add a Web browser, e-mail and fax capabilities
to the wireless phone. The small Web browser can display up to 6
lines and 16 characters at one time. Users can edit which e-mails
are forwarded to their wireless phone. Replies are typed in, using
the phone's number pad and a predictive speller technology.
</P>
<P>
   The company initially targeted businesses with a mobile
workforce but has been adding traditional business customers, said
Robert G. Dawson, Southern LINC's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
