<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMM08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supercomm99 to showcase merger of mediums, ADSL standardBy
Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Convergence of the telephone, other telecommunication
devices and the PC is the hot topic at this year's Supercomm99
going on now through Thursday at the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   Billing itself as the Number One communications industry event,
Supercomm has more than 700 exhibitors and plenty of flash and
glitz to promote the latest products and services for what is now a
very hot part of the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 46,000 attendees walked the floors of last year's
conference, and an equal, if not larger number of industry
professionals, analysts and entrepreneurs are expected to attend
this year. High on this year's agenda is the deployment of
high-speed Digital Subscriber Line telephone access to the
Internet, fiber optics and ``last-mile'' access from the
telecommunications provider to the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The Supercomm exhibitors and panels are focused on products and
technologies that can speed the process of bringing ``always on''
Internet access to home Net users. Most major telecommunications
companies including BellSouth, BellAtlantic, SBC and others are
beginning to deploy high-speed Internet service, but getting that
service to every telephone customer has been rough going for a
variety of technical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Also topping the agenda is the adoption next month of the
Universal ADSL standard, a type of modem jointly developed by
telecommunications and computer companies that facilitates the
installation and use of high speed Internet access service.
</P>
<P>
   One lesson the conference learned from last year is that a
number of analysts, brokers, venture capitalists and others come
trying to find ``the next big thing'' in telecommunications. To
accommodate this audience segment, Supercomm will offer financial
presentations by communications companies.
</P>
<P>
   Along with traditional telecommunications companies, there is
also an increasing number of start-up companies looking to find a
niche in a rapidly expanding sector. Highlighting the diversity of
this year's Supercomm is this year's keynote address from Microsoft
president Steve Ballmer, who is expected to discuss how the
software giant plans to establish its presence in the broadband
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Information about Supercomm: www.supercomm99.com
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
