<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, June 8. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Bonn, Germany) _ Ledeall. Daylong talks among
foreign ministers of the United States, six other Western nations
and Russia break up without Moscow's agreement on tough NATO peace
terms for Kosovo that are laid out in a draft U.N. Security Council
resolution. Developing. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ When he heard the news of a
peace deal between NATO and the Yugoslav government last week _ a
deal that might send him back home after two months as a refugee _
Ismet Memaj reacted by celebrating. ``I drank all day,'' said
Memaj, a 52-year-old construction worker. ``It's true. I was so
happy.'' By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Jazince, Macedonia) _ Macedonian government
officials say that more than thirty rounds were fired into this
border village by Yugoslav forces Sunday night from inside Kosovo.
The attack was the most serious eruption of violence along the
Kosovo-Macedonia border since NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia began in
late March. What motivated the attack was not clear, but they
illustrated both the ability of Yugoslav forces to destabilize the
border area and the continuing operations of the Kosovo Liberation
Army in Macedonia. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BIRTH (Mexico City) _ Like many old-style Mexican
matriarchs, Emma Castro Amador bore so many children that she can't
keep their birthdays straight. In a generational divide repeated in
millions of Mexican families, all 14 of her children say they are
determined to limit their own families to two or three children.
The national fertility rate is down from an average of 7 to 2.5 and
that means a lot, for the entire continent. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   STUN-GUNS-PRISONS (Undated) _ Amnesty International says prisons
are using stun belts to control prisoners. Is this legal? By
Williams Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta) _ Ballot counting continues amid a
sense of exhilaration. But the ruling party is getting a bit
fidgety; top party official talks about fears of having to settle
for third place. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BALLOTING (Dadap) _ As the ballot counting began in
this fishing village west of Jakarta today, a crowd of eagle-eyed
locals encircled a makeshift polling place. They watched as workers
laboriously unfolded and called out each vote. It was a tedious
business, but nobody here was complaining. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CABINET (Jerusalem) _ Parliament is sworn in; oddly,
Netanyahu is still in charge because there is no new government. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH-CONFERENCE (Washington) _ White House mental
health conference: the two first couples are together again,
pushing for parity in mental health insurance coverage; we look at
how they interact and what it means to the coming campaigns of the
two candidates. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FREE-HEROIN-PROGRAM (Undated) _ Taking a bold approach to
drug addiction, researchers at Columbia University are offering
free heroin to addicts and paying them to use it under a federally
authorized program aimed at finding a cure for their addictions.
Two trials involving heroin injections are among six related
drug-addiction studies being conducted at Columbia's College of
Physicians and Surgeons, all of which focus on the role existing
medications can play in defeating drug addictions. By Christopher
S. Wren. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
