u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEY-CAPSULE-C     06-07 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY-CAPSULE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stanley Cup Finals at a glance
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buffalo Sabres vs. Dallas Stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Resumes: Buffalo went 37-28-18 during the regular season and
eliminated Ottawa (4-0), Boston (4-2) and Toronto (4-1) in the
Eastern Conference playoffs. Dallas went 51-19-12 during the
regular season and eliminated Edmonton (4-0), St. Louis (4-3) and
Colorado (4-3) in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   _ Head to head: Each team won at home in two regular-season
meetings. The Stars won 4-1 Oct. 10, scoring three power-play goals
against Dominik Hasek. Buffalo won 2-1 on March 5 behind rookie
goalie Martin Biron when Hasek was injured.
</P>
<P>
   _ Final exams: Neither franchise has won a Cup. The Sabres lost
to Philadelphia 4-2 in 1974-75. The Stars lost twice when based in
Minnesota, 4-1 to the New York Islanders in 1980-81 and 4-2 to
Pittsburgh in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
   _ Numbers: Hasek (11-2, 1.82 goals-against, .938 saves pct.) has
been typically impressive, but he has had to be a one-man team of
late. Offensively, the Sabres have been led in the playoffs by
Curtis Brown (7-5-12), Dixon Ward (6-5-11), Michael Peca (4-8-12)
and Jason Wooley (3-10-13). Miroslav Satan (40 goals regular
season) recently returned from an ankle injury. For Dallas, Joe
Nieuwendyk (9-9-18) has been unstoppable and remains the best
face-off man in the league. Just behind are Mike Modano (5-11-16),
Jamie Langenbrunner (9-5-14) and Brett Hull (5-7-12). Ed Belfour's
numbers (12-5, 1.83, .927) rival Hasek's.
</P>
<P>
   _ How Dallas can win: The Stars are deeper and more experienced,
and they excel in positional, reactive hockey. If the Stars force
the Sabres' speedy wingers to the outside and limit rebound
attempts against goalie Ed Belfour, they have the ability to sweep
this series. Dallas' power play has struggled in the playoffs (12.3
percent) but has successfully killed 88.7 percent of its penalties.
</P>
<P>
   _ How Buffalo can win: The Sabres need to exploit their two best
weapons: Hasek and speed. If the world's best goalie can keep
Dallas in check, the Stars might wear down. They are a relatively
old team and have played consecutive seven-game series. Buffalo has
been off for 10 days and creates scoring chances off its speed. The
Sabres also have become a more aggressive offensive team as the
playoffs have gone on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Dallas in six.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
