<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL Notes: Expansion team begins search for coach
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ While two teams prepare to play for a Stanley Cup, the
general manager of the Atlanta Thrashers takes his coaching search
to a new level today.
</P>
<P>
   Don Waddell will interview former Phoenix coach Don Hay today
for Atlanta's head-coaching vacancy. Hay becomes the first
candidate brought to Atlanta to get past the
informal-interview-and-lunch level. Hay, a long-time successful
coach in the Canadian juniors, coaches Tri-City in the Western
League.
</P>
<P>
   A new name is on the Thrashers' list of candidates: Ron Low. Low
resigned as Edmonton coach late Sunday after refusing a one-year
extension without a raise from his salary of $325,000, which was
the second-lowest among league coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should talk to him,'' said Waddell, who has been
doing background checks on Low and several other potential
candidates. ``He did a good job in Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell would not say if he would bring Low to Atlanta for a
formal interview. The GM also has had preliminary meetings with
former Buffalo coach Ted Nolan and Ottawa assistant Mike Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Low coached the financially strapped Oilers for five seasons,
the second longest tenure in the league to Scotty Bowman's six with
Detroit. His cumulative record is 106-125-28, including 33-37-12
this year and three playoff appearances in a row, but the Oilers
never made it past the second round. Low's contract expired June 1,
and Edmonton GM Glen Sather offered only the one-year deal.
Assistant Kevin Lowe is expected to be named his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, neither Buffalo assistant coach Don Lever nor Dallas
assistants Doug Jarvis or Rick Wilson, all possible Atlanta
candidates, have been contacted. Lever said Monday that he got in
touch with Thrashers assistant GM Les Jackson during the season.
``I'm hoping to hear from them when we get done with the
playoffs,'' said Lever, who played for the Atlanta Flames for four
months. ``I'd like to have a crack at it.''
</P>
<P>
   No underdog
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said his team has no reason to
underrate Buffalo. ``They were a seven seed (in the East) only
because they had injuries,'' Hitchcock said. ``They were a one or
two seed around Christmas, but injuries pushed them down. After
they swept Ottawa in the first round, you could see this was a
legitimate hockey team. When we lost to them in Buffalo this year,
our players left the game feeling that New Jersey and Buffalo were
the two best teams we had faced.''
</P>
<P>
   Slush update
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff didn't expect the ice in Reunion Arena
to be very good _ and his fears were realized. ``It's good for
about the first five or 10 minutes, then it's a problem,'' Ruff
said. ``It will hinder us because we're a skating team but we'll
have to adjust to it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
