A6303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOYERS-TV-REVIEW-NYT     06-07 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOYERS-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION REVIEW: THE ISSUE OF FREE SPEECH, THE VOICE OF BIG
MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Moyers begins ``Free Speech for Sale,'' Tuesday
night's vigorous assault on the power of moneyed interests in
American politics, with the story of Cindy Watson, a Republican
member of the North Carolina General Assembly who took on the
state's hog farmers. When her constituents complained about the
odors of hog waste and its effect on drinking water, she pushed for
restrictions on the growth of hog farms, the state's biggest
agricultural industry, until they cleaned up their act.
</P>
<P>
   Well, in the next election, Ms. Watson was cleaned away with a
big-money television blitz by a group calling itself Farmers for
Fairness, a euphemism for the hog growers. As long as such front
groups avoid the words ``vote for'' or ``vote against,'' they are
not regulated by campaign finance laws. Thus, by courtesy of a much
criticized Supreme Court ruling, special interests have been
granted the rights of free speech once reserved for individuals,
insuring that plenty of money is available to enhance corporate
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Moyers' report, which echoes the arguments of advocates for
tougher rules on campaign spending, confirms that the hoggish
pursuit of power is not confined to the hog business.
</P>
<P>
   Take the cigarette companies. In their 1998 fight to defeat the
popular McCain bill, which would have held the tobacco industry
accountable for the deleterious health effects of smoking, big
tobacco spent a record $40 million on what Moyers calls ``salvo
after salvo of half-truths and distortions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Free Speech for Sale'' offers little hope that television news
can be depended on to cover touchy issues. Critics of the 1996
Telecommunications Act, which is described Tuesday night as a
giveaway to media heavyweights, report that in nine months of
debate the three major networks' evening news programs carried only
19 minutes on an act that meant billions for their bosses. The
crucial question of whether broadcasters should be made to pay for
control of the new digital spectrum, which promises to bring them
fresh fortunes, went largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lewis of the Center for Public Integrity, who keeps an
eye on big-money propaganda, says that for the networks to have
covered the digital spectrum issue ``would be like a bank robber
stopping the bank robbery and saying: `Look at what we're doing
here. Let's have a press conference in front of the bank while
we're doing it.'''
</P>
<P>
   With media conglomerates being steadily engorged through mergers
and consolidations, the prospect of news departments' taking on
their own industries becomes ever dimmer. The message of ``Free
Speech for Sale'' is that speech has become an expensive commodity
that only the very wealthy can afford and can be counted on to use
to drown out less powerful voices.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A BILL MOYERS SPECIAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Free Speech for Sale'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 9) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith Davidson Moyers and Judy Doctoroff O'Neill, executive
producers; Bill Moyers, executive editor; Kathleen Hughes and Tom
Casciato, producers; Andrew Fredericks, editor; Greg Henry,
associate producer. A production of Public Affairs Television Inc.
with Okapi Productions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
