<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARRIERE-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-07 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARRIERE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WRITER FOR FILM DIRECTORS PUTS HIS IDEAS INTO PLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In any accounting of the most important people in the performing
arts this century, Luis Bunuel and Peter Brook would figure
prominently. Because he is far less well known, Jean-Claude
Carriere would probably not make the list. But he is the primary
writer behind the vastly different directors: Bunuel, the creator
of dreamlike reveries on eroticism and society; Brook, the ensemble
explorer of cultural myths.
</P>
<P>
   It is with Carriere that the directors have had their longest
and most rewarding creative relationship. By his own description,
he is ``a transmitter'' who has chosen to spend most of his life as
a conduit for the visions of other artists, as, in effect, a
servant of two masters.
</P>
<P>
   Carriere, who is French and lives in Paris, wrote six of
Bunuel's most memorable films, including ``Belle de Jour'' and
``Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie.'' Over 25 years, he also did
the adaptations for Brook's stage productions of ``The Conference
of the Birds,'' ``The Tragedy of Carmen'' and ``The Mahabarata,''
among others.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, explaining his relationship with Carriere, Bunuel
said, ``I give my ideas and we discuss them and then he writes for
me.'' The director wanted an instant reaction, and each had a right
of veto. During a recent visit to New York, Carriere said, ``I had
to help him find what he really wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In his memoir, ``Threads of Time,'' Brook wrote about their
decade of work together on ``The Mahabarata.'' Carriere, he said,
was ``never satisfied, always open to criticism, untiring, never
short of ideas, writing all the time.'' He added, ``I cannot
imagine a better collaborator.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the adaptable Carriere was the writer or one of the
writers for the films ``Danton,'' ``The Return of Martin Guerre,''
``The Tin Drum'' and ``The Unbearable Lightness of Being.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another, more personal aspect to his career. He has
written four original plays, the latest of which, ``La Terrasse,''
is in previews and is scheduled to open Tuesday night at the
Manhattan Theater Club. In New York briefly for that production,
Carriere talked about his play and his collaborative techniques.
The idea for his new play had been fermenting for 30 years, ever
since he and Milos Forman were working on a screenplay in an
apartment in Paris. A real estate agent arrived with a prospective
tenant. Carriere thought that would be an interesting way for
characters to meet.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally wrote ``La Terrasse'' several years ago, it
became a comedy about diverse people who come together in an
apartment suddenly on the market. A stranger inspects the rooms at
the same time that the couple living there are breaking up. The
intrusive visitor begins making demands. Soon he is in the kitchen
fixing a late lunch. Later he decides to take a nap. As other
characters enter, slamming doors and jumping off the apartment's
terrace, the play evokes the feeling of a classic French farce with
a touch of Ionesco. The playwright freely acknowledged the
influences while adding that the writing was also intuitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream of a writer is to be surprised by his characters,''
he said. ``All of a sudden, they are living their own lives; they
are not prisoners anymore.'' In this case, he has an adapter, Mark
O'Donnell, who did the English-language version of the play. It is
directed by Mike Ockrent.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his career, Carriere, a large, bearded and
effusive man, said it was a natural progression for him to become a
writer and an adapter of the works of others. He was born 67 years
ago in Colombieres sur Orb. At first he had considered teaching
history, but then he wrote a novel. From there, it was a sidestep
into films, in which he always had a major interest.
</P>
<P>
   Carriere gave full credit to his directors for their
inspiration. As he once said, ``My collaborators oblige me to
think.'' He met Bunuel in 1963 when he was one of many candidates
to write the screenplay for Bunuel's ``Diary of a Chambermaid.'' At
their first meeting at a hotel in the south of France, the director
asked Carriere if he drank wine. He answered that not only did he
drink wine, but that his family owned a vineyard. Apparently that
was the right answer. It endeared him to the director, who
immediately began what turned into a 20-year working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Carriere also wrote Bunuel's autobiography,
``My Last Breath,'' one of many signs of his power of mimicry. When
Bunuel read a sample chapter, he said: ``This is very strange. I
have a feeling I have written this.'' Carriere took that as a very
high compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Bunuel's effect on him was so strong, Carriere said, that 16
years after the director's death there is ``no one day in my life
that I do not pass some time with him.'' He added, ``He helps me
now not only in my work but in my life.'' He was absolutely
faithful to his principles. ``He said what he would not do for one
dollar he would not do for one million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the two directors, Carriere reached for metaphors:
``Peter is a brook, like clear water going from one ground to
another one, bringing fertility. Bunuel was a block of Spanish
stone. You have to dig inside to find if there is some corner of
the stone which has not been explored yet.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bunuel, the work was all done privately between the
director and the writer. With Brook, Carriere became a member of
the director's company, even exercising with the actors. He was
responsible for the text and he was expected to be able to explain
the dramatic movement to the actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no neat separation between the writing and the
directing,'' he said. ``If I need Peter _ and very often I need him
when we are translating Shakespeare because he knows Shakespeare
better than anybody in the world _ he is with me, on my shoulder.
And when we go from the writing to the directing, I am with him.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
