<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PA SENATORS REACT TO KOSOVO PEACE AGREEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mary M. Shaffrey  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 7 - The peace agreement reached last week
between Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and the international
community has fallen apart, but Pennsylvania's senators still want
the issue addressed and are not backing down from their original
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter (R) sent a letter to President Clinton last
Thursday urging him to make sure any peace agreement reached would
include the extradition of President Milosovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a peace settlement that leaves Milosevic as
President of Yugoslavia, we invite his initiating future wars...and
we allow him to get away with murder because we acknowledge his
bargaining power,'' Specter said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   He also went on to say Secretary of State Madeline Albright has
recognized the threat of keeping Milosevic in power, because his
history of starting four wars in the past indicates he will start
another war in the future.
</P>
<P>
   John Ullyot, a spokesman for Specter, said it was too premature
to comment on the status of the peace talks, but that Specter is
``anxious to see that Milosevic is brought to trial at The Hague
(Netherlands) for his war crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Traynham, Press Secretary for Sen. Rick Santorum (R) said
that Santorum shares the same concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still unanswered questions, specifically how do you
treat Slobodan Milosevic and who is going to pay for everything,''
said Traynham.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania residents' calls into Santorum's office have been
mixed, but people are getting their thoughts across.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are calling and saying that we shouldn't be over
there in the first place and say this recent action is just the
proof in the pudding,'' Trayhnam said.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's office has not received that many calls, said Ullyot.
But according to the www.senatevotes.com site, where constituents
can post e-mail messages for their senators, Specter is getting an
earfull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't we learn anything from Viet Nam? Haven't we learned to
stay out of others Civil Wars?'' asked Paul Cruce. Cruce went on to
say that President Clinton was using this war to divert attention
from ``Chinagate,'' and he urged Specter to ``Quit being the
Demoncraps accessories to the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The peace talks broke down over the weekend when Serbian
military leaders rejected the terms of the agreement reached last
week. Milosevic stated today that he is committed to peace in the
area, but there is still disagreement over when the Serbian troops
will leave Kosovo and what role Russia will play in the
peacekeeping operation. Talks are scheduled to resume tomorrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARRIERE-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      06-07 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARRIERE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: with him.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each was the most demanding of directors, he said: ``You can't
work with them with your hands in your pockets. You have to prepare
and concentrate. It's like going in the finals of the Olympic
games. If you are distracted, they will feel it immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Carriere has never been interested in directing, he has
occasionally acted. For Bunuel, he played a priest in ``Diary of a
Chambermaid'' and a bishop in ``The Milky Way.'' He recalled that
the director told him, ``You are a very good actor, but only for a
priest.'' Once he played the role of a veterinarian in a movie for
another filmmaker. After the film was shown to Bunuel, Carriere
asked him what he thought of his acting. He said, ``You are very
good, but only for priests _ and veterinarians.'' Carriere
commented, ``My field was enlarging.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of his career, Carriere worked with another
celebrated movie artist, Jacques Tati. Because he had written a
novel, he was asked to write novelizations of Tati's films ``Mr.
Hulot's Holiday'' and ``My Uncle.'' At their first meeting, Tati
asked him what he knew about filmmaking. Carriere answered, ``Very
little,'' and Tati assigned one of his film editors to give him a
quick course. Carriere recalled that the editor put the script of
`` Hulot'' on a table next to the first reel of the film. ``She
told me that the only problem is to go from this to this. You have
to change from one language to another. It's like alchemy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tati taught me how to observe,'' Carriere continued, ``how to
sit in a cafe in Paris and to look at the passersby and to guess
what their story is, even a little moment of their story, a comic
effect. Tati supposed that the world had been created by God in
order to lead to a comic film.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining how he is able to work with so many disparate
directors with distinct points of view, he said, ``The quality of
the work is the same.'' Realistically, he added, ``It doesn't work
every time. It depends on the director and on the story. My real
collaborations are always very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Each is a hand-tailored project, and for its duration it is a
preoccupation, in which Carriere acts as scholarly investigator as
well as adapter.
</P>
<P>
   His interests, on and off screen, are wide, from art to
astrophysics. One of his recent projects is a book about science
written without using scientific language. As he said, ``Nobody
should be excluded from knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has occasionally worked with French directors like
Louis Malle and Jean-Luc Godard, generally Carriere's collaborators
have been foreign, and he has often undertaken non-French subjects.
``I've never written what can be called a Parisian film or play,''
he said. ``When I work on my own French culture, I like to do it
with Bunuel or Andrzej Wajda, who can look from outside.'' For
Wajda, he wrote ``Danton,'' about the French Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `Discreet Charm,' Bunuel's look is unique,'' he said. ``No
French director would show the French bourgeoisie the way he did.''
Bunuel described the film as illogical and irrational. Strange
things occur during an interrupted dinner. At one point, the French
army stops by while on maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Carriere added that his initial distance from ``The Mahabarata''
and ``The Conference of the Birds'' enhanced his work on those
plays. With equal agility, he was one of the screenwriters of
Volker Schloendorff's film of ``The Tin Drum,'' Guenter Grass'
novel about Germany in the first half of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which of his many films best represented him, Carriere
said: ``That's the only question I never ask myself. Louis Malle
once told me, `You are very lucky, you have no ego.' I don't know
if that's true, but I don't feel I have a message to deliver. If I
am somewhere, I am in this scattered curiosity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
