A6309 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-COX     06-07 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charter closing controversial hospitals
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alpharetta, Ga.-based Charter Behavioral Health
Systems is closing a Charlotte, N.C. facility featured in a CBS
News program that alleged problems in the psychiatric hospital
chain.
</P>
<P>
   Charter Pines in Charlotte will close due to care issues
determined during an internal company investigation, Charter said
Monday. Charter, a private company, also will shut psychiatric
services at a second hospital, in Largo, Fla., merging those
operations with its Tampa facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Charter's chief executive officer said Monday the closures will
occur for several reasons, and not because of the ``60 Minutes II''
report.
</P>
<P>
   But the month-old company probe followed the ``60 Minutes II''
report, anchored by Ed Bradley and aired in April, that alleged
patient care problems, including injuries and two deaths, at
Charter facilities. In the program, a social worker, employed for
eight weeks at the Charlotte hospital, wore a hidden camera to
detail conditions there. The CBS News report alleged unsafe
conditions, falsification of medical records, and lack of employee
training at Charter facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the hospital closings, Charter CEO Mike French
said, ``These were facilities where we needed to take immediate
action.''
</P>
<P>
   French, who took over as Charter president and CEO last October,
added that he didn't anticipate other closings, but didn't rule out
such action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it absolutely clear to the communities we
serve that we will be in compliance with established industry and
company standards, or we will take swift and immediate action,''
French said, insisting that overall, Charter hospitals maintain
good relationships with local communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take great issue with comments'' made on the ``60 Minutes
II'' program, French added.
</P>
<P>
   Charter, which operates about 90 psychiatric hospitals, denies
system-wide wrongdoing. The company is half-owned by Magellan
Health Services, which is moving its corporate headquarters from
Atlanta to Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the federal agency that oversees Medicare and
Medicaid said deficiencies recently found at a Charter hospital in
New Hampshire ``constitute a serious and immediate threat to the
health and safety of people receiving services at this facility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration report cited injuries
among child and adolescent patients while restrained; improper use
of seclusion; inappropriate sexual activity by patients; and injury
to patients from self-abuse. No new Medicare or Medicaid patients
can enter that Nashua, N.H., facility after Wednesday, and patients
there currently will be relocated to another facility, HCFA said.
</P>
<P>
   An HCFA spokesman said Monday that the exclusion of the New
Hampshire hospital as an immediate threat to patients is the first
in the agency's history.
</P>
<P>
   Charter said it hoped that a corrective action plan, submitted
to federal officials, would persuade HCFA to rescind the order for
the Nashua hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The federal probe of Charter hospitals in Boston and Nashua,
N.H., came as a result of a routine review, Charter said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has hired consulting firm Towers Perrin to review
its policies and procedures, including training and staffing.
Charter is also reviewing clinical care at all its hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   French acknowledged the ``60 Minutes II'' program had a brief
impact on company revenues. He said managed-care firms that had
suspended patient referrals to Charter facilities have resumed much
of that business.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Office of the Inspector General, which fights
health-care fraud, is reviewing the CBS News allegations against
Charter. And a recent Magellan filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission said the OIG, the Department of Justice and
other federal agencies are investigating Charter facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The National Alliance for the Mentally Ill, a consumer advocacy
group, said Charter's patient-care problems also are present in
psychiatric facilities run by other organizations, including
state-run hospitals and residential treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
   Poorly trained workers, in understaffed facilities, often resort
to violence, including placing patients in physical restraints when
patients become agitated, noted Clarke Ross, NAMI's deputy
executive director for public policy.
</P>
<P>
   NAMI supports congressional legislation limiting use of
restraints, and increased regulation of psychiatric facilities,
including public reporting of deaths and serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want more external review of the use of restraints,'' Ross
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``60 Minutes II'' program opened with a discussion of the
death of a 16-year-old at Charter's Greensboro, N.C., hospital. The
patient, Tristan Sovern, died in restraints. According to CBS News,
Sovern had a towel and then a sheet wrapped around his mouth, and
died of asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Charter opposes the increased regulation, Ross said, the
company ``is making a conscientious effort to improve their
internal operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
