<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS URGE BUSH TO SEEK LAW AGAINST HATE CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ About two dozen people marked the one-year
anniversary Monday of the dragging death of James Byrd Jr. with a
prayer vigil and a plea to Gov. George W. Bush to call a special
legislative session to pass a bill against hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers, who did not include members or representatives of
the Byrd family, urged Bush to delay his foray into presidential
politics, if necessary, to deal with the issue by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to begin a four-day trip Saturday to Iowa and
New Hampshire to test the waters for his all-but-announced bid for
the Republican presidential nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise you had we not received a tax break, (Bush) would
have called a special session to make sure a tax break bill would
have been passed,'' Kyev Tatum, a spokesman for the National
Coalition of African-Americans United for Self Empowerment, said of
major legislation that passed in the just-completed Texas
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're asking for him to do is to do the exact same thing
he would do with taxes or with education reform or with any of
those issues he is extremely compassionate about,'' Tatum added.
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive hate crimes bill named for Byrd, the Jasper man
who was dragged behind a pickup truck for more than 2 miles until
his body lay in tatters, passed the Democratic-led Texas House but
died in a Republican-controlled Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have stiffened penalties for most crimes fueled
by race, ethnicity, gender, disability, religion or sexual
preference.
</P>
<P>
   The issue split lawmakers along party lines with Democrats
charging their Republican colleagues with backing off the
legislation because it provided protections for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   GOP lawmakers responded that it was more divisive to split
people into groups by making them different in the eyes of the law.
The Republican governor, who has resisted saying whether he would
have signed the bill if it had reached his desk, said he does not
believe new legislation is necessary to deal with crimes motivated
by hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush encourages prosecutors to use the tough hate
crimes law already on the books in Texas,'' said Scott McClellan, a
Bush spokesman. ``Texas has tough anti-crime laws on the books, and
those who commit heinous crimes will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the James Byrd Jr. Act, however, contend the
state's current law on hate crimes is based on a vague concept of
bias, which makes it difficult to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   Three white suspects were charged in connection with the death
of the 49-year-old Byrd. One defendant, John William King, 24, was
convicted earlier this year and sentenced to death. The others are
still awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   One of the participants in Monday's brief prayer session, the
Rev. Herman Foster of San Marcos, said Bush's response to the
group's cries will, in Foster's mind, offer a glimpse of the
governor's mettle for higher office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is looking to run for president,'' Foster, 63, said. ``I
would think he would show himself now in terms of taking a stance
on a very important issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
