<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES DEAL BLOW TO TEXAS CASE INVOLVING DEAD TODDLER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday dealt a devastating
blow to prosecutors seeking to convict an El Paso-area woman who
allegedly killed her baby daughter and then enlisted the public's
help in finding her ``missing'' child in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear the prosecution's
appeal of a Texas judge's decision prohibiting them from using at
trial incriminating statements the mother, Heidi Schramm Consaul,
allegedly made to police after requesting to speak with an
attorney. The high court's rejection of the appeal might end the
prosecution's case against Consaul, as lawyers will be unable to
use perhaps the most damning testimony _ her own statements _ at
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed,'' said John Davis, chief appellate lawyer
in the district attorney's office for El Paso, Hudspeth and
Culberson counties. ``At this point, it's very doubtful that we can
go forward with a prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Consaul's compelling story of her missing 18-month-old daughter,
broadcast on local television, inspired sympathy from residents.
The FBI, sheriff's deputies and local rescue teams _ including one
from a nearby New Mexico county _ joined the hunt for the baby
girl.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso County detectives, suspecting the mother's involvement,
brought Consaul in for questioning and informed her of her right to
an attorney, which she accepted. She then demanded that the
officers find her daughter and later urged a television news
audience to aid in the search.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, after being informed she had failed a
lie-detector test, Consaul told officers she had awakened from a
nap and found her daughter had suffocated on a plastic bag. The
mother then allegedly led the officers into the desert near Horizon
City, where they found the child's body.
</P>
<P>
   When an autopsy revealed that the girl had been killed, Consaul
was charged with capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the mother rests largely on her incriminating
statement that she had abandoned her daughter's body. Hence, the
trial judge dealt a severe blow to the prosecution by ruling that
and other statements inadmissible because they followed Consaul's
request to speak with an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Once the mother asked for counsel, the police were
constitutionally barred from questioning Consaul without a lawyer
present, the trial judge ruled. The Eighth District Court of
Appeals agreed with the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, without comment, declined
to hear the prosecutors' appeal, prompting them to turn to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal to the high court, the prosecution argued that
Consaul effectively rescinded her request for counsel when she
later told the police to find her daughter. Karen Landinger, an
assistant district attorney in El Paso, also said the mother's
request for an attorney expired when she left police ``custody''
and returned home, days before she told officers where they could
find her daughter's body.
</P>
<P>
   Consaul's demand for police action ``represented a desire of the
mother to open up a more generalized discussion with law
enforcement personnel relating directly or indirectly to the
investigation of her missing child, and constituted a re-initiation
of contact and waiver of her previous invocation of her right to
counsel,'' argued Landinger in a legal brief to the justices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
