<HEADLINE>
TONY AWARDS BROADCAST FALLS IN RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Without a big musical or Rosie O'Donnell to attract
viewers this year, the Tony Awards broadcast fell sharply in the
Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In overnight figures from the country's 45 biggest cities, the
Tony Awards' rating was 7.9 on Sunday for the portion of the show
broadcast on CBS. That was down from a 10.3 rating last year, when
``The Lion King'' and ``Ragtime'' battled it out for best musical.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, the first time Ms. O'Donnell was the host, the
broadcast hit an 11.2 rating. (Each overnight rating point
represents 598,000 homes.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6316 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-WHITNEY-REVIEW-SF     06-07 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-WHITNEY-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMBITIOUS END TO A CROSS-COUNTRY COLLABORATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH BAKER  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. &LR;   &LR; _ ``Surroundings: Responses to the American
Landscape,'' which opened Sunday at the San Jose Museum of Art,
culminates a four-year program of loan exhibitions from New York's
Whitney Museum of American Art. The four yearlong shows have drawn
a thematic survey from New York's greatest public collection of
20th century American art.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the last installment is neither climactic nor conclusive. It
portrays the century's end as a moment of artistic confusion,
marked by clashing ideas of art's social relevance.
``Surroundings'' leaves us wondering not only which of the works in
the exhibition future audiences might consider 20th century
classics, but also whether the idea of classic artworks will even
have a future.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at certain things in the show for the first time, such
as Keith Sonnier's glass and neon ``Ba-O-Ba, Number 3'' (1969) or
Alan Saret's tangle of wire, ``Mount Tai'' (1987), it is easy to
forget that landscape is the unifying thread of ``Surroundings.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's curators, Beth Venn of the Whitney and Cathy Kimball
of the San Jose museum, make a brave attempt to expand the
visitor's thinking beyond the traditional scope of landscape
imagery in painting.
</P>
<P>
   It may take several passes through the exhibition to notice some
of the less obvious linkages. For example, Sonnier's neon piece and
Edward Hopper's ``Railroad Sunset'' (1929) appear very different in
form and sensibility. Yet the play of color in them is startlingly
similar, almost as if Sonnier's work were an abstraction of
Hopper's.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing their chromatic rhyming, one might start to relate
Sonnier's work to neon street signs and thus to the emotional
desolation of the urban landscape, the subject of so many Hopper
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, were Sonnier's piece to be encountered in
another context _ say in San Jose's last Whitney show,
``Alternating Currents: American Art in the Age of Technology'' _
it might never be related to landscape at all.
</P>
<P>
   Too many of the affinities in ``Surroundings'' seem cleverly,
but superficially, contrived. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  For example, it is exciting to see Alex Katz's ``Dark
Reflections'' (1995) _ an unusually fine picture by an overrated
painter _ alongside Christopher Wilmarth's glass and steel
sculpture ``Clearing No. 1 of Nine Clearings for a Standing Man''
(1973). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The Katz, a nearly abstract image of a tree reflection in a
lake's surface by night, exudes a thin, gray-green light like that
which diffuses through the upright panel of green frosted glass in
Wilmarth's sculpture. Behind the glass the edges of a folded sheet
of steel soften and vanish as they recede, as though disappearing
into mist.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilmarth may be concerned with sensations of closeness and
distance, but to think of it as landscape sculpture is to take its
title too literally and shut down its mystery.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of works among the 59 pieces that fall readily
under the show's subtitle, ``Responses to the American Landscape.''
But for every Charles Burchfield, Georgia O'Keeffe or Marsden
Hartley, there is something such as George Sugarman's meandering
painted wood sculpture ``Inscape'' (1964) _ a satisfying, seldom
exhibited work _ or Louise Nevelson's ``Rain Forest Columns,''
which seem to be included more because of their titles than for
what they are.
</P>
<P>
   And there are some curious omissions. Robert Morris and Michael
Heizer are represented by drawings, so where is Robert Smithson?
</P>
<P>
   The show tightens up again in the last room, where the line
between social and natural landscape is blurred not by the curators
but by the artworks themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A drawing for Christo's colossal 1976 ``Running Fence,'' a
project that still lives in local memory, reminds us how powerfully
social and aesthetic dimensions can converge in artworks done on
the land. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Roger Brown's painting-with-diorama ``XXX Exxon'' (1989), on
the other hand, responds to the Exxon Valdez disaster so
heavy-handedly that its outrage is laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mindful that ``Surroundings'' was their last shot,
curators Venn and Kimball have tried to do too much, to blur too
many categories, call too much into question at once. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Still, the San Jose/Whitney program has been a success
overall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, San Jose director Josi Callan struck a deal for a
series of long-term loans from the Whitney's permanent collection
with David Ross, then the Whitney's director. In June 1998, Ross
became director of the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   Because San Jose has a small permanent collection, the idea was
to use the Whitney's resources to lay a foundation for future
programming. Each show has lasted a year, giving the South Bay art
public plenty of time to revisit it and see it play off against
other, more transient museum events.
</P>
<P>
   How much educational staying power the San Jose/Whitney
partnership will have remains to be seen. But the value of the
program during its run is beyond question. It argues for a home
truth about art: that there is no substitute _ high-tech or
otherwise _ for eyes-on confrontation with art objects themselves,
especially those considered canonical.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope that other museums around the country take note
of San Jose's initiative and follow its example.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
