A6328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONY-LAWSUIT-NYT     06-07 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLUES' PROTESTS BEING CUT BY CBS FROM TONY SHOW
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The morning after the Tony Awards ceremonies, it
wasn't the winners that theater professionals were talking about.
It was the musical number from ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues''
that was dropped from the CBS broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The awards presentation, which is considered vital to the
financial health of many shows, featured high points from all the
other nominated musicals, including ``The Civil War,'' ``Fosse''
and two shows that have closed, ``Parade'' and ``Little Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Sunday night Tony broadcast was running long, the
production number from ``Blues'' was eliminated at the last minute
to meet the network's strict cutoff time of 11 p.m., Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really unconscionable what happened,'' said Rocco
Landesman, the president of Jujamcyn Theaters, which experienced a
similar incident in 1996 with ``Smokey Joe's Cafe.'' He said, ``The
producer didn't seem to have control of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers of the awards show, Tony Award Productions,
responded to an interview request by issuing a statement saying the
number was cut because ``it became clear that the show was running
long.'' The statement indicated that other material was cut as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share in the disappointment of our community that the fine
performance of `It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues' and the other
elements of the broadcast fell prey to one of the inherent perils
of live television,'' the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   Producers of ``Blues'' said the effect could be dire. ``Cutting
this because of a disorganized Tony event could actually close
us,'' said Anita Waxman, one of the producers of ``Blues.'' She
added, ``So there are a lot of serious consequences to this
ridiculous little thing that happened last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning a Tony Award can mean a boost at the box office as well
as artistic bragging rights, but a live appearance on the
nationally broadcast show has also proved pivotal to many a
musical's future.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running success of ``Smokey Joe's Cafe'' is largely
attributed to the number that was featured on the Tonys in 1996. A
second number from ``Smokey Joe's'' was cut from the broadcast,
prompting protests from the producers. ``This can be devastating to
a show,'' said Landesman, who produced ``Smokey Joe's.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Blues'' said they needed the visibility. The
show has been doing business slightly above break-even, said Eric
Krebs, one of the producers. ``In a year of problematic musicals,
clearly we would have had a major boost from national exposure,''
Krebs said. ``Much of our strategy as to how to promote the show
was based on this national broadcast _ reaching audiences
interested in musical theater.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the ``Blues'' producers mobilized immediately. As
soon as the ceremony ended, they met backstage at the Gershwin
Theater with the broadcast producers to air their complaints. They
also enlisted a high-powered Hollywood lawyer, Bertram Fields. And
on Monday, the ''Blues'' producers planned to meet with members of
the League of American Theaters and Producers and of the American
Theater Wing, which jointly presented the Tonys, in the hopes of
gaining some sort of redress.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Blues'' producers may ask to be reimbursed for the
six-figure amount they paid to appear on the Tonys _ each Broadway
show is assessed a certain amount of money, depending on the costs
of mounting each number. The producers may also try to obtain
appearances on other CBS programs to compensate for their loss of
national exposure.
</P>
<P>
   But the disappointment felt by the actors, producers say, will
be lasting, particularly because ``Blues'' was the only black show
among the nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do volunteer work with troubled kids in L.A., and I asked
them to watch the show last night,'' said Ron Taylor, the
co-creator of ``Blues,'' in a statement. ``I have a hard enough
time telling these kids that the establishment cares about them,
and last night showed them that the establishment doesn't care.''
Taylor was also nominated for his performance in the musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blues'' moved to the Vivian Beaumont Theater from an Off
Broadway house right before the deadline for consideration in order
to capitalize on a Tony appearance and the chance for an award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this will be the catalyst to create a show that really
reflects better on the industry,'' Krebs said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Broadway producers felt that the ``Blues'' incident
signaled a need to make the awards ceremony better managed, as well
as more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Several people who attended said they thought the segment
featuring straight plays in which actors did an overlapping montage
of their lines was an indecipherable waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   For at least one show, the Tonys were a potential life raft.
They were just what ``Side Man'' had been waiting for _ or hanging
by a thread for. The play has been hemorrhaging money, holding on
in hope of a ticket-building Tony Award. It got that on Sunday
night, winning the award for best play, along with a victory for
its dogged featured actor, Frank Wood, also a sentimental favorite
as an actor who had toiled for 12 years in downtown theater only to
be finally rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   In a season heavy on British imports and short on new American
work, ``Side Man'' was the only entry in its category written by a
living American. (It competed with Tennessee Williams' recently
rediscovered play, ``Not About Nightingales,'' which came over from
London.)
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, ``The Iceman Cometh,'' which originated in London,
featured several British actors and received wide critical praise,
lost in all the categories in which it faced off with ``Death of a
Salesman,'' which originated at the Goodman Theater in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how the voters voted, and these are strange
competitions,'' said Emanuel Azenberg, an ``Iceman'' producer.
``I'm comforted by the fact that it's sold out _ and that's no mean
comfort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
