<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-CABINET-NYT     06-07 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CABINET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAGMENTED WITH 15 PARTIES, THE 15TH ISRAELI PARLIAMENT IS SWORN
IN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Ahmed Tibi, a longtime adviser to Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, pledged his allegiance to the state of Israel
on Monday. A healthy white carnation gleamed on his lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Tibi, a Jerusalem resident and a freshman member of
the new Israeli parliament, was asked pointedly if he had really
meant it. Smiling proudly, Tibi, a physician, said that from now on
he should be known as an Israeli member of parliament representing
the Arab population _ and a former adviser to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   With trumpets and choral music, the 15th Israeli parliament was
sworn into office on Monday afternoon. It is one of the most
fragmented and colorful in the country's history, with 15 political
parties _ Jewish and Arab, secular and ultra-Orthodox, dovish and
hawkish _ whose varied interests represent a roiling challenge for
prime minister-elect Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its political and personal makeup, it's an impossible
parliament,'' said Nachum Barnea, a leading columnist for Yediot
Ahronot. ``And its first victim will be the new government.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak was not sworn in as prime minister on Monday, because he
has not yet forged a coalition government from the competing and
disharmonious forces.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, he has until July 8 to do so, but he is the first
prime minister who failed to assemble a coalition by the official
swearing-in date for parliament.
</P>
<P>
   That is largely due to a change in the electoral system when the
outgoing prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, was elected in 1996.
Netanyahu overcame the problem by hastily cobbling together a
government. Learning from Netanyahu's mistakes, Barak is in no
rush.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this created an odd frame for the afternoon's brief,
relatively pomp-free ceremonies. Netanyahu, who plans to quit
parliament, still occupied his old chair as the leader of the
nation, surrounded by many of his former Cabinet ministers. Thus
the defeated government sat front and center for an event that
effectively ushered it out of office.
</P>
<P>
   President Ezer Weizman, opening the ceremonies, said Israel,
divided by so many splinter groups, was ``plagued by exaggerated
internal criticism and a poor self-image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it seems as though you have to travel abroad to hear
kind words about Israel,'' he said. ``We are a country with a great
past and a contentious present, but with a promising future. Please
stop the self-criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   The new 120-member parliament is bound to be a different
organism from its predecessor. A third of its members are new.
There are more immigrants and more women _ 14 _ than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new women is Dalia Rabin-Pelosoff, 49, daughter of the
late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was assassinated in 1995 by
a Jewish extremist. Watching the ceremony, Leah Rabin, his widow,
beamed as her daughter, a lawyer, joined parliament as the sixth
member of the new Center Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very touching,'' Mrs. Rabin said. ``And not only the
question of being a mother. I cannot help but think of Yitzhak's
absence. He's missing here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new parliament, the two major parties that dominated
Israeli politics for 20 years, Labor and Likud, have shrunk,
reshaping the balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   Labor, now a coalition party called One Israel, has 26 members,
making it the largest party, but still smaller than ever in its
history.
</P>
<P>
   Likud has dwindled to 19 and lost its leader, Netanyahu. Ariel
Sharon, the outgoing foreign minister, serves as temporary
chairman. But the party, suffering disunity and disarray, is
gearing up for a leadership battle. Ehud Olmert, the mayor of
Jersualem, plans to announce his candidacy on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, the Sephardic ultra-Orthodox party, has grown, making it
almost the equal of Likud in numbers, with 17 members. But Shas,
too, has lost its leader, Aryeh Deri, who was convicted of
corruption this spring and gave up his seat after the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament used to be split fairly cleanly into doves and hawks,
but now its dividing lines are more varied. Russian immigrants,
absent just over three years ago, now fill 10 seats between two
parties. A new center has emerged. And the secular and religious
camps are both beefed up _ and ultra-antagonistic _ after a
rancorous campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the seating charts will force accommodations. Monday,
Tommy Lapid, for instance, a cantankerous television personality
whose antireligious platform earned his new Shinui Party six seats,
took his seat in parliament for the first time, next to another
newcomer, Rabbi Chaim Druckman, head of the yeshiva system for the
National Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
   Others joining parliament include Rabbi Michael Melchior, leader
of the dovish Orthodox Meimad movement and the chief rabbi of
Norway (which is obviously not a full-time job); Uri Savir, a
Center Party member and one of the architects of the Oslo accords
that have guided the Israeli-Palestinian peace effort; Gennady
Riguer, a Ukrainian-born engineer who began his life in Israel as a
street sweeper; and Husseina Jabarra, the first Israeli Arab woman
to serve.
</P>
<P>
   As the members' names were called out in alphabetical order,
there were two Levys, three Katzes and five Cohens. Ran Cohen of
Meretz and Raanan Cohen of One Israel were so confused that they
answered for each other.
</P>
<P>
   With a new parliament in place, Barak will return to the
daunting task of forging a government. He has said he anticipates
forming a mid-size coalition of 66 members, including the left, the
center, one Russian party, the settlers and the ultra-Orthodox of
European descent. But disagreements among them remain.
</P>
<P>
   Barak could turn to the 10 members of the Israeli Arab parties,
but he seems unlikely to take the politically explosive step of
including them in his cabinet. Sensing this, the left and the
Israeli Arab community, which supported him almost unanimously,
have been harshly critical.
</P>
<P>
   But even if not admitted to the inner circle, the Israeli Arabs
are almost guaranteed to support Israeli-Arab peace negotiations _
and a One Israel government.
</P>
<P>
   Whether to include Shas is the thorniest question, but top
politicians in One Israel have been seeking to rehabilitate Shas'
image and to argue for its inclusion. They have portrayed Shas,
which is a both a religious and an ethnic pride movement, as a
necessary partner for peace. And Barak seems inclined to seek the
party's participation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
