<HEADER>
A6333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACAPULCO-FILM-FEST-2T     06-07 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACAPULCO-FILM-FEST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK HOLLYWOOD SALUTES ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif. N.Y., Pa., Mexico)   (jw) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is an incubator for the next generation of black filmmakers,
a chance to network and a respite from the business and art
conundrum. The Acapulco Black Film Festival in Mexico, now in its
third year, is also gaining a reputation for putting a high gloss
on hard work.
</P>
<P>
   The roster for this year's festival, which runs Tuesday through
Saturday, is a Who's Who of black Hollywood: Samuel L. Jackson and
Pam Grier are to receive career achievement awards this year. Spike
Lee, Denzel Washington, Oprah Winfrey, Angela Bassett and Whoopi
Goldberg are among this year's award nominees in a range of ``best
of'' categories in film, acting, writing, directing and music. The
poet Maya Angelou; Forest Whitaker, the actor and director; Regina
King, an actress, and Taye Diggs, an actor, are to take part in
workshops and panels.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the festival is the screening of seven new
films and a new works in progress section to present and give
critiques of six others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a process of self-validation,'' said the
director and producer Warrington Hudlin, president of the Black
Filmmaker Foundation. The foundation sponsors the festival with
UniWorld Films, a division of Uniworld, a Manhattan-based black
advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   Hudlin and his associates started the festival 19 years after
the founding of the Black Filmmaker Foundation because of blacks'
minuscule representation in Hollywood, from executives to actors,
as well as a sense that blacks received token representation at
most film festivals and award ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't allow your validation to come from outside your
community,'' said Hudlin, who with his brother Reginald has
produced and directed ``House Party'' ``Boomerang'' and ``Cosmic
Slop.'' ``Hollywood's psychic needs and emotional needs are often
so antithetical to the black community's needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudlin says that too many Hollywood executives support films
that uphold whites as the exemplars of beauty, courage,
intelligence and the like at the expense of people of color.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed reviews and disappointing box office returns for
``Beloved'' last year made things worse for black film, some say.
``Beloved,'' based on the Toni Morrison novel about the trauma of
slavery, starred Ms. Winfrey and was directed by Jonathan Demme.
Virtually every studio has been increasingly reluctant in recent
years to bankroll serious black films, saying they do not bring in
audiences or money. Given its star wattage, ``Beloved'' was seen by
Hollywood as a litmus test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get out there and do it for ourselves,'' said
Debbie Allen, the actress, writer and director, who won a career
achievement award last year at the festival. One of her most recent
film projects was ``Amistad,'' the story of a slave ship revolt
that she proposed to Steven Spielberg and for which she was a
producer. She is now writing and directing a film about a woman who
is possessed by the soul of a former lover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real point is volume,'' Ms. Allen said of black films.
``There are so many films made by whites that don't do well. If you
have 10 comedies or 10 dramas, surely you'll get one blockbuster.''
</P>
<P>
   The film festival is not only an opportunity to nurture new
talent; it also exists to create networks of power like those that
exist in the music industry, the backers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are rich African-Americans who can finance movies,''
said the filmmaker Robert Townsend, the festival's master of
ceremonies. ``It's really about encouraging people to take charge
of their destiny.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Townsend said the goal of parity in Hollywood had to be viewed
as a long-distance run rather than a sprint. His own 1987 film,
``Hollywood Shuffle,'' is a classic paean to blacks in the movie
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Duke, actor and director of films like ``Sister Act 2: Back
in the Habit'' and ``A Rage In Harlem'' and a 1997 career
achievement award winner, is conducting an actor's ``boot camp'' at
the festival. He said the gathering had already led to some film
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Scott Cherot's film ``Hav Plenty'' was shown at the
first film festival in 1997 and went on to theatrical release by
Miramax in 1998. He directed, wrote and starred in the film, which
was called a ``witty screwball comedy'' by Stephen Holden, a film
critic for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Swan's film ``Mixing Nia,'' about the adventures of a
young woman who is black and Jewish, won the Magic Johnson Best of
Festival Award last year and was subsequently sold to HBO, which
plans to show it in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of contacts there,'' Ms. Swan said of the
festival in an interview from Los Angeles, where she is working on
a film adaptation of ``The Other Side of the River: A Story of Two
Towns, a Death and America's Dilemma,'' a book by Alex Kotlowitz
about the mysterious death of a black teen-ager in a small Michigan
town. In addition to meeting other filmmakers, she was able to get
a job directing a show on Nickelodeon that led to getting into the
Directors Guild of America.
</P>
<P>
   Donnice Wilson, a Los Angeles-based producer and writer whose
festival entry is a comedy about a womanizing minister called ``The
Rev. Do Wrong Ain't Right!'' said that being featured in the
festival's ``works in progress'' segment was a career breakthrough.
``I went to the first festival and I learned `don't be afraid to be
different,' '' Ms. Wilson said. ``Just because urban drama is what
we see, it doesn't mean that's the only thing out there.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rob Hardy, who grew up in Philadelphia and made his first
film in high school, the festival and the growing visibility of
black filmmakers have made a career in movies seem viable to many
young African-Americans. Even so, Hardy notes that he earned an
engineering degree to allay the worries of his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy wrote and directed ``Trois,'' about a corporate lawyer who
persuades his wife to enter a menage a trois and has to live with
the results. It will be screened in Acapulco as a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a plan for independent theatrical release,'' said
Hardy, who works in Atlanta. ``Getting the film made is the first
great obstacle. Getting the film to market is almost as great an
obstacle.''
</P>
<P>
   More buyers _ cable companies, motion pictures companies and
production companies _ will be in Acapulco this year than in past
years, Hudlin said, adding that Miramax, Cinemax, Showtime and USA
Studios were expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   HBO, which Hudlin says has been especially supportive, is the
festival's presenting sponsor and will present winners of the HBO
Short Film Award. The grand prize winner is to receive a grant and
paid apprenticeship with HBO NYC Productions, a movie division of
the network. The Walt Disney Co., Magic Johnson Theaters and Bank
of America are among other corporate partners of the festival.
</P>
<P>
   The festival theme this year is love, sex and romance. The four
films from the United States include ``Love and Action in
Chicago,'' directed by Dwayne Johnson-Cochran and starring Courtney
Vance as a religious hit man; ``Personals,'' directed by Mike
Sargent and starring Malik Yoba as a journalist investigating the
dating business; ``An Invited Guest,'' a psychological thriller
directed by Timothy Folsome about a screenwriter who neglects his
wife, and ``Loving Jezebel,'' directed by Kwyn Bader, about a man
who always ends up with someone else's woman.
</P>
<P>
   Three foreign films from directors in Tunisia, the Congo and
Canada are to be screened. Two films explore questions of identity
and one is the story of an overweight musical prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   Some hard conversations are inevitable. As Hudlin and his
associates noted at the festival's founding, there are virtually no
blacks in the top echelons of movie studios. And blacks represent
less than 5 percent of the members of the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences and the Directors Guild of America.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities for black actors also remain scarce, studies by
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the
U.S. Commission on Civil Rights and film industry groups have
shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge need for this, still,'' Kristal Brent Zook, a
professor of Pan-African studies at California State University in
Northridge, said of the Acapulco festival. Ms. Zook is the author
of ``Color by Fox: The Fox Network and the Revolution in Black
Television'' (Oxford University Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``Black films always have to fit into a paradigm that's
comfortable for mainstream audiences,'' she said, adding,
``Mainstream media are behind in that they haven't grasped the
complexities of America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Americans have had to understand white culture to
survive,'' Ms. Zook said. ``There is a fine line that white America
walks between being interested in black culture and willingness to
engage black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is more than a business. It's a reflection of where
we are as a society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
