<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TERM NEARS END, SUPREME COURT FACES TOUGH CASES 
</HEADLINE>
 COURT-HNS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before the end of the month, the Supreme Court may
decide some of its toughest cases of the year _ whether
disabilities that have been corrected should be a bar to
employment, whether police can force loiters to move on and under
what conditions victims of job discrimination can sue for punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   In two cases, the court is asked to determine whether people who
correct disabilities through medication, eyeglasses, hearing aids
or other medical devices still deserve to be protected by the 1990
Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   The cases involve a man with high blood pressure who was fired
as a truck driver and two nearsighted women who wanted to become
United Airlines pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Murphy of Manhattan, Kan., was fired by United Parcel
Service because of hypertension. When he sued, a judge threw the
case out because medication controls his problem and eliminates the
disability. Murphy since has found another job but is still suing
UPS.
</P>
<P>
   In the airline case, twin sisters Karen Sutton and Kimberly
Hinton, who were licensed as pilots for commuter airlines, applied
for jobs with United Airlines but were rebuffed because they
couldn't meet United's requirement for uncorrected vision of
20/100.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters claimed in their lawsuit that the requirement is
unfair. But the airline replied that because their eyesight was
corrected by glasses, they are not disabled under the meaning of
the ADA. A court of appeals ruled for the airline, but other
federal courts have ruled the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, employers have fared well in ADA court battles.
They've won 92 percent of the 700 ADA cases resolved in court from
1992 to 1997, according to a study by the American Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   But now employers feared that victories by the workers in the
current Supreme Court cases could lead to another slew of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way in which the court defines the ADA will make all the
difference in the world as far as protecting the rights of disabled
people in the workplace,'' said Sally Dunaway, spokeswoman for the
American Association of Retired Persons, a Washington-based
organization for people 50 and older.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the court unanimously decided that people who received
federal benefits because of disabilities can still sue under the
ADA to force employers to accommodate them at their jobs. A Texas
woman named Carolyn Cleveland had suffered a stroke, temporarily
received Social Security disability pay, and with some
rehabilitation, returned to work part time. But after what she said
were taunts from fellow employees and the refusal of her company to
help her accommodate her disability, her work deteriorated and she
was fired.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision the high court overruled lower courts that had
said someone who is or was on Social Security disability benefits
is by definition unfit for employment and is either barred from
suing on grounds of disability discrimination or faces special
judicial hurdles in pursuing such a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Another important case awaiting decision will determine if a
commonly used police tactic is constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   As issue is a 1992 Chicago ordinance that allows police to tell
loiters and others to move on and then arrest them if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 45,000 people were arrested under the law before the
Illinois Supreme Court in 1997 declared it an unconstitutional,
``arbitrary restriction on personal liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the law say it criminalizes ordinary behavior in a
way that restricts First Amendment freedoms of assembly,
association and expression.
</P>
<P>
   The last major case yet to be decided involves the definition of
``reckless indifference'' _ two words in a federal anti-sexual
harassment law that could end up costing employers who lose
workplace bias lawsuits millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A law that Congress passed in 1991 allows bias victims to
collect punitive damages in addition to back pay. But such damages
can be awarded only in cases when an employer's conduct shows
``reckless indifference'' to the bias that the employee suffered.
</P>
<P>
   During arguments before the high court in March, Chief Justice
William Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Sandra Day O'Connor,
Anthony Kennedy and Stephen Breyer accused Congress of enacting an
ambiguous law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This statute is simply confusing,'' Rehnquist said. ``Nobody
can pretend that's a clear guideline.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By the end of its term on June 28, the court is expected to have
decided 90 cases, a number significantly lower than in years past.
Ten years ago, the court issued opinions in 146 cases. In 1981 it
handed down 170 opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the decline, according to legal experts, has been
court's increasingly conservative nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court simply has decided that it isn't the place where
people should go to get answers to every question,'' said Sherman
Cohn, a Supreme Court expert at Georgetown University here.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn said the court's most conservative members _ Rehnquist,
Scalia and Clarence Thomas _ often want state legislatures and
Congress to decide policies on most controversial issues such as
school vouchers, campaign financing, affirmative action and gay
rights. ``They just don't believe the court should be the last word
on these issues,'' Cohn said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
