<HEADER>
A6340 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-07 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTER THE BALL, MAYOR GETS A DEGREE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No sleeping in on Sunday morning for San Francisco Mayor
 &UR; Willie Brown &LR; , who waltzed in his City Hall palace at the Black &AMP;
White Ball. Brown flew to Birmingham, Ala., on Sunday to be honored
for his commitment to education by the University of Alabama at
Birmingham, which made him a doctor of humane letters.
</P>
<P>
   He was nominated for the honor by the university's president,
 &UR; W. Ann Reynolds &LR; , who had been chancellor of California State
University when Assemblyman Brown was a trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Brown spoke about diversity in San Francisco and at the
Birmingham medical school. The Birmingham News quoted his speech:
``As graduates you have taken the first step to a life  &LR; long
commitment to learning,'' said Brown. ``All of this represents
something very special.''
</P>
<P>
   The university was recently in the news when researchers
announced they had traced the origin of the AIDS virus. Among the
past recipients of honorary degrees is  &UR; Stevie Wonder &LR; , who is a
major donor to the university.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EX-SENATOR HAS &LR;   &UR; A WAY WITH WOMEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an advice column written by  &UR; Alfonse D'Amato  &LR; in George
magazine, a woman in her ' &LR; 30s asks the former Republican senator
how she should handle a relationship with a ladies' man who is also
a younger man.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're just looking to fool around,'' advises D'Amato,
``then I say have a good time. But if you want a long-term
relationship, you need to look elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato appended a little notice of his own availability: ``I
suggest that you look for an older man who's not wealthy but can be
very charming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time,'' he wrote charmingly, ``include your phone number,
and I'll give you a call.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIERRE SALINGER RUES A DAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pierre Salinger &LR; , journalist and former press representative of
JFK, says he ruined his own credibility by reporting as fact
Internet rumors about TWA Flight 800 being shot down by the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the saddest things that has happened to me was the
damaging effect this affair had on my future speaking engagements
around the United States,'' Salinger wrote in a column in the
Georgetowner. ``My agent  &UR; Janet Cosby &LR; , who used to engage me for
15 important speeches a year, &LR;  (at $10,000 to $20,000 per speech),
has only given me one since my comments on TWA 800.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinger still seems to believe the rumor. He wrote of a tape he
has since found that provides evidence that ``there were three Navy
ships in the area which could have shot down the plane.''
</P>
