<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6346 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUN-BELTS-PRISONS-NY     06-07 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUN-BELTS-PRISONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE OF STUN BELTS POSES QUESTIONS FOR NATION'S COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., skedded earlier as STUN-GUNS-PRISONS)  
(rm) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last June, a municipal court judge in Long Beach, Calif.,
decided that a defendant, Ronnie Hawkins, was being disruptive at
the defense table. The judge issued an order to a court officer
and, by remote control, Hawkins was zapped with 50,000 volts of
electricity from a stun belt the guards had placed on him before he
entered the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' case of high-tech discipline led to a temporary
injunction by a federal judge against officials' use of stun belts
in Los Angeles County courts. It was one of the first such rulings
nationally against devices that are becoming standard equipment for
court officers and prison guards across the country. Though
law-enforcement officials say the devices are actually activated
sparingly, the jolt through a person's kidney can cause temporary
paralysis and loss of control of bodily functions.
</P>
<P>
   The California case and a report to be issued by Amnesty
International on Tuesday morning are focusing attention on the
devices, which are attached to some inmates in federal and state
prisons and local jails across the country, and some prisoners when
they are taken to court.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say it is becoming increasingly urgent for the
courts nationally to rule on whether new stun technologies are
permissible.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say they violate the Constitution's prohibition of
``cruel and unusual punishment'' and international human rights
agreements. The manufacturers and some law-enforcement officials
say that the stun devices can often be the least violent method of
maintaining control.
</P>
<P>
   But because the stun belts can be abused, the courts need to
address the legal issues posed by the new requirement that some
prisoners wear them, said Paul G. Chevigny, an expert on
law-enforcement procedures at New York University Law School. ``I
don't think there is an ironclad answer,'' Chevigny said. ``If you
think the person is misbehaving, the legal question is whether the
force you use is reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, like Amnesty International, say they believe use
of stun belts is inherently unreasonable and should be banned even
if they are activated rarely. In the report to be issued on Tuesday
morning, Amnesty International says the prison authorities and
other law-enforcement officials are increasingly requiring inmates
to wear stun belts and other electroshock equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that laws and regulations now permit the use of
stun belts in correctional systems in 20 states, by local
law-enforcement officials in 30 states and by federal officials,
including the Federal Bureau of Prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International said it found more than 130 jurisdictions
in America where officials attach stun belts to inmates or where
correction officers used shields that can stun inmates. Incidences
of people stunned by the devices were in Gwinnett County, Ga., Dade
County, Fla., and Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The belts are illegal in Michigan, Massachusetts and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last several years in conjunction with a rapid rise
of the prison population, institutions all over the country are
looking for new ways to control prisoners and they are turning to
stun belts at an alarming rate,'' Curt R. Goering, deputy executive
director of Amnesty International, U.S.A., said in an interview on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some prison authorities, like those in New York state, choose
not to use stun belts even though they are legally permissible.
``We feel we have appropriate procedures in place and don't feel
the need to use stun equipment,'' said Mike Houston, a spokesman
for the New York state Department of Correctional Services.
</P>
<P>
   Some prisons which have authorized corrections officers to have
some inmates wear the belts say they have strict limitations on
when they might be activated. The Federal Bureau of Prisons has
permitted officers to require some inmates to wear the devices, but
the bureau's spokesman, Todd Craig, said there were careful
safeguards requiring that they be worn only by inmates who present
security risks, like potential escapees.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said no federal prison official had yet administered a
shock to an inmate. But he said federal prison officials had
concluded that the belts were effective deterrents. ``If there are
technologies we can use to stop an escape or prevent an assault,
which will ultimately protect the public, we're going to use those
technologies,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the device, in wide use for only a few years,
is too new for the courts to have reached any consensus about
whether it is legally permissible for officials to require inmates
to wear them. In general under the Constitution, said David A.
Strauss, a constitutional law expert at the University of Chicago,
the Supreme Court has said that ``wanton and unnecessary force''
against inmates can be unconstitutional as a violation of the
provision barring ``cruel and unusual'' punishment.
</P>
<P>
   But, Strauss and other legal experts said, courts have given
prison authorities wide latitude in controlling emergencies like
possible escapes or assaults. ``Judges, including the Supreme Court
justices, are inclined to give officials a lot of leeway before
deciding that there has been `wanton and unnecessary force,'''
Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   In the California case, Hawkins filed a federal civil suit
seeking damages from officials and an injunction barring the use of
the belt. He asserted that the devices violated not only the
Constitution but also international human rights guarantees. Many
international treaties include language barring ``cruel, inhuman
and degrading treatment or punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary ruling in January, the federal judge, Dean D.
Pregerson, agreed that even if the belt were not activated it would
have a ``chilling effect'' on a defendant forced to wear it. For
example, Pregerson said, a defendant who was forced to wear a belt
and was representing himself, as Hawkins was, might be afraid to
object to a judge's ruling for fear of being shocked.
</P>
<P>
   He issued a temporary injunction while the case was awaiting a
full trial. Before that could be held, Los Angeles County appealed
to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit, in San
Francisco, where the case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hammond, a spokesman for Los Angeles County, said Hawkins'
case was the first time court officers had activated a stun belt.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been somewhat of an embarrassment for the industry
that manufactures electric-shock devices. Dennis Kaufman, president
of one of the large manufacturers, Stun-Tech Inc. in Cleveland,
said Monday that any use of a stun belt to punish a defendant would
be inappropriate. He said the belt was designed to stop escapes and
potential assaults, like attacks on corrections officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The belt is not to be used for punishment,'' Kaufman said.
``If it is, consequently, it is clearly a violation of civil rights
as well as a violation of what the belt was designed for.''
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates for prisoners say the devices present a worrisome
new turn of technology. ``In prison settings, it is a clear opening
for abuse,'' said Elizabeth Alexander, director of the National
Prison Project of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   But some corrections officials say there has been no evidence of
abuse. James Turpin, legislative liaison of the American
Correctional Association, a national trade group for correctional
officers and administrators, said he knew of no evidence that the
devices were used with any frequency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
