<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      06-07 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DELAYS TRIAL OF FORMER HUD SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge on Monday postponed until after
Labor Day the conspiracy trial of former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros on charges that he paid hush money to a former lover and
lied to the FBI about it.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin said he would go ahead
with a June 21 hearing to determine whether taped telephone
conversations between Cisneros and Linda Jones of Lubbock, Texas,
will be admitted as evidence when the trial starts on Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar, a former San Antonio fund-raiser known by her married
name, Linda Medlar, is expected to testify June 21 as a government
witness that the tapes are authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Simon, a Cisneros lawyer, is asking the judge for a
psychiatric examination of Medlar to determine whether she is
competent to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said Medlar has ``suffered from a severe mental illness''
and once became addicted to medication she was prescribed for her
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackowski, a prosecutor for Independent Counsel David
Barrett, said he would file a response with the court opposing the
psychiatric exam. Jackowski said Medlar suffers from depression.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin is expected to rule on the motions June 21.
</P>
<P>
   In a jab at the defense, Jackowski said a previous examination
found Medlar to be straightforward and clear in her accounts and
actions.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Simon to counter: ``The government jailed Mrs.
Medlar for lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Medlar is currently serving time in a federal prison for bank
fraud, obstruction of justice and money laundering. The charges
were filed in a 28-count indictment returned by a federal grand
jury in Texas as part of Barrett's $7 million investigation into
Cisneros' tryst with Jones. She pleaded guilty to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   She also faces one count of conspiracy in a 21-count indictment
handed down in December 1997 accusing her, Cisneros and two of his
aides, John Rosales and Sylvia Arce, with concealing from the FBI
$250,000 in payments from Cisneros to Medlar.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros and Medlar made their affair public in 1988, when he
was a popular mayor of San Antonio. Although the relationship
crumbled and Cisneros reconciled with his wife, Mary Alice
Cisneros, he continued to pay Medlar, who was unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Those payments, the indictment charges, were concealed from FBI
agents conducting a background investigation into Cisneros'
nomination by President Clinton to be secretary of Housing and
Urban Development. He served in that job from 1993 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is the second Clinton Cabinet member to face a jury
trial on charges of wrongdoing. Former Agriculture Secretary Mike
Espy was cleared by a jury on charges of taking bribes and illegal
gratuities.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin has agreed to let prosecutors and defense lawyers poll
prospective jurors to determine the impact the independent counsel
investigation of Clinton has had on their ability to render a fair
verdict in the Cisneros case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been the target of an independent counsel
investigation into of his role into the failed Whitewater land
development in Arkansas since 1994. Last year, independent counsel
Kenneth Starr expanded that probe to include the president's sexual
affair with a White House intern. That investigation led to
Clinton's impeachment by the House of Representatives, although the
Senate failed to muster the votes to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The judge admonished defense lawyers in the Cisneros case not to
ask personal questions and refrain from seeking essays from the
jury pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a lot of questions that are impertinent and
violate people's privacy,'' Sporkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge delayed the start of the trial for three months to
allow for the questionnaire to be assembled and to give ample time
to seat a jury from a pool of 300 prospective jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Paret, the U.S. District Court's chief deputy for
administration, said the summer vacation months would make it hard
to gather that number of potential jurors in four weeks. The trial
was scheduled to begin July 6.
</P>
<P>
   The June 21 motions hearing is expected to last two days. Simon
has vowed to challenge Medlar's credibility on the tapes, which she
admits she altered.
</P>
<P>
   The tape-recorded conversations are considered crucial to the
government's case against Cisneros, who is heard instructing Medlar
avoid talking with FBI agents conducting the background
investigation and questioning their ability to track down things
financial.
</P>
<P>
   Simon told the court he would use the government's tape
recording expert to prove the tapes are not the originals, have
been altered, and therefore should not be admitted as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Jackowski has countered that ``very few'' of the tapes were
``edited.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI contends that Cisneros told investigators he paid Medlar
about $60,000 before he was nominated to head HUD. The indictment
charges Cisneros paid her $250,000, including $73,000 after he took
office on Jan. 21, 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
