<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-NY     06-07 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY ELECTION RETURNS TROUBLING TO INDONESIA'S RULING PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A top official of Indonesia's ruling party
said on Monday that early returns in national elections suggested
``we are losing'' and that the party would need to fight for a
place in a future government coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all tentative,'' said the official, Marzuki Darusman,
who is a deputy chairman of the party, Golkar. ``But early returns
are indicating that we are sort of trying to stabilize around third
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an outcome would turn Indonesian politics upside down after
three decades during which Golkar dominated the nation's political
and administrative life as the obedient tool of former President
Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   But it would not be the end of the struggle for the presidency.
Monday's vote is only the first step in a long process that will
involve coalition-building and closed-door maneuvering in which
Golkar will have the advantages of incumbency and money.
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki's assessment matches fragmentary early returns and
anecdotal information from different parts of the country, as well
as the apparent momentum of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It also matches the optimistic private soundings of an aide to
Megawati Sukarnoputri, the candidate of the main opposition party,
the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But the official vote tally was coming slowly from around the
country in Indonesia's first free election in more than four
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nail-biting time,'' said Dewi Fortuna Anwar, a close
adviser to President B.J. Habibie, who is trying to hold on to his
office as the Golkar candidate. ``I don't think we will know for
sure until a few days from now.''
</P>
<P>
   However the vote comes out, she said, ``I feel good. There's a
real celebratory mood here. Before, there was the feeling that you
have to vote a certain line. I hope that, whatever the result, we
continue to have a good mood.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on the eve of the vote, Habibie said, ``Maybe it is
no exaggeration if I suggest that the 1999 election is the day of
awakening of democracy in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, he may have to abide by a result that does not make him
happy. Even in his home town, Parepare, in the province of South
Sulawesi, there were signs of trouble for Golkar. The party of the
native son won only 48 percent of the vote, far below local
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   And in the wealthy Jakarta district of Menteng, where Suharto
lives and where he cast his vote on Monday morning one year after
being forced to resign, his neighbors also turned against his
party.
</P>
<P>
   Like the three-week campaign that preceded it, voting throughout
most of the country was notably peaceful. Turnout was mostly high
except for some insecure areas like the province of Aceh, where
separatist guerrillas have tried to disrupt the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes cheering and whooping as returns were tallied in
300,000 polling places around the country, voters seemed thrilled
just to be able to exercise their will without the pressures and
intimidation of past Golkar governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the entire mood is different from before,'' said Jani
Dipokusuma, 58, who owns a bookstore in Jakarta. ``There is a sense
of elation and a sense that change has got to come. Before,
everybody had to vote for the ruling party. Not any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other voters interviewed on Monday, he refused to
reveal his choice, hoarding the happy secret of his newly free
vote.
</P>
<P>
   However exhilarating the experience was for the voters, though,
they were choosing just 462 members of a 700-member assembly that
is to select the next president later this year. No party is
expected to win a majority of Monday's votes. And the struggle for
the remaining 238 seats in the electoral assembly _ representatives
of the military, sectoral groups such as religious leaders and
provincial assemblies _ could decide the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing, of course, and that's a disappointment,''
Marzuki said. ``But it's not too bad. The system allows a building
of a numerical coalition where the winning party in the election
would be merely the first past the post. There is still some
distance until we get a new government, which may not precisely
reflect the percentage of the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts here have predicted that Golkar would
not place first in Monday's vote but have held out the possibility
that it could still secure the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The first returns on Monday came from Jakarta and surrounding
areas and indicated an expected win in this part of the country for
Mrs. Megawati's party. Golkar's strength lies in the more distant
islands of this far-flung nation of more than 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki said, however, that he had indications that Golkar was
not doing as well as he had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the first time we will have to take into account
the real possibility that they might emerge as a winner and we
might not even make it for the second place,'' he said, referring
to Mrs. Megawati's party.
</P>
<P>
   The future scenario, he said, depends on the final results. But
the scenario he depicted for an eventual Golkar presidency was a
tenuous one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get around 25 percent, we still have a good chance
of participating as a lead member of a coalition,'' he said.
``Under certain circumstances we might even end up as president
with the winning party sharing the speakership, for example, as a
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the party's top official, Akbar Tandjung, publicly
predicted that Golkar would win 40 percent of the vote, well above
the predictions of most political analysts. Privately, Golkar
officials told foreign diplomats that they were expecting to win 30
percent of the vote. That is still a high number in a political
field that has expanded since Suharto was in charge to 48 parties
from just 3.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, and the joy, of this year's vote is its
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in the last of Suharto's triumphant five-yearly
self-coronations, Golkar announced more than a month ahead of time
that it would win 70.2 percent of the vote. It was then happy to be
able to report that it had slightly exceeded its target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it much better now because you can choose,'' said
Frisdia, 23, a civil servant who voted in the eastern Jakarta
suburb of Tangerang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, we always knew who would win; it was always solid
yellow,'' he said, referring to the party color of Golkar. ``There
was only one party to choose. So why did we even have elections at
all? It was strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
