</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CLINTON (Washington) _ New facts are emerging about the
White House's hopes for revamping the Medicare system. By Robert
Pear. (This story includes competitive elements that will not be
available until the story moves, at 9 p.m. ET, in the ``w'' news
file).
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   STUN-BELT-PRISONS (Undated) _ A California case and a report to
be issued by Amnesty International on Tuesday are focusing
attention on stun belts, electrical shocking devicees that are
attached to some inmates in federal and state prisons and local
jails across the country, and some prisoners when they are taken to
court. Some critics question the legality of the belts. By Williams
Glaberson. (The story has moved ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   reefer:INDONESIA-ELECTION; story inside, with graphic and
sidebar, INDONESIA-BALLOTING.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ Members of the House of
Representatives return from a recess to confront a looming battle
over gun control that has already become more fraught with
political anxiety than it was before they left. Increased tensions
over new gun control measures partly reflect the activity of the
National Rifle Association, which used the recess to rally its
supporters, lobby lawmakers and sprinkle the radio airwaves with
ads. By Frank Bruni. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BIRTH (Mexico City) _ Like many old-style Mexican
matriarchs, Emma Castro Amador bore so many children that she can't
keep their birthdays straight, but all 14 of her children say they
are determined to limit their own families to two or three. The
national birth rate is down from an average of 7 to 2.5 and that
means a lot, for the entire continent. Next year, Mexico's
population is projected to reach 100 million, and the contrast
between Mrs. Castro's family and those of her children illustrates
the extraordinary changes under way in the country's population
patterns. By Sam Dillon. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
With graphic. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-WHITMAN (Trenton, N.J.) _ As she prepares to run for the
Senate, Christie Whitman finds herself in a political squeeze
between conservative and moderate Republicans. By Jerry Gray.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH-CONFERENCE (Washington) _ The Gores and Clintons
share a stage at the White House Conference on Mental Health. The
president announces that the government will begin offering
employees insurance that covers for mental illness as well as other
ailments, and will require carriers who do business with the
federal government to do likewise. By Melinda Henneberger.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECT (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Final election
results in South Africa show that the ruling African National
Congress was returned to power with even more votes than it won in
1994, but it fell just one seat short of a two-thirds majority in
Parliament. By Suzanne Daley. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FREE-HEROIN-PROGRAM (Undated) _ Taking a bold approach to
drug addiction, researchers at Columbia University are offering
free heroin to addicts and paying them to use it under a federally
authorized program aimed at finding a cure for their addictions. By
Christopher S. Wren. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
