<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN KILLS RADIO AND TELEVISION STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A popular television and radio personality often
described as Mexico's Johnny Carson was ambushed and fatally shot
on a Mexico City street Monday morning, numbing his fans and
bringing renewed calls for authorities to clamp down on rampant
crime in the world's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco ``Paco'' Stanley, 56, was murdered as he was leaving a
restaurant in the southern neighborhood of San Angel after
appearing on his morning television variety show.
</P>
<P>
   Police and witnesses said Stanley and one of his co-hosts, Jorge
Francisco Gil, were shot several times at close range as they got
into Stanley's sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley died instantly. Gil, 38, was hospitalized in serious but
stable condition with gunshot wounds to his legs. The assailants
fled the scene in a car and were still at large Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   News of the noontime shooting sent waves of grief and anger
across the country, which for the last five years has been plagued
by violent crimes. For more than 20 years, Stanley entertained
Mexicans with his dry, sarcastic wit on the radio and on the
country's two television networks.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for killing was unclear, but investigators voiced
suspicion that the number of shots fired signaled a deliberate hit.
Before being put into an ambulance, Gil reportedly told colleagues
at the television station, Azteca, that ``it was not a robbery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems clear that the intention was to kill Paco Stanley,
but what we don't know is why,'' Samuel Del Villar, Mexico City's
top prosecutor, told the station Televisa.
</P>
<P>
   Both TV Azteca, which aired Stanley's show, and Televisa, his
previous employer, interrupted regular programming for live reports
throughout the afternoon. Normally composed newscasters shook their
heads in sadness and called for local and federal police officials
to work quickly to solve the crime and stem Mexico's plague of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who was the victim of a gunpoint mugging in December,
reportedly traveled with four bodyguards, but it remained unclear
where they were at the time of the shooting. TV Azteca also
reported that investigators had found at least one gun in Stanley's
car.
</P>
<P>
   There was chaos at the scene of the crime in front of a taco
restaurant. Colleagues and fans wept openly on the street as they
watched puzzled police try to piece the events together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason he should be killed,'' Clara Guzman, 42,
said with tears in her eyes as she stood near the scene. ``He made
us laugh. But no one has any respect for life anymore. This is a
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile murder was sure to put new pressure on both
Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a presidential candidate for
the 2000 elections, and on President Ernesto Zedillo, who has tried
unsuccessfully to halt the country's crime wave.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying was one of the most sensational killings here since
the 1994 assassination of Luis Donaldo Colosio, a leading
presidential candidate, who was shot in the head while campaigning
in Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Experts, however, say the current crime surge began with the
country's financial crisis in 1995 and has persisted because of
endemic police corruption and the growing influence of organized
crime and drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   The violence has hit both affluent and poor.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the son of one of Mexico's most beloved singers,
Vicente Fernandez, was kidnapped and had two fingers chopped off
before his family paid an undisclosed ransom. The father of soccer
goalie Jorge Campos was also kidnapped but later released unharmed
after a ransom was paid. And American boxing promoter Don King was
robbed of a Rolex watch here in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The brother of interior minister and presidential candidate
Francisco Labastida Ochoa narrowly escaped a kidnapping attempt
earlier this year. And last week, a driver for another presidential
candidate, Vicente Fox of the conservative National Action Party,
was shot in the chest outside a Mexico City bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
