<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMORESE ARE SUBDUED ON ELECTION DAY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ East Timorese voters offered a generally
subdued response at the start of voting in Indonesia's national
elections on Monday, with many people saying they were more
concerned about a U.N.-organized vote on self-determination
scheduled for Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've voted, but this is not important for East Timorese
people,'' said a university graduate who gave his name as Marcos.
``What is important is independence.'' He was among about 400
people at a polling place in Becora, on the outskirts of the
capital, Dili. Becora has been a longtime haven for
pro-independence supporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, addressing a candlelit Mass that attracted
10,000 people, Bishop Carlos Belo said in a sermon that East
Timorese should vote in both the election and the referendum
according to their conscience. People should not feel forced to
vote he said. A church official said the bishop would be ``staying
home'' on Monday and would not vote.
</P>
<P>
   Voting outside Dili appeared less relaxed. In Ulmera, in the
troubled Liquica district, about 600 voters waited to vote. The
district is a stronghold of a pro-government militia, and
human-rights groups say voter intimidation has been widespread in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Voters appeared nervous, but one elderly woman, acknowledging
that militia members were there, said, ``I'm old. I vote for who I
want to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
