A6363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-VOTE-BOS &LR;      06-07 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIANS GO TO POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Closing the curtain on decades of
authoritarian rule, Indonesians voted largely peacefully Monday in
their first free election in 44 years, defying widespread
predictions of violence and taking the first step toward becoming
the world's third-largest democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy in Indonesia starts now. I hope this election will
make a new Indonesia, a better Indonesia,'' declared Arif Ridwan,
33, a hotel supervisor in central Jakarta after he proudly dropped
his ballots in locked wooden boxes and dipped his fingertip in
purple dye _ a device to keep people from voting more than once.
``I hope change starts today, because people are very tired of the
old way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridwan, like two-thirds of the population that was either not
yet born or too young to have voted in the 1955 election, had never
cast a ballot in an open and fair election. Until former President
Suharto was forced out last year after 32 years in power, there
were only three government-approved parties and people were
pressured to vote for Suharto's ruling Golkar party, which always
won.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, 48 parties fielded 11,000 parliamentary candidates,
and there were only isolated reports of coercion or intimidation.
Unregistered voters who were barred from casting ballots burned
three polling boxes in Tangerang, 25 miles west of Jakarta, police
said. In the troubled province of Aceh, some 15,000 people
reportedly fled their homes and were unable to vote following
threats from separatists or the military, a network of university
election monitors reported.
</P>
<P>
   Still, voter turnout was estimated at more than 90 percent, and
there were no reports of injuries or killings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with results still being tallied Tuesday morning and surveys
predicting that no party will win a majority, the hard work may be
just beginning. A disparate spectrum of parties will be forced to
form coalitions in the new national assembly in order to govern,
and it is possible that tensions will rise if expectations for a
reformist leadership are dashed.
</P>
<P>
   Some election observers also fear that even if voting was
conducted fairly, the results could be falsely reported. Because
the president is not being directly elected _ the national assembly
will choose the president later this year _ the stage may be set
for months of horse-trading, vote-buying, and alliance-breaking
among electors.
</P>
<P>
   Voters cast ballots Monday for 462 elected members of
parliament. The military, excluded from voting, will appoint 38
members. That group of 500 will join 200 government-appointed
assembly members from regional and social groups, and together will
select a president in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of targeting 130 million voters, you're targeting 700
people, and that's where the potential for money politics really
comes out,'' said Charles Costello, director of the democracy
program at the Atlanta-based Carter Center, which sent 100
observers to polling stations Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter led a delegation of observers who watched poll
monitors at several stations take an oath of honesty, shake out
ballot boxes to prove they were empty, and check the count of
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Much is at stake for Indonesia's 210 million people. For
decades, Suharto's party muzzled and jailed its opponents and
gagged the press, even as it was accused of massive corruption and
abuse of power in the world's fourth-most populous nation. In the
last year, President B.J. Habibie, who replaced Suharto when his
mentor was ousted from power, has launched several overhauls,
including freeing many political prisoners and discussing
independence for the disputed territory of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for many, the only acceptable outcome would be a thumping
defeat for Golkar _ something that is not guaranteed, especially in
remote, rural areas where people have known of nothing else and may
have limited information about newer parties. Election observers
worry if Golkar does better than expected and cheating is
suspected, frustrated voters may lash out.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results early Tuesday showed opposition candidate
Megawati Sukarnoputri's Indonesian Democratic Party for Struggle
ahead with 55 percent of the vote, with Golkar next with 21
percent. But that reflected just 17,500 votes out of an estimated
118 million ballots cast.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, the mood among voters was expectant, calm
and optimistic. On a soccer field in Rempoa village in the province
of West Java, voters waited patiently in chairs for an hour before
polls opened, beneath a hand-painted banner declaring, ``Go to Hell
with Money Politics!'' Most declined to say who they were voting
for, reminding questioners with a smile that the ballot was secret
and that for the first time, they were free to choose whom they
wanted without fear.
</P>
<P>
   Aisah, 21, a clerk, recalled that in the last election, her high
school teachers said she had to vote for Golkar or she wouldn't
graduate. ``Golkar came to my school and gave computers, so we were
told we must choose them. Too many people were scared to do
anything else. But now I'm free,'' she smiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
