<HEADER>
A6365 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURAGEOUS-GYMNAST-2n     06-07 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURAGEOUS-GYMNAST-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: made a difference. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was like instant, overnight success,'' he said.
``Everything went from mediocre to pretty up there.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of his junior year, Endsley wanted to take on the
pommel horse, an event that takes considerable abdominal and
upper-body strength to support complicated leg swings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he has part of his upper leg, he could control that on
the pommel horse and imitate doing scissors,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   During his senior year, Endsley earned 10s, the highest score,
on parallel bars and rings in his compulsory routines. He also
began doing double back-flip dismounts off the high bar and rings
and landing them with a deep knee bend, and an occasional hop.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by the dream of competing in the all-around, Endsley
decided to try vault and floor routines two months before the
district meet this year. He learned to tumble and vault, taking
several hops to generate speed instead of running. On the floor, he
learned how to hop his way into the same actions used by two-legged
gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   Mustering enough force on the springboard to fly over the vault
in a handspring position was the biggest challenge Endsley faced,
he said. But he kept working at it with Gonzalez's encouragement
and succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone told him, `Why do this? You're already winning with
your three events,''' said Dominguez, who also competed in the
all-around. ``He said, `Because I can do it.' People said, `I don't
think you can do floor. And what are you going to do, hop your way
to vault?' But Chance said he was going to get everything he could
out of his situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chance boldly went where no one-legged man had gone before.
That's courage. That's heart. That's what makes him special.''
</P>
<P>
   With a strong all-around performance at the district meet this
spring, Endsley qualified for the Region III championships in the
all-around _ his personal goal. Although his performance at
regionals fell short of earning him a berth in the all-around at
state, he took the Region III parallel bars title, qualifying for
state in that event for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am beside myself,'' Tana Samford said. ``I never, ever
thought seven years ago, I never knew there would be so much he
could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm speechless every time'' he does any of his events.
</P>
<P>
   At the state competition, Endsley's performances showcased his
playful spirit. He learned to loosen up and play off the crowd,
grinning as he prepared to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to realize, after 10 years of training, if I don't
have it now, there's no sense worrying about it,'' he said. ``So I
just decided to go out there and have a good time, and it worked
great for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the Abilene High School gymnasium would hush amid
the commotion of several simultaneous events to focus on Endsley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's known statewide, and I don't think he knows half the
people who know him,'' Dominguez said. ``When he competed at state,
everyone was saying, `Chance is going,' `Shhhh, Chance is going,'
`Hey, be quiet. Chance is going.' Even the competitors themselves
don't salute the judge (to begin their routines) until they see
Chance go.''
</P>
<P>
   Endsley finished third in the parallel bars with a three-day
score of 28.925. But when awards were given at the end of the meet,
Endsley took home more than a bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
   He was selected by the Texas High School Gymnastics Coaches
Association for the new Spirit of Courage Award, which the
association has said will not be given unless it is truly deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really hit home,'' Endsley said. ``I was the first person
to ever receive the award, so that made it even more special.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was selected by the association to compete on Team
Texas, a group of seniors who participated last month in the
National High School Gymnastics Championships in Lincoln, Neb. His
performance on parallel bars helped the boys team to its seventh
consecutive national championship, and he earned fourth place in
the parallel bars finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chance is a role model for everybody, for the country,'' said
Trinity High School gymnast Aaron Jackson, Endsley's Team Texas
teammate. ``People stub their toe and get down on themselves. Well,
he lost a leg, and he never gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Although gymnastics became his love and his life the past seven
years, Endsley plans to attend University of Texas of the Permian
Basin in Odessa in the fall to concentrate on academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I went to OU, gymnastics would be there, and there'd
be no way I'd be able to stay out of it,'' he said. ``I decided I
wasn't going to put myself in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Endsley said he is determined to be an orthopedic surgeon so he
can help people similar to himself.He said he will miss gymnastics
but hopes that his time in the sport will leave a lasting
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people who saw me compete think, `Hey, if he can do it,
then I can do it. Maybe my problems aren't as bad as I thought.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (To see video footage of Chance Endsley, including his high bar
and parallel bar routines from this year's Texas High School
Gymnastics Championships in Abilene, go to
www.star-telegram.com/specials/99chance. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
