r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURAGEOUSGYMNAST-150     06-07 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURAGEOUSGYMNAST-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURAGE VAULTS GYMNAST BEYOND PHYSICAL LIMITS
</HEADLINE>
 (DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``s'' sports category) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching Chance Endsley compete in varsity gymnastics is a wild
ride down an emotional superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   Shock: ``Oh my gosh. He only has one leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Awe: ``Wait a minute. He's really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear: ``OK. There is no way he's landing on one leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Endsley nails the landing.
</P>
<P>
   On one leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't anticipate what he's about to do because they
don't know the person,'' said Gustavo Dominguez, Endsley's best
friend and a teammate at Odessa High School in West Texas. They
both graduated recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an icon of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Endsley's courage helped take him to the state and national
gymnastics meets as a senior _ seven years after he lost his right
leg in a freak accident.
</P>
<P>
   Endsley, then 11, was on a family trip to Sheffield, about 90
miles southeast of Odessa in a hilly region of the West Texas oil
patch. He and his siblings and cousins were pushing large rocks off
the mountainside when one of the rocks, ``about the size of a
Volkswagen,'' rolled back onto Endsley's leg, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rock shattered his leg, breaking bones in 16 places and
leaving him bleeding profusely.
</P>
<P>
   His stepfather, Gary Samford, who was a medic in the Navy,
fashioned a makeshift stretcher and kept Endsley conscious while
they drove to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only thing keeping me from dying,'' Endsley said.
``He made me stay awake all the way down to Iraan'' just north of
Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I died in the hospital. They had to bring me back.''
</P>
<P>
   For 11 days, doctors tried to save Endsley's leg. Then Endsley
decided he had had enough. He told the doctor to amputate his leg,
said his mother, Tana Samford.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor gave Endsley a marker and told him to draw a line on
his leg where he still had feeling, and the leg was amputated from
that point _ his upper thigh _ the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever been in the hospital 11 days, where you're just
being drugged and in pain and everything else?'' Endsley said. ``I
was tired of it. It was the best way out. It was the only way out.
It wasn't going to be saved.''
</P>
<P>
   After the surgery, Endsley developed a blood yeast infection, a
condition that Endsley was later told is survived by 10 percent of
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew anything was wrong with me,'' he said. ``People
would come in with a big smile on their face. I had no idea I only
had a 10 percent chance of living.''
</P>
<P>
   After being hospitalized about two months, Endsley went home. He
had already accepted his loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandma came in (the hospital room) and asked me, `Your leg
is gone. Aren't you upset?' I said, `No. It doesn't do any good to
be upset. It won't make it grow back,''' Endsley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I decided to make the best of what I had.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to school to start sixth grade on crutches, happy to
be back after missing the last month of fifth grade. During the
next three months, he learned to walk with a prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   That year, he returned to gymnastics, which he had enjoyed
before the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``My coach said, `Why don't you try it again?''' Endsley said.
``I didn't think I had much of a chance at it. But I gave it a
shot. And I'm glad I gave it another shot.''
</P>
<P>
   In seventh grade, Endsley began competing while wearing his
prosthesis, under the tutelage of Odessa High gymnastics coach Tony
Gonzalez, who said he had never turned away a student with a
disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Chance as a challenge, to see how far he was going to
get and how much I was going to be able to teach him,'' Gonzalez
said. ``The first year was a trial, but I could see, even now when
I see video, there was improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``More so than any other team member at the time, I could see a
difference in him, a difference in him trying to learn and excel.
So when I saw that desire, I said, `We can do something here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Endsley said he never won an event while wearing his prosthesis,
although he did not do poorly. The highest he placed was third on
the parallel bars in a dual meet in junior high school, and he said
the competition in junior high was not that strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``His prosthesis got in the way on landings and swings,''
Gonzalez said. ``He didn't have total control of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, a physics teacher, wondered about Endsley competing
without his prosthesis. Toward the end of Endsley's sophomore year,
Gonzalez persuaded him to try it.
</P>
<P>
   With clearance from Endsley's parents and his doctor, Gonzalez
and Endsley embarked on a scientific and physical challenge. To
perform forceful, flipping dismounts on events such as the high
bar, Endsley would need to absorb a great impact on one leg. His
doctor said Endsley's leg could handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there, I said, `OK, Chance. Now we've got to condition
that leg,''' Gonzalez said. ``That was going to be the critical
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez stacked mats in the weight room and had Endsley jump on
and off them to strengthen his leg muscles. Endsley also did more
squats than he could count.
</P>
<P>
   He soon found his routines running more smoothly on parallel
bars, rings and high bar. He isn't sure why, he said, but the
freedom from his prosthesis clearly made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
