<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-530&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO HOLDS BACK ON THREATENED BOMBING OF BELGRADE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO held back most of Monday on carrying
out threats to intensify its bombing of Yugoslavia if Belgrade did
not promptly accept allied terms on Kosovo. Allied officials said
they hoped that the restraint would help persuade Russia to back a
U.N. Security Council resolution on ending the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Still confident that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
would finally be forced to withdraw from Kosovo, the allies kept
pounding his army overnight Sunday, hitting about 50 armored
vehicles. But they did not strike the capital, Belgrade, or other
sensitive targets on Monday as long as negotiations on the
resolution continued near Bonn, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Led by France, the continental European allies moderated
American and British outrage over the refusal by Yugoslav military
commanders on Sunday night to accept NATO military terms despite
Milosevic's agreement in principle last week to pull out 40,000
troops from Kosovo and let security forces and ethnic Albanian
refugees in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we finalize a draft resolution in talks with the Russians
and get it approved by the Security Council, then we can go ahead
with heavier strikes if Milosevic still refuses,'' a French
official in Paris said.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac feared that Russia might balk in talks
at a conference center outside Bonn on Monday if the allies resumed
blasting targets all over Yugoslavia and in Belgrade with more than
300 bombing runs a day, as they were doing until last week.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov of Russia agreed to attend the
talks in Bonn only after Chirac called President Boris Yeltsin over
the weekend and pleaded with him to let Ivanov travel on Monday,
the French official said.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of allied ambassadors here, American and British
representatives did not object to this European strategy for
keeping the Russians engaged in the diplomacy, officials said.
Though officials left the intensity of the bombing up to NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana and the top allied commander, U.S.
Gen. Wesley Clark, no big step-up in the bombing was evident while
talks continued in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   There, the allies hoped, Ivanov, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and their counterparts from Britain and France, both also
permanent members of the Security Council, and the four other
countries attending would reach agreement on a draft resolution.
The allies also hoped that China would go along, giving Milosevic
no choice but to do what the resolution said and withdraw the
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the allies have pledged continued resolve to keep up
the bombing, which began its 76th day on Monday, and heaped scorn
on the Yugoslav leader for going back on his word. But the allies
also said they were confident that their firmness would soon allow
them to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still believe we've come a very, very long way in these 75
days,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea. But he put off a champagne
celebration he had planned for Monday, letting the hordes of
journalists who cover NATO lunch off the cocktail sandwiches that
he had apparently ordered for a party Monday afternoon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
