<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT &LR;      06-07 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRUSSELS, Belgium: Monday afternoon.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   British Defense Minister George Robertson accused Milosevic of
``bad faith'' and ``procedural trickery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is trying to cull elements of victory out of the
defeat that last week's agreement represented,'' he said in London.
``We have moderated the air campaign in the last few days. They
will feel pain again.''
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance, which early Monday said that air operations
were ``accelerating toward their prior intensity,'' took its foot
off the accelerator, officials said, to give the foreign ministers
a chance to reach an agreement in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov did not arrive in a conciliatory mood, accusing NATO of
going beyond military issues in the weekend talks with the Yugoslav
military. ``NATO is trying unilaterally to say in this document
that an international force will be based on NATO units and have
the right to use force,'' Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia wants security forces to be under U.N. command and has
refused to discuss participating in any NATO security mission,
allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also seemed to agree with a Yugoslav demand that allied
diplomats said had scuttled the military talks on Sunday in
Macedonia. The Yugoslav officers insisted that the 45,000 security
troops planned by the allies could enter Kosovo only if the
Security Council gave them a mandate to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Security Council, in line with the political agreement and
principles set out in Belgrade, is the only institution in charge
of scope, modalities and mandate of an international presence in
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia,'' a spokesman for the Yugoslav
Foreign Ministry, Nebojsa Vujovic, said Monday in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Allied diplomats said the Yugoslav commanders had also gone back
on Milosevic's pledge to Russian and European Union mediators on
Thursday in Belgrade that all 40,000 Serbian military, paramilitary
and police troops in Kosovo would withdraw when the international
community took over administration.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of Britain said Monday on
BBC Television that the Serbs had said that ``for the time being''
they wanted to withdraw their troops only to what they called
``peacetime levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That could mean them keeping 10,000 to 15,000 troops in
Kosovo,'' Cook said. ``Well, that's a nonstarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The British lieutenant general who will command NATO operations
in Kosovo, Sir Michael Jackson, rejected that proposal in his talks
over the weekend in Macedonia with the Yugoslav officers, allied
diplomats said. Sir Michael also turned down Yugoslav requests for
more than seven days to complete their withdrawal and more than 48
hours to deactivate their air defenses so that allied planes could
monitor the Serbian pullout, both parts of the agreement in
principle that former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin of Russia
and President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland worked out with Milosevic
on Thursday in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian officers also made other attempts to go back on the
agreement, allied diplomats said. They wanted NATO forces, not the
retreating Serbs, to be responsible for clearing land mines from
Kosovo, according to allied officials. They also wanted to permit
only refugees with proof of citizenship to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   About 850,000 of 1.8 million ethnic Albanians have been driven
out of the province this year, and thousands said Serbian
authorities had confiscated and destroyed their citizenship and
identity papers before pushing the refugees into Albania and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demands of the international community remain the only way
to guarantee the safe return of the refugees to their homes,'' Shea
said. ``General Jackson remains in the former Yugoslav republic of
Macedonia and is fully ready to discuss concrete implementation of
the Chernomyrdin-Ahtisaari agreement whenever the Serbs are ready.
The flap of his tent remains open.''
</P>
<P>
   General Jackson called off the talks with two Yugoslav generals
late Sunday night after the Serbs had balked at the agreement. But
officials said that lower-ranking officers from both sides had
established contact and that talks could resume any time.
</P>
<P>
   Before the talks Monday in Bonn, NATO planes flew more than 480
missions, down from 700 and more earlier last week, when the
weather was clear. The bombing continued Monday, with missile
strikes on Jagodina and Dobricevo in Serbia, the state-run Tanjug
news agency reported in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, most of the allied strikes appeared to be
concentrated on Serbian positions in Kosovo near the Albanian
border, where Serbian forces have been engaged in heavy fighting
with ethnic Albanian rebels from the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy bombing by American B-52s continued for the second day in
a row there, reports from the field said. Despite the pounding,
Serbian forces fired artillery at rebel bases across the border in
Albania on Sunday and kept up heavy fighting against rebel
positions just inside the province and near the Pagarusa Valley
town of Orahovac, said a military command spokesman, Maj. Gen.
Walter Jertz.
</P>
</TEXT>
