<HEADER>
A6373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTAL-SIDE-COX     06-07 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter Center joins mental health debate
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Teenagers and tornadoes, communities and crisis were
among the diverse range of topics discussed Monday during the
Carter Center's contribution to the White House Conference on
Mental Health.
</P>
<P>
   Via satellite feed, Georgia therapists, activists, behavioral
scientists and high school students listened to Vice President Al
Gore, his wife, Tipper, and first lady Hillary Clinton discuss the
importance in making mental health issues a part of comprehensive
health care and a part of household, school and church
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher led the panel discussions at
the Carter Center, along with Jane Delgado, president of the
National Coalition of Hispanic Health and a Carter Center mental
health task force member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental health is everybody's business,'' Satcher said. ``And
there should be community health centers that promote strong mental
health programs so the community knows `We're here for you,' and to
not be afraid to seek help.''
</P>
<P>
   Doris Smith spoke about losing her son, Mark Alan, when he
committed suicide at age 27, and how the suicide rate among young
African-American men continues to rise. ``For many reasons, the
African-American community will not discuss suicide,'' she said.
``It's a taboo subject in our churches, and among many people. I
know there are suicide survivors in Atlanta who will not come
forward and talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith now actively works with Georgia Survivors of Suicide, the
national Suicide Prevention Advocacy Network and Project HOPE, a
Georgia project to train leaders in the African-American community
about depression. At the Carter Center, her son's photo and song
lyrics were among many faces displayed on the Georgia Lifekeeper
Memory Quilt dedicated to those who had taken their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   On everyone's mind were troubled teenagers in the wake of recent
school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Before the conference began, Satcher met privately with 20
Atlanta-area high school students in a roundtable discussion. They
talked about threats of violence at their schools, and the fear
that teenagers have in coming forward to talk about emotional
stress and problems at home.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Veneno, a panelist from Dulce, N.M., who listened in,
offered one solution he's seen work in the small 3,000-population
Jicarilla Apache community of Dulce. Responding to suicide rates
that were twice the national average, the community borrowed a peer
program from Seattle called Natural Helpers in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Dulce High School surveyed its students and asked what peer they
felt comfortable talking to about home problems, alcohol, drugs,
thoughts of suicide and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody picked someone within their own group they could go
to and tell them, `My dad's been drinking again,' or `I feel like
going on and getting drunk,''' Veneno said.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of Natural Helpers at Dulce's middle and high
schools, the number of suicides dropped. ``It used to be two, three
or four kids killing themselves every year,'' Veneno said. ``But
since 1995, there's been only two completed suicides.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisis counseling in the aftermath of Dunwoody, Ga.'s 1998
tornado and the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing were also addressed at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
