<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HABEAS-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES FIND SHORTCUTS TO FEDERAL APPEALS BY STATE INMATES
UNACCEPTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.) (sw) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday shut the door tighter
on state inmates' access to federal court, ruling that prisoners
who have not first appealed to their state's highest court forfeit
their right to federal court review even if it was evident that the
state appeal would be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal law governing habeas corpus _ constitutional
review of a conviction or sentence _ a state inmate must first
``have exhausted the remedies available in the courts of the
state'' before seeking a federal court's assistance. The question
for the justices today, in a case from Illinois, was whether the
available remedies that must first be exhausted include an appeal
to a state high court where the criteria for selecting cases make
it virtually certain that the inmate's case will not even be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-to-3 decision overturned a ruling by the 7th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, in Chicago. That court held last year that
because the Illinois Supreme Court's rules were clearly intended to
discourage the filing of routine criminal appeals, it would be
unfair to penalize prisoners who try to follow those rules by going
directly to federal court. In 1997, the Illinois Supreme Court
reviewed only 33 of 1,072 criminal cases, a ratio roughly similar
to the justices' own rate of granting cases.
</P>
<P>
   All convicted defendants in Illinois are guaranteed the right to
an initial appeal before an intermediate court. The inmate in this
case, Darren Boerckel, a convicted rapist, had raised six issues
for appeal before the intermediate court, but presented only three
of them to the Illinois Supreme Court. The 7th Circuit ruled that
the Federal District Court in Peoria could nonetheless consider all
six.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority on Monday, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor
said that as a matter of federal-state relations, as long as a
state has given its supreme court the choice to review a case,
federal courts should require that state inmates make use of the
available process so that the state court has a chance to exercise
its discretionary jurisdiction. Any issues not raised in the state
supreme court should be considered defaulted, she said. If the
state declines to hear a case, the inmate can then appeal to
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The principle O'Connor invoked was the doctrine of ``comity,''
an aspect of federalism meaning that the federal government should
respect state institutions. ``This rule of comity reduces friction
between the state and Federal court systems by avoiding the
unseemliness of a Federal district court's overturning a state
court conviction without the state courts having had an opportunity
to correct the constitutional violation in the first instance,''
O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 20 years, the court has been invoking federalism
principles to cut back on the federal courts' ability, through
granting writs of habeas corpus, to review the quality of justice
being administered by the states.
</P>
<P>
   But the dissenters on Monday, Justices John Paul Stevens,
Stephen B. Breyer and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, objected that comity
really supported the opposite result in this case, O'Sullivan vs.
Boerckel, No. 97-2048. If a state high court made it clear that it
did not want to be burdened with routine appeals, Stevens said in
an opinion the other two dissenters also signed, then federal
courts should not adopt a rule that has the effect of forcing
inmates to add to this unwanted burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most ironically,'' Stevens said, the court's decision ``will
undermine federalism by thwarting the interests of those state
supreme courts that administer discretionary dockets.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's majority opinion was joined by Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist and by Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy,
Clarence Thomas and David H. Souter. Souter also wrote a concurring
opinion to say that state supreme courts could insulate themselves
from the impact of the decision by issuing more precise rules about
the kinds of appeals they wanted to deflect to the federal courts
and did not want to hear themselves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the court's momentum seemed to flag with less than a month to
go in term, there were also these other developments on Monday:
</P>
<P>
   _ The court ruled that federal laws dating to early in the
century, which gave the government ownership of coal found under
millions of acres of Western land, did not apply to the methane gas
that is also found in the coal beds. The property owners own the
gas, Kennedy said in a 7-to-1 opinion. Ginsburg dissented and
Breyer did not participate.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, Amoco Production Co. vs. Southern Ute Tribe, No.
98-830, was a victory for a group of energy producers who owned the
lands. It overturned a ruling by the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in Denver. The government argued unsuccessfully that the
Coal Lands Acts of 1909 and 1910 reserved to itself both coal and
gas. Kennedy said that was not the intent of Congress, because
methane gas was seen at the time as a dangerous and unwanted
byproduct, only much later acquiring economic value.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Ute tribe had been granted the coal rights by the
government and had been seeking ownership of the gas as well.
</P>
<P>
   _Acting on an appeal by a Nevada death-row inmate who committed
a double murder in 1993 at age 16, the court asked the Clinton
administration for its views on the issue the inmate raised:
whether Nevada is bound by an international treaty the United
States has signed that bars executing those who committed their
crimes before age 18.
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter signed the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights in 1977. When the Senate ratified it in
1992, it attached a ``reservation,'' at the urging of President
George Bush, declining to accept the capital punishment provision.
An additional question raised by Michael Domingues, the inmate in
this case, Domingues vs. Nevada, No. 98-8327, is whether that
action was valid. The treaty has been signed by 144 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1989 that it did not violate the
Constitution to execute someone who had killed at age 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada Supreme Court upheld the death sentence in this case
in 1996. Subsequently, lawyers for Domingues filed a new appeal
seeking a ``correction of illegal sentence.'' The Nevada Supreme
Court rejected that appeal last year by a 3-to-2 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's views, expected next fall, are not binding
on the Court, which will eventually make its own decision, if it
chooses to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
