u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-07 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV GENERALS ARE SAID TO STALL FOR UN ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Yugoslav Army generals who refuse to sign an
agreement for their withdrawal from Kosovo are buying time so they
can hand over control of the Serbian province to the United Nations
instead of NATO, political and military analysts here say.
</P>
<P>
   Those analysts say the generals are acting on the orders of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, who in order to stay in
power needs to portray his capitulation as a victory by pushing
NATO aside and getting the UN to take over peacekeeping operations
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But to do that, Milosevic needs a Security Council resolution
that would spell out that the UN will oversee the international
peacekeepers, which will include NATO troops. Efforts to draw up
and submit that resolution to the UN will resume Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the talks broke down, NATO on Monday night started bombing
the capital, Belgrade, for the first time in five days, a lull that
had been interpreted here as a good-will gesture.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal of Yugoslav generals to sign the six-page document
that stipulates the withdrawal of 40,000 Serb troops from Kosovo
had been seen by some as a split between the army and the
government in Belgrade. Some have even suggested the generals'
refusal to accept the terms that Milosevic and the Serbian
parliament had approved Thursday as having the makings of a
potential coup.
</P>
<P>
   But both political and military analysts said that Milosevic
remains committed to ending the war based on the principles
outlined by the Group of Eight industrialized nations and Russia,
and that the military remains loyal to the regime.
</P>
<P>
   The United States asked the Security Council to schedule a
meeting Monday to approve a resolution to end the war over Kosovo,
but the G-8 foreign ministers were unable to agree on the language.
Negotiations are scheduled to resume Tuesday in Bonn, with the
Russians arguing on behalf of the Serbs. The Russians are demanding
an immediate halt to the bombing, and could use their veto on the
Security Council as leverage.
</P>
<P>
   However, National Security Council spokesman David Leavysaid
there was ``substantial progress'' Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talks haven't broken down. There's still mil-to-mil talks
in Macedonia, and the G-8 ministers meeting in Bonn. We always said
we had to be cautious here, but they're making substantial process,
going over in detail what the elements of the agreement are,
synchronizing various steps. We're going to keep at this until we
find a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland, who helped persuade
Milosevic to accept the deal last week, said Milosevic had assured
him Monday by telephone that he intended to honor the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin spoke
Monday for about 10 minutes, going over the remaining
disagreements. They agreed the Ahtisaari-Chernomyrdin agreement
should be the basis of the settlement. Leavy said there is ``no
question'' Yeltsin supports the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Matic, a spokesman for the Yugoslav government, gave an
upbeat assessment Monday, saying that a Security Council resolution
would resolve the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his Belgrade home, the former Yugoslav Army
chief of staff, Stevan Mirkovic, insisted that the army command
staff was still under Milosevic's control, and that their refusal
to sign the withdrawal document was merely a stalling tactic meant
to allow a Security Council resolution that would transfer from
NATO to the UN responsibility for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be over in three days or less,'' said Mirkovic, 70,
who was harshly critical of both Milosevic and the military, saying
they should have fought to hold on to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mirkovic said the chief complaint put forward by Serb generals _
that seven days was not long enough to pull out 40,000 troops and
equipment _ is specious. He said the Serb forces could withdraw in
less time.
</P>
<P>
   But he and others said the generals had legitimate concerns
about the threat posed by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army both to
withdrawing Serb forces and Serb civilians living in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mirkovic said that, whether in the name of NATO or the UN, the
acceptance of the peace plan that calls for a withdrawal of Serb
troops and their replacement with international peacekeepers ``is
the end of Kosovo'' as part of Serbia. He said that to survive
politically, Milosevic must persuade the public that he had managed
to sidestep NATO and let the UN, to which Yugoslavia belongs, help
the Serbs disarm the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have rather seen a real war. I would have rather lost
the war honorably, as we did in the 14th century, when our leaders
died in war rather than surrender,'' said Mirkovic, referring to
the 1389 battle in Kosovo that the Serbs lost to the Turks in a
defining moment which Serbs see as the birth of their nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no winner here,`` he added. ``NATO has been shamed,
by refusing to fight on the ground. We have been shamed, too, by
giving in to NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratislav Grubacic, a political analyst in Belgrade, said
Milosevic remains firmly in charge. He sees the generals' refusal
to sign the agreement as an attempt to secure political cover for
Milosevic _ a UN resolution on Kosovo that the president can sell
to the public as a victory over NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs an alibi,'' said Grubacic.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear, meanwhile, how many of the 10 million people
in Yugoslavia know what is going on. Government-controlled
television, on which the vast majority of people rely for
information, has been reporting that the discussions in Macedonia
have been between Yugoslav generals and UN officials, not NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The official media has also suggested that NATO has tried to
make new demands on the Yugoslav government. Many people here
express worry that the deal will collapse, but others say their
government should not be humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Zarko Culum, 41, a tram driver, voiced the sentiment of the
latter group, saying, ``We've given up enough. They've squeezed us
like lemons.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant General Mike Jackson, commander of NATO's 16,000
troops in Macedonia, which are set to move into Kosovo, announced
early Monday that the Yugoslav generals were refusing to sign the
withdrawal document.
</P>
<P>
   In response, he said, NATO would intensify its bombing campaign,
which had been scaled down last week in response to Milosevic's
announcement that he accepted the G-8 terms.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a string of broken promises by Milosevic throughout the
decade, NATO has said it will not stop its bombing campaign until
it sees evidence of troops withdrawing from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO underscored its determination to continue its pressure by
using B-52 bombers to pound Serb positions just inside Kosovo near
the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombs also hit the Ekohrana agricultural complex near
Boljevac about 12 miles southeast of Belgrade in the afternoon,
killing three people, the official news agency Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Djindjic, the leader of a main opposition party, said that
he believes Milosevic will honor the peace plan he accepted, and
that the reluctance of generals to sign is an attempt to give
Milosevic a ``fig leaf'' that would make the end of the war look
like a victory rather than a defeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
