<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RALLY ON MERGER NEWS AND EASED INTEREST-HIKE WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rallied Monday, lifted by a brace of
merger announcements and an apparent sense that any move by the
Federal Reserve Board to raise interest rates would be a one-time
event rather than part of a prolonged tightening of policy.
</P>
<P>
   Paced by Allied Signal, which said it was merging with
Honeywell, the Dow Jones industrial average rose for the fifth time
in the last six sessions, closing at its highest level since
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Sectors that have been battered recently, including computers,
Internet stocks and financial services, rebounded, helping to push
up broader market averages.
</P>
<P>
   However, trading volume was quite light _ it was the
second-slowest day of the year on the New York Stock Exchange _
leading some analysts and traders to question the significance of
the rise in prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting a lot of movement on very thin volume,'' said
William Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald. ``From
an investment point of view, there is an extraordinary amount of
risk in the market. But from a short-term perspective, it looks
like people want to trade this thing higher.''
</P>
<P>
   By the close, the Dow was up 109.54 points, or 1 percent, at
10,909.38.
</P>
<P>
   Gains in stocks like Dell Computer; American International
Group, the big insurance company, and DuPont pushed the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index ahead by 6.77 points, or five-tenths of 1
percent, to 1,334.52. Weakness in drug stocks like Pfizer and Eli
Lilly limited the S&AMP;P's advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index soared 45.87 points, or 1.9 percent,
to 2,524.21, propelled by technology stocks. TheStreet.com's
Internet index did even better, rising 32.41 points, or 5.9
percent, to 583.87. And small-cap stocks did well: the Russell 2000
index gained 4.32 points, or 1 percent, to 446.65.
</P>
<P>
   Some traders suggested that the increase in prices was a
follow-through from the gains on Friday, after the release of May
employment data showing that the nation's labor market remained
robust.
</P>
<P>
   But the bond market, which more or less shrugged at the jobs
figures, failed to rally Monday; traders appear convinced the Fed
will raise rates at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts were not so sure. ``I am pretty clearly in the
minority, but I don't expect the Fed to raise rates,'' said Henry
Herrmann, chief investment officer at Waddell &AMP; Reed in Overland
Park, Kan., a firm that manages more than $27 billion in assets,
adding, ``I see too many signs saying there is no inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial service stocks, battered by the recent run-up in
interest rates, recovered a bit Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America, a component of the S&AMP;P 500, rose 1], to 66\.
American Express, a Dow component, gained 2}, to 128. Merrill Lynch
was up 1| at 73~. And Morgan Stanley Dean Witter jumped 3 1/16, to
94 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal, the leading maker of flight systems, rose 4 7/16,
to 62 13/16 after confirming that it would buy Honeywell, the
world's largest maker of automated controls, for $14.8 billion in
stock, plus the assumption of debt. Honeywell jumped 7, to 112.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Energy Group jumped 7 7/16, to 63 3/16, after
disclosing that it had received a hostile takeover bid of $68 a
share from Nisource Inc., a natural gas and electricity company.
Nisource shares fell |, to 27 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Among technology stocks, IBM rose 4{, to 120{, after it
announced an $8 billion technology sales agreement with Acer Group
of Taiwan. Microsoft, which introduced Office 2000 Monday, gained
11/16, to 80\. EMC rose 1 15/16, to 53}. Dell Computer rose 1~, to
35}, and Hewlett-Packard gained 3{, to 94.
</P>
<P>
   Internet issues, which have been in a correction phase in recent
weeks, recovered some lost ground Monday. At Home rose 9\, to 103};
Ebay was up 14} at 183\; Yahoo gained 4 7/16, to 151~, and
Amazon.com rose 8 15/16, to 117].
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks fell on concern that pharmaceutical companies would
be forced to cut prices if the Clinton Administration succeeded in
its effort to offer drug benefits to elderly Americans insured
through Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer fell 4[, to 111; Merck was down 1 5/16 at 69 5/16; Eli
Lilly dropped 3], to 71~, and Schering-Plough was off 1] at 47{.
</P>
</TEXT>
