<HEADER>
A6393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-     06-07 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS SNAG OVER U.N. ROLE IN PEACEKEEPING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ The military talks intended to seal the
withdrawal of Serbian forces from Kosovo stalled in part because
the Yugoslav military balked at provisions that would have avoided
any further U.N. action on the peacekeeping force, according to
NATO officials and Western diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Western diplomat familiar with the NATO document said
Western political leaders had tried to slip that provision into
what was supposed to be a highly detailed technical agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was this idea that if you call it a technical
document it would hide the fact that it went beyond the nuts and
bolts of the military arrangement and was essentially creating the
legal basis for the Kosovo peacekeeping force,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO source said NATO's military officials themselves had been
unaware of these implications. According to the source, alliance
commanders had been assured that all of the political questions
were resolved last week during negotiations between President
Slobodan Milosevic, Finland President Martti Ahtisaari and Russian
special envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   In the third point of that political agreement, a direct
reference was made to the United Nations for the deployment of
peacekeeping troops to Kosovo, but officials here said the six-page
agreement under negotiation never mentioned the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the problem of the U.N. would be exposed during the
talks,'' said a senior European diplomat here. ``Why, then, was the
military encouraged to pursue the talks without the U.N.?''
</P>
<P>
   Another Western diplomat, speaking in Washington, said that the
Yugoslav military had been fully aware of the scope of the document
under negotiation here and their objections about the omission of
the United Nations were an excuse to stop talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think is going on here is that the Yugoslavs want to
have another go at negotiating this, but with the Russians and
Chinese helping them out,'' the diplomat said. ``They want this
done in another venue, and take another crack at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, NATO military officials said Monday that the two days
of talks with the Yugoslav military officers did resolve the basic
aspects of the Serb withdrawal and NATO entry into Kosovo, and
refused to characterize the breakdown as a setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all worked on the level of military men speaking to
military men,'' said Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, spokesman for NATO
forces in Macedonia. ``What this exactly achieved is that firstly
we met and started this discussion process. We know now where each
other is coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks stalled on Sunday after a second day in which both
sides reviewed the document covering the proposed terms of the
withdrawal of Serb troops and their replacement by a NATO-led
force. After 17 hours, the Yugoslav delegation refused to sign
without some form of U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Several military officials and diplomats suggested Monday that
the problem was predictable. They said anyone who had ever
negotiated with Milosevic would never have expected him to sign off
on a document presented on a take-it-or-leave-it basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to have some fig leaf to explain to his people why
they had to endure 2{ months of bombing that has ruined their
country for an agreement that looks an awful lot like the one that
was rejected before the bombing started,'' said a senior Western
official.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, British Minister of Defense George
Robertson made a hastily arranged visit here for talks with Lt.
Gen. Michael Jackson, the commander of KFOR, NATO's peacekeeping
force for Kosovo, and a much-decorated British officer.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks between the general and Robertson were expected to
center on the strategy for convincing Milosevic to accept terms for
withdrawal from Kosovo soon.
</P>
<P>
   However the politicians resolve the U.N. issue, NATO will be in
command of the peacekeeping forces, which will be made up of 50,000
troops. Nearly 16,000 troops have been deployed here over the past
two months and are prepared to enter Kosovo as soon as an agreement
is reached.
</P>
<P>
   However, NATO officials said here Monday that they did not
believe they had lost the momentum for a peace settlement. In spite
of the collapse of the military talks Sunday, NATO and Yugoslav
military officials had a short ``exchange of information'' meeting
Monday at the French air base where Sunday's talks were held.
Clifford said the meeting was an attempt to make the best use of
this new contact between the two warring sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having established the contact, the one thing we are very keen
to do is to keep these lines of communication open,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
