<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NY     06-07 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REFUGEES CAUTIOUS AFTER RECENT SEESAW ON PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(ms) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ When he heard the news of a peace deal between
NATO and the Yugoslav government last week, a deal that might send
him back home after two months as a refugee, Ismet Memaj reacted by
celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drank all day,'' said Memaj, a 52-year-old construction
worker. ``It's true. I was so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, after hearing that the deal might be in danger, he
was more sober-minded. He took his 4-month-old daughter, Daniela,
to a photo shop here to have her passport pictures made. If the
peace deal goes forward, he will go back to Kosovo and wants to be
ready because the family's old identification cards were stolen by
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no deal, he will use them to apply to go far away
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He simply has no idea which way the talks will tip, and for him
and the hundreds of thousands of other Kosovo Albanians who have
been forced from their homes, this most recent chapter in the
Kosovo crisis has only added more maddening uncertainty to the
uncertain life of a refugee.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the moment, we have lost our hope,'' he said. ``It all
depends on NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it stopped neither the NATO bombing nor the war between
Serbian forces and the rebel group fighting them, the tentative
peace agreement had completely changed the focus in the camps here.
</P>
<P>
   The question of what to do when winter arrived gave way to plans
for an orderly return. The drive to move refugees away from camps
near the border _ away from the fighting and the overstrained town
of Kukes _ had been picking up steam. But Monday the NATO buses to
camps in southern Albania were canceled because so few people
signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as NATO, the Serbs and Russians all dicker over the details
of the peace accord, people here say they have no idea what will
happen next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a kind of a trauma,'' said Ymredin Krasniqi, a
47-year-old elementary school teacher living in a small room next
to an electric motor repair shop with 17 other family members.
``They are talking about a peace agreement, but the peace agreement
is nowhere. Where is this peace agreement?''
</P>
<P>
   Military officials from Yugoslavia and NATO were supposed to
sign an agreement in Macedonia on Saturday finalizing technical
details of the pact made last Thursday between NATO and President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. But the talks broke down, with
Yugoslavia raising questions about the agreement's fine print.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, NATO officials announced that they would escalate the
bombing if the deal was not made final. While it seemed to show
some restraint on Monday, NATO continued its attacks on Serbian
positions near the Albanian border, where the fighting has been
heavy between Yugoslav troops and the rebel forces of the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 3:30 p.m. and lasting almost an hour, NATO planes
bombarded several targets near Mount Pastrik, overlooking the main
border crossing here.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly giving credence to speculation that the rebels and NATO
are working together closely _ though NATO has said it has been
taking advantage of the concentrations of Yugoslav troops amassed
to attack the rebels _ the targets Monday were several miles deeper
into Kosovo than similar strikes on Sunday. And Monday the rebels
announced that they had in fact advanced a mile on Sunday after
those bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coincidence,'' said one rebel official, Masar Shala, when
asked to what extent NATO and the rebels were coordinating their
attacks. Shala also contended that more than 200 Serbian soldiers
were killed in the attacks by NATO and the rebels on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the border on Monday, another 100 refugees crossed over into
Albania. They said they came from a prison in northern Kosovo where
other refugees have reported that Serbian forces have taken
thousands of men for interrogation before expelling them from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men who crossed Monday, Batir Kurti, 47 _ who said he
was held for a week _ said the jail, which holds 3,000 or more
people, is still completely full.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know about any peace agreement,'' he said just after
crossing the border in a line of tired men sweating from their
walk.
</P>
<P>
   Around the town of Kukes, roughly 70,000 refugees have found
housing in addition to those in the camps, several people said that
even though they were happy when the agreement was announced last
week, they did not ever really trust Milosevic to honor his pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't believe him,'' said Selmon Limoni, a 75-year-old
refugee, as he sat on a stone near downtown Kukes as the sound of
evening prayers lifted from a mosque at sunset. Like several other
refugees, he said that NATO should send ground troops into Kosovo,
even without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wait for Milosevic to sign, the troops will never get
in _ never,'' he said. ``I thought the United States, Germany and
all these powerful countries were not scared of Milosevic. To be
afraid of him, it's shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahrie Shala, 19, said she has been suspending any excitement
about the deal. ``I won't believe it until I get to my home,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But others had more faith. The refugees had left at a moment's
notice and were ready to return as quickly, but there were still
errands to run. Two days ago, Zijadin Shala, 27, took his wife and
child to the Kukes city hall for a document proving he was a
refugee to whoever might ask on the trek home.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the document is useless, he said on Monday evening
after dinner as his wife yet again scraped the family dishes into a
common trash heap for dozens of families who live with their
tractors near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just waiting for what the world will say to us,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
