<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMEN RETURN TO INTENSIFIED BATTLE OVER GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of the House of Representatives returned
from a weeklong recess Monday to confront a looming battle over gun
control that is even more fraught with political anxiety than it
was before they left.
</P>
<P>
   Increased tensions over new gun-control measures partly
reflected the febrile activity of the National Rifle Association,
which used the congressional recess to rally its supporters, lobby
lawmakers and sprinkle the radio airwaves with advertisements in
opposition to some of the gun-control measures under consideration
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA is pursuing a much more aggressive campaign in the House
than it was able to organize in the Senate, where the gun-control
debate flared with little advance notice. In the Senate, measures
restricting sales of firearms at gun shows and a ban on the import
of high-capacity ammunition clips passed over the rifle group's
objections. The NRA will attempt to beat back similar gun-control
measures that will likely be folded into a juvenile crime bill that
is expected to come to the House floor later this week or early
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA also appears to have taken aim at a rival lobbying
organization of gun manufacturers that supported some of the
measures passed by the Senate last month.
</P>
<P>
   By just about every lawmaker's estimation, the House is certain
to follow the Senate's lead and pass several new gun-control
measures, possibly within the next two weeks. Speaker J. Dennis
Hastert has promised a floor debate within that time frame and
personally signaled his support for a number of new restrictions on
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle association is most fervently opposed to any provision
requiring mandatory background checks on buyers at gun shows that
contains language and details identical to the contents of a
measure passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate measure, vendors at gun shows would have three
business days to complete those checks. The rifle association,
complaining that most weekend gun shows do not last that long,
wants to put a 24-hour limit on the time given to vendors. They
will fight for a shorter background check in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Although most background checks take just minutes, a small
percentage of them can take several days.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle association and many Republicans also contend that the
Senate measure contains a thicket of unnecessarily bureaucratic
paperwork for vendors and gun-show operators.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter that the group sent to its supporters last week, it
warned that what these regulations would do is ``impose a
cradle-to-grave massive federal regulatory scheme on gun owners
throughout America _ and that's no exaggeration!''
</P>
<P>
   The House battle will provide a more definitive measure of the
rifle association's political muscle in the aftermath of a series
of bloody school shootings that created a new momentum for
additional restrictions on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're touching base with just about everybody up there, except
for the people who have absolutely, positively staked out their
position,'' James Jay Baker, the group's chief lobbyist, said
Monday. In addition, Baker said, ``We put together a lot of
grass-roots efforts that came together over the break.''
</P>
<P>
   The recess also provided an opportunity for House Republicans to
reassess their strategy. They said Monday that they might cancel a
scheduled meeting of the House Judiciary Committee on Wednesday at
which committee members were expected to debate, and vote on, the
precise gun-control measures to be folded into the juvenile crime
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, according to senior aides, Republican leaders would
bypass the committee, bring the crime bill to the floor without gun
control provisions and allow those measures to be introduced on the
floor as amendments.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
