<HEADER>
A6400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-NYTR &LR;      06-07 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING DAYS CALLED CRITICAL TO FUTURE OF MEDICARE REFORM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly everyone in Washington has an opinion on how
to fix Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats want to add drug coverage to the program to give
financial relief to beneficiaries relying on a growing array of
costly prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans generally favor running the program more like those
now available in the working world, providing retirees with a
subsidy toward coverage to be chosen from competing insurance
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The medical community wants higher reimbursements, complaining
that reductions in spending arising from the 1997 balanced budget
law are squeezing many hospitals, nursing homes, home-health
agencies and managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the desire is strong for reforms in the $215 billion
program that insures 38 million older and disabled Americans. The
problem is, one side's solution is viewed as another's step
backward.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are leery of the Republican approach, saying it would
weaken the guarantee of insurance seniors now enjoy. Republicans
are nervous about adding a new drug benefit without making other
structural alterations. Health- care providers worry any changes
could carry costs that cut deeper into their payments.
</P>
<P>
   These profound conflicts go to the heart of Medicare reform, a
politically volatile subject now nearing a pivotal moment.
President Clinton is due to unveil his approach to overhauling
Medicare this month and a separate bipartisan proposal will soon be
introduced in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next few weeks are critical,'' declared Sen. John Breaux,
the Louisiana Democrat who led a blue-ribbon panel that failed to
agree on a new Medicare model earlier this year. Now he and Rep.
Bill Thomas, R-Calif., plan to push a congressional version of the
commission plan to give seniors a subsidy toward insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux still believes sweeping Medicare change could be enacted
this year in light of the president's commitment to advancing a
plan and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott's own call last month
for movement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be done,'' Lott, R-Miss., told the Finance
Committee on May 26. ``Medicare is over 30 years old. Not many of
us drive a 30-year-old car. It is time we look at Medicare and
upgrade this car, get a little better model.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and other lawmakers are skeptical that substantial
progress can be made. In the House, Democratic leaders are
reluctant to agree on a plan and sacrifice a winning issue for them
in the fight for House control. And the savings wrung out of the
program have now extended its financial life until 2015, sapping
the urgency from the push for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are going to do anything big this year,''
predicted a top lobbyist for the American Association of Retired
Persons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a very tight squeeze to get anything
done,'' agreed Rep. Karen Thurman, D-Fla., who sits on a House
subcommittee with jurisdiction over Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The more likely outcome is that Congress will attempt to fix
some of the most pressing Medicare concerns and leave the heavy
lifting until after the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman would like to see Congress enact a proposal that forces
drug companies to offer prescriptions to beneficiaries at the same
prices they charge bulk users such as health-maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a new report showing that seniors pay vastly higher
amounts for the drugs, she said the measure could provide some
financial breathing room for beneficiaries in the absence of an
overall Medicare drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Others in Congress are seeking a solution to the crisis caused
in some communities by the sudden withdrawal of Medicare HMOs,
leaving thousands of beneficiaries without a managed care option.
Eight Republican House members recently sent a letter demanding
action on the HMO issue to House GOP leaders on health-care policy.
</P>
<P>
   Health-care providers seem to be making progress in their push
to raise reimbursement rates as Gail Wilensky, a former Medicare
agency chief who now heads a Medicare advisory commission, came out
in support of some increases.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of another round of incremental Medicare
changes is distressing to Breaux and others who believe Medicare's
shortcomings must be addressed comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems you face today _ how to keep Medicare both
solvent and within reach of the modern world _ you will face
forever unless you can fundamentally change the structure of the
program,'' Harry P. Cain, executive director of the Blue Cross and
Blue Shield Association, told the finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux agreed. ``You can't piecemeal this thing,'' he said. ``A
total package of reforms is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
