<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLFCAMERA-PORTRAITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Portraits a new vista for Wolf Camera
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wolf Camera will soon delve into the portrait business
with four studios in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-growing retailer, which spent most of last year
doubling its size through a string of acquisitions, is testing the
new service on its home turf before rolling it out nationwide. Now
one of the nation's largest specialty retailers of photo equipment
and film processing, Wolf Camera is looking at the studio realm as
another way to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the idea from one of the companies we acquired last
year,'' said Wayne Freedman, senior vice president of marketing for
Alpharetta-based Wolf Camera. Last summer, Wolf Camera made the
biggest acquisition of its 25-year history when it bought the
450-store Fox Photo chain from Eastman Kodak Co. Part of the deal
involved 35 Proex Photo stores in Minneapolis equipped with
portrait studios.
</P>
<P>
   According to Freedman, the studio business was too lucrative not
to keep. ``They've got a 30 percent share of the portrait market
there, even with all the competition from mass merchants and other
studios. We learned from them how to do it, and now they're
teaching us how to roll it out here,'' Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Camera is entering a crowded arena. Metro Atlanta has
dozens of independent portrait studios, and it's home to several
studio outfits in large retailers like Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. and
Kmart. Wolf thinks it can lure business away from others by
positioning itself as an expert with a good price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's a lot of dissatisfaction with the portrait
experience among parents with young children. Photographers are not
as patient with kids as they should be,'' Freedman said. Wolf
Camera has hired three to four photographers for each store that
will be trained in social interaction, he said. The Wolf studios,
being built next to existing stores, will also have plenty of toys
and videos to keep children from getting restless, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The other part of Wolf's portrait strategy is to loosen the
restrictions on traditional portrait packages.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Chuck Wolf, widely known as the company's spokesman in
television commercials, will market the concept as ``a portrait
studio where you call the shots.'' Essentially, customers will be
able to pick the proofs in sizes and quantities they want for a set
price. In some instances, they'll get to keep the negatives. That
will enable customers to reprint and copy the photos as much as
they like.
</P>
<P>
   Promotions will start in a few weeks, and the four studios are
set to open in July, Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
   If the test studios are successful, Wolf Camera plans to roll it
out nationwide next year. The retailer now operates more than 700
stores in 30 states, including 73 stores in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
