<HEADER>
A6404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ABORTION-HNS &LR;      06-07 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COUNTY STUDIES HOW NEW LAW WILL AFFECT JUDICIAL SYSTEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new state law restricting abortions for girls has created a
set of legal mysteries in Harris County, where more than 100 minors
a year may go to court to avoid telling their parents about a
pregnancy they want to end.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush signed the legislation into law Monday at a
ceremony at a Dallas hotel. He said the new law ``makes a simple,
urgent point: when a child is in crisis, parents should have a role
and a voice. They should be the first to help, not the last to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   When the law goes into effect Jan. 1, 2000, doctors will have to
notify a parent or guardian 48 hours before performing an abortion
on a patient 17 years old or younger.
</P>
<P>
   There can be exceptions, however. A girl can convince a judge
not to notify her parent or guardian on grounds that it ``would not
be in the minor's best interest,'' that she is mature and
well-informed, or that notification will lead to physical, sexual
or emotional abuse of the pregnant patient.
</P>
<P>
   The law qualifies more than 80 judges in Harris County, which
includes most of Houston, to grant a parental notification
``bypass.'' It says a girl's request can go to a state district
judge, appeals judge, probate judge or county court-at-law judge.
</P>
<P>
   But at a private meeting Tuesday, the judges plan to discuss the
idea of funneling every ``bypass'' request in the county to its
three juvenile court judges: Republicans Mary Craft, Kent Ellis and
Pat Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   The new law makes no mention of designating courts to take
``bypass'' requests. But the county's judicial administrator, state
district Judge Elizabeth Ray, said the local board of judges has
the power to sluice the cases to specific courts.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the juvenile courts and the county's nine family courts
are the most appropriate. But unlike family courts, she said,
juvenile courts have staff investigators who could help the judges
meet the 48-hour deadline.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge does not rule in two business days, the ``bypass''
request is automatically granted, according to the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell at this point how many judicial and staff
hours it is going to take to manage these cases, because we don't
know how many there are,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   The three juvenile court judges did not return telephone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   District Clerk Charles Bacarisse said the abortion hearings are
a new kind of case requiring a novel set of court rules, especially
if they can be brought to any qualified judge in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a challenge for us,'' he said. ``I feel we
can get a good system worked out. It's going to be a process of
getting the right people in the right room, which we have not done
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood of Houston and Southeast Texas Inc., whose
services include abortions, estimates from a survey of its underage
patients that more than 100 girls a year will seek court permission
to have an abortion without their parent or guardian being
notified.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate is based on a survey of 131 girls who obtained
abortions during a three-month span last summer. Of those, 25 said
they did not involve a parent or a trusted adult in their decision
to terminate their pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood is forming a task force of lawyers, clergy
and community leaders to study the law and will consider helping
girls make ``bypass'' requests, spokeswoman Susan Nenney said.
</P>
<P>
   If a girl files a request without a lawyer, the judge must
appoint one for her at state expense.
</P>
<P>
   The new law is silent about whether girls must apply for a
bypass only in their home county.
</P>
<P>
   That means an application by a Harris County girl could be filed
anywhere in the state, according to Joe Kral, legislative director
of Houston-based Texas Right To Life Committee Inc., which opposes
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will monitor statewide rules that will be
developed by Dec. 15 by the state Department of Health and the
Texas Supreme Court, Kral said.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires the health department to publish rules on the
medical rights of abortion patients, information about alternatives
to abortion and the forms doctors must use to inform parents or
guardians. The high court must develop rules for making the court
hearings speedy as well as confidential.
</P>
<P>
   But like many other facets of the laws, those details don't
exist yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the legislation signed,'' Kral said. ``We need to make
sure the Supreme Court creates rules that don't cause a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors of the new law, who joined Bush at the signing
ceremony, vowed that it was ``the building block on which future
legislation will stand,'' a promise to continue trying to expand
restriction on abortions that did not surprise abortion-rights
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is anti-choice,'' said Kae McLaughlin, executive director
of the Texas Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, who
distributed press releases outside the ballroom where the signing
took place. ``He is trying to appear moderate, but this (bill) is
exactly what the Christian Coalition wanted.``
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition agreed. ``This is a historic day for
Texas,'' said Chuck Anderson, the coalition's executive director in
Texas. ``With more than 80 per cent of the public supporting this
legislation and clear majorities supporting other abortion
restrictions, we are moving in the right direction.``
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, the
countrywide arm of McLaughlin's group, is running ads against Bush
in Iowa, where he makes his first presidential campaign visit
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When a parental notification bill was considered by the
Legislature in 1997, representatives of Harris County's 59 state
district judges wrote to lawmakers about ``procedural and
administrative problems'' with the proposal. The judges said they
were especially concerned that a ``bypass'' request would force any
judge to close his court to other business for 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The judges withdrew their statements after Dr. Steven Hotze, a
Houston conservative activist whose endorsements have swayed
several judicial elections, warned that the judges were undermining
efforts to pass the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The judges did not comment about the bill as a group this year,
Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   The new law in Texas, which is similar to those in 39 other
states, was modeled after Minnesota's, which was upheld by the U.S.
Supreme Court last year. Attorney General John Cornyn said Monday
that the Texas act ``is constitutional and will be successfully
defended in a court.``
</P>
<P>
   Kral said the 48-hour hearings will not stymie Harris County
courts because they already handle cases that need immediate
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray said case backlogs in other courts was one of the
reasons the cases might be funneled only to the juvenile courts.
</P>
<P>
   Hotze, whose political agenda features opposition to abortion,
backed Pat Shelton, one of the three juvenile court judges, against
a challenger in the 1998 Republican primary. Hotze opposed the
re-election of another juvenile court judge, Mary Craft, but she
prevailed. Juvenile Court Judge Kent Ellis, was unopposed in the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Houston Chronicle reporter Jim Henderson in Dallas contributed to
this story &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
