<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6407 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BEST-SPI &LR;      06-07 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT THE `BEST' OF THE PAST TV SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the interests of full disclosure, the headline accompanying
this column is like an NBC promotional campaign, that is, not to be
taken literally. Its use of the term ``best'' might suggest we'll
be accentuating only the positive, but we're being coy. Sort of
like the three sisters in ``Charmed,'' who smile sweetly just
before they mess with the space-time continuum.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, some of these acknowledgments of the past TV season aren't
necessarily singing the praises of a particular program or network.
There's plenty of good stuff on television, but there's lot to
complain about, too, even when we're on our ``best'' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Best new series
</P>
<P>
   to be canceled:
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives gave up on ``Cupid'' faster than some kids give
up on green veggies. Too bad. Like lima beans, it was an acquired
taste, but it was rich in fiber, with Jeremy Piven perfect in a
scenery-chewing role that was an actor's dream.
</P>
<P>
   One consolation: Paula Marshall, who played psychiatrist Claire
Allen opposite Piven's manic Cupid, will be back next season in
David E. Kelley's new ABC drama, ``Snoops.'' A second consolation:
``Cupid'' creator Rob Thomas, a man with interesting ideas, is
executive producer of ``Snoops.''
</P>
<P>
   Best new series to be
</P>
<P>
   renewed, network division:
</P>
<P>
   We'll give this one to ``Sports Night,'' but with several
strings attached so we can yank it back if Felicity Huffman's
character, Dana Whitaker, persists next season in trying to join
the Ally McBeal League of Mixed Nuts. What started out as a
different sort of half-hour program on ABC became distressingly
like most other sitcoms by the end of 22 episodes, with Huffman's
Whitaker going from a strong, multifaceted woman to a quivering,
shivering puddle of Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's inevitable that TV series do the
romance-in-the-workplace dance. But if Robert Guillaume hadn't been
forced into a long absence by a stroke, I'm convinced ``Sports
Night'' would have continued as a show about workplace issues, not
relationship issues.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of people named Felicity, The WB's ``Felicity,'' a
drama about a young woman's first year of college, got serious
consideration in this category but ultimately faltered because it,
too, couldn't get out of the romance rut.
</P>
<P>
   While we're at it, let's give ABC credit for keeping ``Whose
Line Is It, Anyway?'' on the fall schedule. Because of its
spontaneous nature, improvisational comedy is a risky business, but
``Line'' is almost always good for a genuine laugh that's not
rooted in sitcom banality.
</P>
<P>
   Best new series to be
</P>
<P>
   renewed, cable division:
</P>
<P>
   Sing it loud, sing it proud: ``The Sopranos.'' This superbly
cast mobster-in-analysis drama was an idea that Fox passed up a few
seasons ago, which is just more proof that you, too _ or maybe that
slug munching the vegetation out back _ could be a network
programming executive.
</P>
<P>
   To be suitable for network consumption, ``The Sopranos'' would
have to lose the bad language and nudity that HBO can get away
with, but the parallel stories of a mob capo struggling with two
dysfunctional families is the sort of thing networks should be
embracing, not rejecting.
</P>
<P>
   Best new cast member:
</P>
<P>
   Some of us thought Steven Bochco was squeezin' our shoes with
the announcement that Rick Schroder would replace Jimmy Smits in
the cast of ``NYPD Blue.'' But as they say in the patois of the
15th precinct, with respect to the Emmy, I'm likin' Schroder for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Best example of
</P>
<P>
   colorful scheduling
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its 1999-2000 schedule last month, Fox left ``The
PJs'' off its fall list, even though Eddie Murphy's gentle satire
of life in the projects had better Nielsen ratings than Matt
Groening's animated sci-fi comedy, ``Futurama,'' which is returning
in the fall in the cushy Sunday night spot after ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely it has nothing to do with race. (``Futurama'' is a
production of Twentieth Century Fox TV, Fox's own studio. ``The
PJs,'' which is on Fox's midseason replacement list, is made by Ron
Howard's Imagine Television, which is affiliated with Disney, which
owns ABC.)
</P>
<P>
   Best ensemble:
</P>
<P>
   With each favorable mention of The WB's ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer,'' I inevitably hear from a few cranks who think I've lost
my ball in the tall grass again. True, the title tends to scare
away people who can't believe good TV lurks behind something so
frivolously named. But there are some who agree that, week in and
week out, ``Buffy'' presents some of the best writing and acting on
the networks. The acting part is thanks to a fine cast that
routinely gets overlooked by the awards-show judges, so here, to
give credit where it's due, is the whole underappreciated lineup:
Sarah Michelle Gellar, Alyson Hannigan, Seth Green, Anthony Stewart
Head, Nicholas Brendon, David Boreanaz and Charisma Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, things may never be the same after this season. Next fall,
Boreanaz and Carpenter will appear in a spinoff series, ``Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Second place goes to the wonderful cast of ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Best supporting cast:
</P>
<P>
   I always liked Fred and Ethel better than I loved Lucy and
Ricky. Same goes for Jack and Karen of ``Will &AMP; Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not be polite to steal scenes, but Sean Hayes and Megan
Mullally do it regularly and with my complete approval as Jack
McFarland and Karen Walker. With exquisite timing and fabulous
physical comedy skills, Hayes and Mullally are naturally funnier
than the show's stars, Eric McCormack and Debra Messing.
</P>
<P>
   Best miniseries:
</P>
<P>
   For four Sundays in April, A&AMP;E was the place to catch a spirited
and stunningly photographed quartet of C.S. Forester's ``Horatio
Hornblower'' stories. Ioan Gruffudd's portrayal of a young naval
officer during the Napoleonic Wars was crisp and clean, devoid of
the melodrama so often associated with such period pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Best voice since Bacall:
</P>
<P>
   It's a tossup between Andrea Thompson (Jill Kirkendall on ``NYPD
Blue'') and Angie Harmon (Abbie Carmichael on ``Law &AMP; Order'').
Thompson's voice is closer to Lauren Bacall's _ a sort of low
rumble that seems to rise from her toes. Harmon's is more the
husky, whiskey-and-smoke type reminiscent of Demi Moore. Either
way, a voice that commands attention.
</P>
<P>
   Best role reversal:
</P>
<P>
   In season two, ``Ally McBeal'' star Calista Flockhart (with an
assist from David E. Kelley) changed an appealingly complex woman
into an angry, mean-spirited harpy.
</P>
<P>
   Best misuse of artistic license
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Noah's Ark,'' for a bad rewrite of Genesis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
