<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-POLAND-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE USES ENCYCLICAL ON FAITH TO DEFEND COPERNICUS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORUN, Poland _ In 1543, the Polish astronomer Copernicus sent
his revolutionary thesis on the movement of the planets to Rome
with a poignant letter seeking understanding from Pope Paul III. He
never received a reply.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, a former philosophy professor, gave an answer
Monday all too familiar to academics. He replied, in essence, read
my book.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I wrote in the encyclical Fides et Ratio'' (Faith and
Reason), the pope told a thousand Polish academics and scientists
gathered in a lecture hall at Copernicus University here,
``deprived of reason, faith has stressed feeling and experience,
and so runs the risk of no longer being a universal proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope used his most recent encyclical to defend Copernicus,
who was born in Torun and whose ``On the Movement of Heavenly
Bodies'' was denounced by the Vatican in 1616 and removed from the
Vatican's index of forbidden books only in 1822. ``Although
Copernicus himself saw his discovery as giving rise to even greater
amazement at the Creator of the world and the power of human
reason,'' the pope said, ``many people took it as a means of
setting reason against faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, 79, who has returned to his native Poland for the
eighth visit of his papacy, once again took time to meet with old
colleagues and former students and bask in the close-knit Polish
academic world that formed him as a scholar as well as a priest. It
was the pope's first opportunity to explain his encyclical,
published in October, to some of the scholars he trusts the most.
He argues that modern philosophy has lost its grounding in human
values and the quest for spiritual truth, and urged his fellow
Poles to teach their students to seek hope, not ``nihilism.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope provided a context that has particular resonance for
his generation of scholars and theologians, many of whom were
persecuted by the Nazis and the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does not the history of our century, with its wars, its
criminal totalitarian ideologies, its concentration camps and
gulags, make it easy for us to yield to the temptation of
discouragement and despair?'' he asked. He quoted Pascal to respond
that, ``In order to discover hope, we need to lift our gaze on
high.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third stop in a grueling day of Masses and special
prayer services in this northern region of Poland, where World War
II began in 1939. But it was clear that the pope relished his brief
return to academia, where he was given standing ovations by
university rectors from all over the country, many of whom wore
velvet caps and ermine-trimmed robes that have not changed since
the time of Copernicus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, he was presented by the rector of Jagiellonian
University in Krakow with a 50th anniversary copy of the doctoral
degree in theology he received there in 1948. The pope eagerly took
hold of the scroll, unrolled it and slowly and carefully read it,
to the delight of his audience. As he left, he exclaimed, ``Vivat
academia! Vivat professores!'' Those Latin phrases, popular in the
Middle Ages, are still the anthem of Polish academia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a little older and weaker, but he is still the same
person, with a beautiful memory for names and faces,'' said Andrzej
Szostek, who studied ethics under the pope when he was Cardinal
Karol Wojtyla at the Catholic University of Lublin and who is now
that university's rector.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Szostek, who teaches ethics, said that Polish universities, even
non-Catholic ones, were not overrun with the moral relativist
philosophers fashionable in Europe and the United States, but that
the pope's message was nevertheless needed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The general tendency is not as strong in Poland, but we are
influenced by contemporary Western thought,'' he said. ``The pope
is a very good observer, not only of social and spiritual matters
but also intellectual life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pope ended his day on a more somber contemporary note. After
beatifying Stefan Frelichowski, a local priest who died at the
Dachau extermination camp and is considered a martyr to Nazi
persecution, the pope linked that war with one still raging nearby,
in the Balkans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak these words in a land that in its history experienced
the tragic effects of the lack of peace, having been victim of a
cruel and ruinous war,'' he told 200,000 followers gathered in a
field at the Torun airport. ``How much innocent blood is being shed
under our very eyes? We are witnesses to how strongly people cry
out for and yearn for peace. The tragic events in Kosovo have shown
us this and are still showing us this so painfully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
