<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-REPAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAIN REVEALS POWER TO REPAIR ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston scientists, experimenting on mice, have shown that they
can repair widespread brain damage by implanting a kind of
uncommitted, all-purpose ``stem cell'' that migrates through the
brain and spawns the needed replacement cells.
</P>
<P>
   The findings raise new hopes for treating devastating conditions
such as multiple sclerosis and diseases that cause severe
retardation in children, and possibly Alzheimer's disease and other
degenerative brain disorders and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   All these problems result from the death or absence of, or
damage to, neurons, the nerve cells that make up the ``white
matter'' of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, scientists thought it would be difficult, if not
impossible, to replace malfunctioning cells scattered throughout
the brain. So they have focused on implanting healthy cells in
brains of people with disorders, such as Parkinson's disease, that
are caused by damage to small, circumscribed areas of brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   But in a new report, researchers at Children's Hospital and
Harvard Medical School say they may have overcome that longstanding
barrier, at least in an animal model. They injected versatile
neural ``stem cells'' into newborn mice with widespread brain
damage that made them shiver uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the stem cells _ ``progenitor'' cells with
offspring that can be any kind of brain cell _ migrated throughout
the brain. And, responding to some precise but unknown signal, they
spawned the exact kind of cell the mouse brains lacked and repaired
the nerve damage. The report says that the repairs dramatically
reduced the shaking in 60 percent of the animals.
</P>
<P>
   The report is in the Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences. The authors are Drs. Booma D. Yandava, Lori L.
Billinghurst, and Evan Y. Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting. I'm very positive about this,'' said Ronald
McKay, a scientist at the National Institute of Neurological
Disorders and Stroke, which is helping finance the research. ``It's
not a cure for multiple sclerosis, and it's not in (mice) adults,
but it's a very interesting step'' in the effort to engineer cells
to repair a wide range of brain disorders and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, the senior author, said although clinical tests in
people are years away, he has begun putting human neural stem cells
into mice in experiments designed to show that human cells have the
same ability to migrate all over the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The key player in this process, the neural stem cell, is a
``totipotential'' cell that hasn't become committed to any
particular role, and can spawn all kinds of brain cells _ including
more stem cells. Scientists have found stem cells (of different
kinds, depending on the organ they reside in) in many other organs
of the body. In addition, researchers recently isolated embryonic
stem cells that form soon after conception, which can give rise to
any type of cell in the body.
</P>
<P>
   Although stem cells are abundant in the developing fetus, they
also can be found in adult human and animal brains, Snyder said.
The discovery of neural stem cells in the last decade suggested
that here was a source of healthy new cells to repair damage _ much
as blood stem cells are transplanted into patients whose own
blood-forming bone marrow cells have been destroyed by disease or
by cancer chemotherapy. ``This is like a bone marrow transplant for
the brain,'' said Snyder, who is an assistant professor of
neurology in the pediatrics department at Children's.
</P>
<P>
   The neural stem cells for the experiment came from the brains of
4-day-old mice. They were implanted into a strain of mice known as
``shiverers'' because of their constant shakiness: The cause is a
gene mutation that results in many nerve cells lacking the normal
sheath of myelin, a protein that acts like the insulation on an
electric line. Multiple sclerosis, an often progressive and
disabling disease, also is caused by a lack of myelin sheathing on
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said he implanted the neural stem cells into the sick
mice just after they were born because at that stage neural stem
cells are normally migrating throughout the developing brain.
Therefore, it was more likely that the implanted cells would spread
through the brain tissue and make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The stem cells differentiated into the kind of cells, called
oligodendrocytes, that were missing in the ``shiverer'' mice.
Snyder said the results suggested that the brains somehow signaled
to the stem cells that oligodendrocytes were needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
