<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0608-C     06-07 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO STEPS UP AIR STRIKES AS SEARCH FOR PEACE CONTINUES
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-0608.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Struggling to rescue the imperiled Kosovo peace
process, President Clinton and his Russian counterpart Boris
Yeltsin ordered their top diplomats to try to craft a resolution on
the matter to go to the United Nations Security Council as early as
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats _ meeting with foreign ministers from other
so-called G-8 countries in Bonn _ spent eight hours hashing over
resolution language Monday and were scheduled to reconvene early
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to press the talks toward closure, Clinton called Yeltsin
to stress that peace is at hand and to ask for Moscow's help in
nailing down language for a Security Council resolution embracing
the peace accord Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic accepted last
Thursday but has yet to implement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very constructive call,'' White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart told reporters. He said the two leaders agreed to
authorize their top diplomats to work out their differences quickly
in Bonn and get the resolution before the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to craft language for a U.N. Security Council
resolution that properly reflects the agreement that Milosevic has
accepted,'' said Mike Hammer, a spokesman at the White House for
the National Security Council. ``We think that will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days after agreeing to pull out his forces from Kosovo,
Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, continued to balk at NATO's
terms for withdrawal on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials made good on their pledge to intensify their air
attacks, ramping up the sortie level to more than 200 strike
missions overnight Monday. They targeted radio relay towers, ammo
dumps and field forces from Kosovo northward into Serbia proper.
</P>
<P>
   After flying 93 strike sorties concentrating on Serb forces in
the field in Kosovo on Sunday, U.S. and allied pilots were
scheduled to fly ``two to three times'' that many overnight Monday,
said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipate that you'll see an intensification over the next
few days,'' Bacon told reporters at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' he said. ``Time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO returned to an all-out war footing, diplomatic efforts
intensified in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his NATO allies were hopeful that U.N. adoption of
the resolution would clear the way for the continuation of talks
between NATO and Serb commanders over the withdrawal of all Serb
troops, police and paramilitary forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   High level talks over the pull-out broke down Sunday after Serb
officials rejected NATO's terms.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic spoke by telephone Monday with Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari, who passed word to diplomats meeting in Germany
that the Serb leader intends to comply with the peace accord he
accepted last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic says he intends to go forward with the agreement,''
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters in Bonn,
where Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is leading U.S.
negotiations over the Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic agreed last Thursday to pull out Serb forces from
Kosovo and permit an international peacekeeping force to police the
war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement called for that force, as well as a group of
civilian organizations, to operate inside Kosovo under U.N.
auspices. U.S. officials interpreted the breakdown of the military
talks to suggest that Milosevic wants to see the Security Council
resolution before making good on his pledge to withdraw Serb forces
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the sequence NATO had in mind last Thursday.
Instead, they anticipated a relatively quick Serb troop withdrawal,
followed by a NATO bombing halt and then a U.N. Security Council
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule has now been disturbed,'' Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov told reporters in Bonn. As a result, he said,
``wording of the resolution has become difficult, and we are
continuing to work on it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albright and Ivanov met for eight hours Monday in Bonn with
their six counterparts from Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy
and Japan _ the so-called Group of Eight major democratic powers _
to try to hammer out language for a 20-point Security Council
resolution. Talks were scheduled to resume early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have managed to solve 17,'' of the issues, said German
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer. ``We do hope that we will clear
those (remaining) points tomorrow, so that we can get a
constructive work to the Security Council and that we can take a
decision in the Security Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the outstanding issues was whether to stipulate in the
resolution that the peacekeeping force would be led by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is opposed to that. Russians share close historical and
cultural ties with their Slavic kin, the Serbs, and have tried to
back Milosevic's demands for a watered-down U.N. security force
that would be largely unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, however, has insisted that the force be a robust combat
contingent led by the trans-Atlantic alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 48,000 troops anticipated to make up the force, NATO
countries have pledged 44,000 troops. Another 4,000 have been
pledged by NATO partner countries.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops are also anticipated, but Moscow has not yet
pledged forces.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials reiterated Monday that the force would be
NATO-led.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not negotiable,'' said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't certain, though, that NATO leadership would be
stipulated in the Security Council resolution. In essence, Russia
seeks ambiguity while the United States would prefer specificity.
Compromise language was seen as likely.
</P>
<P>
   A second issue was how to deal with the matter of Milosevic's
indictment by the U.N. war crimes tribunal. No mention of his
indictment was included in last Thursday's agreement. Some NATO
members reportedly were pressing for explicit mention in the
Security Council resolution, and Russia was balking.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials declined to confirm the third area of outstanding
disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   Low level communications continued Monday between Serb and NATO
commanders, but those talks were well below the decision-making
level, said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's primarily just to keep the phone lines open and the tea
water warm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how soon NATO's bombing might end, Bacon reiterated that
it depends on how quickly Serb forces withdraw from Kosovo, a
matter that remains out of NATO's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think predictions are worth the paper they're printed
on,'' said Bacon. ``At this stage, we just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
