<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX-800&AMP;     06-07 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS STILL HOPEFUL THAT SNAGS IN PEACE ACCORD CAN BE
WORKED OUT
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration officials expressed hope on
Monday that the snag in talks about the withdrawal of Yugoslav
troops from Kosovo would be resolved within the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides acknowledged that they had been excessively
optimistic immediately following the apparent agreement on Thursday
by President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to allied terms for
ending the 10-week conflict. And they implied that they had
overreacted to the temporary breakdown in the talks in Macedonia on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials settled on a more neutral tone on Monday, advising
patience and wariness as diplomats from NATO, Russia and the United
Nations seek a formula for the withdrawal of the Serbian troops
from Kosovo and the entry of an allied peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The White House blamed Milosevic for the breakdown. ``We have
been down the road with Milosevic before and we understand some of
the tactics that he employs from time to time,'' said Joe Lockhart,
the White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do is avoid the situation where we go to
one extreme or another. We have known all along that this is a
difficult process. We have used every means we could think of to
urge caution as we moved along, both on the euphoria and the
depression.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton spoke on Monday morning with President Boris
Yeltsin of Russia, who assured Clinton that Russia would not try to
undermine the terms of the peace agreement with Milosevic. The
agreement was reached last week with the help of Viktor
Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy for the Balkans, and President
Martti Ahtisaari of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for the rapid withdrawal of 40,000 Yugoslav troops from
the once largely autonomous Kosovo province of Serbia, which is the
main entity in Yugoslavia. The Yugoslav forces are to be replaced
with a 50,000-troop monitoring force under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very constructive call,'' Lockhart said of the
Yeltsin-Clinton conversation. ``The two presidents affirmed that
implementation of Ahtisaari-Chernomyrdin document, accepted last
week by Milosevic, should form the basis for a peaceful settlement
of conflict and the suspension of NATO's air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had no public comment Monday on the status of the
negotiations in Europe or the continuing NATO air strikes. Aides
said that he would refrain from making statements until there is
substantial progress or a dangerous collapse of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   In part to spur the negotiations, and in part to take advantage
of new opportunities to hit Yugoslav forces on the ground in
Kosovo, military officials planned new air raids.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said that NATO intended
on Monday evening to double or triple the 93 bombing missions that
NATO warplanes flew on Sunday. Other Pentagon officials said that
targets in and around Belgrade would be hit again after a three-day
hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also warned against fears that the delay could scuttle the
deal. ``Just as there was reason not to be wildly optimistic on
Friday, there are reasons not to be wildly pessimistic today,'' he
said. ``This is a process.''
</P>
<P>
   Other administration officials and Western diplomats were
equally sanguine that Milosevic, after a certain amount of
negotiating, would honor the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Milosevic being Milosevic,'' said one administration
official with extensive experience in the Balkans. ``He's tough. He
makes you press for any gain. He probes for soft spots. And he's
willing to take a few more days of bombing to see if he can get a
better deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Defining that ``better deal'' from Milosevic's perspective, the
official said, ``Anything that waters down NATO's authority and
anything that leaves more Yugoslav security forces in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Galbraith, a former U.S. ambassador to Croatia, agreed,
saying, ``These are characteristic tactics: delay and seeking to
revise the agreement.'' Referring to the Yugoslav demand that the
U.N. Security Council approve a peacekeeping force before NATO
troops enter Kosovo, he said, ``The issue of the U.N. Security
Council Resolution is both face-saving and a delay tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding out for a Security Council resolution also increases the
likelihood that Russia and China would publicly voice some support
for Yugoslavia that Milosevic could use as political cover
domestically and as a possible shield against some NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   American and Western officials said the Yugoslav military
commanders may have some legitimate concerns, like trying to meet
NATO's demand to withdraw all 40,000 troops from Kosovo in phases
within seven days.
</P>
<P>
   But Balkan experts discounted any split between the military and
Milosevic, whom they said still holds on iron grip on the country's
military and security forces.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The military is lockstep with Milosevic,'' an administration
official said. ``They're doing exactly what he tells them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior American officer with experience in the Balkans said
any delay would have two secondary effects that Yugoslavia would
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   First, the longer the delay, the more the armored Serbian troops
in Kosovo can pound Albanian rebels. Bacon said on Monday that
pitched battles were under way between the lightly armed Kosovo
Liberation Army rebels and Yugoslav army forces around the Western
Kosovo town of Junik and at Mount Pastrik, on the border between
Kosovo and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had brought in reinforcements over the past few days,
Bacon said, as the rebels cling to territory against an aggressive
Yugoslav counteroffensive.
</P>
<P>
   Prolonging a final settlement, in Yugoslavia's view, would also
lessen the chances that the more than 800,000 Kosovo Albanians
expelled from the province would return.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon played down reports that Greece would block more than
2,000 Marines now aboard ships in the Aegean Sea from unloading at
the Greek port of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek government is under extraordinary domestic pressure
not to be seen as accommodating anything other than a peacekeeping
force and is likely to allow the marines to land and drive from the
port to staging areas in adjacent Macedonia only after a final
agreement is signed, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today a spokesman for the Greek government said that they
would be allowed to off-load and transit through Greece soon,''
Bacon said, without giving a date. ``We don't believe that there'll
be any problem with meeting the time lines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
