<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-BALLOTING-N     06-07 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BALLOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAKARTA, COUNTING THE VOTE IS A LABORIOUS BUT PRECIOUS EXERCISE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DADAP, Indonesia _ As the ballot counting began on Monday in
this fishing village west of Jakarta, a crowd of eagle-eyed locals
encircled a makeshift polling place. They watched as workers
laboriously unfolded and called out each vote. It was a tedious
business, but nobody was complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are not my friends, so I'm watching to make sure
they don't do anything bad,'' said Hasanuddin Saman, 36, a
fisherman who had just voted in the first democratic election in
Indonesia during his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three decades of strongman rule _ in which
elections were rigged affairs marked by ballot stuffing, payoffs
and intimidation _ Indonesians know how empty an election can be.
They see this vote as a precious opportunity for their country, and
they are determined to keep it clean.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter and 600 other monitors, including
some from Australia, Europe and Japan, were also on hand to observe
the counting. But the outsiders were scarcely more vigilant than
people like Saman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election today is a real election,'' he said without
averting his gaze from the counting table. ``The previous elections
were a joke. We always knew who was going to win before they even
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Saman allowed himself a smile. The voting in Dadap had been
peaceful. And with the ballots being counted in an orderly way, it
looked as if this village of 6,000 people on the northern coast of
Java would do its part to bring democracy to the world's
fourth-most-populous country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, it was free and fair,'' said Ramli, 52, after he
emerged from a voting booth constructed of bamboo and used rice
bags. Ramli, a construction worker who like many Indonesians uses
only one name, said: ``No one has bribed or intimidated us to vote
for any party. I don't miss the bribes.''
</P>
<P>
   Such comments attest to how fervently Indonesians yearn for a
change in their political system. With Indonesia's economy still in
a calamitous recession, villages like Dadap have tumbled into
poverty. Many people have lost their jobs. And the collapse of
Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, has demolished the purchasing
power of even those who still have work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have suffered tremendously,'' said Madi Taufan, 29, a
garment worker. ``Inflation is so high that our money can't buy
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet for all the hardship, nobody here seems to want to
return to the patronage of old-style Indonesian politics. In
previous elections, the ruling Golkar party of former President
Suharto used to pay for votes. Suharto's successor, B.J. Habibie,
hopes this election will confer new legitimacy on Golkar. But here,
at least, he seems likely to suffer a stinging repudiation.
</P>
<P>
   Dicky Ardi, 24, a courier who said he voted for a leading reform
candidate, Megawati Sukarnoputri, said, ``If Habibie stays
president, he won't put Suharto on trial. Suharto cannot be
forgiven for what he has done to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other rural villages, Dadap was spared the riots and
looting that tore through Jakarta last May and precipitated
Suharto's resignation. But Monday one of the village elders said he
still feared that violence would break out during the voting. As he
surveyed the tranquil scene, with villagers lining up to vote while
their children cavorted in a muddy field, the man was visibly
relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, an aging fisherman was repairing a bamboo net. He said
it would be victory enough if Indonesia held an election without
bloodshed, adding, ``I just pray that this will bring the country
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
