<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MOYERS-REVIEW-SFCH     06-07 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOYERS-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FREE' SPEECH THAT'S BOUGHT AND PAID FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad guys have serious TV journalism surrounded, but there
are still a few die-hards refusing to come out with their hands up.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Moyers, for one. He's less prolific than he used to be
because of heart disease and his recuperation from heart surgery in
1994. But he still has the ambition to look large at what ails his
country.
</P>
<P>
   His latest is ``A Bill Moyers Special: Free Speech for Sale,''
airing Tuesday on PBS, in which he suggests that the most effective
``free'' speech these days is the type bought by the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Moyers' concern is that big money is smothering the American
democratic ideal of vigorously competing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   And the culprits may include NBC, ABC, Fox and CBS, which is to
say General Electric, Disney, News Corp. and, well, CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The special is divided into three segments. First, Moyers looks
at how corporate hog farmers used ``issue advocacy'' advertising to
drive a Republican legislator out of office in North Carolina.
She'd had the gall to question the air and water contamination
caused by animal waste.
</P>
<P>
   The second segment is about the tobacco industry's $40 million
media campaign to defeat legislation last year that would have made
tobacco companies accountable for the health damage caused by
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, and perhaps most interestingly, Moyers questions the
shortage of network news coverage of the 1996 Telecommunications
Act, which by and large was a lovely piece of legislation for
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   The act extended broadcasting licenses, weakened stations'
community responsibilities, allowed group station owners (including
the networks) to expand their reach and gave TV broadcasters use of
the digital spectrum in what critics said amounted to a $70 billion
giveaway of a publicly owned resource.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a juicy nugget for NBC News' ``Fleecing of America''
feature. It wasn't. Moyers says that in a critical nine-month
period, the network newscasts devoted a total of 19 minutes of
coverage to the act _ mostly about the V-chip provision _ and no
time to the digital spectrum issue.
</P>
<P>
   The point, Moyers says, is that if money talks, big money
shouts. Or, in the case of covering the Telecommunications Act,
whispers inaudibly.
</P>
<P>
   In each of these cases, the presumed danger was that money alone
could settle public issues. Anyone who's not a bunk-mate of
corporate interests had trouble being heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (James) Madison put that First Amendment in
there just as a device to protect rich people's ability to dominate
the political process,'' says Burt Neuborne, legal director of the
Brennan Center for Justice at the New York University School of
Law.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers could use a broader context. For example, tobacco money
doesn't necessarily carry the day; last year, California's
Proposition 10 and its cigarette tax passed despite a $30 million
campaign against it. And there is the argument, used to help pass
the Telecommunications Act, that TV's explosion of channels, and
voices, has chipped away at the need for tight regulation. The
broadcasting oligopoly is dead.
</P>
<P>
   But Moyers still makes a disturbing case. It has become too
important to be big in order to be loud in American public life.
It's the sort of issue, vital to a healthy democracy, that will
never be squarely addressed on ``Dateline NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   I spent much of last year missing Moyers as the nation was in
the thrall of Monicagate. How would Moyers, the man who made so
much sense of Watergate and Iran-contra, have tackled the peculiar
Clinton crisis?
</P>
<P>
   Moyers, who turned 65 on Saturday, said in a phone interview
that he scratched his head and ruminated along with the rest of us,
and toyed with the idea of a TV special on the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to; I thought about it,'' he said. ``I just could not
figure out a way to get my mind around it in an original way. ... I
just never could figure a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For television's lesser journalists, it came all too naturally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
