<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6440 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-DOMINATOR-COX     06-07 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-DOMINATOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dominik the Dominator: Hasek's journey to the Cup finals
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If the style appears to resemble some panic-stricken
youth, there's a reason. The arms go here, the legs go there,
sometimes in ways that don't seem anatomically possible. This is
the way he taught himself as a youth in the hamlet of Pardubice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always the goalie, from first practice when I was five
years old,'' Dominik Hasek said Monday. ``I remember when I was in
my kitchen or on lake, I never wanted to shoot the puck. I would
put my legs down like this, like posts, and I would tell my father
to shoot the puck. I would do the same in soccer. Always, I wanted
to stop the ball or the puck. I never wanted to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek would stand in the doorway of his kitchen, his father
throwing tennis balls at home. Arms went here, legs went there.
Czech home-schooling for goaltenders. Hasek did not become a
stylist. He became Baryshnikov in a blender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what he looks like,'' Detroit assistant
coach Dave Lewis said. ``Buffalo has the most dangerous weapon in
hockey. They not only have a great goaltender, they have a guy who
elevates everybody else's level of play. That's when you know you
have somebody special.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning tonight, Hasek will try to elevate his own career and
Buffalo to previously unforeseen heights when the Sabres meet the
favored Dallas Stars in the opener of the best-of-seven Stanley Cup
finals at Reunion Arena. Hasek has won consecutive Hart Trophies as
the league's most valuable player, as well as the Vezina as its top
goalie, and led his native Czech Republic to a gold medal in the
Winter Olympics last year.
</P>
<P>
   What he and the Sabres never have experienced is a Stanley Cup.
It's not the goal generally embraced by European hockey players,
but Hasek has been in the NHL long enough (nine years) and had
enough ups and downs that he has gained a hunger for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Nagano, we met each other at the airport, went to the
Olympics and in two weeks it was over,'' he said. ``Here, you must
play one month just to get to the Stanley Cup finals. I know how it
feels to win an Olympic medal. I don't know how it feels to win the
Cup. But I know what it means to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek put himself in position for more post-season honors, going
30-18-14 with a 1.87 goals-against average and .937 saves
percentage. He has been similarly brilliant in the playoffs (11-2,
1.82, .938), carrying a team that entered as a seventh seed to its
first finals in 24 years. But even more miraculous than some of
Hasek's saves is his career evolution. After eight years with his
hometown team, Pardubice, and one with Dukla Jihlava, Hasek came to
U.S. in 1990, signing with Chicago. The Blackhawks did not forecast
greatness. They had drafted him only in the 10th round (199th
overall) in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Hasek split time between the Blackhawks and the
minor leagues. Then Chicago coach Mike Keenan didn't think much of
him and, truth is, didn't need him. The Hawks' starter was Eddie
Belfour, the same Belfour whom Hasek will oppose this series.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Chicago dealt Hasek to Buffalo for one Stephane
Beauregard (who has played for six minor-league teams since). Hasek
was not immediately spectacular (11-10-4, 3.15) and was left
unprotected in the 1993 expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Anaheim nor Florida took him.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, everybody but the Sabres began to feel ill. Hasek
posted a 1.95 goals-against average in 1993-94, winning his first
of four Vezinas. The only player who almost stopped Hasek's ascent
was himself. In the 1997 playoffs, a sprained knee forced him to
miss seven games. But some doubted the injury, especially when
Hasek skated off the ice during Game 3 against Ottawa, went to the
locker room and didn't return even though he had not been required
to make a save that might've aggravated the injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres went on to win the series in seven games but were
waxed by Philadelphia in the next round. Soon after, coach Ted
Nolan popular with most of his players but not with Hasek was
fired. Hasek, who also had been suspended for three playoffs games
and fined $10,000 for grabbing a newspaper reporter took the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Hasek took the ice in Buffalo, he was booed. The
franchise centerpiece and league MVP, booed. But at midseason, he
stoned the world in Nagano, even blanking Canada in a shoot-out,
and all seemed to be forgiven. As he said, ``All of a sudden, I was
the goalie who won the gold medal for the Czech Republic in
people's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is recognized simply as the best. In the playoff opener
against Ottawa, the Sabres were outshot 41-15, but won 2-1. They
have supported their goalie better since. An aggravated groin
injury forced Hasek to miss the first two games of the Eastern
Conference finals. But criticism and doubts about Hasek's desire
was minimal this time.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff likened Hasek's play to ``the way
Jaromir Jagr is playing now, the way Wayne Gretkzy was in his
prime. They're guys who can dominate, win a game, turn a series.
That's Dom.''
</P>
<P>
   If he keeps winning, Buffalo will be sipping Dom.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
