<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-LANDING-COX     06-07 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-LANDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran seeking more landing slots
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AirTran is calling on the government to redistribute
landing ``slots'' at a few key airports, arguing that their control
by major carriers blocks the growth of low-fare competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless some immediate action is taken to allow new entrant
access at the high-density and hub airports, new entrants will be
forced out of entire sections of the country,'' AirTran said in a
letter to the U.S. Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The discount airline, Atlanta's second-largest carrier,
specifically wants the DOT to open slots for it at Washington's
Reagan National Airport, for service from its Atlanta hub.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran also wants more slots at New York's LaGuardia Airport,
where the DOT previously granted the carrier special landing
rights, so it can bolster its current schedule from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``If AirTran is going to continue to serve communities
throughout the East Coast and Midwest, it is essential that we be
immediately provided'' with the requested slots, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   Slots are used at those two airports, along with Chicago's
O'Hare and a handful of others, to control congestion by limiting
flights to a certain number. Atlanta's Hartsfield International is
not slot-controlled.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran argued that major carriers have locked up slots, which
are awarded by the Federal Aviation Administration to specific
airlines. The airlines do not have to surrender them unless they go
unused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large carriers and their partners control 97 percent of
all domestic jet slots at high-density airports and virtually all
commuter slots at these critical airports,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran also accuses major airlines of ``hiding'' slots by
having commuter partners use them if the parent carrier doesn't
have a need for them.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran President Robert Fornaro said fares from Atlanta to
Washington-Dulles Airport, which has no slot controls, are about 45
percent lower than to Reagan National. That disparity will remain
until slots to Reagan National are made available to smaller
carriers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter marks AirTran's second appeal for government help in
the past two weeks. On May 25, it asked the DOT and Justice
Department to investigate its allegations of predatory pricing by
Atlanta rival Delta Air Lines _ an accusation Delta strongly
denies.
</P>
<P>
   Delta had no immediate comment on the latest letter. A spokesman
for the trade group Air Transport Association also had no comment,
saying members' views on slot issues vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
