<HEADER>
A6443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-MAYOR-BUNKER-ART-     06-07 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-MAYOR-BUNKER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SAY MAYOR'S NEW `BUNKER' COULD BE A LIFESAVER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ridiculed only a year ago as an overpriced sky box
``bunker'' built to shield Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and his top aides
from physical and perhaps verbal abuse, the city's $13 million
emergency crisis center officially opened Monday with a blaze of
activity simulating a biological attack on New York.
</P>
<P>
   In a cavernous room with giant overhead television monitors and
digitized aerial photos of the city's entire subway, sewage and
water main systems, city officials stared at their computer
monitors and huddled in small groups, exchanging information and
sorting out rumor from fact about the hypothetical epidemic that
had gripped New York.
</P>
<P>
   The complex, which takes up 50,000 square feet on the 23rd floor
of one of the smaller buildings in the World Trade Center in lower
Manhattan, has been mocked by some City Council members and critics
of the Giuliani administration as just one more manifestation of
the mayor's preoccupation with order, and, perhaps, siege
mentality. But the complex won high praise from many of the federal
and state officials taking part in a drill to test the city's
response to a terrorist emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really state of the art _ the best I've seen,'' said
Col. Robert Fitton, chief of the Pentagon unit that provides
military support to civilian authorities in the event of
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to counter past criticism, Jerome Hauer, the city's chief
emergency manager, escorted a small group of reporters through the
center on Monday, showing off its newly installed computers and
information systems. ``This,'' Hauer declared, ``is not a bunker.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulletproof, the center features some of the most advanced
computer and telecommunications equipment available and is hardened
to withstand bombs, hurricanes, power failures and other crises. It
was completed on time and under its $16 million budget, with its
cost less than half that of a center being built in Hawaii and less
than a third that of a crisis center in earthquake-prone Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The New York command center is intended to coordinate the city's
response to emergencies ranging from blackouts and severe storms to
terrorist attacks involving conventional and unconventional
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Built to withstand winds of more than 160 mph, the center has
three generators to ensure continuous power in the event of a
blackout, 11,000 gallons of stored drinkable water for emergency
management workers, a 6,000-gallon ceiling-mounted fuel tank that
guarantees 72 hours of operation, and a secure communications
system. It can accommodate up to 94 people monitoring a citywide
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the city unveiled the center as it was staging a
drill with federal and state officials for a biological attack.
Several federal officials said they were impressed.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis center still has its critics. Councilwoman Kathryn
Freed, whose district houses the new center, reiterated concerns
about the prudence of the investment, given the city's vast needs.
She also challenged its location in a building not owned by the
city _ and charges $1.4 million a year in rent a year under its
20-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible amount of money to enhance somebody else's
property,'' Ms. Freed said. ``We had a state-of-the-art emergency
center in police headquarters, and I still don't understand why we
needed this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Some police officials apparently share her skepticism,
particularly since the Police Department already has it own command
and control center at its headquarters in lower Manhattan.
Emergency management officials noted that the department resented
the Office of Emergency Management's growing role in crisis
management and said police concerns almost scuttled the project at
one point.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a police spokeswoman, said the department would
maintain its own command center. Asked whether the police resented
giving up command of the city during certain crises, she replied:
``We not giving up anything. We have our own crisis center.''
</P>
<P>
   But a 1994 memo from the commanding officer of the police
operations division questioned the ability of police headquarters
to withstand an emergency. In the event of an earthquake,
hurricane, terrorist act or other crisis, the memo stated, ``One
Police Plaza would likely be unable to sustain operations due [to)
loss of power, water, communications or structural integrity.''
This, in turn, could have a ``devastating impact on our ability to
restore order.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the center's location in the World Trade Center, in
a building across the street from the site of the 1992 terrorist
bombing that killed six people, Hauer said that the site was chosen
after a study of some 50 locations. The complex now has tight
security and is close to the mayor's office, police and fire
departments, and headquarters of other key city officials, he said,
adding that in the event of an emergency, emergency personnel would
want to reach the center on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The command center occupies about half the space of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers had urged that the center not be built in a basement
or converted bomb shelter _ as Los Angeles has done _ because of
Manhattan's city's 100-year-old water mains. An earthquake or
bombing risked turning an underground facility into ``a $13 million
swimming pool,'' Hauer said.
</P>
<P>
   One of several elevators to the 23rd floor, he added, has its
own power supply to assure continued access during a blackout. He
called security at the facility excellent, as no truck is permitted
to enter the building complex without being searched. The 47-story
building, 7 World Trade Center, also rents space on the ninth and
10th floors to the Secret Service, another government agency that
values security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
