<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6445 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-ART-     06-07 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WILL PROPOSE DRUG COVERAGE FOR MEDICARE BENEFICIARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will soon propose revamping the
Medicare program to offer prescription drug coverage to all
beneficiaries, and he will contend that such coverage can actually
save money for the government by reducing the need for hospital
stays and nursing home care, administration officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the drug coverage could be offered for an
extra premium as low as $10 a month and, in any event, less than
$25, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The president intends to unveil his plan later this month as an
alternative to one proposed in March by a 17-member advisory
commission. His proposal will boost efforts by Democratic lawmakers
to cover prescription drugs, a change long sought by older
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that Clinton would not try to impose
federal controls on drug prices. Rather, they said, under his
proposal, the government would hire private companies to help buy
drugs and manage the new drug benefit. Such ``pharmacy benefit
managers'' could control costs by obtaining discounts from drug
manufacturers and drug stores, and by preventing overuse or misuse
of prescription drugs, the administration contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never do price controls,'' said a senior White House
official.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed drug benefit is the centerpiece of Clinton's plan
to modernize Medicare and shore up the finances of the program for
39 million people who are elderly or disabled. The Medicare trust
fund is expected to run out of money in 2015, assuming no changes
in current law.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats say they will include prescription drug benefits
as a major plank of their political platform next year. They look
forward to a fight over the issue with Republicans, who are also
eager to provide drug benefits but fear that the cost of such
coverage could explode.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Podesta, the White House chief of staff, who has taken
charge of efforts to draft the president's Medicare proposal, said
the drug benefit would be ``universal and affordable,'' would have
``a modest premium'' and would be ``better than anything you could
buy today in the open market.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries now pay a monthly premium of $45.50 for
coverage that does not include drugs. Administration officials said
the extra premium for drug coverage would be far less than what
many elderly people now pay for such coverage under private
insurance to fill the gaps in Medicare. Drug coverage under such
Medigap policies often exceeds $80 a month, the White House says.
</P>
<P>
   The president's plan is an alternative to the one devised by the
co-chairmen of the 17-member commission, Sen. John B. Breaux,
Democrat of Louisiana, and Rep. Bill Thomas, Republican of
California. Under the Breaux-Thomas plan, the government would
offer a fixed amount of money to each beneficiary to purchase a
public or private health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the panel finished work in March, Clinton said
its final proposal ``does not provide for an adequate, affordable
prescription drug benefit'' and could cause excessive increases in
premiums for people in the traditional Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Confidential White House documents, outlining Clinton's
proposal, assert that drug coverage can save money for Medicare, by
reducing admissions to hospitals and nursing homes, and the need
for home health care as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A $1 increase in pharmaceutical expenditure is associated with
a $3.65 reduction in hospital care expenditure,'' one document
says. Moreover, it says, effective treatment for Alzheimer's
disease, including drugs like tacrine, ``could keep 10 percent of
patients out of nursing homes, thus saving billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard S. Foster, chief actuary of the Medicare program, is
trying to estimate the cost of various options being considered by
the president. White House officials said they had sent Foster many
studies to support their contention that the proper use of drugs
could save money elsewhere in Medicare. But one official said it
was difficult to persuade Foster, because he was ``very, very
conservative'' in his estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Democratic members of Congress said Clinton had not
shared details of his proposal with them. ``We haven't heard
anything,'' said Rep. Pete Stark of California, the ranking
Democrat on the House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Health.
</P>
<P>
   Stark said he feared that the administration would cut a deal
with Republican leaders of the House and the Senate late this year,
and that the resulting bill would be ``dumped on our doorstep 48
hours before we have to vote on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Clinton's plan would also include
these elements:
</P>
<P>
   _ The government would encourage price competition among health
maintenance organizations, by requiring them to bid for the right
to enroll Medicare beneficiaries. HMOs strenuously oppose this
idea, because the original fee-for-service Medicare program would
not be included in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least 15 percent of the expected federal budget surplus
would be pumped into Medicare, to improve the program's financial
condition and perhaps to help pay for drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Federal officials would have broad new authority to sign
contracts with selected suppliers of goods and services who offer
the best price to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employers who now offer drug benefits to retirees would be
allowed to buy drug coverage from Medicare, presumably at a lower
price than they now pay.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Walter K. Moore, a vice president of Genentech, a biotechnology
company based in South San Francisco, said today, ``We're
encouraged when we hear that the president's plan won't include
explicit price controls.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacy benefit managers and HMOs typically establish lists of
preferred drugs, known as formularies, and recommend low-cost
generic versions of brand-name drugs. Sometimes they also require
doctors to get approval before prescribing certain drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said such restrictions were ``not cause for concern'' at
Genentech because the company had been able to prove the value of
its drugs to HMOs and pharmacy benefit managers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Moore said, Activase, a clot-dissolving drug made
by Genentech, is used in the treatment of heart attack and stroke.
``At $2,200 a dose,'' he said, ``it's expensive therapy. But it can
save tens of thousands of dollars in overall costs. Patients don't
need to stay in the hospital as long, and they don't need as much
rehabilitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drugs were among the benefits that would have been
guaranteed to all Americans under President Clinton's ill-fated
plan for universal health insurance coverage in 1993-94. Under that
plan, the government would have set payment limits for many drugs
and would have required drug makers to provide discounts, in the
form of rebates to the government. Drug companies mobilized a small
army of lobbyists against those ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, many Medicare beneficiaries have obtained coverage
for prescription drugs by purchasing private insurance or by
staying in health plans run by their former employers. But the
White House contends that such coverage is eroding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fewer employers are offering retiree health coverage, and
Medigap is increasingly scarce and expensive,'' the White House
says in a document defending its new proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 23 percent of Medicare beneficiaries are expected to have
private employer-based or Medigap insurance for drug coverage in
2000, according to the Medicare actuary _ down significantly from
1995,'' the White House says. The actuaries estimate that, by 2000,
only 17 percent of beneficiaries will have drug coverage from
former employers, while 6 percent will have Medigap policies
covering drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   More than six million Medicare beneficiaries are in HMOs, and
most have some type of drug coverage. But the White House says
these benefits ``are likely to be reduced or dropped in the
future,'' as health plans cope with budget cuts made by Congress in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Breaux's commission would have guaranteed drug coverage
for low-income beneficiaries. But the White House rejects that
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beneficiaries across the income spectrum lack drug coverage,''
says a White House document explaining the president's plan.
``About 16 million beneficiaries are projected to have no drug
coverage in 2000. Lack of drug coverage is not just a problem for
low-income beneficiaries; 40 percent of beneficiaries without drug
coverage have income above 200 percent of poverty (about $17,000
for a single person, $23,000 for a couple in 2000).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
