<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILK-GUIDELINES-BOS &LR;      06-07 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILK-GUIDELINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILK AS A FOOD REQUIREMENT IS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For generations, mothers have told children ``drink your milk''
and recently celebrities sporting milk mustaches have offered
similar advice in glossy ads, making the beverage seem as American
as, well, motherhood and apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   But now milk is at the center of a major food fight.
</P>
<P>
   As the federal government prepares for the first time in five
years to revise US dietary guidelines, which could affect what
Americans eat and what gets served to schoolchildren and the
elderly through government food programs, it is coming under
increasing pressure to downgrade milk as a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   A separate but just as feisty debate over milk is being waged
over the health claims made in the dairy industry's well-known
milk-mustache ads featuring celebrities endorsing the beverage for
its health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   How milk became the center of this controversy is a story of
politics, money, and race. On one side are some physicians and
health experts who see a cultural bias in the promotion of milk
because many non-whites are lactose intolerant and have trouble
digesting milk. They are up against the powerful interests of the
dairy industry and government officials who are determined to keep
milk near the top of the US Department of Agriculture's food
pyramid. The dietary guidelines now being revised serve as the
basis for the pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Calcium and dairy products are just some of the issues before a
special advisory committee that is helping to revise the US dietary
guidelines. Some industry groups want the committee, which will
meet later this month, to give its blessing to alcohol, citing
studies showing a health benefit from moderate alcohol consumption,
and other health groups want the guidelines to more strongly
emphasize a plant-based diet.
</P>
<P>
   While the government's periodic revision of dietary guidelines
has come under fire before, the arguments over milk have been among
the most contentious, with both sides lining up their celebrity
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a major campaign being planned to try to get adults
to drink three glasses of milk every day. That's what the milk
mustache campaign wants to do,'' said Dr. Walter C. Willett,
professor and chairman of the department of nutrition at the
Harvard School of Public Health, which has completed a study
showing no evidence to support claims that milk and other
calcium-rich foods significantly reduce osteoporosis-related bone
fractures. ``If we do that, we'll increase saturated fat
consumption in adults. That inevitably will increase heart attack
rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Willett and other health professionals argue that dairy products
should be listed as just one source of calcium and should not be
featured on the food pyramid as a separate category, the ``milk,
yogurt and cheese group,'' from which two to three servings a day
should be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   But dairy and government officials, as well as some physicians,
contend that milk and other dairy products still offer one of the
best ways for Americans to get the calcium needed for healthy
bones, and should remain a key component of the US diet. They note
that low-fat milk and milk products with reduced lactose (milk
sugar) are available. Studies showing the importance of dairy
products for bone health are cited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue really is that there is a calcium crisis in this
country,'' said Susan Ruland, a spokeswoman for the National Fluid
Milk Processors Promotion Board, a group created by the US
Department of Agriculture and financed by the dairy industry. It
spends $80 million a year on the milk-mustache ads. ``Dairy
products provide the most economical, most widely available and
easiest sources of daily calcium by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Kennedy, USDA deputy undersecretary for research,
education and economics, acknowledged the higher rate of lactose
intolerance among minorities and whites whose ancestors came from
the Mediterranean, but defended the food pyramid. It can only
``communicate to the majority of Americans. It doesn't communicate
to all Americans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics has no official position on
the current controversy, according to a review of its on-line
policy statements, although it strongly supports breastfeeding in
the first year of a baby's life and has supported a federal effort
to ensure that that children and adolescents get enough calcium.
</P>
<P>
   The group spearheading the make-milk-optional movement, the
Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine, has gotten letters
of support from Muhammad Ali, Alice Walker, US Representative Jesse
L. Jackson Jr. and former Surgeon General M. Joycelyn Elders, as
well as from groups like the NAACP, the Association of Asian
Pacific Community Health Organizations and the National Hispanic
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The letters cite the higher proportion of minorities who are
lactose intolerant: about 90 percent of Asians, 70 percent of
blacks and Native Americans, and 50 percent of Hispanics, according
to a review of the literature by the Physicians Committee. It says
about 15 percent of all whites are lactose intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   Most children of all races have the enzyme to digest milk, but
many minority children lose that ability by their teens or early
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The letters also support the committee's recommendation that the
dietary guidelines encourage a plant-based diet to reduce such
chronic conditions as heart disease and diabetes, since they
disproportionately affect minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the biggest problem we have right now? We are being
bankrupted by our ill health,'' said Dr. Neal D. Barnard, president
of the Physicians Committee. The commitee, a private, nonprofit
group based in Washington, D.C., advocates for disease prevention
and favors a more plant-based diet. ``If we have dietary guidelines
that promote ill health, which disproportionately affect
minorities, it should be our priority to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of a change in the guidelines and food pyramid point
to dark, leafy green vegetables such as bok choy and collard
greens, and fortified juice, as excellent sources of calcium. And
they cite other nations whose diets are low in dairy and meat yet
whose rates of osteoporosis fractures are lower than in the United
States. They acknowledge, though, that other factors, such as
exercise levels, may play a role.
</P>
<P>
   At the Physicians Committee's request, the Congressional Black
Caucus last Friday sent a letter to President Clinton, calling for
more racially sensitive dietary guidelines. Clinton has led a
campaign recently to reduce racial disparities in health
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The committee filed a complaint in April with the Federal Trade
Commission over some of the dairy industry's celebrity-studded milk
ads, alleging they violate federal guidelines for health claims.
</P>
<P>
   The dairy industry's Ruland defended the ads, saying they have
been reviewed by the USDA and lawyers specializing in FTC matters.
She said the Physicians Committee has a hidden purpose. ``They will
purport to be speaking out in the interests of nutrition, when in
fact, they have an animal activist agenda. That's quite
irresponsible for public health.'' The committee is ``anti-meat,
anti-dairy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Milton Mills, a member of the Physicians Committee, says his
group is not trying to impose a vegetarian agenda on the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very clearly, a number of persons of color are out there
suffering needlessly, spending all sorts of money on medication
they don't need,'' said Mills, who is black and lactose intolerant.
He said he has diagnosed lactose intolerance in many of his
minority patients who thought they had irritable bowel syndrome,
spastic colon, or some other chronic lower abdominal disorder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
