<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-420&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS SHELL BORDER TOWN, REKINDLING KOSOVAR FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Locator map  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAZINCE, Macedonia _ One shell exploded in a family's living
room, blasting a hole through the ceiling, embedding shrapnel in
the carpet and freezing the decorative clock hanging from the wall
at 2:58 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Another shell blew out the windows at an elementary school. And
a third landed near a parked car, sending shrapnel through the
passenger's door and window.
</P>
<P>
   Emine Mustafi, 24, sleeping in the next room when the shell
exploded in the living room, said the unprovoked attack terrified
her. Fear of further shelling prompted village leaders to remove
all women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mustafe, still shaken, eagerly supported that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard so much shelling I thought all the village was
burning,'' she said. ``I don't know how we escaped.''
</P>
<P>
   The shells were part of what Macedonian officials said was a
volley of more than 30 fired into this border village on Sunday
night by Yugoslav forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was the most serious violence along the border since
NATO began bombing Yugoslavia in March.
</P>
<P>
   What motivated the attack, which was just after the talks
between NATO and Yugoslav generals had failed, was not clear. The
shelling might be a Serbian push to inflict as much damage and
create as much instability as possible inside and outside Kosovo
before Serbian forces withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces have repeatedly pursued rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army into Albania, and the shelling might have been an
attempt to intimidate them.
</P>
<P>
   Western and Macedonian officials said the rebels regularly
transported weapons and munitions from Macedonia to Kosovo. But the
rebels are careful to use the area only to transport supplies and
do not attack Serbian forces from Macedonia, as they have in
northern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian officials filed a formal protest with Yugoslavia on
Monday about the shelling, as well as the firing of more than 24
shells into two other border villages, Tanysevci and Malino, 30
miles east, early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the motives are for the shelling,'' Defense
Minister Nikola Kljusev of Macedonia said on Monday at a news
conference. ``It's not good that these things are happening at the
time when negotiations for peace are going on.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have asked the rebel guerrillas to refrain from
starting military actions from Macedonia, fearing that it could
destabilize the country, Western diplomats said. But NATO and the
Kosovar group deny that they are in contact or coordinate
activities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Refugees who arrived here last week said that rebel fighters had
recently retaken three Albanian villages around Kacanik in
southeastern Kosovo that had fallen to Serbian forces just before
the bombing began. Those accounts could not be verified.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees, Paula Ghedini, said some of the few hundred refugees who
had trickled into Macedonia recently, mostly over mountain passes,
had reported that Serbs were destroying buildings in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   But two Albanians living in Pristina contacted by telephone
reported no new destruction. They did say Serbian civilians were
looting more Albanian houses and businesses and shipping the goods
to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The differing explanations for the border attacks were
illustrated by a group of 261 men and four women who walked over a
mountain pass near Jazince into Macedonia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the exhausted and sunburned refugees, Ramadan
Niftarkolgeci, 42, said most of the group had endured a six-day
journey through the forest and over the mountains. The men were
separated from their wives and children by Serbian forces a month
ago but only managed to escape now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a Macedonian police official said the Macedonians believed
that the men were Kosovo Liberation Army fighters. When the men
were found crossing the border, a handful were armed or wearing
uniforms, the police said. Because the group surrendered
peacefully, no charges were brought, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The civilians of Jazince called for retaliatory bombing against
the Serbs and a greater NATO presence. On Monday afternoon, a grim
procession of men walked their wives and children out of the
picturesque village of 1,300. Among them were some of 300 refugees
from Kosovo who had been taken in by residents after having fled to
Macedonia. A refugee who is six months pregnant, Fikrije Burnike,
27, said she endured a 24-hour hike from Kosovo with her husband
and two children three weeks ago. But now it has found her here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I escaped from there and now I have to escape from here,''
Mrs. Burnike said as she walked out of Jazince. ``Nowhere are you
safe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
