A6453 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-CONTROL-2NDTAKE-N     06-07 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: as amendments.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That would help them avoid oratorical fireworks in the Judiciary
Committee, whose Republican members do not necessarily reflect the
majority in their party and whose Democratic members have a
penchant for sniping.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were the speaker,'' said Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., a
member of the committee, ``and I was trying to find a bigger tent,
the last thing I'd want to focus on is the Republicans in the
Judiciary Committee, in all their zeal, voting down gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides noted that taking gun-control measures directly
to the floor would also allow Republicans to cast votes on
individual measures _ some more acceptable to them than others _
rather than on a package predetermined by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, favors many new restrictions on firearms and has said
that he would put versions of the gun-control proposals that passed
the Senate into the juvenile crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican aides on the committee said that the House
gun-show measure would most likely contain softer language than the
Senate's.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats expressed fears that their leaders were getting
cold feet and ignoring appeals from the Clinton administration that
the House go further than the Senate, for example by adopting
measures to raise the age for handgun possession to 21 from 18.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Moran, D-Va., said that Democratic leaders were
haunted by the conviction that Democrats lost control of the House
in 1994 in large part because they had pushed gun control and
incurred the wrath of the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so close to getting back the majority,'' Moran noted,
``and they're afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nichols, a spokeswoman for Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the
minority leader, said Democratic leaders in the House simply felt
that they did not have enough votes to add measures to the Senate
gun-control package.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world,'' Ms. Nichols said, ``we'd like to do
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is complicated by the growing intensity of the
rifle association's efforts. In its recent letter to supporters
about events in Washington, NRA officials wrote, ``The air in this
town is so thick with deceit and dishonesty about this gun scheme,
only you can offset it with your action.''
</P>
<P>
   The scheme they were referring to was the gun-show measure
passed by the Senate, which was dissected and disparaged in three
pages of text and an accompanying fact sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ricker, executive director of the American Shooting
Sports Council, a trade group with a more conciliatory tone toward
gun control, said Monday that the NRA was trying to shut his group
down and ``silence us because we are not spouting the party line.''
</P>
<P>
   NRA officials said that was not true.
</P>
</TEXT>
