<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With Klesko out sick, slumping Williams back
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves keep trying to hand Gerald Williams a job.
He keeps handing it back.
</P>
<P>
   Williams took an 0-for-23 slump into Monday's game, back in the
starting lineup in left field while Ryan Klesko remained at home
with the flu. Just one year after hitting a career-high .305 in his
first Atlanta season, his average has dipped to .195.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was that low,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``I
tell you I never look at a lot of those things. I get surprised all
the time when I look up and a guy is hitting .300 and then he's
sitting over there on the bench hitting .150. But for me, he's
doing a lot better than his average indicates.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was hitting a solid .289 until he replaced Otis Nixon
as a full-time left fielder in mid-May and the resultant drop-off
has been dramatic. He wound up hitting just .194 for the month, and
though Cox would not make a formal commitment, Klesko's move from
first base back to left could last the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind of auditioning for playing every day and he hasn't
been selective,'' hitting coach Don Baylor said. ``He hasn't been
in a hitter's count in a while. When he's 2-0, 3-1, he's going to
get a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always 0-2 or 1-2 and he has to chase the split in the
dirt or the slider in the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams thrived while platooning last year, driving in a
career-high 46 runs and matching his career high in homers (10) in
just 266 at-bats. And he killed left-handed pitching with a .336
average.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he is managing just .230 versus LHP. His power has
disappeared. His ninth-inning homer May 20 that forced extra
innings against Chicago is his only home run in a 26-game period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would would have to think,'' Williams said, ``that sooner
or later, things would turn around to a positive end for me.
Right?''
</P>
<P>
   Sick call
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were without Klesko, after he came down with flu-like
symptoms (nausea and high-fever) Monday morning. He remained at his
Covington home, and his availability for tonight is uncertain.
Chipper Jones was also suffering body aches with a fever and was
only cleared to play by team physician David Watson 30 minutes
before gametime.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss missed his eighth game in 12 days with
soreness in his right thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' team batting average, which stood at .275 on May 3
when they were second in the league, has plummeted nearly 20
points. Atlanta entered play Monday hitting .257, 15th in the
league. . . . Jose Canseco played his first game in the field for
the Devil Rays, starting in left field. He played 47 games in the
outfield last season with Toronto, but all of them before July 29.
. . . One of the Braves team buses was involved in a rear-end
collision Sunday evening while the team was en route to Boston's
Logan Airport from Fenway Park. There were no serious injuries
reported, though the entire traveling party squeezed into the
second bus and continued to the airport with some standing in the
aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
