<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-INTERNET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY MAY BUY INFOSEEK, INVEST IN NEW FIRM TO BACK WEB COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ The Walt Disney Co. announced Monday a major
push to bulk up its Internet presence, disclosing it may buy all of
portal partner Infoseek and invest in a new firm to back Web
start-up companies.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank-based Disney also announced it may create a separate
stock to track its Internet assets _ a move that Wall Street
investors have been seeking for months. The new stock will enable
the entertainment giant to take advantage of the sizzling market
for Web stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Separating the Internet holdings will highlight them a give
Disney a currency to make future acquisitions,'' said Linda
Bannister, an analyst with Edward Jones. ``Clearly, the Internet
offers Disney a lot of opportunity to distribute the wealth of
content in a new format.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney and Sunnyvale-based Infoseek launched the Go Network
portal site in January to lure customers and advertisers through an
easy-to-find hub for entering the Internet. Analysts have said the
partnership makes sense as a way for Disney to maximize benefits
from its already popular Web sites such as Disney.com, ABCNEWS.com
and ESPN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Disney will likely have to pay a premium for the rest of
Infoseek since its year-old deal, under which it bought 43 percent
for $70 million plus $165 million in promotional support, precludes
Disney boosting its stake until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Disney made the announcements after the market closed. It did
not disclose the amount of its investment in the new company, which
will be called eCompanies and run by Sky Dayton, founder and
chairman of EarthLink, and Jake Winebaum, who is stepping down as
chairman of Disney's Internet operations.
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena-based EarthLink, which has 1.15 million customers, will
also make an undisclosed investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is only about 20 percent invented,'' Winebaum
said. ``We want eCompanies to play a role in the creation of a
small piece of the remaining 80 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton, who founded EarthLink in 1994, will continue as chairman
of EarthLink while veteran Disney executive Steve Wadsworth will be
promoted to the post of president of Buena Vista Internet Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
