A6458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN08-COX     06-07 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Molder's Open spot eases NCAA sting
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After the disaster that was Georgia Tech's NCAA
championship experience last week, Bryce Molder almost erased the
pain Monday at East Lake Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Even securing a spot in the U.S. Open at Pinehurst No. 2 next
week didn't wipe out the torture of finishing 28th among 30 teams
at the NCAA's and watching rival Georgia take the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's close, but nothing makes up for the team deal,'' said
Molder, 20, college golf's No. 1-ranked player. ``It just makes me
forget about it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Molder, who shot rounds of 66-73 (5-under 139) in the 36-hole
qualifier, earned his Pinehurst trip on the first hole of a playoff
for the last two spots, chipping to two feet for a par at East
Lake's 232-yard, par-3 18th. Victimized was Augusta, Ga.'s Charles
Howell of Oklahoma State, who missed a four-footer a moment before
Molder's putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge dream for me,'' said Molder. ``I probably won't
realize how big a deal it is until I get there.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 63 players competing Monday at East Lake, also making the
Open field were a pair of Nike Tour players _ Bob Heintz, 29, of
Palm Harbor, Fla., the medalist at 8-under-par 136 (65-71); and Tim
Loustalot, 34, of Scottsdale, Ariz. (68-70, 136) _ and North
Carolina State's Mark Slawter, 25, of Raleigh, N.C. (71-68, 139),
the 1994 North-South Amateur champion at Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Nelson, 51, the 1983 U.S. Open champion, shot a 4-under
140 (69-71) and finished a shot out of the playoff. Billy Andrade,
an East Lake member and former North-South Amateur champion at
Pinehurst No. 2, slipped to a par 72 after an opening 69 and missed
by two shots.
</P>
<P>
   Irked about having to qualify as a former champion, Nelson
declared that it would be his last attempt. He only tried this year
because of a fondness for Pinehurst, which served as a sectional
qualifying site when he got his PGA Tour card in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heat and humidity, Nelson, wearing long pants
because he forgot that pros and amateurs were allowed to wear
shorts, almost pulled it off. His second-round 71, however,
included four bogeys and a double-bogey. After a missed, downhill
four-footer for birdie at the par-5 15th, he bogeyed 16 after
catching the lip of a fairway bunker on his second shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played well enough to get in,'' Nelson said. ``Just a few
too many hiccups. I was excited about coming to play, just to prove
to myself that I could still walk 36 holes in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Medalist Heintz had the most pressing reason to get out of town
after his performance. A Yale man, he hurried back to Florida,
where his wife, Nancy, was going into labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't seem too excited (about the Open), it's because I'm
pretty dead right now,'' said Heintz. ``I'm having a son in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
