<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY-CUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS TO TACKLE THE UNDERDOG SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Yee haw.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup finals finally get under way Tuesday night with
the Dallas Stars, who are wrapping up their sixth season in the
Lone Star State, taking on the underdog Buffalo Sabres in the
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   You know it's late in the hockey year when the temperature in
Dallas (a seasonable 90-ish) is fairly close to that in Buffalo
(80-ish).
</P>
<P>
   This marks the first trip to the finals for the relocated Stars,
who last vied for the Cup under the name of the Minnesota North
Stars back in 1991. Quick, who was the goalie who led the Stars
that far? Good old Jon Casey, the ex-Bruin whose team was rubbed
out by the Penguins that year.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Sabres made it this far was 1975, when Floyd
Smith was coach and Buffalo was eliminated in six games by the
Philadelphia Flyers. Don't talk to the Sabres about history,
though. Top center Michael Peca was all of 1 year old when that
series was played. Miroslav Satan was even younger, a mere 7
months. Goalie Dominik Hasek was a little more advanced in age (at
10) but in the Czech Republic, the Stanley Cup was not yet a dream
for the youth of his country.
</P>
<P>
   So, what do we have here? We have the NHL's best regular-season
team (the Stars) against the world's greatest goalie, who lacks
only the very trophy he's fighting for now on an otherwise
impressive resume. Recent history has favored the Western
Conference, with Detroit twice and Colorado once sweeping the
finals the last three years. The year before that, the
lockout-shortened campaign of 1994-95, it was the New Jersey Devils
sweeping the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the first three series, it's patently unfair to talk
about Hasek as being the entire Sabres team. He's a crucial cog,
yes, and deserves the respect of a back-to-back Vezina Trophy and
Hart Trophy winner, but you could argue that he's no more crucial
to his team than Ed Belfour is to Dallas. Both have played well to
make it this far, but Hasek hasn't had to steal a game yet because
his teammates haven't forced him to.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to get caught up in the
Dallas-has-a-million-stars-while-Buffalo-doesn't mantra. But that
would be a little misleading. Take a look at the regular-season
statistics and you'll find that both clubs have the same number of
players with more than 40 points (seven). Yet the Stars have one
player, Mike Modano with 81 points, who far surpasses any teammate
(Brett Hull is next with 58). They have no player with 40 goals,
but the Sabres have one in Satan.
</P>
<P>
   An X-factor here, as it was earlier in the playoffs, is the
health of Hasek, who has been bothered by a groin strain since Feb.
17. Coach Lindy Ruff said Hasek will play Tuesday night, the first
game for the Sabres since May 31 (they had a similarly long layoff
after cruising past the Ottawa Senators in Round 1 and were rusty
in their second-round opener against the Bruins).
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the teams are pretty even, especially in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a team that's built on a really sound foundation of
team play,'' said Stars coach Ken Hitchcock. ``I think the teams
have a lot of similarities. I think, first, we really both learned
a lot from losing last year. We learned a lot losing to Detroit and
I'm sure if you ask Buffalo, they learned a lot losing to
Washington (in the conference finals).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're built on the `who's the new hero?' philosophy. In other
words, we don't rely on one individual player to score for us. Both
teams diversify it through our lineups. Both teams have structured
defense groupings based on chemistry. I think the biggest
similarity when we watch their team play is they play very strong
as a group of five.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have Hull, Joe Nieuwendyk (who has been their best
player), Belfour, Modano and a great supporting cast. The Sabres
have a world-class goalie, the best two-way center in the game in
Peca, a sensational defensive corps (starting with Alexei Zhitnik
and Jason Woolley), and a coach who deserves more credit than he's
been given.
</P>
<P>
   The finals are here, folks, and for the first time in five
years, you can forget about a sweep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
