<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING ASSERTS OFFICE RAID BY FBI WAS UNNECESSARY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three days after the FBI raided his Deerfield Beach, Fla.,
offices searching for information that will link him to a
racketeering investigation being conducted by the U.S. attorney's
office in Newark, N.J., the promoter Don King said that he would
have gladly given authorities any information they wanted if they
had subpoenaed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're out to humiliate and embarrass me,'' King said Monday
by telephone from his home in Deerfield Beach. ``They want to break
my spirits. They want me crying and begging and breaking down. But
it's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give up my fundamental and organic right to
the presumption of innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   King was meeting with HBO executives in New York City when the
raid occurred. He was negotiating with them to remove a clause from
the contract for the rematch of Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis
that calls for King to be removed as the lead promoter if he is
indicted for any wrongdoing associated with the first
Holyfield-Lewis bout on March 13. That fight ended in a
controversial draw.
</P>
<P>
   King said he believes the government's latest pursuit of him
stems from his past and present dealings with HBO. Seth Abraham,
president of Time Warner Sports, was traveling Monday afternoon and
could not be reached for comment. Lou DiBella, the senior vice
president for programming at HBO/TVKO would not comment on what
King had to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an agenda,'' King said. ``This has nothing to do with the
exercise of due process. They're pursuing this agenda with all due
haste. But I refuse to give up on America. I will fight, not only
for my rights, but for the rights of all Americans. I have nothing
to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   King added: ``They have manipulated political and government
institutes of power against me, and now the government is putting
blanket warrants on me hoping they can come up with something. But
I haven't done anything.''
</P>
<P>
   King said workers at his office told him that 74 FBI agents
entered his offices at 8 a.m. last Friday with warrants from the
Federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, known
as RICO. The agents told everyone to remain in certain parts of the
building while they put files and computers in boxes and loaded
them on trucks. King said they were at his offices for 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Holyfield-Lewis rematch in November is in serious
jeopardy because King is refusing to sign the contract with the
indictment clause in it. In lieu of signing the contract, King has
offered HBO $2 million for the United States pay-per-view rights to
the bout. The network has not responded to his offer but is
unlikely to give up the rights to a potentially lucrative bout.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sticking points that was ironed out for the first
bout could be back in a big way this time around, namely that HBO
has exclusive broadcast rights to Lewis' bouts. Holyfield is a
network free agent. &QL; 
Ayala to Fight in July
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ayala Jr., who was released from Bayside State Prison in
Leesburg, N.J., two months ago after serving 16 years on a rape
conviction, will return to the ring on July 31, said his father,
Tony Ayala Sr.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Ayala, who is acting as his son's trainer and manager,
said that they have not picked an opponent and are not sure who
will broadcast the bout, but that it will be held in San Antonio,
Ayala's hometown. Ayala, who plans to fight as a junior
middleweight (154 pounds), returned to training at his father's gym
in San Antonio two weeks ago. Forty seconds into his first session,
he knocked down his sparring partner. Ayala, 37, was the No.
1-ranked junior-middleweight contender when he went to prison in
1981. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
