<SLUG> BC-REED-ELSEVIER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lexis-Nexis parent expects profits dip in '99
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Reed Elsevier plc, the parent company of
Lexis-Nexis, said Monday it expects lower profits in 1999 because
of weak advertising trends in one segment and fierce competition in
the online legal and business information market.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Reed Elsevier announced profits were flat in 1998 and
1999 didn't look much better. The Anglo-Dutch publisher on Monday
told institutional investors in New York that 1999 revenues would
likely fall below 1998 numbers but would not say how much lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the first half of the year, we are just warning the
market,'' said Paul Richardson, Reed Elsevier Inc. vice president
of finance. A mid-year fiscal report is expected Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said Reed Elsevier has seen weak advertising revenues
in Cahners, which produces a variety of trade publications, and
intense competition for Lexis-Nexis in the online information
business.
</P>
<P>
   Lexis-Nexis, which has 7,800 employees worldwide, including
2,400 in Miami Twp., provides legal information and citations to
lawyers and online business and news information to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Lexis' chief rival, Thomson Corp.'s Westlaw, has launched an
intense marketing campaign while Lexis-Nexis has been busy
developing products for late 1999 and absorbing two purchases:
Matthew Bender &AMP; Co. and Shepard's Co., Richardson said. Nexis,
which provides news and business information, faces increasing
competition from Internet sources.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Elsevier bought Lexis-Nexis from Mead Corp. in 1994 for
$1.5 billion and has since bought Matthew Bender &AMP; Co., the
country's leading publisher of analytical legal information, and
Shepard's Co., the leading U.S. legal citation publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Lexis-Nexis is an important component of Reed Elsevier's
portfolio. Last year, Lexis-Nexis' $1.23 billion in sales made up
nearly 24 percent of Reed Elsevier's $5.2 billion in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Elsevier's announcement on Monday led analysts to downgrade
the stock. Reed International's stock price fell 6.9 percent while
Elsevier's price dipped 3.6 percent. Reed (NYSE:RUK) closed at 28,
down 2, while Elsevier (NYSE:ENL) closed at 24, down 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reed Elsevier has been searching for a new chief
executive for nearly a year. Reed Elsevier is co-owned by Reed
International plc in London and Elsevier NV in Amsterdam. Last
August, the two companies announced they would ditch a co-chairman
management system and have been searching for a chief executive
since then. The top candidate backed out this year and two board
members resigned in protest over the search process. Richardson
said the search committee is still working off the short list of
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson declined comment on how the fiscal picture might
affect the search or when a new chief executive may be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
