<SLUG> BC-EXP-KOSOVO-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA HOLDS BACK ON ENDORSING RESOLUTION TO END KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ After eight hours of negotiations, Russia
balked on Monday at final approval of a resolution to be sent to
the Security Council to lay out the future of Kosovo and the role
of 50,000 NATO peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The draft resolution is being worked out by foreign ministers of
the leading industrial countries and Russia. Participants said much
progress had been made Monday, and perhaps 90 percent of the work
on the resolution has been agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   But problems about the role of NATO in the peacekeeping force
remain.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators, especially Russia and the Europeans, want the
Security Council to approve such a resolution detailing the sketchy
document that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to last
week, which called for a U.N. role. The resolution is also meant to
give authority to the peacekeeping force and the civil
administration that is planned for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said he needed to
have further consultations with Moscow. The Russians, through their
emissary Viktor Chermonyrdin, helped secure the agreement last
week. But if they change their mind and block a NATO dominated
force, under U.N. authority, that would be a setback to the peace
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Military to military talks in Macedonia to work out withdrawal
schedules for Yugoslav and Serbian troops from Kosovo were
downgraded to low level officials Monday, after the Yugoslavs made
what the State Department called unacceptable proposals to keep
15,000 soldiers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO held back on carrying out threats to intensify its
bombing of Yugoslavia if Belgrade did not promptly accept allied
terms on Kosovo. Allied officials said they hoped that the
restraint would help persuade Russia to back a United Nations
Security Council resolution on ending the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But there was NATO bombing in Kosovo near the Albanian border,
and at night, explosions and anti-aircraft fire were heard once
again in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials here said they were satisfied that the
draft resolution made clear that the peacekeeping force of 50,000
will have a unified NATO command and control structure. The word
NATO may not be spelled out in the resolution, an official said,
but one section of the draft says that the operation will be
``performed by member states and relevant international
organizations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
