<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6472 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-ART-     06-07 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: now pay. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter K. Moore, a vice president of Genentech, a biotechnology
company based in South San Francisco, said today, ``We're
encouraged when we hear that the president's plan won't include
explicit price controls.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacy benefit managers and HMOs typically establish lists of
preferred drugs, known as formularies, and recommend low-cost
generic versions of brand-name drugs. Sometimes they also require
doctors to get approval before prescribing certain drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said such restrictions were ``not cause for concern'' at
Genentech because the company had been able to prove the value of
its drugs to HMOs and pharmacy benefit managers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Moore said, Activase, a clot-dissolving drug made
by Genentech, is used in the treatment of heart attack and stroke.
``At $2,200 a dose,'' he said, ``it's expensive therapy. But it can
save tens of thousands of dollars in overall costs. Patients don't
need to stay in the hospital as long, and they don't need as much
rehabilitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drugs were among the benefits that would have been
guaranteed to all Americans under President Clinton's ill-fated
plan for universal health insurance coverage in 1993-94. Under that
plan, the government would have set payment limits for many drugs
and would have required drug makers to provide discounts, in the
form of rebates to the government. Drug companies mobilized a small
army of lobbyists against those ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, many Medicare beneficiaries have obtained coverage
for prescription drugs by purchasing private insurance or by
staying in health plans run by their former employers. But the
White House contends that such coverage is eroding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fewer employers are offering retiree health coverage, and
Medigap is increasingly scarce and expensive,'' the White House
says in a document defending its new proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 23 percent of Medicare beneficiaries are expected to have
private employer-based or Medigap insurance for drug coverage in
2000, according to the Medicare actuary _ down significantly from
1995,'' the White House says. The actuaries estimate that, by 2000,
only 17 percent of beneficiaries will have drug coverage from
former employers, while 6 percent will have Medigap policies
covering drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   More than six million Medicare beneficiaries are in HMOs, and
most have some type of drug coverage. But the White House says
these benefits ``are likely to be reduced or dropped in the
future,'' as health plans cope with budget cuts made by Congress in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Breaux's commission would have guaranteed drug coverage
for low-income beneficiaries. But the White House rejects that
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beneficiaries across the income spectrum lack drug coverage,''
says a White House document explaining the president's plan.
``About 16 million beneficiaries are projected to have no drug
coverage in 2000. Lack of drug coverage is not just a problem for
low-income beneficiaries; 40 percent of beneficiaries without drug
coverage have income above 200 percent of poverty (about $17,000
for a single person, $23,000 for a couple in 2000).''
</P>
</TEXT>
