<HEADER>
A6479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOT-WEATHER-ART-780&AMP;A     06-07 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-WEATHER-ART-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY THE WEATHER MAP GOT TURNED UPSIDE DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Maine, D.C., Vt., Texas, Conn., La.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unseasonably miserable front of hot and humid weather
enveloped the Northeast and Atlantic seaboard Monday, establishing
single-day record high temperatures from the nation's capital to
Newark, N.J., to Portland, Maine, making the region seem about as
pleasant as a sponge bath inside a baking oven.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to be worse on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For one of those bizarre days that help explain why people talk
so incessantly about the weather, the meteorological world was
turned upside down: It was hotter in Portland (95 degrees), Boston
(97 degrees), and Burlington, Vt. (94 degrees) _ all records _ than
in Houston, which was 88. The swelter in Hartford (a record 98)
made New Orleans (89) seem almost pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers had to settle for a boiling wet sock of a day that
hit 94 degrees but failed to break any records (96 degrees, 1925).
The average high for Monday in New York's Central Park is 78
degrees, but the heat index, that mysterious formula of heat and
humidity that always equals misery, registered 100. Outside the
city, the heat index was 105 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers steamed on sidewalks outside air-conditioned office
buildings. Nearly 172,000 people flocked to city beaches Monday,
according to the Parks Department, compared with only 20,000 last
Tuesday. Mothers at a playground in Brooklyn jumped with their
toddlers beneath the sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so unbearably hot,'' said Victoria Gonzalez, explaining
why she stood beneath the sprinklers, fully clothed, with her
year-old daughter, Gianna.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sort of day that only a weather junkie could love:
Joseph Petta, a spokesman for Con Edison, the utility serving 3
million customers in New York City and Westchester County, N.Y.,
said the company registered the third highest demand for
electricity in its history. He estimated that the 10,912 megawatt
demand at 5 p.m. was the equivalent of 10.9 million window
air-conditioning units being turned on at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island Power Authority also hit peak demand late in the
afternoon, though 1,400 unlucky customers were without electricity
for several hours because of minor mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   The high temperatures began as far south as Washington, which
registered 98 degrees to shatter its 100-year record of 97, and in
Baltimore, which hit a record of 96. The regional high mark of the
day came in Newark, which touched 99 degrees, another record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually going to be pretty hot again, if not hotter,''
said Jeff Warner, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University,
delivering the unwelcome forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said a strong high pressure system to the south has
brought the region weather patterns more like July or August than
early June. But he also said the siege should be short, with
temperatures in New York likely to drop quickly into the 70s by
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout New York City on Monday, the soggy heat sat heavily
atop the city. The police reported an unusually slow day, perhaps
because criminals did not have the energy or will to go outside.
Street vendors thrived or suffered depending on their goods. At his
newsstand at 110th Street and Broadway on the Upper West Side,
Pervaiz Burki said he sold his entire supply of bottled water and
three dozen sodas within two hours. But if the heat helped
business, it made his life miserable inside the stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a fan but it's still hot,'' said Burki, a native of
Pakistan, as he shook sweat from his shirt. ``I step outside for
five minutes, fix the papers and back in.''
</P>
<P>
   On Montague Street in Brooklyn Heights, vendor Mike Hill had
slashed prices of the ties on his outdoor table from $2 to $1, but
his customers were inside, ordering lunch by delivery instead of
walking outside. With a bank sign reading a temperature of 94
degrees behind him, Hill announced that business would soon end for
the day. ``I'm going to head to the beach, for real,'' he said.
``I'm outta here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, Ana Ally, 6, a kindergarten student at Bank Street
School for Children, waited in line with her mother, Biliana Ally,
for Italian ices. She did not mind the heat one bit. ``I'm hot, so
my mother's getting me ices,'' Ana said. ``I know it's 100 degrees
in the desert, and I hope it gets to be 100 degrees today. Then I
can eat more ices.''
</P>
<P>
   Allister O'Brien, 33, a graphic designer from Dublin, Ireland,
was not so cheery. ``I was out scouting business opportunities, but
it's disgusting,'' he said. ``I almost melted. I'm going back into
my air-conditioned room. In Dublin, it's pouring rain and 45
degrees. It always is. That's what I'm used to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is always someone, of course, who scoffs at weather, hot
or cold, which might explain Edwin Vega, 40. In the middle of the
day, Vega stood on Erie Basin in Brooklyn fishing for striped bass.
There was no shade, not much wind, no trees, nothing. He wore blue
jeans and tinted sunglasses and stood on the concrete and did not
sweat, not a single bead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually cool out here,'' he announced coolly as the bell
jangled at the end of his pole, announcing a strike that he would
miss. He said he didn't mind standing outside for several hours
because his alternative was staying home and refereeing his five
children and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty feet away, Jack Osorio, 33, was also fishing, but from
the inside of his purple Chevrolet Lumina. ``When it's hot like
that, when it's in the 100s, the best thing to do is to be in the
car with the air conditioning on and watch the pole move,'' Osorio
said. When he sees the pole twitch, he jumps out to grab it.
</P>
<P>
   Osorio then looked at Vega and shook his head. ``See, I'm
sweating,'' he said. ``He's got the cool spirit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
