<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMEN KILL POPULAR TELEVISION HOST IN AMBUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In a gangland-style ambush outside a major
broadcast studio, gunmen fired automatic rifles and killed a
popular television host and a bystander on Monday. A reporter and
other bystanders were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Both major television networks reacted with live nationwide
broadcasts for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   The attack drew new expressions of outrage about violent crime
that many Mexicans say is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Francisco Stanley, was host of a morning variety
show on TV Azteca, his latest post in a lengthy career. City
officials said he was 57. His colleagues suggested in their live
coverage that the attack might have been a frustrated kidnapping
attempt, but offered no evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist who was injured in the attack is Jorge Gil,
another broadcast figure on TV Azteca. The ambush occurred an hour
or so after Stanley's show, as he and Gil drove out of a parking
lot of a taco restaurant alongside the studio, where they had eaten
a late-morning snack. A parking attendant, Juan Manuel de Jesus
Nunez, also died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new example of the tremendous insecurity we all
suffer in this city,'' Police Superintendent Alejandro Gertz Manero
of Mexico City said in a broadcast interview. ``It's a reality we
all have to confront. I feel the pain more than anybody because I
live this crisis every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The police were reported to have found 26 bullets around
Stanley's black minivan. The two networks broadcast repeated images
showing the van windows, shattered by gunfire, with mobs of
bystanders and reporters around the chaotic scene.
</P>
<P>
   Recent opinion polls show many Mexicans rank violent crime as
their biggest worry, even ahead of the economic fears that have
been the public's No. 1 concern since a peso devaluaion in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
