<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-WHITMAN-NYT &LR;      06-07 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATES FORCING WHITMAN TO RECONSIDER HER MODERATE POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ It would seem easy to predict how Gov. Christie
Whitman, one of the nation's most prominent Republican moderates,
would deal with a string of conservative proposals that may be
headed her way in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Require parental consent for a teen-ager to get a tattoo or have
an ear pierced? Surely Whitman would not support it.
</P>
<P>
   Require that public schools begin each day by reciting a line
from the Declaration of Independence about life, liberty and the
pursuit of happiness? Hardly a Whitman kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Ban same-sex marriages? Unthinkable for a politician with a
strong record defending the rights of gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   But as Whitman prepares for the next step in her political
career, a race next year for an open U.S. Senate seat, New Jersey
conservatives are making it abundantly clear to her that she will
have to yield ground on those very issues and others if she hopes
to hold on to their crucial _ but increasingly shaky _ support.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman won her two races for governor by less than 1 percent of
the vote, making conservative support critical, especially because
the Senate race is in a presidential election year, when many
traditionally Democratic urban voters are likely to go to the
polls. So the governor, whose standing among conservatives has
weakened over the years largely because of her moderate views on
social issues, needs every vote she can get.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for the first time in her political life, the
governor gave a nod of approval to legislation that would require
parental notification before an unmarried girl under 18 could have
a legal abortion. It was the first of a number of tough choices
that lay ahead for Whitman as Republicans in the Assembly,
concerned about preserving their majority in elections this fall,
are openly courting conservative voters for their support.
</P>
<P>
   Committees have already approved and sent to the full Assembly
legislation requiring that abstinence be taught as the only
completely reliable means of avoiding pregnancy and sexually
transmitted diseases. The same for a measure requiring parental
consent for tattoos and body piercing of minors, and the proposal
to mandate that elementary and secondary school principals and
teachers begin each school day by reciting an excerpt from the
Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   The excerpt in question includes the phrase ``that all men are
created equal, that they are endowed by their creator with certain
unalienable rights, that among these are life, liberty and the
pursuit of happiness.'' Some Democratic critics contend that the
measure is really a subtle attempt to further the anti-abortion
argument: they note that among the unalienable rights is ``life,''
and opponents of abortion describe themselves as ``pro-life.''
Supporters of the bill scoff at that assertion.
</P>
<P>
   Another bill _ the one that would prohibit same-sex marriages in
New Jersey _has been introduced, and its backers are pushing for it
to be considered in the current legislative session, which ends in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Even if some or all of the measures win approval in the
Assembly, their approval is less certain in the more moderate
Senate. But many conservative lawmakers in the Assembly want to go
on record about these social issues before the November elections,
and they want Whitman to take public positions as well.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who hold a 48-to-32 majority in the Assembly, said
that the spate of legislation is intended to draw a clear
distinction between them and Democrats before the elections. But
the maneuvering and pressure to speak out present a quandary for
Whitman, who despite her conservative credentials on education,
crime and fiscal policies has consistently embraced moderate
positions on abortion and on gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been conservative on many, many issues,'' Assembly
Speaker Jack Collins said. ``But what it usually comes down to is,
she is pro-choice and so the media and the people don't view her as
a conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   In her two races for governor, Whitman won each time with 49
percent of the vote _ with conservatives forming the base of her
support and independents and crossover Democrats giving her the
victory edge. Registered Democrats outnumber registered Republicans
25.8 percent to 19.5 percent in New Jersey. But independent voters,
with about 55 percent, top both of the major parties combined,
making it risky for a candidate for statewide office to swing too
wide in either political direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony for Whitman is that in a state with a minority of
Republican voters she must appeal to moderates and independents,
but Republicans still have to count on the conservative vote to
win,'' said David P. Rebovich, a political science professor at
Rider University. ``For a governor who has won her last two races
by 30,000 votes, it doesn't take too many conservatives to stay
home or to jump ship to sink her political future.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's gubernatorial victories were in 1993 and 1997, when
the turnout in the traditionally Democratic-voting urban areas was
at best moderate, and conservatives, despite some defections, stood
behind her. But she has never run for office in a presidential
election year when the turnout is usually stronger across the
board, especially in urban areas, which are Democratic strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   That has made the support from the right wing of her party all
the more imperative for Whitman, and conservatives have moved
swiftly to demand some payments in advance for that support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every piece of legislation has political consequences, whether
you are dealing with kid care or open space,'' said John Tomicki,
the executive director of the League of American Families, a
conservative advocacy group that led the fight for the parental
notification legislation and has helped lobby for the four other
conservative measures that the Assembly is expected to take up. ``I
would hope that Governor Whitman, who has at times called herself a
Rockefeller Republican, has seen that the public really sides with
a more conservative agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Salmore, a Republican political consultant and a political
science professor emeritus at Rutgers University, said that Whitman
has not done the kind of fence-building that can insure her loyalty
from social conservatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLIED-HONEYWELL-MARK     06-07 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLIED-HONEYWELL-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A MERGER MADE IN HEAVEN AND APPLAUDED ON WALL
STREET 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(ms) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now here's a deal that Wall Street really seems to
like.
</P>
<P>
   If past mergers were any indication, investors would have taken
their Honeywell Inc. profits on Monday, after the company and
Allied Signal Inc. announced their deal and spelled out the terms.
And if past patterns held, Allied's share price would have, at
best, not moved at all.
</P>
<P>
   After all, investors had already followed the common practice,
once word leaked out last Friday that Allied, the big diversified
manufacturer, would join forces with Honeywell, a maker of
electronic controls that is half its size.
</P>
<P>
   On the assumption that Allied would be the acquirer and would
take a financial hit, investors bid Honeywell's stock up in late
trading on Friday, and pushed Allied's shares down $2.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently, someone rewrote the textbook of conventional
wisdom over the weekend. By the time the market closed Monday,
investors had bid up Honeywell stock an additional $7, to $112. And
Allied was the biggest percentage gainer among stocks in the Dow
Jones industrial average, up $4.4375, to $62.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Based on those numbers, the deal, structured as a tax-free swap
of 1.875 shares of Allied stock for each share of Honeywell, is
valued at $14.8 billion _ $2 billion more than when the market
closed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So why the break with usual investment practice?
</P>
<P>
   Talks with analysts and investors found a sense of relief at the
financial terms and immediate financial prospects; a firm belief
that the combined company really would be better than the sum of
its parts, and a vote of confidence in Michael R. Bonsignore, the
Honeywell chief who will run the company when Lawrence A. Bossidy,
Allied's chief executive, retires next April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got so many things going for it,'' said Michael Holton,
an investment analyst at T. Rowe Price Associates, the
Baltimore-based mutual fund company, which has Honeywell and Allied
stock in its portfolios. ``It's a friendly deal; that's accretive
to earnings. It answers the Bossidy succession question, which has
hung like a cloud over Allied's stock. And it's created a business
portfolio that is simply stronger than either company had on its
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Holton's view is not unique. After Bonsignore and Bossidy laid
out the numbers, and their plans, at a meeting for analysts and the
news media Monday morning, analysts spent the rest of the day
generating positive reports on the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street simply loved what it heard,'' said H. Giles
Knight, a principal of Allied Investment Advisers in Baltimore,
which also includes Honeywell shares in its portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the Street loved what it did not hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``People figured this would be a dilutive cash acquisition, that
Allied would take out its checkbook and overpay,'' said Nicholas P.
Heymann, an analyst at Prudential Securities. ``Instead, it's a
true strategic deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will probably close as early as September, and the two
companies would be integrated and acting as one entity, to be
called Honeywell International, a few months after that.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many mergers, in which the costs of completing the
deal and integrating the companies requires either a big write-off
against earnings or a drain on profit for several quarters, this
one is structured so that it will be beneficial to earnings per
share from Day 1. The company may take a charge in the fourth
quarter, to account for the inevitable expenses of terminating
4,500 people of a combined 125,000 employees. But Bonsignore said
that the cost savings and added revenue from the merger would kick
in so quickly that the effect will add 17 cents to earnings a share
in 2000, rising to 32 cents a share by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the two companies' businesses fit like jigsaw
puzzles, selling complementary products and sharing, rather than
competing for, many of the same customers. Honeywell is a leading
maker of industrial, aviation and electronic controls. Allied is a
leading supplier of aircraft engines and controls, braking systems
for planes and trucks, and specialty chemicals. Both companies are
seeking more revenue from services _ like designing energy systems
for factories, in Honeywell's case, or maintaining fleets of planes
in Allied's. And both have made significant progress in using the
Internet to buy and sell products.
</P>
<P>
   The synergy is particularly apparent in the aerospace industry,
which the merged company expects will account for $10.5 billion, or
40 percent, of its revenue. Honeywell is a leader in navigational
controls, while Allied is a leader in surveillance controls. By
combining their two technologies, the two companies can offer a
takeoff-to-landing control system for aviation that covers safety
systems inside the plane, in the air-traffic controller's tower, or
at any remote location where someone wants to know where a plane is
at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely going to be a powerhouse company in the
aerospace field,'' concluded Jon B. Kutler, president of
Quarterdeck Investment Partners, a Los Angeles investment banking
firm that specializes in aerospace industry deals.
</P>
<P>
   That presumed power, of course, raises the specter of antitrust
problems. But Bossidy and Bonsignore said that Boeing, which is a
major customer for both companies, is publicly supporting the deal.
``The Federal authorities are generally easier on deals that the
major customers don't see as anticompetitive,'' Kutler said.
</P>
<P>
   What may have also helped both companies' stock price Monday is
that investors got a much closer look at Bonsignore, who is not
nearly as well known as Bossidy. ``At that meeting, Mike took the
initiative on questions, really acted like someone who has the
right stuff, who's really chairman-designate material,'' Heymann of
Prudential said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore thinks that the meeting helped Honeywell's image,
too. The company's earnings and stock price have performed well in
the last three years, he noted, but too many people have still
thought of it as the lackluster maker of home thermostats and other
low-tech gadgetry that it was up through the mid-1990's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday's sharp rise in our stock was based on rumors that
Honeywell's shareholders would receive a premium,'' Bonsignore said
in an interview on Monday. ``But now, investors are finally
recognizing us as the knowledge-based, technology-driven company
that we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
