<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC VOWS STEPS TO PEACE, BUT ALLIES DOUBT IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
promised Monday to advance the lifeless Kosovo peace process, a
U.S. official said, but NATO leaders were doubtful and the alliance
began heavier bombardment of Serb positions.
</P>
<P>
   Russia played for a bigger part in the Balkans conflict, seeking
to guarantee a role for the United Nations, where the Kremlin is
one of five nations with veto power in the Security Council. State
Department spokesman James Rubin said President Martti Ahtisaari of
Finland, an emissary in the Kosovo peace deal agreed to last week
by Milosevic, talked with the Yugoslav leader Monday ``and told him
there was a need to move ahead with the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic said he intends to do so,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea, at alliance headquarters in Brussels
voiced the doubts of many alliance officials when he noted that
with Milosevic there must be agreement on principles and details
and, finally, ``full implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you know you have an agreement'' with Milosevic, Shea
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin spoke with reporters in Bonn, Germany, where Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright met with counterparts from six other
leading industrial nations and Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari, who informed the foreign ministers of his talk with
Milosevic, flew to Bonn to participate in the session rather than
flying to Beijing. He may go later to the Chinese capital to
attempt to sell the peace plan to President Jiang Zemin of China,
another nation that has been critical of the NATO air campaign and
also has a veto in the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin, speaking to Interfax
news agency, renewed his demand that NATO bombing ``immediately
cease.'' A Russian diplomat was quoted as saying Moscow will not
agree in the Security Council to a resolution authorizing an
international force for Kosovo until NATO calls off the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton spoke to Russia President Boris
Yeltsin for 10 minutes by telephone, but the critical issue of the
command structure for a NATO-led international force was not
discussed, said Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman. He also
said Yeltsin did not ask for a bombing pause. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``It was a very constructive call,'' Lockhart said, adding both
presidents ``affirmed that the implementation'' of the peace plan
``should form the basis for a peaceful settlement of conflict and
the suspension of NATO's air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said both presidents also agreed to instruct their
foreign ministers ``to move quickly to work out the details of that
agreement.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Clinton also spoke to British Prime Minister Tony Blair, his
closest ally in NATO. ``They are very much in agreement on our
basic points. The NATO air campaign will continue until we see the
beginnings of a verifiable withdrawal, until the agreement is
implemented,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers meeting near the old German capital sought
to hammer out final details on how the multinational force would be
structured, including a way to finesse Russia's refusal to allow
its troops in the contingent to function directly under a NATO
commander. The senior diplomats planned to seek an emergency
session of the Security Council in New York as soon as a proposed
resolution was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States believes U.N. approval is not required for the
multinational military contingent to follow departing Serb forces
into Kosovo, but there is division in NATO on the point, and Russia
appeared to be attempting to exacerbate the disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   Nations embroiled in the Kosovo crisis scrambled for new ground
Monday after the peace process collapsed when Yugoslav generals
refused to sign the NATO-mandated withdrawal agreement.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea contended at alliance headquarters in
Brussels that ``the talks have not broken off.'' But, at the same
time, he conceded that no formal talks were scheduled between Lt.
Gen. Michael Jackson, the Briton representing NATO in the
discussions, and ranking Yugoslav officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flap to his tent remains open,'' Shea said of Jackson's
willingness to resume discussions with sincere Yugoslav
representatives who ``are ready to talk business .... If the
Yugoslavs are having second thoughts, believe me, they know which
number to ring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this agreement,'' Shea said, but the final plan must
be ``totally consistent'' with NATO demands. The only contacts
between the two sides Monday were logistical details, such as
making certain telephone lines were working.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO might allow the Yugoslav forces more than a week
to withdraw, another point of objection in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's really something which is not fundamental, which is a
question of a day here or a day there, then NATO is prepared to
look at that as long as the overall objective of the rapid,
verifiable and total withdrawal of Serb forces is agreed,'' Shea
told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said that airstrikes against Yugoslavia were ``accelerating
toward their prior intensity'' before the peace plan deal Thursday.
Jertz said targets were primarily Yugoslav forces on the ground in
Kosovo, especially along the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports, Jertz said, were that Serb ground units ``had
to suffer some heavy losses'' as NATO bore down on armored
personnel carriers and artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
