A6487 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     06-07 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Deducting Mortgage Interest On a Rental Building &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm planning to buy a three-unit residential building. I will be
living in one unit and renting the two others. I thought I would be
able to deduct the entire amount of mortgage interest from my
income in figuring my taxes, but a friend told me that I am allowed
to deduct only one-third. Is this so? If it is, what happens to the
other two-thirds?
</P>
<P>
   A: One way or another, you can deduct all the mortgage interest.
Here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   You split the house (figuratively speaking) into two parts: the
part used for your residence and the part used for rental. Find out
the square footage of each.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, for the sake of simplicity, that the residential
portion is exactly one-third of the total. Then you can deduct
one-third of the mortgage interest _ and also one-third of your
real-estate taxes _ on Schedule A of Internal Revenue Service Form
1040.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two-thirds of your interest and real-estate taxes
gets deducted on Schedule E, where you report your real-estate
income. Also on that schedule, you can deduct two-thirds of your
homeowners insurance, as well as certain other expenses such as
utility costs (if you are paying the utility bills for your
tenants). Other potential deductions include repair and maintenance
costs. Such deductions wouldn't be allowed if you used the entire
building as your residence.
</P>
<P>
   So, buying a rental building can make good sense _ until the
first time your tenants turn up the stereo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Why Is EU Meddling?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently I read that the European Union approved the proposal
by Lucent Technologies to buy Ascend Communications. Both those
companies are based in the United States, so where does the EU get
off deciding whether they can merge?
</P>
<P>
   A: Welcome to the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission, an arm of the EU, has the authority to
block or modify mergers between companies with total worldwide
sales of around $5 billion or more and EU sales of around $250
million or more. It wants to prevent companies, foreign or
domestic, from getting a stranglehold on markets or industries
within the EU. If the EU disapproves a merger, the parties have the
choice of calling the merger off or withdrawing at least some of
their business from European markets. Some choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucent-Ascend deal also has been cleared by the U.S.
Department of Justice. The last hurdle, if you can call it that, is
a meeting of Ascend shareholders on June 24. If they approve _ and
why shouldn't they, since the price they are being offered is about
30 percent more than their stock was worth before Lucent proposed
marriage _ the deal will be consummated immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent shareholders don't have to vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Cost Basis of Gift
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am having trouble figuring the cost basis of stock I own _
which I need to know to figure my capital-gains tax when I sell. I
was given the stock by my grandfather and grandmother through a
trust. The problem is that both of them have died, and I haven't
the foggiest idea what they paid for the stock. Does this mean I
have to use a cost basis of zero? I have spoken to two tax
preparers about this, but they gave me conflicting advice.
</P>
<P>
   A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says the
answer depends in part on what kind of trust your grandparents
created _ an irrevocable trust, or a revocable living trust.
</P>
<P>
   If it was a revocable trust, then the stock belonged to your
grandparents throughout their lifetimes; possession didn't pass to
you until the second grandparent died. In that case, your cost
basis is determined the same way it is with inheritances. It is
marked up to the price of the stock on the date of death.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the trust was irrevocable, your cost basis for the
stock would be the same price your grandparents paid for it. If
that is the case, then _ as you say _ you have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Weller says that if you make a good-faith effort to determine
the cost, and fully document your effort, the IRS won't force you
to use a cost basis of zero. Instead, you can use the purchase
price that seems most probable.
</P>
<P>
   You should go through your grandparents' papers and see if you
can find the appropriate brokerage statements, or the confirmation
slips the broker was required to send after each transaction. Also,
ask the brokerage firm whether it still has records of the stock
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, pick a likely date _ or range of dates _
on which the purchases might have been made. One possible starting
point would be the date that the trust was established. A broker
can supply you with the prices of any stock for any date you
choose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
