A6490 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TRAVEL_SFCHRON     06-07 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TRAVEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   When Traveling Abroad, Beware of Surcharges on Credit Card 
 Purchases 
 &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Traveling outside the United States this summer? Advance planning
can shield you against surcharges of 2 to 4 percent on credit card
purchases.
<P>
   For years, credit cards were touted as the best way to pay for
purchases when traveling abroad. That's because exchange rates were
among the best and transaction costs were low.
</P>
<P>
   That's not necessarily true anymore. Some credit card issuers
quietly are slapping fees on consumers who use their credit cards
in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   The trend began a year ago when Providian Financial Corp.
started charging its credit card customers a whopping 4 percent fee
for overseas credit card purchases. Citibank followed with a 2
percent fee and First USA with a 3 percent fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the fee was needed to offset the higher costs we
experience to service foreign transactions,'' said Citibank
spokeswoman Maria Menzler.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates are skeptical. ``It's just another example of
unjustified bank fees that aren't at all cost based,'' said Ken
McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action, a San Francisco
nonprofit advocacy organization. ``It's designed to boost bank
profits.''
</P>
<P>
   For all three issuers, and those that followed, the fee came on
top of the 1 percent foreign exchange fee that Visa and MasterCard
each have charged for years to clear foreign transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, it looked like the surcharge would cascade
through the industry, but a number of us raised a howl and the
stampede stopped,'' said Ed Perkins, a syndicated travel columnist
in Ashland, Ore., and former editor of Consumer Reports' travel
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, First USA has rescinded its fee. But the creeping
surcharge hasn't been nipped altogether. American Express, which
issues its own cards, upped its foreign exchange fee from 1 percent
to 2 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for consumers, the surcharge isn't across the board yet.
Wells Fargo and Bank of America do not charge a separate fee. Their
customers still pay just the 1 percent fee charged by Visa and
MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Your best strategy: Make a quick phone call to your credit card
issuer to find out whether your card has a surcharge and, if so,
how much. Then decide whether it makes sense to use that card at
all.
</P>
<P>
   To get the most out of your vacation dollars, experts say,
consumers should use all the tools in their financial toolbox _
credit cards from different issuers, ATM cards, cash and traveler's
checks, since each is superior in certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``People spend a lot of time planning what they want to see and
researching hotel and airfare costs,'' said Michael Estill,
executive director of the Western Association of Travel Agents.
``You should have a plan on how you're going to handle your money,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other industry experts &UR;  &LR; offer this advice:
</P>
<P>
   _Get enough cash before leaving the United States to cover
initial expenses so you're not at the mercy of the first exchange
bureau you see. Exchange rates and fees vary widely. For example, a
traveler changing $1,000 into British currency last Friday, could
get 600 pounds at money-changer AFEX in downtown San Francisco but
only 570 pounds at the Travelex America kiosk at San Francisco
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   _Carry some traveler's checks with you. The California State
Automobile Association and many banks will issue travelers checks,
to members or customers, without the usual 1 percent fee. In
general, the dollar's strength means it's been better to carry
dollar-denominated traveler's checks than those issued in a foreign
currency.
</P>
<P>
   _Find out if your ATM card can be used in foreign cash machines
to access cash in your bank account. Many can.
</P>
<P>
   ATM cards carrying the Visa logo, for example, can be used at
some 457,000 ATMs in 120 countries. Cards with the MasterCard logo
are good at 463,000 ATMs globally.
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned: Four-digit PINs are standard in most countries.
If you have an alphabetic PIN with more than four digits, you may
need to get a new personal identification number.
</P>
<P>
   Check out pertinent ``ATM locator'' services before leaving home
so you can find the ATMs closest to your hotel or travel route.
Both Visa and MasterCard have excellent Web sites with ``ATM
Locator'' services. The MasterCard site ( &LR; www.master &LR;   &LR; card.com &LR; )
has details on the Cirrus network of financial institutions and the
Visa site ( &LR; www.visa.com &LR; ) lists Plus network locations.
</P>
<P>
   _Charge major purchases to your credit card, if you are carrying
a surcharge-free card. The exchange rate is set by Visa or
MasterCard and is close to the wholesale interbank rate. In
addition, you automatically get protections like arbitration of
disputes with retailers or hotels and protection against theft.
</P>
<P>
   _Use your ATM card to get money rather than to tap the ``cash
advance'' feature of your credit card which often carry higher
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank customers using an ATM card to get cash in London, for
example, pay a fee of $1 to $1.50 per withdrawal. If they use their
Citibank credit card, they pay a minimum fee of $5 or 3 percent of
the transaction amount, whichever is greater. That means it costs
four times as much in fees to withdraw $200 using a credit card
than an ATM card.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think credit card cash advances should be used as more of
an emergency measure than as a way of paying for travel expenses,''
said Citibank's Menzler.
</P>
<P>
   For American Express customers, the cash advance fee is 2
percent of the transaction amount, with a minimum fee of $2.50 and
a maximum fee of $20.
</P>
<P>
   _One final complexity for many travelers concerns collision and
theft insurance on rental cars. Your personal policy won't cover
you abroad, in most cases. Find out whether the car you plan to
charge to your credit card automatically receives protection
through your credit card issuer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell all my customers, call and check the coverages before
you leave,'' said Donna Ludlum, co-owner of Little World Travel in
Belmont. ``It's always changing. I have a group in Europe now and
they were covered in Italy but not in Sicily.''
</P>
<P>
   It varies from country to country and card to card. For example,
Visa International no longer offers automatic insurance coverage to
cardholders renting cars in Ireland, Israel or Jamaica. But
MasterCard and Diners Club still offer this protection.
</P>
<P>
   None of the card companies offers protection for cars rented in
Australia or New Zealand. You'll have to buy coverage from the auto
rental company when you rent the car, often from $10 to $15 per
day.
</P>
<P>
   One last bit of advice from Scott Pinheiro of Santa Cruz Travel:
``If you're flying out of SFO, get there at least 45 minutes
earlier than usual because of traffic tie-ups caused by
construction of the new international terminal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
