<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXECPAY-EXECUTIVECOMP     06-07 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECPAY-EXECUTIVE </SLUG>
 COMPENSATION _ SF CHRON  
 Bay Area Executives Score Big With Generous Stock Options  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Northern California's corporate executives got more of everything
last year: more salary, more bonuses and more stock options _
especially more stock options.
<P>
   In this era of soaring stock prices, cash compensation has
become little more than an afterthought for the region's
executives.
</P>
<P>
   They much prefer to be paid in stock _ and understandably so.
The profusion of new and larger option grants, compounded by the
magic of a stock market that just won't quit, has made many of them
fabulously wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 291 high-ranking executives from 54 large companies
included in The Chronicle's 15th annual executive-compensation
survey, 86 percent received stock-option grants last year with an
estimated total value of $1.05 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That was 43 percent more than the $733 million worth of options
granted to 293 executives in our year-earlier survey.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, nonoption compensation _ salaries, bonuses and
long-term incentive pay such as restricted stock _ totaled just
$338 million for the executives in the latest survey. That
represented a 26 percent gain from the amount the same executives
received in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Options now constitute three-fourths of executive pay, up from
less than one-third as recently as 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The largest option grant of all went to Margaret C. Whitman,
president and chief executive of eBay, the San Jose Internet
auction site.
</P>
<P>
   A former toy-company executive who joined then-private eBay
early last year, Whitman was granted options valued by the company
at $69.9 million, or $22 million more than eBay's 1998 revenues.
She was the only executive whose pay exceeded corporate revenues.
</P>
<P>
   After the grant was made, it became glaringly obvious that the
company's valuation of the options was ridiculously conservative.
Thanks to eBay's spectacular stock-market performance following an
initial public offering in September, the shares awarded to Whitman
currently are worth more than $1 billion!
</P>
<P>
   Pretty good for a year's work.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pursglove, a spokesman for eBay, said nobody at the
company, including Whitman, ``had any idea'' that the stock would
do so well.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman ranked well up among the most overpaid executives in
Northern California last year, based on two objective tests.
</P>
<P>
   Her total compensation _ option grants plus nonoption pay _ was
the highest in proportion to company revenues, even using the
ultraconservative $69.9 million value placed on her option grant.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, her total compensation was equal to more than
one-third of 1 percent of her company's puffed-up $20 billion
market value. By that measure, she was the seventh highest-paid
among 61 CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   (The CEOs in the survey outnumbered the companies because two
companies have co-CEOS and five others changed CEOs during 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the scale, the most modestly paid executive
by any reckoning was Steve Jobs, co-founder and interim CEO of
Apple Computer, who accepted a token $1 salary and no stock options
last year. No other executive in the survey received less than
$121,000 in total compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Huge, untapped stock-market fortunes are piling up for many
Northern California executives. At the end of last year, the
executives in the survey had $7 billion in paper profits from
unexercised options _ an average of close to $25 million per
executive.
</P>
<P>
   That is about twice the average amount of paper profits held by
the executives in the previous year's survey.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen executives were sitting on unexercised option profits of
$100 million or more at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the heap was Millard S. Drexler, the always
lavishly paid president and chief executive of Gap Inc., the San
Francisco apparel retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler got new option grants valued at $39 million last year,
and by the end of the year, the profits on all his unexercised
options amounted to a staggering $659 million _ not bad for a
nonfounder who has been with the company for just 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   However, as Gap's proxy statement points out, the company's
stock increased an incredible 300-fold during those 15 years, and
Drexler's ``decisive management of operational and strategic
issues'' contributed mightily to the climb.
</P>
<P>
   Gap officials declined a request for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Ward, a compensation specialist with WestWard Pay
Strategies in San Francisco, notes that Gap's founding family,
headed by current company Chairman Donald G. Fisher, has cheerfully
handed Drexler enormous amounts of stock year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the founders don't mind, most likely the other
shareholders won't mind either,'' Ward remarks. ``Clearly the
numbers are mind boggling, but it's hard to point to him as an
example of too much. Few individuals have done a better job in the
world of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent compensation expert begs to differ with that
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Graef ``Bud'' Crystal, a former compensation consultant who
publishes the Crystal Report in Santa Rosa, contends that Drexler
is ``wildly overpaid.'' In his characteristically acerbic way, he
complains that Drexler has received ``monstrously sized option
grants that have to be hauled in by 18-wheelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal said Drexler's compensation is particularly hard to
justify when contrasted with the amount paid to ``the average
employee of the Gap, who doesn't make much more than the minimum
wage. It's not like Intel, where the average employee is paid quite
a bit of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranking after Drexler in paper profits was Timothy Koogle,
president and chief executive of Yahoo, the Santa Clara Internet
software company, who has amassed $544 million in unexercised
option profits.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gap, Yahoo has enjoyed phenomenal stock-market growth,
ranking first in that category last year among all the companies in
the latest Chronicle 500 survey.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Yahoo executives also were among the Top 10 in paper
profits: Senior Vice President Farzad Nazem, with $316 million
worth; Chief Operating Office Jeffrey Mallett, with $245 million;
and Chief Financial Officer Gary Valenzuela, with $146 million.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Katz, a compensation specialist with William M. Mercer in
San Francisco, said he worries about what will happen to executive
compensation when what he calls the stock-market ``joy ride'' comes
to an end.
</P>
<P>
   He says that some executives who are riding high now could
actually find themselves inadequately compensated during a bear
market, because of the overwhelming emphasis on options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that are forward-thinking will reduce their emphasis
on stock options and increase their emphasis on long-term incentive
pay based on improving profit margins and cash flow,'' Katz
remarks. ``That will allow them to reward executives for doing the
right thing, disconnected from stock prices.''
</P>
<P>
   While the hottest compensation action took place on the option
front, nonoption pay also moved up strongly last year.
</P>
<P>
   The median salary for all the executives in The Chronicle survey
rose 19 percent to $343,743, while the median bonus _ for the more
than 80 percent of executives who got a bonus _ increased 11
percent to $247,139.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two percent of the executives in the survey received at
least $1 million in nonoption compensation last year, compared with
29 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hazen, chairman of Wells Fargo, the San Francisco banking
giant, led all other executives in nonoption compensation. He got a
total of $14.8 million, including $10.8 million worth of restricted
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Restricted stock also accounted for the bulk of the pay received
by the No. 2 executive on the nonoption list _ Harold M. Messmer
Jr., chairman and CEO of Robert Half International, the Menlo Park
employment agency. Messmer got $11.3 million, of which $8.8 million
was restricted stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Wells Fargo proxy statement indicates that most of Hazen's
restricted stock was awarded on November 2 _ the effective date of
the Wells Fargo merger with Norwest _ ``pursuant to Mr. Hazen's
employment agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazen had served as chairman and CEO of the old Wells Fargo, but
was replaced as CEO by Richard M. Kovacevich, who headed Norwest.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy is unclear on the subject, but seems to suggest either
that Hazen got the restricted stock as a reward for helping to sell
the company, or as a consolation prize for surrendering the CEO
title.
</P>
<P>
   Wells officials declined to elaborate on the proxy.
</P>
<P>
   Restricted stock is a special _ and controversial _ form of
deferred compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Companies offer the stock as an outright gift, although the
executive cannot take full possession until several years have
passed. Executives who leave their companies before the waiting
period ends usually must forfeit restricted shares.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six executives in The Chronicle survey got
restricted-stock grants last year _ up from 39 the year before. The
size of the median grant rose a steep 55 percent to $860,689.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation consultants who are willing to wink at the huge
bonuses and option grants routinely lavished on corporate
executives find restricted stock hard to tolerate. They deride it
as ``pay for attendance,'' because it isn't keyed to performance;
an executive merely has to report to work each day until the
restricted stock becomes vested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to keep entitlements like restricted stock from
infecting the overall pay package,'' said Matt Ward. ``But we're
seeing more restricted stock. It is disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
