A6498 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCC-OCC_SFCHRON &LR;      06-07 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCC-OCC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Regulator Warns Banks, Credit Card Issuers  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A top U.S. bank regulator yesterday warned banks and credit card
issuers to halt misleading sales pitches and other anti-consumer
practices or face a crackdown from federal watchdogs.
<P>
   Comptroller of the Currency John Hawke, speaking at an industry
conference in San Francisco, said banks increasingly are turning to
business methods that harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's mounting evidence of an increase in banking practices
that are at least seamy, if not downright unfair and deceptive _
practices that virtually cry out for government scrutiny,'' Hawke
said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Hawke slammed lenders who fail to report payment
histories to credit bureaus, thereby depriving customers of chances
to fix flawed credit records. He also cited lenders who sell
financial information about customers to outside vendors that use
trickery to sell products over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that exploded on us,'' Hawke said in an
interview before his speech. An agency hotline installed last year
as a service to consumers is logging complaints at the rate of
100,000 a year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke said anti-consumer practices are a red flag inviting
lawmakers to toughen laws protecting bank customers, perhaps as
part of banking legislation currently before Congress. ``Where
there are consumer abuses unremedied by industry, Congress has
invariably stepped in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, reports that the San Francisco district attorney's
office is investigating possible consumer fraud by Providian
Financial Corp., the nation's ninth-largest credit card issuer, has
focused attention on alleged deceptive sales practices by lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Providian allegedly used deceptive tactics to sell add-on
products such as credit protection.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Hawke, whose agency regulates nationally chartered banks,
declined to comment on Providian.
</P>
<P>
   But he said angry customers ultimately could affect a bank's
financial health by withdrawing business and filing lawsuits. That
danger, he stressed, makes anti-consumer practices a legitimate
concern for bank regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, bank examiners only considered whether lenders
formally obeyed the law by, for example, disclosing interest rates.
Now, Hawke said, his agency is considering whether to examine
broader problems that are harder to pin down, such as telemarketing
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the comptroller said in his speech, ``shoddy and
unethical practices, marketing schemes that overreach or exploit,
and offensive sales techniques'' may not actually be against the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke, a longtime Washington lawyer and former Under Secretary
of the Treasury for Domestic Finance before President Clinton named
him comptroller late last year. Consumer groups and some liberal
democrats opposed his appointment because of disagreements over
such issues as the need for customer protections in electronic
banking.
</P>
<P>
   The number of the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency's
consumer telephone hotline is (800) 613-6743.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
