<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-BANKS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-07 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BANKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMOST TIME TO PICK PARTNERS IN FRANCE'S 3-BANK DANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When Andre Levy-Lang, the chief executive of Paribas,
runs into Claude Bebear these days, he asks him whether he has made
up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Bebear, chairman of the big French insurer AXA SA, is not only a
shareholder of Paribas but also of Banque Nationale de Paris, whose
hostile bid for Paribas and Societe Generale is threatening to turn
the proposed merger of these two French banks into a three-way
dance.
</P>
<P>
   So later this month, when big institutional investors that own
chunks of Paribas and Societe Generale decide whether to sell their
shares to Banque Nationale, they will be watching Bebear, one of
the most powerful kingmakers in French finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet Bebear often, and he says he's open-minded, not
decided,'' Levy-Lang said in an interview. Yet to be on the safe
side, Levy-Lang and Daniel Bouton, his counterpart at Societe
Generale, have asked a Paris court to declare the Banque Nationale
bid invalid. A decision is expected June 17.
</P>
<P>
   Banque Nationale's proposed $37 billion share swap for Paribas
and Societe Generale is the latest turn of European banking's
merger carousel. If it succeeds _ and a final decision could come
by June 30 _ it would create a group with $1 trillion in assets,
eclipsing UBS of Switzerland as the world's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of Paribas shares may sell them to Societe Generale or to
Banque Nationale, or hold onto them; investors in Societe Generale
must decide whether to tender their shares to Banque Nationale.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been lukewarm toward both proposals, weakening
the share prices of Banque Nationale and Societe Generale. Paribas,
by contrast, has gained slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Bebear has not been commenting, but if anything he has expressed
in the past a preference for the larger combination.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the battle has turned into a clash of banking
titans. Should the three-way merger come about, the future of
Levy-Lang and Bouton would be at risk; if it fails, Banque
Nationale's chief, Michel Pebereau, would be isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the personal maneuvering, larger stakes are at risk.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Socialist government of Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin will sell its stake in Credit Lyonnais, the nationalized
bank that has lost billions. The largest share, about 10 percent,
will go to Credit Agricole, which is not only France's biggest
retail bank, with 22 percent of the market, but also stands in the
front line of potential cross-border alliances, because of its 23
percent stake in Banca Intesa, one of Italy's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Banca Intesa is expected to announce a merger with
Banca Commerciale Italiana to create a big new Italian banking
group. Credit Agricole would retain a 13 percent share in such a
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Baudoin Prot, the No. 2 executive at Banque Nationale, said the
rationale for his bank's proposal was easy to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to a chart ranking European banks by market
capitalization, he noted in an interview that Paribas' proposed
two-way combination with Societe Generale would rank 14th in
Europe; the three-way combination would be fifth. Without the
larger combination, he said, ``all three would be at the bottom of
the European league; they will be marginalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Each side has frequently been sending senior executives on road
shows to try to woo investors. Moreover, a white knight could enter
the scene to rescue Paribas and Societe Generale from the grip of
Banque Nationale. Recently, Banco Santander Central Hispano of
Spain refused to comment on reports that it was a potential
rescuer, but analysts discounted Santander, itself the result of a
recent merger of two of Spain's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   Aligning Paribas with Societe Generale, which are roughly the
same size in terms of market capitalization, would certainly bring
benefits. Levy-Lang says the two banks can save $3 billion pretax
over three years by merging back-office functions and services like
computer technology. Both Paribas and Societe Generale emphasize
how they complement each other, given Societe Generale's strength
in retail banking and Paribas' focus on investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Levy-Lang cites analysts who say that European bank
consolidation will put pressure on retail banking profits, making
wholesale banking's profit potential appear more attractive. And
the institution created by the two-way link, he says, would have
half its equity in wholesale banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   If there is investor sympathy for the three-way deal, it lies in
part in the potential threat to a smaller solution posed by the
entry of Credit Agricole into the Credit Lyonnais shareholder
group.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Michel Cornudet, the spokesman for Credit Agricole, says
his bank wants to parlay its stake into a long-term partnership
with Lyonnais and has proposed more than a half-dozen areas of
potential cooperation, including consumer credit, leasing,
factoring and asset management. Together, Credit Agricole and
Lyonnais would have more than $200 billion of assets under
management. `'Once privatization is done in July, we can begin
talking about project implementation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Lyonnais will not comment on its future alliance plans,
and at any rate under the terms of its privatization none are
allowed for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Cornudet acknowledges that the biggest uncertainties in Credit
Agricole's future with Credit Lyonnais involve questions of control
of any banking combination and the possibility of other more
attractive alliances for Lyonnais. But if the three-way merger
around Banque Nationale succeeds, few domestic French alternatives
would remain for Lyonnais. He added, however, that ``partnerships
can only live in the long term if they are desired by both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, John Leonard of Salomon Smith Barney, said he
thought Banque Nationale's chances of success ``have marginally
increased'' recently given the lack of success of the target banks
in persuading French stock market regulators to invalidate the
hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   The worst outcome, he said, would be if Paribas shareholders
opted to sell their shares to Banque Nationale, but Societe
Generale stock owners refrained, leaving a stalemate in which
Banque Nationale wound up with Paribas but not Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody hopes for that,'' Leonard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
