<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6503 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT_S     06-07 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Microsoft Officially Launches Office 2000  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
On the same day a new report said Microsoft is winning the browser
war, the software giant demonstrated how Office 2000 will extend
its reach into the Internet.
<P>
   At a launch party for Office 2000 in downtown San Francisco,
Microsoft President Steve Ballmer showed how the upgrade to the
widely used Office 97 software package weaves the Internet into
business memos, spreadsheets, e-mail and PowerPoint presentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're integrating the best of Web technology with the best of
Office technology,'' Ballmer said as he formally launched Office
2000 before about 600 guests at the Sony-Imax Theater in the new
Metreon center.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000, which includes word processing, e-mail and other
business productivity software, goes on sale at retailers on
Thursday. It replaces Office 97, which has about 100 million users
and most of the business productivity software market.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations and computer-makers have already bought 15 million
copies of Office 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000 should only increase Microsoft's lead in the browser
market. Yesterday, InfoBeads, a Ziff-Davis research group, reported
that in January, there were 33.8 million U.S. PCs using Microsoft's
Internet Explorer compared to only 32 million for Netscape's
browsers. This was the first time Netscape, which only last year
had 54 percent of the market, had surrendered the lead to
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft included Internet Explorer with its Windows operating
system, which runs about 90 percent of the world's desktop PCs.
Microsoft has denied charges by the federal government and 19
states that the Redmond, Wash., firm used its monopoly position to
gain an unfair advantage over competing browsers including
Netscape's.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000 integrates the basic language of the Web, HTML, into
each of its programs, including Word, Outlook and PowerPoint, and
is designed to let computer users share documents on the Web the
same way they might on a corporate network.
</P>
<P>
   For example, workers in one office could post a memo on a Web
site and it could be reviewed or changed by workers in other
offices. The product is designed for companies that don't have
internal networks, or who want to share documents with people in
other firms. However, Ballmer said certain features will work only
with Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer also announced partnerships between Microsoft and two
major Internet service providers _ Concentric Network Inc. of San
Jose and Verio Inc. of Colorado _ to offer new Web-based business
services for small and medium-size firms.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the launch party, Ballmer denied rumors that
Microsoft planned to make an Office 2000 version for Linux, an
alternative computer operating system that is gaining grassroots
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Metreon, San Francisco police ordered two Linux
supporters, one dressed as a big penguin, away from the launch
party entrance as they tried to hand out flyers about Penguin
Computing's Linux products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft and the evil empire decided that we were somehow a
threat to them,'' said Justin Cheung, a Penguin Computing employee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
