<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     06-07 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW GOING ON THE ROAD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Nev., Calif., Wyo., Conn., Ohio)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a traffic jam in the Spaghetti Bowl. This tangle of
highways at Las Vegas, including Interstate 15, which carries
traffic to and from California, and U.S. Route 95, is being redone
at a cost of $92 million in what Scott Magruder, a Department of
Transportation spokesman, says is Nevada's most costly road
project. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This choke point is one of 12 on major arteries that the AAA,
based in Heathrow, Fla., says will affect motorists on vacation
trips this summer. Families getting organized should be aware that
roads with easy daytime flow may be home to bright lights and
construction crews at night.
</P>
<P>
   As the interstate system moves along in its middle age, state
transportation agencies try to make the repairs outside major
travel hours. If you are running late, particularly if you like to
drive while the children sleep in back, you may meet unexpected
stoppages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are brief reports on a few major road-work sites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Las Vegas is pressing Orlando as the most popular
destination in the United States, the Spaghetti Bowl road work,
which will eventually increase Las Vegas-California traffic to
three lanes in each direction from two, is more than a blip on the
traffic radar.
</P>
<P>
   Magruder said that eight major ramps on the vintage-60s highways
were being redone, with only two finished so far. The overhaul is a
three-year project, and it is half done. Signs overhead warn
travelers of what is coming at the Spaghetti Bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right now the construction means that drivers arriving from
California _ those coming from the airport south of town will miss
the mess _ should allow an extra 10 or 15 minutes. The situation is
easier on weekends, Magruder said, and construction ceases on
holiday weekends _ a precaution taken after New Year's, when
traffic into California backed up from the state line 36 miles into
downtown Las Vegas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information about this work can be found at www.nevadadot.com,
the state highway Web site. Magruder said that despite the
difficulties, the Interstate was still the way to travel into Las
Vegas, since drivers should not miss the night trip along the
Strip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Road repairs in and east of Yellowstone Park in Wyoming continue
to slow visitors. Families with Yellowstone in their plans for
summer should get up-to-date information before setting out; cars
arriving late in the evening could find the East Entrance blocked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A stretch of eight miles in the center of the 50-mile route from
Cody to the East Entrance on U.S. Routes 14, 16 and 20 is under
repair. This section, between mileposts 27 and 19, includes
bridges, and there is no alternative route. Kerry Lang of the
Yellowstone Park administration says that drivers should allow an
extra half hour for the Cody-East Entrance trip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inside the park, she said, where road work continues between the
entrance and Fishing Bridge, extra time, probably another half
hour, should be budgeted. Farther west, the road along Yellowstone
Lake between Fishing Bridge and West Thumb will probably be closed
at night starting June 15, and delays of 30 minutes at other times
are likely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After July 6, the East Entrance will be closed at 9 p.m., and
there will be warning signs in Cody. Mrs. Lang urges those making
plans to call (307) 344-2109 well in advance to get maps and other
information, and (307) 344-7381 to learn the latest conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Although the National Park Service Web site, www.nps.gov, said
it was having technical problems at the end of May, and most links
were not working, I had no difficulty starting out with
www.nps.gov/yell, where ``maps and orientation'' offers a link to
construction reports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The state is working almost continuously on its frayed
interstates, according to Sue Reynolds of its Department of
Transportation. But work is being conducted without shutting down
lanes for long periods of time, she said. This is done by narrowing
the lanes and rerouting traffic onto breakdown lanes. Most work
goes on at night, or in daylight hours between the morning and
evening rush periods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I-95 in Greenwich will be worked on all summer between 8 p.m.
and 6 a.m., Monday to Friday, Ms. Reynolds said. At Exits 8 to 10
in Stamford, there will also be night work, as there will be from
Exits 26 to 29 in Bridgeport, where there are extensive ramp
projects under way. In Stratford and Milford, the I-95 work will go
on between 9 a.m. and 3 p.m., as it will on the Merritt, or Route
15, in Stratford and Trumbull. I-84 in West Hartford will be worked
on at night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``On weekends and holidays, we just stop work, so as to speed
people through the state,'' Ms. Reynolds said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Radio advisories for drivers on I-95 are expected to be
broadcast on 520 AM frequency starting July 1. When this was being
tested, entertaining quizzes on safety and other stay-alert items
were included, and they are to continue. One of these was:
``Without looking in your rear-view mirror, do you know what color
the car behind you is?''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AAA says it is hearing from motorists most about a project
in Cincinnati, where I-71, which bears a major traffic load from
Cleveland on Lake Erie southwest to Louisville, Ky., where it
debouches into I-64 and I-65. At Cincinnati, this highway crosses
the Ohio River into Covington, Ky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The work focuses on a one-mile stretch in Cincinnati called the
Fort Washington Way. As befits a major star among road projects,
this one has its own Web site, www.fww2000 .com. It shows detour
maps and is brought up to date daily by the construction company,
Parsons Brinkerhoff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julie Harrison, an information officer for the project, said
that the old four-lane road was carrying 150,000 cars a day _
almost triple its intended capacity. Now, with the slowdown, and
with westbound traffic routed off the roadway, eastbound traffic is
down to 50,000 a day. probably because local eastbound drivers are
using alternate routes.
</P>
<P>
   The suggested westbound detour is four and a half miles long to
get around the one-mile blockage. It leads through traffic to
I-275, rather than through local streets. There are many signs for
guidance, Ms. Harrison says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffic Information &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Smartraveler Web site, www .smartraveler.com (note: just one
``t''), has been adding to its databases steadily since it got
Massachusetts on line in 1996. It now has travel information about
Boston, Chicago, Cincinnati, Los Angeles, Milwaukee,
Minneapolis-St. Paul, New York, Philadelphia, San Diego, San
Francisco and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Users can click on the medallion for the route number and get
information about construction and how fast traffic is moving.
Transit information is also sometimes available. Stacey Kevorkian
of Smart Route Systems, the organizer of this project, says that
the San Francisco link will be augmented, and the company hopes to
have Denver on line before the ski season begins, with Los Angeles
and others due through 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
