<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGANSTANLEY-CURRY-N     06-07 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGANSTANLEY-CURRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY ACCUSES FORMER EMPLOYEE OF FALSE EXPENSE FILINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter has accused a former
employee who filed a discrimination suit against the firm of brazen
theft of the firm's money through systematic false expense filings,
and said that the employee's contentions of racism and homophobia
there amount to an ``extortion scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm also defended a $10,000 payment it made to an informant
involved in a police undercover operation against the former
employee, calling it a ``reward'' made as a ``token of
appreciation'' for help in thwarting a crime. The firm said that
after the payment was made, the informant made ``vigorous and
extensive efforts to extort larger sums of money'' from the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations are part of a 28-page response Morgan Stanley
made to a civil lawsuit filed against it by Christian L. Curry, the
former employee. The lawsuit seeks $1.35 billion in damages and
alleges multiple counts of racism, homophobia and false arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley lawyers said Curry, a graduate of Columbia
University who hails from a prominent New York family, was
dismissed solely for expense-account abuses. The abuses occurred on
a grand scale _ more than 150 separate false expense filings in 10
months, they said. The decision to dismiss Curry, who is black, had
already been made before photos of him appeared in a gay men's
magazine, the lawyers said, even though he was not actually
dismissed until shortly after the magazine appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action is nothing more than a well-orchestrated extortion
scheme cloaked with a caption and docket number,'' the firm said in
answering Curry's lawsuit, which was filed last month. Paul, Weiss,
Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, the law firm handling Morgan Stanley's
defense in the matter, filed the response on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The sharply worded response marks Morgan Stanley's most spirited
defense of its actions since the firm was caught in a whirlwind of
accusations about its conduct in the Curry case last month.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict P. Morelli, Curry's lawyer, has said that Morgan
Stanley's claim of expense account abuses is a cover for the real
reason for dismissing Curry, which he said was racism and
homophobia. Curry has said that he is not gay, but that his bosses
at the firm thought he was. Morelli did not return phone calls
seeking comment on Morgan Stanley's response Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The matter began a year ago when Morgan Stanley dismissed Curry
shortly after photos of him appeared in Playguy, a pornographic
magazine for gay men. Morgan Stanley has said that he was dismissed
for expense account abuses, but until now provided few details.
Last August, police arrested Curry and charged him with conspiring
to plant fake e-mails on the firm's computer system to bolster a
planned discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Manhattan district attorney's office announced
that it was dropping charges against Curry. It also said that it
had begun an investigation into a $10,000 payment Morgan Stanley
made to Charles Joseph Luethke, a college friend of Curry who
played a key role in the police undercover operation. That
investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley suspended with pay two inhouse lawyers in
connection with the $10,000 payment.
</P>
<P>
   In the response on Monday, the firm defended its ``reward'' to
Luethke for his help in preventing a crime. The firm said it had
legal advice from one of its outside law firms, Davis, Polk &AMP;
Wardwell, that such a reward payment is legal. It said that after
the payment, Luethke barraged the firm with calls and letters
seeking to ``extort'' more money from the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke denied on Monday that he ever sought to extort money,
and contended that his discussions with the firm were attempts to
work out a legitimate business contract.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the Morgan Stanley response details what it calls a
pattern of expense account abuses by Curry. It says, for example,
that he submitted vouchers seeking hundreds of dollars in
reimbursements for what he described as work-related meals with
colleagues, but that the colleagues denied dining with Curry on
those occasions.
</P>
<P>
   On numerous occasions Curry submitted phony expense claims for
meals that were in fact receipts from purchases of personal items.
After investigating, the firm found that Curry was claiming to have
dined at stores like Cole-Hahn, FAO Schwarz, Lots of Linens
furniture, House Aoxo electronics, Virgin Megastore, Blockbuster
Video, as well as movie theaters, liquor stores and photo labs.
</P>
<P>
   Fully half of the expense claims Curry made in his 10 months at
the firm were false, the lawyers said. Many of the violations were
discovered after Curry's dismissal, the lawyers acknowledge in
their filing. But it says that prior to Curry's termination, it had
already uncovered a pattern of expense account violations that was
``willful and brazenly premeditated, not a product of inadvertence
or carelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   The violation first came to Morgan Stanley's attention when
Curry submitted an expense claim from a Manhattan strip club called
Flash Dancers, and was denied reimbursement, the lawyers said.
Robert Weaver, one of Curry's bosses, then began examining his
expense records. He found that Curry systematically tore the
receipts he submitted to hide the name of the establishment, and
frequently _ at least 14 times _ named fellow employees he had
dined with who denied having dined with him.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that when Curry was confronted with evidence of
fraud, he tried to shift the blame to his secretary, who had
recently retired. Subsequently he acknowledged the abuses and asked
for a chance to resign. But he then retracted his offer to resign,
and the firm dismissed him, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm also defended itself against allegations that it sought
to frame Curry for a crime he did not commit by paying a middleman
to set up his arrest. That claim is also contained in Curry's
lawsuit against the firm, and is one of the matters being
investigated by the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley said it did have contact with the New York Police
Department before Curry's arrest, but that it had nothing to do
with managing the undercover operation, as the lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The firm also said that it has evidence that Curry approached an
employee of Morgan Stanley to help him execute his scheme to plant
fake e-mail messages there. Curry offered an employee that he knew
from Columbia University $100,000 to help him plant e-mails, the
lawyers said, but the employee declined to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
