<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer Garden Tours In Rhode Island &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Rhode Island this summer will have a chance to tour
a variety of gardens, big and small, during the first annual
Gardens Open for Blithewold tour. The event, which benefits
Blithewold _ a 1908 mansion, garden and arboretum in Bristol _ s
scheduled for one day each month, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., in June,
July and September. More than 30 private gardens in all (at least
10 a day) will be showcased.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, the first segment, called the East Bay and
Providence Tour, will encompass Blithewold itself and a number of
in-town gardens. In Bristol, guests can inspect the formal gardens
of the artist Penelope Manzella, who incorporates sculpture among
her blooming trees, topiaries and roses overlooking the Warren
River.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24, the South County Tour will feature several gardens
created by Louis Raymond, who was the designer for this year's New
England Spring Flower Show in Boston. On view, for example, will be
the grounds of a 15-acre 1917 Shingle Style mansion in Matunuck,
which are planted with espaliered magnolias, rare evergreens,
bamboo and bottlebrush buckeye.
</P>
<P>
   The final Newport County Tour, on Sept. 25, takes in a garden
bordering a salt marsh and several seaside gardens, including a
rose-filled tract belonging to the former Rhode Island Sen.
Claiborne Pell and his wife, Nuala.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets ($30 for the day or $75 for the three-day series) are
sold in advance only. Information and reservations: (401) 253-2707.
</P>
<P>
   _Megan Fulweiler &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How Do You Say Rickshaw in French? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Paris have a new way to tour the city: three-wheeled
black-and-yellow velo-taxis, or taxi-bikes. These rickshaws have
fiberglass passenger carriages and 21 gears. The 20 taxi-bikes,
operated by bilingual students, follow a three-mile circuit
beginning and ending at the Place de la Concorde. The trip lasts an
hour, and passes the Jardin des Tuileries, Place de l'Opera, Place
de la Madeleine, Place Vendome, the Louvre and the Musee d'Orsay.
Passengers can request stops for photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was hatched by two brothers, Patrick and Didier
Leonhart, both veterans of the French Foreign Legion, as an
environmentally friendly and noiseless way to see Paris. Cost: $15;
$21 for two (a child under 2 can sit between two adults). The taxis
operate daily, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; (33-1) 47.42.00.01. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iberia, Beset by Delays, Cuts Flight Schedule &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spain's state-run airline, Iberia, has scaled back plans to
expand its schedule in Europe and Latin America, canceling 900
flights, or 3.5 percent of its scheduled departures, in June. These
include suspension of service from Madrid to Moscow and to
London-Gatwick. The decision, announced in May, is an effort to
reduce delays at Spanish airports, especially in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   A recent labor agreement between the pilots' union and Iberia
was seen as a step to ease the delays, which began in late March
and have been frequent front-page news in Spain. But Iberia said
the reduced June schedule was necessary because the situation was
still not back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   There have been numerous passenger complaints about extensively
delayed flights, and on the worst days this spring, more than 90
percent of the flights at Barajas Airport in Madrid were delayed by
at least 30 minutes and, in some cases, hours. The causes for the
delays, among the worst in Europe, are said to include a shortage
of several hundred air traffic controllers in Spain, a
restructuring of European air routes, the Iberia pilots' strike in
late March and early April, and the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Iberia, which said it lost $26 million because of the pilots'
strike, has had the most delays and canceled flights, followed by
Spain's two main private carriers, Spanair and Air Europa. Other
European and United States airlines operating in Spain have been
more punctual, relying where possible on their own ground crews. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mount Rainier Park Celebrating Centennial &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mount Rainier National Park, a pristine enclave of forests,
glaciers and alpine meadows surrounding the Pacific Northwest's
loftiest mountain, turns 100 this year. The centennial will be
commemorated with a series of activities, both inside and outside
the park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When established on March 2, 1899, Mount Rainier, in Washington
State, became the nation's fifth national park, preceded only by
Yellowstone in 1872, and Yosemite, Sequoia and Kings Canyon, all in
1890. Ranging in elevation from 1,760 feet to the 14,410-foot
summit of Rainier _ a dormant volcano visible for 100 miles _ the
park has a remarkable variety of flora and fauna. It is
crisscrossed by 147 miles of roads and 240 miles of maintained
trails, and about two million people visit each year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The calendar of centennial events includes photography exhibits,
interpretive park programs, a one-day bike ride around Mount
Rainier, weekend festivals in communities surrounding the park, and
a 60-mile Summit-to-Sound Relay from the top of Rainier to the
Puget Sound by foot, bicycle, Rollerblade, horseback and kayak.
</P>
<P>
   To receive a calendar of events, call the park at (360)
569-2211, or visit the Web site at www.mtrainier100.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Washington State History Museum in Tacoma will mark the
centennial with an exhibition that examines the cultural and
natural history of the park through interactive displays,
historical photographs, artifacts and computer animation. Titled
``Sunrise to Paradise: The Story of Mount Rainier National Park,''
the exhibit will run through Jan. 9, 2000. The museum is at 1911
Pacific Avenue, Tacoma; (888) 238-4373. Admission is $7; free
Thursday evenings; open daily.
</P>
<P>
   _Christopher Hall &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam's Van Gogh Museum Reopens &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new and improved Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam will reopen on
June 24, 10 months after closing for renovations.
</P>
<P>
   The improved part is the original museum, which was expected to
attract 60,000 visitors a year when it opened in 1973, but was
drawing a million by 1997. Now renovated, it is devoted exclusively
to the museum's permanent collection _ the world's largest trove of
van Goghs (some 200 paintings, 500 drawings, 700 letters and his
Japanese prints collection) plus works by some contemporaries, like
Gauguin and Toulouse-Lautrec, and by older artists he admired, like
Millet.
</P>
<P>
   The new part is a wing designed by the Japanese architect Kisho
Kurokawa that will be used for special exhibits. The opening show,
``Theo van Gogh: Art Dealer, Collector and Brother of Vincent,''
covers the career of the artist's younger brother, who was born in
1857 and died in 1891, six months after Vincent committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition demonstrates the financial and moral support Theo
offered Vincent and also documents his roles as an influential art
dealer in Paris in the 1880s and as a collector. Between 1881 and
1890, Theo was manager of Goupil &AMP; Cie's branch on Boulevard
Montmartre, from which he sold about 1,000 paintings, including
works by members of the Barbizon School like Corot and Daubigny.
Among the works in the show will be Corot's ``Artist's Studio'' and
Daubigny's ``House of Mere Bazot.''
</P>
<P>
   Theo also organized solo shows for Monet, Pissarro and
Raffaelli, lavished attention on Degas and Gauguin and sold works
by all of them. Highlights in the exhibition include Degas' ``Woman
Seated Beside a Vase of Flowers,'' Monet's ``Church at Vetheuil''
and Pissarro's ``Street in Auvers.''
</P>
<P>
   Theo's extraordinary bond with his brother is illustrated by a
group of paintings that were special to Theo, including ``Almond
Blossom.'' Letters, photographs and possessions of Theo end the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theo van Gogh'' closes on Sept. 5, then moves to the Musee
d'Orsay in Paris, where it will be on view from Sept. 27 through
Jan. 9, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Gogh Museum, at 7 Paulus Potterstraat, is open daily.
Admission: $6.25. Information: (31-20) 570-5252 or on the Web at
www.vangoghmuseum.nl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Judith H. Dobrzynski
</P>
</TEXT>
