<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lazard Freres to Integrate U.S. and European Units
</P>
<P>
   Lazard Freres, the boutique investment banking partnership,
plans to integrate its London, Paris and New York operations and to
shuffle its executive ranks in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The integration of Lazard's European and American operations,
long noted for proud individualism, seems intended in part to
compete with the fluid global networks of other investment banks.
As part of the overhaul, William R. Loomis Jr., 51, will replace
Steven Rattner, 47, as deputy chief executive and the firm's top
day-to-day executive in the United States. Rattner will remain with
the firm as vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   New Stock-Trading System Planned
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group and Merrill Lynch have joined with Bernard
L. Madoff Investment Securities to form an alternative stock
trading system. The system will offer electronic access to
investors interested in trading stocks listed on the New York Stock
Exchange, the American Stock Exchange and Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Nisource Bids for Columbia Energy
</P>
<P>
   Nisource Inc. disclosed a hostile $5.7 billion cash offer for
Columbia Energy, whose stock soared $7.4375, to $63.1875. Shares of
Nisource slipped 62.50 cents, to $27.5625. Columbia's chairman,
Oliver G. Richard III responded that while his company was not for
sale and was not interested in merging, he would present the bid to
the board.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel Plans Internet Products
</P>
<P>
   Nortel Networks plans to announce Tuesday that it is developing
a dozen new products to help corporate customers integrate their
phone and data communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Rally in Light Trading
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rallied, with the Dow Jones industrial average rising
109.54 points, to 10,909.38; the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
climbing 6.77 points, to 1,334.52, and the Nasdaq composite index
gaining 45.87 points, to 2,524.21.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds first rose, then faltered, leaving the benchmark 30-year
Treasury unchanged at a price of 90 5/32 and a yield of 5.96
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco in Talks to Acquire Williams
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International, the maker of electronic-security and
fire-detection systems, said it was in talks to buy Williams of
London, which makes fire extinguishers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing Increases $3.7 Billion
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing by consumers through credit cards, auto loans and
other loans increased by $3.7 billion, to $1.335 trillion, in April
after rising a revised $5.1 billion during March.
</P>
<P>
   China Plans Campaign on Trade
</P>
<P>
   China's top trade official, Wu Yi, acknowledging that many
lower-level Chinese officials oppose the nation's proposed entry to
the World Trade Organization, said that the government would begin
a broad campaign to try to temper the internal discord.
</P>
<P>
   The Duel for French Bank Shares
</P>
<P>
   When Andre Levy-Lang, left, the chief executive of Paribas, runs
into Claude Bebear these days he asks him whether he has made up
his mind. Bebear owns shares in both Paribas and Banque Nationale
de Paris, whose hostile bid for Paribas and Societe Generale is
threatening to turn the proposed merger of these two French banks
into a menage a trois. Big institutional investors in Paribas and
Societe Generale will be watching Bebear as they decide whether to
sell their shares to Banque Nationale.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi of France to Buy Pathe
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi of France plans to acquire Pathe, France's biggest film
producing and distribution company, for $2 billion in stock in a
complex deal that promises to push forward the consolidation
already under way in the European television business.
</P>
<P>
   Disney in Talks for Rest of Infoseek
</P>
<P>
   In a series of moves aimed at expanding its role on the
Internet, Walt Disney confirmed that it was in talks to buy the 57
percent of Infoseek that it does not already own.
</P>
</TEXT>
