<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCES MENTAL HEALTH INITIATIVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Monday announced improved
mental health benefits for federal workers at a conference led by
the vice president's wife, who has acknowledged her struggle with
depression.
</P>
<P>
   The mental health conference at Howard University gave the
president a chance to announce new initiatives but also provided a
forum for Vice President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, who are
gearing up for a presidential campaign. First lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, considering a run for the Senate, also participated.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing experts and lawmakers, Clinton spoke both of the
advancements in treating mental illness and of the need for
businesses and government to give patients better access to
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   To remedy at least part of the problem, the president said, he
has issued a directive requiring the 285 health plans serving
federal employees to offer parity between physical and mental
health and substance abuse benefits by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That means that those health plans cannot charge higher
co-payments or impose different coverage limits on mental health
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials estimate that such improved benefits would
increase premium costs by about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said businesses should emulate the federal government on
mental health parity, because the cost will be greater if the
disease is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance plans claim providing parity for mental health will
send costs and premiums skyrocketing. Businesses believe employees
will overuse mental health services, making it impossible for
employers to offer health insurance,'' Clinton said. ``But I
believe that providing parity is something we can do at a
reasonable cost, benefit millions of Americans and over the long
run, have a healthier country and lower health care costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in treating mental illness, long a taboo subject, has
risen in recent years. In 1996 Congress approved a prohibition on
health plans setting lower annual and lifetime limits for mental
health care than other medical service. And this year lawmakers of
both parties are proposing measures that mandate that insurers
provide parity in mental and physical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three states have mental health parity laws, although the
measures vary widely on who and what benefits are covered.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, mental health parity is required for state and local
governments, as a result of a 1991 law.
</P>
<P>
   But many businesses still do not provide mental health parity
benefits because of the cost. Even the National Mental Health
Association, which has been lobbying for the change, does not offer
parity in benefits, although a spokesman said the group is
negotiating a new contract that will provide equal treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was dominated by Clinton's political proteges who
may benefit in 2000 by embracing mental health initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper and Al Gore and the first lady took turns interviewing
mental health experts and former patients in a talk-show style
format.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore talked with Mike Wallace of television's ``60
Minutes'' about his bouts with depression and also referred to her
own illness following a serious accident involving her son who was
hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of the importance of public figures sharing their
stories ``so that people can see that it is very wrong to
discriminate against people who have a mental health issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, who is expected to run for the White House in 2000,
also interviewed a woman, Robin Kitchell of Franklin Tenn., whose
son had bipolar disorder and the vice president of the Bank One
Corp., which offers parity in mental health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, who is expected to stress her interest in
health care in a likely New York Senate bid, spoke to several
medical experts, including Harold Koplewicz, the director of the
New York University Child Study Center, who talked about ways of
treating mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
