<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICAN-ANTIGONE-NYT &LR;      06-07 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-ANTIGONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AFRICAN `ANTIGONE,' PRESENTED IN PARIS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The underlying themes of the Greek tragedies have easily
survived the 25 or more centuries since the plays were written:
power versus morality; laws of man vs. laws of God; reasons of
state vs. reasons of the heart. Indeed, their very universality
makes them ever topical and easily adaptable, and that perhaps
explains why a West African version of Sophocles' ``Antigone'' has
just been presented to acclaim in Paris. The French-language
production, which will be touring Mali, Guinea and Senegal in the
coming weeks, remains true to the story of Antigone, who risks
death by defying King Creon's order that her brother be denied a
proper funeral. But there are twists: here the actors are dressed
in ornate and colorful African gowns and use the formal gesture of
tribal ritual, while the role of the chorus is supplemented by
African chants and musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The text, prepared by Jean-Louis Sagot-Duvauroux and Habib
Dembele, has also been adapted to add a few moments of humor and,
above all, to make the play even more topical. It develops a theme
only touched on by Sophocles, that Creon finds Antigone's
disobedience all the more intolerable because she is a woman. ``So
you have decided that I am no longer the man?'' he asks her
indignantly. ``So, from now on you, you are the man?''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that women represent the voice of reason is underlined
by having five women serve as the chorus and by giving a woman,
Helene Diarra, the crucial role of Tiresias, the blind seer who
warns Creon that disaster will befall him if he insists on
condemning Antigone to death. Finally, after his son Haemon and his
wife, Eurydice, commit suicide, the chorus tells him that this is
his punishment for not following the path of women.
</P>
<P>
   Sophocles did not go that far (his final admonition was about
arrogance of power), but he certainly pointed the way. ``It is
better to fall from power, if it is so fated, by a man's hand than
we be called weaker than women,'' Creon tells Haemon when he begs
for Antigone's life in Sophocles' play. Minutes later, Creon again
scorns his son with ``Poor creature, submitting to a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its West African trappings, then, this version holds
firm to universal messages. This was certainly the aim of the new
Mandeka Theatre in Bamako, Mali, when it chose ``Antigone'' for its
inaugural production. It wanted a play that it could adapt and
export so that classical theater could be seen in West Africa and
West African theater could be seen abroad.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this experiment is Sotigui Kouyate, 63, an
actor from Burkina Faso who for 15 years has been a member of Peter
Brook's Paris-based experimental theater company. Kouyate not only
directs this production and plays the central role of Creon but
also is the driving force in creating a company of actors at the
Mandeka Theatre. He was able to recruit some experienced actors,
including Dembele and Ms. Diarra, but he also looked for new
talent. For one, Djeneba Kone, the beautiful young actress who
plays Antigone, is a newcomer to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Given the poverty of Mali, it was inevitable that the company
would have to look to an array of French sources to finance the
production. As a result, this ``Antigone'' has been seen in France
_ in Paris, it was presented at the Theatre des Bouffes du Nord,
Brook's permanent home _ before West Africa. And while here the
company has been trying to raise money from the public so that West
African schoolchildren and students can also see the play. A
donation of the equivalent of $5 will pay for one ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Still, perhaps most important for the new company's morale is
that the production played to full houses here and was applauded
not as an expression of African folklore but as an original
interpretation of a classical play. It was helped by the
coincidence of a Paris production of a different Sophocles play,
``Oedipus Rex,'' which was far less well received by French
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Kouyate's choice of a Greek tragedy also proved surprisingly
suited to the stylized rituals of West African village life. The
Mandeka Theatre ``has carried the story toward the African custom
of storytelling where the chants, music and commentaries directed
at the audience form an integral part of the action,'' wrote Noelle
Moris, a theater critic, in the Paris daily Liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Sagot-Duvauroux, who a decade ago wrote both a play and
screenplay dedicated to Toussaint L'Ouverture, the rebel Haitian
slave leader, said this storytelling tradition corresponded to the
structure of the ancient tragedies by giving the chorus the
importance it deserves. Similarly, he noted, the formality of the
play made it possible to use West African hand gestures, including
expressions of respect for elders, without sliding into what he
called ``ethnographic transposition.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer said that one reason for emphasizing the man-woman
confrontation in his version was that it seemed more credible today
than arguments over funeral rites. ``But in some aspects,'' he
said, ``notably marriage ceremonies and the weight of male power,
but also the entrenched tradition of female autonomy, West Africa's
societies and cultures are in harmony with the tragic debate that
prompts Antigone to challenge Creon.''
</P>
<P>
   Brook, whose blessing of productions in his theater is not
always assured, said that Kouyate had gone ``to the heart'' of
Greek tragedy. ``In this production, it is not we who are
transported to another era,'' he said. ``On the contrary, it is
another era that suddenly is present, and we live it with the
actors as if for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for one hour 50 minutes one recent evening, the Theatre
des Bouffes du Nord seemed closer to Africa than Greece, closer to
Bamako than Thebes. The language was French (although some chants
were in the Malian tribal language of Bambara), but the costumes,
the movements, at times even the humor, were definitely African.
Indeed, after the final curtain on the last performance here, the
show went on. An African band took over the cafe next to the
theater and the dancing began.
</P>
<P>
   This, perhaps, Sophocles did not have in mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
