<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6524 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-PRISONERS-BOS &LR;      06-07 0173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-PRISONERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATINGS, FEAR OF DEATH IN CRAMPED SERB PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for clients)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA, Albania _ On Saturday, Niman Kurti was in a Kosovo
prison, crammed in with hundreds of other ethnic Albanian men who
say they were being beaten and nearly starved.
</P>
<P>
   Kurti had no idea that two days earlier, Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milsevic had signed an a NATO-imposed peace plan that
promised he would begin pulling out military forces from the
province and allow Kosovar refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
   He had no idea where his family was, or whether he would survive
his internment at Smrkovnica Prison, near Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   He said Monday he had been crammed against a wall with other
Albanian men when he overheard one of the guards saying to a
colleague, ``We must do something with them immediately, because we
don't know what's going on with them tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurti froze. He thought the guards were plann
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
