<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 06/07/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SPARTANBURG, S.C. -- June 7, 1999 --
HANDICAPPED-CYCLIST-NYTR, 6-7 -- Van Epps, 35, of Spartanburg,
became the first person riding an arm-powered cycle to qualify for
the prestigious 750-mile Paris-Brest-Paris in France. The bicycle
ride through France, which is held every four years, begins on Aug.
23. Because of its length, it is considered one of the toughest
cycling events in world. (Tammi Tuten/Spartanburg Herald-Journal
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- June 7, 1999 -- MEDICARE-CLINTON, 6-7 -- John
and Mary Greenan in November 1998, with documents mailed by their
health insurance company which informed them they were being
dropped from the health plan. President Clinton will soon propose
revamping the Medicare program to offer prescription drug coverage
to all beneficiaries, and he will contend that such coverage can
actually save money for the government by reducing the need for
hospital stays and nursing home care, Administration officials said
on Monday. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MEXICO CITY -- June 7, 1999 -- MEXICO-BIRTH-2, 6-7 --
Emma Castro Amador, points to a photograph of her family in her
home. Like many old-style Mexican matriarchs, Mrs. Castro bore so
many children that she cannot keep their birthdays straight.
However in a generational divide repeated in millions of Mexican
families, all 14 say they are determined to limit their own
families to two or three children. (Keith Dannemiller/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- June 7, 1999 -- HEAT-WAVE-2, 6-7 -- New York
City Transit electricians George Vanderhoef, left, and Frank Guzzi
cool off after working on a refurbishment project near the
Williamburg Bridge on Monday. Temperatures soared into the 90s
Monday across much of the East, making it too hot and too sticky
too early in the season. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) JAZINCE, Macedonia -- June 7, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
6-7 -- Residents leave their village on Monday which lies near the
border with Kosovo after it was shelled by Yugoslav forces.
Macedonian government officials said that more than thirty rounds
were fired into this border village by Yugoslav forces Sunday night
from inside Kosovo. The attack was the most serious eruption of
violence along the Kosovo-Macedonia border since NATO's bombing of
Yugoslavia began in late March. (Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KUKES, Albania -- June 7, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 6-7 --
Selmon Limoni, a 75-year-old ethnic Albanian refugee from Kosovo,
watches the sunset near a refugee camp near the border with Kosovo.
Like several other Kosovars seeking refuge in the border town,
Limoni said that NATO should send ground troops into Kosovo, even
without an agreement with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) TRENTON, N.J. -- June 7, 1999 -- WHITMAN-CONSERATIVES,
6-7 -- Governor Christie Todd Whitman of New Jersey talks with
fifth graders from Bais Faiga Elementary School in Lakewood, N.J.,
during their visit to the State Capitol on Monday. A year before
the formal start of her race for the United States Senate, Mrs.
Whitman is already facing a stern political test from conservatives
who have threatened to withhold their crucial support unless she
accommodates them on issues as varied as abortion rights to
restrictions on tattoos for teen-agers. (Laura Pedrick/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON, Mass. -- June 7, 1999 -- HEAT-WAVE, 6-7 -- Nelson
Hastings, 5, attempts to drink from a fountain in Walnut Park on
Monday where his day care class headed to escape the heat.
Temperatures soared into the 90s Monday across much of the East,
making it too hot and too sticky too early in the season. (Pam
Berry/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MEXICO CITY -- June 7, 1999 -- MEXICO-BIRTH, 6-7 -- Emma
Castro Amador, seated, with her children and grandchildren in her
home. Like many old-style Mexican matriarchs, Mrs. Castro bore so
many children that she cannot keep their birthdays straight.
However in a generational divide repeated in millions of Mexican
families, they 14 say they are determined to limit their own
families to two or three children. (Keith Dannemiller/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 7, 1999 -- CARRIERE, 6-7 -- Jean-Claude
Carriere in Manhattan last April. Carriere, who has written
screenplays for Luis Bunuel and Peter Brook and adapts the works of
others, also writes plays. His comedy ``La Terrasse'' opens Tuesday
at the Manhattan Theater Club. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MORINI, Albania -- June 7, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 6-7 --
An exhausted and dehydrated ethnic Albanian refugee from Kosovo is
helped across the border into Albania on Monday. Refugees continued
to cross into Albania on Monday as a stalemate over details on
withdrawing Serb troops from Kosovo delayed a final agreement to
end the conflict in the region. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- June 7, 1999 -- MENTAL-HEALTH-CONFERENCE,
6-7 -- President Clinton, with his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton,
waves to participants at the conclusion of the White House
conference on mental health on Monday at Howard University. In the
background is Vice President Al Gore and his wife Tipper. The two
first couples were together again, pushing for parity in mental
health insurance coverage. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) JAZINCE, Macedonia -- June 7, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
6-7 -- Asdiselam Mastefa stands under a hole in his roof on Monday
caused by Serb shelling of the area on Sunday. More than 50 shells
fired from Yugoslavia fell on the territory of Macedonia during the
last three days, the Macedonian interior ministry said Monday.
(Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 7, 1999 -- ENRIQUE-MARTINEZ-2, 6-7 --
Elisa Sanchez, owner of the fashion house Enrique Martinez, models
an outfit from the upcoming fall collection. Enrique Martinez, a
new fashion company from Mexico, will be opening its doors on
Madison Avenue this summer. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 7, 1999 -- ENRIQUE-MARTINEZ-1, 6-7 --
Elisa Sanchez, owner of the fashion house Enrique Martinez, models
some dresses from the upcoming evening wear collection. Enrique
Martinez, a new fashion company from Mexico, will be opening its
doors on Madison Avenue this summer. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 7, 1999 -- HEROIN, 6-7 -- Michael
Donovan, left, and Dr. Sandra Comer showing how they monitor heroin
addicts through a one-way mirror. A staff member sat in as a drug
user. Taking a bold approach to addiction, re searchers at Columbia
University are offering free heroin to addicts and paying them to
use it under a federally authorized program aimed at finding a cure
for their drug habits. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
