<SLUG> BC-LAZARD-REORG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZARD FRERES REPLACES ITS TOP U.S. EXECUTIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lazard Freres &AMP; Co., the boutique investment banking
partnership, announced plans on Monday to integrate its London,
Paris and New York operations and to reshuffle its executive ranks
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are significant for the elite private firm. Though
highly profitable, Lazard has fallen behind rivals like Goldman,
Sachs and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in the lucrative business of
advising top executives on strategy. The integration of Lazard's
European and American operations, long noted for proud
individualism, seems intended in part to compete with the fluid
global networks of other investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the overhaul, William R. Loomis Jr., 51, will replace
Steven Rattner, 47, as deputy chief executive and the firm's top
day-to-day executive in the United States. Rattner, who held the
post for two years, will remain with the firm as vice chairman but
has indicated to colleagues that he may pursue outside interests.
</P>
<P>
   The moves by the firm were reported on Monday by The Wall Street
Journal.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rattner decided to step aside on his own, several people at the
firm said, rather than take on the increased administrative duties
involved in merging Lazard's international operations. A longtime
contributor to the Democratic Party, Rattner has been an active
supporter of Vice President Al Gore. But Monday he played down the
possibility of leaving Lazard to join Gore's campaign for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep all my options open,'' Rattner said. ``But to
paraphrase Mark Twain, reports of my departure are wildly
premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Michel A. David-Weill, Lazard's chairman and chief executive,
said that the integration of the three Lazard units should be
completed within six months. He said in an interview that partners
based in New York, London and Paris, who now divide the profits
generated by their individual units, would share the profits pooled
from the three units. The units will also do more to share
expertise and specialist bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating the only true international partnership in our
business,'' David-Weill said. ``It will not be French, American or
British, but rather a global partnership built on a common
philosophy of independent advice for clients.''
</P>
<P>
   David-Weill's family has controlled the 151-year-old Lazard
franchise for generations. Though people at the firm say that
David-Weill, who is 66, does not play a hands-on role _ he spends
nearly the entire summer in the south of France _ he has sometimes
intervened to change managers and has long pushed to get the three
units to cooperate more.
</P>
<P>
   That task has been difficult. A private partners meeting last
fall to discuss measures to integrate concluded without a solid
decision to do so, people close to the firm said. Lazard partners
in New York have resisted integrating with their European
counterparts because they take home more money each year on average
than partners in London or Paris and are reluctant to share their
profits.
</P>
<P>
   But that territorial approach has become increasingly
anachronistic. Nearly every other major investment bank has long
since established seamless global operations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Goldman, Sachs, the last bulge-bracket investment bank
_ that is, one with substantial activity in all global banking
areas _ that still operated on the partnership model, recently went
public. Resistance at Lazard has broken down in recent months,
people there said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The necessity of it is now perceived throughout the whole
organization, in a real fashion,'' said David-Weill, who has worked
to bring the houses together since 1975, when he replaced his
father as head of Lazard in Paris. ``When people are all convinced,
it's time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Loomis will be the key executive overseeing worldwide
cooperation for the firm. A graduate of Williams College and
Harvard Business School and a Lazard partner for 15 years, Loomis
has had several responsibilities in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Loomis was the clear and obvious choice to succeed Steve
Rattner,'' David-Weill said, adding that he regretted Rattner's
decision to relinquish his post. ``We would have preferred to have
Steve remain as deputy chief executive, but we understand and
respect his desire to step back from his operating responsibilities
as we begin the next phase of consolidating our worldwide
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   During Rattner's run as deputy chief executive in 1997 and 1998,
the firm posted record profits. Earnings grew 40 percent in 1998, a
tough year for many other investment banks. But Lazard has slipped
a bit in the rankings of mergers and acquisition advice, its core
business, dropping to tenth last year worldwide from fourth place.
Its performance in this year's first quarter was stronger, with
Lazard benefiting from a wave of mergers in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has experienced management turmoil in recent years,
including the departure of several leading bankers. Among them was
Rattner's predecessor, Felix Rohatyn, a Wall Street legend who
helped save New York City from bankruptcy in the 1970s. He is now
the United States ambassador in France.
</P>
<P>
   Rattner has sought to institute a corporate overlay to the
partnership, with mixed success, people there said. The firm now
plans to set up an international, seven-person executive committee
to coordinate activities at all its operations. The members of that
committee were not named Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even as chief executive, Rattner continued to be one of Lazard's
top deal makers. He has recently advised clients including Comcast,
America Online, Starbucks and The New York Times and will continue
to serve as a senior banker.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Lazard has taken steps to bring its houses closer
together. The last significant reorganization of the three banks
was in 1996, when the firm began pooling some profits to share
among partners worldwide. Last year, Lazard Asset Management merged
with Lazard Brothers Asset Management in London and Lazard Japan
Asset Management in Tokyo, a move now seen as a model for
integrating the investment banking operations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
