<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CUPLESS-TEX </SLUG>
 
WANTING THEIR FIRST STANLEY CUP KEY TO SEVERAL STARS (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DALLAS _ Two inches, maybe less. That's all that separated Stars
captain Derian Hatcher from his lifelong dream.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He remembers thinking that if he just extended his fingertips
he'd be able to grab hold, to touch the Stanley Cup. It was right
there, cradled like an infant in his childhood friend Shawn
Chambers' arms.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, now a Stars defenseman, had been along for New
Jersey's Cup-winning season in 1995, and as dictated by tradition,
he had his day to do whatever he wanted with the Cup. Chambers
decided to hold a party in the house where he had grown up and on
the street where he and Hatcher had played so many games of street
hockey together.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers urged Hatcher to rub the shiny metal for luck, to have
his photo taken as they had always dreamed of doing as boys, to
just reach out and touch the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never touched it. I never picked it up,'' Hatcher said. ``It
really wasn't a superstitious thing. It was that I didn't win it. I
realized that one day I'd have a chance to win it, and I'd pick it
up then.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Hatcher finds himself so close to the Cup that he
can almost reach out and touch it. Four victories, and he will. It
will be his party and his right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely exciting,'' Hatcher said, the smile spreading
across his face.
</P>
<P>
   With all that has been said about the Stars' Cup experience _
eight players already have their names engraved on the Cup with
other teams _ the Stars' players who have never won the Cup might
be the key in getting the Stars' organization its first.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is something to be said for winning it. Former Cup
winners Guy Carbonneau, Craig Ludwig and Joe Nieuwendyk will tell
you there is nothing more motivating than holding the Cup while
skating around the rink after the Stanley Cup-clinching game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I remember,'' said Nieuwendyk, who last touched the
Cup with Calgary in 1989. ``I was also a young guy when I went
through this 10 years ago, and I don't think I had the appreciation
of it like I do now, whether it's just age or having gone through
the wars of 10 more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Ludwig described it: ``There's a lot of us who know what
it's like at the end of the rainbow, and we want that back. For a
few of us, we know we don't have many kicks of the can left. To us,
this is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   But, there is also something to be said for wanting it. Stars
players Ed Belfour, Darryl Sydor and Mike Modano, among others,
will tell you there is nothing quite as motivating as getting close
then having to watch somebody else hold the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour went to a Stanley Cup Finals in 1992, but his Chicago
Blackhawks were swept by Pittsburgh. Sydor went to a Stanley Cup
Finals with the Los Angeles Kings in 1993, winning Game 1 in
Montreal, only to lose the next four.
</P>
<P>
   Modano went with the Stars in 1991, back when they were the
North Stars and located in Minnesota. He says he hasn't forgotten
that feeling of being, like Hatcher, so close and yet unable to
reach his hand and grab it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream about it and think about it when you are alone,''
said Modano, whose team lost 8-0 to Pittsburgh in the sixth and
final game of the series. ``The anticipation of having the
opportunity, the chance to be here and play for it since \Rthen\S.
It's been something we've all been looking forward to and trying to
get to.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano turned 29 yesterday, and was in his first season when he
went to the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Dave Reid has been playing for 16 seasons now, and
this marks his first trip to the Finals. He has been to the
semifinals a couple of times, with Boston in 1992 and the Stars
last season.
</P>
<P>
   He says he hasn't allowed himself to think ahead to what he
would do if the Stars were to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' Reid said. ``I remember playing with my brothers,
street hockey, table-top hockey, anything to do with hockey, and we
were always playing for the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   He finally saw the Cup in person not too long ago. He didn't
touch it, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really an unwritten rule,'' Stars winger Pat Verbeek
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek had a chance to touch it. He was 17. His father wanted
to get a photo with him and the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said no,'' Verbeek said. ``I didn't want to get a picture
with it until I had a chance to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years have passed, and Verbeek has never been as close
as he was that day. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent 16 years trying to get this far,'' said Verbeek,
who was a victory away from a berth in the Stanley Cup Finals in
1988 with New Jersey, which lost to Boston, 6-2. ``You've got to
make the best of it while you're here because you may never get
another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is something to be said for winning it. But, there is
also something to be said for wanting it.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek has wanted to hold the Stanley Cup ever since he was a
little boy in the back yard pretending he played for the Boston
Bruins. And at the end of a long game, he thrust his arms in the
air, pretending the Cup was there.
</P>
<P>
   It was a childhood moment shared by guys like Modano and Hull
and Belfour and Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's within their grasp. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
