<HEADLINE>
AFFORDABLE SPAS  
 HEADING TO SARDINIA  
 PUERTO RICO SUMMER EVENTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like to go to a spa for a week or so to work on my
weight and fitness, but most seem to be very expensive. Are there
any that are more affordable? _ C.M. Kulwin, Upper Montclair, N.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The popularity of spas is based on pampering at least as much
as sweating, so prices are going to reflect that. But if you
consider less than $1,000 reasonable for a week's accommodations,
three meals a day and exercise and relaxation programs, there are a
few places in the Northeast that fit the bill, at least outside of
peak season. The three here offer shorter stays, too.
</P>
<P>
   At Deerfield Spa, in Marshall's Creek, Pa., near East
Stroudsburg, double-occupancy rates range from $799 to $970 a week
(plus 6 percent tax and a 15 percent service charge) and include
two half-hour massages. Heather McMahon, a spokeswoman, said that
the spa features low-fat cuisine and that exercise programs range
from a ``boot camp'' experience to Pilates to aquatic aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   The spa has a gym for strength training, an outdoor heated pool,
hot tub and sauna. A naturalist leads hikes on Pocono trails.
</P>
<P>
   Deerfield accepts up to 33 guests for what Ms. McMahon described
as a ``nonchalant, not ostentatious'' program. Most guests stay in
the three-floor main house in rooms decorated country style, with
lots of floral prints. A one-story annex has larger rooms, two with
king-size beds. Deerfield is open April to mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Deerfield at 650 Resica Falls Road, East Stroudsburg,
Pa. 18301; (800) 852-4494, fax (570) 223-8270; or
www.deerfieldspa.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vatra Mountain Valley Lodge and Spa is on 15 acres at the base
of Hunter Mountain in the Catskills. Exercise options include a
variety of aerobics, aqua fitness, yoga and dance. There is a
fitness room and tennis, volleyball and basketball courts.
</P>
<P>
   The spa has 27 rooms with televisions and phones, some with
balconies and skylights. Meals are vegetarian totaling up to 1,200
calories a day. Weekly guests get four 30-minute massages in the
$978 to $1,290 rates, which include all fees and taxes. Other
treatments, which are extra, include seaweed wraps ($75) and a
European facial ($60)
</P>
<P>
   Vatra Mountain, Route 214, Post Office Box F, Hunter, N.Y.
12442; (800) 232-2772, fax (518) 263-4994.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Catskills is New Age Health Spa, where, says
Patricia Fahie, director of marketing, most guests seek stress
reduction. But it offers fitness classes and for the seriously
overweight a program meant to lead to the loss of 50 pounds or
more.
</P>
<P>
   A typical day at the spa might include Zen meditation, an
aerobic walk, water aerobics and yoga or tai chi. The spa features
a 50-foot Alpine tower for climbing while wearing a harness. There
are Trotter strength machines, free weights and cardio equipment,
and indoor and outdoor pools. A variety of salon services cost
extra.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly double rates are $855 to $1,064 a person, plus 8 percent
tax and 17 percent service charges. Here and at Deerfield (but not
at Vatra), singles can be assigned a roommate. New Age, Neversink,
N.Y. 12765; (800) 682-4348, fax (914) 985-2467;
www.newagehealthspa.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am planning a trip to Sardinia this fall. What is the best
way to get there from Italy and what are some important sites? _
V.M. Palacios, Staten Island, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Going to Sardinia should be easier in the fall than in
summer. The chances are the crystal-clear waters will still be warm
enough to swim in and there won't be the crush of tourists that
flock to the beautiful beaches, especially on the Emerald Coast in
the north, in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the beaches, the island's capital, Cagliari, in the
south, is worth a visit for its 13th century cathedral, national
archeological museum and a Roman amphitheater. Sassari, the second
largest city, has a medieval center, and 11 miles away is the
12th-century Camaldulian abbey.
</P>
<P>
   The inland areas are rural and hold many ruins. Remnants of the
nuraghi, cone-shaped fortified tower houses made from massive
stones well before the birth of Christ, dot the interior. Some of
the most interesting of these are at Barumini, about 35 miles north
of Cagliari.
</P>
<P>
   Alitalia, (800) 223-5730, flies to Cagliari from most major
Italian cities. There are at least eight daily flights from Rome,
for example, costing about $210 round trip, at 1,868 lira to $1. A
regional airline, Meridiana, (800) 275-5566, flies to Olbia as well
as Cagliari from Rome, Milan and other cities, for about $100 each
way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to take a ferry. Among the major lines is
Tirrenia Navigazione, which has an overnight ferry from
Civitavecchia, near Rome, to Cagliari each evening at 6:30. It also
has a three-and-a-half-hour hydrofoil crossing at 8:30 a.m.; a
round-trip ticket is about $85. According to the Italian government
Tourist Board, it's best to call the Naples office for
reservations: (39-081) 720-1111, fax (39-081) 720-1441.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian State Railway runs ferries to Olbia, a board
spokeswoman said, for about half Tirrenia's prices. Tickets must be
bought at railroad stations, though. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Could you tell me what cultural events are on the schedule in
Puerto Rico in July and August? _ Phyllis Mate, Brooklyn, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A couple of summer highlights on the island involve lively
music and dance. From July 26 to 31, the World Salsa Congress will
spice up El San Juan Hotel and Casino in Isla Verde. Richard
Goenaga, general manager of the congress, said that the event
focuses on the dancers, coming from 32 countries to show off
different styles. Each night at least three top bands will play, as
well. Nightly tickets are $40, a four-night pass $150. For more
information, call (787) 274-1601.
</P>
<P>
   The Loiza Carnival, July 23 to Aug. 1, is an annual celebration
of the African heritage of the northeastern town of Loiza. Besides
parades, it features performances of the bomba, the lively
Afro-Caribbean dance form. Free; (787) 876-3570.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional music and dance is also part of the Tourism Artisans
Fair, July 30 to Aug. 1 at Plaza de la Darsena and Paseo de la
Princesa in Old San Juan. This free event will include several folk
dance and singing performances, and will bring together more than
200 artisans showing and selling their crafts.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about these and other events on the island,
including the many town patron-saint festivals, contact the New
York office of the Puerto Rico Tourism Co. at (800) 233-6530, or
see www.prtourism.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
