<HEADLINE>
CHINA SEEKS TO WIN OVER DISSENTERS ON JOINING TRADE GROUP
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China's top trade official, acknowledging for
the first time that many lower-level Chinese officials oppose the
nation's proposed entry to the World Trade Organization, said in
newspaper reports published on Monday that the government would
begin a broad campaign to try to temper the internal discord.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Wu Yi, said the government was preparing a report
to explain why China should join the organization that sets the
rules for global commerce. She said that a series of meetings was
planned for senior officials and leaders of state enterprises to
explain the status of negotiations and solicit opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wu is a member of China's Cabinet, with responsibility for
trade issues. Her comments, printed in the China Market Economy
News and other government-run publications, appeared to mark a
distinctly new public approach to the effort to join the trade
organization, by seeking to assuage internal opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Beijing's stance has been to pretend no opposition
existed, even though many Chinese officials are known to be unhappy
at the prospect of more open competition with international
companies, one of the consequences of joining the trade
organization.
</P>
<P>
   As relations between China and the United States were battered
in the political furor that followed NATO's bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade on May 7, supporters of trade organization
entry became vulnerable to accusations that China was giving away
too much to demands from Americans, who were demonized as China's
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's report, Ms. Wu used a more humble tone than in
previous public discussions, arguing that since negotiations are
still under way, Chinese leaders can still change proposals that
have been made in negotiations with American officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody feels it is unacceptable, that America's price is
too high, then we can withdraw'' the proposals, Ms. Wu said at a
meeting in Shanghai in May, the report said. ``It is possible to
make a fresh start again.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond sounding a conciliatory note to those who oppose
membership in the trade organization, Ms. Wu's comments also
contained an implicit warning to American negotiators not to push
China too hard, since internal support for membership is delicate.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, China's leadership has insisted that it was unanimous
in desiring to enter the trade organization, and has not wavered in
the 13 years it has sought membership.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Ms. Wu said that the central committee of the Communist
Party had carefully weighed the pros and cons of entry in the trade
organization, suggesting that objections had been raised
internally, before finally deciding in favor of entry. Ms. Wu has
spoken forcefully in support of Prime Minister Zhu Rongji's
position that China needs to join the trade organization, which
would open vast new markets to Chinese exports as well as granting
greater foreign business access to China's 1.2 billion consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wu's comments appear to reflect the leadership's confidence
that different opinions can now be discussed openly. It is unlikely
the leadership would publicly start a campaign it did not think it
could win.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most surprising element in Monday's report was Ms.
Wu's pointed mention that senior officials from China's
telecommunications industry would be invited to briefings on trade
organization negotiations, since they are known to be among the
strongest opponents of entry.
</P>
<P>
   Wu Jichuan, China's minister of telecommunications, submitted
his resignation earlier this year in an intense bureaucratic battle
with Prime Minister Zhu. After contradictory public statements
about Wu's status, he has officially remained in his position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
