<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH CONGLOMERATE TO ACQUIRE FILM PRODUCTION COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Vivendi SA of France is to acquire Pathe SA, France's
biggest film producing and distribution company, for $2 billion in
stock, in a complex deal that promises to push forward the
consolidation already under way in the European television
business.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced on Monday in Paris, tightens Vivendi's grip
on Canal Plus, its television affiliate, and gives it a 17 percent
stake in British Sky Broadcasting, the television company
controlled by Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Messier, Vivendi's chief executive, said the company
wanted to be a ``major European player in pay television, and in
this context the stake in BSkyB is important.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal, and Messier's remarks, raised speculation that he
might attempt to restart negotiations to merge Canal Plus and
BSkyB, the two largest pay-for-view television companies in Europe,
which broke down earlier this year after Canal Plus demanded
management control. Officials at BSkyB declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Canal Plus rose nearly 7 percent Monday, BSkyB shares
rose 2.5 percent and Vivendi's share price rose a half percent.
Pathe shares were suspended from trading.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal will give Vivendi, a $35 billion conglomerate that
derives most of its profit from utilities, full control of Pathe.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms, the family of Pathe's chief executive, Jerome
Seydoux, which until now owned a controlling share in Pathe, will
subsequently buy back Pathe's film business and shares in the Paris
daily Liberation and a French soccer team. Vivendi then gets
Pathe's shares in a Canal Plus satellite television venture,
CanalSatellite, and in BSkyB, and the Seydoux family holding
company, Fornier SA, will then be renamed Pathe. Messier, the
42-year old executive who reorganized Vivendi after taking control
in 1996, when it was known as Generale des Eaux, said the deal was
``good for Canal Plus shareholders, and notably for the most
important of them, Vivendi.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Lescure, chief executive of Canal Plus, told reporters in
Paris that the link would enable Canal Plus to cooperate with BSkyB
in developing services, most notably for the Internet, but he did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The pay-for-view television market in Europe is valued at $10
billion and is expected to double by the year 2005. In recent
months, Murdoch has made sporadic attempts to negotiate with Canal
Plus, but the most recent effort collapsed in March over management
control. Earlier, Messier had increased Vivendi's stake in Pathe,
and through it in BSkyB, to exert greater influence on any deal
with Murdoch, who owns 40 percent of BSkyB.
</P>
<P>
   BSkyB is the biggest pay-for-view broadcaster in Britain, with 7
million subscribers, but Murdoch's efforts to move onto the
Continent have met less success. In March, Murdoch opted not to
join a deal between the Kirch group of Germany and Fininvest, the
television holding company of Silvio Berlusconi. In April, the
British government blocked BSkyB's planned $1 billion takeover of
Manchester United, the soccer team at the forefront of European
sports marketing.
</P>
<P>
   For Canal Plus, the benefit of a deal with BSkyB would be in
avoiding a costly battle for market share, especially at a time
when it is digesting major expansion moves, including the $1.2
billion takeover of the Dutch digital broadcaster Nethold. Last
year, Canal Plus reported net losses of $31 million, though it
expects to make money this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Murdoch will not play dead. In recent weeks, he signed a
deal giving News Corp. a stake in Stream, an Italian pay television
venture that competes with a Canal Plus affiliate, Telepiu, and won
a bidding war in Germany to broadcast soccer that gives him a
bridgehead into German pay television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
