<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY SEEKS TO BUY BALANCE OF INFOSEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a series of moves intended to expand its role on the
Internet, Walt Disney Co. confirmed on Monday that it was in talks
to buy the 57 percent of Infoseek that it does not already own.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the
company said only that it was in talks with Infoseek, an Internet
search service that has helped Disney set up Go Network, its own
Internet portal. It gave no details of any proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Disney also said that Jake Winebaum, who has headed
Disney's Internet operations, was leaving to start Ecompanies, an
incubator for Internet companies, with Sky Dayton, the chairman of
Earthlink Network Inc.
</P>
<P>
   John Tinker, an analyst at Bank of America Securities, called
the departure of Winebaum _ who oversaw the creation of Disney.com,
ABCNews.com and ABC.com _ a disappointment. But Tinker added that
Disney was somewhat protected because it would have a stake in
Ecompanies.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has apparently become eager to create an Internet
currency to buy and invest in new businesses. Buying the
outstanding 57 percent of Infoseek _ a stake worth about $1.5
billion on Monday _ would provide it with such a currency.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, Disney said it was considering acquiring
Infoseek's outstanding stock in exchange for shares of Disney. It
also said it was considering issuing a tracking stock that would
reflect the operations of both Infoseek and Disney's Internet
businesses, an indication that Disney planned to meld the two
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stocks are shares that belong to the parent company but
track the performance of underlying assets. Analysts say that
tracking stocks give the parent company more control over the
existing assets, a circumstance presumably preferable to Michael
Eisner, the Disney chairman, who tends to like to keep control over
his company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Infoseek rose $6.3125 Monday, to $43, as rumors of a
deal swept through Wall Street. Disney rose, too, up 25 cents a
share, to $30.875.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a tracking stock remains a somewhat unusual security, and
it has not been Disney's style to create spinoff companies with
unusual characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst said that the move signaled Disney's intense concern
about the weak performance of its own stock, which is off its
52-week high of $40.3125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
