<SLUG> BC-LA-CHARTER-MEASURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATIONS FOR L.A. CHARTER REFORM MEASURE HIT FRENZIED PACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The battle over reform of Los Angeles city
government climaxed Monday in a barrage of mailers, TV ads and more
controversy over funding of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   City Council members who spearheaded the fight against charter
reform with public employee unions attacked a late $50,000
contribution from the Los Angeles Times' parent corporation, Times
Mirror Co., to Yes on Measure 1 -- the ballot issue to be decided
by voters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism erupted even as Council President John Ferraro was
donating a second $50,000 from his officeholder account, which was
funded by political contributors, and Councilwoman Ruth Galanter
was giving $10,000 from hers to the opponents of charter reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a problem when a newspaper gets involved
because it makes you wonder if it affects the reporting of the
issue,'' said Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg. ``You wonder. Reporters
aren't allowed to get involved, but publishers are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the inimitable words of Samuel Clemens, you will have the
best government that money can buy,'' said Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Times spokesman David Garcia said the criticism was misplaced
since the donation came from the corporate entity and not the
newspaper directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is the newspaper, the other is the corporate entity,''
Garcia said. ``And it has no impact on the news coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times and Times Mirror are located in the same building in
downtown L.A. Records indicate the Times Mirror contribution was
made last Thursday, the same day Times Mirror Chairman and CEO Mark
Willes relinquished the role of publisher of the Times to
concentrate on corporate matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Times has strongly endorsed charter reform and previously
criticized the Daily News for giving $60,000 last year to the San
Fernando Valley petition drive to get a formal study of cityhood,
an issue that will only go before voters if the county Local Agency
Formation Commission orders a ballot measure. The Times has
strongly opposed possible secession by the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Among other significant late contributions was a $100,000
donation by Mayor Richard Riordan, who has organized an estimated
$1.5 million effort to win passage of a new charter to replace the
city's 75-year-old constitution that has been amended nearly 400
times.
</P>
<P>
   Also joining Riordan in backing the proposal was Michael Milken
and the Petersen Properties, each giving $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has been a longtime supporter of charter reform and
he's putting his money where his mouth is,'' said Deputy Mayor
Noelia Rodriguez, who is on a leave during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, it's not the money that should be the issue, but the
issue of charter reform and the future of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Disclosure last week of a $200,000 contribution from media and
entertainment mogul Rupert Murdoch, who owns Fox television and
20th Century Fox among many other properties, sparked fiery attacks
from council members, but the reaction to the Times Mirror
contribution was more subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original charter was reformed because big business tried
to control it,'' Councilman Mike Hernandez said. ``Riordan wasn't
around, but the L.A. Times was.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective it's not going to change the reality that
around the kitchen table, people aren't talking about charter
reform. And the reality is that ... that very few people will be
deciding the constitution to our city. I don't think those are
people who can be bought.'
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE EXTRA: Details of contributions to city political
campaigns, expected to be updated today, are available on the
Internet at www.cityofla.org/eth.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
