u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NYT     06-07 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOVES ARE OFF AS THE STANLEY CUP FINALS OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ On the eve of the Stanley Cup finals, the Dallas Stars
and Buffalo Sabres exchanged psychological thrusts and parries on
Monday. The Sabres talked about how those Stars cheat on face-offs
and how maybe the officials should be aware of it. The Stars
mentioned that Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek sometimes gets upset
when he is bumped and how maybe he should worry about the Stars'
bumping him _ legally, of course. And what about Mike Modano's
comments about the finals being anti-climactic?
</P>
<P>
   Amid the winks and the nudges and the tongues in the cheeks,
someone asked Stars Coach Ken Hitchcock about the entertainment
value of the championship round for an ice-bound, winter sport that
struggles for the sports spotlight in the heat of June. Some
critics have said that Dallas plays an effective but dull style by
emphasizing defense and that the Sabres play the same way. How will
this style help sell the game to casual viewers in the Sun Belt and
even up north? Hearing this, Hitchcock turned quite serious and
contrasted his sport with figure skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, this isn't going to be a series made for television,''
Hitchcock said. ``If you look for `Champions on Ice,' you're
watching the wrong game. This is going to be a hard-fought,
passionate contest, where ice is going to be defended very tough.
And it is going to be a series that is going to have both teams'
wills get extended to the max.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two teams as committed, it's going to make for
very emotional hockey. I don't know if that's going to go across
television. But if you are in the building, you are going to see
two teams passionately go at each other like no other series.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-of-seven-game series begins here Tuesday night in
Reunion Arena, with Game 2 here on Thursday night. Games 3 and 4
will be in Buffalo on Saturday and June 15. The Stars are heavily
favored because they were top-seeded over all, while the Sabres
were seventh-seeded in the East.
</P>
<P>
   By playing from October to the brink of summer, the National
Hockey League has tested the attention span of even its most
devoted fans. With four consecutive sweeps, the finals since 1994
have been anticlimactic. Modano, the Dallas center, said as much
last week, after the Stars ousted the Colorado Avalanche in seven
games in the Western finals. He was speaking about the perception
of others, but he also said he stopped watching the Eastern half of
the tournament after high-seeded teams like New Jersey and Ottawa
were upset.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Modano backtracked, saying that his comments were taken
out of context and that he did not mean to disparage the Sabres.
``It was nothing to light a fire under them,'' Modano said. ``I
don't want to get into a war of words. Grade me the way I play, not
the way I talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone certainly will. In that any motivational edge can help
an underdog, Dixon Ward made it clear that he and other Sabres were
aware of what Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the Dallas-Colorado round was the true
championship, Ward said: ``I didn't remember them pulling the
Stanley Cup out for that series. It doesn't matter to us. It's not
anticlimactic for us whatsoever. We've earned the right to play for
the Stanley Cup. Nobody's handed us anything. Nobody gave us a free
ride. We beat three very good hockey teams. Whatever people's
perceptions are, that's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for cheating on face-offs, Buffalo Coach Lindy Ruff brought
it up and captain Mike Peca amplified it. When asked about the
Stars' winning ways on the draws, Ruff said: ``The one thing they
are very good at is cheating on face-offs. We've got to be aware of
that. Sometimes, they don't get their stick down. We want both
players to have their sticks down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got Brian Skrudland. He cheats with the best of them.
He's been playing for 20-plus years; he's got a lot of experience
behind him. Obviously, it's a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca added: ``Like Lindy said, they've got a lot of experienced
cheaters on the face-offs. Our guys go in and put our sticks down
and have our feet in the right spot. We've just got to make sure
that we're either cheating a little bit ourselves or making the
linesmen aware of their guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland added some gamesmanship when talking about Hasek, the
best goalie in the sport, who has not fully recovered from a groin
injury and sometimes becomes upset when opposing forwards jostle
him. Skrudland, who carries a full bag of tricks from team to team,
recalled the third round of last spring's Eastern Conference finals
and how the Washington Capitals took the momentum from Buffalo
after an incident between Hasek and Petr Bondra of the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he was throwing his gloves at Petr Bondra last year and
people said, `Gee, that might have been the turning point,'''
Skrudland said. ``If it takes that, we'll do whatever we have to do
to win. Everything within the rules. We never cheat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
