<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-PRISONERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATINGS, FEAR OF DEATH IN CRAMPED SERB PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to restore missing portion)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA, Albania _ On Saturday, Niman Kurti was in a Kosovo
prison, crammed in with hundreds of other ethnic Albanian men who
say they were being beaten and nearly starved.
</P>
<P>
   Kurti had no idea that two days earlier, Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milsevic had signed an a NATO-imposed peace plan that
promised he would begin pulling out military forces from the
province and allow Kosovar refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
   He had no idea where his family was, or whether he would survive
his internment at Smrkovnica Prison, near Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   He said Monday he had been crammed against a wall with other
Albanian men when he overheard one of the guards saying to a
colleague, ``We must do something with them immediately, because we
don't know what's going on with them tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurti froze. He thought the guards were planning to kill him and
the other Albanian males, ranging in age from 12 to 85, in the
camp. After they reached Albania on Monday, they said they had been
systematically rounded up from villages near Mitrovica, separated
form their wives and children, and packed into the nearby
Smrkovnica prison.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 33-year-old Kurti was herded onto a bus with other
jailed men, beaten again, and then forced to walk across the border
into Albania. He was among the most recent refugees to arrive in
Albania at the Morina Pass, where every day for 10 days the former
prisoners, perhaps 2,000 to 3,000 of them by some estimates, have
been straggling over the border.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the prisoners, the flow of refugees has dwindled in
recent days, aid workers say. Immediately after the NATO bombing
began, refugees were streaming over the border at the rate of 1,000
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   With the war in its third month and three-quarters of a million
refugees now out of Kosovo, the sad men from the Smrkovnica Prison
are virtually the only refugees still arriving. And their stories
are perhaps more terrifying than those of their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The former camp inmates are gaunt, even skeletal, the result of
days or weeks of near starvation by their Serbian captors, they
said. Their bodies are marked with deep purple bruises, and many
have black eyes and split lips, the legacy of frequent beatings,
they said. They tell of being forced to squat for hours, then made
to stand _ which makes the knees buckle. Those who fell were beaten
badly, the men said.
</P>
<P>
   Meals consisted of two pieces of bread a day, sometimes served
with cold tea, according to accounts by dozens of men. On the way
to the feeding area, the men had to run to avoid being beaten by
the Serbs _ some of them police and some of them regular prison
guards, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Go to Bill clinton, he is protecting you,' and all
the time they were beating us,'' said Nexhat Kurti, 33, his jeans
so loose on his gaunt frame that they had to be tied in place with
a piece of string. His tank top did not disguise his sunken chest
and protuding ribs.
</P>
<P>
   At a refugee center in Kukes, the dazed men sat weakly in a tent
and lined up for a meal of milk, bread and a thick noodle soup _
the first real meal they had had in days or even longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nobody helps Mitrovica, everybody there will be dead in a
couple of days,'' said Nexhat Kurti, another prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   The prison is the only instance that human rights workers have
heard of involving large groups of people incarcerated in Kosovo.
Most refugees have told stories of summary execution, or more often
of being harassed, robbed, beaten and forced to leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, as many as 500 of the former prisoners are struggling
over the border pass every day, human rights workers said. The men
arrive dehydrated and undernourished and must pass through a border
station that has become increasingly dangerous in the past weeks
amid NATO bombing and fighting between Serb forces and fighters of
the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Loud booms and massive billows of black smoke were visible from
Morina Monday as NATO bombed nearby areas of Kosovo while Serbs and
the KLA exchanged gunfire and shelling nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The imprisonment of the Albanian men ``seems to have a pretty
consistent pattern,'' said Joanne Mariner, a researcher and lawyer
for Human Rights Watch, a private organization. Typically, the men
were separated from women and children and taken to one of two
Serbs schools for processing. They were then hustled to Smrkovnica,
where they were held for five days to several weeks and subjected
to abuse and starvation the entire time, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of it, supposedly, is to find out if they are UCK,''
she said, using the Albanian acronym for the KLA. The men were
forced to sign statements that they were ``terrorists'' in the
ethnic Albanian fighting force.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't sign, you were beaten like a criminal,'' said a
man who refused to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Serb guards brought their children _ young as seven
years old _ to view the men, choose which would be beaten, and
sometimes beat the Albanians themselves, former prisoners reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``One policeman said to his son, `Which one do you want to beat?
Choose.' And he chose me,'' said Ibish Ibishi, 28. ``The policeman
beat me, and said to his son, `Is that enough?' The son said `no _
a little more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are animals,'' Ibishi said, struggling to keep his
trousers up on his emaciated body.
</P>
</TEXT>
