<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves' new game is close to his heart
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Reeves will return this morning to Piedmont
Hospital's ``Intensive Care-Red,'' where last December he got a
second shot at living after quadruple-bypass heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, the Falcons coach will be the one playing
doctor. And he'll try not to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he'll tour the intensive care unit where he stayed
after his Dec. 14 surgery and visit patients, including a man who
had open-heart surgery Monday and doesn't know Reeves is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Then Reeves and cardiologist Charles Brown will share the
coach's story.
</P>
<P>
   One-hundred fifty people will be allowed in the Richard H. Rich
Auditorium to listen to Reeves explain how he ignored early warning
signs last season and nearly waited too long to alert medical
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Titled, ``The Half-time show: Straight from the Heart,'' the
noon discussion will be the first of eight around the nation over
the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The tour is sponsored by a pharmaceutical company and a public
relations firm. Reeves hopes he can help others avoid some of the
mistakes he made.
</P>
<P>
   And he hopes he can avoid getting as upset as he was at his news
conference the day he was discharged Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not as emotional as it was when I checked out,''
said Reeves, who also will visit hospitals in Boston, Chicago,
Washington, Nashville, Los Angeles and Dallas. ``All I've got to do
is talk about my experience. For example, a lot of people don't do
anything even when they find out their cholesterol is high. ``Mine
was 214 the day I went in. I've got it down to 135 now with the
medications I take, exercise and improving my diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who was approached about this tour after speaking to
heart patients at a Miami hospital in February, also will hand out
a pamphlet titled, ``Crossing the Goal-line: Dan Reeves' Playbook
for Surviving Heart Disease.''
</P>
<P>
   He's become very mindful of the fact that, according to the
American Heart Association, some 58.8 million people suffer from
some sort of cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down there (in Miami), it was a really unique experience
because you realized that we all had shared the same thing,''
Reeves said. ``This can be very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day after my surgery, at first it was amazing how much I
could do. I stood up and everything, but then just taking a shower
was so exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves still visits Brown about every two weeks, and he's
leading a largely normal life now _ if you don't count his diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chocolate, I loved. Lots of salad dressing. Lots of butter on
my bread,'' he said, thinking of the old days. ``Doughnuts for
breakfest instead of cereal.''
</P>
<P>
   That's changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surrounded in the office now by fruits in and out of
meetings,'' he said, not referring to his assistant coaches. ``I
rely more on the people around me and delegate more authority. The
message is when you suffer heart disease, your life is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
