<HEADLINE>
LIFE AFTER TOCCA 
AND NOW, `OPRAH' 
A FASHIONABLE EYE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFE AFTER TOCCA
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a good reason Marie-Anne Oudejans named her
new line of clothes Loch-Ness Couture. ``I've always liked
monsters,'' said Ms. Oudejans, who will show her collection of 21
evening looks on Tuesday afternoon at Julian Schnabel's West
Village studio. ``It also sounds mysterious.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oudejans, 34, is something of a mystery herself. A year ago,
she abruptly left Tocca, the fashion company whose sweet cotton
dresses established the Dutch-born Ms. Oudejans as a hip designer.
Tocca continued, but Ms. Oudejans seemed to drop from sight. ``To
be honest, when I left, it was personal,'' she said Monday,
explaining that instincts, more than anything, told her it was time
to move on. ``It's like a marriage: sometimes it's better to leave
before the relationship changes.'' Last December, Ms. Oudejans
said, she formally severed ties to Tocca, in which she was a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a year of globe-trotting and option-weighing (she
briefly toyed with the idea of designing a hotel interior), Ms.
Oudejans and her current business partner, Daniel Spoor, approached
Kashiyama USA, a licensing company, about producing a line of
evening clothes. ``At our first meeting, I told them, `I'm ready
now, and we won't talk about Tocca,''' Ms. Oudejans said with a
laugh. Apparently, a lot of people have been wondering what she
planned to do for an encore.
</P>
<P>
   Loch-Ness is a departure. The dresses, which will be made in
Italy and priced from $1,000 to $4,000, are classic, with high
collars and open backs, with just enough flesh to keep a modern eye
focused. The colors are cloudlike: pale gray, pink and beige. Ms.
Oudejans plans to produce three collections annually; this one will
be in stores in October.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ouedejans is a little anxious about how retailers will
respond to gowns that conjure up a hot night in Rome _ or wherever
her nomadic customers land. ``You know, they're going to be shocked
because the collection is really different,'' she said. ``But it's
another stage in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW, `OPRAH'
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Be honest: isn't there something marvelously nutty
about the prospect of Stefano Gabbana and Domenico Dolce _ the
Abbott and Costello of high fashion _ appearing on Oprah Winfrey's
show? The pair will be in Chicago next week to tape the show, to be
telecast on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what the designers have calculated is Ms. Winfrey's
mainstream appeal. If she can do for their over-the-top fashion
what she's done for books, there's no telling how many women will
be phoning in, saying, ``Get me Dolce &AMP; Gabbana.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone in Milan, where he and Dolce were working on
their spring men's wear collection, Gabbana said, ``We're very
aware that `Oprah' is one of the few vehicles to reach Middle
America.'' He added, with a laugh, ``I know what being on her show
can do for Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, yet, living in Italy, I don't think I
realize how huge it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally _ surprise, surprise _ Messrs. Gabbana and
Dolce will be on television the day before their ``new best pop
star'' client, Whitney Houston, opens a tour. They've produced
about 15 different looks (in triplicate) for Ms. Houston, who met
with the designers 10 days ago and selected outfits from their fall
collection, though she also ordered a few of their signature
stretch gowns, which she will wear with brightly colored fur
chubbies.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the designers dressed Madonna for a tour, but
``because of Whitney and Oprah together,'' Gabbana said, ``we'll
reach a different audience.''
</P>
<P>
   A FASHIONABLE EYE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Kenneth Paul Block retrospective at the Society
of Illustrators Museum, 128 East 63rd St., brings to mind Yves
Saint Laurent's famous phrase about ``the silence of fashion'' _
clothes that don't need to call attention to themselves. Block's
drawings of the chic and restless of the 1970s and early 1980's
show women who knew how to wear clothes, not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   A regular illustrator for Women's Wear Daily, Block has an eye
for fashion's absorbing little intimacies. In one drawing, he had
Diana Vreeland, Babe Paley and C.Z. Guest all wearing the same
Balenciaga coat. The show continues through June 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
