u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRIT     06-07 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA HOLDS BACK ON ENDORSING RESOLUTION TO END KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Inserts ``UNITED NATIONS'' in 1st graf; subs through graf 11
to clarify Russia's stance, update with quotes from Kofi Anan ) 
 (rm) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ After eight hours of negotiations, Russia
balked Monday at final approval of a resolution to be sent to the
United Nations Security Council to lay out the future of Kosovo and
the role of 50,000 NATO peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Russia does not want any of its troops to be under the control
of NATO, and insists that the United Nations have some role in the
peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas considerable progress was made, and the latest
stumbling blocks may be quickly resolved. Secretary General Kofi
Annan said at the United Nations on Monday night that he expected
the foreign ministers to agree on a resolution by Wednesday, and
expressed the hope that the Security Council would adopt it within
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should then move on with the troops,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators, especially Russia and the Europeans, want the
Security Council to approve such a resolution detailing the sketchy
document that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to last
week, which called for a U.N. role. The resolution is also meant to
give authority to the peacekeeping force and the civil
administration that is planned for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said he needed to
have further consultations with Moscow. The Russians, through their
emissary Viktor Chermonyrdin, helped secure the agreement last
week. But if they change their mind and block a NATO dominated
force, under U.N. authority, that would be a setback to the peace
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Military talks in Macedonia all but collapsed over the weekend,
and Monday were downgraded to low level officials.NATO had promised
to intensify its air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   NATO at first held back on carrying out threats to intensify its
bombing. Allied officials said they hoped that the restraint would
help persuade Russia to back the Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But there was NATO bombing in Kosovo near the Albanian border,
and at night, explosions and anti-aircraft fire were heard once
again in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   At the military talks, Yugoslavia asked to keep 15,000 of its
forces in Kosovo, an idea that the State Department rejected as
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official insisted that the draft
resolution satisifed the longstanding NATO demand that the
peacekeeping force have NATO ``at the core.'' The official said
that ``we're going to have unified command and control'' under
NATO, endorsed by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was told by Chernomyrdin and the Finnish President
Maarti Ahtisaari, that the phrase ``substantial NATO
participation'' in the document he agreed to last Thursday meant
``unified command and control,'' by NATO, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of Russian participation in the peacekeeping force
still remained unresolved. Moscow has said it will not allow its
soldiers to work under a NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's accord with President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia calls for all Yugoslav and Serbian police and military
to leave Kosovo. But Milosevic's troops appeared to be playing for
time in a last ditch effort ot drive ethnic Albanian guerrillas
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The stalling by the Russians and the refusal by the Yugoslavs to
negotiate seriously on the withdrawal left an uncertain atmosphere
over how and when the Kosovo plan would move forward.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Germany's defense minister, Rudfolf Scharping, described the
situation as ``very precarious'' Monday morning
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to propel the process forward, President Clinton
spoke by telephone with President Boris Yeltsin of Russia. As well,
the Finnish negotiator, Ahtisaari, who helped secure the accord
with Milosevic, flew to China Monday on a mission to convince the
Chinese not to block the Security Council resolution on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the lack of cooperation by the Russians on final
agreement of the draft, the foreign ministers reported that
considerable progress was made on major details.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the foreign ministers, including Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, decided that the civilian leader of
Kosovo would be a special representative of the secretary-general
of the United Nations, chosen by the secretary general, State
Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The draft resolution was informally circulated among members of
the Security Council in New York on Monday afternoon, Western
diplomats said here.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov promised to rejoin the other foreign ministers, who are
convening here under the auspices of the G-8 _ the seven richest
industrial countries and Russia _ on Tuesday morning for another
session. If the Russian said yes to the draft, the resolution could
be considered by the Security Council as early as Tuesday afternoon
in New York, officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   In a best case scenario, a Clinton administration official
traveling with Albright said Monday night that the momentum of the
security council resolution could put pressure on the Yugsolavs to
come to an arrangement with NATO for the withdrawal of their
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Once the withdrawal began, NATO would consider a suspension of
the bombing. These steps, one following the other, were described
by French officials as ``synchronization.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they had no quarrel with
the French notion. ``I would expect all this to happen relatively
quickly,'' an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials here said they were satisfied that the
draft resolution made clear that the peacekeeping force of 50,000
will have a unified NATO command and control structure. The word
NATO may not be spelled out in the resolution, an official said,
but one section of the draft says that the operation will be
``performed by member states and relevant international
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have insisted that the United Nations have some say
in the peacekeeping operation and it appeared, the official said,
that this demand could be satisfied by the supreme commander of
NATO, Gen. Wesley Clark, making a written report to the United
Nations Security Council over specific periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already crossed the Rubicon that it will not be run by
the United Nations,'' the State Department spokesman, Rubin, said
of the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow is unwilling to have its troops work under a NATO
command.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has made clear that it would be happy
for Russian soldiers to participate in the peacekeeping force under
the same arrangements that prevail in Bosnia. There, the Russians
report to an American commander who is not the chief NATO commander
in that force. ``We'd like to see them participate,'' Rubin said
Sunday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. ADDITIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The draft Security Council resolution, which has been a work in
progress for many weeks and was fine tuned paragraph by paragraph
Monday by the foreign ministers, laid out the responsibilities of
both the peacekeepers and the civil administration, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The list of duties of the peacekeepers included enforcing a
ceasefire, ensuring the withdrawal of Yugoslav and Serbian forces,
securing the return of the ethnic Albanian refugees, taking out the
mines placed by the Serb forces and preventing the return of those
forces.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping force, which will be dominated by European
soldiers and include 7,000 Americans, as well as soldiers from
non-NATO countries, would also patrol the borders, the draft
resolution says.
</P>
<P>
   The responsibilities of the civil administrator chosen by the
United Nations secretary general will include organizing elections
and policing operations. Under the terms of the agreement with
Milosevic, the Kosovo Liberation Army, is called on to disarm. That
agreement does not spell out what the ex-guerrillas would do, but
officials working on the Security Council resolution said they
would be encouraged to help form a new police corps.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the draft resolution dealt with new
documentation for returning refugees, many of whom had their
identification papers, passports, educational certificates and car
licenses taken from them when they were forced out by the Serbs.
But the new civil administration would have to deal with this
question as well as physical reconstruction of the burned homes and
properties.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution also dealt with compliance required with the war
crimes tribunal in The Hague by the new authorities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the European Union, Niko Wegter, said that
Russia had objected to the wording of the provision on the
tribunal. Milosevic, and four of his top aides including those who
ran operations in Kosovo, were indicted by the tribunal nearly two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that because the plan agreed to by Milosevic
called for kosovo to be cleared of all Serbian and Yugoslav forces
and paramilitaries, the question of the arrest of indicted
officials _ like Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic who remained in
Bosnia after the peace agreement _ was unlikely to arise.
</P>
<P>
   But asked if the peacekeeping force would have the mandate to
arrest indicted Serb and Yugoslav officials, a senior
administration official said he would not speculate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the planning on the resolution, there was still
nervousness among the foreign ministers' delegations about whether
Milosevic would give clear orders to his generals to move their
troops out of Kosovo or whether, even under NATO bombing, he would
chip away at the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari visited the foreign ministers Monday morning before
leaving for China and told them to move rapidly on finalizing the
United Nations council resolution, which is specifically called for
in the document that Milosevic agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish president also told the gathering he had spoken to
Milosevic Monday and was told by the Yugoslav leader that he
intended to abide by the plan he agreed to last week, an
administration official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
