<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ADS-COLUMN-1000(2T     06-07 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ADS-COLUMN-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: A SALES BONANZA FOR PRIME TIME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Wash.)   (jw) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the hottest phenomenon on television today? For the
public, it might well be a hit show like ``Ally McBeal'' or ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer,'' but for the broadcast networks, it is
something more fleeting: those brief interludes known as commercial
time.
</P>
<P>
   In a frantic period of negotiations, the sale of prime-time
commercial slots for the fall season _ known as the up-front market
_ is exceeding even the most optimistic forecasts made by top
television executives as recently as last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an extraordinary up-front this year,'' said David
Verklin, chief executive at the Carat North America media services
agency in New York, a unit of Aegis Group PLC that buys advertising
for marketers. ``If you blinked your eyes, you missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Network and advertising executives are projecting that up-front
sales by the six networks _ ABC, CBS, the Fox Broadcasting Company,
NBC, UPN and WB _ will climb at least 13 percent, to $7.25 billion,
from about $6.4 billion last year. Only a few weeks ago, they were
estimating a more moderate increase to a range of $6.8 billion to
$7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And broadcasters are enjoying increased sales for daytime, news
and late-night programs as well as for prime-time shows. Add the
revenue from those spots to the prime-time take and the total
up-front take could reach $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was a lot of money out there, but not that
much,'' said Paul Schulman, president of Schulman/Advanswers NY, a
media services agency in New York owned by the Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, the rivulet of advertising money from all those hot
Internet companies that have gone public lately could soon become a
flood, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising bonanza, fueled by a strong economy and a rush
by marketers to the medium that remains the quickest and surest
route to consumers' wallets, is confounding a longstanding
assumption that broadcast television is in an irreversible decline
as cable TV steals market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollars pouring in surprised both the networks and the
advertisers,'' said Peter Chrisanthopoulos, president for broadcast
and programming in the United States at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide
in New York, the giant agency owned by WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, a paradox: the broadcast networks' raking in
more money than ever even as they deliver fewer eyeballs to
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 season brought all-time low Nielsen ratings as only
one of the six broadcast networks, WB, owned by Time Warner Inc.
and the Tribune Co., attracted a larger audience than in 1997-98.
In the last five years, the audience share for the broadcast
networks has declined to 55 percent from 69 percent as cable
television draws more Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting that, the cable up-front market, now under way, is on
fire. There are estimates that the cable networks will sell $3.6
billion to $3.8 billion worth of commercial time ahead of their
1999-2000 season, compared with $2.8 billion for the 1998-99
season.
</P>
<P>
   So why the sudden surge in advertising dollars? There are a lot
of factors, but two stand out: the economy, and the power of being
No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   America's eight-year economic expansion, the second longest on
record, is one of the wonders of the 1990s. It has been largely
fueled by consumer spending, and that means, of course, that
companies have a powerful motivation to increase their advertising
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, for all the audience losses, all the
defections to cable and the Internet, all the problems of broadcast
television, there remains the salient fact that television is still
the most powerful influence on consumer behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television in general is the most impactful medium, the medium
that can sell clients' products best,'' Chrisanthopoulos at Ogilvy
&AMP; Mather said. ``The sight, the sound, the motion, the ubiquitous
nature of it makes it the most integral part of most clients' media
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast TV can still command huge audiences, even if they are
smaller than in the days when Desi loved Lucy, Archie loved Edith
and Sam loved Diane. And those audiences are much larger than those
commanded by any cable network.
</P>
<P>
   In a fractionalized media market, audience size is relative,
according to Verklin of Carat North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the land of dwarfs,'' as he put it, ``the 5-foot guy is the
center of the basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, about 127.5 million Americans saw Super Bowl
XXXIII on Fox in January. About 78 million people watched at least
part of the Academy Awards broadcast on ABC in March. And last
month, when the sitcom ``Home Improvement'' presented its series
finale, 35.5 million viewers came to watch ABC.
</P>
<P>
   That means that marketers both in traditional categories like
automobiles, financial services and retailing, and in booming
industries like telecommunications, computers and
electronic-commerce need to keep peddling their wares on the
broadcast networks. Indeed, advertising revenues, adjusted for
inflation, have been fairly strong in the last three years after
more than a decade of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to get to the mass audience,'' Schulman said,
broadcast TV ``is where you have to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For anybody introducing anything who has to lasso audience in
a hurry _ a new product, a new campaign, a new movie _ the networks
are still the biggest show in town,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments are, of course. music to the ears of the sales
executives at the broadcast networks. They prize their ability to
reach broader audiences than most cable networks, which appeal to
narrower audiences with their focus on subjects like sports, news
and weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a concern when your audience is eroded,'' said
Randy Falco, president of the NBC-TV Network unit of NBC in New
York, part of General Electric Co., but ``to get through to
America, you have to come through the networks.''
</P>
<P>
   The sizzling up-front market shows that broadcast TV ``is still
working,'' he added. ``That's the message.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, broadcasters are scheduling additional series this fall
aimed at the younger audiences that advertisers crave, filled with
teen-agers and 20-somethings whose looks are easy on the eyes and
whose plot lines will no doubt be easy on the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a major crisis,'' said Bob Igiel, president for the
broadcast division of the Media Edge in New York, the media
services arm of the agency company Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. ``There
isn't a kid left in high school in Los Angeles; they're all doing
TV shows.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, networks also have to cope with rising costs for
programs. Moreover, it is almost impossible to calculate the impact
of the surge in advertising on the profits or stock prices of the
networks' owners because they are generally huge conglomerates,
like GE or the Walt Disney Co., the parent of ABC, that have so
many other sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   And the networks are not just sitting back and enjoying the
advertising windfall, either. ``The lesson for all of us'' in the
shrinking audience shares, said Falco of the NBC-TV Network, ``is
that you can't stand still.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why NBC is ``embracing'' the Internet, he added, with
services like Snap.com; investing in cable networks like MSNBC, a
joint venture with the Microsoft Corp., and ``starting the process
of cross-selling'' among its older and newer media properties.
</P>
<P>
   For ABC, the answer to ``how you stop erosion'' is ``to get the
viewer more interested,'' said Marv Goldsmith, president for sales
and marketing at the ABC Television Network unit of ABC in New
York. That includes a presence on the Internet, with the Go
Network, he added, as well as this self-evident strategy: ``You put
on better programs. It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, needless to tell anyone who sat through the many lame
sitcoms, violent ``reality'' programs and soporific dramas that
characterized the 1998-99 season, easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any tremendously exciting things the networks are
doing to justify this,'' said Gene DeWitt, president and chief
executive of DeWitt Media in New York, a media services agency,
referring to the higher prices in the up-front market. ``It's not
like there's great new programming to get more audience.''
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on how you define ``great,'' of course. DeWitt
predicted that the six networks' erosion in audience would slow to
a 3 percent decline in the coming season from a 7 percent loss in
1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   And the reason? Dewitt anticipates that a two-hour weekly
wrestling series to be added to the prime-time schedule of UPN, the
low-rated network owned by Chris-Craft Industries and Viacom Inc.,
will lure viewers from the hugely popular wrestling shows on cable
networks.
</P>
<P>
   But as a TV industry saying proclaims, at this point in a new
season, every show is a hit.
</P>
<P>
   And at this point, too, another saying comes into play: Success
begets success. Almost nobody thinks the advertising bonanza will
reverse itself anytime soon, barring a recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a significant amount of money to come,'' said
David Poltrack, executive vice president for research and planning
at CBS Television in New York, part of CBS Corp., to be spent after
the 1999-2000 season starts by ``the new part of the advertising
marketplace,'' particularly the so-called dot-com advertisers like
E-commerce Web sites and other Internet marketers.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it is a time for celebration on broadcast row. ``We
all thought it was going to be a very, very strong marketplace,''
said Jon Nesvig, president for sales at Fox in New York, part of
News Corp., ``but it was much stronger than either side thought it
would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nesvig had a one-word response when asked how
broadcasters fared in the up-front: ``Phew!'' as in relief at not
losing sales because of a shrinking audience.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded of that last week, he replied, laughing, ``This year,
maybe it's a `Wow!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
