<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESSES DENY ASTROS OWNER MADE OFFENSIVE REMARKS ABOUT HISPANICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Three participants denied Monday that Houston Astros
owner Drayton McLane Jr. made offensive remarks about Hispanics
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The three said they participated in all or part of McLane's
conversation with executives of a Spanish-language television
station that erupted into controversy.
</P>
<P>
   KTDM-Channel 48 Telemundo reported that McLane had told its
General Manager Marco Camacho on Thursday night that the Astros
don't market Hispanics better because they don't understand the
game, among several alleged slights.
</P>
<P>
   But advertising buyer Ron Lucas and his wife, Lori, said they
were present for all of the conversation and that Camacho and his
two executives misinterpreted it.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Lucas said Camacho took the remarks ``totally out of
context'' because McLane was talking generally about his problems
marketing baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason that conversation was talking about Hispanics
is he was talking with Hispanics from an Hispanic broadcasting
station,'' Ron Lucas said. ``I think he felt the same way about
Anglos, African-Americans and Asian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to say this, and maybe I'm hedging my bet. Everyone
has a right to hear what they want to hear. But as an Anglo, I
didn't hear (McLane say) that.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising consultant Tami Weitkunat said Camacho
misrepresented the portion of the conversation she heard.
</P>
<P>
   According to Camacho, McLane had said the Astros don't market to
Hispanics because they buy cheap tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Weitkunat said, McLane was responding to a question
about the high cost of attending sporting events by pointing out
that the Astros have $2 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Lucas and Weitkunat said they complained to Camacho later
in the evening when they heard he might broadcast what they called
McLane's misinterpreted statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got into a heated argument and we said, `That is not what
was said,''' Weitkunat said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she declined Camacho's request to verify the station's
report.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho would not comment Monday, but KTMD spokeswoman Cassandra
Castellano said the station stands by its story.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may think this is public relations, a stunt for public
relations or self-aggrandizement, but it is not, not at all,''
Castellano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a function of two perspectives, or two cultural
perspectives. Maybe what is offensive to one race is not offensive
to someone else of a different perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Castellano said Camacho had called Ron Lucas on Friday to make
sure he verified the report and would not mind if the station
referred reporters to him. Lucas affirmed that what KTMD had
reported was accurate, Castellano said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she said, Camacho used Lucas as a reference later
Friday when he confronted McLane at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   But Lucas said Camacho was not specific in their conversation
about what he was alleging of McLane. Not until he returned from a
trip did he learn the full extent of what Camacho was saying, Lucas
said.
</P>
<P>
   McLane has said his comments were taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged comments came during a Houston Advertising
Federation banquet Thursday night at the downtown Aerial Theater.
McLane was there to receive the federation's Trailblazer Award.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho had said Friday that after his and two other station
executives' conversation with McLane, they huddled to make sure
each had the same impression of McLane's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Lucas, a guest of Camacho's at a Telemundo table at the
banquet, said he was a little hesitant to come public with his
views because he works for Boone-DeLeon, a Hispanic firm that does
business with Telemundo but does not do business with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said he is worried that his company could lose business as
a result of his speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pains me; I just know there will be repercussions,'' he
said. ``I wish it weren't the case, but I feel that it's the right
thing to (tell what happened.)''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, speaking for himself and his wife, said McLane never
stated that Hispanics are not smart enough to understand baseball.
</P>
<P>
   On McLane's allegedly saying the Astros don't market Hispanics
because they only buy cheap seats, Lucas voiced a similar story as
Weitkunat.
</P>
<P>
   On the allegation that McLane said Hispanics can't follow
baseball because they can't read newspapers, Lucas said McLane made
a different observation.
</P>
<P>
   McLane stated that baseball must be followed on a daily basis
and that fans must stay abreast of statistics, but that Hispanic
newspapers don't carry such statistics, Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take it that Hispanics don't read the newspaper, it's
just that their newspapers don't carry the statistics and box
scores,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with El Dia, Houston's Spanish-language daily
newspaper, said it prints the box scores (statistical
interpretations of a baseball game) about once a week. El Dia
doesn't have enough space to run them daily, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whose interpretation of McLane's comments is
correct, the issue remained a hot topic in the Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish-speaking KQQK radio was again flooded with callers
Monday, but instead of being angry as they were Friday, many were
laughing about the situation, said talk show host Beau Corona.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners played a game about ``Drayton McLane's Dictionary,''
making up definitions one might find in McLane's personal
dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one caller described an RBI (runs batted in) as
``Real Bad Indigestion,'' a lampoon of McLane's alleged suggestions
that Hispanics don't like Astrodome food.
</P>
<P>
   Another said McLane believes a shortstop ``is the shortest
player on the team.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The remarks are still in the back of their minds,'' Corona
said. ``We still love the Astros, and we're going to go out there
and support the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he said it, maybe he didn't. The truth probably lies
somewhere in between.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
