<HEADER>
A6563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BUDGET-TALKS-NYT     06-07 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER REVISES HIS OFFER TO CUT SPENDING DEMAND
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Last week's apparent progress toward a state
budget evaporated Monday as Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver
appeared to retract his offer to cut his house's spending demands
by as much as $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Senate majority leader, Joseph L. Bruno, seized
on Silver's offer of last week and said the two houses should
immediately convene a conference committee to work out a detailed
budget, a move the speaker has been demanding for months.
</P>
<P>
   But Silver responded that his lowered spending figure was not
addressed to Bruno. Rather, he said, it was an offer to Gov. George
Pataki, a Republican, that the Democrats would lower their demands
in exchange for the governor's pledge not to veto significant
portions of the Legislature's budget. The governor has refused to
make such a promise, so Silver said the Democrats are back at their
earlier, higher figure.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a lengthy news conference on Thursday, when he made
his concessions public, Silver never said his house's decreased
spending demand was contingent on a no-veto promise, and it was not
taken that way by the Governor's office, other legislators or
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's comments Monday dashed the hopes he raised last
week of completing a budget by June 16, when this year's
legislative session is scheduled to end. The budget will be 69 days
overdue on Tuesday, tying the mark for the third-latest in state
history.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's remarks on Thursday were apparently a feint intended to
draw Pataki into the process. It failed. The governor has insisted
all year that once he proposed his $72.7 billion budget, it was up
to the Legislature to act, and he would play no role in
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are looking for a way to avoid a repetition of last
year, when Pataki vetoed $1.6 billion in spending and borrowing
approved by the Legislature, the vast majority of it in projects
and programs championed by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bruno publicly invited Silver to convene conference
committees this afternoon, ``using his numbers'' of last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Silver said: ``I didn't make that offer to him. I made that
offer to the governor. The governor has not indicated an
acceptance.'' The overture to Pataki, he said, was in return for
``his not vetoing the items in the overall plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate leader ``is attempting to lay a veto trap for the
Governor,'' the speaker charged. ``He probably has a deal with the
Governor: veto the Assembly items, not the Senate items.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said there was no such deal. He accused Silver of trying
to return to the pre-1998 practice of the governor and legislative
leaders negotiating the budget in private meetings, a system often
derided as secretive and undemocratic. ``He doesn't want to go to
conference committees,'' he said. ``That's clear now, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said Silver had an eye on the June 30
expiration of $1 billion a year in Medicaid spending cuts that were
enacted in 1995 and 1996. Pataki wants to keep the cuts in place,
so the Speaker, his allies say, believes that he gains leverage by
pushing closer to that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has said he wants to keep the overall increase in
state spending within the inflation rate. To do that, he would cut
health care and higher education spending, and eliminate the
state's two-year-old commitment to paying for prekindergarten and
full-day kindergarten classes in every community, and reduced class
sizes in the early grades. Pataki has also called for salting away
all of the state's $2 billion surplus to pay for future tax cuts,
rather than spending the money.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republicans have proposed a budget $1.1 billion
larger than the governor's, a number that Pataki has said is too
high.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Democrats' original plan was $2 billion to $4
billion above the Governor's, depending on whose interpretation one
uses. But last week, Silver said he was willing to drop to $1.1
billion to $1.5 billion above Pataki's figure, the same range as
the Senate set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took Shelly Silver four months to get to $1.1 billion, and
now he's reneging on that number,'' said Charles Deister, a
spokesman for Pataki. ``It's now clear as a bell that he wants to
drag out the budget process as long as possible for his own
political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Speaker's retreat Monday puts the Legislature back in the
bind it has been in for three months. Bruno says that the two
houses must agree on an overall spending figure, or at least be
close to agreement, before a conference committee can begin. Silver
says that the question of an overall figure could be the first
thing decided by the committee, and that the panel should convene
right away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
