<HEADER>
A6567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENRIQUE-MARTINEZ-FASH     06-07 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENRIQUE-MARTINEZ-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S AMBASSADOR OF ELEGANCE BEYOND HUARACHES 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It takes courage to open a designer boutique on
Madison Avenue that doesn't have a recognizable name. It takes even
more courage if the name belongs to a dead designer who won't be
around to charm potential customers. But Elisa Salinas, who is
opening the Enrique Martinez boutique in the fall at Madison Avenue
and 67th Street, doesn't seem the slightest bit daunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I produce soap operas,'' she said last week on a trip from
Mexico City, her home. ``Every time I make a decision about a soap
opera, it's $5 million. I produce 10 soap operas. My business in
Mexico is $50 million. I'm used to big numbers and taking big
risks. I think the risk is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Old hands of the New York retail scene, who see boutiques
opening and closing with regularity, might consider her naive, if
not foolhardy. But though she won't say what it is costing her to
set up the Enrique Martinez business, it's nowhere near the $5
million it costs her to get a soap opera on the air. She sells soap
operas to stations all over the world and considers it her mission
to make Mexican fashion stand for more than peasant wedding shirts
and huaraches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about Mexico,'' Ms. Salinas said. ``It has
no image in this country. Can you think of one Mexican designer?
No. Nobody is willing to take the risk, so I decided to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   She may be chauvinistic about her country, but she is not naive.
She's a world traveler who speaks fluent English, went to school in
France and has been coming to New York since she was 5, first with
her parents and in recent years with her husband, Juan Davide
Burns, and their three young daughters. She was at last week's
American Fashion Awards, drawing attention in a backless white
dress by Vera Wang and an impressive diamond solitaire as she
presided over a table beside the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinas has been involved in the business world since she
was 17 (she's now 33). She owned 32 shoe stores in Mexico and a
chain of 24-hour supermarkets, she said, before her family bought
control of the Television Azteca network for $641 million in 1993.
``That changed my life,'' she said. She sold the stores and went
into television. She is vice president of television production for
the network and intends to remain so while running the Enrique
Martinez business. Her entrepreneurial spirit comes from her
father, Hugo Salinas Rocha.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a self-made man with everything from TV networks
to 800 retail stores all over Latin America,'' said Ms. Salinas,
who is not related to the former Mexican President, Carlos Salinas
de Gortari. ``He was the cliche of the tycoon,'' she added. ``But
he started to lose his eyesight when I was about 17, and I started
working for him. I went with him to see business executives and
bankers and learned how to read financial statements. When I
decided to go into the retail business myself when I was 19, I went
for shoes. My father said, `There are 90 million Mexicans walking,
and they all need shoes.' My shoes sold for $1 to $5, so everyone
could afford them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Enrique Martinez clothes are not for everyone, ranging in
price from $500 to about $2,500. But Ms. Salinas and the executive
director of her company, Sandra Seroy, whose fashion experience
includes stints at Max Mara and Genny, believe that classic styles
in fine fabrics will appeal to women who shop on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel our customer is a very active woman,'' Ms. Salinas
said. ``She's very self-confident and feminine. She may be a
professional and powerful, but she has a great appreciation for the
feminine side. The clothes are not androgynous at all. I believe
clothes can be useful and comfortable and can help you look chic,
no matter if you've been in an office for 10 hours and then go to
cocktails.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinas could be describing herself.
</P>
<P>
   Except for slinky jersey evening dresses, the Enrique Martinez
clothes are the kind a woman could wear all day. There are suits,
blazers, coats, simple shift dresses and knits, all made in Italy
of fine Italian wools and cashmere, often with a touch of stretch.
They come in black, browns and dark red as well as checks of
russet, green and beige. Sweaters are in 12 colors.
</P>
<P>
   There are double-breasted blazers, shaped jackets and a
zip-front collarless style; slim knee-length skirts, and narrow
pants. Some of the jackets for fall have beaver or fox collars,
which add an aura of luxury. There will also be cashmere and
pashmina shawls and scarves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clothes are not trendy,'' Ms. Salinas stressed. ``That's
not what we're looking for. The concept is casual haute couture.
There will be very few pieces of each style, and a woman can order
something in another fabric. And we will offer custom-designed
evening wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez designed about 75 percent of the fall collection before
he died last November. There is now a design team headed by Georges
Zeldis, who has worked in Europe for Valentino and Anna Molinari.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds odd to name a new business for a dead designer,
especially one whose name is not known outside his native Mexico,
but Ms. Salinas was committed to honoring him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enrique came to Mexico City from a small town when he was
17,'' she recalled. ``He went to work for Manuel Mendez, who was a
very important designer in Mexico then. My mother was a client. I
was 6 when I met Enrique. He taught me how to wear lipstick, how to
dress. He was a mentor, the eldest brother I didn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez worked in Paris before opening his own custom salon in
Mexico City, where Ms. Salinas' mother bought clothes. Ms. Salinas,
who is tall, and striking, modeled for him when she was only 14.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled being in New York with Martinez early last year,
walking along Madison Avenue, when they started talking about
starting a business here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like playing, talking between friends,'' Ms. Salinas
said. ``Then it went on, and I thought, This could be a reality. I
made the decision in March last year, and Enrique agreed to close
his business and work with me. I think Enrique lives in this
project and is here with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinas' commitment involved signing a 10-year lease, with
an additional five-year option, for a two-story retail space at 785
Madison Ave. She won't disclose the annual rent except to say it is
in the high six figures _ not unusual today. Because of the demand
for Madison Avenue retail space, it has become a landlords' market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landlords want names, someone with 50 global stores,'' Ms.
Seroy said. ``We were in negotiations for months. But Ms. Salinas
is not accustomed to have anyone say no.''
</P>
<P>
   As someone who manages 2,000 employees in her television
production company, Ms. Salinas operates on a large scale. Running
just one boutique on Madison Avenue would not be worth the
investment of her time or her finances, she said. The boutique is
meant to be the first step in establishing an Enrique Martinez
brand name, so there are plans for more boutiques in this country
and to wholesale the line, perhaps as early as next year, to a few
high-end stores.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Klein (who shoots some of Calvin Klein's ads)
photographed the advertising campaign, which will be in fashion
magazines and on billboards and buses. They star Eugenia Silva, a
Spanish-born model with the same dark-haired Latin beauty and air
of sophistication that Ms. Silva exudes.
</P>
</TEXT>
