<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL IS READY TO FIRE NEW SALVO IN INTERNET TELEPHONY WAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   (jw) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nortel Networks Corp. of Canada, in the battle to transmit
phone calls using Internet technology, plans to announce Tuesday
that it is developing almost a dozen new products to help corporate
customers integrate their phone and data communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel, formerly called Northern Telecom, is North America's
second-largest maker of traditional telecommunications equipment,
behind Lucent Technologies Inc. Nortel and Lucent are locked in
battle not only with each other but also with leaders in data
networking, including Cisco Systems Inc., to develop technology for
unified voice and data networks.
</P>
<P>
   Such unified networks could allow companies to reduce the amount
they spend maintaining separate voice and data systems, and could
even open the door to new sorts of services, including phones that
communicate with address book software.
</P>
<P>
   Developing so-called Internet telephony technology requires big
engineering commitments, and Nortel has recently appeared to lag in
that effort behind Lucent, Cisco and small Internet telephony
start-ups like Vocaltec Communications Ltd. and the Clarent Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the products that Nortel intends to introduce Tuesday
will not be commercially available for another year or so, but the
announcement seems sure to add momentum to Nortel's efforts to
become a leader in Internet telephony.
</P>
<P>
   While data networking companies like Cisco have appeared more
aggressive in encouraging customers to anticipate scrapping their
traditional phone networks in favor of more advanced Internet-based
systems, older companies like Lucent and Nortel have encouraged a
more evolutionary approach. That approach is geared to appeal to
companies that could be concerned about the reliability and
capabilities of Internet phone systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that most alternatives offered to customers for
telephony over I.P. have been very primitive in the features they
offer,'' said James Long, president of the Nortel group that sells
products to business customers, referring to Internet protocol, the
language of cyberspace. ``What we are announcing are a spectrum of
products that allow customers to implement a converged network
along a whole spectrum, from continuing to run separate networks to
using an advanced Internet protocol network.''
</P>
<P>
   That spectrum of products ranges from Internet add-ons for
existing office phone systems made by Nortel, which will be
available immediately, to phone systems designed around Internet
technology from the ground up, which are not scheduled to become
available until the second quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   If Nortel meets that goal, it will find itself in roughly the
same ball park as its major competitors. Cisco wants to deploy
Internet-based office phone systems broadly early next year. Lucent
plans to sell Internet-based phone systems for small customers this
fall and to expand the products for large companies early next
year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Long said that among the institutional customers that had agreed
to try Nortel's Internet phone technology were the University of
Texas at Austin; Countrywide Credit Industries, the mortgage
company; Kinko's Inc., the copy shop chain; Safeway Inc., the
supermarket company, and the Symantec Corp., the software maker.
</P>
<P>
   But developing systems for business customers is only part of
the Internet telephony equation. The other big part is developing
Internet phone technology for communications carriers like AT&AMP;T
Corp. Nortel's competitors seem slightly ahead in that part of the
industry, but the Internet telephony market for carriers is
immature and the eventual technology winners remain undetermined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MEDICAID-INQUIRY-N     06-07 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR ARE BEING SHUT OUT OF MEDICARE, FEDERAL OFFICIALS FEAR
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Concerned over the steep declines of the Medicaid
rolls in New York, federal officials are looking into whether local
governments across the state are improperly preventing the poor
from signing up for health benefits under the program.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has already been examining stringent new
welfare policies in New York City that advocates for the poor and a
federal judge say have prevented many poor people from getting
prompt access to Medicaid coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But now, federal officials are looking into whether similar
problems exist outside the city and what, if anything, Albany is
doing to insure that localities are not erecting improper hurdles
to applying for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry was outlined in a letter that Sue Kelly, a regional
administrator for the Federal Health Care Financing Administration,
sent to state health officials last month expressing her concerns
about New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Ms. Kelly said that it ``appears that barriers
exist in the application process'' for Medicaid both inside and
outside New York City. The letter specifically cites long delays in
approving the Medicaid applications of over 1,000 people in Nassau
County. Ms. Kelly noted that the agency would, as a result, conduct
a ``program review'' of the state's Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   New York State officials said that they welcomed the inquiry,
and that they would provide documents outlining the thoroughness of
their oversight. ``We look forward to that meeting so that we can
show HCFA the significant monitoring effort that the department has
undertaken in the Medicaid program,'' said John Signor, a spokesman
for the state's Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns of federal officials are underscored by recent
statistics showing that many localities in New York State _ from
Nassau and Suffolk Counties to the Syracuse area and the Buffalo
area _ have reduced their Medicaid rolls far more than even New
York City has.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth Ryden Benjamin, a lawyer for the Legal Aid Society who
represents Medicaid recipients, called the federal inquiry a
significant development. ``This is an extremely serious step,'' she
said. ``The state needs to walk very carefully because what is
happening in the localities is a field full of land mines.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Medicaid recipients has drawn increasing attention
in New York and across the nation since 1996, when the federal
government passed a law overhauling its welfare program. That law
gave states sweeping new powers to impose a host of restrictions on
their poverty programs, such as strict time limits on cash
assistance to the poor. But that law also specified that poor
people would be able to keep their Medicaid coverage even if they
lost their eligibility for welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In most states, eligibility for welfare benefits and for
Medicaid have been traditionally linked, and it has taken time for
states to implement procedures formally severing the two programs.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been of particular interest in New York, where the
Medicaid rolls have decreased by 276,973, or 9 percent, since
President Clinton signed the law overhauling welfare in August
1996. The enrollment decline among New York's Medicaid population,
now at about 2.7 million, has drawn harsh rebukes from advocates
for the poor and other critics who say that many local governments
have erected huge hurdles to getting Medicaid insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In January, for example, a federal district judge ruled that New
York City had improperly denied applications for Medicaid from poor
people because they had not complied with the city's requirement
that they work in exchange for their welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The steep enrollment decline is not limited to New York City,
where the Medicaid rolls have dropped by 8.3 percent since the
federal welfare law was passed in 1996. In that same period, the
caseloads have dropped by 15.5 percent in Suffolk County, 10.8
percent in Nassau County, 11.5 percent in the Syracuse area and
13.9 percent in the Binghampton area, according to state
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   New York state officials have themselves expressed concern that
federal rules intended to preserve Medicaid for people deemed
ineligible for welfare have not always been followed. In fact, last
January, state health investigators visited eight welfare offices
in New York City and found that four had failed to provide Medicaid
applications promptly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
