<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONEYWELL-IMPACT-NYT     06-07 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONEYWELL-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER DEAL BRINGS DISMAY TO HONEYWELL'S HOMETOWN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Minn)  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Honeywell Inc.'s merger with Allied Signal would
result in the loss of a corporate headquarters here, the loss of up
to 1,000 local jobs, and the migration of one of the region's
leading philanthropic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Known in millions of American homes for its thermostats, the
company is rooted in the Twin Cities and is renowned here for
making generous charitable donations, amounting to about $13.4
million last year. Honeywell said the merged company would maintain
its financial commitment to the area, particularly to the
low-income neighborhood in which its headquarters is situated. But
local officials and civic leaders expressed dismay at news of the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   In the Phillips neighborhood, where the company is based, and
which is perhaps the poorest section of Minneapolis, there was a
strong reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've always given us grants on a large basis as long as we
kept performing the tasks we set out to do,'' said Anna
Bowlds-Perkins, chairwoman of the board of the Phillips Community
Development Corp., a job-training center. She added, ``With them
leaving, yeah, I think it's going to make a big difference. Their
presence is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely to help bolster the Phillips area, the company
established the Honeywell Foundation in 1957, and has funneled most
of its charitable donations through the foundation, which will move
to New Jersey, said Pearse O'Laughlin, the company's corporate
public relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitments we've made in the Twin Cities will be
maintained,'' O'Laughlin said. The company, one of the 10 largest
in Minnesota, will retain the headquarters building, he said, and
continue to be the center of the home and building control
division, which includes the thermostat operation.
</P>
<P>
   Of more than 7,000 Honeywell employees in Minnesota, where the
general economy is booming, more than 6,000 will remain, he said.
The others will transfer to New Jersey or other locations, or be
laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Among Honeywell's philanthropic efforts is a high school, called
New Vistas, which has operated within the headquarters since 1990.
It will continue there, he said. New Vistas provides education to
pregnant and teen-age mothers. Already, 142 women have graduated
from the school.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell has also donated $4.8 million, and thousands of
employees donated their labor and helped build 51 new
owner-occupied, three- and four-bedroom houses here. So far, 20 of
the 51 houses are finished. They cost $60,000 to $90,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been making dramatic progress,'' said Peter McLaughlin,
a Hennepin County Board member representing the south Minneapolis
area, who worked closely with Honeywell on the project. But he
added: ``Now we're being victimized by larger corporate powers over
which we have no control. To lose that capacity is a huge loss for
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Phenix, a spokeswoman for Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton of
Minneapolis, said the loss of Honeywell was very disappointing.
``Honeywell has been a community partner in the city of
Minneapolis,'' she said. ``I think simply its presence in the city
for 114 years as a major corporate powerhouse will be of a great
loss, but we're not feeling completely gloom and doom.''
</P>
<P>
   And McLaughlin said: ``I think that's true that the
philanthropic contributions will continue. But after some time, the
impetus, the energy will dissipate because Honeywell will no longer
be in the neighborhood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
