<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLPHONE-FCC-COX     06-07 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONE-FCC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dollars may come from dialers
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If federal regulators get their way, you won't need a
cellular phone to get billed for cellular calls. A move afoot could
make consumers pay for calls they place to cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Now, cellular subscribers pay for calls they place and receive.
But the Federal Communications Commission is considering changing
the rules this week. It hopes the billing change will spur growth
in cellular use as it has in European and South American countries.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC will seek public comment on the rule change, commonly
referred to as calling-party-pays, before making a decision. The
FCC proposal would give wireless phone owners the option of whether
or not to have calling-party-pays.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth opposed the change, said Linda Lancaster, directory of
regulatory affairs for the Atlanta-based Bell, saying there's no
consumer demand and the change would be expensive. The increased
costs would be passed on to cellular subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, from a good business standpoint, we'd need to
recover those costs and there's no one else (to pass them on to),''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans' cellular use ranks third in market penetration after
Detroit and Greensboro, N.C., according to a recent report by
Scarborough Research.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster disagreed such a billing change would spur a growth in
cellular.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, she said, the U.S. market and the European and
South American markets differ. In South America, where BellSouth
offers the billing option, customers can see at a glance _ based on
the number's prefix _ that they are calling a cell phone and may be
billed. Separate prefixes aren't feasible in the United States, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the United States must have a calling-party-pays
policy before consumers will view wireless service, a $40 billion
market, as a true alternative to traditional wired phone service in
the $190 billion U.S. phone market. Mexico adopted
calling-party-pays rules in April, and wireless use increased 10
percent the first month, said Michael Altschul, general counsel of
the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2249EDT &QL; 
