<HEADER>
A6586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSANA-PROFILE-NYT     06-07 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSANA-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SUCCEED AS A TV ANCHOR WITHOUT REALLY TRYING
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Insana, the fast-talking CNBC anchor, is best known for his
unflappability. It's why he gets to interview the big guns of the
money world: Soros, Galbraith, Rubin; senators, CEOs, reclusive
hedge fund titans. His publicity agent actually called him Cool
when describing him.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't know the half of it. Late last week, he walked
into CNBC's studios in Fort Lee, N.J., smiled sweetly, and said,
``I just wrecked my car.'' (Actually, he had taken a sharp corner
in the parking garage and added a racing stripe to his E-class
Mercedes. The door will have to be replaced.)
</P>
<P>
   Then, looking calm and collected in full on-air makeup, he
followed his crash story by asking, ``So, we going to lunch?''
</P>
<P>
   Insana's center of gravity has always served him well. During
the last 14 years, he has built a reputation as one of the best
television journalists in the exploding field of business news. He
even seems to be taking with aplomb the news that has sent tremors
through his field during the last two weeks, that the Nasdaq Stock
Market may start evening trading as soon as September and the New
York Stock Exchange may consider extending the 4 p.m. close next
year. For most traders and those who cover them, it was like
hearing that the very laws of nature were being rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   But Insana says that with the ever upward arc of the market and
technology, the new hours were probably always just a matter of
time. And people should consider themselves lucky to have had it so
easy. ``We business journalists have had the closest thing to a
Civil Service job over the last 15 years,'' he says. ``You're off
at 4 o'clock, or at least I am. No weekends to speak of. Very
nice.'' Turning back to his iceberg lettuce salad, he says
offhandedly, ``What has been an incredibly normal life for being a
journalist may change dramatically, soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at the incredibly normal life of Insana, 38, it's
not easy for anyone, including Ron Insana, to figure out exactly
how he became a big-time journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Buffalo and later just north of Los Angeles, where
his parents moved when he was 13, he dreamed of being a rock
drummer. He soldiered away in a high school band that managed to
stay together into college, playing mostly ``bad 70's pop'' and
wedding gigs. Then at California State University at Northridge, he
majored in film and resisted his family's entreaties to take
business classes. If writing and directing failed, they asked,
wouldn't he like to be a producer?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he wanted be the next Woody Allen or Mel Brooks. Or
Roger Corman. Or something. His first student short films included
``The Vampire Strikes Back.'' Plot? ``Dracula coming out of
retirement for one last gig. Transylvania was running a little low
on blood.'' Next: ``Edifice Rex,'' about ``a landlord with an
apartment complex.'' He feels the need to elaborate. ``It was about
a Jewish guy living in ancient Greece, married to his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   But as college ended, no one had offered him a corner office at
a studio. He was living with his parents, selling vitamins at a
mall. He was going to pitch meetings where entertainment executives
said no before he began his pitch. When a friend offered him an
entry level job at the Financial News Network, the fledgling cable
network that eventually merged with CNBC, he took it.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, the network downsized, and he found himself
back at the mall. (``I made more with vitamins than I did at FNN,
actually.'') But then somehow, as if business journalism just would
not give up on him, he was hired back as a producer. And in May
1985, the fateful day arrived: both anchors (the network had only
two) called in sick on the same day, and Insana stepped up to the
anchor desk.
</P>
<P>
   He began to educate himself about business, because ``I couldn't
have an intelligent conversation with anybody in the room, and it
got really frustrating.'' But at first it was slow going. He would
interview executives, who would tell him ``they were going to use
their tax-loss carry-forwards to offset this and that and the other
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd repeat it verbatim in a story, and then I'd ask somebody
later, `What the hell was I talking about?'''
</P>
<P>
   But he kept at it, and finally, ``It just started to get so
interesting to me that I couldn't help but learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, James Cramer, fund manager and founder of TheStreet.com,
calls him the most serious business journalist on television. He's
regularly on ``Today'' and ``NBC Nightly News'' with Tom Brokaw to
explain the market's movements to the masses. He has the honor of
being called a ``geek'' by Don Imus, who enlists him for financial
chat on his radio show. His 2 to 4 p.m. show on CNBC, ``Street
Signs,'' was the highest rated show ever on the network when the
market dived in October 1997. (He also managed to marry; he and his
wife, Melinda, have a 16-month-old daughter, Emily.)
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Insana looks at his watch. It's 1:30 p.m. and his
program begins in 15 minutes. His check has arrived but not his
car. Now it's 1:45. Outside on the sidewalk, he chats amiably. He
is not worried. A colleague dashes back into the restaurant and
emerges with a smiling diner named Rudy, who is a member of
Insana's country club. Everyone jams into Rudy's car, and Insana
makes it back to the studio with five minutes to spare.
</P>
<P>
   He ducks into the makeup room. ``Plenty of time,'' he says,
smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTIL-HOSTILE-BID-NYT     06-07 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTIL-HOSTILE-BID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISOURCE DISCLOSES $5.7 BILLION HOSTILE BID FOR COLUMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NiSource Inc. disclosed a hostile $5.7 billion cash offer for
the Columbia Energy Group, Monday and Columbia's chairman responded
that while his company is not for sale and is not interested in any
merger transaction he would present the bid to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver G. Richard 3d, the chairman, president and chief
executive of Columbia, was responding to a letter sent by Gary L.
Neale, the chairman, president and chief executive officer of
NiSource, a major Midwest utility. Neale offered to buy Columbia
for $68 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Neale Monday made public a letter he had sent to Richard on
April 1 in which he made the offer. Columbia rejected the offer and
refused to engage in any discussions. The contents of Neale's
letter were reported in The Wall Street Journal on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Neale said in an interview yesterday that he was encouraged that
the proposal would be presented to the Columbia board. He added,
however, that he would court large institutional holders to support
its unsolicited bid to acquire Columbia, a major gas company in the
East.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was encouraged by a meeting Monday with David Kiefer,
the portfolio manager for the Prudential Utility Fund, which is the
second largest holder of Columbia stock.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer said that a combination of the companies would open up
opportunities under deregulation and would create ``a lot of room
for many smart people'' at both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said that since Columbia's stock is 74 percent
owned by institutional investors the hostile offer had a better
chance than normally in the utility industry, where hostile
takeovers are very rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're offering a nice premium,'' said Robert Rubin, a
utility analyst for Bear Stearns. The NiSource bid is 30.7 percent
higher than the average closing prices for Columbia common stock
for 20 trading days ended last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to believe that the offer might go through as
Columbia stock soared Monday, closing up $7.4375 to $63.1875 on the
New York Stock Exchange. Shares of NiSource were down 62.50 cents,
to $27.5625, also on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that large institutional holders had little loyalty
to a company in comparison with smaller investors and are more apt
to ``just want to max out their value.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, Richard had done a good job of
helping grow Columbia, which emerged out of a reorganization under
Chapter 11 in November 1995, and seemed determined to rebuild the
company on his own.
</P>
<P>
   An indication of this was that Richard began a hostile takeover
attempt of his own on April 18, offering to buy the Consolidated
Natural Gas Company for $6.3 billion. It was an attempt to break up
an agreement reached by Consolidated to be acquired by Dominion
Resources Inc. a large utility based in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   But Consolidated, which is based in Pittsburgh, accepted
Dominion's offer, valued at $6.3 billion on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually large holdings by institutional investors go back
to Columbia's filing for bankruptcy protection. It frightened away
most smaller stockholders, but large holders bet that Columbia
could emerge from bankruptcy and do well.
</P>
<P>
   Since its reorganization plan was accepted in November 1995,
Columbia's annual earnings have have been growing, and it has been
increasing its dividend.
</P>
<P>
   Richard, in a glitzy annual report, stressed that the utility
was training many of its people to operate in states that have
deregulated natural gas and are moving to do the same in
electricity. In his letter rebuffing Neale, he said that Columbia
``is not for sale and is not interested in any merger transaction
in which another company acquires control of Columbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia is based in Herndon, Va. and had revenues of $6.6
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Neale said that the companies would be a good fit. Columbia
serves 2.1 million natural gas customers in 34 states and is an
integrated company producing, shipping, storing and selling natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
   NiSource, which is based Merrillville, Ind., is smaller than
Columbia. It had $2.9 billion in revenues last year distributing
electricty to 421,000 customers, natural gas to 1 million customers
and water to 254,000 in the Midwest and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Neale said that adding Columbia's capacity to produce and store
gas would help NiSource hedge its gas supplies. The ability to
hedge gas has grown more important as the industry has been
deregulated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
