<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-KC-TIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING CANDIDATE FOR LAS VEGAS MAYOR NO STRANGER TO KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. - If the next likely mayor of Las Vegas ever
decides to visit Kansas City, he won't have to ask for restaurant
or hotel recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s, flamboyant defense attorney Oscar Goodman has
made regular stops in Kansas City to defend some of the city's most
notorious organized-crime figures, including Anthony ``Tony Ripe''
Civella.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman has parlayed his flamboyant representation of mob
luminaries elsewhere _ such as Meyer Lansky and Anthony ``Tony the
Ant'' Spilotro _ to make himself one of the most recognized
criminal-defense lawyers in the country. Spilotro once reputedly
placed a rival's head in a vise and squeezed his eyeballs out.
</P>
<P>
   From 1971 to 1986, Spilotro ruled Las Vegas. Spilotro's role was
captured by actor Joe Pesci in the movie ``Casino,'' and Goodman
appeared as himself in the film. The mob's influence in Las Vegas
waned when Spilotro was buried alive in an Indiana cornfield at the
behest of Chicago mob bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, 59, is the odds-on favorite to win election today as
the mayor of America's glitziest ZIP code. Goodman is running on a
populist platform of increasing fees on developers to refurbish
older neighborhoods, and solving the city's traffic and
air-pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   In May's primary election, he came within 277 votes of winning
the office outright. His only opposition today is a sitting City
Council member whom one Las Vegas paper recently described as
``bland.''
</P>
<P>
   Bland and ineffective Goodman is not, say lawyers who have
worked with and against him in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't quarrel with how he got his reputation,'' said F.A.
White, a Northland criminal-defense lawyer who once worked with
Goodman on a local case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Goodman won a five-year probationary sentence for a
Leawood man convicted of stealing $20 million from a Nebraska
insurance company so he could care for his severely handicapped
10-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, Goodman pronounced himself pleased with the
4-year term Civella received in a pharmaceuticals-fraud case. He
called it a ``breath of fresh air'' that a member of Kansas City's
most storied organized-crime families hadn't received a harsher
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodman's identification with organized crime has been his
opponents' harshest weapon in Las Vegas. They're concerned that he
might lend a new mob aura to a city that has come a long way from
the days when Bugsy Siegel held court there.
</P>
<P>
   Some attorneys who have squared off against him here have a
similar concern.
</P>
<P>
   David B.B. Helfrey, now a St. Louis defense lawyer, led the
Justice Department's Kansas City Organized Crime Strike Force in
the 1980s. He said Goodman's traditional attitude toward government
might not fit well with holding elective office.
</P>
<P>
   ``His historical perspective has been that government is evil
and that his clients were being maligned and unfairly treated,''
Helfrey said. ``As opposed to a dispassionate approach, his was a
personal approach, closely identifying with his clients. Whether he
can separate himself from his clients in his new position, I don't
know. I'm not sure he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, however, discounted those concerns in a recent
interview with /{The Associated Press/}.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just their attorney and their mouthpiece and
spokesman,'' Goodman said. ``When the media took a whack at my
clients, I would speak on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just have the image of the mob lawyer things.
But I, honest to God, believe I'm going to be the best mayor Las
Vegas ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City lawyer Byron Neal Fox said Las Vegas has nothing to
fear from Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really go to the fiber of what he does, it's truly to
defend everyone's civil liberties,'' said Fox, who calls Goodman
his best friend. ``He can't succeed in the courtroom if the law
doesn't allow him to. Anybody who believes in justice and fairness
has no better friend. He's the most honorable guy who exists in
this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Helfrey said he was particularly concerned about the influence
that Goodman could wield over the Las Vegas gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman's gaming experience in Missouri hasn't been without
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1994, the Missouri Gaming Commission banned a Las
Vegas gaming company from the state for two years, ruling that it
had failed to disclose a $6 million deal with a group of lobbyists
and lawyers, including Fox and Goodman. No money ever changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said Goodman had been a magnet for such scrutiny, but said
he has always withstood it with ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI has looked him over a thousand times and never has
there been a problem,'' Fox noted.
</P>
<P>
   White and Helfrey said Goodman's charismatic personal style
sometimes masks a lack of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd want him as my own lawyer, but I wouldn't
pass the opportunity to watch him,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox denied that Goodman sometimes spreads himself too thin. His
critics don't understand the uncommon gifts and energy Goodman
brings to life, Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't recognize his unlimited capacity to give,
professionally, family-wise and to his friends,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
