<SLUG> BC-YELLOW-FREIGHT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELLOW FREIGHT ACQUIRES PHILADELPHIA TRUCKING FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Yellow Corp. has agreed to buy a
Philadelphia area trucking company in a deal valued at $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow, the Overland Park-based trucking company, has offered to
buy Jevic Transportation Inc. for $14 a share. Jevic's board of
directors has recommended that its shareholders accept the offer,
which includes the assumption of Jevic's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow is financing the deal through existing debt facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Jevic, based in Delanco, N.J., employs about 2,300 people,
including 1,200 drivers. Its non-union work force is not expected
to be affected by a Yellow acquisition, and Jevic would operate as
a stand-alone company, both parties said.
</P>
<P>
   Jevic would maintain its current management team, including
Harry Muhlschlegel, its founder and president.
</P>
<P>
   If acquired, Jevic will be Yellow's fourth regional carrier.
Jevic operates in the upper Midwest and the Northeast, regions
where Yellow previously did not have a strong presence.
</P>
<P>
   Jevic posted $226.1 million in revenue last year, which would
boost Yellow's revenue from regional carriers to nearly 25 percent.
Yellow reported revenue of $2.9 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jevic operates as a cross of a truckload carrier and a
less-than-truckload carrier. The company has a network that lessens
the need for terminals where large freight loads are rerouted, as
is the case with less-than-truckload companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jevic has origin terminals in eight metropolitan areas where
freight is loaded into a trailer based on the driver's sequence of
stops.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow said it would form a separate management team to oversee
its regional carriers. A search for a president is under way, said
A. Maurice Myers, Yellow's chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Jevic can terminate the deal if it receives an unsolicited,
better offer from another suitor. If that occurs, Jevic would be
required to pay Yellow $4.75 million and cover legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Jevic's stock closed at 13 Monday on the Nasdaq Stock Market, up
3. Yellow closed at 17, up , also on the Nasdaq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
