<SLUG> BC-LEVITT-KC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC CHAIRMAN TO ATTEND TOWN HALL MEETING IN KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The nation's top securities cop is coming to
Kansas City on June 30 to help small businesses learn how to raise
money.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, chairman of the {Securities and Exchange
Commission}, will be among the speakers at a Small Business Town
Hall Meeting. The SEC has been conducting these meetings around the
nation, though Levitt has been able to attend only a few.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour meeting will begin at 3 p.m. at Pierson Hall at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City. The hall, which holds about
600, is at 5000 Holmes Road.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt and others will talk about how small businesses can raise
capital through public offerings of securities, the Internet and
exempt offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Levitt spoke in Kansas City as chairman of the White
House Commission on Small Business. He praised then-SEC Chairman
Harold Williams' efforts to address the problems of small
businesses. Levitt even worked in Kansas City early in his career,
handling the acquisition of cattle and property for {Oppenheimer
Industries Inc.}
</P>
<P>
   Others scheduled to speak June 30 include Brian Lane, director
of the SEC's division of corporation finance; Brad Douglas,
regional advocate for small business for the {Office of Advocacy}
in the {U.S. Small Business Administration}; David Brant, Kansas
securities commissioner; Mary Hosmer, Missouri's assistant
securities commissioner; and Rich Bendis, president and chief
executive officer of the {Kansas Technology Enterprise Corp.}
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is being sponsored by the SEC, the {Greater Kansas
City Chamber of Commerce}, the university's {Bloch School of
Business} and {Kansas Technology Enterprise}.
</P>
<P>
   There is no fee to attend. Reservations are recommended but not
required. Contact the university's central ticket office at
235-2700. A reception will follow the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
