<SLUG> BC-HKO-IHL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER A DULL MOMENT IN THE IHL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Houston Aeros deserved to win the Turner Cup. They had the
strongest team in the International Hockey League and on Saturday,
beat the Orlando Solar Bears, 5-3, in Game 7 of the Turner Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Not to diminish the Aeros' title, but what was most striking
about this season is the Solar Bears' run. While the Aeros should
be considered one of the most dominant teams ever assembled in the
IHL, the Solar Bears accomplished a much rarer feat.
</P>
<P>
   The Solar Bears recovered from a 3-0 deficit to beat the Detroit
Vipers, 4-3, in the Eastern Conference finals. No NBA or Major
League Baseball team ever has come back from trailing 3-0 to win.
The Solar Bears became the fifth professional hockey team to do so.
The 1942 Toronto Maple Leafs and 1975 New York Islanders were the
only NHL teams to stage such a comeback. Two American Hockey League
teams rallied from 3-0 deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Several elements of the Solar Bears' comeback, or Vipers'
dismantling, were bizarre. As ``You Gotta Be There'' was the IHL's
marketing slogan for the playoffs, you gotta hear this.
</P>
<P>
   Through circuitous rule bending, Marc Lamothe started in goal
for the Vipers in Game 7 of the Eastern Conference finals. Several
weeks ago, this column touted Lamothe as the ``story of the IHL
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamothe had two playoff shutouts as the Indianapolis Ice's
goalie. Even though he had been a backup for most of the season,
Lamothe came in relief in the playoffs and, more or less,
single-handedly led the Ice to a first-round upset over the
Cincinnati Cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   Lamothe nearly did the same against the Vipers, but the
Cinderella-esque Ice finally were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where Lamothe's story changes. One of the Vipers'
goalies, Kevin Weekes, spent the end of the season with the
Vancouver Canucks. (Weekes, by the way, was part of the deal that
sent Pavel Bure to the Florida Panthers.)
</P>
<P>
   Weekes refused to report to the Vipers at the end of the
Canucks' season. The Vipers looked for loop holes to get a strong
emergency backup goalie.
</P>
<P>
   They found a loop hole. The Chicago Blackhawks are affiliated
with both the Ice and the Vipers.
</P>
<P>
   Lamothe, property of the Blackhawks, conveniently was moved from
the Ice to the Vipers by the NHL team.
</P>
<P>
   Although it didn't violate IHL rules, the move shouldn't have
happened. It made a mockery of the league. Come on, should the
Dallas Stars be allowed to have Patrik Roy as an emergency backup
in the Stanley Cup Finals? Allowing the Vipers to acquire Lamothe
was an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   But hold on, there was another embarrassing move. Lamothe had to
start in Game 7 because the league suspended Vipers starter Andrei
Trefilov. Trefilov allegedly threw his stick into the crowd during
Game 6 and hit a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged incident was not captured on videotape, so the
league went by a police report to make its ruling.
</P>
<P>
   So the Solar Bears won Game 7. They did so in ultra-dramatic
fashion by erasing a two-goal deficit with three minutes left. The
Solar Bears then won in double overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Vipers' mojo turned the wrong way when they acquired
Lamothe. They got him when they led, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ICE DOGS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The Ice Dogs expect to have a similar affiliation with the Kings
this season, which most likely will keep about six players in Long
Beach. The Ice Dogs also are in preliminary talks with the Phoenix
Coyotes to develop a secondary affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   BOXY'S BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Ice Dogs general manager/coach John Van Boxmeer still is being
considered for the Kings' coaching job. Speculation is buzzing that
Van Boxmeer will get the job. However, Kings GM Dave Taylor hasn't
confirmed that.
</P>
<P>
   The Ice Dogs' stance on Van Boxmeer's future is clear. While the
organization would love to have him back, they would be pleased to
see him go to the Kings. If Van Boxmeer goes to the Kings, it could
only help the Ice Dogs' relationship with the NHL team.
</P>
<P>
   A curious fact about Van Boxmeer's four seasons as the Ice Dogs'
coach is that his run with the organization is extremely long by
hockey coaching standards.
</P>
<P>
   With Ron Low announcing that he is stepping down as the Edmonton
Oilers' coach, that leaves only one NHL head coach Scotty Bowman,
who took over the Detroit Red Wings for the 1993-94 season who has
been with his team longer than Van Boxmeer has been with the Ice
Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   COUNT ON 14
</P>
<P>
   Barring an off-season surprise, the IHL will have 14 teams next
season, down from 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas Thunder folded, and the Fort Wayne Komets most
likely will move to the United Hockey League. Although Fort Wayne
keeps edging toward moving, the team has not officially announced
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
