<SLUG> BC-MISSING-EVIDENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WON'T FACE THIRD TRIAL IN SLAYING OF HIS WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BENITA Y. WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ After two murder trials and almost eight
years in jail, Clarence Dexter on Monday left the Clay County
Courthouse a free man.
</P>
<P>
   Special prosecutor Tim Finnical dropped the first-degree murder
charge against Dexter in the death of his wife, Carol, because key
evidence has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   The case began to crumble this spring when prosecutors could not
find a police 911 tape, samples of a T-shirt Dexter allegedly wore
the night of the killing, bullet fragments from the autopsy and a
newspaper from the crime scene with a bloody footprint on it.
</P>
<P>
   Finnical asked for the dismissal after a two-hour debate about
evidence with Dexter's lawyers. Finnical first requested a recess
to privately tell Carol Dexter's family of his plans.
</P>
<P>
   When the case was dismissed, Clarence Dexter quietly said
``thank you'' and hugged his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Dexter's family was silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our tears have dried up a long time ago,'' her brother,
Olan Thrasher, said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not letting him out because he's innocent,'' he said.
``They're letting him out because they lost the evidence....What we
wanted was closure and justice, and we haven't gotten it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finnical said he would continue searching for the evidence and
would refile charges if it is found.
</P>
<P>
   ``That evidence could turn up,'' he said. ``If I go forward now
and I lose and three weeks later they find these items, I'm going
to look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrasher said his family is devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give them a couple or three weeks to find (the
evidence)...,'' Thrasher said. ``But someone has to be held
responsible....Someone has to take responsibility for letting
(Dexter) walk free.''
</P>
<P>
   Dexter, 57, who developed heart, colon and kidney problems in
jail, left court in a wheelchair and later celebrated at his
lawyer's office with a chocolate milkshake and pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is get a pole and go fishing,'' Dexter said.
``I knew I was innocent all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dexter said he planned to live with his mother in Butler, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter was accused of shooting his 50-year-old wife four times
at their Kansas City, North, home on Nov. 18, 1990. Prosecutors
alleged that Dexter then went to the supermarket. When he returned
and found her still alive, prosecutors alleged, he beat her with a
hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter contended that an intruder killed his wife and that he
found her body after returning from the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   His first trial ended in a mistrial. The Missouri Supreme Court
overturned a murder verdict in his second trial because lawyers
talked in court about how Dexter was silent when arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Finnical said Monday that he is looking through evidence bags
from other Clay County cases that went to trial in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The missing items ``could have been inadvertently placed in with
evidence from other cases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter's defense team, public defenders Cyndy Short and Tom
Jacquinot, issued a three-page statement Monday saying that
evidence in the case _ including several items that are missing _
is flawed.
</P>
<P>
   They said that investigators ignored a broken pane of plastic
glass and an unidentified palm print at the scene that could prove
that a burglar killed Carol Dexter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
