<HEADLINE>
FOUR MONTHS AFTER SHOOTOUT WITH POLICE, ESCAPED INMATE RECAPTURED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An inmate who escaped from jail a month after
a shootout that left five Missouri law officers wounded was
recaptured in Missouri on Monday night, Chariton County sheriff's
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No other details on the capture were available.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Lee Fisher escaped about 8:20 p.m. Sunday by picking a
lock on his shackles with a piece of wire and breaking through a
fence in the jail's exercise yard, Chariton County Sheriff Chris
Hughes said. Fisher struck a female guard who tried to stop him and
ran east from the prison, the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was among 20 inmates in the exercise yard under the
supervision of two jailers, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were holding him until he was ready for court,'' Hughes
said. ``I dealt with him personally. We had him about a month. He
wasn't a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was involved in a shootout with police in Huntsville,
Mo., in February. That shootout followed an escape by Fisher and
two other inmates from a Georgia prison.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two dozen state, county and city law enforcement agencies
in and around Keytesville in north-central Missouri searched for
Fisher Sunday night and Monday, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher had been scheduled to appear in court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is originally from Belle, Mo., and has family and friends
in Boone County, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   He had been serving an eight-year sentence for kidnapping at the
Georgia State Prison in Reidsville, but on Feb. 15 he and two other
men hid in the back of a food service van as it left the prison,
overpowered the driver and escaped.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fugitives, Danny E. Pierce, 48, was captured soon
after the escape.
</P>
<P>
   Officers tracked Fisher, 28, and Roy Kenneth Sanford, 30, to a
trailer in Huntsville early Feb. 25. Five officers from Huntsville
and nearby Moberly were wounded in the shootout before the
fugitives surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The officers had thrown tear gas into the trailer to smoke the
men out. After waiting about 45 minutes, the officers walked toward
the trailer to arrest the two, believing they were unconscious. But
as the officers reached the door, police say, the fugitives began
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Two officers were shot in the face and two others were hit in
the legs. Another was grazed by a bullet. Police believe the
fugitives used rags as makeshift gas masks.
</P>
<P>
   After about 25 minutes of gunfire, Sanford and Fisher waved a
white rag out a window, threw out their shotgun and surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher has an extensive arrest record. He was convicted in 1991
of kidnapping and robbery in Pulaski County, Mo. In 1994, he began
serving an eight-year sentence in Georgia for kidnapping charges
there. Sanford was serving 60 years for armed robbery, aggravated
assault and kidnapping. Pierce had been serving a life sentence for
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and Sanford also are charged in the February shootout.
Both men were charged with five counts of first-degree assault on a
law enforcement officer, six counts of armed criminal action and
one count of first-degree burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher last month pleaded not guilty to the charges, telling the
judge, ``They shot me first.'' Sanford also pleaded not guilty.
The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
