<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Basque Talks Confirmed
</P>
<P>
   Ending days of speculation, Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar said
at a news conference that aides from his conservative government
have met directly with leaders of the Basque separatist group ETA
to explore peace prospects. The rebels are blamed for about 800
deaths since 1968 in their fight for an independent Basque
homeland, but they have observed a cease-fire since September.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Pinochet Lawyers Drop Appeal
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Lawyers for Gen. Augusto Pinochet dropped their
challenge to a decision giving the go-ahead to hearings on his
possible extradition to Spain to face torture charges. A High Court
justice turned aside their challenge last week, but they could have
appealed that ruling to a three-judge panel of the court.
Extradition hearings are due to begin Sept. 27 in London.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Social Democrats Gain
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democratic Party made
large gains in elections in Bremen, the smallest of Germany's 16
states. The Social Democrats, led by Premier Henning Scherf, won
42.6 percent of the vote, up from about 33 percent in 1995. The
Christian Democrats won 37.1 percent, up from 33 percent four years
ago. The environmentalist Greens took heavy losses, dropping from
13.1 percent in 1995 to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland: Ex-Spy Ordered Out
</P>
<P>
   Richard Tomlinson, a former British agent accused of publishing
on the Internet the names of people he said were fellow agents, has
been told to leave Switzerland. He is ``an undesirable person,''
said a spokesman for the Swiss attorney general's office. Tomlinson
is being investigated on the ground that he violated a Geneva
court's order not to publish any agents' names. Tomlinson, who has
been living in Geneva, has denied listing any names on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   North Korea: China Trip Ends
</P>
<P>
   A senior North Korean delegation returned home after a five-day
visit to China with both sides saying they had reaffirmed friendly
ties. During the visit, led by Kim Yong Nam, chief of Parliament
and the highest ranking North Korean to visit China in eight years,
China pledged to give its stricken neighbor 150,000 tons of grain
and 400,000 tons of coal this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir: Indian Plea to Pakistan
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide broadcast, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
of India asked Pakistan to ``undo'' the armed intrusion in Kashmir
and said talks between the two countries could be held only on one
issue _ how Pakistan proposes to end it. The Indian army said 221
Pakistani soldiers had died in Kashmir. Pakistan said only 19 or 20
of its soldiers had been killed and that it provides only
diplomatic and moral backing for rebels fighting in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Libya: Lockerbie Trial Delayed
</P>
<P>
   Two Libyans awaiting trial in the Netherlands on charges of
being involved in the blowing up of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in 1988, have been given an extra six months to prepare
their defense. It means that the trial, taking place on Dutch soil
but under Scottish law, is not likely to begin before next February
and may be delayed even further.
</P>
</TEXT>
