<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKS DON'T KNOW HOW TO FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's even money what I find more silly when athletes resort to
fists to settle their differences the fight itself, or the
post-mortem media reflections.
</P>
<P>
   As for the actual confrontation, it inevitably proves, as the
Dodgers' Chan Ho Park showed graphically the other afternoon during
his crude frolic with the Angels' Tim Belcher, that most
well-conditioned jocks haven't the faintest idea of how to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Park's scandalously inept kick to Belcher's ample
midriff had to be the most embarrassing moment for karate since a
bodyguard named Chuck Zito floored martial arts film star Jean
Claude Van Damme last year at a New York gentlemen's club called
Scores, or at least since Steve Seagal was choked out on a movie
set a while back by stunt man Gene LeBell.
</P>
<P>
   But even more inane than Park's temporary lost of sanity was
those who viewed Park's move as a heroic gesture that actually lit
an inspirational fire to his lifeless team, saying it wasn't
exactly a coincidence that the Dodgers staged a game-winning
five-run rally an inning after Park committed his indiscretion.
</P>
<P>
   Humbug!
</P>
<P>
   I quite doubt that Devon White drew his motivation to hit his
dramatic grand slam that inning from Park's ridiculous outburst.
</P>
<P>
   It long has been the view here that the most farcical fights
I've seen and I've seen several thousand over the years have not
been in the ring, but, instead, on the ice, hardwoods and sporting
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes untrained in defending themselves should resist their
macho inclinations during periods of temper because all they wind
up doing is setting themselves up for cruel ridicule when the taped
highlights of their actions are continually replayed on the nightly
sports shows.
</P>
<P>
   How mortifying do you think it was for Alonzo Mourning and Larry
Johnson when their sorority-like pillow squabble last year was
shown over and over again on TV?
</P>
<P>
   What did their less than memorable quarrel prove, that neither
hadn't the foggiest notion how to throw a punch, or duck one?
</P>
<P>
   Athletic fights are meaningless, anyway, because the combatants
are well aware that they will be quickly separated by arbiters and
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, if a couple of antagonists are serious about resolving
hostilities, why don't they choose to settle matters in a venue
where there is no one around to intervene?
</P>
<P>
   This is a tack the late combative manager, Billy Martin, pursued
several times during his career, once as a player meeting a tough
catcher named Clint Courtney under the ball park stands in
Washington D.C. and giving him a frightful beating.
</P>
<P>
   A most famous incident during the 1963 NFL season occurred when
a couple of Philadelphia Eagle players, Ben Scotti, a 180-pound
defensive back, and John Mellekas, a 250-pound defensive tackle,
duked it out in a hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Scotti emerged triumphant, as he unmercifully beat
up Mellekas, leaving him bloodied and battered and barely
conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Shamefully, your unflappable correspondent must admit he once
lost control of his senses, although he displayed fine sporting
instincts in sticking to the Marquis of Queensberry rules and never
cutting lose with the kind of comical flying leg kick that Chan Ho
Park must have learned from watching old Charlie Chaplin movies.
</P>
<P>
   As a senior at Fowler High School in the San Joaquin Valley a
few years back, I got into a fight in the school's main hallway
that was broken up immediately by a couple of teachers that ushered
me and my adversary into the vice-principal's office.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was one of those trivial misunderstandings and since no
serious punches were landed, the proper thing would have for both
of us to quickly make up and accept whatever minimal punishment
that was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we glared at each other and refused to shake hands,
leading the vice-principal to shake his head disapprovingly and
decide on a plan that would be unthinkable in these litigious days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys wanna fight so bad I'm goin' to give you the
opportunity,'' he said. ``Let's go to the gym right now, and you
guys can put on the gloves and fight to your heart's content.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what we did.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing boxing gloves but bereft of headgear and mouthpiece, we
went after each other with a vengeance without a break for about 15
minutes in the closed gym, in front of the vice-principal, the
school nurse and the head football coach.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to report that I wound up the stirring winner,
but that would be a Clintonesque fib because the match ended the
moment I dropped to my knees from overwhelming exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, such a lengthy brawl taught me a painful and
humbling lesson fighting should be the sole refuge of people who do
it for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Those faux-gladiators you see flailing haplessly away like Chan
Ho Park only make fools out of themselves and serve no viable
purpose other than to unnecessarily interrupt the flow of a game
and cause a few cackles among the onlookers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
