u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-TICKETS-COX     06-07 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-TICKETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs win prompts box-office bonanza
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Shelby Brown arrived for work at Ticket
City on Monday at 6 a.m., two hours before the ticket brokerage
firm opened for business, the phones already were ringing.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been a hint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's off the wall,'' Brown said several hours later as phones
rang incessantly in the background, the majority of callers
inquiring about tickets to see the San Antonio Spurs play in the
NBA Finals. ``I can't even pick up the phone fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently folks are willing to pay to see history _ pay big, in
many cases. The Spurs' first trip to the Finals in their 26-year
existence in San Antonio had ticket buyers and sellers scrambling
on Monday in advance of the first two games, which will be played
in the Alamodome. The first game of the Finals is scheduled to
start as early as June 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs announced at 4 p.m. Monday that the first two games
were officially sold out in the Dome, which will have a seating
capacity of slightly more than 38,000 for the Finals. Tickets for
any other possible home games in the 2-3-2 Finals arrangement won't
go on sale until it's known if there will be a sixth game in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty wild around here,'' said Pat Quinn, the
Spurs' director of ticket operations. ``Normally I'm on vacation
this time of year, but I certainly don't mind delaying my vacation
for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans started camping out in the Alamodome parking lot Saturday.
They were allowed to begin lining up Sunday evening as soon as the
Spurs clinched the Western Conference title at Portland, although
tickets didn't go on sale until 8 a.m. Monday. The scene was no
less chaotic at several Austin ticket brokerages, some of whom were
offering courtside seats for between $4,000 and $6,500 each,
although there had been no takers for those by late Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nuts. I didn't expect it to be this crazy,'' said Tracy
Morris of Showtime Tickets in Austin. ``Man, I'm tired of saying,
'$85 and up.' If I had a dollar for every time I've said '$85 and
up,' I'd be rich by now.''
</P>
<P>
   For $85, a buyer could get a ticket in the upper reaches of the
Alamodome behind the basket, a seat that normally sells for $5
during the regular season. But in the Finals, even the official
face value for that ticket has increased to $15. First-row floor
seats that normally have a face value of $325 during the season are
selling for $500 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The interest is) kind of like when the Final Four was in San
Antonio, but with a more localized crowd,'' Showtime owner Kent
Taylor said. ``About 95 percent of the calls are from people
comparing prices. I didn't expect the amount of calls, but I felt
more people would be buying than have actually bought.''
</P>
<P>
   UT TicketMaster received about 450 tickets for each of the first
two Finals games in San Antonio. They went on sale at about 30
H-E-B outlets at 8 a. m. Monday and were gone in about 15 minutes,
which TicketMaster manager David Hess said is not unusual for a
high-demand event.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Riggs writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
