r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX     06-07 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW THAT BELFOUR'S CALM, HE'S REALLY UNDER PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DALLAS _ Ed Belfour has never had less control of his future. And
yet he's never been more in control.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest story of the Stars goalie, in fact, drips irony. It
is somewhere between a Dickens novel and a Danielle Steel
miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he got into actually thinking about everything that's going
on, I think it would be a little overwhelming,'' said Buddy Voth,
Belfour's business manager and friend since childhood. ``Right now,
he's focused on winning, and that's all that matters to him.''
</P>
<P>
   As Belfour steps onto the ice tonight at Reunion Arena to face
the Buffalo Sabres in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals, he will
stare down his past and wonder about his future. Belfour, 34, has
the chance to finally grasp the Cup that he has dreamed about since
a hockey-bred youth in the tiny farming community of Carman,
Manitoba. He has the chance to silence critics who for years have
said he can't win the big one. He has the chance to lay claim to a
home he has been seeking, possibly for his entire life.
</P>
<P>
   Or, he could end up blowing his big chance at redemption and
never play in a Stars uniform again. The possibility exists that Ed
Belfour could be the property of the expansion Atlanta Thrashers at
the end of the month, that he could be further from his goal than
ever in his career.
</P>
<P>
   That's how important this is. Ed Belfour's crossroads will come
in the next two weeks _ a fortnight that will forever burn as a
turning point in his life. And how will the enigmatic Belfour
respond?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just concentrating on playing hockey; it's
pretty simple,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, and maybe for the first time in his NHL life, Ed
Belfour has one goal in mind. Controlled and composed In the past,
nothing Ed Belfour did was simple. In the past, he was both admired
and feared, scrutinized and convicted. In the past, Ed Belfour was
a conundrum. But that was the past. Today, at a time when Belfour
should be under the most pressure in his career, he is controlled
and composed and witty and ... normal.
</P>
<P>
   And that might be the greatest irony of all. Ed Belfour, normal
guy _ it sends shock waves through the hockey world. Ed Belfour,
the guy who has fought with backup goalies. That's what you expect.
Ed Belfour, one of the most penalized goalies in league history.
That's what you expect. Ed Belfour, the perfectionist, loner,
wild-eyed, stick-swinging rebel without a clue. That's what you
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more. And the difference is tangible, Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Belfour was a defensive person when he came here. And for
us to get the best out of Ed Belfour, the determination was that we
needed the defense mechanisms dropped,'' Hitchcock said. ``And
they're dropped. He's happy where he lives. He's just a happier
person.''
</P>
<P>
   So how can Hitchcock tell? Well, for one thing, Hitchcock said
he has actually heard Belfour whistling at practice. And secondly,
he hasn't heard Belfour blame anyone else for a goal _ a trait that
used to make teammates cringe, a flaw that maybe even kept him from
the ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's willing to look in the mirror at the end of the game,''
Hitchcock said. ``He's not willing to talk in terms of `It went
over here and it hit a bird and flew into the net' or whatever.
He's just talking normal. When he talks normal, and when he talks
black and white, realistic stuff, then he's being truthful with
himself. And that's what he's being.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's comfortable here,'' Hitchcock added.
</P>
<P>
   Voth, his business manager and friend, said Belfour would like
to stay in North Texas. The Stars at the end of the month will have
to make a decision on keeping either Belfour or 29-year-old
wunderkind backup goalie Roman Turek. An expansion draft will be
held to stock the Atlanta Thrashers, and the Stars will be able to
protect only one goalie. Either Belfour or Turek will be traded or
made available for the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation, and they really haven't let him know
one way or the other,'' Voth said. ``He really wants to focus on
the game and not let that bother him. But I think if you asked him,
he'd love to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has found a home, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everywhere he's been he's looked for a place where he
could be comfortable. And I think he's found it here,'' Hitchcock
said. ``I really believe he sees this as home.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour is a divorced father of two, and his children still live
in Chicago with their mother. And although moving away from his
children was difficult, Belfour has come to grips with the
situation. Facing his past Now, ironically, he will look back at
that rocky past _ the rough days in Chicago that helped lead to the
divorce from his wife and from his former team, the Blackhawks _ to
see if he can build a better future.
</P>
<P>
   Across the rink tonight will be Buffalo Sabres all-world goalie
Dominik Hasek. Once a backup to Belfour, who owned the NHL in 1992
as Chicago went to the Finals, Hasek has since gone on to pass
Belfour's accomplishments. Belfour has two Vezina trophies (1991,
'93), the award given to the NHL's top goalie annually; Hasek is
expected to win his fifth this season. Belfour has won three
Jennings trophies for having the lowest goals-against average.
Hasek is the only goalie in NHL history to twice be chosen league
MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a great job; he's a great goalie,'' Belfour said.
``What can you say.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who want to say Belfour hated Hasek and that
Hasek hated Belfour. There are those who want to say this battle of
goalies will forge forever which one is better, which one gets his
first Cup, which one reaches the goal.
</P>
<P>
   The old Belfour might have bitten on such a confrontational
issue. The new Belfour just laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything wrong with the relationship,'' Belfour
said. ``Maybe he had a problem with it because I was the No. 1 guy,
and whenever that's the case and the other goalie wants to be the
No. 1 guy. Maybe he doesn't feel comfortable. I didn't ever have a
problem with Dominik.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, that's not to say Belfour wasn't competitive. He has
been competitive since he kicked around the cradle. He has been
competitive every day that Voth has known him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't be around Eddie without getting into a battle
over something,'' Voth said.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Belfour, Ed's mother, said the family couldn't ``just go
fishing'' when Ed was young.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to have a fishing tournament,'' she said. ``Eddie had
to have the biggest fish or the most fish. When he played baseball,
he had to strike everybody out.''
</P>
<P>
   And that competitiveness is still there, players assure. But the
Norman Bates unpredictability seems to be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it in his eyes,'' Stars winger Pat Verbeek said. ``You
can see he's focused, you can see he wants to play the best that he
can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hrkac, Belfour's roommate on the road and his teammate when
they both played for 1987 NCAA champion North Dakota, said Belfour
has matured.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that book, ``Don't Sweat The Small Stuff'',' '' Hrkac
said. ``I think he read that.''
</P>
<P>
   And even in the eye of this maelstrom, this life-changing
playoffs, Belfour has kept the small stuff at a distance. He has
been chatty with the media, calm in his crease, downright humble in
the face of hot-dog tactics by Colorado Avalanche goalie Patrick
Roy. In the end, Belfour's newfound inner peace probably helped
produce the victory over the much-ballyhooed Roy. In the end, it
was Belfour drawing all the praise and Roy being accused of a
meltdown. In the end, it seems, Ed Belfour can best control his
critics _ best control his future _ by staying in control.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it wasn't that difficult a lesson for Belfour to
learn, once he bought into the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's probably matured. I think we all do,'' Alma
Belfour said. ``Let me tell you, you're never too old to mature.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
