<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SERIALKILLER-CO     06-07 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SERIALKILLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One man is being sought for questioning in Weimar homicides
 &HT;    By Kelly Daniel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMAR, Texas _ No one simply goes to bed here these days.
</P>
<P>
   There are flood lights to install, position and watch. Guns to
load, and clench. Locks to turn, some for the first time in a
lifetime. Police are hunting a killer, and the 2,000 residents here
are facing a new, unwanted neighbor: fear.
</P>
<P>
   Three people who lived in or near Weimar have been bludgeoned to
death in their beds in the past 37 days, the killer entering
darkened homes that sit within a stone's throw of railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Two Houston women have been killed in similar fashion and,
although police investigators haven't determined if the cases are
linked, one man is being sought for questioning in all the
homicides.
</P>
<P>
   In Weimar, where vacant storefronts outnumber thriving
businesses and the mostly elderly populace has gone decades without
locking their doors, the town's ``dying and bored'' way of life has
slipped into haggard wariness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, death comes to a small town,'' said Jill Dwyer,
owner of Weimar Country Grocery. ``I don't want to be here. I don't
want to sleep here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such fright didn't exist until Josephine Konvicka, 73, was
discovered beaten to death Friday in her Fayette County home about
four miles west of Weimar. Her slaying came nearly five weeks after
the Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife, Karen, 47, were
found May 2, beaten to death with a sledgehammer in the parsonage
of the Weimar United Church of Christ, where he was the minister
and she the church secretary.
</P>
<P>
   People either grew up in Weimar or came to escape Houston or San
Antonio, both within 100 miles. Most folks are hard pressed to
recall Weimar's last homicide _ a bar brawl nearly 20 years ago _
and say crime here usually stops at simple break-ins.
</P>
<P>
   The Sirnic slayings had been shocking, the kind of news that
hits like a punch to the windpipe. The city was just beginning to
recover when Konvicka's death halted people in their tracks,
raising goosebumps on their skin, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once that lady that lived out there got it, too, you started
thinking, `Yeah, he's really in this area,' '' said Michael Wick,
whose family owns the town's Western Auto.
</P>
<P>
   Police are looking for Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, 38, considered a
suspect in the Sirnic deaths. He was featured in an ``America's
Most Wanted'' television segment over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar Police Chief Bill Livingston, who is heading the
investigation, did not return repeated phone calls and was not at
the police station Monday afternoon. Fayette County Sheriff Rick
Vandel said his department believes Resendez-Ramirez has left the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez also is a suspect in the December 1998
bludgeoning death of Dr. Claudia Benton of Houston, and Houston
police are investigating a second bludgeoning death _ of Noemi
Dominguez, 26, found Saturday _ for similarities. Both women lived
near railroad tracks. Kentucky police also want to question
Resendez-Ramirez about the 1997 slaying of a University of Kentucky
student.
</P>
<P>
   There are few other topics of conversation in Weimar these days.
Friends and relatives trade rumors _ he was spotted in Flatonia,
where officers searched railroad tracks with bloodhounds Sunday; he
was seen under someone's front porch; he was noticed atop a
railroad boxcar _ while shopkeepers and customers trade security
tips.
</P>
<P>
   The M-G Inc. store, where browsers can find everything from
garden seeds to hunting equipment, sold several guns first thing
Monday morning, ran through its entire stock of Mace and did a
steady business in security lighting kits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got plenty of shells,'' said Erna Rose, 70, a lifelong
Weimar resident. She came to the store for a bulb for her outdoor
security light, having already taken out her shotgun at home and
loaded it. ``Everybody's coming home earlier at night, not staying
out after dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Every person has a story, either his own or a friend's, of
teen-agers too scared to sleep alone, of elderly relatives moving
in with family members, of lights being kept on all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of scared people (and) a lot of people with guns by
their beds,'' said Dwayne Wick, Michael's brother.
</P>
<P>
   The healing has begun at the Sirnics' church, where crime scene
tape was removed from the parsonage around the same time it was
going up around Konvicka's single-story white house over the
weekend. The church entered into a contract with an interim
minister on Monday, hiring the Rev. Ralph Ludwig of El Paso, said
Ted Neely, president of the Weimar United Church of Christ council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the fear level is totally different now because of
what's happened'' with Konvicka's death, Neely said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents are using a label no one has officially attached
to the cases _ ``serial killer'' _ while others alternate between
sorrowful acceptance and a growing cynicism about the erosion of
that quintessential intangible: small town values.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear people say 'It never happened here before,' ``
Dwyer said. ``But it's everywhere. Get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Daniel writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
