</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGBAYANI HITS TWO HOMERS AS METS WIN BACK NORMALCY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets desperately want some normalcy to
return to their season. After three coaches were dismissed and
Bobby Valentine was sent in an obvious message about his own
status, after the draining series with the Yankees last weekend and
after finally ending their eight-game losing streak on Sunday, the
Mets would love to focus on baseball and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is normal for the Mets is still uncertain. Are they a
dysfunctional team that will continue to underachieve and
eventually cost Valentine his managerial job? Are they a talented
team whose starting pitchers will eventually perform better and
push them into post-season contention? No one knows yet.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Benny Agbayani can help the Mets answer those tricky
questions. Maybe Agbayani can continue forcing the fans to chant
``Ben-ny, Ben-ny'' and continue to help guide the Mets back to what
they hope is normalcy. Agbayani ripped two homers as the Mets
silenced the Blue Jays, 8-2, Monday night at Shea Stadium, which,
oddly enough, was almost a normal night for the burly outfielder
who is fast becoming the most popular of Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Following Agbayani's second two-homer game in 19 days, he has
eight homers in 63 at bats this season and has proven again and
again that Valentine must start him every day, erratic glove and
all. Agbayani launched two homers off Roy Halladay, Mike Piazza
also stroked one against the 22-year old and Orel Hershiser was
gritty for six innings as the Mets won their second straight game.
That had not happened since May 25 and 26.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets managed to exhale for the second night in a row.
Obviously, it will take more than two victories for the Mets to
obscure eight straight games of futility. But there were positive
signs for the Mets. Hershisher hung onto a 2-0 lead the Mets built
in the first by limiting the Jays to three hits in 13 at bats with
men on base, by spearing two sharp grounders to foil rally attempts
and by allowing two earned runs. The 40-year old has won three of
his last four starts and is 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   When Agbayani and Roger Cedeno contributed to Monday night's
victory, Valentine probably felt vindicated since he fielded
questions about his lineup before the game. Even after the Mets
beat Roger Clemens and the Yankees, 7-2, on Sunday, Rickey
Henderson insisted that a cloud of negativity hovered above the
Mets because five outfielders do not fit into three positions. The
attitudes worried him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get that way,'' said Henderson. ``If we get that way,
you might as well say we're done. We can't win that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson proceeded to claim that he told Valentine he would
monitor the other outfielders and try to stop negativity from
invading the clubhouse. But Valentine did not act like a manager
who is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sounds. Yeah, there's sounds,'' said Valentine, when
asked if he noticed negativity. ``Just so you understand, I am not
going to play what I don't think is the best lineup to eliminate
the sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The only sounds Monday night emanated from rowdy fans at Shea
and they were in favor of the lineup that had Cedeno in right,
Brian McRae in center and Agbayani in left and Henderson and Bobby
Bonilla left out. How can Valentine not start Agbayani? How about
Cedeno? Cedeno had three hits, scored a run and pilfered his major
league best 31st base while Agbayani blasted a homer in the fourth
to break a 2-2 tie and crushed another in his next at bat.
Agbayani, who was intentionally walked before he could shoot for
three straight, has 22 hits in his last 46 at bats. For a 27-year
old who had 22 days of service in the majors before this year,
Agbayani's ascent has been astounding.
</P>
<P>
   Which outfielders sit today? Valentine already told Henderson he
is playing and it will be almost impossible for him to bench
Agbayani or Cedeno. It is a dilemma that will follow Valentine all
summer if the Mets do not move any outfielders. But it will be much
easier for Valentine if the Mets find what they hope is normalcy
and keep winning.
</P>
</TEXT>
