</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprawl explanations _ unlike solutions _ abound
</P>
<P>
   BY TOM BAXTER
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Should they run out of conversation starters, the new
members of the Georgia Regional Transportation Authority might want
to look at an article by a University of Kentucky professor,
Jefferson Edgens, on how estate taxes cause sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Edgens' thesis, buttressed with statistics from Georgia, is that
by forcing the inheritors of family farms into selling out to
developers sooner than they would have, estate taxes have speeded
the process by which farmland and open space get converted into
shopping centers and subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   Not to say he doesn't have a point _ estate taxes do have a
pernicious effect on small businesses and family farms. But Edgens'
argument illustrates a primary difficulty the GRTA board will face
as it sets about its task: It's a lot easier to come up with novel
explanations for how we got in this mess than it is to propose
realistic solutions for getting us out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Since he named the board last week, Gov. Roy Barnes _ who has
thus far been on an extended honeymoon _ has taken lumps from
various corners for naming a board with noticeably little
representation from CEOs, environmentalists or community activists.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes seemed unperturbed by the criticism Monday at a
conference on public transit at Georgia State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not about bringing a halt to growth,'' the governor
said at a luncheon session. ``Georgia and Atlanta need to continue
to grow. It's how we grow that is at issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to compare GRTA with the Education Review
Commission, also named last week.
</P>
<P>
   The ed board also has some notable omissions, with little
representation from the state's big education interest groups. Like
GRTA, it is stamped with a big ``RB'' monogram: Loyalty to the
governor was obviously not a detriment to getting on either board.
It follows that Barnes will be accountable for the success or
failure of both.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference is that GRTA, about which there was much more
speculation before it was named, has 15 members, while the
relatively less heralded Education Review Commission has a whopping
63, with Barnes himself as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that on educational issues, Barnes is content to
let a thousand flowers bloom, generating a lot of ideas and culling
from them as he puts his legislative agenda in place.
</P>
<P>
   GRTA, on the other hand, seems more like a limited-access
highway, put in place to move things in a direction already
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawl means a lot of different things to different people _ a
point made by Sam Staley, a critic of anti-growth policies, at a
luncheon last week sponsored by the Georgia Public Policy
Foundation (which also published the Edgens paper).
</P>
<P>
   Barnes on Monday offered his own definition. Sprawl isn't
suburban or exurban growth, he said, but ``the failure to recognize
that growth and infrastructure must go hand in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   That failure being obvious to anybody who's ever been in a
mile-long traffic jam at noon on a two-lane in north Fulton, it's
up to the governor and his board to do something about it. And now
is when the rubber meets the road.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution political editor Tom Baxter
provides opinion, analysis and commentary in his column.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
