</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JOUSTING WITH BELGRADE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 8: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic is a master at using delay, surprise and
confusion to divide his opponents, and he is now using all three to
undermine the peace agreement that he accepted in Belgrade last
week. NATO will prevail in this diplomatic contest if it remains
faithful to the peace deal, retains a reasonable degree of Russian
cooperation and keeps military pressure on Serbian forces until
Milosevic orders them removed from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate obstacle to peace is Belgrade's refusal to accept
a detailed NATO plan for the rapid withdrawal of Serbian forces and
the arrival of international peacekeepers, most of them from the
alliance. Serbian generals balked at the plan over the weekend,
arguing that seven days was not enough time to exit Kosovo. They
also maintained that as many as 15,000 Serbian troops could remain
behind, though no such deal was made in Belgrade, and that
peacekeeping units could not move into the province until the
United Nations Security Council approves the operation. Milosevic
is clearly playing for time, hoping that Russian and Chinese
misgivings about the details, coupled with their veto power in the
Security Council, will lead to more favorable peace terms for
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal timetable can easily be extended by a week if
Serbian forces in Kosovo lack the fuel required for a speedy
departure, and if roads and bridges hit by NATO bombs must first be
repaired. But all Serbian forces have to leave, as agreed last
week. A small number may return once Kosovo is pacified. NATO
planes should not hesitate to continue bombing Serbian troops in
Kosovo while Milosevic is obstructing peace.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. role in Kosovo is important, but need not be cause for
diluting the peace terms that Milosevic approved. He knew that NATO
would send in a force of 50,000 peacekeepers, including 7,000
Americans. Several thousand Russian soldiers may also participate.
If possible, all the troops should be dispatched under a U.N.
mandate to show the broadest possible support, and Kosovo should be
temporarily placed under U.N. administration. There is no reason
for Russia or China to oppose these measures. If anything, U.N.
involvement would make the foreign presence more palatable for
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But the Security Council can become a graveyard for good
intentions. Washington needs to guard against that by insuring that
a Kosovo resolution closely adheres to the peace plan. That means,
among other things, that peacekeeping forces operate under a NATO
chain of command rather than the muddled system the U.N. used in
Bosnia before the Dayton peace agreement. Russian concern about the
peacekeeping force and other issues slowed the drafting of a U.N.
resolution yesterday by Washington and its allies. To encourage
Russian and Chinese cooperation, NATO may need to cut back on
bombing over Serbia itself for now. The endgame with Milosevic is
always difficult, but unless he disowns the peace deal he endorsed,
the mechanics for ending the war in an acceptable way can be worked
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0508 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-FACILITY-     06-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FACILITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXCLUSIVE: Falcons consider new nest
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First came the big rock _ Stone Mountain. Then
Southern history was chiseled upon the rock, a park was built
around it and a laser show created.
</P>
<P>
   And now Stone Mountain's attractions may also include the
Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials have signed a letter of intent with Stone
Mountain Park, and with the private company that manages the park,
to build a training complex at the recreation area. Under the
agreement, Silver Dollar City, a Branson, Mo., company that
specializes in managing theme parks, would build a training
facility there and then lease the facility and about 30 acres to
the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   The area will be leased because the park is owned by the state,
and none of its 3,200 acres can be sold without an act of the state
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Nobis, Falcons vice president of corporate development,
said it is premature to assume that the deal is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a nonbinding letter of intent,'' said Nobis, who is in
charge of the project. ``We have essentially given them additional
time to . . . research to see if they can deliver what they say
they can. It's not a big story yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious benefit is that the team could have someone
else pay to build a 70,000-square-foot office building and locker
room, multiple practice fields and a domed 80-yard practice field _
all at a price tag expected to be well above $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also might have marketing opportunities _ such as a
gift shop, and/or Hall of Fame _ that don't exist at the team's
outdated 21-year-old facility in Suwanee, in Gwinnett County. About
4 million tourists visit Stone Mountain Park annually.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same sales pitch heard by the Braves when they made
Disney World their spring training home in 1998. The Braves moved
their spring training site from West Palm Beach, Fla., to the
Disney complex just outside Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Stone Mountain, located about 15 miles east of downtown Atlanta,
was a late-comer to the process, entering the race two months ago
after the Falcons had narrowed their list of potential sites. The
other six sites _ two each in Barrow and Hall counties, one in
Forsyth and another in Suwanee _ could not offer the same benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The facility is expected to be built near the old Stone Mountain
Airport, east of the mountain. The airport closed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent site because nothing has to be taken down,
and it's flat,'' said Ned Stancliff, senior vice president of
Silver Dollar City. ``The details of how we cross-market are to be
worked out, but it's the No. 1 tourist attraction in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very honored and flattered that the Falcons would even
consider us. All the parties involved have worked extremely hard to
get the Falcons to be in Stone Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Those groups included the Atlanta Convention and Business
Bureau, the state Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism, the
Atlanta Sports Council and the DeKalb County Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Stone Mountain officials ``are going to build a facility for
(the Falcons), period,'' Suwanee Mayor Chris Yoder said. Suwanee
had proposed that the Falcons move about 3 miles north and remain
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's economics,'' Yoder said. ``How can you beat that? Do I
like it? No. How is that going to affect people who go to the park?
Are ticket prices going to go up at the park to pay for this? I
better not say more. The Falcons have been a very good neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has outgrown the 20,000-square-foot building it moved
into in 1978. Also, the value of the complex's more than 100 acres
_ along I-85 about 28 miles northeast of downtown Atlanta _ has
skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   Nobis said the notion that construction could begin in late July
or early August _ a must if the team is going to move in before the
2000 season _ is still just that, a notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to build a state-of-the-art facility, but . . .
we've got a lot of work to do,'' Nobis said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
