<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ROBERTSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HUMILIATION FOR A SCOTTISH BANK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 8: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland has emerged thoroughly embarrassed from its
ill-fated effort to get into consumer banking in the United States
in partnership with Pat Robertson, the television evangelist and
politician.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, which pioneered telephone banking in Scotland in
partnership with a grocery chain, agreed in March to start a
similar venture with Robertson. The hope was that it could combine
its expertise in dealing with customers via telephone and the
Internet with Robertson's mailing lists and ability to reach people
through his ``700 Club'' religious program.
</P>
<P>
   Then Robertson used that program to denigrate Scotland as ``a
dark place,'' adding that ``you can't believe how strong the
homosexuals are'' in Scotland. That made the front page of a
Scottish newspaper and provoked anger both from gay rights groups
and from Scottish citizens. Public pressure grew, and the Bank of
Scotland announced over the weekend it was backing out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement added that, in accordance with its contract
with Robertson, the bank was buying out his stake in the venture.
Neither the bank nor Robertson will comment on just how much that
will cost the bank, but it is remarkable that the bank must pay
even though it was Robertson's comments that scuttled the deal.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see whether Robertson, having gained
not only money but, perhaps, details of how to organize and operate
such a bank, now starts a similar venture without the Bank of
Scotland. (His spokesman would not comment on Robertson's plans.)
The bank, for its part, needs to be more careful both in its choice
of partners and in the contracts it signs with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
