<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYHEALTHCHIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DUBIOUS CHOICE AS HEALTH CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 8: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki's decision to name Antonia Novello as New
York state's new health commissioner has drawn angry responses from
Planned Parenthood and other abortion rights groups _ and for good
reason. In selecting Dr. Novello, a strong opponent of abortion
rights, to oversee the state agency in charge of insuring access to
the full range of reproductive health care, the ostensibly
pro-choice governor was plainly thinking more about improving his
standing in the national Republican Party than his duty to protect
the reproductive freedom of New York women.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes Dr. Novello's strengths. A pediatrician by
training, she campaigned strongly against the marketing of tobacco
and alcohol products to young people while she was President Bush's
Surgeon General. As commissioner she will make important day-to-day
decisions, many of them beyond public scrutiny, that affect the
availability of abortion services. Dr. Novello, who opposes
abortion except in cases of rape, incest or a threat to the health
of the mother, said her beliefs would not compromise her
performance. But one important duty of hers will be to enforce
rules mandating that providers of Medicaid managed care make
available referrals for abortion services. It is hard to believe
that someone who supported Bush's ``gag rule,'' prohibiting workers
at family planning programs receiving federal aid from even
discussing abortion with their patients, would approach this
particular obligation with much vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Novello's approval by the Republican-controlled State Senate
seems assured. But before confirmation she should be required to
explain how she plans to reconcile her anti-choice views with the
state's pro-choice policies. She can begin to reassure her critics
by promising now to preserve the special unit in the health
department that works to advance quality reproductive services.
Pataki says Dr. Novello's nomination is not a retreat from his
generally pro-choice stance. The proof will be in her performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
