<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0511 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTAL-HEALTH-CONFERE     06-07 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-HEALTH-CONFERENCE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS AND GORES ADDRESS ISSUES OF MENTAL HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 6th graf placing the conference at Howard Univ.
No other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Gores and Clintons shared a stage for two hours
at the White House Conference on Mental Health on Monday, and took
turns interviewing people who have struggled with mental illness as
a patient, parent or researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last great stigma of the 20th century that we need
to make sure ends here and now,'' said Tipper Gore, who ran the
show. She recently revealed that she had been clinically depressed
after her son, Albert, nearly died when he was hit by a car in 1989
when he was 6. ``I was not myself,'' she said of her own
experience, until she sought medical help, including medication.
``I'm happy to say that it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton asked Congress on Monday to ensure that
Americans with mental illness get the same insurance benefits for
treating depression as they do for treating physical ailments like
asthma, and announced that the federal government would now make
sure that employees are covered for mental illness just as they are
for any other malady. On Monday, the government sent a letter to
285 participating health plans telling them they must comply.
</P>
<P>
   The president also announced that 1,000 schools would get free
satellite programming on dealing with students prone to violence,
and announced several other programs for mentally ill homeless
people, elderly people and young Native American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been too long since we've come together over something
this real that touches so many of us,'' he said, and praised the
Gores by saying that while most politicians talk about family
values, ``no couple in public life has ever done remotely as much
to try and figure out how to help families.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, held at Howard University, was attended by
several hundred people and included several events throughout the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore is the president's mental health adviser, and bounded
upon the stage as if pumped as for a political rally, giving the
thumbs-up and even jumping a little at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting side by side for two hours, the family dynamic between
the Clintons and the Gores, at a time when Al Gore has been
portrayed as competing with Hillary Clinton as campaign season
approaches, ranged from supportive to adoring.
</P>
<P>
   Each nodded attentively at the others' remarks, and Mrs. Gore
introduced Hillary Clinton by saying that when it came to shedding
light on new research about how the brain works, ``no one could do
that any better than the sunshine of all our lives, our first lady,
Hillary Rodham Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton returned the compliment by saying, ``If I had any
voice I'd break into `You Are the Sunshine of My Life,' and
dedicate it to Tipper.''
</P>
<P>
   In her role as moderator, Mrs. Gore choreographed both Clintons
and her husband, at one point telling the vice president, ``You
might want to get up and go over now,'' pointing him toward a
corner where he was to interview two more people about their
experiences with mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am,'' he told her, laughing. ``I'm anxious to follow
instructions carefully, but to depart from my destruct _ or, to
depart from my instructions, I want to say I hope you can see how
proud I am of Tipper.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore began the program by interviewing Mike Wallace, of
television's ``60 Minutes,'' about his experience with depression,
sitting beside him and repeatedly patting his hand and arm as he
spoke. When, at one point, Wallace tried to break off, saying, ``I
don't want to monopolize this,'' Mrs. Gore urged him to continue,
saying, ``It's important because you're a man and you come forward
and you can help so many men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in effect on trial for my life, a libel trial,'' Wallace
told the crowd, describing the nightmare of spending weeks in a
courtroom where the case was being heard, and of being grilled by
other journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, now, we love our friends in the press,'' Mrs. Gore
interjected.
</P>
<P>
   He went on, saying, ``I was lower than a snake's belly,'' and
described how he took to calling his doctor late at night,
wondering what was wrong, only to be told, basically, to buck up.
He was eventually hospitalized, and after winning the libel case,
relapsed because he went off his medicine. Now, on medication ``for
the rest of my life, I feel better up here than ever in my life,''
Wallace said, pointing to his head.
</P>
<P>
   As President and Mrs. Clinton listened intently to the story,
they were mirror images of one another, each holding one finger in
the crook of their chins.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also seemed riveted by the story of a young woman who
had battled anorexia, once limiting herself to only 20 calories a
day, less than half an apple, and doing situps until her back was
covered with sores. ``How much weight did you lose?'' the president
asked her. ``How much did you weigh?''
</P>
<P>
   When it came Gore's turn to interview a mother whose
eighth-grader has bipolar disorder, he sounded a little like a
therapist himself: ``What I hear you saying is that anyone who
talks about how important it is for families to stay together and
be strong ought to also be supportive of families in these
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   He also spoke to a medical director who found that providing
preventive treatment and full mental health benefits saved his
company money, and again spoke about how his wife had helped
educate him on mental health issues over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mrs. Clinton led a discussion with researchers and Rep.
Lynn Rivers, D-Mich., who said that drugs to treat her bipolar
disorder had at one time eaten up half of her family's income.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the president spoke, saying he was educated on mental
illness by reading the work of the novelist William Styron, then
adding, ``but it is not enough to be moved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of feel like an anticlimax at this convention _ and not
for the reasons the political reporters think,'' he said, praising
those who had told their stories.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, the Gores hosted what they called a town
meeting on the theme of ``busting myths'' about mental illness, and
Gore appeared to go off script to discuss a conversation he had had
with a nun at the conference earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another myth,'' Gore said, ``is that if you pray hard enough,
if you get your relationship with God in order, that's going to
handle this. For those of us who are religious, that's the first
thing we turn to, but ... if you needed a heart transplant, you
wouldn't think, `If I just pray harder, it will take the place of a
new heart.' You need to work with God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
