<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES WON'T BE SWEPT AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup Finals have arrived, good news for hockey
fanatics who lack a well-rounded existence because the onset of the
NHL's championship series means next season's training camps open
in a mere 13 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dallas Stars and Buffalo Sabres complete their
best-of-seven series, which begins tonight in Dallas, there'll be
just enough time to melt the old ice before making a new patch.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the Finals once again will produce
another sweeps week, one markedly different from TV's traditional
sweeps weeks, which produce high Nielsen ratings and plenty of
melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey's sweeps weeks the past four years have been the Stanley
Cup Finals _ four series completed in the minimum four games,
devoid of drama and earning Nielsen ratings just a few degrees
warmer than those of the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The natural inclination is to predict that this year's
championship series will be more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   From the Western Conference _ which has won the past 12 Stanley
Cup Finals games _ come the Stars, who had the best regular-season
record in the NHL. You would never get Dallas players to admit it,
but it wouldn't be unreasonable if some were thinking they won the
Stanley Cup last week when they defeated the Colorado Avalanche in
the seventh game of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   From the Eastern Conference _ which last won a Stanley Cup in
1995, when New Jersey swept Detroit _ come the Sabres, who unfairly
and inaccurately are portrayed as Dominik Hasek and a bland helping
of Buffalo wings and defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   The easy thing to do would be to predict a Dallas sweep, which
would bring the Stanley Cup south of Philadelphia for the first
time in history.
</P>
<P>
   The gutsy thing to do would be to predict that the Sabres will
succeed in the NHL where the Buffalo Bills failed four times in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   We'll cop out and take the middle ground: Dallas will win the
Stanley Cup, but it won't be a sweep. The Stars will take more than
four games to beat the Sabres, but ultimately they will overwhelm
Buffalo with physical play and stifling defense.
</P>
<P>
   Before they finish off the Sabres, however, the Stars will have
a tussle. Buffalo's biggest strength is its lack of dependence on
any one player, which has allowed its goalie to become its most
identifiable performer. Because of Hasek, and because the Sabres
play so well together, it is irrelevant that Dallas finished first
overall with 114 points, 23 more than Buffalo, which finished
seventh in an Eastern Conference that is much stronger top to
bottom than the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres had little trouble knocking off three higher-seeded
teams in the Eastern Conference, and have been resting and healing
for more than a week since eliminating the Toronto Maple in five
games to reach the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, on the other hand, were taken to six games by St.
Louis and seven bruising and emotional games by the Avalanche, and
enter tonight's opener with a just-right four days' rest, which
might give them an early advantage over the potentially stale
Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Over a long series, however, the strengths and weaknesses of the
teams will be what matters, not how much time each side had off.
And the reality is that the Stars' edge is not as pronounced as one
might think.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are the deeper team, but not by much, and the Sabres
have an edge in speed. If forwards such as Brian Holzinger, Geoff
Sanderson, Miroslav Satan and captain Michael Peca can enter the
Stars' zone with speed, Dallas will have a difficult task
consistently stopping them.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Stars have received major postseason
contributions not only from predictable sources such as Mike Modano
and Joe Nieuwendyk, but also from role players such as Jamie
Langenbruner, Dave Reid and Mike Keane.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres have more depth, too, than they're given credit for,
and it becomes increasingly evident that productive third and
fourth lines are the true key to success in the playoff marathon.
</P>
<P>
   The past two seasons, when Detroit won the Cup, Steve Yzerman
and Sergei Fedorov got the headlines, but the Red Wings' edge came
from players such as Darren McCarty, Kris Draper and Martin
Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as important as depth are special teams, and this series
will present an intriguing faceoff of Buffalo's potent and
consistent power play and Dallas' outstanding penalty-killing unit.
If one side dominates the other in this aspect of the game, that
team will lift the Stanley Cup within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   An intriguing and depressing sidelight to this series for
followers of the Kings is the presence of two defensemen who should
have helped lead them into the new millennium and the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago as rookies, Darryl Sydor and Alexei Zhitnik helped
lead the Kings to their only appearance in the Finals. Within three
years, both had been traded, and since then, both have become
mainstays on their subsequent teams, Sydor with the Stars and
Zhitnik with the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Now, six years later, Sydor or Zhitnik finally will win a
Stanley Cup, because there's no way both can be done in by the
illegal curvature of a hockey stick.
</P>
<P>
   And Sydor will be the fortunate one, because he plays for a
veteran team built to win the Cup this year, a team that has been
preparing for this moment for the past few years, a team with
offensive depth that also can play defense so tight that
goaltending becomes irrelevant. Dallas goalie Ed Belfour is far
from irrelevant, but inevitably will be overshadowed by Hasek, the
international hockey hero.
</P>
<P>
   It will take six games before the Stars finish off Hasek and the
Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor and his teammates better enjoy it while they can. It will
be June 19 when the Stars win the Cup, and training camp will be
only 11 weeks away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
