<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HASTERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKER PLANS SPEECH TO UNITE HOUSE GOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Dennis Hastert will meet with House
Republicans on Tuesday in what is being described by party members
as a very pointed political pep talk and an effort to strengthen
his own position as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert will express his views ``on where we are and where we
need to go,'' a spokesman for Hastert, Pete Jeffries, said on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffries said he could not comment on a report in The Washington
Post on Tuesday that the speaker's get-tough speech had been
prompted by his worries that the party could lose control of the
House if dissension within the ranks continued.
</P>
<P>
   The Post reported that Hastert planned to tell Republican
conservative dissidents that they could be undermining their
party's future unless they rallied behind his agenda. It is no
secret that the speaker has been worried by a lack of party unity
on issues like health care, taxes and domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   A close ally of the speaker, Rep. Ray LaHood, was quoted by The
Post as saying that Hastert needed to realize that part of being a
leader was ``putting your fist on the table and saying, `O.K.,
folks, I've listened to everybody and here's what we're going to
do.''' LaHood is from Hastert's home state, Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's brief tenure as speaker has been marked by paradox, in
a way. He has kept a low profile _ deliberately, many people on
Capitol Hill have said _ and he has not seemed to be a political
disciplinarian. Yet he is a bear of a man, physically, and was a
high school wrestling coach.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Monday night whether the speaker's private address to
his troops should be described as an effort to sharpen an agenda,
or an effort to rally emotional support, or an old-fashioned
coach's pep talk, Jeffries replied, ``A little of each.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffries said the meeting had been foreshadowed by weeks of
meetings Hastert has held with House Republicans on the budget
process. The spokesman described the meetings as collegial
``listening sessions'' with party members, both conservatives and
moderates.
</P>
<P>
   It has been widely reported that Hastert returned from the
Memorial Day recess determined to rewrite Republican spending
plans, shifting some money from military spending and into social
programs like health and education. The House is far behind in its
work on more than a dozen appropriations measures to finance the
government for the fiscal year 2000, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's problems are interlocking and, in a way,
contradictory. He must try to restore some domestic spending cuts
to please moderate Republicans and enough Democrats to pass
legislation, yet he does not want to risk infuriating his party's
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he wants to unite his party enough so that
Republicans do not lose the House they won in 1994 after four
decades in the wilderness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
