<DOCNO> NYT19990607.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BB-REDSOX-EXPOS-BOS &LR;      06-07 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
PAVANO DEALS SOX A SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
 BB-RED SOX-EXPOS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ As a rags-to-riches tale, Carl Pavano has been the
rags in this deal, while Pedro Martinez has amassed the riches.
</P>
<P>
   But lest anyone rush to judgment too soon about the trade in
which Red Sox prospect Pavano and Expos star Martinez swapped
uniforms two years ago, this public service reminder: Pavano is
still only 23 years old.
</P>
<P>
   And while Martinez is making a compelling case that he is a
pitcher for the ages, Pavano reminded the Red Sox Monday night that
given a little time, he might mature into the pitcher Dan Duquette
thought he would be back when Pavano was twinned with Brian Rose as
Boston's hopes for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano gave up a two-run home run to Brian Daubach in the first
inning, then shut out the Red Sox on four hits until the ninth in
what turned into a Canadian carpet cleaning, an 8-2 Montreal win
before a gathering small enough (7,003) to cram into one Metro
train.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable, the best pitcher in baseball,'' Pavano said
of the man for whom he was traded in November 1997. ``Sometimes I
think to myself, `What were they thinking?' That's an honest
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he is amazing. If they're looking at me to become that
kind of pitcher one day, I'm going to have work at being the best I
can be. My goal is to be the best, to set precedents, make an
impact on the game. I don't just want to say that I was a major
leaguer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos, who began the night 13 games under .500 and as losers
of as many games (33) as the Sox had won, took turns tattooing Bret
Saberhagen, who hasn't won since Patriots Day, and relievers Derek
Lowe and John Wasdin to send the Sox to their third straight loss,
the first time since May 5 the Sox have hung that many L's in
succession.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, a week into his return from the disabled list, was
hit early and often by the Expos, who numbered two doubles, two
triples, and a home run in the first four innings among their nine
hits off Saberhagen, who went six.
</P>
<P>
   The home run, a two-run shot that gave the Expos a 4-2 lead in
the third, was struck by Orlando Merced and was one more hit than
he had in the five weeks he was with the Red Sox last summer.
Merced, who came to the Sox in a trading-deadline deal with the
Twins last July 31, had only nine at-bats before being released by
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he forgot his contact lenses on his way to the ballpark,
but his wife came to his rescue in time for him to make connections
against Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing was with my off-speed pitches,'' said
Saberhagen, who saw the Expos double their advantage the inning
after he left with a two-out rally against Lowe, who walked two
batters with two out and nobody on, then put the Sox away with
Orlando Cabrera's two-run home run off Wasdin in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was leaving everything up in the zone,'' Saberhagen said.
``That's when they really did a lot of damage. It was almost like I
was putting the ball on a tee, the way they were hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what hurt me most is when I fell behind Merced, 3 and 0.
He's hit me well in the past, but you don't want to walk him and
put runners on first and second with (Vladimir) Guerrero coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw him fastballs and he missed a bunch of them, but then
he got one.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavano, who suffered the humiliation of a 15-0 beating by the
Sox and Martinez last July in Fenway Park, allowed six hits, walked
one, and struck out five while pitching into the ninth inning for
the first time in his fledgling big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to tip your hat to Pavano,'' Saberhagen said.
``We'd just gotten a two-spot early, and he was able to shut us
down the rest of the game. He really kept us off balance all night.
He threw a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, Pavano said, he'd like to be remembered for more than
this double negative: The Man Who Was Traded for Martinez, and The
Man Who Gave Up Mark McGwire's 70th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it was sweeter beating Boston, the team that traded
me,'' said Pavano, whose record is an exceedingly modest 4-5 with
an indecent 6.29 ERA even after beating the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to stay away from making headlines about giving up
home runs. I've just got to keep working hard, keep my head on
straight. For really everyone, the sky is the limit, as long as you
can stay healthy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
