<SLUG> BC-BKW-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP ON THE WAY FOR SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The two highly regarded Yugoslavian players
expected to join the Sparks' training camp roster late will be
arriving in Los Angeles today and have one day to practice with the
team before the season opener Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But still, the 5-foot-10 guard Gordana Grubin and 6-6 center
Nina Bjedov are expected to make the 11-player cut Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pair has been with the Yugoslavian national team competing
in the European Championships, which concluded Sunday in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks coach Orlando Woolridge saw both last year when he was an
assistant coach on the USA Basketball women's national team.
Woolridge speaks highly of Grubin, 26, who can play the point or
shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really impressed me,'' he said. ``We had Shannon Johnson
on her, who I feel is one of the best defensive guards in the
league, we had Nikki McCray, we had Sheryl Swoopes ... we had some
of our best perimeter players on her and she was just a dominating
force.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks will have five guards in camp with Grubin joining.
She is expected to put pressure on point guards Penny Toler and
Jamila Wideman. Rookie Ukari Figgs has received the nod as the
starting point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Bjedov will help in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's 6-6, a very good body, and does a great job of shooting
the ball from outside facing up,'' Woolridge said. ``She has good
post moves. She relly understands the game. We're fortunate to have
two other Olympians to join what we have here right now. They have
a style that fits right in.''
</P>
<P>
   Toler, a former All-American from Long Beach State, suffered a
minor sprain left ankle in practice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA, three days from opening its third season with 12
teams, announced it will add teams in Miami, Seattle, Indianapolis
and Portland, Ore., next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had not anticipated expanding this quickly,'' WNBA
president Val Ackerman said. ``But the combination of the success
of the league in the first two seasons and the strong interest
expressed by NBA owners has convinced us that the time is right.''
</P>
<P>
   The league opened teams in Detroit and Washington last year and
Orlando and Minnesota this season. The 16 teams in 2000 will double
what the league started with in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks guard Tamecka Dixon, who wrote ``You Can Be A Woman
Basketball Player
</P>
<P>
   '' (Cascade Pass, Inc.), will have a book reading and signing
July 25 at Borders bookstore, 6510 Canoga Ave., in Canoga Park, and
another one will be planned later for August in Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the WNBA All-Star game go on sale today. The tickets
costs $10, $30, $40 and $75 and are available at all Ticketmaster
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural game will be held July 14 at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
